<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-CHILLS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
23.) 
RECORD FREEZE IN LOS ANGELES MAKING NEW YORK SHINE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention editors: ``Today'' in story refers to Wednesday, Dec.(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES_ Whether they're schlepping Christmas gifts or
searching for a hot sidewalk pretzel, winter-weary New Yorkers
frost with envy this time of year over their counterparts in Los
Angeles, all toasty and warm in the sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Right?
</P>
<P>
   Forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's high in Central Park hit 63 degrees. The L.A.-area
suburb of Canoga Park peaked at 60 degrees and shuddered through a
low temperature of 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this time of year, it's uncanny, but you enjoy it,'' said
Jeffrey Bailey, a doorman at New York's Carlyle Hotel, glad to
forgo his muffler and heaviest overcoat.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, the ice age will continue today, with the
National Weather Service issuing a frost warning and predicting
temperature records.
</P>
<P>
   The mercury is expected to dip to 28 degrees just before
daybreak today in some areas, forecaster Clint Simpson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Records have been falling and more will fall,'' Simpson said.
</P>
<P>
   The culprit is a blast of arctic air from Canada. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Residents awoke to ice on their porches, nearly frozen pipes
and a treacherous commute for some, as roads had patches of nearly
invisible ice. The damage to homeowners' landscaping has only
begun.
</P>
<P>
   The Boething Treeland nursery in West Hills, an L.A. suburb,
already lost some delicate ficus trees and fuchsia plants to the
cold Tuesday. Later in the day, workers checked enclosures and
heaters protecting other plants, and watered greenery that the cold
wind had dried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing dying is the workers from the cold,'' joked a
nursery employee, Mike Naiditch, 52, of West Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just layer. You can always take off what you have,''
54-year-old John Herkins added. But he faced a dilemma _ his layers
were too bulky for the rain suit he wears while watering the
plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually if it's windy, the stuff will blow back on you. Then
you're really cold. Your fingers get numb,'' Herkins said.
</P>
<P>
   It's the blazing summer sun that roofers usually dread while
working with hot tar. But Bob Tinsey, general manager of Golden
Eagle Roofing in Van Nuys, said a cold day can be just as
miserable &UR;  &LR; _ and more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got up on a roof this morning and there was ice. I thought
we were in Fresno or something,'' he said of a tile-replacement job
in Toluca Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unseasonably cold. It's unbelievable,'' said Tinsey, who
has been in the business 45 years. ``It's an inconvenience. But the
harder you work, the warmer you get. If you're standing around, you
get cold.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Los Angeles Zoo, the staff protects the animals from the
chill by heating their night quarters, and protects itself by
donning heavy jackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the reptiles are kept warm 24 hours a day,'' and an
arthritic goat named Bob has his own heated stall, said Michael
Dee, general curator. ``But it's surprising the number of birds
from the tropics that we don't have to give any heat.''
</P>
<P>
   They've gotten used to the cold and simply perch under branches
for cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``You become acclimatized to a hot environment or a cold
environment,'' Dee said, comparing it to a Chicagoan or New Yorker
visiting Los Angeles who might consider Tuesday balmy.
</P>
<P>
   Layering clothes is the key to weathering a cold night sleeping
in a car, said 54-year-old John White of Encino, homeless since
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night was the first night it was pretty cold,'' White
said Tuesday. ``But there's guys who are a lot worse off than I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   When he hunkers down for the night in his 1973 Volkswagen Super
Beetle, which he bought new as a Marine in Hawaii, White wraps
himself in three sweat shirts, then lies underneath a woolen
blanket he got from a shelter last year, and another blanket he
received at the Veterans Administration hospital recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's uncomfortable, but I'd rather have the cold than the El
Nino. I don't like the rain,'' said White, sitting in his car at
Woodley Avenue Park.
</P>
<P>
   He's lucky he is not in New York, where unseasonably warm
weather is expected to be followed today by a cold blast into the
20s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
