<HEADER>
A3419 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCLANE-HNS &LR;      12-23 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCLANE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
After Roger Clemens ruled out playing for the Astros under current
management, owner Drayton McLane Jr. stood behind his front-office
personnel Tuesday night and said he hopes to resolve any
differences with baseball's only five-time Cy Young Award winner.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Clemens withdrew his demand for a trade from
the Toronto Blue Jays while saying he has no desire to play for
Astros president Tal Smith or general manager Gerry Hunsicker, who
called a news conference during the winter meetings to blast
Clemens' financial demands.
</P>
<P>
   McLane admitted the Dec. 13 news conference was unfortunate but
said the Astros have no plans for any front-office moves in the
wake of Clemens' remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry Roger feels that way,'' McLane said. ``We're
certainly not going to acquire Roger if we can't rectify the
problems. We are certainly not going to consider changing anything
in our leadership. We hope Roger will reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very committed to Gerry and Tal. I think Tal is one of
the most respected baseball executives in baseball. Gerry has been
our general manager for two years, and all we've done is win two
division titles.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker also was named the National League Executive of the
Year by The Sporting News, as was Smith in 1980 when he was the
club's GM.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, McLane said he hasn't given up on the idea of
landing Clemens, whose agents, Alan and Randy Hendricks, proposed
to the Astros a one-year contract extension worth $27.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   McLane, who has been the chief negotiator in the Astros'
discussions with Clemens' agents, said he is confident the
situation can be resolved over time. He never formally has had
discussions with or met Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but believe this can be resolved. Hopefully, time
solves a lot of problems,'' McLane said. ``At the appropriate time,
I hope to sit and talk this through with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens expressed his anger Tuesday at the Astros' remarks
during the winter meetings that he claims portrayed him as greedy
while damaging the reputations of his agents. McLane said that when
he called the Hendricks brothers to apologize, it was on behalf of
the entire organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak for the team,'' McLane said. ``Them being upset with
Gerry and Tal I feel they are upset with me. We're all part of a
family and team. I consider it my problem as well as theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens notified the Blue Jays on Dec. 2 that he was demanding a
trade closer to home or to a contender under a 1996 agreement with
former club president Paul Beeston. The Astros, Texas Rangers, New
York Yankees and Cleveland Indians had been considered the
front-runners to acquire Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   If the Astros are to pursue Clemens further, McLane said one
thing won't change: the club's hesitance to part with too many
front-line players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't give up major talent that will hurt the team in the
long run,'' McLane said. ``In the long run, that would accomplish
nothing. Our goal is to be a champion. That's why we need Roger
Clemens. It has to work financially.''
</P>
</TEXT>
