<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Dec. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DRUGS (Washington) _ An ambitious United States effort to
help train and equip Mexico's armed forces to pursue drug smugglers
is in a shambles, officials of both countries say, souring American
relations with an ally that Washington has worked intensely to
court. By Tim Golden.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   ANGOLA-WAR (Luena, Angola) _ In this little town in eastern
Angola there is little doubt that a war, which had been dormant for
nearly four years, has begun again. The peace treaty that gave
Angola, a country rich in diamond and oil deposits, its longest
cease-fire in 30 years is in ruins. Since June the Unita rebel
forces have retaken more than half the countryside, engaging the
Angolan army in hundreds of places and flushing more than 200,000
Angolans from their villages. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-OPPOSITION (Washington) _ Looking at U.S. options, military
strategy and political realities in Iraq. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ News Analysis: A vignette in
Parliament of Prime Minister Netanyahu alone, ridiculed from left
and right, perfectly captured his political crisis. But while his
opponents have joined together as never before, the left and right
are fragmenting. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CHIAPAS (Acteal, Mexico) _ A year later, Chiapas massacre
is an open wound for villagers here. By Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-SEX (Clearwater, Fla.) _ The dating game never stops.
For couples who move to retirement communities, it abruptly resumes
after a decades-long hiatus as soon as one spouse dies. The need
for companionship, tenderness, love and, yes, sex, remains as
important as ever, but the rules of the game have changed. One
woman described her dream man: ``I would like a note from his
doctor stating that he's healthy _ or if he isn't, that he only has
six months to live.'' She paused. ``And he has to drive at night.''
By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-CORE-EDUC (Chicago) _ The University of Chicago is
rethinking its rigorous core curriculum. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-POLL (Undated) _ In virtually every major poll taken in
recent weeks, the people who believe that President Clinton should
be removed from office show up in the minority. But they are
clearly resolute in their opinion, with most saying that the
president lied both under oath and in his famous early
pronouncement to the nation that he ``did not have sexual relations
with that woman,'' and that such lies are automatic grounds for
dismissal. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-SHOPPING (Undated) _ Malls around the country, in a
growing move to stem shopper defections to the Internet, catalogs
and their competitors down the highway, are enticing customers this
season by giving them something new: rewards for shopping. By
Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   GRACE-SEC-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Federal securities regulators
charged W. R. Grace &AMP; Co. and six of its former executives with
financial fraud Tuesday, saying the company had deceived
shareholders over a span of five years by falsely reporting
earnings. The move was part of a larger plan by the Securities and
Exchange Commission to crack down on the growing number of
companies that break accounting rules so that they can manipulate
earnings. By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOMER-SERVICE (Undated) _ For most of America, `customer
service' frequently remains an oxymoron. Especially at this time of
year, shoppers often have to deal with temporary salespeople who
may be poorly trained. Judging from shoppers' stories, many
encounters with sales ``help'' turn decidedly sour. By Constance L.
Hays.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on customer satisfaction has been sent to NYT
graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   VH1-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ After years of struggling, VH1, the
music cable network, is seeking to capitalize on recent gains in
viewership and advertising revenue with a campaign that is intended
to solidify an image as the best way to ``go behind the music.'' By
Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FLEDERMAUS (New York) _ Comden and Green talk about their
approach to ``Die Fledermaus'' at the Met. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE-RANIER (Seattle) _ Arts in America: A Seattle gallery's
Mount Rainer exhibit. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd on the mood in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Frank Rich comments on sex scandals and
politics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKC-BERKOW-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on Pam
Valvano, the widow of Jim Valvano, the N.C. State basketball coach
who died of cancer. Her husband is honored tonight with the Jimmy V
Classic, a basketball charity double-header. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PLAYOFFS (Miami) _ On Pro Football: The Denver Broncos, who
started off the season with 13 consecutive victories, have now lost
two straight and seem to have lost momentum. The Minnesota Vikings,
on the other hand, are owners of the league's best record and are
clearly peaking. By Thomas George.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA-FINANCES (Undated) _ What are the typical revenues and
expenses of an National Basketball Association team, and how are
they changing because of the lockout? A look at the financial
statements of the San Antonio Spurs and Boston Celtics offers a
glimpse at this world. By Richard Snadomir.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAVIAR (Undated) _ A caviar connoisseur is someone who relishes
the various. Bursting between the tongue and the roof of the mouth,
caviar never tastes the same. Its flavor varies from fish to fish,
region to region, season to season. That is part of its allure.
This year, however, the wild disparity in caviar prices is more
than matched by incongruent flavor, texture and quality of the roe.
Findings of a tasting by experts. By Molly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CAVIAR-FARM (Davis, Calif.) _ For two decades and more, Mats and
Dafne Engstrom have been working on a project that he compares to
making paper by planting a forest. Their goal is to produce caviar
comparable to that from the Caspian Sea _ specifically the variety
known as osetra _ from the eggs of farm-raised California sturgeon.
The process works well; the problem is that it takes the
slow-growing sturgeon a very long time to reach an age at which
they produce roe. This is the future of caviar now that the Caspian
Sea is almost depleted of sturgeon. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CAVIAR-NOTEBOOK (New York) _ A critic's notebook on caviar in
restaurants. By Ruth Reichl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
