r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWA-TALKS-2TAKES-KAN &LR;      12-23 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-TALKS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWA IN STANDSTILL WITH UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  (Kansas City, Mo.) _ More than a year of
``preliminary'' talks for Trans World Airlines employees appears to
be over.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now it's crunch time for TWA management and more than 16,000
workers represented by the Machinists union.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are awaiting a decision by a federal mediator on the
union's request to allow a 30-day ``cooling off'' period to begin.
</P>
<P>
   During that 30-day period, talks would continue in efforts to
reach a new agreement. If a pact isn't reached during that time,
management would be free to lock out the workers and the union
would be free to strike the airline.
</P>
<P>
   Neither scenario seems likely, aviation analysts say, given that
a TWA shutdown most likely would mean the end of the airline.
However, industry experts watching TWA's talks with the Machinists
say both sides need to make certain concessions to ensure the
carrier's viability in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations with the Machinists union affect more than
2,200 workers at TWA's overhaul base in Kansas City. Including its
administrative center, TWA has more than 3,600 employees in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's predicament, analysts say, is that it still is trying to
complete a financial turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``TWA has a revenue disadvantage with the rest of the
industry,'' said Glenn Engel, aviation analyst with Goldman Sachs &AMP;
Co. ``They'd like to give their people more pay, but they also want
to close that revenue gap.''
</P>
<P>
   As TWA awaits word from the National Mediation Board, the union
remains firm in its demand for a new contract that brings employee
wages up to the industry standard.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Nelson, president of Machinists Local 1650 in Kansas City,
said the company's workers had given enough in previous contracts
with TWA. Now the employees want wage increases on par with the
rest of the industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to strike and, if necessary, put this company
out of its misery so we can get on with our lives,'' Nelson said in
a recorded message to members on an informational hot line. ``There
will be no more concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   The union said no progress was made during the final
``supermediation'' sessions that concluded Dec. 11, but TWA said 30
issues involving mechanics and passenger service workers were
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   James F. Martin, TWA's senior vice president of human resources,
said he expected to see the two sides back at the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides, it seems, have a long way to go to reach common
ground. According to the union, the company made a proposal asking
for work rule changes that would eliminate more than 2,000 jobs
systemwide, reduce staffing at 22 stations, close a reservations
center and allow maintenance work by outside contractors.
</P>
<P>
   TWA said it made an offer that included wage increases that
would bring TWA employees to within 90 percent of the industry
standard.
</P>
<P>
   That was what TWA's pilots accepted earlier this year, but
negotiators for the Machinists are seeking a contract to bring
their members' wages completely up to the industry average.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Machinists want assurances in the contract that
TWA will not close any of its maintenance bases, including the
overhaul base in Kansas City. Such a provision was included in the
previous contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't give that'' assurance, said TWA spokesman Mark Abels
in an October interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't manage the business that way,'' Abels said. ``Some
people think buildings create jobs. We tend to think a successful
business strategy creates jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   But such big differences on important issues are typical in such
talks until the 30-day countdown begins, one observer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the nature of labor negotiations under the Railway
Labor Act,'' said David W. Levine, contributing editor for
/{PlaneBusiness,/} a financial newsletter on airlines. ``You can't
float an idea out there and take it back easily. It's hard to take
an offer off the table, so both sides start out wanting'' what
would be their ideal agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But Levine and other analysts agree that some fundamental
problems have to be addressed in any new contract with the
Machinists.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's employees, after continually giving concessions to help
bail the airline out of financial straits, generally are paid
significantly less than the industry average.
</P>
<P>
   For example, TWA's top pay for mechanics is $17.93 an hour,
compared with hourly rates of $21.63 at Northwest Airlines and
$23.98 at US Airways. Baggage handlers at most airlines earn more
than TWA's mechanics, according to industry observers.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, has made it difficult to attract and keep younger
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty of maintenance work in the rest of the
industry, so some people train here and go on to other airlines,''
Nelson said. ``I've even heard of TWA mechanics at JFK
(International Airport) with 30 years at the company leaving
because they can get better pay at another carrier.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lower pay, TWA's overall labor costs aren't the
lowest in the industry. In various measures of labor costs and
productivity, TWA's numbers are average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reputation in the industry is that TWA is top quality when
it comes to maintaining their planes,'' Levine said. ``But TWA is
at the absolute back of the pack when it comes to productivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine said that since TWA reduced its fleet and eliminated
widebody jets such as the Boeing 747 and Lockheed L-1011, its
maintenance operation had become too big for the airline.
Maintenance costs have remained the same while the airline has
gotten smaller and acquired newer jets that require less
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the airline no longer is doing the third-party
maintenance on other airlines that used to be a revenue generator
for the company. TWA said it could no longer make money on such
work. MORE
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, TWA canceled what was thought to be a lucrative defense
contract to work on jets for the U.S. Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question TWA is long on maintenance capacity,''
Levine said. ``And there's something wrong when you're not able to
make a profit on a Department of Defense contract.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, according to union officials, has been TWA's
neglect of its maintenance operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ended up making us totally inefficient by not buying the
tooling that we needed and not buying the spare equipment we needed
to do the work,'' Nelson said. ``We made sacrifices in our
contracts so they could make those investments in our operation,
but the company has reneged on those commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, according to Nelson, TWA is investing most of its resources
in flight operations and appears to be on a course to outsource its
maintenance work.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Machinists officials are working with Kansas City
Mayor Emanuel Cleaver and the Economic Development Corp. of Kansas
City in hopes of coming up with a package that will persuade TWA to
operate the city-owned overhaul facility beyond May 2000, when the
airline's lease with the city expires.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson questioned TWA's timing of its acquisition of new
aircraft earlier this month. TWA plans to add 125 narrow-body
Boeing and Airbus Industrie aircraft from 2000 to 2007.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to fix our immediate problems, which is a contract for
most of the airline's employees,'' he said. ``The new aircraft is a
moot point if they don't settle our contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts think a wage compromise will be found while TWA's work
force is reduced over the next few years, either through early
retirement buyouts or attrition.
</P>
<P>
   The contentious relationship the Machinists union has had with
TWA through the years doesn't help the talks, Levine said. During
investor Carl Icahn's ownership of TWA, there was no emphasis on
improving labor relations, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they bought Icahn out, there was a management team of
the year every year,'' Levine said. ``This group (headed by Gerald
L. Gitner) seems to be bringing some stability at the top. But
there are a lot of bitter, entrenched employee groups within TWA.
They've heard all the talk about change before.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, TWA's management and union workers will have to
find a way to work together if the airline plans to be around in
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think either side has much choice,'' Engel said. ``But
with labor-management relations in the airline industry, you never
know what might happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
