<SLUG> BC-GUS-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BULL RUN FROM PAGES OF THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   (Undated) _ Gene Ayres, a reporter for
BEGIN ITAL The Star END ITAL from 1957 to 1963, was mindful of this
paper's long reputation as a place hospitable to good writers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A generation earlier, Ernest Hemingway had served a cub's
apprenticeship here before going off to war, to Paris, and to fame.
And Gene was much affected by Hemingway's writing, as who among us
in those years was not.
</P>
<P>
   He had devoured the master's books, especially those that were
set in Spain and dealt, either directly or in passing, with the
subject of bullfighting.
</P>
<P>
   He held forth with authority on the sport, or spectacle, or
drama _ or whatever you prefer to call it. And he had mastered all
the technical terms, rendering them with such a perfect accent you
never would have guessed that was the only Spanish he knew.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, Gene and I traveled several months together in Europe,
two footloose youngsters on leave from the paper. Much of the time
in Spain was spent nursing our wreck of a car along dusty roads
from one BEGIN ITAL feria END ITAL to the next, to watch matadors
confront the bulls in a pageant with mortal stakes.
</P>
<P>
   That was what Hemingway would term ``the dangerous summer,'' in
his book about the competition in the bullring between two
brothers-in-law and fierce rivals, Antonio Ordonez and Luis Miguel
Dominguin.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't know that. But when we saw the notices of an upcoming
festival in the town of Badajoz, near the Portuguese border, and
read that Ordonez and Dominguin would be featured, it was clear the
week could be something special.
</P>
<P>
   And it was.
</P>
<P>
   Dominguin was more the showman. Ordonez was reserved, less
demonstrative, but elegant in his passes with the cape. What's
more, he was uncommonly tall for a Spaniard. That gave him a great
advantage in dispatching the bull with the sword _ the drama's
final act, which can be messy and repellent in inept hands.
</P>
<P>
   As the summer and the journey drew toward its end, I took a room
in a fishing town on the coast and settled in to write. Gene went
north to the feria of San Fermin to run with the bulls through the
streets of Pamplona.
</P>
<P>
   That's been 40 years ago. But often, when we've been together
since, we've spoken of those adventures of our youth. Two years
ago, when Dominguin died, Gene sent me a clip of the newspaper
item.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday(DEC. 20), in BEGIN ITAL The New York Times, END ITAL
there was a photograph of Ordonez in the bullring, seen over the
rump and humped shoulders of a massive fighting bull, whose
needle-tipped horns are aimed directly at his torso.
</P>
<P>
   His expression, as he looks the creature in the face, is a
mixture of excitement and admiration. There is no fear at all. He
is in his late 20s in the picture, just as we were that summer.
And, like us at that age, he believes he is immortal.
</P>
<P>
   The headline and story under the photo told that Ordonez was
dead at 66, of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Ayres left BEGIN ITAL The Star END ITAL for the West Coast,
and practiced journalism there, stylishly, fearlessly, until he
retired. He died, this past August, also of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe he'd have rather had it said he ``beat Ordonez to the
barn'' _ which is how Gary Cooper was reported to have put it to
his pal, Hemingway, when the doctors told him his run was near its
end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 0058EST &QL; 
