<SLUG> BC-FAKE-GOODS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BATTLE AGAINST COUNTERFEIT TRADEMARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   (Kansas City, Mo.) _ With Christmas fast
approaching, Kansas Citians are crowding accessories counters and
riffling through racks of clothes to find the perfect gifts with
the perfect brand names.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's nice to find a well-tailored shirt, an elegant handbag or a
pair of UV-blocking sunglasses under the tree. But to many people,
that all comes second to finding the right brand name on each gift.
</P>
<P>
   A recent FBI raid on Replicas, a Lenexa store where agents said
they found counterfeit brand-name merchandise, was part of a
continuing war on black marketeers who make ordinary items more
desirable by slapping on trendy labels.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem like a crime with few victims _ customers who pay
90 percent less than they would for the real thing usually know
they're buying fakes, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   But trademark counterfeiting is a huge problem for the companies
that make the real things.
</P>
<P>
   One group, the International AntiCounterfeiting Coalition,
estimates that trademark counterfeiting will cost U.S. industries
$200 billion this year in lost sales, jobs and taxes, up from $21
billion in 1983. That number covers all counterfeit merchandise,
including software and music, and assumes that people who buy
counterfeit goods would have bought the genuine product if the
knockoff hadn't been available.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no longer about cutting and sewing labels onto
T-shirts in back rooms,'' said George Abbott, managing director of
the anticounterfeiting coalition.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman Jeff Lanza agrees with the $200 billion estimate.
</P>
<P>
   But some who traffic in knockoffs say many people who buy fakes
would never shell out the money for the genuine article.
</P>
<P>
   One customer, Robin Barker of Olathe, shopped at Replicas for
lookalikes of her family's favorite name-brand goods because she
doesn't think the real things are worth what they cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lower your prices and we'll buy from you,'' Barker said.
</P>
<P>
   Trademark piracy picks up around Christmas and just before the
school year starts, and these days the black market is so busy that
private investigators hired by trademark holders have more cases
than they know what to do with.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Smith, who investigated the Lenexa case for the Guidry
Group, a Dallas security firm and consulting agency, said he spent
58 hours a week recently, working on 125 cases of trademark piracy.
Two clothing factories he's watching have started working 24-hour
days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few stores in the Kansas City area openly display counterfeit
merchandise. Street vendors and flea market stalls also carry the
counterfeits, but they're not as easy to find on the street as they
are in California and New York, where much of the merchandise
enters the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have more of in the Midwest is an underground network
of people who have house parties,'' Abbott said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, guests order fake brand-name clothes at the parties
and the host sends a fax or an e-mail to a supplier on the coast,
who ships in just enough knockoffs to fill the orders.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after Thanksgiving last year, FBI agents raided a
Mission Hills house where fake goods allegedly were being sold.
Authorities hauled away what they said were pirated goods, but no
one has been charged.
</P>
<P>
   People on both sides of the black market agree that few people
ever face charges for trademark piracy. MORE
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Foote, the Lenexa man who owns Replicas, took that into
account when he set up a shop that openly sold fake goods with
brand names such as Adidas, Tommy Hilfiger, Dooney &AMP; Bourke and
Mont Blanc. He said he wasn't too surprised when FBI agents seized
most of his stock early Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens to anybody sooner or later. You just have to expect
it,'' Foote said.
</P>
<P>
   Foote hasn't been charged and is free to sell legitimate goods
from his store. And the raid hasn't had an obvious effect on other
area outlets for counterfeit goods. Last week, a small Johnson
County shop was openly selling purses with Dooney &AMP; Bourke labels
for $39.
</P>
<P>
   The real thing goes for $220 at Jacobson's in Leawood's Town
Center Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at Jacobson's who agreed to examine the cheaper purse
said it was obviously a knockoff, and some of them could tell the
fake purse from real Dooney &AMP; Bourkes from more than 10 feet away.
After three or four months of use, anyone would probably be able to
tell the difference between the vinyl counterfeit and the genuine
leather purse, employees said. For now, a quick peek at a tag
inside the purse shows it's a fake.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Made in Korea' is a big signal,'' said accessories sales
manager Honey Tishgart.
</P>
<P>
   The real purse has a tag that says ``Made in the U.S.A.'' with a
serial number on the back.
</P>
<P>
   The small shop probably paid $7 for the counterfeit purse, which
likely came without any labels, said Smith, the investigator. Then
the wholesaler probably put the shop in touch with someone who
provided fake Dooney &AMP; Bourke tags, Smith said. The leather patch
with an image of a duck and the words ``Dooney &AMP; Bourke All-weather
leather,'' complete with the registered trademark symbol, typically
costs a dollar. A metal tag hanging from a leather strap goes for
22 cents.
</P>
<P>
   An investment of $8.22 yielded a $30.78 profit, less shipping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it; it isn't considered to be a crime of violence,
so you can bet that the charges if you get caught are not anywhere
near as severe as for a drug case. In fact, a lot of prosecutors
won't even touch these cases and the criminals know that,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a crook can realize that kind of profit and then if he's
not caught, doesn't face any serious charges or any serious time,
which would you choose if you're considering a life of crime?''
</P>
<P>
   It helps that relatively few buyers of counterfeit goods
consider themselves victims.
</P>
<P>
   About 95 percent of customers on the black market know what
they're buying, Smith estimates. Foote said he named his store
Replicas because he wanted to make sure there was no doubt. He
figured that his business helped trademark holders because he put
brand names on the backs of customers who wouldn't have bought the
real thing anyway. Investigators say it doesn't help a company to
have its name attached to shoddy fakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were selling fake Rolex watches for $20,'' Foote said.
``It's not the same market. It's a toy. It's a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   And it helps parents who want to satisfy their children's
brand-consciousness without overly taxing the family budget, said
former Replicas customer Barker. With Foote's help, she kept her
12-year-old son outfitted with clothes that looked like major brand
names. The FBI raid cut off her supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``My 12-year-old is very disappointed,'' Barker said. ``He'll
just be wearing the plain old, no-name clothing that doesn't have
the Nike name on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 0101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
