<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3448 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASINO-INQUIRY-2TAKES     12-23 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASINO-INQUIRY-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERJURY CLAIMED IN CASINO INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS, JOE LAMBE AND RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   (Kansas City, Mo.)A former Hilton Hotels
Corp. executive instrumental in locating the Flamingo Casino in
Kansas City was charged Monday with three state counts of felony
perjury before the Missouri Gaming Commission.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The charges against former Senior Vice President Markland
Rousseau are the culmination of more than two years of state and
federal investigations into a $250,000 grant the company awarded to
K.C. Perspectives. Former Port Authority Chairman Elbert Anderson
and his aide, Michelle Lathan, controlled K.C. Perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority selected Hilton in early 1993 over two other
casino applicants vying for rights to the site at the foot of the
Paseo Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Rousseau, now an Atlanta businessman, pleaded not guilty at his
arraignment Monday in Jackson County Circuit Court and was released
on a signature bond. His attorney, Tom Bath, denied all charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole government case rests on the word of Elbert
Anderson, which I find curious at best,'' Bath said. ``The federal
government didn't think this was worthy of prosecution. I don't see
why the state did.''
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Rousseau faces a maximum sentence of five years in
prison and a $2,500 fine on each count.
</P>
<P>
   The new charges come as the Gaming Commission considers renewing
Hilton's license, which expired last October and was conditionally
extended pending the outcome of an investigation by Jackson County
Prosecutor Claire McCaskill.
</P>
<P>
   One of the conditions was a satisfactory conclusion ``to the
outcome of the (commission's) investigation into (Hilton's)
relationship with former Kansas City Port Authority Chairman Elbert
Anderson and related matters.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement Monday, the Gaming Commission Executive
Director Mel Fisher said the agency expects to deal with Hilton's
Kansas City license when it meets Jan. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reviewing the evidence gathered in the various
investigations and will proceed accordingly,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill said her investigation began this fall at the request
of the Gaming Commission. She also probed a $3 million severance
payment made to another Hilton official, former chief executive
officer and board member Raymond Avansino. He left the company with
Rousseau.
</P>
<P>
   That payment raised no legal problems, McCaskill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have brought all the charges we think that are appropriate
under the evidence,'' McCaskill said.
</P>
<P>
   Rousseau assembled Hilton's bid for a Kansas City site in 1992
and was still a company employee when he testified before the
Gaming Commission at an Oct. 2, 1996, hearing that explored the
K.C. Perspectives grant.
</P>
<P>
   Although at the hearing Rousseau described all of his actions as
being proper and above-board, he and two other top-level Hilton
officials quickly resigned afterward. The Gaming Commission then
granted the company its Kansas City riverboat license.
</P>
<P>
   In the charges, Rousseau is accused of lying under oath to the
Gaming Commission three times during that 1996 hearing. Each
question dealt with who raised the idea in 1993 of Hilton
sponsoring a seminar//fashion show tour as part of its development
agreement with the Port Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Rousseau told the commission that Anderson did not raise the
issue of sponsoring such a tour, that he was not influenced by
anybody in Kansas City in offering the grant, and that when he
conceived the grant he had no specific recipient in mind.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sworn statement supporting the indictment, Missouri
Highway Patrol Trooper Eric S. Wilhoit said that Anderson raised
the idea in a February 1993 meeting at Winstead's Restaurant near
the Country Club Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``They agreed on a monetary sum of $1 million,'' Wilhoit wrote.
``As a result of this agreement, Anderson understood that his vote
had been `financially secured' by Hilton Hotels Corp. for future
developments, including attempts to open a temporary or permanent
facility (near the Paseo Bridge).''
</P>
<P>
   Only a $250,000 payment was made to K.C. Perspectives, which
used the money for staff salaries and to stage fashion shows and
seminars in Kansas City and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Both Anderson and Lathan have been convicted in federal court on
public corruption charges unrelated to Hilton. MORE
</P>
<P>
   (Kansas City, Mo.) _ unrelated to Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Monday, Hilton described the new charges
as ``stale allegations'' that are not against ``Hilton Hotels
Corp., any Hilton entity, or any current Hilton employee, officer
or director.''
</P>
<P>
   ``...there are no new facts and no new evidence here...At no
time in any investigation _ and we have cooperated with six of them
in the past five years _ have we seen any evidence that in any way
changes our firm conclusion that there was no wrongdoing by anyone
acting for Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of which makes it particularly difficult for us to
understand the continued pursuit of these stale allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, Hilton agreed to pay the federal government $500,000
to avoid criminal charges that an executive _ identified Monday as
Rousseau _ had rewarded Anderson for his support of the casino.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Steve Hill said he opted for the out-of-court
agreement because the base fine of $500,000 was the maximum Hilton
would have paid in a guilty verdict. Hill also said a conviction
might have amounted to a ``nationwide death penalty'' for Hilton's
14 casinos in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling regulators in Nevada and New Jersey said Monday they
would continue to watch Hilton developments in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt our investigators will be monitoring that,'' said
Nevada Gaming Control Board spokeswoman Joanie Jacka. ``The board
does not usually act until whatever is happening is finished.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harry Curtis, a gaming stocks analyst with BancBoston
Robertson Stephens, said he doesn't see the Missouri charges having
much impact on the Hilton Hotels Corp., with billions in annual
revenue, or its stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to lose their license in Nevada or any other
jurisdiction because of the allegations brought against one
individual,'' Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Hilton's regulators also have been watching a
federal investigation unfold in Florida, where a $240,000 payment
was made in 1994 to the speaker of the Florida House by Bally's
Entertainment Inc., a casino company since acquired by Hilton
Hotels Corp.
</P>
<P>
   As in the Missouri case, Hilton executives have said nothing
improper occurred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
