<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-BLUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS AND BLUES TIE, 3-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Three months after the season's start, there
was an opening-night feel at Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Islanders' franchise player, Zigmund Palffy, was on
the ice Tuesday night, electrifying the fans, a rare capacity
crowd, gathered to witness Palffy's season debut as well as the
unveiling of a new scoreboard to replace the one that was the
center of so much controversy last summer.
</P>
<P>
   When the game ended, the $3 million scoreboard showed Islanders
3, Blues 3. The $27.5 million player's scoring line showed two
assists.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, whose feet were up to speed but whose hands looked a bit
rusty, helped get the Islanders on the new board in the first
period, and he helped them gain a 3-2 late in the game. After that,
it was impossible not to wonder where the Islanders would be had
Palffy, a holdout until last week, been playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a lot of practice,'' said the 26-year-old Palffy, who
signed a five-year contract last Thursday that pays him an average
of $5.5 million a season. ``I had good jump. This first game was
very important. I will get better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Claude Lapointe scored at 10 minutes 32 seconds of the final
period to give the injury-riddled Islanders a short-lived 3-2
advantage, knocking in a pass from Robert Reichel, who got the puck
after a shot by Palffy.
</P>
<P>
   But then, just as the Islanders were closing in and the clock
was running out, Todd Gill spoiled the home team's special night
with a lob shot from the side boards that eluded the Islanders'
goalie Wade Flaherty, tying the score at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We left our legs in Arizona,'' said Coach Mike Milbury, whose
Islanders were coming off of a 2-1-1 West Coast swing that ended
with a 4-2 loss on Sunday in Phoenix. ``There's not much positive
to say about tonight's game except for we gained a point.''
</P>
<P>
   Flaherty, who played for the injured Tommy Salo, made 25 saves
for the Islanders. Grant Fuhr made 14 for the Blues. Palffy merely
saved the season.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the excitement of his return, for the fans at least,
was the scoreboard, which the Islanders purchased last summer but
refused to hang because of the allegedly unsafe hoist system. It
was introduced by a laser show on Tuesday night, complete with 3-D
glasses for all in attendance. On the video screen during the
player introductions, the Islanders welcomed back Palffy with a
lengthy tribute that showed dozens of his highlight-reel scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell he's not 100 percent,'' Milbury said of Palffy.
``But it sure helped to have him out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're markedly better'' with him, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's game was the Islanders' second sellout this
season. Among the organization's reasons for not giving into
Palffy's demands earlier was the perception that he did not sell
tickets. But the 16,297 fans who chanted, ``Ziggy, Ziggy,'' when
Palffy hopped over the dashers for the first time proved otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before Palffy was showing off those flashy
skills, the slick stick-handling and speedy skating, that make him
one of the league's most entertaining players. With Palffy laying
on a line with Reichel and Mariusz Czerkawski, the Islanders
fashioned a 2-0 lead with a couple of first-period goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders' lead, however, did not last for long as St.Louis
struck twice, tying the score, 2-2, on goals by Scott Pellerin and
Marty Reasoner late in the first period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 0104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
