<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-JIMMY-CLASSIC-NYT     12-23 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-JIMMY-CLASSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE SENDS WILDCATS A MESSAGE FOR MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ How this game was to be played was
decided early, barely eight minutes after tip-off. The decision was
dictated from the Duke sideline when Kentucky's Saul Smith, all 6
feet 2 inches of the coach's son, hurtled himself into the 6-8
Shane Battier to block what look like a certain dunk. It was a foul
_ a hard foul.
</P>
<P>
   On the sideline, Blue Devils Coach Mike Krzyzewski vaulted from
his seat and stalked down the hardwood right past the officials. He
did not have a beef with them. ``Don't let them do that to you,
don't let them do that,'' he said to Battier, Trajan Langdon and
whatever other Blue Devil answered his glare.
</P>
<P>
   From that moment, the No. 2-ranked Blue Devils turned bullies.
They took what was a lackadaisical 4-point lead and wrung it in
their hands and banged it against their elbows for a 71-60 victory.
It was a hard-nosed but not hard-hearted effort before a sellout
crowd of 20,092 at Continental Arena in an all-out war at the Jimmy
V. Classic.
</P>
<P>
   By kicking up dirt underneath what was often an aerial ballet,
Duke (11-1) grounded the nation's No. 3 team in bruising, punishing
fashion. The Blue Devils blocked eight shots. They outmuscled the
Wildcats (10-2) on the backboard, squeezing 45 rebounds to
Kentucky's 36. They committed 22 fouls, their promising freshman
Corey Maggette picking up his fifth and final one minutes into the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Every time the No. 3-ranked Wildcats threatened to fight back,
Duke invited them back into the mosh pit to scrum some more. The
last time came with 3 minutes 51 seconds left in the game with the
Wildcats within 9 points. Langdon shot and missed. Elton Brand
missed a follow. But there was Chris Carrawell on the floor
underneath the basket. He picked the ball up and stretched the lead
to 11.
</P>
<P>
   When the Blue Devils forced a 35-second violation the next time
down the floor, the Wildcats looked as if they wanted to throw in
the towel. They did, finally, when Brand bulled into the lane,
banged home a twisting finger roll and drew the foul. ``We wanted
to wear them down _ it was body to body all night,'' said the 6-8,
265-pounder who scored 22 points on 9 of 12 shooting and pulled
down 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue hammered South Carolina, 80-64, in the first game of the
doubleheader, whose purpose was to raise money for cancer research
in the name of Jimmy Valvano, the former Iona and North Carolina
State coach, who died in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   There was no holiday spirit evident on this hardwood even though
the Krzyzewski and Tubby Smith, the coaches for the two most
dominant college basketball programs of the 1990's tried to soft
sell it beforehand as nothing more than an early-season checkup. A
chance to test reflexes, to plunge a thermometer into their
players' wills and see if they had begun to burn.
</P>
<P>
   But Krzyzewski acknowledged this was something more, that he
indeed intended to send a message to his young Blue Devils when
Smith hammered Battier. ``It wasn't about being pretty tonight,''
he said. ``If you scored, you had to earn it. Everybody talks about
this being a December game. Well, it's an important December game.
I have five sophomores and a freshman. They need to get better.
They need to learn during the games. I wanted them to walk away
from here with something.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils and the Wildcats have been in epic struggles
before _ though this was the first time they have met in the
regular season since 1988. Both teams have won two titles in the
1990's. Both have more weapons than the Pentagon among its deep,
athletic teams.
</P>
<P>
   Battier and company answered Krzyzewski's early challenge by
going on a 21-14 run over the next 10 minutes as their backcourt,
William Avery and Langdon, suffocated the Wildcats into committing
10 turnovers that turned into 19 Blue Devil points.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats, who came into the game holding opponents to just
37 percent shooting, had their defensive intensity turned back on
them. They shot just 34.9 percent and the two Kentucky stars,
Heshimu Evans and Scott Padgett, scored only 13 points each on a
combined 8-for-24 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   There were moments of acrobatics that promise more highlights as
both teams drive toward the National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournament. Brand, a sophomore from Poughkeepsie, N.Y.,
engaged in a game of ``top this'' with the Bronx's Evans. He
drop-stepped beneath the Wildcats' Michael Bradley for a reverse
layup that was sweetly touched off the glass. Evans sliced the
middle, feigned once and arched a left-handed rainbow to answer
right back for the Wildcats. They could have been two guys playing
horse on a netless rim in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, Kentucky, which had already beaten four of the
nation's top 11 teams, got outbullied by its top rival. Smith
conceded his team got ``timid.'' ``When you get bumped and get hit
inside,'' he said, ``you still have to come out with something. We
didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
