<HEADER>
A3484 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEWISH-SANTA-LADN     12-23 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWISH-SANTA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN FOR ALL SEASONS: JEWISH SANTA BRINGS JOY TO CHILDREN FOR 15
YEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Surrounded by dozens of excited children tugging
at his white beard and cuffs, Arnie Cohen delivered Christmas joy
and bits of wisdom Tuesday at the Sylvan Park Children's Center.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in his own bright red suit, it was Cohen's latest
appearance as one of Santa's helpers during a 15-year stint with
the Los Angeles Fire Department's Toys for Needy Children campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen is a practicing Jew who just finished celebrating
Hanukkah, but playing Santa is no conflict for the L.A. man, who
first took on the role in 1951 during a tour of duty in the Air
Force during the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Santa is not a religious figure,'' Cohen, 66, said.
``He's a person that the kids see as someone special, and to look
into their eyes and see how happy they are brings me emotions I
can't describe.''
</P>
<P>
   And happiness is precisely what was on the menu Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids' faces, they just lit up,'' said Susan Han,
psychological coordinator for the center, which caters to
underprivileged children. ``Some of the kids were afraid, but they
all know the holidays are coming when they get a visit from
Santa.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's military buddies in Guam were the first to cast him as
St. Nick, they wanted Santa to deliver food and gifts to native
children of the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked around and I was the only Jewish guy and they
said: Hey, Arnie, you're not doing anything for Christmas, so
you're the man,'' Cohen said. ``And that was that.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the military he continued playing Santa at a
market he owned in Echo Park, an L.A.-area suburb, where the order
of the holidays was handing out candy and small gifts to
neighborhood children.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Fire Department role came along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to fly a delivery in on a helicopter, and the Fire
Department had it, so I started working with them 15 years ago,''
he said. ``It's been so much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hofbauer, a Fire Department paramedic who organized
Tuesday's visit, said Cohen has been a valuable asset to the Toys
for Needy Children campaign, which has been running for more than
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he gets sent out three or four times a day,''
Hofbauer said. ``But he helps us interact with the children at an
impressionable age _ we tell them not to play with matches and to
stop, drop and roll _ and give some of them the only Christmas they
will really have.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost nothing these days will stop Cohen from putting on that
suit. He played Santa one year with a broken foot. Last year he had
undergone surgery for prostate cancer and had to be helped into a
truck. Some time ago he did it right after a hernia operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should probably be in the Guinness Book of World Records for
the amount of times I've been Santa,'' Cohen said after spending
the morning at the Children's Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that some kids can't even get to a mall to see Santa,
and I might be the only Santa they've seen. That keeps me going,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll keep doing it as long as I'm able.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 0120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0020 </DOCNO>
