<HEADER>
A3499 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-MARIST-ARIZONA &UR; ST     12-23 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MARIST-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN DEVILS SURVIVE SCARE 
</HEADLINE>
  STATE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona State didn't so much beat Marist Tuesday night at Wells
Fargo Arena as the Sun Devils survived the Red Foxes, 85-77, to
extend their winning streak to four games.
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of factors working against the Sun Devils, not
the least of which is that Marist came in with an 8-0 record and
has a senior backcourt tandem that can play with anybody.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sun Devils had more than that to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   First, guard Eddie House, the team's leading scorer, who has had
three 30-point-plus scoring performances, was so ill Monday night
that he was given liquids intravenously Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Mike Batiste, playing his first home game of the season
after being reinstated late last week, suffered an ankle sprain in
the game's opening minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And the Sun Devils, after building a 16-point lead early in the
first half, watched the Red Foxes go on a 13-0 tear to close within
three with 15:40 to play in the game. ASU built the lead back to 13
and then surrendered a 12-2 Marist burst.
</P>
<P>
   But they survived it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a little adversity to this point this year, but I'm
proud of them,'' ASU Coach Rob Evans said. ``Mike came back in and
played through some adversity and some pain, enough to get us by.
These guys are learning how hard they've got to play, how long
they've got to play and what they've got to overcome to be a good
basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie's really under the weather. He wasn't able to come to
shootaround or pregame meal. He was pretty ill. I was very pleased
with him. He didn't have his usual game, but he fought through it
and helped us win the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   House gave the Sun Devils 27 minutes and scored 10 points while
handing out six assists. Batiste put in 34 minutes, finishing with
19 points and eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to let a little ankle injury keep me out of my
first home game of the season,'' Batiste said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he needed some help, and he got it.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Bobby Lazor led the Sun Devils in scoring with 22 points
and added six rebounds and five assists. And he produced a couple
of big baskets that helped the Sun Devils weather Marist's second
rally.
</P>
<P>
   And reserve point guard Ron DuBois came off the bench to settle
the Sun Devils down offensively in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to get us into something,'' DuBois said. ``I
was just trying to get us to slow down and execute.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't a problem in the first half, when the Sun Devils _
the Pac-10's worst shooting team at 39.6-percent for the season _
fired at a 64.5-percent rate to build a 49-36 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said he has told his team that if they could shoot 50
percent then, with their typical defensive effort, they might blow
teams out by 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sun Devils, who have won with their defense and grit
this season, forgot their identity for a stretch in the second half
and turned the ball over five times and missed four straight shots.
That's when Evans called on DuBois.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, we needed somebody to get the basketball to the
right people and steady the ship,'' Evans said. ``Ron got in there
and got us moving a little bit, which we needed to have happen.''
</P>
<P>
   And Evans adjusted, in part because of House's illness, and
switched from man-to-man defense to zone for some stretches. House
was too fatigued to stay with his man defensively, and also was in
foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils got it done, but it wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   Red Fox guard Bobby Joe Hatton hit from beyond the arc for three
of his team-high 21 points to start Marist's final surge, and guard
Bo Larragan finished it with another three that cut ASU's lead to
72-69 with 3:58 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Lazor hit a fadeaway jump shot and followed that by diving to
the basket and taking a nice pass from Batiste for a layup and
seven-point lead. The Red Foxes got no closer than five after that
as the Sun Devils were good enough from the free-throw line to
finish the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost to a good team, and I think that they're going to
surprise some of the teams in their league now that they're at full
strength,'' Marist Coach Dave Magarity said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 0127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
