<HEADLINE>
COYOTES SEE RED  
 TAKE APART WINGS FOR 2ND TIME 
</HEADLINE>
 WINGS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ It might not rank up there with the role reversals
undergone by Christine Jorgensen or Renee Richards, but the Phoenix
Coyotes found themselves the major focus of a huge one themselves
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, always the hunter, were the hunted. Believe it or
not, the Detroit Red Wings, winners of consecutive Stanley Cups and
a team that has eliminated Phoenix from two of its past three
Stanley Cup playoff appearances, were using the Coyotes as a
benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure, eh?
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings didn't come close to getting the answer they
wanted, as the Coyotes whipped them for the second time this
season, 6-2, at Joe Louis Arena, setting a season high for goal
production and raising their record to 19-5-4 to climb within two
points of Pacific Division-leading Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's how they felt coming in, then we complemented each
other, because that's how we felt, too,'' said Keith Tkachuk, who
had a goal and an assist. ``They still have a great team over
there, one that has won two straight Stanley Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight we limited our turnovers in the neutral zone and got
another great effort from Niki (Khabibulin) in goal. But, hey,
don't ever give up on them. This is the regular season. They'll
still be there at the end. Count on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit (17-13-1) is atop the Central Division standings, which
would be enough to satisfy most teams and their fans, but not those
in Hockeytown, where perfection is expected.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Wings are also a team that is 0-7 against division
leaders and is 4-10 against teams better than .500, which has fans
in a bitter mood. Tuesday night they booed ``Rudolph the Red-Nosed
Reindeer`` and cheered ``Grandma Got Run Over By A Reindeer.''
</P>
<P>
   To show Detroit's resolve entering the game, witness center Igor
Larinov's comment between the first and second periods, after his
power-play goal at 11:54 of the first period gave the Red Wings an
early 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big test for us,'' he said. ``Phoenix is playing
great this season, and we have to beat a team like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Larionov's thoughts were echoed by several teammates before the
game, including center Kris Draper, who said a victory over Phoenix
would make a statement for Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Say, do the Coyotes have a Stanley Cup stashed away somewhere?
No, but if they continue to play as they did Tuesday night, who
knows?
</P>
<P>
   To beat Detroit, a team has to dominate the neutral zone, an
area that Phoenix controlled most of the night while capitalizing
on 19 giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   When they did err, Khabibulin was providing another stellar
effort. He stopped 36 of 38 shots, and none bigger, perhaps, than a
series of three in the last minute of the second period while
protecting to 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I had a lot of tough shots because the guys
played so well in front of me and cleared the rebounds,'' said
Nikolai Khabibulin, who improved to 13-4-2. ``This was a good test
for us to start winning again against one of the best teams in the
league. It was the perfect team for us to have a great game
against.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised they stopped skating hard in the
third period, though.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone typified Phoenix's effort, it was Dallas Drake, who
showed up at the arena in a walking cast to protect an injured
middle toe. Drake gave Phoenix a 2-1 second-period lead with a
second-effort, diving goal off a turnover by Larionov. Drake later
dived to knock the puck away as Dareen McCarty was firing a
point-blank slap shot from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a typical Dallas Drake play, a second, third-effort
goal,'' Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld said. ``He not only got that,
but also a big block. He gives you maximum effort on every shift of
every game.''
</P>
<P>
   The game winner came from center Juha Ylonen at 13:15 of the
second period. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
