<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-TOYS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON PLAYS NICE, GETS HOLIDAY BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kids waited in a long line on the streets and sidewalks that
circled Phoenix's Madison Square Garden gym. Toys filled the ring.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mike Tyson's turn to play Santa in his continuing effort
to rehabilitate his image.
</P>
<P>
   But, first, he had several other roles to fill.
</P>
<P>
   After sparring Tuesday, the fighter talked about history and
Napoleon, Russia and Haiti, Archie Moore and forgotten eras, new
ways and bad habits. Tyson even got around to Clinton and
impeachment, even though he can't vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a felon, but they'll take my tax money,'' Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   Bada-boom, bada-bing.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson worked his audience as though it were a speed bag. Nobody
knows if Tyson can still throw a punch. But there was no doubt that
he could deliver a punch line along with philosophical bits and
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   For one afternoon, at least, this was no Iron Mike.
</P>
<P>
   More like Mercurial Mike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always heard that the more important you are, the more
humble you should be,'' said Tyson, who has been training at the
central Phoenix gym since mid-October for his comeback bout against
Frans Botha on Jan. 16 at Las Vegas' MGM Grand. ``I've always been
a hell-raiser. But I'm trying to practice humility. I'm working at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For a man with earnings and losses of untold millions, the
battle never ceases. He fought it Tuesday before a scheduled
workout for his first fight since he bit Evander Holyfield's ears
in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in my room and a man brought me my lunch,'' he
said. ``He called me Mister Tyson. I said, `No, no, no. Call me
Mike.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But, no, he kept calling me Mister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I looked at him and said, `Look, I have millions of
dollars and no friends.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Since his move to the Valley, Tyson has worked hard to find
those elusive friends. He has signed autographs, passed out
Thanksgiving turkeys and, on Tuesday, delivered about 500 toys to
underprivileged kids. Today, he'll visit Maricopa County Sheriff
Joe Arpaio's Tent City jail in an attempt to counsel juveniles
imprisoned at the compound for adult convictions.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release, Arpaio said the youths might listen to Tyson
because of his own prison experience.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson did not talk about jail or the possibility of a return. He
faces sentencing in Maryland on Feb. 5 for a no-contest plea on
misdemeanor assault charges. The sentence could affect his parole,
which he has been serving since his 1995 release from prison on a
rape conviction.
</P>
<P>
   But Tyson did talk about what he hoped to accomplish. He
mentioned writer Norman Mailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He defined an era,'' Tyson said. ``When I die, I'd like people
to say, `Mike, he defined an era.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For Tyson, that attempt will come in the ring. Throughout his
turbulent career, he either has been ill-defined, or a fighter
whose definition is incomplete. More always has been expected of
the youngest man to ever win the heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   But, over the years, he exceeded expectations only outside the
ropes with his own personal excesses and a crazy menagerie that
served as his entourage.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Don King, John Horne and Rory Holloway are gone. Adviser
Shelly Finkel and trainer Tommy Brooks, a former Evander Holyfield
cornerman, are there instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like Shelly are around me so I won't give all my money
away,'' said Tyson, who has a reported $10 million loan from
promoter Dan Goosen of America Presents and a $13 million debt with
the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   In Brooks, Tyson appears to have a low-key, no-nonsense trainer
who was in Holyfield's corner on the night of the infamous Bite
Fight. Brooks understands what happened then. Tyson's fearful
image, his intimidating presence, was stripped away like a thin
veil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bully syndrome won't work anymore,'' Brooks said. ``Now,
he's got to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   But, on this day, the fight would have to wait. Mercurial Mike
still had to play Santa. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
