<HEADER>
A3504 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-FREEAGE     12-23 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-FREEAGENTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CARDINALS FINDING LIFE NOT GREENER ON OTHER SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When middle linebacker Eric Hill left the Cardinals in free
agency last winter, he said he wanted to go to a playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   Hill has helped the St. Louis Rams to four victories, half of
the total of the Cardinals, who are only one win away from
clinching their first non-strike playoff berth in 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Brent Alexander, who signed a free-agent deal with
Carolina in the off-season, knows how Hill feels. The Panthers have
only three victories this season, the same number as former
Cardinals defensive end Michael Bankston has won in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Giants were 3-7 when ex-Cardinal Kent Graham
replaced Danny Kanell as the starter five games ago. Graham has
gone 4-1 as a starter, but the Giants can't get into the playoffs
unless the Cardinals and Tampa Bay lose their regular-season
finales Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Punter Jeff Feagles, who left for Seattle in free agency,
started the season 3-0. But the Seahawks have struggled since, are
8-7 and will miss the playoffs for the 10th consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the free agents who departed, only Kevin Williams, the
wide receiver-return specialist who signed with Buffalo last
February, will be in the playoffs. But each has made big enough
contributions to his team that the Cardinals should get several
compensatory picks in the 1999 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Compensatory picks are awarded to teams after Rounds 3-7 and are
based on salary and performance.
</P>
<P>
   The number of picks a team receives equals the net loss of
compensatory free agents up to a maximum of four.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals lost six unrestricted free agents (the sixth is
Giants running back LeShon Johnson, who has been out all season
recovering from a cancerous tumor in his chest) and signed only
one, running back Mario Bates, formerly of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive guard Lester Holmes, middle linebacker Mark Maddox and
backup quarterback Dave Brown signed as free agents but don't count
in the formula because they were released by their teams before
signing with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what we lost, we should get at least an extra
third-rounder,'' a Cardinals official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals already own San Diego's No. 1 choice in the 1999
draft. If the season were to end today, the Chargers (5-10) would
pick seventh or eighth overall.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's Williams has been the most successful of the free
agents who left the Cardinals after last season. He is eighth in
the AFC in punt returns with a 10.1-yard average and has 27 catches
for 373 yards and one score.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who signed a two-year, $5.25 million deal, struggled early
when he suffered a broken hand in the season opener. But he stayed
in the lineup and has started 14 games. He is fifth on the Rams in
tackles with 86 and has one sack, one interception and one forced
fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who signed a three-year, $3.025 million deal, has
started 15 games for Carolina and has 99 tackles, third most on the
team. But, just as he did with the Cardinals, he has made few big
plays and has no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Bankston has been one of the Bengals' most consistent players on
the league's worst defense. He has 67 tackles and 3.5 sacks in 15
starts. He has led the defensive line in tackles eight consecutive
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Graham has completed 90 of 179 passes for 1,086 yards and five
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Feagles is seventh in the AFC in punting with a 44.2-yard
average. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 0136EST &QL; 
