<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ABL-WNBA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY SADDENED BY RIVAL'S COLLAPSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the WNBA's only competition in North American
professional women's basketball folded up business Tuesday, the
Phoenix Mercury didn't see it as a reason for celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one sense, it's a sad day for women's basketball,'' said
Seth Sulka, the vice president of operations for the Mercury. ``I
know there has been a lot of talk about the rivalry between the two
leagues, but in many ways the ABL was a positive because it gave
year-round exposure to the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that people in the WNBA never have had anything
negative to say about the ABL, and appreciated what that league did
for women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even think there's a rivalry between the players. A
lot of them are friends because they played together in Europe
before the two leagues formed. That's where the best collegiate
players went to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Mercury will be watching closely to see how the WNBA
handles the situation.
</P>
<P>
   There will be an influx of talent from the American Basketball
League into the WNBA, and it must be determined how that will be
done. Before the announcement, there already had been talk of a
possible merger of the leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Will the WNBA take over operation of existing teams? Will there
be a supplemental draft of ABL players? Will the players simply be
there for the signing as free agents?
</P>
<P>
   And how will the two expansion teams, Orlando and Minnesota, fit
into the reallocation of talent? If the players are all free
agents, theoretically Orlando and Minnesota could put together what
amounts to ABL All-Star teams that could threaten the best of the
WNBA's teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what will work,'' Sulka said. ``We're at the
beginning of our own negotiations with our players' union that
formed about six weeks ago. Obviously, both leagues have some of
the best players in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just up in Portland, and I saw an ABL game between the
Portland Power and the Seattle Reign. The ball was great. They had
a nice little crowd, and talent-wise, the players definitely have a
place in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Portland has a player, Natalie Williams, who's unbelievable.
She would look great in a starting lineup alongside Jennifer
Gillom.''
</P>
<P>
   For fans, the collapse of the ABL ultimately is likely to result
in a better WNBA product.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury was regarded as one of the WNBA's deepest teams,
having upgraded its bench considerably between its first and second
seasons. But most WNBA teams were not more than six or seven
players deep.
</P>
<P>
   Now there will be some star-quality players coming in, along
with other experienced, talented players without big-name
recognition. It will also mean that some current WNBA players will
have a battle on their hands to keep their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody would argue that their players aren't
comparable in talent to ours,'' Sulka said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 0138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
