<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINAL-S-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER WINS WEEKLY LEAGUE, CLUB MVP HONORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardinals quarterback Jake Plummer's week keeps getting better.
</P>
<P>
   He was picked as the NFL Player of the Week on Tuesday, one day
after he signed a four-year, $29.7 million contract extension to
become the NFL's second-highest-paid player.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer, who threw for 394 yards in Sunday's 19-17 victory over
New Orleans, becomes only the third Cardinals player to get the NFL
Player of the Week honor, joining previous winners Chris Chandler
(1992) and Boomer Esiason (1996).
</P>
<P>
   He also was selected Tuesday as the team's Most Valuable Player
for the 1998 season in voting done by the Phoenix chapter of the
Professional Football Writers of America.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer has guided the team to back-to-back, come-from-behind
victories the past two weeks, two of eight winning rallies he has
directed the past two seasons. He has completed 60 percent of his
passes for 3,463 yards this season, fourth-most in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   Also honored by the Pro Football Writers group was middle
linebacker Ronald McKinnon, who was selected as the team's Most
Courageous Player, an award named for the late Republic
sportswriter Lloyd Herberg, who covered the Cardinals when they
moved to the Valley in 1988 until his death in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Despite not being drafted, McKinnon has been a starter the past
two seasons and has a team-high five interceptions this season,
including three in an October victory over the Chicago Bears. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jealousy not allowed &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin said he is not worried that players
whose contracts are up at the end of the season might resent
Plummer's getting a new deal with another year left on his rookie
pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that it will affect them,'' Tobin said. ``They
should be happy Jake is going to be here for many years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a message that we want to keep the players here. We
plan to keep the football team intact.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Christmas spirit &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive day, there were long lines at the
ticket windows for Sunday's game against the San Diego Chargers at
Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As of early Tuesday afternoon, the team had sold 50,748 tickets,
including 10,000 the past two days.
</P>
<P>
   Those standing in line at the team's Tempe training facility
were given unspiked egg nog.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stadium reverberates noise,'' Tobin said. ``I'd love to
see 70,000 there to make it hard for San Diego.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Giving back &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plummer plans to give about $1 million to charity.
</P>
<P>
   He has set up a scholarship fund at his high school in Boise,
Idaho, to rebuild the physical plant for athletics.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to endow a full scholarship at Arizona State,
where he played four seasons. He and his agent, Leigh Steinberg,
are starting the Plummer Foundation, with money to be given to
abused and ill children and for research to combat Alzheimer's
disease. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``I'm so happy for the guy and proud of him,'' ASU Coach Bruce
Snyder said. ``The lesson I see is that he is consumed and driven
by winning. I don't think he set out to make money or be famous.
It's a byproduct of his focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Short shots &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Frank Sanders, who leads the NFC in receptions
with 81, is trying to become the first Cardinals player to
accomplish that feat since J.T. Smith in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety Tommy Bennett was limping noticeably Tuesday
because of a sprained ankle, but Tobin expects him to start Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin won't know the availability of backup cornerback Tommy
Knight (broken hand) until later in the week. ``We'll have to see
what the cast is and how limiting it is,'' Tobin said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
