<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE DEFENSE DOMINATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It will take time for most of Los Angeles to
forget what happened to Cal State Northridge against UCLA during
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of time. Which means absolutely nothing to the Matadors
now.
</P>
<P>
   More imperative was how quickly CSUN forgot about what happened
at Pauley Pavilion and got on with its season, which continued with
a defensive gem against James Madison.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps their best defensive effort of the season, the
Matadors rolled to a 77-64 home win Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a good way to come back from the UCLA game, and
that's what our coaches were looking at,'' CSUN coach Bobby
Braswell said. ``They wanted to see how we would respond. They came
out and really defended, which is what we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN didn't do it by creating turnovers off its pressure
defense, but rather by shutting down any option the Dukes had
offensively.
</P>
<P>
   James Madison (6-4) entered the game shooting 49 percent from
the field. But a tenacious CSUN defense, something missing in the
17-point loss to UCLA, held the Dukes to a woeful 31 percent. They
made 4 of 25 shots from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two practices all we did was stress our defense,
getting back,'' CSUN guard Jason Crowe. ``We tried to stress to get
back in transition. The only points they were getting were on
drives, so we knew if we could contain their drives with a little
zone we could shut them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, CSUN's offense was efficient for most the night, and
it was again led by sophomore center Brian Heinle. He was 4 of 5 on
3-pointers and scored a game-high 19 points while Derrick Higgins
added 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence right now. I know the ball is going in,''
Heinle said. ``With Rico (Harris) out, we have to pick up the
scoring a little bit and I feel I can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   There was added significance to the win.
</P>
<P>
   It ended CSUN's two-game losing streak and also ensured the
Matadors (7-4) of entering the Big Sky Conference with a winning
record.
</P>
<P>
   With NAIA Lewis-Clark State as the remaining tune-up to the
Jan.2 league opener at Northern Arizona, the Matadors should enter
the new year with eight wins for the first time since 1988 turned
into 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost two games in a row and didn't want that to become a
big issue, which is why it was important for us to win this game,''
Braswell said. ``This was a system win for us. It means our guys
stuck to our system, believed in it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fallout from the UCLA loss, Braswell didn't resort to a
screaming, tirade-infested practice following the Bruins loss.
Instead, he made the Matadors endure a more grueling endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   They watched the game film in which the Bruins shot 65 percent
from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Painful, but effective.
</P>
<P>
   Less than seven minutes in against James Madison, the Matadors
had a double-digit lead.
</P>
<P>
   Heinle then hit a 3-pointer at the 9:32 mark to trigger a 9-0
run, which featured easy lay-ins in transition and on backdoor
cuts, to put CSUN ahead 29-17. The Dukes never got closer than
eight points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells you they have a lot of pride,'' Braswell said.
``That's part of building a program, having guys that have attitude
where losing is not acceptable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 0154EST &QL; 
