<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3519 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     12-23 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABL'S GRASS-ROOTS BRAND OF BALL DIES ON VINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Before delving into the inevitable dollars and cents
issues like operating costs, TV rights and marketing _ all key
issues that the pioneer American Basketball League could not
successfully address _ it seems appropriate to offer a moment of
silence.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle lost a friend Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle lost a good-faith, feel-good, hearts-in-the-right-place
enterprise called women's professional basketball _ grass-roots
style.
</P>
<P>
   That's a heavy blow, especially in these days of locked out,
overpaid, ego-driven, Age of Entitlement professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA and its players are fighting over $2 billion in annual
profits. They won't take the court.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL, with its perhaps too idealistic model for success, is
out of business.
</P>
<P>
   The Reign closed its doors with the rest of the league. Two and
a third seasons are on the books. And the books are closed.
</P>
<P>
   So much was accomplished in the promotion of the women's game.
So much was left to do, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Reign was off to its best start ever _ on and off the court.
</P>
<P>
   But the ABL is out of money, which is why the league plans to
file for bankruptcy. The league is out of time, too, although I
suspect the will to go on was strong, from the commissioner's
office on down to the players.
</P>
<P>
   A women's basketball enterprise founded and promoted as ``A
League of Their Own'' has a power beyond the bottom line, even if
the bottom line is ultimately unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of Jennifer Azzi's 3-pointers in San Jose, there
are empty gyms.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Teresa Edwards' full-court mastery in Philadelphia,
there are unused tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Jennifer Rizzoti's floor-burning dedication in New
England, there is one women's hoops hotbed fresh out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   And here in Seattle, instead of Shalonda Enis' inside muscle or
the freestylin' offense of Kate Starbird, there is disbanded
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Shocked is how Enis, Starbird and Reign general manager Karen
Bryant described their reaction to Tuesday's abrupt announcement by
league commissioner Gary Calvelli.
</P>
<P>
   Shocked, too, will be the fans in Seattle, San Jose, Portland
and New England, where ABL teams were holding their own in
attendance and revenue projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``But on our last road trip East, some of the crowds we saw,
some of the hotels we stayed at, we could see things might be
coming to an end,'' Starbird said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Nashville, Columbus, Colorado, Chicago and Denver were
having a tough time putting fans in the seats.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this was a day that most ABL observers could see coming,
although this sudden midseason shut-down seemed out of character
with the player-friendly, fan-conscious spirit of the league.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, just before the Reign opener, Calvelli indicated
that there was enough sponsor money to make it though 1998-99, at
least.
</P>
<P>
   But the warning signs were all too apparent.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, as the WNBA reeled in most of college basketball's
All-Americans, the ABL knew it was losing the public relations war.
</P>
<P>
   That was nothing, though, compared to the serious, substantive
problems that could not be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   When league officials could not find a suitor at CBS or Fox
willing to give the ABL a national TV package, there was little
hope the ABL could survive on the sheer benevolence of some
good-intentioned sponsors, like Reebok nationally and US West here
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   If the NBA lockout was going to present the ABL with any
additional opportunities for a TV deal, league officials must have
been shocked when nothing materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Even Fox's regional stations refused to bite at broadcasting ABL
games.
</P>
<P>
   In that most important way _ TV coverage _ the ABL could not
approach the muscle of the WNBA, the other women's pro league that
comes courtesy of NBA marketing, money and leverage.
</P>
<P>
   The central debate over the fate of women's pro hoops has
conveniently broken down along ABL vs. WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL had the superior talent and the longer, winter schedule.
It was a players' league, with a salary scale that benefited all
players, not just the superstars, as in the WNBA, where there is
great disparity between the top and bottom players.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA, meanwhile, was assisted by the NBA's marketing skills,
its TV deals with NBC, ABC and ESPN and the fan-friendly NBA
arenas.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA's summertime schedule was seen as a way to expose the
game during a ``down time,'' while the ABL clung to the ideal of
holding its season during the real season _ winter.
</P>
<P>
   But now the ABL model has imploded. Certainly, the easy
assumption will be that the ABL lost and the WNBA is winning.
</P>
<P>
   That is not entirely the correct interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WNBA always thought it was positive for there to be two
leagues as a way to expose women's basketball,'' Mark Pray, WNBA
director of media relations, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a synergy to the arrangement,'' Pray said about
having two leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But that synergy was lost Tuesday. And for everyone who rooted
wildly for the ABL to win its grass-roots battle to raise a women's
league up from the ground, there is no shame in hoping now that the
WNBA continues to grow, shoddy politics or not.
</P>
<P>
   For Seattle, as well as other cities where the ABL has shown the
women's game has fans, it is the next step, the best hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our long, long-term goals have been to have a WNBA team in
every NBA city,'' said Pray, who noted Minnesota and Orlando will
be the WNBA's two expansion franchises this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the nine ABL teams are in NBA cities.
</P>
<P>
   However, the promise of a new league does not diminish the sad
news right here, right now.
</P>
<P>
   Saying goodbye is tough, for sure. Ending this way is terribly
bitter. But the Reign proved women's pro basketball can work in
this market. The Jan. 2 game at KeyArena date, now canceled, was
going to bring out more than 12,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   There is a baseline of support and enthusiasm from regional
sponsors. Something says that the Reign's legacy won't be anything
less than a stupendous effort toward an as yet unfulfilled goal.
</P>
<P>
   Along with somber condolences must come the sincere kudos.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
