<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3530 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      12-23 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WORLD AWASH OF BOWLS, HAWAII TWIN BILL HAS VISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ On the long list of things the world needs, another
college bowl game fits in somewhere between a $13 million baseball
pitcher and House impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   But we're talking big-time college sports here, which is never
about needs and always about wants.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever someplace with a yearning for the spotlight wants to
stage a bowl game, the NCAA wants to comply. And hearing no
objections, the city and the NCAA boom out ``voila!'' and 19 bowl
games appear out of no particular need.
</P>
<P>
   Only one counts for much. The Jan. 4 Fiesta Bowl between
Tennessee and Florida State is the schedule's only item of
substance. The rest are strictly raindrops on roses and whiskers on
kittens.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, these are the holidays, when irrelevant cuteness is
not only allowed, it is virtually mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   So in a culture where too much of a good thing is never enough,
why not a bowl doubleheader?
</P>
<P>
   And why not in the best location?
</P>
<P>
   Or as Husky center Brad Hutt put it Tuesday: ``It's 80 degrees
and sunny here. And 20 degrees and snowing in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merry Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   The sublime logic is overpowering, and a prime reason why his
Husky teammates will play Air Force on Friday in the new Oahu Bowl,
the second game of a twin bill featuring Oregon and Colorado in the
lid-lifting Aloha Bowl. For the $45 tickets, fans also get a
between-games Hawaiian dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks and Huskies were awarded this sandy gig by virtue of
finishing fourth and fifth in the Pac-10 race, respectively. For
the Huskies, who were in the Aloha Bowl last year, Hawaii is
becoming their home for the holidays away from home. And given that
prospects for a higher finish in the next couple of years aren't
high, they might want to consider buying instead of renting.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is not to get too good, because the league's
third-place finisher goes to the Sun Bowl in El Paso, Texas, which
is to Hawaii what the Wicked Witch of the West is to Cindy
Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the fact that the Hawaii bowls' payouts are the
NCAA-required minimum of $750,000 per team, which often doesn't
cover expenses, and thereby draws the least distinguished eligible
teams, the set-up is grand _ beachfront hotels, multiple tourist
draws, perfect weather and Christmas Day sports exclusivity on
national TV, made even better this year by the absence of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   This thing is too good to stay long in the warm backwater. So
guess what is up the sleeves of the bowl folks here (were they to
own clothing with sleeves).
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to host for the Final Four of college football,''
Lenny Klompus, the bowls' chairman and CEO, said Tuesday. But not
exactly like college basketball's Final Four. The Hawaii dreamers
want to bring here the nation's four best college teams for a
doubleheader much like Friday's, only with meaning. But that's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that any championship game has to be in a big
metropolitan area, like the Rose Bowl or Stanford Stadium,''
Klompus said. ``But we think the two semifinal games would work
well in one day on one site.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's twin bill is the initial step toward that goal. The
NCAA was intrigued enough with the doubleheader idea to have
granted the Oahu Bowl a sudden, quick certification last April,
partly to see how the logistics work.
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest problems for Hawaii hosting a big-time event are
the expensive, long flight from the U.S. mainland, and Aloha
Stadium, a baseball/football hybrid that seats only 50,000 and is
mostly minor-league.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the matter of playoffs. College football doesn't
have any. While this year's Bowl Championship Series was purported
to be the closest thing to playoffs, it still isn't right, and
never can be. The BCS debates will only help the slow momentum
toward a playoff. Klompus thinks it's inevitable, and wants to be
ready.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, after Washington and Miami divided the mythical
national championship, Klompus made an informal pitch to the NCAA
for the Hawaii semifinals idea _ bring the four best teams, which
would get free air fare and hotel rooms. The NCAA could keep all TV
revenues as long as it split the gate receipts with the bowl
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch was premature. It's now six years later, and the NCAA
football poohbahs still don't get it. But they will eventually,
because there's too much money to be made _ the siren song of the
NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   The inadequate stadium problem remains. But if Klompus and
others get a some sort of serious nod from the NCAA, it would give
a jump start toward a better facility.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature in January for the first time provided
public funds for underwriting the bowl games. Hawaii's strong ties
with Asia also mean that a bigger stadium wouldn't have to rely
exclusively on hosting North American events.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is a long shot. But when one's toes are dug into white
sand, one's ears are filled with the tinkle of ice cubes, and one's
alabaster skin is pinked by the sun, dreams come easily and often.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Friday will provide the first answer to the question
of how much pigskin and poi can be consumed locally, and
nationally, in one holiday gorge.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
