<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN27-CO     12-23 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Dollar bill an endangered species
 &HT;    For release Dec. 27, 1998.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'd better become accustomed to that new funny-money-looking
$20 bill because it won't be long before you're going to have to
begin grappling with a new $1 coin.
</P>
<P>
   Even though you rarely see or use the Susan B. Anthony dollar
coin, her replacement has been decided _ and, likely, there is an
ulterior motive in issuing a new $1 coin.
</P>
<P>
   It may foretell the demise of the dollar bill.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in 2000 or 2001, it is estimated that the SBA coins,
which have not been minted since 1981, will be out of circulation
and the new coin established to replace it.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the size, shape and content of the coin have been
selected in addition to the person it will honor: a Native-American
woman, Sacagawea, who accompanied Lewis and Clark on their
expedition to the Pacific in 1805.
</P>
<P>
   The really bad news about this coin is that it is going to be
the same size as the SBA. That's all got to do with not having to
retool America's vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   To help avoid the continuing confusion between the quarter and
the alike-sized SBA _ a major reason the SBA was in disfavor _ the
Feds have decided to make the new coin gold-colored, although color
will not be a differentiating factor when jiggling for a coin in
your pocket.
</P>
<P>
   For some time now, the government has been looking at the dollar
bill with the intention of retiring it. It has a life of only about
18 months, is easily counterfeited and is becoming more expensive
to produce. Although there is no existing legislation to do away
with the dollar bill, it is the long-range intention to do exactly
that.
</P>
<P>
   I, for one, will not be happy about this. A recent trip to
England, where the smallest paper currency is the five-pound note
(about $8.25) easily illustrated the discomfort of carrying around
a mess of coins in your pocket, or purse. The British have eight
denominations of coins, from the 2-pound coin down to 1-pence, with
the humongous 2-pence coin being most outrageous in size for its
worth. The 1-pound coin is thick and heavy.
</P>
<P>
   All told, a pocketful of change is weighty.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S. we have six denominations of coins, although one of
them _ the 50 cents piece _ is rarely seen or used. Simply
replacing the SBA with the almost-unpronounceable Sacagawea dollar
coin is one thing; you could shun them as you did the SBA. But to
eliminate the dollar bill and make the Sacagawea the only form of
the dollar starts adding bulk beau coup to our pockets and purses.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great things about U.S. currency is its stability in
look and size, whereas currency elsewhere is a befuddlement of
sizes and colors. Americans do not go much for change, or
international conformity. Recall, please, the effort to switch us
from feet to meters, and of how that failed.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, it appears we will be asked to give up one of our most
trusted forms of exchange, the dollar, the good old buck. Instead,
we will have a coin that feels like a quarter but isn't because
it's colored gold.
</P>
<P>
   I have a hunch the American public will see and use it as it did
the SBA, only when absolutely necessary _ unless the dollar bill is
done away with.
</P>
<P>
   And I also would expect that it is only a matter of time before
Native American organizations begin to agitate about the selection
of Sacagawea for the face of the coin. After all, her place in
history is that she, as Lewis and Clark's intepreter, played a
major role in bringing the white man into the Native American's
western lands, and all that happened as a result.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 0917EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3697 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-PRESIDENT24-COX     12-23 1710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PRESIDENT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush: The potential presidential candidate with all the right
moves
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ While official Washington slogs through the
impeachment process, uncandidate George W. Bush, officially and
unofficially, is doing the kinds of things a fellow might do if he
had a hankering to be president.
</P>
<P>
   None of the moves _ a mix of public actions that make political
advisers happy and private actions that make moms proud _ can be
offered as proof positive that Bush has decided he wants his dad's
old job. But collectively, and combined with his high name
identification and league-leading potential for raising money, they
offer plenty of fuel for political observers prone to pole vaulting
to conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The official moves that could have White House overtones _ or
not _ include Monday's naming of Michael Williams, an African
American, to the Texas Railroad Commission, Bush's recent
appointment of a trusted family friend as chairman of the State
Board of Education, the naming of a Hispanic aide to the Texas
Supreme Court and what could be the first step in a
campaign-related staff shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   On the unofficial, more private side, a proud father in
Davenport, Iowa, is convinced he found evidence of a Bush
presidential campaign on his answering machine this month. For some
reason, the governor of Texas decided it was important for him to
congratulate Steve Grubbs on the birth of his fourth child.
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance baby-kissing, or just a guy who remembers a
mother's lessons about thoughtfulness?
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly,'' Grubbs said, ``it was a courtesy call to the
chairman of the Iowa GOP.''
</P>
<P>
   The baby talk over, the governor and Grubbs _ who said he'd love
to work for a Bush presidential campaign when his term as party
chairman ends this month _ talked some business.
</P>
<P>
   ``You running for president?'' Grubbs said he asked Bush, who
fields the question enough in his waking hours to hear it in his
sleep. ``He said, 'I'm seriously thinking about it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Grubbs, who has seen presidential candidates come and go in
Iowa, said Bush sounds like a comer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't really know what they are getting into
when they start exploring it,'' Grubbs said. ``He knows what it
means to run for president, and he knows what it means to serve as
president. Here is a man who is not going into this thought process
blind. He knows what it is all about, and he hasn't ruled it out.
That says a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Texas, insiders _ who sometimes see what they want
to see _ see a governor getting things aligned for a presidential
race. Bush, who insists no decision has been made, discounts all
the speculation as nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking about it,'' Bush said of the present state of his
potential presidential candidacy. ``I'm thinking about it a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also thinks he has nothing to gain by taking sides in the
current Washington fratricide, an ongoing mudfest that has many
Americans _ yet again _ looking to places like big-state capitals
for the next president.
</P>
<P>
   While one probable GOP White House contender, Steve Forbes,
jumped headfirst into the impeachment fray last week with
pro-impeachment radio ads, Bush declined to talk about what was on
the lips of everyone else in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will see what happens,'' he said in his Capitol office last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid it though he might, presidential politics frequently comes
looking for Bush. If it's not reporters, it's tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope to vote for you in a couple of years,'' the Kesslers of
Olympia, Wash., recently wrote in the visitors book in the
Governor's Reception Room.
</P>
<P>
   ``George, run for president,'' the Enzlers of Woodbridge, Va.,
wrote in the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush,'' wrote the Rowells of Baton Rouge, La., ``you
are very much needed as president of these United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Board of Education
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, while presumably still thinking about whether he
wants to be president, Bush announced his selection of Williams to
replace Carole Keeton Rylander on the three-member Texas Railroad
Commission. Rylander was elected state comptroller last month.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he will run for the seat when it is on the ballot
in 2000, a decision that _ assuming he wins the nomination _
guarantees that Texas Republicans will have a black candidate on
the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   It's a significant move for a GOP governor who made
unprecedented efforts to capture African American votes this year.
Exit polls showed Bush pulled almost one-fourth of the black vote,
unprecedented for a Republican gubernatorial candidate in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said it ``would be inappropriate to suggest that race
played no role'' in his appointment. But so did his ties to the
Bush family. In 1980, Williams and Bush served as co-chairs of
Midland's United Way campaign. In 1990, President George Bush made
Williams assistant secretary of education for civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Bush named family friend Chase Untermeyer as
chairman of the State Board of Education, a panel the governor
believes does not always put the best face on Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The board, including high-profile members of the Christian
Coalition, occasionally sees one-worldism and other forms of
intrusive government lurking in the public schools. Some board
members are leery of school-to-work plans, a program called Goals
2000 and other federally driven programs that critics see as
impinging on local control of schools.
</P>
<P>
   Untermeyer is a card-carrying conservative, but of the
Bush-like, more pragmatic stripe. He first got mixed up in politics
as a state House member from 1977-81.
</P>
<P>
   Under President Bush, he was director of presidential personnel.
In the Reagan administration, he was assistant secretary of the
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Now director of government affairs for Compaq Computer Corp. in
Houston, Untermeyer insists he and the governor have not chatted
about the overlap of the State Board of Education and a race for
president.
</P>
<P>
   He discounts insider talk that his job is to push hard on the
rudder to steer the board toward the middle and away from
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any marching orders like that,'' he said. ``And
I'm not sure how any one person could throw a blanket of silence on
14 very able, energetic people, all of whom have won election in
districts with over a million people in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff, travel and rumors
</P>
<P>
   Other personnel moves that could be interpreted as good state
government or White House-related include the shuffling of State
Insurance Commissioner Elton Bomer to a new senior adviser post in
the governor's office and the appointment of former Bush aide and
former Secretary of State Al Gonzales to the Texas Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy theorists who see a presidential race lurking behind
every Bush move see Bomer winding up as the governor's chief of
staff when, and if, Chief of Staff Joe Allbaugh heads over to get a
White House race on track.
</P>
<P>
   Even faraway job moves have been spun into White House-related
rumors. Earlier this month, Bush insisted he had nothing to do with
Condoleeza Rice's resignation as provost at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, who was a national security adviser to President Bush, has
talked with the younger Bush about those kinds of issues. But
``there was nothing formal,'' she said. There are no immediate
plans for her to join a Bush campaign, Rice said, but she did not
rule out the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's trip last month to Israel also pumped up the presidential
talk and was billed by some as a governor in search of instant
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   On the home front, Bush entertained a guest last week whose name
also carries potential presidential race connections. Brad Freeman,
a Los Angeles investment banker and longtime Bush friend, spent the
night of Dec. 16 at the Governor's Mansion. Though not the subject
of a news release, Freeman's visit was not exactly maintained as a
state secret. He was there the night of Bush's annual holiday party
for the press.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Freeman was host of a Los Angeles lunch that raised
more than $500,000 for Bush, showing off a talent that could come
in handy for a guy running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Freeman's visit had any kind of political
overtones, Bush replied, ``that's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Some kind of signal
</P>
<P>
   Bush insists all the speculation, tea-leaf reading and
old-fashioned rumormongering amount to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The decision-making process is under way, but the governor says
he has reached no conclusion. Now working toward next month's
inaugural and state of the state speeches that will draw national
attention, Bush says he knows he will have to give some kind of
signal soon, perhaps as early as February, as to whether he wants
to follow his dad in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The most common signal is the exploratory committee, set up,
ostensibly, to explore. History is short on folks who formed an
exploratory committee, explored and then reported finding little
interest in candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is running,'' CBS's Dan Rather said matter-of-factly in a
recent column. ``He may get knocked out along the way, or he may
yet decide to pull out. But his campaign is already formed,
well-financed and moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, there is no such thing as the George W. Bush for
President Committee. His gubernatorial re-election campaign has
morphed into an inaugural committee, raising money and making plans
for the Jan. 19 event.
</P>
<P>
   Bush discounts comments like Rather's as uninformed patter from
folks who can't imagine there is a big-state governor who might not
want to be a big-nation president.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to understand about me: If I choose not to run for
president, I won't think anything less of myself,'' he said last
month. ``I'm comfortable with who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, there is at least one politically connected dad willing
to do anything to help make Bush comfortable with the concept of
life in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should have named him Jared Bush Grubbs,'' Grubbs said
of his son, Jared Reagan Grubbs.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
