A3699 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-PIGS24-COX     12-23 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PIGS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet pigs: Your kind of web site has arrived
 &HT;    By Howie Paul Hartnett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's got a pig picture gallery. It's got
Paul Thompson's views on the benefits of playing music for pigs.
It's even got a little section on pig humor.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to www.pigfarmer.com.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-month-old site was set up by Thompson's daughter and
son-in-law in response to the Stuart, Fla. pig farmer's continuing
problems with his golf community neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something that everybody involved thought we should
do,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Club officials have complained to the county and Martin
County's sheriff's office several times that the music and stench
emanating from the Thompson homestead is disrupting business.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the Club and a resident filed suit against Thompson
and fellow swine farmer Thomas Rossano, claiming the country music
the two play for their pigs was too loud under the county's new
noise ordinance. County commissioners muffled loud activities in
October, but the ordinance exempts farms.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rossano has been ordered by Judge Larry Schack to turn
down his music, and Florida Club attorneys expect to bring Thompson
to trial in June.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Thompson is using his website to solicit
information about playing music for animals and garner support. So
far, he's received overwhelming amounts of both.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a person in this country that we've talked to in
the past year that didn't have the same comment, `But you were
there first,' '' Thompson said. ``(The Florida Club) has just done
all the underhanded stuff they can to get me out.''
</P>
<P>
   The site isn't just getting raves from supporters. It's also
gotten some official kudos. America Online spotlighted the site in
November and ranked it No. 2 among the five websites reviewed each
month.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's lawyer doesn't see anything wrong with the site. In
fact, Stuart attorney Lance Richard wants to see some improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to him about posting some of the information about
the litigation,'' Richard said. ``He's interested in gathering
information from other people in similar situations.''
</P>
<P>
   A few have been close, but not exactly the same, Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a guy who said, `My brother has a horse farm and he
plays music for his horses,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But no other musically inclined swine have stepped forward yet.
It's not because Thompson hasn't been asking.
</P>
<P>
   Since being sued, Thompson has talked to newspaper and
television reporters in 47 states. He also has been on radio
programs in England and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   His message is simple: When you give up your rights, you give up
your freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are using our civil court system and out
taxpayers' money to sue me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Howie Paul Hartnett writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
