<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3701 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-BANISHEDBABIE     12-23 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-BANISHEDBABIES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One of Ireland's 'Banished babies' on search of his life
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Between 1949 and 1973, at least 2,200
babies born to unwed mothers are known to have been spirited out of
Ireland and adopted to families in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Many birth records were altered and many intentionally
misplaced. Church and state acknowledge they conspired to keep the
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that to have a child out of wedlock in
Catholic Ireland back in the '50s was the most heinous thing you
could do,'' says Bill Neylon. ``It was considered shameful and
despicable. It was a mortal sin in the eyes of the government as
well as the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Neylon, a 44-year-old West Palm Beach physical trainer, was one
of the 2,200 who would become known as the ``banished babies'' of
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up with an Irish-American family in Chicago. He was told
his birth parents had died, and he had been adopted out of an
orphanage in Roscrea, Tipperary.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can try to stuff anything they want under the carpet, but
an adopted child grows up with questions,'' Neylon says. ``We don't
want to tear open anybody's family. We just want to know. I had a
chapter of my life missing, and I had a burning desire to learn
about my heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was 20, that desire led Neylon to southern Ireland and
the convent at Sean Ross Abbey where he had been told his life
began. A nun met him at the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is the birthing room,'' she told him. ``Here is the
chapel. This is where your mother had you baptized when you were
five days old.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean,'' he asked, ``my mother was alive?''
</P>
<P>
   The nun bristled and quickly recanted. She said Neylon's mother
had probably died after his baptism, or perhaps moved to Australia.
Even if she were alive, there was no way she could ever be found,
he was assured.
</P>
<P>
   For 23 years, Neylon grudgingly accepted that part of himself
might forever remain a mystery. Then last year he was training two
clients from Dublin at the gym where he works on Palm Beach Lakes
Boulevard. They encouraged him to search again, and within two
months he had Kevin Cooney on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Cooney, 30, with 18 other volunteers, works for the Adopted
Peoples' Association of Ireland, a Dublin group that seeks to
reunite birth mothers with their lost children. The movement for a
national reconciliation was energized by Mike Milotte, a reporter
with the Irish TV network, who two years ago wrote Banished Babies:
The Secret History of Ireland's Baby Export Business.
</P>
<P>
   Cooney, a secretary to an Irish Parliament member, has assisted
in some 50 reunions between adopted Americans and their natural
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assume everything you've been told about your adoption to be a
lie,'' Cooney told Neylon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to find my mother to tell her I love her,'' Neylon told
him. ``I want to tell her I turned out all right. I want to tell
her that I know it was very difficult for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Neylon was instructed to request from the Irish government a
copy of his birth certificate, a document he had been told did not
exist. He mailed off $15 and a month later, a paper written in
English and Irish was delivered to his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe what it said. `Mother: Nora Fitzpatrick.'
Until then, she had been a figment _ an abstraction. Suddenly she
had a name. Nora.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooney researched records this spring and found eight Nora
Fitzpatricks who might have been Neylon's mother. The most likely
was in Cahirciveen, Kerry, a town of 1,200 on the southwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   Neylon carried on research himself in West Palm Beach. He
learned that a musical duo from Cahirciveen was playing at O'Shea's
Pub on Clematis Street. After a set, Neylon approached one of the
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I about knocked him off his trolley when I asked him about
Cahirciveen,'' he said. ``It's such a little place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, you've got a Kerry man's face,'' the musician told him.
``To find your family, you need to look up Mike the Yank.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike the Yank is Michael Murphy, the county's genealogist who
lived 20 years in the United States before retiring to Ireland.
Cooney contacted Murphy, who immediately identified ``Paddy Fitz''
as the head of the Fitzpatrick family in Cahirciveen. Patrick
Fitzpatrick was a 67-year-old master carpenter who had lived a
dozen years in the Bronx. He was Nora's oldest brother.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Neylon flew to Ireland, and with Cooney and Mike the
Yank, knocked on Paddy Fitz's door.
</P>
<P>
   What was the name on the birth certificate, Fitzpatrick wanted
to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``William Joseph Mary Fitzpatrick,'' Neylon told him.
</P>
<P>
   It was a critical point of detail. In 1954, all Irish babies
born in convents were given ``Mary'' as a middle name in honor of
the blessed virgin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some time during the night,'' said Cooney, ``the penny
dropped. We won them over.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick agreed to call Nora but worried about how she would
take the news. She was living in England and consumed in sorrow,
mourning her husband who died six weeks before.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Paddy handed me the phone, I could hardly talk,'' Neylon
said. ``I said, `Hello, Nora.' She said, `Hello, son.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Fitzpatricks then took Neylon to his grandparents' graves
and to the small farmhouse where his mother grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sensed this was the highest compliment they could pay me,''
Neylon said.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Neylon flew to England and met Nora at the airport
gate. He took her a single red rose, and she, a slight woman,
barely 5-foot-3, held a handwritten sign with his name.
</P>
<P>
   She was 18 when she last saw him, 16 when he was born. Nora and
Neylon's father, who died many years ago, went separate ways long
before adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were screaming when the nun came to take you out of my
arms,'' she told him. ``They brought me into a room with two
priests and a solicitor. I signed my name three times and that was
it. You were gone. You had such beautiful curls.''
</P>
<P>
   Nora had believed her son had been killed in the Vietnam War, as
``so many American boys were.''
</P>
<P>
   Letters will be exchanged regularly until their next visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is all about God's impeccable timing,'' Neylon
said. ``He brought me into Nora's life after she'd lost her
husband. All the Masses she had said for him _ this was God's
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Moffett writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
