<HEADER>
A3703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MYLAN-LAWSUIT24-COX     12-23 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYLAN-LAWSUIT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Patients prescribed lorazepam take Mylan Labs to court over
prescription costs
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When she went to the drug store last spring for
her monthly $30 prescription, Barbara Gamsu was ``horrified'' to
learn the price had more than tripled. Her generic anti-anxiety
medication, lorazepam, now cost $96.85.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people all knew me at the drug store, so I had a fit right
there at the counter,'' Gamsu recalled Tuesday. ``'What the heck is
going on here?!' This was a generic drug.''
</P>
<P>
   The indignation of Gamsu and countless other lorazepam customers
will surface in court through lawsuits filed by the U.S. Federal
Trade Commission and 10 state attorneys general, including Ohio's.
Ohio is seeking to recoup $7 million in Medicaid expenses and
unspecified millions more on behalf of individual consumers and
health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The separate suits allege price-fixing by lorazepam's
manufacturer, Mylan Laboratories of Pittsburgh, its supplier and
two distributors. They are based on a nine-month FTC investigation
that charges Mylan forced competitors out of the market by reaching
agreements with the other companies that gave Mylan the only
reliable sources of the active ingredients for lorazepam and
clorazepate, another anti-anxiety drug.
</P>
<P>
   Mylan officials have denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nerve of that company,'' said Gamsu, a Medicare
beneficiary in Clayton who's on disability with Crohn's disease, an
intestinal disorder. She said she spends $4,000 a year
out-of-pocket on prescription drugs, and although it hurts her
pocketbook, ``I'm lucky. There are so many people that obviously
had to go off of it.''
</P>
<P>
   While state and federal government sources said the price
increases were more than 2,000 percent, a local pharmacist and
health plan administrator put the actual cost to consumers in the
500-600 percent range. Even so, the increase caused an aberrational
hike of 0.2 percent last May in the Producer Price Index, a federal
tool for measuring inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a pharmacist have to become a commodities broker,
buying large supplies before the price goes higher,'' said Rich
Gunza, the Dayton executive director of Anthem Blue Cross and Blue
Shield.
</P>
<P>
   Lorazepam probably was underpriced before the increase,
Kettering pharmacist Terrell Mundhenk said, ``but going up 500
percent instantly? That's just not right.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the generic now costs more than 80 percent as much as
the brand name, Ativan, which accounts for nearly 17 million U.S.
prescriptions a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``And generic manufacturers aren't incurring research costs or
clinical trials or anything else that the brand name incurs,''
Gunza said. ``The purpose of a generic drug is to provide high
quality without the expenses that go into marketing a new drug. If
generic houses are getting into the mind-set that they can charge
almost as much as brand names, that's a big problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Other anti-anxiety drugs are available as generics, but Mundhenk
said doctors often prefer lorazepam because it leaves the
bloodstream after 4-6 hours, as opposed to 12-24 hours for Valium
and others. Gamsu said she can take it only as needed without any
feelings of withdrawal on other days.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers of the drugs won't be able to contact the state about
restitution until after the lawsuit is decided or settled, said
spokesman Chris Davey for attorney general Betty Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our effort is to get the money back,'' Davey said, ``and in
doing so, attempt to prevent these and other companies from doing
these things in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
