<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3705 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALLBIZ-INTERNET24-C     12-23 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLBIZ-INTERNET24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Logging on to future can be stressful
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner and Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For small businesses, the Internet is a lot like
stepping up to the blackjack table in Vegas. You place your bet,
cross your fingers and take your chances.
</P>
<P>
   Many entrepreneurs figure they need to be on the Internet
because everyone is telling them so. But going online isn't cheap,
and the payoffs often are unclear at best.
</P>
<P>
   So why even bother?
</P>
<P>
   With global electronic commerce expected to top $220 billion and
as the percentage of people who will buy and sell goods online
grows to about 40 percent by 2001, the Internet has become the
ultimate shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet's like a 24-hour-a-day, seven-day-a-week retail
store,'' said Larry Bohn, chief executive of net.Genesis, a
Cambridge, Mass., firm that helps companies evaluate their Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   But to cash in, you've got to log on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest mistake any small business can make is to think
this thing will go away and ignore it,'' says Jeffrey Kagan, an
Atlanta-based telecommunications analyst. ``The old way of doing
business won't go away. But this new channel _ the Internet and
electronic commerce _ is going to be as important for delivering
products to the marketplace as the invention of the automobile was
100 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last year alone, small-business owners have embraced the
Internet in a big way. The U.S. Small Business Administration
estimates that millions of small-business owners _ ranging from
one-person shops to home-based businesses _ are online.
</P>
<P>
   But most aren't taking full advantage of the Internet, largely
because they're confused about how it works.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it's fear and misunderstanding and not knowing how to
go about it,'' says Diane Gannon, Washington-based manager of the
SBA's Internet Services division.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Chamber of Commerce/IBM study of 1,000 companies found
that firms using the Internet have been on it less than two years.
Most were using it for e-mail or research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they're taking small steps onto the Net,'' says
Brian Meincke, director of small- and medium-business development
for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   One of the study's biggest surprises, Meincke said, was that
most small-business owners relied on family or friends for
information on technology. He also noted that many small businesses
haven't made provisions for technology in their business plan.
</P>
<P>
   Dun &AMP; Bradstreet's study for Enterprise Magazine, a publication
for small-business owners, had similar findings: Younger companies
were more likely to use the Internet, and companies less than a
year old were more likely to have Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost 1999, and I'm seriously amazed that there are
businesses who aren't on the Internet,'' said Entrepreneur
editorial director Rieva Lesonsky. Lesonsky says she repeatedly
encounters small-business owners who say they see no value in being
on the Internet. She recently chastised the holdouts in a column in
the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are serious about growing the business, you cannot do
it unless you have a Net presence, whether that's for e-commerce or
just using it for sales and advertising and marketing,'' Lesonsky
said.
</P>
<P>
   Danger for holdouts
</P>
<P>
   For many Internet holdouts like Frank Momodu, it's simply a
question of time. ``I haven't been able to find the time to find
out how it would exactly benefit my business yet,'' said Momodu,
owner of Lennox Limousine in Atlanta. But Momodu and others may not
be able to avoid it much longer.
</P>
<P>
   The Web is fast becoming as indispensable as the telephone, and
small businesses working without a Net run the risk of losing
clients or market share to Web-savvy competitors.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you want to do business with the federal
government in the future, for instance, you're likely going to have
to plead your case and place your bids for contracts online.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to put RFPs (request for proposal) online.
Those are actual bids,'' said Gannon at SBA, which gets about 3
million weekly hits on its Web site. The SBA also has an online
procurement network called PRO-NET.
</P>
<P>
   Companies ranging from BellSouth to IBM to American Express and
Online Office Supplies Co. are going after small firms with
offerings aimed at making their introduction to the Internet smooth
and trauma-free.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth alone estimates 260,000 of its small-business
customers will go online before the close of this year. It offers
software and Web sites to help customers build their own Web sites.
A whole subculture of Internet consultants has sprung up, offering
workshops promising to make the online venture a profitable one.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, small-business owners can use the Internet to
``research a competitor, do statistical analysis, find out how
(customers) are using your services and whether you have the
products or services customers need,'' Gannon said. ``And it's
instant feedback.''
</P>
<P>
   But is the Internet gold rush for everyone? And how realistic
are small-business owners?
</P>
<P>
   For entrepreneurs like Cathy Cunningham Hays and John Landstrom,
the Net is a natural, according to experts. The two metro Atlanta
business owners offer hard-to-find items. Cunningham Hays has a
gourmet snack food company. Landstrom sells BMW motorcycles. Both
have gotten online inquiries from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a big company. You just have to have
something that specialized and of value,'' Bohn of net.Genesis
said. ``The Internet gives you a way to get to a much, much wider
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempering expectations
</P>
<P>
   But Internet and small-business experts caution those who
venture online shouldn't expect sales to skyrocket overnight, nor
should they look at the Internet as the cure-all for existing
business problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their thought about getting business on the Internet is a lot
like Alice in Wonderland,'' said Jerry Chautin, who counsels small
business online as a volunteer with the Atlanta chapter of Service
Corps of Retired Executives. ``They think they can put a Web page
up there and business will come. It doesn't work like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chautin cited the popular Amazon.com to make his case.
``Amazon.com is a glaring example of getting a lot of traffic and
not making a profit,'' he said. ``They're spending all of their
revenues to get traffic to their Web site. I think a Web site is
important to give them (small businesses) credibility in today's
world. But if they don't have more traditional ways of generating
business, they're not going to make it. If they're in retail, they
need to open a store. If they're a service business, they have to
go out and bang on the door to get sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Large corporate counterparts can write off Internet losses and
move on. When companies such as Macy's or Barnes and Noble go
online, their sheer size enables them to take risks most small
businesses can't afford. Losing $10,000 on an Internet venture
won't break Federated Department Stores, but it could bankrupt many
small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses can still use the Web to establish credibility
and showcase their goods and services. The Web can give a lot, but
you can also lose a lot. The Internet itself probably won't make
you rich, but it might be able to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big fallacy if you think you're going to make all this
money overnight by having a Web site. It doesn't work that way,''
says Debra Dixon-Stringer, a Decatur-based computer and Internet
consultant who has worked with hundreds of small businesses in the
last four years helping them design Web pages and market their
business on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Joyner and Frances Katz write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
