<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes `dedicated' to Y2K preparations
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov.-elect Roy Barnes has already tackled what may be
his administration's biggest problem, Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who will be inaugurated Jan. 11, discussed the
Millennium Bug recently at his transition office in the state
capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appropriated $152 million last year,'' Barnes said, noting
there's ``a request for a little over $200 million additional
money'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm dedicated to making sure that there are sufficient
resources allocated for this problem,'' Barnes added. Y2K ``will be
the highest single figure in the supplemental budget'' that Barnes
will send to the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here,'' Barnes said, ``the first person I met with
was'' Michael Hale, Georgia's chief information officer and project
manager for Y2K. ``I spent about half a day with him. He's done a
grading system and a time line for every department, so I can keep
up with where we are. And I've reviewed every department.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said someone from his transition office talks to Hale
every day.
</P>
<P>
   Hale said, in a November interview, the state's mission-critical
systems should be compliant March 31.
</P>
<P>
   But it's evident that much needs to be done. The state's
Department of Administrative Services, for instance, maintains 191
different computer software programs, 89 of which are mission
critical. Just 30 were compliant in early November.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Barnes said he asks department heads is, ```Are you
going to make your Y2K deadline?' They tell me, `Yes.' I tell them,
`Listen, there will be repercussions in your job if you don't make
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Barnes followed up with a memo to state department
heads, reiterating the state's ``Y2K efforts have entered a
critical phase requiring our immediate and constant attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The state doesn't as yet have a contingency plan for
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we're talking about now and trying to get
full information about what other states are doing and what
coordination exists between the federal and state governments. We
generally have a contingency plan for every emergency. Y2K and what
it might affect are what we're reviewing now,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, this is a problem. I can't tell you if it's overblown. I
can tell you this: We're going to plan and do whatever is necessary
_ considering worst-case scenarios.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that worries Barnes is lack of public awareness and
the potential for the public to overreact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to raise consciousness about this problem,''
he said. ``It's like (Donald) Ratajczak (of the Georgia State
Economic Forecasting Unit) says, 'If you understand the importance
of the problem, you'll probably make whatever efforts are necessary
to address it. But if you're not cognizant of the problem, that may
be the biggest problem.'''
</P>
<P>
   To check the state's the progress, go to Georgia's Y2K Web site
(http://www.year2000.state.ga.us).
</P>
<P>
   F
</P>
<P>
   P
</P>
<P>
   O
</P>
<P>
   FWednesday, Dec. 23, 1998 HHHHH The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
