</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLBIZ-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Employee leasing gains popularity
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ McNairs Appliance Co.'s 35 workers wear uniforms
emblazoned with the McNairs name and drive McNairs trucks as they
deliver new washers and refrigerators to homes throughout Central
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But technically, they get their benefits _ and paychecks _ from
someone else.
</P>
<P>
   That's because 59-year-old McNairs is part of one of the latest
trends in small-business management _ employee leasing.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the way large corporations are choosing to rid
themselves of non-core parts of their business, small businesses
such as McNairs are increasingly turning to outside companies for
human resources services that can also help them compete for
workers.
</P>
<P>
   For the past six years, McNairs employees have been co-employed
by the Austin appliance company and by Administaff Inc., a
so-called Professional Employer Organization, based near Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Fred McNair, president of McNairs, also is technically a leased
employee. He said employee leasing has unburdened him of keeping up
with federal and state regulations, eliminated the yearly chore of
rebidding his company's medical and workers' compensation insurance
and allowed McNairs to offer better benefits than he could
previously. Through McNairs relationship with Administaff, the
appliance company also can tap into a plethora of human resources
services _ ranging from criminal background checks to employee
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even large corporations are farming out parts of their
businesses that didn't make sense for them to do. This is basically
the same thing,'' McNair said. ``Basically, I'm farming out a human
resources department and payroll department.''
</P>
<P>
   Through Administaff, which has an agreement with Aetna U.S.
Healthcare, McNairs offers its employees a full range of medical
plans, as well as vision and dental care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't cost me less, but it's much better insurance
than we had before, much more comprehensive,'' McNair said.
Depending on what they need, however, some small-business owners
may not find it advantageous to pay the extra fee or may dislike
how it changes parts of the employee relationship.
</P>
<P>
   At McNairs, for example, Administaff's fee runs roughly 3
percent of payroll, or $1,800 on its $60,000 biweekly payroll. That
doesn't include what the appliance company also pays for health
insurance, workers compensation insurance and payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman DeBusk, owner of DeBusk Electric Co. in Austin, said he
looked into employee leasing a year ago and decided it wasn't for
him. He said he was concerned about his potential liability as a
licensed commercial electrical contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave up quite a bit of control,'' he said. ``I didn't like
it. They didn't offer enough benefits to change. I like owning and
controlling my own company entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   Employee leasing companies can also require clients to adhere
strictly to employment laws. At McNairs, for example, Administaff
requires the appliance company to use its employment application
forms and makes employees provide proof of citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has 189 companies that are licensed to offer staff
leasing. Along with Adminstaff, several companies _ including some
based in other states _ do business in Austin. Texas began
licensing the companies in September 1993, becoming the second
state to do so, because of complaints about the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Ketchum, a spokesman for the Texas Department of Licensing
and Regulation, said the agency handled about 50 complaints on
about staff leasing companies last year. He said most related to
unlicensed companies and insurance complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has the potential for serious growth.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Small Business Administration estimates there are more
than 6 million small companies with fewer than 500 employees. Of
that group, only 180,000 companies _ less than 3 percent _ lease
their employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically at the stage where it has reached a critical
mass, and it's really starting to proliferate,'' said Paul Sarvadi,
chief executive of Administaff.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Tyson writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. Send information to her at P.O. Box 670, Austin, 78767 or by
e-mail at ktyson(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
