<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All I want for Christmas is . . .
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I had a great time in the supermarket
the other day. Waiting for my husband to pick up an item, I parked
our basket in front of a display of dolls. Each of the little
creatures _ identical except for colors of clothes and skin _
represented a 3-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   To check out the cuddle factor, I poked one through the
cellophane of the box. To my delight, she spoke. Actually, she
commanded: ``Touch my foot.'' When I obeyed, she directed me to
touch other appendages. I probably would still be poking her body
parts had my husband not returned and dragged me into the checkout
line.
</P>
<P>
   How different today's dolls are from the one I knew as a child.
I speak literally, for, from my earliest memory, I had one doll. I
played house with her, but ours was a love-hate relationship.
</P>
<P>
   First, you must picture this doll, whom I secretly called ``Miz
Pellum.'' She was indeed a ``baby'' doll, for, with a
synthetic-paste body molded in a rigid seated position, she was
designed to represent an infant. Her hair was a mass of brown curls
_ painted on in circular swirls. Her face was also painted on. She
had no movable eyes (like the doll of the girl next door), no open
lips, no pearly teeth peeking forth to form a smile.
</P>
<P>
   No. Miz Pellum's facial expression was as placid and
expressionless as a figure of Buddha. Indeed, had I known such a
personage existed, I might have named my doll after him. But I
didn't. I did, however, know a Miz Pellum.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever my grandmother needed more eggs than our chickens
produced, she went to visit Miz Pellum. The plump, petite white
woman raised ducks and chickens on the bank next to a drainage
stream. She always sat just inside her screen door. Though blind,
she could identify people by their steps. Without rising, she would
greet my grandmother by name and invite us into her house.
</P>
<P>
   After Grandma Annie explained what we had come for, Miz Pellum
would count out the eggs from a bowl in the middle of the kitchen
table and accept the money. Transaction completed, she would return
to her seat. All the while, her facial expression remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   So, my expressionless doll, fused in a seated position, became
Miz Pellum. Studies have been done on the effects of black kids
playing with white dolls, but I don't think I suffered any
permanent damage. I simply longed for a soft doll that would yield
to my touch or one that cried when patted on the back or one whose
eyes moved or that had a rubber body I could bathe.
</P>
<P>
   So, each year, I wished for a new doll, pointing out my choices
in the Sears Christmas catalog every November. And every December,
I fought reality with denial as I heard the treadle of the sewing
machine pumping away after I had gone to bed. Mama would be sewing
little garments: a new dress, underwear and a bonnet for Miz
Pellum. Sometime before Christmas Eve, the old clothes would be
washed and ironed and put into a shoebox. As if delivered by Santa,
Miz Pellum would be dressed in the new outfit and placed under the
Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   There would be other gifts: skates one year, a bicycle another,
puzzles and books. But always and forever pink, Miz Pellum reigned
over the lot, impassively staring ahead. The only permanent trauma
to my psyche I can attribute to her presence is a fascination with
dolls. I bought them for my daughter long after she became an
adult.
</P>
<P>
   Watching antiques experts assess the value of old toys on PBS,
I've wondered how much Miz Pellum would be worth today had I kept
her. I will never know. One summer day, when I was 10 or 11, my
younger cousin came to visit. I let her play outside with Miz
Pellum. When a sudden shower came up, my cousin ran inside and left
my doll outside in the rain. I found her hours later, her fat,
little plastic body puckered and blistered, her stolid face
unrecognizable. I said I didn't care.
</P>
<P>
   That night, I went to bed and cried.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson is a columnist for The Palm Beach Post, West
Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
