<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kenneth Starr should've investigated further
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If Clinton had lied about eating Mexican food,
would it be perjury?
</P>
<P>
   That's the philosophical tortilla my Bubbaland pea brain has
been chewing on ever since I saw a funny new T-shirt that's selling
like fajitas here.
</P>
<P>
   The tongue-in-cheek shirt, available at Chuy's restaurants in
Austin and around the state, shows a cartoon of the president
wagging his finger. In the bubble, the president is saying, ``I did
not have Tex-Mex with that woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuy's, with restaurants in Austin, Dallas, Arlington, Houston
and San Antonio, has sold right at 1,000 of these T-shirts in about
a week.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's just suppose for argument's sake that the statement on
the T-shirt is bull tweedle, and that the president did indeed
have, you know, just Tex-Mexual relations with that woman.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current thinking in the House of Representatives,
would the president lying under oath about having Tex-Mex with that
woman amount to perjury? Would it be grounds for impeachment?
</P>
<P>
   Sure it would, since Mexican food is as important as sex. And I
know that's true, from looking at some of the lard behinds on
y'all.
</P>
<P>
   So if you can bust Clinton for lying about sex, surely you could
bust him for lying about Tex- Mex, right?
</P>
<P>
   I can hear you Republicans whining now. You're saying, ``Kelso,
you're a bowl of queso short of a Number One Dinner. That Tex -Mex
question is stupid. Kenneth Starr wouldn't ask the president if he
had Tex-Mex with that woman, or anybody else, because it doesn't
make any difference.''
</P>
<P>
   You're telling me Tex-Mex isn't as important as sex? What part
of Nuevo Yorko did you just move here from?
</P>
<P>
   So if Kenneth Starr can badger the president about his sex life,
why shouldn't he bother him about lunch?
</P>
<P>
   You tell me. Which is more critical to the future of this
Republic? Hanky panky or a good plate of migas?
</P>
<P>
   I say it's a two-way tie for first place. A dead heat. Although
you could make the case that Tex-Mex is easier to deal with than
sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our enchiladas never get a headache,'' said Mike Young, one of
Chuy's owners. And after you're finished with a tamale, it doesn't
get half of everything, either.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton detractors are constantly pointing out that it doesn't
matter what the president was lying about. What matters, they
argue, is that he lied under oath _ period. End of story.
</P>
<P>
   Bingo. My point exactly. So I can imagine Starr going after
Clinton for lying about Tex-Mex, since sex and Tex-Mex share many
similarities:
</P>
<P>
   You never hear anybody complaining about getting too much of
either.
</P>
<P>
   After you get started, they both take about half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Both can earn an X rating based on amount of heat.
</P>
<P>
   It's best if neither is served overly greasy.
</P>
<P>
   Either goes well with a margarita. But if you have more than
three, it'll screw up your appetite.
</P>
<P>
   Having too much of either can make you feel guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you just have to go back for seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, you figure you ought to branch out and try
another place. But you'll get better service if you stick to the
same establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, sitting there waiting for it to show up at your table
is better than when it actually gets there.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
