<HEADER>
A3713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUNG-TRANSPLANT24-COX     12-23 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNG-TRANSPLANT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life sweet after lungtransplant: `I like ordinary'
 &HT;    By Shannon Colavecchio
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Wake up. Take a long, deep breath. Go to
work. Come home. Spend time with wife and dogs. Fall asleep with
quiet, easy breaths. Repeat every day for eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Dull? Monotonous? Not if you're a 28-year-old still getting used
to two new lungs. Not if you're breathing easily for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   Not if you're Leland Herring.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't like the ordinary patterns of life,''
said Herring as he briskly walked the grounds of Wellington
Christian School, where, at 5-feet-4 and 112 pounds (``Enough not
to blow away in strong winds!''), he has gone from being ``The
World's Smallest Gym Teacher'' to ``The World's Smallest Chapel
Coordinator.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like ordinary, because I've never had it this way before. It
was always one chaotic moment to the next chaotic moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I wake up, I go to work, I come home. It's nice.''
</P>
<P>
   It's nice because before the doctors at Duke University Medical
Center gave him the lungs of a 13-year-old shooting victim on April
26, Herring's days centered around hourlong ``therapies.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice a day, every day without fail, ever since he could
remember, Leland Herring would lie down with his feet elevated
while someone vibrated his chest until he could cough up the mucous
and phlegm that kept him from breathing normally _ trademarks of
the cystic fibrosis he inherited from his parents, both symptomless
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our life before,'' says 23-year-old Melissa Herring,
who has been pounding and vibrating Leland's chest every morning
and evening since they started dating five years ago. ``It was wake
up, do therapy. Come home, do therapy. We tried not to let life
revolve around it, but it did. (The transplant) was, like,
liberating!''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Leland Herring doesn't have to schedule dinner around
therapy. He doesn't get winded after walking up a flight of stairs.
The oxygen tank is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've been cured. My life is very easy compared to
before.''
</P>
<P>
   He can take out the trash, mow the lawn and go for long walks
with Melissa. And he can breathe without even trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets to do the masculine `husband' things now,'' says
Melissa, married to Leland for three years a week ago today. ``A
year ago, he never would have been able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   His lung capacity was about 15 percent before the transplant,
``and they stopped testing me because they couldn't even finish the
test, I was so weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he was at 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal is 80 to 100 percent,'' he proudly explains.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are things to remind Leland Herring of the CF that
remains in his body: It is hard to digest some foods. Every
morning, he has to weigh himself and take his blood pressure and
temperature. He writes it all down and gives the reports to the
doctors at Duke and St. Mary's Cystic Fibrosis Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   He takes 30 pills a day, including Cyclosporin, Prednisone and
Imuran to keep his body from rejecting the foreign lungs. Then
there are the pills to combat the side effects _ irritability,
nervousness and sensitivity, warts, high blood pressure, vitamin
depletion _ of the antirejection drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a connoisseur of fine pills,'' he smiles, massaging his
goatee and holding up one bottle like it's a vintage wine. A shelf
in his garage holds dozens of bottles and packets of pills, big and
small, square and round.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't go down smooth, I don't like 'em. But it sure
beats the heck out of the therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Leland and Melissa are back at Duke for a two-hour
checkup, the third since the transplant.
</P>
<P>
   He will be there ``every three months for the rest of my life,''
getting his blood gases tested, taking X-rays and breathing for the
doctors. Doctors gave him a 40 to 50 percent chance of living four
to five years, admitting they are unsure whether the CF will infect
his new lungs.
</P>
<P>
   He and Melissa are staying with friend and fellow CF patient
Bret Weinstein, 19, of Palm Beach, who is awaiting his own set of
new lungs. Weinstein got married in May. He took his oxygen tank
with him down the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   This time last year, Leland's lungs finally got so bad he and
Melissa moved from their Royal Palm Beach home to a Durham, N.C.,
efficiency apartment. There, they waited near the Duke transplant
team for new lungs _ more specifically, small lungs with Leland's
Type A blood.
</P>
<P>
   After two false starts, and just when doctors said he couldn't
wait much longer, he got The Call. And just after 9:30 p.m. on
April 26, Leland began life with good lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Is he worried about his lungs giving out in five years?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, because it's a heck of a lot better than a month!'' he
says, slapping his desk in Wellington Christian's P.E. storage room
for emphasis. ``I said, `I'll take five years.'''
</P>
<P>
   But he thinks he'll get more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of transplant recipients have rejection or
infection within the first 45 days. Doctors at Duke thought Leland
Herring would fall into that group because he had a ``bug,''
Burholderia cepacia, that was resistant to antibiotics. The doctors
were so worried, they almost didn't perform the operation.
</P>
<P>
   But an antibiotic cocktail from Toronto Medical Center fought
the bug, which doctors can't find anywhere in Leland's compact
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's surprising everybody,'' remarks Wellington Christian
headmaster Doug McLaughlin, who hired the 1992 Palm Beach Atlantic
College graduate three years ago. ``His health is even stronger
than it was when he first started working here.''
</P>
<P>
   He works all day around children, but he hasn't been sick once
since school started in August.
</P>
<P>
   Leland Herring, now the school's chapel coordinator and ``Mr.
Miscellaneous, the Spiritual Guru _ I go wherever they need me,''
spends his days planning chapel programs and counseling the kids
who need special attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just seemed to work out well, putting him in front of the
children and letting him serve as an inspiration,'' McLaughlin
said.
</P>
<P>
   So here is Leland Herring, talking about the future, about maybe
adopting a child, about taking long trips far from hospitals, about
getting recertified so he can teach in a classroom again. But he
hasn't forgotten where he was eight months ago and how close he
came to dying.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, a pastor at Wellington Church _ looking almost
guilty as he said it _ told Leland he had his eulogy written.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said `I wrote it when you left for Duke.' So I told him,
`That's OK, I'm going to make a video for the funeral soon.' What's
gotten me this far is Jesus, and I want that to be what's gotten
across at my funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The amazing thing is, I've outlived people I thought were
healthier than me. But they were angry at God, and I'm not angry at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all going to die. The question is, are you ready to meet
your maker? I was, and I am. I was ready to die, but I'm ready to
breathe, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The 32nd annual ``65 Roses Gala,'' to benefit the Cystic
Fibrosis Foundation, will be Jan. 9 at 7 p.m. at The Breakers in
Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Colavecchio writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
