<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life in Washington couldn't get weirder
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Send in Bruce Willis! Could this be anything but
the political apocalypse, the Beltway Armageddon?
</P>
<P>
   Consider the omens:
</P>
<P>
   Larry Flynt as Deep Throat. It was Hustler magazine, not The
Washington Post, that hounded House Speaker-designate Bob
Livingston from his post.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Hyde as the Enforcer of Conscience. This is the same man
who, during the Iran-Contra scandal, bashed those who sermonized
about how terrible lying is and complained that ``it just seems to
me too simplistic'' to condemn all lying.
</P>
<P>
   The President, already in trouble for his, er, poor impulse
control, bombs Iraq on the eve of his impeachment vote. The news
toggles back and forth between Iraq and impeachment. Meanwhile, the
President's job-approval ratings soar to a record 73 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Do you wonder if you died and are spending the afterlife in a
Fellini movie? Could it get any weirder? I spent Saturday curiously
detached, not turning on the TV. Yet when our friend The Bearer of
Bad Tidings arrived with the expected news _ two counts _ I erupted
in anger: ``They stole our vote! They acted from Clinton's first
day in office as if it were an outrage against humanity that a
Democrat was elected and they were going to do whatever it took to
get him out of office! They stole our vote!'' Muttering something
about the evils of ``partisan politics,'' my friend beat a hasty
retreat.
</P>
<P>
   In a calmer mood, I hosted a small dinner party that night. My
friend the Bringer of Wine provided the first post-impeachment
laugh by taping a new label to the bottle of merlot: ``Bob
Livingston Whine: If I quit, he should too. Potomac River Valley.
1998.''
</P>
<P>
   He was angry too. We talked about the hypocrisy of a Congress
that shows by its own posturing that Clinton's behavior doesn't
meet the standard of high crimes and misdemeanors: ``Just act a
little more remorseful, Mr. President, tell us you did it, but
you're really, really sorry, and we won't impeach you.'' If the
President is guilty of an impeachable offense, it shouldn't matter
if he wears a hair shirt and sings Gregorian chants for a month.
</P>
<P>
   We sipped our Bob Livingston Whine and vented and laughed. And
vowed to keep hopeful. It has been, as the Queen might say, an
``annus horribilis'' year in Washington. The President acted
disgracefully and lied about it for seven months. The halls of
Congress reek of sexual McCarthyism and poisonous partisanship. Our
representatives refer to each other as ``gentleman'' while hissing
like cobras.
</P>
<P>
   Yet we still can hope that American democracy will rise from the
ashes of this debacle, stronger than ever. That we will become more
engaged and alert citizens, and our Congress more civil, more
productive, less partisan.
</P>
<P>
   My friend the Student of History, in fact, is downright cheerful
about last week's events. They only prove that those guys who wrote
the Constitution are ``the minds of the Millennium.'' Andrew
Johnson's impeachment was also ferociously partisan, he points out
_ even worse, because Johnson hadn't done anything wrong. The
democracy survived, the scandal all but forgotten. Now our
president has been impeached in the middle of an airstrike, the
probable Speaker of the House goes down in flames, and people
aren't rioting in the streets. They're not firing howitzers into
the Kremlin. Folks are singing Christmas carols and happily doing
their shopping. All is well; the system is stronger than we
realized; the Constitution works.
</P>
<P>
   I can't quite work myself up to ``cheerful,'' or much past
bitter and disillusioned, but the Student of History has a point.
Send back Bruce Willis. The events of the past week are not, after
all, political Armageddon. They are a reminder of what we have, and
how we should all be better stewards of it.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
