<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wholesale displeasure: Columnist rings up many complaints by
retail workers
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``It's obvious you have never worked in retail,''
wrote Mrs. Gail Micek of Bellevue, Neb., who said she was writing
for ``all sales associates everywhere'' who took offense at my
column.
</P>
<P>
   The column that upset Mrs. Micek began: ``It's amazing how many
people work in retail sales but don't know anything about the
products they sell.''
</P>
<P>
   The column went on to describe unhappy encounters with ``sales
associates'' who had little or no knowledge of the products they
sold and who often didn't even know what products their employer
stocked.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the column referred to a ``Superior Service''
policy used by Safeway Stores, Inc. that is generally popular with
Safeway customers but not that popular with Safeway employees who
oppose forced friendliness.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Micek started to work in retail sales 28 years ago,
she said, buyers and sales representatives held classes on new
merchandise so the store's sales staff would know the new products.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, now as retail stores keep expanding, communication
isn't what it used to be _ even in this computer age.''
</P>
<P>
   She dared me to work a day in a big department store and see how
much product information I learned as I was running the cash
register, answering the telephones and getting yelled at by
customers for being understaffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to what you may want to believe,'' wrote another
sales person, many people have to live off the wages paid for sales
jobs. Since that is nearly impossible, those who could left sales
jobs to take jobs that paid a living wage, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Those who couldn't get better jobs ``have been evicted so many
times for being unable to pay the rent that we are sleeping on our
parents' couches.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers will continue to get poor service ``as long as service
with a smile means slavery,'' wrote ``the guy on the couch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most sales people are underpaid, undertrained, overworked and
stores are understaffed,'' wrote Chris, a former retail employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good to know that clueless newspaper writers are still
confounding readers,'' began another e-mail letter from an upset
reader.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when being a store clerk was a professional
job with good enough pay and commission incentives to raise a
family and take pride in learning all about the products your
company sells,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, it (retail sales) is an extremely unglam- orous job
that not many want and generally leads nowhere. Or, if you are
lucky, you can be promoted to an assistant store manager that pays
a salary and where you get to do lots of mandatory overtime for
free.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when if you asked about Model 500 widgets,
the store and its management had held a weekly or daily sales
meeting and explained all the new products with the benefits and
uses, and set up a compensation plan that rewarded people who
actively worked with customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The fast-buck artists, the writer said, sold the retail
businesses down the drain, laid off experienced workers and cut
pensions.
</P>
<P>
   The real culprits, he said, are buyout artists who wring the
retail chains dry and customers who want only the cheapest prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the chains give them what they want, and now you're whining
that there is no service. Please spare me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Risley of Dayton, Ohio, made a similar point by suggesting
that I find out more about the training, pay, duties and
aspirations of today's retail sales workers.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, I don't feel comforted now that I know why service from
retail sales clerks has deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   I guess we are just getting what we deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(AT)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
