<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3718 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEPMOMS24-COX     12-23 1895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEPMOMS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When broken families remarry, new parents work to stay ... One
step ahead
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Instant love.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one big myth common to stepfamilies, it's that
children and their stepmothers or stepfathers should instantly love
each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love me, love my children. You don't need to love them to be
successful,'' says Dr. Elaine Rotenberg, a West Palm Beach family
psychologist. ``It's OK to realize that stepparents and
stepchildren may never really like each other, and they don't have
to love each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But she adds: ``They can get along with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Love takes time. And stepmothers in particular have a hard time
as heads of new families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to realize that stepmothers are sometimes a safer
person to be mad at than the biological parent,'' says Margorie
Engel, president of the Stepfamily Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   That can reinforce the tired image of the ``wicked'' stepmother.
And it forces many stepparents into avoiding confrontations,
Rotenberg says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best advice to stepmothers struggling with the label of
`wicked stepmother,''' she adds, ``is not to take on the burden of
erasing someone else's label for you. Instead, you will be better
off creating your own unique relationship with your stepchildren
and your entire family.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is to say, step-parenting is never about the kids alone.
</P>
<P>
   It's about couples working on their own relationships while
coping with children and ex-spouses who feel threatened.
</P>
<P>
   The new movie Stepmom, which opens Friday, tackles those rocky
issues. It's about two women who don't particularly like each
other, two kids and a man in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first movie endorsed by the Stepfamily Association of
America because the movie showed that life can go on, happily, when
families break up and form new bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Here we give some local stepmothers a chance to tell their side
of the story, in their own words.
</P>
<P>
   Name: Robin Bernstein
</P>
<P>
   Age: 45
</P>
<P>
   Married to: Richard, 14 years
</P>
<P>
   Stepmom to: Arthur, 20
</P>
<P>
   Mom to: Ariel, 11; twins Alexandra and Julia, 5.
</P>
<P>
   Lives in: Palm Beach
</P>
<P>
   ``I first met Richard when I was 29 and Arthur was 5. I knew I
was never there to replace someone, but to be there in addition to
his mother. It was a joint custody arrangement. We had him
sometimes during the week and sometimes during the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it was fun. I didn't have to give birth. I inherited
him past the diapers. He was fun, creative, ornery.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Step-parenting) wasn't really an obstacle early on in the
relationship, and I do love my stepson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the difficulty begins is when the parents have their own
child.''
</P>
<P>
   Ariel was born when Arthur was 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the stepchild always feels that he's not part of the
family, or that he's part of the family, but in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There also were different parenting styles, which did cause
conflict between the two homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One was more structured than the other due to increased
parental responsibilities in our home when Ariel was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through a very difficult period. What we ended up
doing was sending Arthur to a boarding school because the dual
environments, the different parenting styles, were not good for
Arthur. This was done after many meetings, and consultations with
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave him a stable environment. He became much more mature,
and independent and really considerate of the different parents'
homes, and his relationships with his siblings improved greatly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went to Israel for his bar mitzvah, we all went
together as one big family: his mother, grandmother, all of us. So,
I think at critical stages in his life, whether graduation, or
whatever, there always was a time when everybody could be there for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Name: Gay Koehler
</P>
<P>
   Age: 49
</P>
<P>
   Married to: Dennis, 14 years on New Year's Eve
</P>
<P>
   Stepmom to: Joshua, 21.
</P>
<P>
   Mom to: Brittany Koehler, 13; Ken Hutcheson, 30; Rob
Satterthwaite, 28.
</P>
<P>
   Lives in: West Palm Beach
</P>
<P>
   ``Josh was 6 when I first met Dennis. I have two older children
so I did have some experience being a mom. I already had experience
being involved, going to the games and events children go through,
so it worked well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly a challenge from time to time with Josh, but
no more so than with the other children. After Brittany was born, I
was a stay-at-home mom. At the end of the day, Josh would be picked
up by his nanny and go to his mom's house, and he would call me and
I would really enjoy that. I felt that I was appreciated, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Brittany was born, since she was a daughter, I think
maybe it made it easier for Josh to take. His dad didn't have
another son. I remember Josh being pleased she was a girl. I don't
know if he thought, `Is my status going to be threatened?'
</P>
<P>
   ``But having stepparents can give a child an extra set of
parents to count on. I remember when Josh auditioned for Super
Sloppy Double Dare (a TV show), and they asked about his parents
and he said three were attorneys, and one was a hairdresser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Josh now sees relationships as being lifetime
commitments. When I met Dennis, I don't think he had that concept
at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he feels close to me; I certainly feel close to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've just been one of the lucky ones. I've talked to
people who have had horrible experiences. Maybe they just don't
hang in there long enough to work everything out. Maybe when two
people do love each other, maybe the kids do pick up on that and
everyone feels the love.''
</P>
<P>
   Name: Olivia Tartakow
</P>
<P>
   Age: 51
</P>
<P>
   Married to: Sheldon Bufferd, eight years
</P>
<P>
   Stepmom to: Marci, 31; Gary, 28
</P>
<P>
   Lives in: Palm Beach Gardens
</P>
<P>
   ``When we married, they were both out of the house. There was no
custody problem because both were adults.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of excited about being a stepmom because I didn't
have my own children and it was like having an instant family with
none of the burdens, except financial. They were good kids and they
were very accepting of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, I tried to increase the relationship he had with
the kids. His having been in a divorce and (shuttling) the children
back and forth, their relationship with him was not as solid as it
could have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``My relationship with Marci has always been very good. She
calls me WSM _ wicked step mommy. It's a joke. She just said it one
day, but it was said affectionately.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Marci, I see her about twice a year. Gary became
estranged from the family. We're not quite sure what the situation
is, but it's nothing to do with my stepmothering, nothing to do
with our marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my also being a stepchild made me more sensitive to
just letting the relationships develop as they would. I know what
kind of pain and hurt I went through when I was younger. My parents
were divorced when I was 13 and I had chosen to live with my
father. My mother remarried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I maintained an excellent relationship with her, and my
stepdad is the one we go on vacations with when we have our family
vacations. He was just always basically there.''
</P>
<P>
   Name: Kathy McCarron
</P>
<P>
   Age: 37
</P>
<P>
   Married to: Brian, 16 years
</P>
<P>
   Stepmom to: Adrea, 20
</P>
<P>
   Mom to: Ariana, 11 months, Samantha, 4 1/2, and Kelsey, 11.
</P>
<P>
   Lives in: Boca Raton
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very young when we married. (She was 19, he was 28) My
stepdaughter was 5. She never remembers a time when I wasn't
around. I have always been there with her dad. Being a stepmom was
easy for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first married, she visited in the summer for about two
months. She was living in Indiana and had to fly on the plane by
herself. In the third grade, when she was 9, she came to live with
us full-time. I was pregnant and she wanted to be part of our
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good dad and wanted to make a family for his
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he wanted her to move in with us. It took a long time
to work it out without a big custody battle that would have been
bad for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only trouble I remember is she didn't like to eat very
much and we made her sit at the table until she finished, but I had
that with my kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some things with her mom, but we tried not to say bad
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her biological mom really wanted to do what was right for
Adrea, but I have always been like her parent. Her mom had like a
totally different parenting style; she wanted to be her friend
instead of her parent. Adrea was 18 when her mom died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so much like her mom. I can really relate to her, she's
such a levelheaded kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought twice about marrying him because he had a
child. I was so in love with Brian and his daughter was so cute.
Most people think stepkids are nasty, but she was sweet, an
angel.''
</P>
<P>
   Name: Terra Lynn Cay
</P>
<P>
   Age: 30
</P>
<P>
   Married to: Danny, 7 years
</P>
<P>
   Stepmom to: An 18-year-old stepdaughter (who doesn't want to be
named)
</P>
<P>
   Lives in: Boynton Beach
</P>
<P>
   ``When we met, she was 9 and I was 21. She and I were actually
friends before Danny and I. I volunteered at a church youth group,
so my focus was youth. Danny and I met through another church
group, and I found out he was a single dad with a young daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because his daughter didn't have a mom, I asked him if I could
take his daughter horseback riding. So, she and I began spending
time together. Danny and I were acquaintances. I would go to the
house and pick her up. It still wasn't a dating relationship for
about a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we got married, I didn't think (being a stepmom) was a
lot to deal with. I didn't want to have kids of my own; I wanted to
adopt or foster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe strongly in God, and I believed before we got
married that when we did get married, that I would feel a bond with
her as if she was my own daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny and his daughter talked about the marriage, but once it
actually happened, it opened up a lot of anger in her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been seven years that she hadn't been in contact with
her mom. After we got married, her mom called. From that point on,
she was in and out of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was dealing with it fine. But things got harder.
She internalized things, and she started stealing and lying. She
was 13. That's when I started feeling like she wasn't appreciating
my love. What does she want from me? That's when it became
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started having marriage problems, and going to counseling.
The really neat thing was it strengthened our communication skills
and the counselor was very supportive of us and how we were
handling things with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role of stepmother was a lot tougher than I thought it
would be. I felt like a failure. Her problems kept getting worse
and it got to a point where she left home. There's been some
reconciliation now that she's 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish that I had known somebody who I could have talked to
before I got married. I don't know whether it would have changed my
decision to marry. I'm happy I did get married. But if you have
foster or adopted kids, they come with their own issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Susman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
