<HEADER>
A3720 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-STODA-COLUMN24-CO     12-23 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STODA-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    J.J. deals with his personal loss the best way he knows
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The mother said her son made the call
every week.
</P>
<P>
   The mother knew well enough, though, that her telephone would
ring later rather than sooner back in Port Arthur, Texas, during
football season if that son's team had lost a game.
</P>
<P>
   Allene Johnson, 77, who died Sunday, understood and loved that
about her boy, Jimmy, who went about his business _ remember that
word _ Monday night in Pro Player Stadium as head coach of the
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful for all of the concern and support I have
received, especially from the people who knew my mother,'' Johnson
said in a statement issued before Miami's stunning 31-21 victory
over Denver that qualified the Dolphins for the playoffs. ``This is
a matter that is private and personal, and I appreciate being given
the latitude to handle it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was.
</P>
<P>
   Even during pre-game drills with coaches and players scattered
around the Dolphins' half of the field, Johnson wandered mostly
alone. There was nothing particularly unusual about that, because
Johnson is often a solitary figure at such a time.
</P>
<P>
   But there seemed to be even fewer conversations _ however brief
_ than usual ... a handshake ... a wave ... a pat on the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing more than quick tidings of comfort without joy in this
holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a businessman,'' said Dolphins wide receiver Lamar
Thomas, who caught three touchdown passes. ``He always tells us
there are certain things that go along with life, and you have to
separate them when you go to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a hypocrite.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami defensive end Jason Taylor, who was one of the few players
who approached Johnson during warm-ups, said there was no official
announcement to the team that the coach's mother had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word just got around,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Business.
</P>
<P>
   The only time Johnson initiated a meeting with anyone prior to
kickoff was when he noticed team owner H. Wayne Huizenga strolling
a sideline. They spoke for a moment, and Johnson posed for pictures
at Huizenga's request.
</P>
<P>
   Again, though, Johnson was alone with his head bowed as staff
and team afforded him space during the invocation before the game.
</P>
<P>
   These are perhaps nothing more than observations made from afar
shaded exaggeratedly by a voyeur's knowledge of circumstances. And
perhaps, too, Johnson would object to any sympathetic portrayal of
him in sorrowful pose.
</P>
<P>
   Do not presume.
</P>
<P>
   Do not intrude.
</P>
<P>
   Do not presume to intrude.
</P>
<P>
   Those are Johnson's shields.
</P>
<P>
   But it's nice _ and maybe even important _ to remember Allene
and her husband, C.W., watching their son's Dolphins win a game
earlier this year in Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And it's nicer still to remember Johnson's first season in Miami
when the Dolphins went to Houston just down the road from Port
Arthur, and his mother and father watched a Miami victory over the
Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   That was back when Allene was spending four hours a day three
days a week hooked to a dialysis machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not including the 30 minutes it takes to stop the bleeding
from the needles,'' she told me once.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Allene and C.W. satisfied themselves most of the time
by watching the Dolphins on a big-screen television in their quiet
house on a quiet street in the same town to which they moved from
Arkansas in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs were lives far removed from their son, who found glitter
and national-championship glory in Miami (during his college
coaching days with the Hurricanes) and Dallas (winning two Super
Bowls coaching the Cowboys) and is now more at home in South
Florida with the Dolphins than he ever was in an oil town-gone-bust
on the Gulf Coast of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But calls back to Port Arthur always remained a touchstone.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson coached a football game Monday night in the wake of his
mother's death, and he did it in his standard out-loud style. He
ranted and raved over slights real or imagined. He stomped and
pointed.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services will be held Wednesday morning in Groves,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The son's call to his mother would have come sooner rather than
later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stoda writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
