<HEADER>
A3732 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSIC24-COX     12-23 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This American dish has been enjoyed for nearly a century
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Oysters Rockefeller is an American classic.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the name, based on the richness of a Rockefeller, but
it is a special occasion dish, one that is perfect for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   If the measure of classic dish is that it endures, this one
meets the test. Flip the calendar to 1999 and it will be 100 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   Created in New Orleans, the specialty became popular in upscale
restaurants everywhere and managed to survive the era of
continental cuisine, when Beef Wellington and Cherries Jubilee
flourished. Over the decades the thumbprints of hundreds of chefs
have left their mark on the dish.
</P>
<P>
   As the late James Beard, the dean of American cuisine, once
said, ``It's such a misquoted classic that there are as many
recipes as there are cookbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, most of the recipes include a topping made with spinach,
and that's completely wrong, say the owners of Antoine's
Restaurant, where the recipe was created in 1899 during a shortage
in the supply of French snails. The first owner of the French
Quarter restaurant responded by cooking native oysters under a pale
green puree.
</P>
<P>
   While the recipe for the original topping is still a secret, the
descendents insist that the puree includes more than one green
vegetable _ and that spinach is not among them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most recipes from imitators today are based on spinach.
Some innovators, guessing at the original, rely on watercress.
Parsley and green onions are frequent additions, and some anise
flavoring is essential, either from Pernod or bulb fennel.
</P>
<P>
   And the recipes always include butter, lots of butter.
</P>
<P>
   If Oysters Rockefeller comes in many guises, some are better
than others. On the menu at Kettering, Ohio's l'Auberge restaurant,
the Oysters Rockefeller bear the stamp of chef/owner Dieter Krug.
He dispenses with shell oysters, buying fat ones from Virginia that
are always a uniform size and easier for the home cook to deal with
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Spinach is the correct green ingredient, he insists, and he
cooks it briefly in butter. He flavors it with Pernod, just enough
to add the faint anise taste, but not so much that any sweetness
can be detected. And in this presentation, the oysters, briefly
poached in a little white wine, are laid on top of the bright green
buttered spinach, instead of being baked and buried under some
mysterious green puree.
</P>
<P>
   The chef's whim at l'Auberge is a ladle of hollandaise sauce on
top and a stardust sprinkling of Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   These are, to be honest, nothing like the ones I tasted at
Antoine's years ago. These are much better. Call them a different
take on a classic.
</P>
<P>
   Krug willingly shares his recipe, which he says is prepared
quickly _ a la minute .
</P>
<P>
   That's true if you have someone to clean the spinach and mince
the garlic and shallots and onions and make the hollandaise, to
have them all ready when you go to the stove.
</P>
<P>
   But take a clue from the chef and do all those preparations
ahead and you, too, can make Oysters Rockefeller part of your
holiday entertaining. It truly does just take minutes to finish
this classic.
</P>
<P>
   While restaurants usually serve six-oyster servings, that's a
lot to precede a big holiday dinner. I suggest four per person, but
you can adjust that and bump up the amount of spinach filling if
you like.
</P>
<P>
   OYSTERS ROCKEFELLER
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoons minced shallot or green onion
</P>
<P>
   cup finely minced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh spinach, rinsed and dried, all stems removed
</P>
<P>
   salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons Pernod
</P>
<P>
   16 select oysters
</P>
<P>
   cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons grated Parmesan cheese, divided
</P>
<P>
   hollandaise sauce (recipe on Page 3C)
</P>
<P>
   Heat the butter in a large skillet. Add the garlic, shallot and
onion and cook several minutes until the onions are softened. Add
the spinach to the pan, season with salt and pepper and cook,
shaking the pan occasionally, until the spinach wilts, about 2
minutes. Drizzle the Pernod over the top, cover and let the spinach
steam for a minute or two. Sprinkle 2 tablespoons of the cheese
over the spinach and stir. Remove from heat and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place the oysters in a skillet and add the wine and sprinkle
with salt and pepper. Cook over medium heat 1 to 2 minutes, then
turn. Cook another minute or two and remove from the heat. The
oysters should be warm and firm but not overcooked.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, spoon cup spinach on a warm plate. Arrange the drained
oysters over the top and ladle cup hollandaise over the top.
Sprinkle lightly with remaining Parmesan and run under the broiler
for a minute or two to brown the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 529 calories, 43 g
fat, 289 mg cholesterol, 785 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Blender hollandaise is the easiest choice for the home cook. It
can be made a good half-hour ahead and kept warm in a heated
thermos. Remember that this sauce contains eggs that are not fully
cooked, which is a health issue for some. Blender Hollandaise Makes
1 cups 3 egg yolks 2 tablespoons boiling water cup warm melted
butter 1 tablespoon lemon juice salt dash cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   Put the egg yolks in an electric blender. Turn to low speed and
slowly add the boiling water and then the butter, very slowly in a
thin stream. Add the lemon juice, cayenne and salt to taste.
(Recipe from the Fannie Farmer Cookbook by Marion Cunningham).
</P>
<P>
   James Beard's recipe, which he published in American Cookery
contains no spinach, but a mixture of green onions, celery,
chervil, fennel, parsley and watercress run through a blender until
pureed.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
