<SLUG> BC-GOOD24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good Stuff
 &HT;    c. 1998 Dayton Daily News
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ We've all heard all the helpful hints people
suggest to dry up the tears while cutting up onions. Well, this
month Cook's Illustrated tested 20 of the household hints to see if
any really work. Two that do are wearing contacts, or, if you
don't, wearing goggles, which admittedly looks silly in the
kitchen. So did a number of other suggested solutions. Best of the
others was to have a lighted candle nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Change baking soda two times a year
</P>
<P>
   We all know to check the use-by date on the baking powder can.
But did you know to change your baking soda every six months?
</P>
<P>
   So says Dorie Greenspan, the ``baking evangelist'' for the Land
O'Lakes Holiday Bakeline who worked on the Baking With Julia
cookbook that accompanied Julia Child's PBS series.
</P>
<P>
   But don't just pitch the old baking soda; put it in the
refrigerator to trap odors.
</P>
<P>
   One good source
</P>
<P>
   U nless your idea of a good time is sitting around skinning
nuts, recipes for toasted hazelnuts can move you to turn the
cookbook page. While the nuts can be hard to find, raw skinned
hazelnuts (also called filberts) can be found at nut specialty
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
