<HEADER>
A3752 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EURO-BERLIN-$ADV27-CO     12-23 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-BERLIN-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RESURGENT BERLIN RIDING THE EURO WAVE
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    With EURO-NEW-$ADV27.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The view from a snow-covered observation platform above
Potsdamer Platz offers three telling sites.
</P>
<P>
   The first is the spare glass and terra cotta geometry of new and
burgeoning office towers rising from the hubbub and confusion of
construction. This is Sony Corp.'s $5 billion European
headquarters, which is rising alongside Daimler-Benz' new $2.2
billion mega-development with its offices, stores, restaurants,
apartments, Germany's largest casino, a 10-screen cinema, musical
theater and a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40,000 men and women in blue work clothes and white
helmets hustle day an night in the largest construction site in
Western Europe -- perhaps anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Next, nearly unseen in the construction, a remnant the Berlin
Wall snakes through the equipment and scaffolding on the plaza,
which until World War II was the pulsing heart of Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the old Reichstag -- the old parliament building --
which was torched by the Nazis in 1933 and bombed by the allies in
1945, rises above scores of construction cranes. A new translucent
cupola pops up from the gutted and renovated building, an
architectural marriage of very old Berlin to the future -- a future
that promises big things.
</P>
<P>
   On May 23, the bundestadt -- the federal assembly -- will
convene in the Reichstag to elect the nation's next president, the
first official act in the building since Hitler was chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   And next November, most of federal government will finish the
move from Bonn to Berlin, completing a long symbolic journey home.
</P>
<P>
   For Berliners, who have lived through a remarkable decade, it
sometimes seems unreal. ``Berlin is a fantasy,'' said Dirk Kroegel,
a spokesman for the city government. ``It is a dream that seems to
be coming true.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also the rising capital of the wealthiest and perhaps most
influential country in Europe. Its importance is expected to grow
with the monetary union, which begins with the introduction of the
euro as the continent's primary electronic currency on Jan. 1.
Bills and coins will begin circulation three years later.
</P>
<P>
   Germany pushed hard for monetary union in hopes of creating a
more stable economic environment for its financial and industrial
prowess to flourish. While the European Commission will remain in
Brussels, the powerful European Central Bank will operate from
Frankfurt. The most powerful national government will be in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, more than 30,000 federal workers and
their families will pack up and move from Bonn to Berlin. An
estimated 70,000 lobbyists, lawyers and other institutions that
travel with government will also move in. Embassies are also
returning to the old capital, including a proposed $140 million
U.S. compound planned for its pre-war site near the Brandenberg
gate in what had been East Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The move is costing the German government about $12 billion in
new construction, renovations and moving costs, said Gerda Renatus,
a spokeswoman for the government's office that is coordinating the
move.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to refitting old buildings including Hitler's old
Aviation Ministry new government buildings are rising along central
parts of the Tiergarten and Mitte districts, near where the River
Spree river curves sharply west of the Reichstag.
</P>
<P>
   Private construction projects unrelated to the government's move
are worth an estimated $10 billion to $15 billion. The amount of
construction is so vast -- about triple the construction in
pre-Olympic Atlanta and Barcelona combined -- it is hard to soak
in.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the planned $11.5 billion reconstruction of the
Lehrter Bahnhof rail station is underway to provide a 21st-Century
juncture for two great European rail routes: from Paris to Moscow,
and from Stockholm to Vienna. The station will have a 1,400-foot
glass concourse, 58 escalators and 37 elevators. A new airport is
scheduled to open in 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the boomtown feel of Berlin, the city is in an economic
slump. Office occupancy is less than 50 percent, according to the
city government. The unemployment rates is about 18 percent, and
industrial production has fallen 6 percent in 1998. Things are so
slow that plans for a major new complex of skyscrapers planned for
Alexander Platz in the old eastern sector have been placed on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Things are expected to improve, but not for another five or six
years, officials say. Many business leaders expect the city's
prospects will rise as the economic situation in Russia gets sorted
out. ``Russia will come back, and when it does it will mean a lot
for Germany and Berlin,'' said Joachim Volz, an economist with the
German Institute for Economic Research.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, truth is no one seems to know what to expect
with the return of the government and the advent of a monetary
union, both of which could have dramatic uncertain impact.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Berliners seem most interested in figuring out the
identify of their city -- a complex matter given its mixed history
and puzzling future. There seems to be a desire to reach back
before Hitler's times to the Berlin of Sally Bowles, the character
played by Liza Minelli in ``Caberet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Berlin is like a ghost,'' Koegel said. ``People remember the
way it was before the Third Reich, and they want it the way it was
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is more haunted than Potsdam Platz. In the 1920s, it had
legendary cafes such as Josty and Vaterland, and the hotel
Esplanade was one of Europe's most coveted addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The square was reduced to rubble in the last months of World War
II, and left desolate and overgrown on the dividing line between
East and West Berlin. That all changed in 1989 when the Berlin Wall
came down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine years ago, Berliners destroyed the Wall with hammers,''
Daimler-Benz chairman Juergen Schrempp(CQ) said a few weeks ago at
the opening of his firm's development. ``Today we are marking a new
Berlin, a country on the move and a continent that has rediscovered
its equilibrium.''
</P>
<P>
   With Berlin again at the center.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
