<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3753 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EURO-BIZ-$ADV27-COX     12-23 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-BIZ-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESSES SEE PROMISE, PROBLEMS CONVERTING TO EURO
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    With EURO-NEW-$ADV27.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ While much of world takes a break at the end of the
year, the dense honeycombs of money-making in central London will
be abuzz.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long weekend from Dec. 31 to Jan. 4, The City --
London's financial district -- will swarm with 30,000 bankers,
stockbrokers and computer wizards assembled to make ready for the
euro.
</P>
<P>
   While the new bills and coins won't be around for three years,
the euro will become the electronic currency of choice at the first
of the year. The briefcase-wielding army will face a monumental
mission: Converting millions of electronic financial transactions
to the new currency.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. on New Year's Eve, European finance ministers in
Brussels will fix the conversion rates between their currencies and
the euro. The Bank of England will then post the rates on computer
screens around The City, setting off a 55-hour race to be ready for
business when the Far East markets open at midnight on Jan 3.
</P>
<P>
   The work is being taken so seriously that some banking
institutions have asked London hotels, where many of the troops
will be housed, to remove the booze from the minibars.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Levene of Portsoken, the chairman of Bankers Trust and the
Lord Mayor of London, said the job is made complicated because
these institutions will be fiddling with something uniquely
sensitive: Other peoples money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my bank, we have two huge task forces, one on the euro and
the other on YK2000, the euro requirement is more difficult,''
Levene, also chairman of Bankers Trust, said at a recent luncheon
at the grand Mansion, what amounts to London City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   A Citibank guide to the euro circulated among corporate
treasurers put it this way, ``It is like the U.S. deciding to
switch to driving on the left by 1999. Moving the steering wheels
on the cars is the easy bit. What to do about the roads, interstate
highways, traffic signs, traffic management, driver education and
so on is far more complex.'' European banks will spend $10 billion
to make the change.
</P>
<P>
   Because the euro will be phased in over the next 3 1/2 years on
a largely voluntary basis, American businesses -- like their
European counterparts -- will have to work with both euros and the
old currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the hassle, there are three key advantages for
American businesses:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Price transparency: It will be easier to compare prices across
Euroland, making it easier for companies to shop around and,
consequently, forcing more price competition. This also will make
it easier for companies to give their products consistent prices.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A strengthened European stock market: That would provide
American companies a new source of capital.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Economic stability: Unified interest rates and a broad attack
on inflation will make it easier to manage the business cycle, to
moderate the highs and lows.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, companies may experience a savings of 25 percent
to 40 percent in bank foreign exchange fees.
</P>
<P>
   For many businesses, the monetary union will create a vast and
exciting marketplace that may look a lot like the United States.
``The country boundaries, the currency boundaries, will be replaced
by boundaries of groups of people who are distinguished only by
their buying preferences,'' said Jim Reed, the director of European
programs for Dell Computer Corp., the Austin, Texas-based computer
maker.
</P>
<P>
   A vast restructuring is likely as businesses reassess their
approach to Europe, most likely centralizing and consolidating
operations, said Reed, whose company manufactures its computers in
Ireland and sells them across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing is to be able to make sure that we can price,
trade and settle in euros from the first of January within any
country in the euro zone,'' Reed said. ``As customers are ready to
transition to euros, we want to be ready for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many businesses will switch completely to the euro, billing
customers and paying suppliers electronically in the new
currencies. They will be free to pay employees in euros, which will
be converted into national currencies by their banks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its advantages, no one thinks the change to the euro
will be easy. The most often cited concerns are the long delay
before bills and coins appear, the lack of a single European
government to take responsibility in a banking crisis and varying
pressures on the new -- and ostensibly independent -- European
Central Bank. There also are concerns about ancient national
rivalries that can't be ended by sharing money.
</P>
<P>
   Another big unanswered question is the euro's effect on the U.S.
dollar and economy. Many economists believe that over time, the
euro may challenge the dollar as the world's currency, a status
that brings many rewards and privileges.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that is in the future, the immediate task is to be
ready for dawn 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Things, after all, can go dreadfully wrong. A power outage is
one popular nightmare scenario. ``What we all fear is the
unknown,'' said Mitchell Shivers, the euro conversion coordinator
at Merrill Lynch in London. ``There is an unprecedented third party
risk, so we have tons of contingency plans.''
</P>
<P>
   And on that point, Lord Levene sounds Churchillian: ``We are not
just determined to be ready,'' he said. ``We will be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
