<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3755 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EURO-NEW-$ADV27-COX     12-23 1765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-NEW-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EUROPEANS LAMENT LOSING IDENTITY, RESIGNED TO THE FACT EURO IS
THE FUTURE
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    With EURO-BERLIN-$ADV27, EURO-BIZ-$ADV27, EURO-GREECE-$ADV27,
EURO-WANNABES-$ADV27, EURO-BOX-$ADV27.
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: The Atlanta Journal-Constitution will place a color
graphic in the International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEUILLY-SUR-SEINE, France _ Sipping a vintage pomerol in the
sitting room of his small apartment in this pretty Paris suburb,
Franck Berchier laments he may never be able to forget his francs
and centimes.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, when he buys something at the market downstairs he will be
forced to go through the same mental calculations of value he
endures when he travels abroad. ``I will see something with the
price of 20 euros, and I will have to think about what that is in
francs so I will know if it is expensive or not,'' Berchier says in
a tone of mild annoyance. ``With the euros, I will be like an alien
in my own country.''
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end for the franc -- and deutsche mark,
lira and peseta for that matter -- will come Jan. 1, when 11
European countries begin switching to the new, unified currency.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the euro will exist only as virtual money in bank and
credit card statements, investment portfolios and on other bills
and pricetags placed by merchants as a reference point and learning
tool.
</P>
<P>
   In January 2002, euro bills and coins will begin circulating.
Six months later the old money will be history.
</P>
<P>
   For Berchier and millions of other Europeans, the demise of a
national currency represents more than just switching money. It
also means the loss of a unique, portable and familiar expression
of who you are. When a French man or woman unfolds a 100-franc
note, he or she sees the familiar and affirming face of the great
French impressionist painter Paul Cezanne. It is a subtle reminder
of what it is to be French, just as the image of Independence Hall
on the back of a US$100 bill is a reminder of what is special about
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When the day comes when his wallet holds euros instead of
francs, Berchier wonders if he might feel that much less French and
more something else, something not so clearly understood even after
eons of definition: A European.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the way of the future, isn't it?'' Berchier asks with a
shrug as he takes another sip of wine.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of the euro is generally regarded as the next step
in the evolution of Europe from a continent of often quarreling --
occasionally warring -- countries into something bigger. Someday
the union may challenge the United States for the economic
heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   Already a unified market, the 11 euro countries -- often called
Euroland -- will become a single economy, a concept not far removed
from the idea of 50 semi-autonomous states operating for business
purposes as the United States of America. Interest rates will be
set by a Central European Bank, which also will deal with a broad
range of economic issues. In theory, this will create economic
conditions in Bonn that match those in Dublin or Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The initial euro club will include Austria, Belgium, Finland,
France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands,
Portugal and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, Denmark and Sweden opted not to participate in the
single unified currency, and Greece failed to meet the required
economic criteria.
</P>
<P>
   While the Euroland countries will surrender individual control
over interest rates, inflation management and other economic
policymaking, they will retain authority -- for now -- over
taxation, wages and labor law. Yet, it is widely accepted that over
time, even these politically charged matters will become
standardized.
</P>
<P>
   The overriding theory behind economic union is that the
individual countries will all gain in efficiencies and stability:
the whole will add up to more than a sum of its parts.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders spare few superlatives in describing the advent
of the euro, which is seen as the economic equivalent of the
tearing down of the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most significant economic event in Europe's
history,'' said Jim Reed, an executive with Dell Computer Corp.,
the Austin, Texas-based computer maker that builds its products in
Ireland and sells them across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a handle on inflation will be a major benefit in
countries such as Italy and Spain, which have been ravaged by
recurring rounds of price instability over the years. At the very
least, ending the need to change currencies will create an
immediate savings of $40 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   If the euro countries can get their act together -- not a small
``if,'' mind you -- then many European economists believe the
continent may in time challenge the United States. On paper
Euroland stacks up nicely against America. The 11 countries have a
combined population of 290 million, 22 million more than the United
States. Each controls slightly less than a quarter of the world's
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there are profound differences. Europe is far more divided
by culture, history and language -- even distinct regional
dialects. This problem is easing by the rise of English: When a
German speaks to an Italian, the conversation is in English. A
recent study showed that 63 percent of the people in France can
speak English, while the number is 94 percent in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in Euroland believe that their union already has paid
off by easing the impact of a worldwide economic slowdown,
particularly in Asia and South America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Already, we have seen the euro work,'' said Joachim Volz, an
economist with the German Institute for Economic Research. ``Our
markets did not suffer from the global crisis nearly as they would
have before.''
</P>
<P>
   Toiling in her tiny office in Neuruppin, 100 miles north of
Berlin, it is sometimes hard for Christine Gerhardt to remember the
grand ideas that possessed Europe's leaders to change to the euro.
</P>
<P>
   For Gerhardt, the whole thing is a stomach churning mess.
Gerhardt battles in the euro trenches.
</P>
<P>
   Her job is to prepare the government in this town of 33,000 to
handle the new currency. When the euro fully replaces the deutsche
mark, then parking meters, land taxes, swimming pool fees --
everything -- will have to be billed and collected in euros.
</P>
<P>
   For her, the rubber will meet the road In the summer of 2002,
when moms leading packs of kids show up at the city pool to learn
that price of swimming has jumped because of the euro. The calls
won't go to Brussels or Berlin, they'll go to Neuruppin City Hall.
``People may not understand what happened, and they may be angry,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In this former East Germany military center, people for the most
part are ambivalent about the euro, said Otto Theel, the
burgermeister. The city still has its hands full just making the
change from socialism to capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   For residents, the euro is just another twist in an already
unfamiliar road, Theel said. ``People worry that unemployment,
which is already not good, will go up because people from other
countries will come to Germany because it is a rich country. They
worry how it will effect their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In most countries, the support for the euro has been declining
for some time. In Germany, the most powerful country in the union,
popular support for the euro has fallen to 43 percent -- exactly
the same as the level of opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The word most often used to describe the attitude of the public
is ``resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us is doing it because we want to be European,'' said
Emma Davis, an English woman who is married to Franck Berchier.
``We're only doing it because we're scared stiff about America or
Japan knocking the hell out of us if we don't. It's totally
mercenary.''
</P>
<P>
   Profound fears remain that economic unity will lead to the
surrender of political autonomy to some multinational collective of
bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Such anxieties seems most acute in Britain, where the press
seems particularly hostile toward Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were once an island-based empire fighting off these
European invasions for hundreds of years while Americans we're
running around in the woods trying to find a country,'' said
Herbert Smart, a small grocer in Manchester. ``You will excuse us
if we don't embrace the idea of being in this new empire dominated
by the Germans and French.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Taylor, a professor of European politics at the London
School of Economics, believes these concerns are exaggerated.
Taylor believes Europe is evolving into a kind of confederation of
independent states with economic decision-making centralized but
conventional government powers retained by the individual
countries. ``I don't see any indication that any of the member
states want to dissolve themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor believes the British should find some comfort in their
own history: Great Britain is itself a collection of different
peoples. ``The Scots and the Welsh and the Irish have survived with
a quite distinct identities in what is a United Kingdom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he acknowledges that many Britons resist even admitting
that they are Europeans. ``But this is different from talking about
views about the relationship with Europe,'' he said. ``The British
public as a whole is resigned to the fact that we're in Europe, and
there's a certain impatience for those who are not prepared to make
the best of this.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the potential benefits of the forging a greater Europe,
there also are worries that cultural diversity may be a casualty of
economic integration.
</P>
<P>
   ``One speaks quite a lot about Europe these days, and one speaks
of it as an industrial trust,'' said Jorg-Ingo Weber, an official
in Berlin's municipal department of science, research and culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diversity in culture, language, the things that make
Germany and Europe special, if not protected, will go away. It is
what I call the 'vanilla-ization' of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, many view becoming part of a greater Europe not so
much as a cause for celebration as an unalterable reality with
which they must come to terms, particularly in the way they define
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Berlin is my home, Germany is my fatherland, and Europe,''
Weber says, ``Europe is my future.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
