<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3756 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EURO-GREECE-$ADV27-CO     12-23 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-GREECE-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GREEKS REDEFINE THEMSELVES IN PURSUIT OF MEMBERSHIP TO THE EURO
CLUB
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    With EURO-NEW-$ADV27.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ Pity poor Greece. Three thousand years is a
long slide from grand empire to European also-ran.
</P>
<P>
   The land of Hercules and Mount Olympus is the poorest country in
the 15-member European Union and the only one which wanted to enter
the single European currency, the euro, but couldn't meet the
economic standards. (Britain, Sweden and Denmark chose not to
join).
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Greece was known as the EU's ``black sheep,''
hamstrung by double-digit inflation, labor strife and a colossal
budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greece is the only country that wanted to be part of the euro
and could not make the grade. There is a sentiment of exclusion, of
somehow being second-class and less than European,'' said Ilias
Nicolacopoulos(CQ), a pollster and political scientist at the
University of Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Greece, which joined the EU in 1981, has launched an epic
struggle for acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Its failure to become a founding member of the euro club -- the
11 countries which will adopt the single currency on Jan. 1 -- has
resulted in uncommon unity among Greece's notoriously divided
political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   They resolved to reduce Greece's deficit and improve its economy
by the end of 1999 for possible inclusion in the euro zone by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Athens pushed hard and won the rights to host
the 2004 Olympics. New airports, roads and rail links are under
construction in preparation for the games.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a new image taking shape across the Greek isles
and in the minds of Greeks themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of being ``European'' is immensely popular. Polls
indicate that the idea of a shared European currency is supported
by two of every three in this country of 10 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two Greeces: One is in the past. It is heroic and
unique. It celebrated great victories and suffered greatly, too.
The new Greece is simply normal. It has managers and technocrats.
It thinks not in terms of territory and nationalism, but of
economics and pragmatism,'' said Theodore Couloumbis(CQ) of the
Hellenic Foundation for European and Foreign Policy, a think tank
in the capital, Athens.
</P>
<P>
   To join the core club of EU players like France and Germany
would lend an image of stability to Greece.
</P>
<P>
   That is important in a country worried that violence in the
turbulent Balkans -- notably the Yugoslavian province of Kosovo --
could erupt into a regional war, or that Greece's perennial
disputes with longtime adversary Turkey could unexpectedly explode
into conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Prime Minister Costas Simitis and his moderate Socialist
government, Greece's main political factions and industrial leaders
have set out to transform the country into a business and
transportation hub for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Separated from the rest of the EU by the Balkans, Greece is now
looking to make its location an advantage -- as a link between
Western Europe and emerging markets in Eastern Europe and the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The $7 billion tourism industry remains vital to the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
   But reflecting a new sophistication to broaden its economy,
Greece -- with the help of the EU -- set up a publicly-financed
company to sell foreign investors on Greece's attributes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its not just the three S's -- sand, sun and sex -- an image
many in America and Europe have of Greece. It's a place to do
business,'' said Efthimios Mouratidis, project manager for the
Hellenic Center for Investment.
</P>
<P>
   Substance, not image alone, has hampered Greece. Inflation stood
at 22 percent in 1991. Trade union strikes continue to periodically
paralyze the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Socialist government of former Prime Minister Andreas
Papandreou, which ruled through most of the 1980's, stoked
organized labor and generally neglected the business community.
Major industries were nationalized. Liberal wage accords caused
industrial productivity to drop, and fed inflation. Papandreou was
driven from office in 1989, returned to power in 1993, but died in
1996 and was succeeded by Simitis.
</P>
<P>
   He initiated a renewed drive to join the single currency. In
all, the EU has contributed about $35 billion to Greece's efforts
to improve its economy and meet the economic criteria to join the
euro.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Greece's lingering inflation that could continue to
bar its euro membership. Running as high as 5.3 per cent this year,
Greece must cut it in half by the end of 1999 to meet the target
for euro membership by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the government has remained committed to a program
of slashing state subsidies, eliminating some services, raising
taxes and privatizing state enterprises, where workers once enjoyed
virtual jobs-for-life security.
</P>
<P>
   The changes have left many unhappy. Nearly every labor union has
held some sort of protest against the austerity initiative in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something rotten in the state of Hellas,'' headlined
the daily newspaper Kathimerini in recent special section dedicated
to Greek woes.
</P>
<P>
   But public opinion and political will seem firmly behind the
effort to join the euro. Many Greek businesses, including the
nation's largest supermarket chains, have agreed to freeze most
prices in an effort to hold down inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of replacing the national currency, the drachma, for
the euro is widely accepted, said Nicolacopoulos, because of the
drachma's mercurial history as a shaky currency. An estimated 35
percent of the national economy remains underground, carried out in
dollars, German deutsche marks and other hard currency.
</P>
<P>
   An Athens taxi driver, Costas Samos, says Greeks will always be
Greek. ``We have our own language that is difficult for outsiders,
our own history and culture. I'm not worried about being less
Greek. I am worried that we will be left behind if we don't follow
the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But do Greeks really believe the euro will change their lives?
</P>
<P>
   ``The euro offers validation, but not very high expectations,''
said Nicolacopoulos. ``The stabilization of the currency is the
prime objective for Greece. That, and perhaps a little more respect
for our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
