<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EUROPEAN MONETARY UNION: A GRAPHIC BREAKDOWN
 &HT;    With EURO-NEW-$ADV27.
 &HT;    EDs: The Atlanta Journal-Constitution will place a color graphic
in the International folder on the Cox Server. Also the information
will work with a map of Europe somehow keyed to show the EU and
non-EU countries.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELCOME TO EUROLAND
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of the 15 countries in the European Union have agreed to
join their financial and
</P>
<P>
   monetary systems within the Economic Monetary Union (EMU). This
step will bring the people and governments of the continent closer
together than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   TIMELINE
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Jan. 1, 1999, 11 European countries will take the
first step toward using a new, unified currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, new currency will be used in many business and
investment transactions as well as in credit cards and other
electronic transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 1998 -- Exchange rate for euro and 11 national currencies
is set.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 1999 -- Euro is launched for bank transactions, stock
exchanges, credit card and other electronic transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 2002 -- Euro coins and bills are introduced.
</P>
<P>
   July 2002 -- National currencies are withdrawn from circulation.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER ECONOMIC POWER?
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the Euro 11 stacked up against the United States in
1997:
</P>
<P>
   ....................................................................
..............Euro 11...............United States
</P>
<P>
   Population (in 
millions)..................................................290......
....................268
</P>
<P>
   Gross Domestic Product (in
billions).........................$5,942.....................$8,080
</P>
<P>
   GDP per person (in U.S. 
dollars................................$20,188..................$30,
147
</P>
<P>
   Share of World's 
Wealth...............................................23.1%..........
...........24.3%
</P>
<P>
   GDP, growth 
rate............................................................2.6%
.......................3.8%
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment 
Rate.....................................................11.6%......
.................4.9%
</P>
<P>
   Inflation...........................................................
................1.8%.......................2.4%
</P>
<P>
   Source: Eurostat
</P>
<P>
   A NEW EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   The Insiders: The Euro 11
</P>
<P>
   Dominated by France and Germany these countries will swap their
own national
</P>
<P>
   currency for a plan intended to bring stability, growth and
order.
</P>
<P>
   France
</P>
<P>
   Germany
</P>
<P>
   Portugal
</P>
<P>
   Spain
</P>
<P>
   Italy
</P>
<P>
   Belgium
</P>
<P>
   Luxembourg
</P>
<P>
   The Netherlands
</P>
<P>
   Austria
</P>
<P>
   Ireland
</P>
<P>
   Finland
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders: The non-Euro 4
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Greece, which must get its economic house
in order before it can
</P>
<P>
   join the European Monetary Union, these countries have been
reluctant to surrender their independent currencies and financial
policymaking to EMU officials in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark
</P>
<P>
   Sweden
</P>
<P>
   United Kingdom
</P>
<P>
   Greece
</P>
<P>
   EURO POLICYMAKING GLOSSARY:
</P>
<P>
   Economic and Monetary Union -- The countries within the European
Union where the euro will become the only official currency. Within
the EMU, people, goods, services and capital are supposed to move
without restriction.
</P>
<P>
   Maastricht Treaty -- Adopted by member countries in 1992, to
establish the rules and institutions of the EMU, and the single
currency.
</P>
<P>
   European Council -- The primary political body of the European
Union, it comprises the heads of state or government of each member
state. The council presidency rotates among the member states.
</P>
<P>
   Council of Ministers -- Includes representatives of ministerial
level -- finance ministers,
</P>
<P>
   for example -- from each European Union country. In the case of
euro policies, the governing body is the Ministers for Economic
Affairs and Finance.
</P>
<P>
   European Central Bank -- This body's primary responsibility is
to manage the monetary policy for the euro, including foreign
exchange operations and managing foreign reserves of member states.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
