<HEADER>
A3765 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EURO-WANNABES-$ADV27-     12-23 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-WANNABES-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CENTRAL, EASTERN EUROPE EAGER TO JOIN THE EURO CLUB, REJOIN THE
WEST
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    With EURO-NEW-$ADV27.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW _ Poland, like much of the rest of Central and Eastern
Europe, has a clear image of itself in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the Anti-Soviet Pact, former satellites of the Soviet
Union eager to shed their association with Moscow and become
clearly linked with the West.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of ``being European'' is simultaneously appealing
and ambiguous to the nine Central and East European countries
lining up for European Union membership.
</P>
<P>
   They know they want to join the club. They simply are not
certain what the fine print will mean, particularly as 11 members
of the union are set to launch a single currency on Jan. 1 and
enter unchartered territory in the realm of economic unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may not be completely happy with the EU and what
membership will do for them, but all that is negligible compared to
the prime motivation: They clearly want to draw a line that defines
them with the West and protects them from Russia,'' said a Western
diplomat in Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic are set to become the
newest members of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization next
spring, expanding the Cold War security organization beyond what
had been the iron curtain.
</P>
<P>
   The three nations and others are on a separate path to EU
membership. The crash of Russia's economy last August sent shock
waves through Eastern and Central Europe and reinforced the need
for stronger economic alliances with the European Union and
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the alternative? There is no alternative. We have
nothing to take from Russia. Our path is to the West,'' said Robert
Soltyk, deputy foreign editor of the Gazeta Wyborcza, Poland's
largest circulation daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The EU has opened membership talks with the front-runners who
hope to join early in the next decade: Poland, Hungary, the Czech
Republic, Slovenia, Estonia and the Mediterranean island nation of
Cyprus. Another five countries -- Bulgaria, Latvia, Lithuania,
Romania and Slovakia -- will be the second wave to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   But expanding the European family is problematic.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion will cost around $50 billion through 2006, according
to the European Commission, but nobody wants to pick up the bill.
The European Union's 15 current members are divided over how to
proceed and at what speed.
</P>
<P>
   The applicant countries must adopt some 80,000 pages of
intricate legislation and regulations to conform to EU standards.
It is a daunting task considering that many of the countries, which
concentrated earlier on their economic overhaul, are only now
beginning to tackle significant social reforms and junk old
Soviet-era laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``While speed is desirable, quality is essential. Thus, each
candidate will join only when it is ready,'' said Hans van den
Broek, the EU commissioner in charge of expansion.
</P>
<P>
   With a vigorous entrepreneurial class and billions of dollars in
long-term foreign investment, Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic have become the dominant emerging economies of the region.
The signs in Warsaw, Budapest and Prague are unmistakable as
multinationals like Sony, IBM and McDonald's have entered the
markets and illuminated the once-bleak skylines.
</P>
<P>
   Following the collapse of communism a decade ago, Poland enacted
swift and painful economic reforms that worked. Today, only 8
percent of Poland's exports go to Russia, and 64 percent go to the
European Union, a complete turnabout compared to Soviet times.
</P>
<P>
   Poland also represents the region's largest consumer economy,
with 39 million people. In the last 10 years, more than 2 million
new businesses have been formed, mostly by Poles, spawning millions
of new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Poland's economy has slowed as a result of the Russian and Asian
economic shocks, but expanded 5.8 percent in 1998 and is projected
to grow at a hearty 5 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Such success on its own has led some in Poland to wonder why the
country should rush to join the European Union and take on dictates
from Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   More than two out of three Poles support EU membership, though
more than half of them think it will position Poland as a
second-class member in a weak position.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are mixed feelings. People are wondering whether Poland
should be a second-class country in the big leagues, or a
first-class country in its own league,'' said Lena
Kolarska-Bobinska, director of the Foundation of Public Affairs, a
Warsaw-based think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Poland also must address massive problems.
</P>
<P>
   By one estimate, it will cost nearly $30 billion merely to clean
up the environment and bring factories up to EU operating standards
in terms of safety and environmental standards.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity levels still lag well behind Western Europe,
America and Asia. A local joke in Poland goes: ``How many people
work at this factory?'' Answer: ``Half of them.''
</P>
<P>
   A huge task facing Poland will be the overhaul of its system of
2 million mostly small farms, which employs 27 percent of Poland's
workforce -- 3.8 million people.
</P>
<P>
   To become competitive Poland must restructure the system and
consolidate farming into larger operations to make them more
competitive. This, at a time when the EU is trying to reduce its
costly farm-subsidy programs, which consume half of the union's
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Poland, we want EU membership to happen as quickly as
possible and we want it to be as good as possible. These can be
contradictory objectives unless we do it right. The worst thing
would be to join and somehow be considered a second-class member,''
said Artur Zawisza, cabinet secretary for the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Even the euro-skeptics in Poland consider EU membership
inevitable. The prime objective is recognition as something other
than a country in transition.
</P>
<P>
   Poland's success is self-evident. In a dreary stone building
that was once headquarters of Poland's Communist hierarchy during
Soviet times, the Warsaw Stock Exchange now thrives.
</P>
<P>
   If that weren't a vivid enough symbol of Central Europe's
transformation in the past decade, consider this: the stock market
moved to bigger quarters. The building might have been spacious
enough to house the party bosses for decades, but capitalism is
busting out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main task is to make our nation wealthier,'' said Zawisza.
``That's what all the political discussion is about. It is what our
national psychology is about.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
