<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3767 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-GOLD-$ADV26-CO     12-23 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-GOLD-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN POOR KAMCHATKA, A GOLD MINE AWAITS -- BUT AT WHAT PRICE?
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Dec. 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PETROPAVLOVSK-KAMCHATSKY, Russia _ Desperately low on fuel to
run its power plants and short of food to feed its people, this
region suffers grim hardships facing much of Russia amid an
economic crisis and a cruel winter season.
</P>
<P>
   What's a poor Russian region far away from Moscow to do?
</P>
<P>
   There's gold in them there hills.
</P>
<P>
   Embedded in the pristine, snow-capped mountains of the Kamchatka
peninsula in Russia's Far East is a fortune in gold, platinum,
silver and other minerals.
</P>
<P>
   The riches have remained undisturbed for millennia in a remote
wilderness region that boasts more salmon, bears and eagles than
people.
</P>
<P>
   The volcanic mountains are far from civilization in a vast
peninsula that was cloistered for much of this century by Soviet
secrecy. The region's only city, Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky, is home
to a nuclear submarine base and an air force base and thus closed
to foreigners and most Russians before the Soviet Union collapsed
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the 400,000 Russians living in Kamchatka have survived
on the bountiful waters that have made this one of the world's
richest fishing regions.
</P>
<P>
   But the seduction of gold is growing as the sea and rivers are
being overfished and the region's other main employer, the
military, suffers cutbacks by the near-bankrupt federal government
5,000 miles away in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be very important for our area, where unemployment
is very high. It would diversify our economy and bring tremendous
wealth,'' said Alexander Gorbunov, director of industry, energy and
mineral resources for the regional government.
</P>
<P>
   Kamchatka alone could provide 10 percent of Russia's gold
production, as much as $10 billion worth to be mined over the next
few decades.
</P>
<P>
   But a vigilant community of environmentalists and anglers has
fought to ensure that any mining will not spoil the idyllic
landscape of volcanoes, rolling hills, rivers and lakes and one of
the world's largest salmon spawning grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gold is nice only in a museum. Gold mining is a dirty
business,'' said Robert Moisseev, director of the Kamchatka
Institute of Ecology and Nature Management. ``This business
destroys nature.''
</P>
<P>
   This being Russia, where nothing is easy, getting to the gold is
difficult. Despite the interest of American, Canadian and
Australian mining companies, Russia's tangled bureaucracy and
economic morass have made it difficult to do business.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen Western and Russian companies have applied for
permission to mine gold in Kamchatka, but no projects have begun.
The costs are daunting. Roads are poor and helicopters are
necessary to reach the remote region.
</P>
<P>
   The largest proposed project involves a company called Kamgold,
a Russian-U.S.-Canadian joint venture that proposes building an
industrial mining plant in the mountains at Aginskoe. Such plants
produce a potentially dangerous by-product, large volumes of water
tainted with heavy metals and toxins which must be stored in
retention ponds.
</P>
<P>
   For more than four years, the project has been delayed by
environmentalists who have appealed to the Russian government and
the United Nations. The conservationists allege that the mine and
gold-refining plant would pollute the region and the holding ponds
would be susceptible to rupture in the earthquake-prone zone.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 10 million acres of the peninsula were placed on the
list of protected World Heritage Sites by UNESCO, the U.N. agency
which oversees the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how heavy the Russian crisis might be, we don't have
the right to spoil the lives of our next generation,'' Moisseev
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the project's investors are armed with reams of impact
studies which conclude that their plant, which will create about
300 jobs, will not spoil the environment. If there is any
substantial hazard, it is to the Westerners attempting to do
business in Russia's rickety economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take any part of the world, and when mining there is a
technical risk and there is a political risk. In Russia, the
technical risk is zero. The political risk clearly is quite high,''
Robert Buchan, chairman and chief executive of Kinross Corp. said
in a telephone interview from Toronto. Kinross holds a 25 percent
interest and is the managing partner in the Kamchatka
joint-venture.
</P>
<P>
   After the fall of communism in 1991, there was a rush of
interest in mining. But the prospects were more attractive when
gold was at $341 an ounce at its high in April 1997. Now the world
price has dipped below $300, and Russia is in the midst of an
economic and banking crisis which has discouraged many Western
investors.
</P>
<P>
   But it has spawned interest among others. By some local
estimates, freelance prospectors panning and digging without
permits are yielding $50,000 to $60,000 worth of gold in the summer
months, before the rivers freeze and snow covers the hills.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how bad the local economy may be,
environmentalists argue that the risks are not worth it for mines
that would be exhausted within 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Sequestered for decades by Soviet secrecy and dictated to by
leaders in Moscow, Kamchatka now faces a classic dilemma of
democracy -- economy-vs.-environment -- and must decide its fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mining interests say, 'Look how much we could gain for the
economy.' The fishers and environmentalists say, 'But if you dump
your chemicals in the river we will lose it all.' I think the truth
lies in between,'' said Vladimir Yefimov, a local journalist.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
