<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THEN AND NOW, RUSSIANS SUFFER UNDER ECONOMIC CRISIS
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-YEAR-$ADV27.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, December 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A comparison of some key indicators of Russia's economy at the
end of 1997 and the end of 1998:
</P>
<P>
   .............................................End of
1997...................Now
</P>
<P>
   Average
income..................$160...........................$52
</P>
<P>
   (monthly)
</P>
<P>
   Annual
Inflation..................11%.............................70%
(projected)
</P>
<P>
   Ruble value to
US$1............6.1.............................21
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment
%................11.1............................11.6
</P>
<P>
   Back wages owed...............$9.6 billion..........$15.2
billion
</P>
<P>
   (in rubles)
</P>
<P>
   of Russians living
</P>
<P>
   below poverty line.............31 million..............44.3
million
</P>
<P>
   Savings in banks.............$100 billion.............$37.9
billion
</P>
<P>
   Moscow Stock Market...$73.7 billion............$11.0 billion
</P>
<P>
   (capitalization)
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Russian-European Center for Economic Policy; Russian
Central Bank; Moscow Stock Market-Russian Trading System.
</P>
<P>
   LOW EXPECTATIONS . . .
</P>
<P>
   Russians have been battered by their feeble economy since the
Soviet Union disintegrated in 1991. Currency devaluation, bank
failures and inflation have reduced their standard of living and
left them with low expectations for life.
</P>
<P>
   A Moscow-based polling firm surveyed 1,600 Russians in late
November about their aspirations. They were asked whether they
expected merely to survive, to live no worse than others or to live
better than others.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how they responded:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Expect simply to survive at the most basic level
................................ 28%
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Want to live no worse than most families in your city/region
...... 48%
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Want to live better than most families in your city/region
............ 12%
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hope to live as well as the middle class in U.S. or Europe
.................. 9%
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hope to live better than the middle class in U.S. or Europe
................ 3%
</P>
<P>
   Source: Russian Center for Public Opinion and Market Research;
poll results reflect cross-section of Russian public opinion with a
margin of error of +/- 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
