<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3774 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-YEAR-$ADV27-CO     12-23 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YEAR-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AN UNHAPPY NEW YEAR: RUSSIA'S PROBLEMS ARE EXPECTED TO MOUNT IN
1999
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-BOX-$ADV27.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, December 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ There is nothing happy about the New Year for Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Its erratic post-Soviet economy went into a coma last August and
has shown little signs of life since.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin, sick with pneumonia in the fall and
clearly frail throughout the year, remains largely out of sight
from his people and has left a power vacuum at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of Russians have lost their jobs, while
millions simply have not been paid for months. The national
currency, the ruble, has lost two-thirds of its value since the
economic crisis struck on Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   How bad could 1999 be for Russia?
</P>
<P>
   At least as unpleasant, but likely worse, analysts predict.
</P>
<P>
   The worst-case scenario is chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation could degenerate as in the former Yugoslavia.
There is a real danger of the population turning to extreme
nationalistic solutions,'' said Judith Shapiro, co-author of a
status report published this month on Russia for the United Nations
Economic Commission for Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's drive toward democracy is tentative seven years after
the collapse of the Soviet Union. Its deep economic problems have
left the Clinton administration and other Western governments
watching carefully and hoping for the best.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists simply predict more of the same in 1999. The
government under Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov continues to
solicit the International Monetary Fund and others in the West for
aid and meanwhile prints more rubles to pay salaries and keep the
economy limping along.
</P>
<P>
   The ailing Yeltsin, 67, has turned over virtually all his
responsibilities to Primakov, a consensus candidate for the job
after the August crisis.
</P>
<P>
   A Soviet-era spymaster and most recently Russia's foreign
minister, Primakov has plodded forward, concentrating mainly on how
to get Russia through its long winter, but not what to do about its
problems in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking a political truce with the Communist-dominated
parliament, he appointed key Soviet-era economists to his
government. The result was political calm, but few economic
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to expect any sharp turn around,'' said Jan
Lundin of the Russian-European Center for Economic Policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government has announced it will be able to pay only
$9.5 billion out of $17.5 billion in foreign debts in 1999. This
after Russia defaulted on $40 billion in short-term debt --
one-third owed to foreign investors. That move last summer
unsettled the world's financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   To make ends meet, the government wrote a federal budget for
1999 based on an assumption that it will receive $7 billion in
foreign loans -- money that may not materialize from the IMF and
other wary donors who lack confidence that Russia can fix its
structural economic mess.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, ordinary Russians are ignoring their
government's deep political and economic predicament. The nation of
147 million is busy trying to survive the harshest winter in 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow is having difficulty keeping some of its remote areas in
the Arctic and Siberia supplied with food and heating fuel. Some of
the country's more successful regions are hoarding supplies and
cutting ties to the federal government. Poorer regions have
reported that some residents have resorted to eating dogs to stay
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Russian expectations are low. A recent poll showed most
Russians, 76 percent, simply want to live no worse than their
neighbors. Only 12 percent expressed any hope that they could raise
their living standards to match or exceed America's.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of those polled by the Russian Center for Public
Opinion and Market Research said they expect the economy to worsen
in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Political conditions are not much better.
</P>
<P>
   National elections for parliament are scheduled for late 1999,
but presidential elections -- not set to take place until mid-2000
-- could be necessary in 1999 should Yeltsin's health deteriorate
further or another economic shock occur. Potential successors like
Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, and former presidential candidate, and
now Krasnoyarsk Gov. Alexander Lebed are already marshalling
campaign teams.
</P>
<P>
   Without some outside aid in the form of direct loans, Russia
will be forced to print billions more rubles, which inevitability
will weaken the currency and threaten to spark inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF approved a $22.6 billion bailout for Russia last July --
a deal closely overseen by the U.S. Treasury Department -- but put
it on hold after the August crisis. IMF officials want Russia to
carry out promised market reforms and not lurch back toward
hyperinflation and Soviet-style economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the financial support of the IMF it will be hard for
us to repay the debts. Russia risks becoming isolated financially
and I don't think anyone wants that,'' said Deputy Finance Minister
Mikhail Kasyanov.
</P>
<P>
   The worst-case scenario is all-out bankruptcy and hyperinflation
-- inflation in the triple or quadruple digits that could make the
forecasted 70 percent figure for 1998 look attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inflationary problem is like the one with the genie --
once you let it out it is very difficult to put it back in. So you
would have to live with high inflation problems for many, many
years,'' said Lundin.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, Russia has asked the IMF to provide a $4.2 billion
loan installment in 1999. IMF officials are planning to return to
Moscow in early January to consider the request. Without it,
Russia's Finance Ministry forecasts that the economy could contract
by 5 percent to 7 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, analysts are talking about years, not
months, for Russia's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Offering a status report on Russia in December, World Bank vice
president Johannes Linn said the economy could decline another 10
percent to 15 percent in 1999 but ``could regain momentum over the
next 5 or 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``But on the downside, if hyperinflation is not avoided, if
total default on all debts were to be part of an extreme response,
a much more severe decline could be imagined,'' added Linn, who is
responsible for Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
