</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MALE BASHING, PLEASE 
 FOR USE FRI., DEC. 25, OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION: People tell me that I'm independent, attractive,
funny, successful and sexy, but I haven't had a date in eight
months. My gay friends say I'm too strong for today's men and
threaten the pants off all of them.
</P>
<P>
   I'd just like a co-equal relationship in which we're both free
to pursue career goals and then come together to enjoy each other's
company, minds, bodies and incomes. I am ready to be a companion
and partner rather than some little girl wanting a daddy. What's
wrong with men today anyway? _ Valley Stream, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: Hey _ no male-bashing allowed: Men aren't the problem,
but they aren't the solution either.
</P>
<P>
   We are a society in transition. Many men feel that the gains
women have made in the workplace have been at the expense of the
male ego. They are unsure not only of what women want from them but
don't know if women want them at all. Most men long for the good
old days when everybody had a place.
</P>
<P>
   Since a powerful man can have his choice of females, he most
often will choose one who makes him feel good about himself and
doesn't threaten his masculinity. Powerful women, laboring under
the old-fashioned male standard, naively assume that they too are
entitled to their choice of men in society. They opt for a powerful
man with whom they can be coequal, but that powerful man is opting
for a lesser woman who is willing to defer to his needs. Instant
problem.
</P>
<P>
   As powerful women become more common, as power is redefined, as
relationships and male and female roles are redefined, powerful men
and women may or may not be together, but most likely powerful
women are going to have to decide to deal with a non-traditional
male or choose to revert to a ``traditional'' female role or go it
alone.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I retired to Costa Rica in 1991 after a career in the
U.S. Immigration Service. At 67, I have a 21-year-old son in
college who has made me very happy, but I am still living with the
regrets of losing my children from my first marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Before my twin sons were a year old, I was divorced and ruined
financially. I saw them only twice in the next three years as I
struggled to afford a lawyer to fight for my right to see them. The
judge threatened their mother with jail if she didn't allow me to
see them, but when I arrived to pick them up, the house was empty.
</P>
<P>
   Private investigators finally found them for me when they were
18, but they wanted nothing to do with me and considered me a
stranger. They are now 42 years old and are both dentists in
California. I send letters and cards each birthday and Christmas,
but they do not respond. I am tired of waiting for them to
acknowledge me, but how can I ease decades of pain? _ San Jose,
Costa Rica
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: What a sad situation! The only bond you have with your
twin sons is genetic. From their point of view, you really are a
stranger. We can't undo the past, but we can create family today.
Find some younger adults close by with whom you can become involved
on a daily give-and-take basis. They can serve the function of your
lost children.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: Joy, I'm in my final year of a social work degree and
required to take two psychology courses: introductory and child
development. I hate psych and am barely passing. Is there any way I
can make learning about this stuff more interesting? I've tried to
apply it to everyday life situations but that isn't always easy. _
Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: I'm a great fan of psychology as well as a
practitioner. Psychology is about understanding why people do what
do they. Before you give up on applying it to everyday life
situations, apply some of that psychological jargon in a little
self-analysis. How are you going to be a social worker if you don't
care about why people act as they do?
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: Do I have to tell people my age? I'm single and I
don't know what to say when guys ask me how old I am. I don't want
to lie, but I don't want to turn them off right away. _ Des Moines,
Iowa
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: It doesn't have anything to do with being single or
with telling a man your age. I just smile sweetly and say one of
two things: I'm timeless and ageless, or Everyone in my family is
29. I'm 29; my mother's 29, my daughter's 29. Or I'm honest about
it and say I always lie about my age.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne, c/o The New York Times
Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, NY 10168, or to
drjoy &LR; nytsyn.com. Questions of general interest will be answered in
this weekly column. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished letters cannot
be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   Copyright 1998 by Dr. Joy Browne Distributed by New York Times
Special Features
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   For information on subscribing to Dr. Joy, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
