<HEADER>
A3797 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-HOLLYWOOD-STARS-     12-23 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-HOLLYWOOD-STARS-OSCARS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OSCAR GUESSING GAME GETS UNDERWAY 
</HEADLINE>
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slide and black and white photo of Roberto Benigni in ``Life
is Beautiful'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's soon going to be Oscar time again in Hollywood, but no one
seems all that impressed with this year's list of potential
candidates.
 &HT;    ``It's a very thin year,'' laments producer-director Irwin
Winkler of ``Rocky'' (1976) and ``Goodfellas'' (1990) fame.
 &HT;    ``I haven't seen much that's really knocked me out,'' agrees
Steve Tisch, producer of ``Forrest Gump'' (1994) and ``American
History X'' (1998).
 &HT;    Nonetheless both Hollywood veterans are talking _ as everybody
in Hollywood does this time of year _ about the Oscar race in
March.
 &HT;    Who's in, who's out? Whose chances are climbing and whose
momentum has slipped? It's a year the much praised _ some would say
overpraised _ ``Saving Private Ryan'' from Steven Spielberg would
seem to have a lock on a Best Picture nomination. But don't count
on it.
 &HT;    Way back in 1969, the winner of the Best Picture and the Best
Foreign film were one and the same _ Costa Gavras' political
thriller ``Z.'' Could 1999 be the year it happens again with
Italian actor/director/producer Roberto Benigni's hymn to the
positive _ ``Life is Beautiful''?
 &HT;    While ``Saving Private Ryan'' was much admired for its brutal
battle scenes, pundits say it didn't inspire the kind of devotion
that brings Oscars. The Italian contender, on the contrary, sent
audiences into the streets to call their friends, and that's the
kind of momentum that often makes a difference. I wouldn't be
surprised to see a best picture, best actor and director for
Benigni.
 &HT;    This was the year some pricey movies fell by the wayside. Oprah
Winfrey's ``Beloved'' was an expensive bomb. Brad Pitt's ``Meet Joe
Black'' was a disaster as was Robin Williams' ``What Dreams May
Come.'' ``Primary Colors'' was a clever sophisticated adaptation of
a clever sophisticated book _ too clever, some say. So don't expect
much in the way of nominations except the brilliant Kathy Bates a
Best supporting actress candidate for ``Primary Colors.''
 &HT;    This year's surprise hit a la ``The Full Monty'' (1997) could be
``Waking Ned Devine,'' which has charm, Irish blarney, the always
popular lust for life and the kind of independent stamp that these
days often produces winners.
 &HT;    A rival to ``Saving Private Ryan'' could be another World War II
film, ``The Thin Red Line.'' But it didn't open until late
December, and only then in limited release.
 &HT;    In fact many of the big studio contenders this year didn't open
until Christmas. Among them ``Stepmom'' with Susan Sarandon and
Julia Roberts, ``A Civil Action'' with John Travolta, and
Dreamworks animated contender ``Prince of Egypt.''
 &HT;    Traditionally, the later in the year a movie is released the
more likely it is to get a nomination. Early releases sometimes get
forgotten. ``Zorro'' was charming and Anthony Hopkins gave a
performance of style and grace as the elder Zorro. ``The Truman
Show'' with Jim Carrey, on the other hand, is likely to remembered
on Oscar night.
 &HT;    So who's hot and who's not? Don't be misled by critics from the
major cities. The Los Angeles film critics awarded best screenplay
to Warren Beatty for ``Bulworth'' _ a film that moviegoers rightly
ignored.
 &HT;    So here are some likely contenders.
 &HT;    The illness stakes: Emily Watson as cellist Jacqueline du Pre
battling multiple sclerosis in ``Hilary and Jackie,'' versus fellow
British actress Helena Bonham Carter playing a wheelchair bound
victim of Lou Gehrig's disease in ``The Theory of Flight.''
 &HT;    The history prize: ``Elizabeth'' with Cate Blanchett as the
queen versus ``Shakespeare in Love'' with Gwyneth Paltrow _ plus a
great best supporting role by Judi Dench as Queen Elizabeth.
 &HT;    WW II stakes: In one corner there's Spielberg's ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' and in the other ``The Thin Red Line.'' In the middle is
``Life is Beautiful.''
 &HT;    Smiling through the tears award: ``One True Thing'' with Meryl
Streep, versus ``Stepmom'' with Susan Sarandon. (Streep could tie
herself with her other likely best actress contender ``Dancing at
Lughnasa.'' )
 &HT;    The great book becomes great film stakes: ``Primary Colors''
versus ``A Civil Action'' versus ``A Simple Plan.''
 &HT;    And here are my picks in main categories:
 &HT;    Best Actor: Tom Hanks ``Saving Private Ryan.'' (Unlikely because
he won twice before.) Sir Ian McKellan, ``Gods and Monsters,''
Roberto Benigni, ``Life is Beautiful'' (because he's so talented
and reminds everyone of Charlie Chaplin and Buster Keaton.) Jim
Carrey who kept his mugging under control in ``The Truman Show,''
and Edward Norton as the racist skinhead in ``American History X.''
 &HT;    Best actress: Cate Blanchett for ``Elizabeth.'' (Her acting was
Glenda Jackson style and the Academy loves that). Meryl Streep,
``One True Thing,'' Gywneth Paltrow, ``Shakespeare in Love,'' Emily
Watson, ``Hilary and Jackie'' (if enough voters see it) and Helena
Bonham Carter for ``The Theory of Flight.'' (because she lost for
the 1997 film ``The Wings of The Dove'')
 &HT;    Best Director: Spielberg for ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Peter Weir
for ``The Truman Show,'' Shekhar Kapur for ``Elizabeth,'' Roberto
Benigni for ``Life is Beautiful,'' and John Madden for
``Shakespeare in Love,'' or Terence Malick for ``The Thin Red
Line'' (Hollywood loves a redemption story and Malick is certainly
that.)
 &HT;    Best picture: ``Saving Private Ryan,'' ``Elizabeth,'' ``The
Truman Show,'' ``Life is Beautiful'' and ``Shakespeare in Love.''
 c.1998 Ivor Davis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
