<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUR FLIES OVER FURBY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hottest-selling toy this Christmas is the Furby, a fat,
squat, Gremlin-like thingy that costs $30, assuming you can find
one, which you can't.
</P>
<P>
   As they did with Tickle-Me-Elmo and Cabbage Patch dolls in years
gone by, many parents have convinced themselves that they must have
a Furby. Fights have broken out in toy-store aisles as dazed,
glassy-eyed moms and dads, wired from 300 miles of high-speed
driving, sacrifice their last shred of dignity for a
battery-operated assemblage of microprocessors and cheap, plastic
gears that will most likely cease working long before the tree
comes down.
</P>
<P>
   Listen up, parents: It does not have to be this way.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you need to do is stop looking at this Furby
thing as some sort of personal challenge. It is one thing to pursue
a heart or liver transplant obsessively for your sick child; it is
another thing entirely to kick and gouge one another over a fuzzy
doll.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking the Furby habit is a lot like kicking the cigarette
habit: You've got to convince yourself that your life will be
better without a Furby than with it.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you light one up and smoke it, you will probably not get
cancer or heart disease from a Furby. Still, the little suckers
have lots of unappealing qualities over and above the fact that you
can't find one.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ Furbys look like a cross among a penguin, an owl and a kitten.
Genetic engineering is a troubling-enough subject, what with
who-knows-how-many identical sheep roaming the planet, without
exposing our children to this kind of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Furbys talk. Parents should not invite a talking anything into
their homes, let alone the grotesque aftermath of some sick,
twisted cloning experiment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Furbys are of undetermined sex. Kids get all they need of that
kind of stuff from Marilyn Manson music videos. Why encourage it?
</P>
<P>
   _ You can buy a Furby off the Internet for $300. Anytime you
hear the words ``Internet'' and ``buy'' used in the same sentence,
you should grab your wallet with one hand and lock the door with
the other. Add the word ``Furby'' and you are talking serious
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Furby was invented by a 47-year-old guy named ``Dave.''
Forty-seven-year-old guys named ``Dave'' should be writing
semi-amusing columns for a mid-size, chain-owned newspaper situated
somewhere in the love-bug-infested swamps of Southwest Florida, not
soldering sexually ambivalent pieces of penguins, owls and kittens
together into something that can be bought on the Internet for
$300.
</P>
<P>
   _ Furbys can speak to one another in a language called
``Furbish.'' It is not good to have toys that talk. It is
especially not good to have toys that talk to one another in a
language we cannot understand. While I am not saying that the 2
million Furbys sold so far are plotting world conquest, I think it
is safe to say that if such a thing were to happen, most of us
would sell on the Internet for considerably less than $300.
</P>
<P>
   _ When they're not plotting the overthrow of the human race,
Furbys pout, burp, get bored, make raspberry sounds, sing, dance
and pass gas. Your kids can get all of this stuff for free by
watching ``South Park'' or ``Ren and Stimpy'' cartoons. And no
batteries are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   _ Although they respond to the spoken word, Furbys cannot really
carry on a conversation. Do we really need another teen-ager in the
house?
</P>
<P>
   There you go, parents! Feel free to use any or all of these
reasons as you attempt to explain to your grief-stricken child on
Christmas morning why every other kid on the planet got a Furby
except her!
</P>
<P>
   Good luck!
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
