<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAVIAR-ART-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CAVIAR, A NEW WORLD ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rl) 
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A caviar connoisseur is someone who relishes the various. Bursting
between the tongue and the roof of the mouth, caviar never tastes
the same. Its flavor varies from fish to fish, region to region,
season to season. That is part of its allure.
</P>
<P>
   But this year the variety is less alluring than it is baffling.
The world of caviar _ from the harvesting to the selling to the
buying and tasting _ has degenerated into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The market is glutted with stale, substandard caviar shipped
before more stringent import regulations took effect in April,
although fresh, pristine caviar imported since then is also
available. For the first time, a significant amount of caviar is
being imported from China. Add the growing amount of farm-raised
caviar from California, Russia and France, and you get an array of
choices that can be thrilling _ and confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the confusion is mostly a symptom of transition.
The new regulations from the Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species, or Cites (the acronym is pronounced
SIGHT-ease), seek to protect the threatened sturgeon by regulating
its harvesting and the taking of its caviar. By April 1999, people
in the industry say, the substandard caviar predating the
regulations will be gone. Labeling will be clearer, quality will be
more consistent and prices will reflect the grade of the eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, buying caviar this season is complicated, and a
mistake can be costly: Beluga is going for as much as $150 an
ounce. ``What's so great about this?'' is a perceptive response to
the taste of most caviar being sold in New York right now.
</P>
<P>
   And if all that weren't enough, last week three distributors
were indicted on federal charges of smuggling illegal caviar into
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   News like this compounds the confusion that has surrounded
caviar since the breakup of the Soviet Union, the source of most
caviar. Before, a central authority controlled the caviar industry
and protected the sturgeon stock and, ultimately, the consumer.
Today the Caspian Sea waters that were regulated are worked by
fishermen from two independent republics (Kazakhstan and
Azerbaijan) and two Russian regions (Astrakhan and Degestan),
producing caviar whose taste and quality are completely
unpredictable. Overfishing and poaching are rife, as are unskilled
handling and processing of the precious roe.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the American trade embargo against Iran, no Iranian
caviar can be legally imported into the country, but some caviar
dealers are nevertheless using the Iranian grading system as a
marketing tool. Triple-zero beluga was the best, double-zero second
best, single-zero runner-up; A-rated osetra was top-grade, B
something less. Sevruga was graded 1 (best) and 2 (second best).
But those grades are not reliable indicators of quality. Even the
Russian term malossol, which means ``little salt,'' is a marketing
tool; the saltiness varies from tin to tin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to anarchy on the banks of the Caspian, there are
the newcomers. China has developed a caviar industry that is
shipping tons of caviar to the United States this year. Fishermen
along the Mississippi River are landing hackleback sturgeon, and
the roe from those fish is being sold as caviar, along with that of
paddlefish from the Great Lakes. Stolt Sea Farms in Sacramento,
Calif., has developed some excellent caviar from farm-raised
sturgeon, as have five tiny sturgeon farms in France and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Some retailers are trying to wedge these new varieties into the
three traditional classes of caviar _ beluga, osetra and sevruga _
thus diminishing the meaning of those terms. Other retailers are
coining names like Royal Black for the new caviars, which may be
poetic but say little about the taste, quality or provenance of the
roe.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to clarify the meaning of the traditional terms,
and to assess the most serious contenders among the new types of
caviar, I recently convened a panel of six tasters to compare 16
types.
</P>
<P>
   To compose the panel, I surveyed a dozen of Manhattan's top
chefs for the caviar tasters and purveyors they most trusted, and
combined their suggestions with my own experience buying caviar
over 15 years in Manhattan. The panelists were Eric Ripert, chef of
Le Bernardin; Eve Vega, president of American operations for
Petrossian, which has offices in Paris and New York; Hossein
Aimani, owner of Paramount Caviar in Manhattan; Rod Mitchell, an
owner of the Browne Trading Company in Portland, Maine; Florence
Fabricant, who writes about food for The New York Times, and
myself. We sampled wholesale specimens, which are often repackaged
under a retailer's own name.
</P>
<P>
   We found that 1998 is not a good year for sevruga, the scarcest
caviar right now, but is fairly good for osetra and beluga, the top
types, from Kazakhstan. The quality of Astrakhan caviar is
inconsistent. And we were stunned to find the Sterling caviar,
which comes from farm-raised sturgeon in California, comparable to
the best osetra.
</P>
<P>
   But the main object of the tasting was not to rank the samples _
indeed, we tasted only the best caviar that is available. Our
effort was to identify the characteristics of the main types of
caviar being sold in New York City today, and to compile a sort of
Baedeker of caviar _ a guide to buying, selecting and enjoying the
season's ultimate indulgence.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Techniques
</P>
<P>
   Would you buy a diamond without seeing it? Don't buy caviar
without sampling it first, and don't be intimidated _ it is
customary to ask for a taste. And if you don't like what you taste,
don't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh caviar should glisten; upon close inspection, the eggs
should be luminous, pert-looking and consistent in size and color.
If they look noticeably different, different grades of caviar may
have been mixed together and the offering inaccurately labeled and
overpriced. Smashed or misshapen eggs are likely to have been
mishandled or frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Caviar should not smell fishy. The grains should be firm, but
not rubbery or tough. Hard grains usually mean that the caviar has
been pasteurized, which destroys its integrity.
</P>
<P>
   For higher-priced caviars, the purveyor should be able to show
you a copy of his Cites permit, which includes a detailed account
of where the fish was harvested and processed. (The fish will be
identified by its Latin name _ Huso huso instead of beluga, for
instance). If you are spending top dollar, you are paying for
freshness; you want evidence that it was harvested last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Tasting Techniques
</P>
<P>
   Use small spoons made of bone or mother-of-pearl, which do not
affect the flavor of caviar. (Most metal spoons impart unpleasant
metallic notes; even plastic is preferable.)
</P>
<P>
   Before tasting, inhale the aroma; there should be very little.
Then slip the caviar into your mouth. As it sits on your tongue,
pull a little air into your mouth, close your eyes and, without
hesitation or any attempt at delicacy, crush the eggs by forcing
them against the roof of your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate taste should be oceanic. The middle sensations
should evoke earthier things: fruit, nuts, even truffles. The final
sensation should be a slight brininess, tinged with the sort of
coppery nuance of a Belon oyster. The overall impression is the
balance of the disparate sensations in the mouth. This final
equation lingers; don't rush to a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Varieties
</P>
<P>
   BELUGA (Huso huso, $50 to $150 an ounce). The king of the 27
varieties of sturgeon that produce edible roe, beluga has a snub
nose and the appearance of a pit bull. It can grow 20 feet long and
weigh a ton. It takes 15 to 20 years to reach maturity, lives about
150 years and can contain up to 15 percent of its body weight in
roe.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions in the Caspian Sea, where temperatures can become
tropical in the day and freezing at night, seem to produce the most
succulent beluga.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, beluga caviar is pale to steel gray; the eggs are
the largest, and perhaps the most tender. The texture is buttery,
and the flavor is the most delicate of all caviar; it should taste
less salty than oceanic. Beluga can have hints of nuts or fruit and
can finish with a subtle copper taste or a delicate herbaceous
flavor, depending on its origin.
</P>
<P>
   This year's beluga from Kazakhstan, a seat of the caviar
industry from the days of the czars, has a nice bead that tends to
be quite large. The flavor is very buttery; the texture creamy; the
overall impression sultry and deep.
</P>
<P>
   Beluga from Astrakhan can be the most pronounced in flavor, yet
most subtle of all. But production difficulties have made the
supply inconsistent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Russian beluga is almost always from the old Guryev fishery and
is milder and mushier this year than beluga from Kazakhstan or
Astrakhan. While the fruitiness is pronounced, it tastes more
acidic than delicate.
</P>
<P>
   Beluga from the Sea of Azov is very mixed in quality this year.
It tends to have a small egg, closer to black than gray. While it
can have a mild, creamy taste, the muddy flavors of the egg tend to
overpower all other nuances.
</P>
<P>
   Beluga from the Amur River, which forms a part of the
Russian-Chinese border, is not impressive. The eggs vary and tend
to be smallish and very separate, with a greenish hue. They have a
sharp, herbaceous taste that is not unpleasant, but not buttery,
either. If the taster were not expecting the rich creaminess of a
Caspian beluga, Amur River caviar might represent a whole new
tasty, affordable world.
</P>
<P>
   OSETRA (Acipenser gueldenstaedti, $14.50 to $75 an ounce). The
fish has an elongated jawbone like a swordfish and can grow to 7
feet long and about 400 pounds. It reaches maturity in 12 years,
lives about 40 years and can contain nearly 3 pounds of roe. Chefs
tend to prefer osetra to beluga: the egg is firmer, and the color
varies from gold to dark brown. Osetra is rich and nutty tasting.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan has produced a large quantity of osetra this year. It
has a large, light-colored bead, often tortoise-shell in tone, with
a rich hazelnut flavor and a clean, smooth, oceanic taste.
</P>
<P>
   Russian osetra from Guryev comes in two distinct types this
year. One has a smaller bead, with a pronounced briny flavor and
tart finish. It tastes peppy and young, but doesn't have its usual
voluptuousness. The other has a big, voluptuous bead, a tawny color
and a rich, almondy taste.
</P>
<P>
   Osetra from the Amur River is very mixed in quality but has been
steadily improving as China's processing improves. Caviar labeled
Amur River most likely comes from China, and like the beluga, the
osetra grade is typically fresh and sprightly. It's a nice,
easy-eating caviar _ good but very different from its Caspian Sea
cousins.
</P>
<P>
   FARMED AMERICAN STURGEON (Acipenser transmontanus, $35 an
ounce). Domestic caviar has come into its own this year. Virtually
all of it comes from Stolt Sea Farms in Sacramento, whose top grade
is called Sterling caviar and is comparable to Kazakhstan osetra in
both quality and price. The bead is small and firm, with a lively
pop, a subtle hint of the sea and a deep, pronounced hazelnut
flavor. The color ranges from violet to a nearly cream-colored
gold, touching all the steely and tawny points between.
</P>
<P>
   SHIP (Acipenser nudiventris, $12 to $23 an ounce). The ship, a
Caspian Sea sturgeon, is being most closely monitored because its
numbers are dwindling. It is traditionally mixed with osetra or
sevruga. This year, with mixing illegal, some ship caviar is being
sold on its own. It falls between osetra and sevruga in appearance,
but has a flavor like that of sevruga _ intense, but with an odd
and indefinable musty, dusty aftertaste. The bead tends to be quite
dark and small.
</P>
<P>
   SEVRUGA (Acipenser stellatus, $7 to $25 an ounce). This is the
smallest of the three sturgeon that produce luxury caviars, at a
little over 5 feet and 70 pounds. It matures in seven years but
produces precious little caviar, an average of a little over 11
pounds per fish. Because it matures young, sevruga sustained the
most damage from overfishing after the breakup of the Soviet Union
and is therefore the most likely to be mixed with ship caviar, or
roe from American hackleback or paddlefish.
</P>
<P>
   The best comes from Russia this year: tiny, glittering, nearly
black eggs with a characteristically intense flavor, deep on the
briny side, with a dark, dangerous sexiness as opposed to the
languid sensuality of both beluga and osetra. Very, very little
good sevruga is available.
</P>
<P>
   KALUGA (Huso dauricus, $15 to $25 an ounce). This sturgeon is
harvested from the Amur River; if it is landed on the eastern
banks, it is Chinese; on the western banks, Russian. The eggs are
firm, large and beautiful; they seem to glow a deep olive green and
tortoise. Their taste is less breathtaking: lighter, fresher and
younger than Caspian beluga. Kaluga shares part of its Latin name
with beluga and is often mislabeled either beluga or osetra,
depending on the size of its egg.
</P>
<P>
   PRESSED CAVIAR (About $15 an ounce). A jammy confection made of
broken beluga, osetra and sevruga, this can be very good indeed. If
you plan to cook with it _ in an omelet, as a topping for potatoes,
as a filling for crepes or even blini _ pressed caviar is an
economical option. Unfortunately, very little good-quality pressed
caviar is available this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
