 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
All things considered, I'd rather use a mouse 
By Jack Warner  
c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Under the heading of ``What Will They Think of Next,''
we have for our examination and amusement today the Cruise Cat from
Cirque, a touchpad device aimed at the Internet addict.
</P>
<P>
   The Cruise Cat is a modified touchpad-pointing device, a thin
little pad that connects to a serial port and does not cancel out
or confuse your mouse. It simply competes with it for your
attention.
</P>
<P>
   In case you have no experience with a touchpad device _ they
have become rather common as built-in pointing devices on laptops _
it is simply a little panel on which you lightly move your finger
to control the mouse, tap gently for a single click and double-tap
for a double-click.
</P>
<P>
   They work as well as a mouse. Whether you would prefer one to a
mouse is another matter. Personally, I have seen no alternative
device that suits me as well as a mouse. This is due in large part,
certainly, to the fact I learned to use a mouse years ago and it is
second nature.
</P>
<P>
   It was interesting to see the reaction of many of the newsroom
staff when the personal computer, in the form of Macintoshes, made
its appearance. Those who had never used a mouse had no end of
trouble for a while. Some never got used to them and wound up with
trackballs by preference. I find trackballs to be a minor torture
device.
</P>
<P>
   For me, touchpads are a decent alternative to a mouse, better
than trackballs and a lot better than those stupid stubby sticks
they put in the middle of laptop keyboards. However, if a mouse is
available, I'll use that in preference to anything else.
</P>
<P>
   The Cruise Cat has some interesting embellishments _ chief among
them the gesture.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind this is cute. If, for instance, you want to look
at your bookmarks, you draw a little B and voila! here come your
bookmarks. If you want to close the active program, you describe an
X with your finger on the pad.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a fatal flaw here. You can't just suddenly
scribble an X on the pad and do anything but move the mouse around.
First, you must place a finger in a depression to one side of the
screen and wait for a little image of the Cruise Cat to appear.
Then you make your symbol on that image. Now, if you compare the
act of pressing the finger into a depression to produce a little
box on which you then draw an X to the simple act of seizing the
mouse, moving the cursor to the Close box with a simple little
wrist movement and clicking a button, you can see we are not
talking convenience here. We're talking gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   The Cruise Cat is doubtless the spawn of some wunderkind at
Cirque Corp. who conceived of yet another way to market the Glide
Point pad. In fact, the Cruise Cat has no particular attachment to
the Internet. You can create your own gestures, and they will work
anywhere, in any program I tried. None, however, turns out to be as
easy as using the mouse for the same task.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cruise Cat sounds really catchy, does it not? We can
carry this idea almost anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Why not give it a few built-in gestures to accomplish basic
tasks in Word 7 such as inserting the date or saving the file, fix
it all up and market it as Word Wompus? Tie in a few calculations
and presto! Excel Eel.
</P>
<P>
   Two or more can play this game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
