<SLUG> BC-CPT-VIRUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Network Associates Says Killer Virus Hit MCI WorldCom  
 By Benny Evangelista   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new, highly sophisticated computer virus that installs itself
in network servers surfaced last week in MCI WorldCom Inc.'s
corporate system.
</P>
<P>
   Network Associates Inc., the world's leading maker of anti-virus
software, publicized the existence of the new Remote Explorer virus
yesterday, calling it the ``most destructive virus ever seen.''
However, the Santa Clara company added that so far, the damage was
limited and a cure already is available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does represent an entirely new kind of virus, but at this
point, there's no reason to panic,'' said Peter Watkins, general
manager for Network Associates' security division.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said Remote Explorer was programmed to install itself
primarily into Microsoft Windows NT network computer servers and
workstations though it also can reside on, but not infect, Unix
systems. The virus systematically encrypts documents and other
files with a code that has to be unlocked before the files can be
accessed again.
</P>
<P>
   He said the virus appears to be the work of a technologically
savvy programmer and ``is the first one that is really targeted at
attacking a network environment.''
</P>
<P>
   It was far more sophisticated than other viruses like the new MS
Word Macro 97 Class Virus, which also recently appeared, that
normally are activated by a computer user opening a file or
document.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not (the work of) a weekend hacker; this is a pro,''
Watkins said. ``It's scary. This is a completely new strain that is
self-propagating.''
</P>
<P>
   Network Associates would only say Remote Explorer was discovered
last Thursday in one of its Fortune 100 clients, but it declined to
name the company. However, MCI WorldCom spokesman Jim Monroe
confirmed that MCI is so far the only known victim of the Remote
Explorer virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We detected it very quickly, and it had no impact on our
customers,'' Monroe said. The company is investigating how the
virus entered the system, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said the virus was only programmed to encrypt files and
that it also was programmed to move more rapidly between 3 p.m. and
6 a.m. weekdays and all day Saturday and Sunday, when program
administrators normally are not at work.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, however, could have been programmed for greater
destruction, such as deleting files, Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Network Associates has a Remote Explorer detection program
available to its customers and is working on a program to clean up
files infected by the virus, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bradshaw, spokesman for Network Associates' chief rival,
Symantec Corp., said his company has not encountered another
instance of the virus and was awaiting a sample from Network
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   COL. 1 of VIRUS22 (84030 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Peter Rogers of Volpe Brown Whelan said it was too soon
to tell whether Remote Explorer will erupt into an epidemic, but he
said technology has always found a cure for viruses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of sophistication and complexity of viruses has
increased pretty dramatically,'' Rogers said. ``Each level has been
overcome by technology, and I suspect that will be the case here.''
</P>
<P>
   Network Associates stock rose 12 percent to close at $60.38, up
$6.38. Rogers said news of the virus had an effect but that Network
Associates also benefited from a strong market for technology
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-21-98 2223EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
