<HEADER>
A3872 &Cx1f; tic-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-A     12-23 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS BRIGHTENS UP WEB, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID HOYE   
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Ho, ho, ho! Merry computing, everyone!
</P>
<P>
   Santa Claus just sent me an e-mail, and it says I should write
about stuff to help get people into the holiday spirit! If I don't,
Mr. Claus says he's going to replace my operating system with coal.
</P>
<P>
   So I best get cracking!
</P>
<P>
   - Want to treat the kids to something a bit different this
Christmas? Check out www.eaze.net/citius//santa.htm. It offers a
program for PCs called Tracking Santa. The shareware ($6.99 to
register) offers a world map that ``tracks'' Santa on Christmas
Eve, holiday songs, a version of the Christmas Story and features
you can customize for your family. It runs on Windows 3.1, 95, 98
or NT. My advice: If this interests you, download it now and test
it. You don't want to disappoint the kids on Christmas Eve!
</P>
<P>
   - There's still a few days left before Christmas. And, if you're
like most people, you'll have to work right up until Christmas Eve.
Not to worry. My advice: Goof off at work! The easiest way is to
download and play with ``Twinkle Bulbs.'' It's the shareware you
probably saw a co-worker using last year. It allows users to
decorate their desktops with Christmas lights. Find them at
softseek.mdonline.net/DesktopEnhancements/FunStuff/Review42 &QL; 
16index.html.
</P>
<P>
   - Want a laugh? You'll think this version of '`'Twas the Night
Before Christmas'' is funny if you know anything about computer
programmers. Find it at www.citilink.com/
jgarrick/vbasic/humor/nightbeforechristmas.html.
</P>
<P>
   - ``Away in a manger, ya da da da dum, dee dum . . .'' I can
never remember the words to all those holiday songs. Can you? If
not, check out www.primenet.com/kringle/. You'll find the words and
some decent .wav files that will have you singing in no time!
</P>
<P>
   - Well, the geese and maids-a-milking still cost the same as
last year. But just about everything else in the traditional song,
``The Twelve Days of Christmas,'' cost more in 1998. Check out an
official accounting at www.pncbank.com/12days/.
</P>
<P>
   - Oh yes. I know you want to hear them. Yes, yes. You deny it.
Go ahead. But you'll sneak back to your desk to listen to them
again later, won't you? I'm talking, of course, about ``Jingle
Cats'' and ``Jingle Dogs'' and, yes, this year's special, ``Jingle
Pigs.'' And they're not just singing, they're in QuickTime movies!
Find them at www.forthnet.gr/astronet/business/jingles/index.htm.
</P>
<P>
   - Looking for images of Santa or Rudolph? Check out a new image
search site called Arriba Vista at www.arribavista.com. It works
pretty well, offering up a quick list of images available on the
Internet. The folks behind the site were billing it as
``pornography free.' But I managed to pull up some off-color images
with a single search. (No, I won't tell you how!) The Arriba Vista
folks said they'll stop claiming the site is porn-free, but
maintain that they've taken many steps, including blocking specific
Web sites and search terms, to keep pornographic images from
showing up during searches. They deserve some credit for their
effort. So, give it a try, but be forewarned that Arriba Vista
isn't perfect. (I'm not sure any site is!)
</P>
<P>
   - If you have the urge to cook this holiday season, and you'd
like to try something besides that pork stuffing dish your mother
always made, check out Christmas Recipe.com at
www.christmasrecipe.com. The site offers a wide variety of recipes
and cooking tips. There's also a glossary so you can look up
confusing ingredients. Additionally, the site allows users to
search its recipe database for just the right dish. You can search
using any keyword or ingredient. Yum!
</P>
<P>
   - The final days before Christmas can be hectic. Gifts to buy.
Rooms to clean. Relatives arriving. And, of course, the kids are
out of school! Want to keep them busy? Check out the Crafts for
Christmas page at www.imagitek.com/xmas/crafts. The site offers
basic instructions for many holiday crafts, including snowflakes
you can hang on the tree, paper angels, tin can toys and lots more.
</P>
<P>
   - When Uncle Harry starts boring everybody with his know-it-all
attitude, ask him if he knows how cold it is at the North Pole.
Then, stand up and say, ```You know, Harry, we can find out real
quick if you're right!'' Then, check out The Weather Channel's
North Pole page at www.weather.com/northpole/. If Harry is wrong,
maybe he'll stay quiet for a couple days. Then again, he might be
right!
</P>
<P>
   - Want to send Santa some e-mail? It's getting late, but you can
still give it a shot. One site to check is Santa's Official Web
Site at northpole4kids.netnation.com/1998/america/west/server.htm.
You can send e-mail not only to Santa, but to Rudolph, the elves
and others. While you're there, you can check out the Christmas
tunes, stories, contests and lots more! While you're at it, try
www.santaclausonline.com/, which offers many of the same features.
</P>
<P>
   - Every year, the U.S. Postal Service receives thousands of
letters from kids across America to Santa Claus. The USPS has
created a special Web site that honors this tradition, and allows
visitors to read some of the very best letters to Santa. Find it at
www.usps.gov/letters/volume2/santa-main.html. (You best keep a dry
hanky handy.)
</P>
<P>
   - Uh-oh. You just opened the mailbox and found a Christmas card
from somebody who wasn't on your list! Don't panic! If they have an
e-mail address, you can send them an electronic holiday greeting
card free. There are many Web sites that offer this service. One
you can try is www.123greetings.com/christmas/. Have fun!
</P>
<P>
   - Ever heard of the term ```Webring?'' It's a way Web sites of
similar topics can group themselves together. It's kind of like an
advertising co-op. Similar sites link to each other. Tap into the
right Webring, and you might find hundreds of sites offering what
you need. You can tap into Santa's Christmas Webring at &QL; 
members.aol.com/Lisa1929/santa.html. Links toward the bottom of the
page allow visitors to visit random sites in the Webring or view an
entire list of all the sites that belong. Sure, it's not that much
different from using a Web directory, such as Yahoo! But give it a
shot!
</P>
<P>
   - OK, so the guy across the street put up enough Christmas
lights to attract attention from astronauts in the space shuttle.
Well, be glad you don't live across the street from Nat George. He
spends weeks each year putting up his Centralia, Wash., display.
And if that ain't enough, he has a Web site to show it all to those
who can't drive by! Check it out at
www2.localaccess.com/NGeorge/lights/.
</P>
<P>
   - Hey, guess what. They celebrate Christmas all over the world!
Yep. I figured you'd like to know that. Anyways, there's a great
Web site at christmas.com/worldview/ that will show you h ow the
celebrations are conducted. The site features a clickable world map
and information ranging from music to recipes.
</P>
<P>
   - OK, here's one last site: If the kids keep asking, ``Mom, how
much longer is it until Santa comes?'' Don't scream. Sit them down
in front of the computer and call up Nick's Countdown 'Til
Christmas!! page. It's at
home.weborbiter.com/users/user2/countdwn.htm. The page displays the
exact number of days, hours, minutes and seconds left until the Big
Day.
</P>
<P>
   That's about it. Hope it makes you happy, and keeps Santa off my
case! &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-21-98 1349EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
