<HEADER>
A3947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-CHRISTMAS-1224-C     12-23 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-CHRISTMAS-1224-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CUBA CELEBRATES CHRISTMAS, BUT SANTA CLAUS ISN'T INVITED
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ This week, Cuba officially celebrates Christmas for the
first time in three decades. As such, the government is discounting
roast pork and other traditional fare, while youngsters are acting
out Jesus Christ's birth at a pageant in Old Havana's National
Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a limit to the yuletide spirit of hard-line
Communists.
</P>
<P>
   They are demanding that Santa Claus, for example, not come to
town.
</P>
<P>
   Official newspapers warn that the jolly old man in red is an
unwelcome agent of U.S. cultural imperialism that threatens the
ideological integrity of this socialist nation.
</P>
<P>
   The daily La Tribuna de La Habana said that Christmas imagery
such as fake trees and Santa Claus foment ``ideological confusion''
within Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The workers' weekly Trabajadores -- which means ``workers'' --
called Santa Claus a threatening symbol of U.S. ``consumerism,''
``cultural hegemony,'' and ``mental colonization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there no true Cuban way to celebrate Christmas?'' the
newspaper pointedly asked.
</P>
<P>
   The newspapers -- all of which are state-owned -- also blasted
Santa Claus as the leading representative of the ``hagiography of
U.S. mercantilism.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's been no shortage of cardboard cutouts of Santa
Claus in stores and hotels -- imported, of course -- in Cuba this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, though, most Cuban children know little about the
beloved chubby elf so popular in the United States -- just 90 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of decorations in hotels and in stores, but
kids here don't know who Santa Claus is,'' Eli Lopez, a mother of
three, said by telephone from Havana. ``Santa Claus is something
they're just not used to, so he's just another decoration to most
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   She said most average Cubans can't afford to decorate their
homes with Santa Claus or any other imagery.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas trees, for example, cost up to $50, or more than twice
the monthly salary of a Cuban doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Despite growing strains between Cuba's churches and a government
that declared itself atheist in 1962, Christmas remained an
official holiday in Cuba until 1969.
</P>
<P>
   That year, the Cuban government declared that Christmas was no
longer a public holiday, asserting at the time that it interfered
with the sugar harvest.
</P>
<P>
   But last month(Nov.), the Communist Party said mechanization had
reduced the need for manpower in the harvest so that Christmas can
again, become a holiday.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Cuba observers say the re-establishment of
Christmas is yet another concession to the Catholic Church
following Pope John Paul II's visit to Cuba last January.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba also has released about 100 political prisoners and has
allowed more foreign priests to enter the country.
</P>
<P>
   This year, decorated Christmas trees adorn hotel lobbies and
store windows display scenes with artificial snow throughout
Havana.
</P>
<P>
   But even church leaders in Cuba lament the fact that holiday
expressions on the Caribbean island are, mostly, secular.
</P>
<P>
   Many Cubans are glad to have the day off, but few understand
that Christmas observes the birth of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Catholic Cardinal Jaime Ortega said Tuesday that the
church must strive to restore the religious traditions of
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a job that I think will take many years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Cubans planned to attend Midnight Mass on Christmas
Eve for the first time in years. Others had purchased cheap plastic
Nativity scenes for their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Santa Claus is in good company. Mickey Mouse, too,
has been criticized by hard-line Communists as a tool of U.S.
cultural imperialism.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Mexico withdrew its ambassador from Cuba
after Cuban President Fidel Castro suggested that Mexican children
knew more about Mickey Mouse than their own national heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
