<HEADER>
A3983 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-BOOKS-2TAKES-H     12-23 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-BOOKS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIFT IDEAS FOR THE SPORTS ENTHUSIAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christmas is looking you in the face and you're still four gifts
short, rushing through the holiday crowd to find something,
anything, that's doesn't smell funny and isn't broken.
</P>
<P>
   But before you give up and buy some piece of cheese that'll be
thrown in the trash as soon as it's opened, take a glance at these
books for the sports fan on your list:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Great Moments: The Official Book of the 1998 World Series.''
Edited by David Burgin. Woodford Press, San Francisco. $19.95. 144
pages.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain train of thought that says the event justifies
the means. You see this a lot at rock concerts, where people shell
out $25 for so-what T-shirts just to say they've been there. The
same holds true in sports, from the Final Four to the NFL playoffs
to the World Series _ you buy something because it says the event
was important to you.
</P>
<P>
   Enter ``Great Moments: The Official Book of the 1998 World
Series,'' published by the Woodford Press. Once you say the writing
in ``Great Moments'' is good and the photography is ordinary,
you've said it all. After that, the only question is whether you
want to spend $19.95 for a large paperback about the '98 World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great Moments'' offers plenty of good writing, including Ray
Ratto, the sports columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, talking
about the Yanks' Chuck Knoblauch and Andy Pettite and the way the
Padres took defeat to heart. Here's Ratto on Paul O'Neill's catch
of Wally Joyner's long fly ball with two men on and two out in Game
Two: ``Ask any old baseball man the question and he will give you
the answer: `There is always one point in a game when you have a
chance to win.' For the Padres in Game Two, the chance came in the
very first inning. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Koppett makes the argument for the '98 Yankees being the
best team of all time, Orange County Register columnist Mark
Whicker speaks up for the Padres, and Boston Globe columnist Martin
Nolan looks back at the past year.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the words, there are the pictures _ and the pictures
are no better and no worse than every other World Series paperback
of the past 20 years. Pitchers are pitching. Batters are batting.
Runners are running. Fans are fanning. Winners are celebrating.
There are a handful of Hollywood faces and the same grainy look to
night games you find in all sports books.
</P>
<P>
   Except for some curiosities, like the Star Trek outfit Padre
catcher Carlos Hernandez insisted on wearing behind the plate,
there is nothing that separates these pictures from the '97 Series
or the '96 Series or the '95 Series or, for that matter, any Series
since the pajama-clad October Classics of the '70s. It is hard to
believe anyone but a tried-and-true Yankee fan would need to have
this on his shelf.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrating 70: Mark McGwire's Historic Season.'' Edited by
Ron Smith. Sporting News Publishing, St. Louis. $29.95. 184 pages.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a picture book you want, this is the one. ``Celebrating
70'' has a breakdown of each McGwire homer _ the count, how many on
base, how many outs, McGwire's batting average, RBIs, and the homer
counts of Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The book also offers the best quotes and most memorable pictures
of the homer race, topped off with the good writing of Ron Smith,
Bernie Miklasz, Mike Eisenbath and Dave Kindred.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't just an endless series of shots of McGwire swinging
the bat _ the photos are crisp and colorful and to the point.
There's a section on ``The men who came before,'' black-and-white
studies of Roger Maris and Babe Ruth, a section on Sosa's hottest
weekend, a section on McGwire's batting practices, and a set of
little-known statistics, such as the fact that McGwire finished the
year with nine more homers than singles, that his homer total was
three better than Earl Webb's 1931 record for doubles in a season,
and that 70 homers was three more than the Cardinals hit in 1982,
the year they won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The book is well laid-out and the quotes are given good play,
from Giants' pitcher Rich Rodriguez _ who gave up No. 22 _ saying,
``At least I made SportsCenter,'' to the Astros' Craig Biggio
saying, after a two-homer day from McGwire, ``You've got to get
that family of four out of the left field seats before he kills
somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   The book smacks too much of hero worship, but this is the
Sporting News' hometown team and what McGwire did, after all, was
historic. As McGwire said at the end, ``I can't believe I did it.
Can you? It blows me away.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Values of the Game.'' Bill Bradley. Artisan, New York. $30.
160 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, former NBA player and senator who is at times
mentioned as a presidential candidate, has written an intelligent,
readable memoir of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   He writes about his teammates in the National Basketball
Association, about the solitary joy of standing behind your house,
sinking one free throw after another, of the days when his mother
would challenge him in a one-on-one game, and how easy it was to
decide between the Boy Scouts and basketball when he was told he'd
be cut from the team if he missed another practice.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who grew up in Missouri, wore shoe weights to improve
his vertical leap, learned to dribble the ball without ever looking
down and got into every pickup game he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I practiced three to four hours a day Monday through Friday
and five hours a day on Saturday and Sunday,'' he writes. ``In the
fall, before basketball season began, I ran along streets in town,
through fields, over railroad tracks, down to the banks of the
Mississippi and back.''
</P>
<P>
   Commitment makes all the difference, argues Bradley (``For high
school and college players, there is no excuse for not being `up
for the game'''), and that commitment can lead to excellence in the
sport he loves the most. It's an expanding sport, open to both men
and women, writes Bradley, who pays homage to the women's game _
``I used to love to watch Kate Starbird spark her Stanford team
with her tenacity, intensity and 3-point shooting skill, but the
epitome, for me, is Chamique Holdsclaw of Tennessee, the female
Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Football's Best Short Stories.'' Edited By Paul D. Staudohar.
Chicago Review Press. $22. 328 pages.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a book for preteeners, with Chip Hitchcock breaking
tackles all the way down the field for Winsocki U. This is a sports
book for adults. Or, more correctly, a sports book for adults who
feel nostalgic for the way football was played when they were
growing up, when they were playing themselves, when it had a real
hold on their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The theme is set from the opening story, ``56-0,'' a saga of a
losing team that's meant to be belly-laugh funny but isn't. The
stumbling sadness of ``56-0'' sets a tone for lost times and
broken-heart football that runs throughout the book. Irwin Shaw's
``The Eighty-Yard Run,'' maybe his best short story ever, repeats
that theme. So does Don DeLillo's ``Game Plan'' and John Updike's
``In Football Season,'' with its opening, ``Do you remember a
fragrance girls acquire in autumn? As you walk beside them after
school ... ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Football's Best Short Stories'' is exactly what it's cracked
up to be _ the best stories ever written about the game. But don't
expect it to be an easy read.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Power, Money &AMP; Sex.'' Deion Sanders. World Publishing,
Nashville. $21.99. 194 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you have a born-again Christian on your list or can't get
enough of that talk-show cliche about the eternal curse of riches,
give this book a pass.
</P>
<P>
   There are some interesting passages, especially when Sanders
offers his reasons for dumping a bucket of water on announcer Tim
McCarver and taking a chartered jet between a Falcons and Braves
game to play two sports on one day. But the ex-Braves, ex-Reds,
ex-Falcons, ex-49ers standout spends precious little time talking
about his sports career.
</P>
<P>
   Basically the book is a sermon, with Sanders continually
repeating the theme that, ``Some people spend their whole lives
thinking that if they could just get more power, money and sex,
they would be happy. But as somebody who has had more than my share
of all three, I can tell you this: In themselves, those things will
not make you happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
