<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Young Frankenstein' lurches onto DVD
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What better companion piece for a (James) Whale of an evening on
home video than the special edition of Mel Brooks' inspired 1974
spoof, ``Young Frankenstein,'' starring Gene Wilder, Teri Garr and
Peter Boyle as the Monster (who joins his creator in a rendition of
``Puttin' on the Ritz''). The DVD format beautifully conveys the
film's luminous black-and-white cinematography. Bonuses include a
36-minute documentary featuring Brooks' comments and the
ever-popular original theatrical trailers (``See `Young
Frankenstein,' in black and white and echo!''). There's also a
selection of bloopers, but they're mostly disappointing stuff _
like Wilder and Garr cracking up during their love scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
