<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of movies released on video
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel and Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cousin Bette'' (R) _ Balzac's 1846 novel may have been
whittled down, but there's still much to like about this
deliciously tart comedy of ill manners and worse morals that slowly
ripens into a revenger's tragicomedy. Jessica Lange stars as the
overlooked and underestimated spinster who devises some elaborate
revenge scenarios for her shallow, wealthy relatives. The artful
supporting cast includes Elisabeth Shue and Bob Hoskins. Grade: A-
ER
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' (R) _ Is he or isn't he?
That's the very thin question stretched to feature length in this
comedy about a gay man (Sean P. Hayes, bottom left, with Brad Rowe
) who wonders if a supposedly straight waiter secretly isn't. The
movie is colorful and breezy, but like its dimpled object of
desire, it's cute but shallow. Grade: B- SM
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Midaq Alley'' (unrated) _ Salma Hayek is among the large
cast of this drama, a bittersweet series of interrelated tales
about misplaced love and heartbreak among neighbors in Mexico City.
Based on stories by Nobel Prize winner Naguib Mahfouz. In Spanish,
with subtitles. Grade: A- SM
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel and Steve Murray write for the Atlanta
Jounral-Constitution.
</P>
