<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-BLADE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vampire flick adds cartoon gore to the Christmas season
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Blade'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   Chestnuts roasting on an open fire, vampires popping like fat
tics... New Line Cinema gives us a bloody little Xmas with this
frantic film version of the comic book hero, starring Wesley Snipes
as Blade, a half-human, half-bloodsucker vampire slayer in modern
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has its amusing moments, recasting the undead as
leather-wearing hipsters who frequent nightclubs that become
literal bloodbaths. Stephen Dorff plays the upstart vampire who
wants to climb the bloody ladder, which gives the actor a chance to
smolder and walk around with beard stubble. Meanwhile, Snipes takes
his role very, very seriously, which makes him pretty boring.
</P>
<P>
   What few cartoonish pleasures the movie offers are killed by an
overblown finale, featuring computer-generated special effects that
seem to transform the bad guys into giant, bloody hemorrhoids.
Scary. Grade: C +
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
