<HEADER>
A4004 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-RINGEL24-COX     12-23 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The giant talent of James Whale
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fate has a serious sense of humor. More than 40 years after
dying in near-obscurity, director James Whale has suddenly become a
hot ticket again, thanks to the new movie ``Gods and Monsters'' and
Ian McKellen's prize-winning performance in it. But some of us have
been wild about Whale since, well, since Forrest J. Ackerman
published the first copy of ``Famous Monsters of Filmland.'' But if
``Gods and Monsters'' has piqued your interest, here are a few
Whale rentals to consider. And, yes, we do emphasize the
monster-mash side of his oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   `Frankenstein' (1931)
</P>
<P>
   The one we all know, with Boris Karloff as the Monster and Colin
Clive screaming, ``It's alive!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Casting coup: Having just scored with ``Dracula,'' Bela Lugosi
was seriously considered. But Whale thought that having the same
actor play two classic monsters was absurd (plus, he thought Lugosi
wrong for the part). Enter struggling actor and former truck driver
William Henry Pratt _ stage name, Boris Karloff. Whale interviewed
him and told him he wanted to test him ``for a damned awful
monster.'' He got the part.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Look for: Mae Clarke. She plays Clive's fiancee, but is better
known for being on the wrong end of Jimmy Cagney's grapefruit in
``Public Enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Think about it: In one of the most famous scenes, the Monster
is taught by a little girl to toss petals into a lake. A few
minutes later, he tosses her, thinking that she too will float like
the petals. Years later, the young actress, 7-year-old Marilyn
Harris, recalled that after a few takes she complained because
hitting the water hurt. Whale promised her anything she wanted if
she'd do it again. After the wrap, she blurted out that she wanted
two dozen eggs, which Whale _ probably relieved that it wasn't a
pony or a diamond _ delivered.
</P>
<P>
   `The Old Dark House' (1932)
</P>
<P>
   On the proverbial dark and stormy night, an assortment of
travelers are stranded at a very strange domicile.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Casting coup: Brought over for another film that was delayed
by co-star Tallulah Bankhead's illness, Charles Laughton actually
made his American debut working for Whale. He's relatively
restrained in a cast of scenery-chewing loonies who range from
Karloff to Ernest Thesiger (Dr. Pretorius in ``The Bride of
Frankenstein'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Look for: Gloria Stuart. Yep, the lovely old lady whose
memories launch James Cameron's ``Titanic'' is the ingenue here.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Think about it: A house full of crazies. A stormy night. Some
stranded innocents. Do the words ``The Rocky Horror Picture Show''
come to mind?
</P>
<P>
   `The Invisible Man' (1933)
</P>
<P>
   H.G. Wells' classic about a scientist who invents a formula for
becoming invisible but is driven mad by its side effects.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Casting coup: Universal, naturally, earmarked this for its
monster-in-residence, Karloff. Whale had other ideas. He went with
Claude Rains, who'd never made a movie before. Whale knew Rains'
stage work and felt that his soothing voice was a perfect contrast
to the violence he commits. Rains went on to make movies such as
``Casablanca'' and ``Notorious.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Look for: Gloria Stuart. Again.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Think about it: It took nine writers, six treatments and 10
different screenplays to get ``The Invisible Man'' onscreen. Among
those who passed through the writers' mill were a couple of guys
named Preston Sturges and John Huston.
</P>
<P>
   `The Bride of Frankenstein' (1935)
</P>
<P>
   The Monster wants a bride. Whether she wants him is another
story.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Casting coup: Karloff returns as the Monster, even though he'd
clearly been blown to bits in the original. Ah, the magic of
sequels.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Look for: Elsa Lanchester, not once but twice. Most movie fans
know that she plays the Bride with the electro-shock hair. But she
also plays Frankenstein's true creator, Mary Shelley, in the film's
prologue.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Think about it: ``The Bride of Frankenstein'' is one of the 25
movies added this year to the Library of Congress's National Film
Registry.
</P>
<P>
   `Showboat' (1936)
</P>
<P>
   That's right. The celebrated musical by Jerome Kern and Oscar
Hammerstein II.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Casting coup: This is the version with Paul Robeson singing
``Ol' Man River.'' 'Nuff said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Look for: Hattie McDaniel as Queenie. She replaced the
originally cast Tess Gardella. What was wrong with Gardella? She
was a white actress who had performed the role on stage in
blackface. It being the late 1930s, the problem, alas, wasn't
blackface, but the protests that could arise from a white actress
playing a black actor's (Robeson's) wife.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Think about it: This was Whale's public declaration that he
was out of the monster-movie business. Five years later, his career
was over. He completed his last feature in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
