<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4053 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISAAC-NEWTON-HNS &LR;      12-23 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISAAC-NEWTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISAAC NEWTON AND THE SPIRIT OF SELF-SACRIFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA BASS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On Christmas Day, in addition to everything
else, we celebrate the birth of the greatest intellect in human
history.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 25, 1642, in the tiny village of Woolsthorpe, England, a
Christmas baby was born. The mother was a grieving widow whose
husband had died less than 10 weeks earlier. She christened the
baby Isaac, after his father. Born prematurely, he was not expected
to live.
</P>
<P>
   This baby grew up to be Isaac Newton, the most important
physicist and mathematician of all time.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of how Newton, while still in his early 20s, came up
with the law of universal gravitation after watching the apples
fall in his mother's garden is well-known, and probably false.
</P>
<P>
   Less well-known _ but most definitely true _ is that Newton
accomplished most of his great work during a two-year explosion of
creativity in which he also invented calculus, determined the
particle nature of light, pinned down the binomial theorem and
demonstrated that white light is not white at all but instead is
made up of all the colors of the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   During this same two years _ from the summer of 1665 to early
spring, 1667 _ he also formulated the observations he was to later
write up in ``Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica,'' the
single most influential scientific treatise ever written, and the
key to all known physics till the dawn of this century.
</P>
<P>
   What came forth from Newton's mind during these two fevered
years of concentration, curiosity and imagination was a true
revolution _ a revolution not only in how to observe and calculate
but also in how to explain the universe and everything in it.
</P>
<P>
   And it is a mark of Newton's enduring flame that Newtonian
physics _ now well over 300 years old _ remains the tool modern
science employs both to describe most of what takes place in our
world and to create nearly all of our latest technologies. Even
relativity and quantum theory, which have replaced the Newtonian
view at the subatomic and galactic edges of the universe, are
themselves deeply rooted in Newton's two years of inspiration and
insight.
</P>
<P>
   How did these two years come about? Although not, in all
likelihood, gaping at falling apples, Newton was indeed in his
mother's garden in Woolsthorpe for much of his two-year miracle _
and when not in her garden, then upstairs in his bedroom or
otherwise on her property. Newton was staying so close to home
because home was safe, and the rest of England was not; the Great
Plague was ravaging London, and it looked like the end of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The plague hit London with unparalleled violence. By April 1665,
it was an epidemic; by September, it was killing 8,000 people a
week. Newton, who received his bachelor's degree from Cambridge in
May 1665, went to Woolsthorpe soon afterward, just as the
university was closed as a safety measure. Only when the epidemic
ended did Newton's self-exile end.
</P>
<P>
   The bleak and unusual circumstances in which this Christmas baby
accomplished his greatest work offers a special lesson this holiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   Most people associate ``the spirit of Christmas'' with
self-sacrifice _ the deliberate giving of oneself, body or soul (or
both), in the name of a greater good.
</P>
<P>
   By this definition, Newton does not appear to have sacrificed
himself; he fled the plague to survive, not to help humanity.
However, once safe in his mother's garden, he managed to help
humanity by bequeathing a most marvelous, useful and powerful gift
_ the gift of knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Newton was able to offer so mighty a gift because he did, in a
very real sense, sacrifice himself. Newton _ like Galileo and
Shakespeare before him, or Einstein and Picasso in our own century
_ gave himself up to his art.
</P>
<P>
   He dedicated himself, body and soul, for two years, to the
highest standards of intellectual excellence and the unwavering
commitment to scientific truth. And it was this willing dedication
_ this selfless commitment _ that led to the greatest outburst of
scientific inspiration in world history.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson of Isaac Newton is that the giving of oneself, in the
name of a greater good, takes many forms.
</P>
<P>
   This season, we can all be thankful for, and inspired by, those
who have so sacrificed, whether by giving their time, their wealth,
or their very lives _ or by committing themselves to the high
calling of knowledge and the simple pursuit of truth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cynthia Bass is a historical novelist and columnist for the San
Francisco Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
