<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-MILITARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US MILITARY TIGHTENS ITS TIES WITH HONDURAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO AMARATECA, Honduras _ It was here, where the bridge along
Highway 15 was ripped away by a raging river, that Nelson Martinez
met Jerry Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez owns a cement company near the river and has been
working overtime to make cement culverts for Harris, the chief of a
US Navy construction battalion that is rebuilding the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   They met only a month ago, but they sound like best friends.
``Great guy,'' Harris said of Martinez. ``I'm glad they're here,''
Martinez responded.
</P>
<P>
   Through the widespread destruction caused by Hurricane Mitch,
there are signs throughout this hurricane-damaged country of
stronger ties between Hondurans and the US military.
</P>
<P>
   These new bonds may prove even more valuable as American
officials start shopping for new locations in Central and South
America for military forces that must soon leave Panama. Already,
preliminary discussions for new US locations have begun with
governments in Honduras, Peru, and Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement to hand over control of the Panama
Canal by the end of next year, the United States must close Howard
Air Force Base, its main airfield, by May 1. The base has been the
center of most of the US-led operations to stem the flow of cocaine
and other illegal drugs from Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Already, plans are underway to move some Panama operations _ as
well as some Miami-based US Southern Command offices _ to Puerto
Rico. But there is still a desire to have an operating location
elsewhere in Central or South America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at some places, but this is still in the very
early stages,'' a State Department spokesman said. ``I don't
believe any formal requests have been made to any country.''
</P>
<P>
   The US military has maintained a base of operations since 1983
at the Soto Cano Air Base north of the capital city of Tegucigalpa.
As many as 2,000 troops were stationed here in the late 1980s, when
Honduras served as the base for American-backed Contra rebels in
Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the base is home to an assortment of humanitarian,
reconstruction and anti-drug efforts throughout Central America
known as Joint Task Forces Bravo. More than 2,000 US troops are now
stationed in Honduras, most of them involved in medical and
rebuilding projects following Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closure of Howard is a great concern strategically for
this theater,'' said Colonel Chuck Jacoby, commander of US forces
at Soto Cano. ``There will be some migration of missions, but there
is a general belief that no one site can replace Panama.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are no immediate plans to expand the US presence
at Soto Cano, Jacoby and other officials said, it is likely that
some of equipment currently housed in Panama may be sent to
Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Honduran government offered to take in more US
personnel and equipment from Panama, but the Americans declined
because they were negotiating an extension to their stay at Howard.
Those talks broke down in September.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the stronger feelings of cooperation that have blossomed
recently with the Hondurans, the idea of a permanent presence of US
soldiers here is still a sensitive issue.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the American military has been at Soto Cano for 15
years, permanent barracks have never been built for troops who
still sleep mostly on wooden cots. In addition, officials have been
cautious to closely coordinate hurricane cleanup efforts with the
Honduran government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very careful about the messages we send to the Honduran
people,'' one US officer said. ``We don't want to make them think
that we're trying to control things.''
</P>
<P>
   President Carlos Flores, who has requested a free trade
agreement between Honduras and the United States, is in Washington
this week to meet with other Central American presidents, financial
institutions and Clinton administration officials. Flores has not
commented publicly on the issue of a larger American military
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Mario David Villanueva, the Honduran military's chief
spokesman, praised his US counterparts for ``their constant support
and cooperation over the years and especially after Mitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva added: ``They responded quickly because they were
already here. With our history together, it might make sense'' to
expand their presence at Soto Cano. ``But that is something that
must negotiated at the highest levels of government and with the
permission of the Honduran people.''
</P>
<P>
   Some US officials say a larger site at Soto Cano might
logistically restrict efforts only to Central America. For that
reason, distributing some of the Panama personnel and resources to
Ecuador or Peru would provide more immediate access to anti-drug
efforts in South America.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Jacoby said, his troops will continue to help rebuild
Honduras, Nicaragua, El Salvador, and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission remains relatively unchanged as the strategic
gateway to Central America,'' he said. ``This has been a calamity,
but it's given us a brighter picture of how well we can work
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
