u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-GAMES-BOS &LR;      12-23 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GAMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET REALITY IMPINGE BEFORE BUYING LATEST VIDO GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SAUNDERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judging by the crop of Christmas computer games, it seems game
developers have finally grasped the concept that, just as not every
car on the highway is a Corvette, not all gamers own screaming
systems with processors churning at 300 MHz and faster.
</P>
<P>
   Games have become more egalitarian and more accommodating of the
variety of configurations populating the real world, but before
anyone cues the orchestra to play ``Fanfare for the Common Man,''
there's a bit of reality to consider first.
</P>
<P>
   While minimum game system requirements have hovered within the
same range over the past year, most hot new games still severely
tax the processing power of most PCs under $1,000, the
fastest-growing area of computer sales. Those requirements are
listed on every box, and any potential game buyer should heed
carefully these estimates of the lowest-powered configuration that
will support the calculation-intensive graphics a game will demand.
</P>
<P>
   Console video games usually don't encounter those pesky hardware
compatibility problems, which is one reason for their popularity.
Just remember that a PlayStation is to a Nintendo 64 machine what a
PC is to a Macintosh _ they're totally different systems. Sega is
another animal altogether, and don't even ask about Dreamcast. It's
a new console developed, in part, by the Sega and Dreamworks
partnership that was supposed to hit stores this Christmas but is
still available only in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Console buyers have less to worry about, and can forget about
squinting at the bottom-of-the-box declarations designed to give
PC-game buyers advance warning. Those fine-print details only
assure that a game will load and run somewhat without crashing; no
guarantees are made that the graphics won't look like day-old
scrambled eggs, regardless of how great they appear on the box. No
doubt hundreds of people who bought a $500 Wal-Mart special will
discover this when they attempt to play Shogo: Mobile Armor
Division or Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six, two of 1998's best action
games. (Speaking of Wal-Mart, strong sales of Deer Hunter and Big
Game Hunter II have launched these stalk-and-shoot games into the
bestseller list. Also a hot ticket at the nation's megaretailer:
Deer Avenger, a hunting game parody in which the animals exact
their revenge.)
</P>
<P>
   With so much to consider before dropping $50 on a stocking
stuffer, there's a need for guidance _ especially for the gamer who
doesn't have everything.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Details, details
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If that special someone has a 486-66 or a Mac II, nearly all
current games are beyond the capabilities of these once-powerful
machines, which, to the gaming industry, are now little more than
oversized Palm Pilots. All is not lost; some children's software
will perform adequately on these machines, and major retailers
usually bundle ``old'' games in packs of three or five and sell
them at deep discounts.
</P>
<P>
   More options emerge when there's a Pentium or PowerMac in the
home, and these make up the bulk of the home computers sold in the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Rally Championship is a great racing game that performs
surprisingly well on low-end Pentiums, even those powered by
relatively poky P75 and P90 chips. (The numbers indicate the speed,
in megahertz, of transactions handled by the microprocessor; higher
is faster.) It sacrifices detailed scenery for smooth transitions
between each computer-rendered picture. The faster these
transitions, or frame rate, the more realistic the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Most children's software will operate quite well on Pentiums
running at 120 MHz, and the best news is that the excellent titles
tend to stick around for several years. We've seen little to
dethrone the Logical Journey of the Zoombinis from this year's
list, a great game that emphasizes problem solving and fortifies
symbolic logic skills. It has strong company in SimSafari, designed
by the developers of the gaming classic SimCity. In this virtual
safari, children build their own game park and populate it with a
variety of animals, with the goal of ecological balance.
</P>
<P>
   Teens and adults who love chess might enjoy Chessmaster 6000,
the latest version of a long-running PC game. It harnesses
computing power as a teaching tool, and can help beginners build
talent and hone the skills of intermediate players. There's a
well-designed, intuitive interface that is easy to navigate, but is
a supplement to a human coach, not a substitute.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Speed and status
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bigger still are the choices available for buyers with computers
that are a smidgen faster (P133-200) and with a tad more memory (16
to 32 megs of RAM). These machines can display most of the games on
shelves, with some tweaking needed for high-graphics simulations
and action games. The PC version of Final Fantasy VII immediately
rises to the top, a smooth version of the breakthrough role-playing
game that was last year's must-have for the PlayStation. Ignore the
cartoonish characters drawn in the Japanese anime style and focus
on the cinematic plot-development techniques, which make this one
of the most engaging games ever developed for a console or
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few games share that same rarefied ``classic'' status
with Final Fantasy VII, and two of them are available in one gift
package. Ages of Myst combines Myst with its sequel, Riven, and
links two of the best-selling adventure games of all time. These
are games for those quiet nights when introspection and mental
dexterity can help erase the day's toil. They use lush images and
detailed puzzles to create an absorbing experience that few games
can replicate.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Arts dives into the quirky end of the game pool with
releases like Grim Fandango, a twisted journey through a stylized
underworld. It's a cult hit that blends a rollicking adventure with
intricate gameplay, and delivers well-timed adrenaline rushes
moderated with humor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Microsoft-headed
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Microsoft endures its trials in Washington, the company's
games division continues to release well-made, challenging titles.
One of this year's best is Combat Flight Simulator, probably the
most aptly named game of the bunch. It's an elegant marriage of
World War II air battles and the sim genre-leading physics of the
Microsoft Flight Simulator graphics engine.
</P>
<P>
   It boasts stellar graphics, especially on a computer outfitted
with the optional 3D-accelerator card, and here we begin to see the
benefits of higher-end machines with processors skipping along at
more than 200 MHz. A fast machine definitely helps Combat Flight
Simulator, but much of its performance can be attributed to the
game developer's careful choice of vintage aircraft that operate at
half the speed of modern jet fighters. With the Mustangs,
Thunderbolts, and Messerschmitts moving relatively slowly, the
computer can draw the detailed terrain faster, eliminating frame
freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Jet lovers should consider Jane's F-15 and Total Air War from
DID, which both deliver impressive realism and sophisticated flight
modeling but put players behind the controls of flame-belching
fighters. Of course, Jane's is a well-established chronicler of
military and civilian vehicles, so there's attention to detail in
its electronic entertainment products that help them live up to the
venerable name.
</P>
<P>
   Combine science-fiction fantasy and a nearly flawless strategy
game and the result is Starcraft, easily one of the best games of
the year. It was released this past January and quickly developed a
strong word-of-mouth buzz due to addictive gameplay and detailed
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Console fans have a wide selection this year, but among the best
is Zelda: Ocarina of Time, a role-play/adventure game for Nintendo
64 that was a show stopper at last summer's Electronic
Entertainment Expo. It's the latest ``how'd-he-do-that'' creation
from Shigeru Miyamoto, the godfather of gaming at Nintendo, who
created Donkey Kong, Super Mario Bros., and other design hallmarks.
PlayStation owners should consider Tekken 3, the console version of
the popular arcade fighting game; Xenogears, a dark morality play
that looks like Final Fantasy VII in the present; and Cool Boarders
3, a snowboarding game that still has a lot of work ahead to catch
up to its Nintendo 64 counterpart, 1080 Snowboarding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1334EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4109 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      12-23 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS WIN SHOWS HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ As the Patriots danced off the field after
Sunday's win over the 49ers, all were ecstatic. But one went out of
his way to send a message as well as share his joy.
</P>
<P>
   From the 50-yard line all the way to the runway leading to the
locker room, Larry Whigham kept pounding his heart with his fist.
Whigham turned toward the stands behind the New England bench and
pounded his heart, and then Whigham faced those true Patriot
loyalists in the end zone seats and pounded his heart even more.
</P>
<P>
   The message was obvious: This football team had just
demonstrated that it has heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't look at this football team this year and show that
we have a lot of heart, that we have a lot of guys willing to put
everything they have out on the football field, then I don't know
what you're looking at,'' said Whigham. ``I mean, it meant a lot to
our coach (Pete Carroll) to win this game, it meant a lot to us
players to win this game, and it meant so much for all us to get
into the playoffs. We're going to have Willie McGinest back next
Sunday . . . and we're going to show that heart as long as we keep
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The absolute requirement of any coach is that he gets his team
to play hard, to play up to its ability. This is true in all sports
but most essential in football, where effort often means as much
as, if not more than, execution.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots did not do that in St. Louis; the Patriots clearly
did so a week later against San Francisco. Just as they had in the
wins over Miami, Buffalo, and Pittsburgh during the last improbable
month after injuries decimated the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows much the character of the team and the players, for
a team to step it up when it loses so many of its key players,''
said linebacker Marty Moore. ``When guys go down, other guys step
it up. And that's what we've been doing all year. That's what
football is all about; when you have guys hurt and other guys step
in and help the team win, that makes the whole team a lot
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of our bigger wins since I've been here,'' said
linebacker Chris Slade. ``With so many ups and downs we had this
year, and so many injuries, this was big. With Drew (Bledsoe) and
Terry (Glenn) and Ted (Johnson) and Willie (McGinest) out . . .
this showed a lot about the heart of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an intangible. But for the Patriots to lose their two
most-feared threats on offense _ not to mention their blocking back
_ and also to lose two of their best players on defense, not to
mention assorted injuries that have slowed those still playing, and
still win is a credit to Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Take four of the best players off any playoff team such as the
Broncos, Jets, Vikings, Bills, 49ers (Steve Young and Jerry Rice
gone?), Packers, or Bills, and surmise what may have happened.
Jacksonville without Mark Brunell already gives a pretty clear hint
of the dire consequences of such losses.
</P>
<P>
   But the tangibles of Carroll's input also were evident Sunday.
In so many ways, this was his most important game since he took
over the Patriots job because he was a Californian, the 49ers had
been his team growing up, he had coached there, and he knew the
personnel and strategy intimately.
</P>
<P>
   Patriot fans always will treat any Jets game with Bill Parcells
coaching the team as the game of games. Of course. And what has
been so frustrating to Patriot fans has been that Parcells (and
Bill Belichick, of course) have used their intimate knowledge of
the Patriots and their players to concoct game plans that have kept
the Patriots off stride in all three games the teams have played
since Parcells took over in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Other coaches also have done this against their old teams. Mike
Holmgren's Packers have virtually owned the 49ers in the last five
years, mainly because Holmgren is a former 49ers assistant coach
who used his intimate knowledge of San Francisco to his advantage.
Dan Reeves brought his Falcons into Giants Stadium this year and
absolutely crushed his former team, for much the same reason. Mike
Shanahan's Broncos also have owned the Raiders since Shanahan left
Oakland as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Could Carroll do the same against his old team?
</P>
<P>
   ``We just stuck to our game plan,'' said Slade, when asked how
the Patriot defense took away so many of San Francisco's familiar
weapons. ``It was a good game plan.'' San Franciso's conservative
play-calling also helped.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the fourth quarter, Young was sacked on key third- down
plays as he looked to his left to throw that usually so-effective
slant pass that is the trademark of the 49er offense. But both
times, as Young looked to his left, Slade had ``jumped'' the slant,
was between Young and the receiver, and the quarterback had to hold
the ball. Too much time passed, and he was sacked.
</P>
<P>
   On that final sack by Greg Spires with little more than 2
minutes left, and the 49ers facing third and 1 from their 20, the
down-and-distance the 49ers always seem to make with the short
slant pass, ``I saw (Garrison) Hearst leaking out in the flat and
that's my man,'' said Slade. ``I remember thinking that if I went
after (Young), he was going to dump it over my head and complete
the ball and get a first down.''
</P>
<P>
   But Slade stayed ``home,'' stayed inside of Hearst, ``and I
could see that's where (Young) wanted to throw the ball. But he saw
me in coverage and he held the ball, and Greg got him. It was a
coverage sack.'' On San Francisco's bread-and-butter play.
</P>
<P>
   It was similar to what the Jets have been able to do to the
Patriots, take away what they do so well and have done so well.
This time, it was Carroll who took away the San Francisco treats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been tough for him,'' said Slade of Carroll's so
often being compared to Parcells. ``He's following a legend:
Parcells. Let's face it, that's the real reason why he's taking
heat. But he's done a good job for us this year. He's following in
big footsteps, and again we're back in the playoffs for his second
year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Slade knows New England and New England's fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take anything away from what (Carroll) has done,''
said the linebacker. ``But until we beat the Jets, it's going to be
that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
