<SLUG> BC-ONBJOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BATTLE FRONT: JOB CLASSIFICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a chilly November morning last year, Mike Gallagher left his
house at dawn and headed to his new $22-an-hour job installing
drywall at Sun Microsystems Inc. in Burlington.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher didn't have much to say when his new boss, Gerard
Poulin, president of Jerry Construction Co. in Hudson, N.H.,
allegedly told him that instead of being classified as a company
employee, he would be working as an independent contractor and
would have to supply his own insurance, and deduct his own state
and federal taxes, pension benefits, and Social Security payments.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days later, however, the 34-year-old Walpole carpenter
talked. So did Jim Cunningham, Roldo Cesaroni, and six others, all
part of a nine-member team of undercover union members _ or
``salts'' _ from the New England Regional Council of Carpenters.
Their statements and pay stubs led to a September 1998 raid of
Poulin's business and home office by the Massachusetts attorney
general's office, which is continuing to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Poulin's attorney, Andru Volinsky, of Concord, N.H., said no
action has been filed against his client. The attorney general's
office declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   With billions of dollars in benefits and pay at stake, unions
and workers from academia to high tech to the blue-collar trades
are battling the misclassification of employees as independent
contractors and contingent workers. Many are turning to the courts
or, as in the case of unions, to salting, organizing campaigns, and
protests.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for workers' anger? No benefits. ``For many, what's
at stake is no workers' compensation coverage in the event of
injury, no health coverage in the event of sickness, no employment
compensation in the event of layoffs, and no Social Security
coverage when they retire,'' said Mark Erlich, senior assistant
administrator for the Boston-based 22,000-member carpenters
council.
</P>
<P>
   In at least one case involving white-collar workers, a court has
ruled that long-term contingent workers are ``common law''
employees. Such workers are like partners in a common law marriage:
they have the same experiences without all the legal protections.
</P>
<P>
   For example, temps and independent!contractors at Pacific Gas &AMP;
Electric in California won a lawsuit in October when a judge ruled
they were common law employees.
</P>
<P>
   This past summer, employees at Allstate Insurance Co. slapped
the company with a suit alleging that an estimated 10,000 temporary
workers were really long-term temps or commonlaw employees, and
deserved the same rights and benefits as their permanent
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Also this fall, the US Department of Labor, following a probe
into journalists' complaints, sued Time Warner Inc., accusing it of
denying pensions and health benefits to some full-time workers by
wrongfully classifying them as temps or independent contractors.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all. Angered by what they described as substandard
treatment, contingent janitors and union activists at Yale
University held a series of high-profile protests that led to a new
six-year contract last year that includes formulas to determine
whether a contingent or temporary janitor ought to become a
permanent, full-time employee.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, meanwhile, a group affiliated with the
Communications Workers of America is attempting to organize
independent contractors and temps at Microsoft Corp., which has
been embroiled in a battle over classification since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood that employers find themselves facing lawsuits or
union protests is increasing as the number of contingent employees
entering the work force rises, say experts. They say deciding who
fits the legal definition of an independent contractor or temporary
employee gets murkier as the length of time such workers are
employed extends beyond a few months to a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we now have is a new species of temps or independent
contractors,'' said Joshua Davis, an employment lawyer at Hill &AMP;
Barlow in Boston. `` We are no longer talking about the temp or
independent who fills in for a few days or months and then
leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there are 8.5 million independent contractors
representing nearly 7 percent of the US work force, according to a
1997 Bureau of Labor Statistics survey. Temporary workers, by
contrast, now represent just over 2 percent of the work force, up
from 0.5 percent in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   A separate federal survey by the agency last year showed that 29
percent of 1.3 million temporary agency workers have been at the
same job for one year or longer, up from 25 percent of 1.1 million
temps in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say the misclassification of workers has mushroomed
since a 1987 report by the Internal Revenue Service estimated 3.7
million workers were illegally reported to the IRS as independent
contractors. The latest statistics, from a study by the former
Coopers &AMP; Lybrand (now PricewaterhouseCoopers), include a
projection of at least 5 million by 2005. But with temps and
independent contractors now constituting more than 9 percent of the
work force, even that estimate may be too low.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Misclassification) is happening in construction, in
high-tech, in education, and in medical services,'' said University
of Massachusetts economist Randy Albelda.
</P>
<P>
   The downsizing craze of the 1990s led not only to a rapid
increase in the number of contingent workers, she says, but also in
the rehiring of laid off full-time employees as independents,
making it even harder for the government to document abuse.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1994 study, Coopers said that misclassification leads to a
loss in federal revenue because of uncollected income taxes, Social
Security, and unemployment payments. The researchers said if
adequate resources were used to insure proper compliance,
reclassification of independent contractors as regular employees
would raise more than $4.9 billion in revenue between 1996 and
2004. If no action is taken, however, the total cost to the US
government over nine years would be $29.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A recent spate of court rulings in favor of long-term
independent contractors and temps has some management attorneys and
consultants scrambling to help corporate clients avoid liability.
</P>
<P>
   While some misclassified workers must pay their own state and
federal taxes and Social Security, high-tech specialists who work
on a contingent basis often rely on temporary agencies to pay
standard health and vacation benefits and make the required
deductions. Many do not receive the stock options, pensions, or
profit-sharing that full-time company employees enjoy, and that
make technology companies especially vulnerable to lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   By not clarifying long-term temps' work arrangements, employers
run a risk of being slapped with lawsuits and court fines. ``I've
been advising computer companies that they need to create a
contractor deployment strategy,'' said Linda Pittenger, chief
executive of People3 Inc., a New Jersey information technology
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contractors should come in, do a project, leave or transfer
their knowledge of new technology to permanent people, and then
leave,'' Pittenger said. ``What employers don't realize is that
they get in trouble when they have independents working
side-by-side with permanent employees indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Length of service is not key in deciding whether a tradesperson
should be classified as an independent contractor. For these
workers, the central factor still boils down to who controls the
work _ the employer or the individual.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal worker classification is pervasive in the construction
trades, said Stuart Rossman, head of the Massachusetts attorney
general's Business Labor Protection Bureau. ``Whenever an employer
misclassifies someone as an independent contractor, it results in
employment fraud, insurance fraud, federal withholding or Social
Security fraud, and it can result in the nonpayment of prevailing
wages on public projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Krause, an attorney at the Massachusetts Insurance Fraud
Bureau, says misclassification cases as a whole ``account for $29
million, or 19 percent of all'' fraud fines collected.
</P>
<P>
   David Powell, director of labor relations for the Massachusetts
chapter of Associated General Contractors, said many employers in
the construction trades are worried, too. ``By misclassifying
people as independents, contractors who don't play by the rules
don't pay prevailing wages, insurance or taxes so they can put in
the lowest possible bid for a job,'' he said. ``Legitimate
employers like us are losing millions of dollars as a result, and
it hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   When Roldo Cesaroni began working for Jerry Construction last
year, company owner Poulin told him he would not be paid unless he
obtained his own workers' compensation and liability insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Cesaroni, a union salter who was hired to work at the Marriott
Residence Inn in Dedham last year, later told state investigators
that Poulin's wife, Joanne, paid him as an independent contractor
and did not deduct taxes, Social Security, or other withholding
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Because the IRS requires 1099 forms be filed for all payments to
vendors exceeding $600, the Poulins insisted Cesaroni give them the
names of other individuals to whom they could make out his
paychecks, according to the search warrant. One check was made out
to Cesaroni's girlfriend; another was made out to his brother,
Steven.
</P>
<P>
   Cesaroni hardly fit the profile of an independent contractor. He
was being paid by the hour and not by the job. He was not working
for several companies at once. And he had not furnished his own
tools. The most important factor, however, was that he had no real
control over his job.
</P>
<P>
   After Cesaroni, Gallagher, and seven others went to the state
attorney general's office, Poulin's offices were raided. A search
warrant alleges that by classifying more than 50 carpenters at
various Massachusetts work sites as independent contractors, Poulin
avoided paying thousands of dollars in workers' compensation and
liability insurance premiums, state and federal taxes, and pension
and Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pursuing the allegations,'' said Poulin's attorney
Volinsky. But he added, ``we are concerned that the search warrant
may have been issued at the insistence of the local carpenter's
union. We feel the attorney general's office should maintain
complete independence from union activities.''
</P>
<P>
   (Questions, comments? Contact Diane E. Lewis at
work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
