<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-FUTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HOUSTON, HELP GATHERS FOR OCTUPLETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ This sprawling city of sudden skyscrapers, of oil and
space exploration, of cowboy boots and sombreros, is as far removed
from the tiny farm town of Carlisle, Iowa, as Oz was from Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   But when some or all of the Chukwu octuplets leave their
hospital womb, the response from this city will no doubt be
measured against the extraordinary embrace the McCaughey septuplets
have received from their hometown of Carlisle in the 13 months
since their birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Houston wants to be known as a supportive community, it's
going to take a concerted effort on their part to help this family
with all its needs, and those needs will be great,'' said the Rev.
Robert Brown of the Missionary Baptist Church of Carlisle,
heaquarters of the McCaughey volunteer effort.
</P>
<P>
   While Nkem Chukwu and her husband, Iyke Louis Udobi, focus on
every breath, every heartbeat of their critically ill babies,
Houston already seems to be giving a Texas-sized welcome to the
littlest celebrities in its midst, showering them with prayers and
promises of goods, money, and time.
</P>
<P>
   And though some observers wondered if criticism from ethicists
about Chukwu's use of fertilty drugs or the race of the babies
might affect the response _ the parents are Nigerian immigrants
with US citizenship _ early signs suggest this is not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that the community of all persons _ black, white,
everyone _ will lend a part of their hearts to these kids, helping
us look at them beyond biological wonderment to see them as human
beings needing and requiring our support,'' said Chido Nwangwu, a
local newspaper publisher who has organized the USAfrica Children
Support Network on behalf of the octuplets.
</P>
<P>
   The six girls and two boys remained in critical but stable
condition Tuesday, with ``no significant changes'' in their
outlook, said Dr. Leonard Weisman, chief of neonatology at Texas
Children's Hospital. ``In these cases, no news is good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Weisman said the smallest infant, known as Baby E because the
parents have not yet announced names, is 10 ounces and 9 3/4 inches
long _ approximately the size of a Beanie Baby toy _ and can fit in
a woman's hand. Weisman said no infant that small had ever survived
at Texas Children's.
</P>
<P>
   The seven babies born Sunday were still breathing with the help
of ventilators Tuesday, leaving only Baby A _ a girl born 12 days
before the rest _ breathing on her own. All were being fed
intravenously; Baby E and one other continued to receive
supplemental oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful that they all will survive,'' Weisman said, ``but
the reality is that we may not be able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu, 27, was described Tuesday by officials at adjacent St.
Luke's Episcopal Hospital as ``much improved and in very good
spirits.'' She had successful surgery Monday to stop bleeding in
her abdomen caused by efforts to postpone delivery as long as
possible so as to help the babies mature.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu was expected to go home Friday, but the babies probably
will be in the hospital for two to three months, at a cost of
$250,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, the family released a statement praising the
hospitals for their care and adding: ``We are very appreciative of
the worldwide support over the past few days, particularly the
prayers and spiritual connection at this special time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   On the family's southwest Houston street _ amid a surburban
development of well-kept, three- and four-bedroom brick homes _
neighbors said Chukwu and Udobi kept to themselves but that would
not prevent them from helping.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's never going to sleep again,'' said Sandi West, who lives
two doors away with her four children. ``I'll do what I can, even
it's just to wash some clothes for her so she can get a little
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Added another neighbor, Charles Massey: ``Everybody around here
pretty much looks out for each other, so I expect we'll go down and
see what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Nwangwu said the USAfrica Children Support Network also was
ready to help. ``In my culture, those kids are all of our kids, and
we expect there to be a flood of material and financial support to
help us raise them,'' said Nwangwu, who said he is friendly with
Udobi and is from the same ethnic group, the Igbo of eastern
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   The first caller to the new organization was Vicki Bell of
Houston, who owns a company that helps cancer patients administer
chemotherapy at home. She said she hopes to ``change diapers, hold
bottles, whatever they need.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot have children of my own, so the only children I will
ever get close to are other people's children. It seemed like a
neat way to make a difference and feel good at the same time,''
Bell said. She also was inspired by reports about teams of
volunteers helping Bobbi and Kenny McCaughey with their children.
``I thought, `Why should they have all the fun?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Williams, program director of the Black Heritage Society
of Houston, said he and others wondered if there would be a
different response to the Chukwus than the McCaugheys because of
race. The general issue arose last year, when a black woman in
Washington who gave birth to five surviving sextuplets was largely
ignored, compared with the McCaugheys.
</P>
<P>
   ``That question has come up, but I see the gifts coming
already,'' Williams said. ``Houston is a giving city. Regardless of
color, people have always been helped, and I don't see where this
should be any different now.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital's philanthropy office offered proof of that,
recording promises of lifetime supplies of diapers, wipes, and
training pants, as well as lifetime oil changes and car tires, and
one-year supplies of groceries and baby formula. A local department
store also pledged unspecified gifts, and ``The New Maury Show,''
starring Maury Povich, promised eight cribs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect money to start coming in (Thursday),'' said Marianne
Dwyer, assistant director of health care philanthropy at St.
Luke's. ``One sweet little woman said she's sending in $5 because
that's all she can afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Local television and radio stations also have become involved,
asking their audiences to drop off donations. Ernie Jackson Jr.,
vice president and general manager of Magic 102, the city's top
black-oriented radio station, said he is organizing an on-air
campaign to help the family.
</P>
<P>
   The model for Houston will no doubt be Carlisle, where in any
given month 70 or more volunteers work shifts helping the
McCaugheys.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the family's pastor in the town of 3,400 people, said he
is part of a team of advisers that has assembled around the
McCaugheys, including a lawyer, an accountant, an agent, and a
financial planner.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the octuplets, the key thing is to sit down with the
family and ask how we can help you most. Don't assume that they
will want the help the people want to give them,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope there is as good a response worldwide as we had
here,'' he added. ``We're excited for them, but we also know some
of the roads they are going to travel. Our prayers are certainly
with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
