<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LATIN REEXAMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Supreme Court appeal makes for good theater, but with thin
prospects for victory, the Boston School Committee is better off
with an entirely new admissions process for Boston Latin School.
</P>
<P>
   It can start by weaning itself from the entrance exams.
</P>
<P>
   Latin is well on its way to becoming a citadel of segregation
after the one-man demolition derby of Michael McLaughlin. His
lawsuit forced Latin to accept his white daughter Julia, who was
denied admission with exam scores higher than African-American and
Latino students. Latin had to drop its policy that granted 35
percent of seats to African-American and Latino students.
</P>
<P>
   The McLaughlin suit spurred Latin to admit 154 more white and
Asian students with higher exam scores. Latin devised a weaker form
of affirmative action, admitting 50 percent of new students on exam
scores alone and 50 percent on the basis of the racial makeup of
the remainging qualifying applicants. The new policy meant a sharp
drop in African-American and Latino students. Only 20 percent of
seventh graders are African-American or Latino.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan was meant to be a compromise between those who
think test scores equal ``merit'' and those who understand that
``merit'' is much too often a euphemism for white privilege, class
advantage, and hoarding of scarce educational resources. But
McLaughlin thrust a battering ram against even this plan. He sued
on behalf of white Sarah Wessmann, who also had higher test scores
than African-Americans and Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   In May, US District Court Chief Joseph Tauro upheld Latin's
50-50 policy, recognizing the need for affirmative action when
studies have shown that racism can depress test scores. The School
Committee estimates that eliminating affirmative action would make
Latin 87 percent white and Asian American. The Boston Public
Schools are 75 percent African-American and Latino.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, the First Circuit Court of Appeals declared the
policy unconstitutional and ordered that Wessmann be immediately
admitted to Latin. A disparaging appeals court said the School
Committee gave ``absolutely no competent evidence'' how past
discrimination fuels the racial gap in test scores.
</P>
<P>
   The School Committee meekly responded as if it had no
alternative. It dropped affirmative action and announced that exams
were the only way to get into Latin, Latin Academy, and the John D.
O'Bryant School of Mathematics and Science.
</P>
<P>
   The committee voted to appeal to the Supreme Court. But equal
opportunity is such a low priority on the high court that none of
its 34 law clerks are African-American. Such a court is far more
likely to side with the appeals court than Tauro.
</P>
<P>
   This leaves the Boston School Committee as the trustee of two
systems, one of low resources and menial expectations for black and
brown children and one that rewards white families who prepare for
Latin by abandoning public schools or taking over the spots in the
few public schools that suit them. In 1996, the Globe found that 70
percent of new Latin students came from private schools or only
five of the city's 75 elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   The School Committee can no longer allow tests to be the primary
determinant of ``merit.'' For all of Latin's hallowed history, it
is being conveniently forgotten that for the first 329 years of its
363-year existence, you did not need an exam to get into it as long
as you had high grades in major subjects and a strong
recommendation from your school. It has only been since the
mid-1970s that a nationally standardized independent school test
began to be used.
</P>
<P>
   In a conservative climate that so equates merit with test scores
that even the Globe substitutes ``merit'' for scores in its prose,
McLaughlin's crusade has made exams even more the executioner's ax,
even as studies show that test scores are not an accurate long-term
predictor of achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The School Committee and Payzant can, should they choose, create
a system that holds the ax at bay. It can have a rigorous
admissions system where test scores are optional.
</P>
<P>
   Exam school applicants are now ranked on a combination of grades
and tests. A new system could qualify students for an interview via
either a high base-level or pass/fail test score and an essay or a
high grade point and an essay. An interview committee would decide
the final mix of students. The committee can factor whether the
life a child with qualifying grades from the projects in Roxbury or
Southie is worth as much as the life of a child who earned a high
test score in relative comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Or it can enact a system similar to the University of Texas,
which, after the demise of affirmative action there, now admits the
top 10 percent of students from each public and independent high
school in the state to its flagship Austin campus, regardless of
test scores. The plan has already seen a rise in the percentage of
African-American and Latino students.
</P>
<P>
   Or, it could take all students who have qualifying test scores
or qualifying grades, or take the top 10 percent of students from
each elementary school and conduct a lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that in a time when Michael McLaughlin is
single-handedly destroying affirmative action, the School Committee
and Payzant must offer more than a sheepish bleating before a
Supreme Court slaughter. Otherwise, Latin will be our white
flagship of privilege while African-American and Latino children
are told that their struggle for excellence against the odds of
public education is a struggle always doomed for second place.
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
