<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WHICH CURIOUS GEORGE LEARNS ABOUT `CHARITY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Margret Rey, co-creator of the classic children's book
character Curious George, died two years ago this week. She died
childless and left a considerable fortune to charity _ a legacy
that has been the subject of curious monkeyshines by some of
Boston's best-known ``charitable'' institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The quintessential Cantabrigian, Rey left a multimillion-dollar
estate to be divided up among public television's WGBH, the Harvard
student social service agency Phillips Brooks House Association,
the Sierra Club, the World Wildlife Fund, and 12 other worthy
causes. Her will built upon an already sizable philanthropic
commitment. Before her death, she had established the charitable
Curious George Foundation and also donated $1 million each to the
Boston Public Library and Beth Israel Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Since Rey died, lawyers for beneficiaries WGBH, Brooks House
Association, and WBUR have been warring with Rey's executors over
what portion of the estate is rightfully theirs. Five mainline
Boston law firms have thrown bodies into the fray, and litigation
costs are threatening to devour Rey's estate. ``What's 'GBH
underwriting here _ `Bleak House'?'' asks investment adviser John
Spooner, a co-trustee of Rey's foundation. ``Maybe they've shown
too much Dickens over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   The man being fitted for the Scrooge suit, 'GBH president Henry
Becton, says he has a fiduciary duty to recover the full donation
he believes the station is entitled to. Like everyone else in this
imbroglio, he claims to be doing what Rey would have wanted him to
do: ``Future donors have to have confidence that we are going to
honor their wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is Rey's deathbed recommitment to her Jewish roots. The
granddaughter of a Hamburg rabbi and the daughter of parents who
fled Nazi Germany, Rey acknowledged her ethnicity though she was
not religiously observant. But as she lay dying, her co-executor
and friend Lay Lee Ong says, Rey added several gifts to her will.
These included sums for VNACare Choices, the hospice organization
that cared for her; the two hospitals where she received treatment;
and a much larger, $1.8 million-dollar donation to the Combined
Jewish Philanthropies of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Easier said than done. Rey died before she could amend her will.
(Her husband and collaborator, Hans, had predeceased her.) Six
million dollars of her estate was to be divided among 'GBH (20
percent), the Brooks House Association (20 percent), and the 14
other charities. Because Rey never put her belated bequest in
writing, Ong decided to sign away rights to a separate $3 million
securities account jointly held by her and Rey, and assigned that
money to the new beneficiaries. But 'GBH got wind of the deal and
sicced their lawyer on Ong, blocking the added gifts. 'GBH asserts
that the $3 million joint account was part of Rey's estate and that
the station deserves 20 percent of it.
</P>
<P>
   How ugly is this? Pretty ugly. Here are two echt-WASP outfits,
'GBH (founded with Lowell money) and the Phillips Brooks House
Association (Harvard money), working with white-shoe law firm Ropes
&AMP; Gray to snatch money from the Combined Jewish Philanthropies.
Becton shrugs off the possible negative public relations
consequences for 'GBH: ``You can't do the right thing by worrying
about what's written in the press.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to redirect her $3 million bequest to charity, Ong
needed the assent of Rey's 16 beneficiaries. But 'GBH's lawyer
fired off a dissenting letter to the same groups, trying to torpedo
Ong's proposal. Signed by attorney Carolyn Osteen of Ropes &AMP; Gray,
it was taken by the Rey camp as a declaration of war. ``Without
more detailed evidence of Margaret (sic) Rey's intent that the
joint account assets be distributed to `Jewish charities' selected
by Lay Lee Ong and John Spooner, I am troubled by your proposal to
disregard the clear statement of intent set forth in the (will),''
Osteen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to strike a compromise, Ong offered to distribute
15 percent of the $3 million to the 16 original beneficiaries, plus
the $800,000 appreciation in the account. No go, said 'GBH. Rather
than share 15 percent of the money earmarked for the added
beneficiaries, 'GBH wants its full 20 percent of the $3 million _
or thinks that a court will give it a better settlement than the
one Ong is offering. ``They're saying, `We'll see you in court,' ''
Ong says. ``We'd like to see them exhibit some kind of good will.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want this to be a battle,'' Becton insists. He says
other beneficiaries, including the American Civil Liberties Union,
WBUR, and Brooks House Association, support 'GBH's stance on the
will. Boston University general counsel Todd Klipp contributed a
belligerent letter on WBUR's behalf, but did not return my phone
call seeking comment. (Privately, the 'BUR brass just wants this
flap to go away.)
</P>
<P>
   As for Brooks House Association, executive director Paul
McDonald now regrets that its lawyer, Samuel Sichko, questioned
Ong's integrity at a meeting concerning the will. ``It's clear that
Lay Lee has a strong moral case,'' he says. ``We're not on
anybody's side at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, several beneficiaries, including the Boys and
Girls Clubs of Boston, the humanitarian Petra Foundation, and
Somerville's Family Center will probably oppose 'GBH in the Rey
dispute. Ultimately, the opponents square off on whether to believe
Ong's account of Rey's deathbed wishes. ``I don't know whether I
believe them,'' Becton says. Family Center chairman Anne Peretz
does believe Ong. ``That sounds like Margret,'' she says. ``I feel
comfortable going along with what Lay Lee is suggesting. I think
she is corrrectly stating Margret's wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Peretz, who also sits on the Brooks House Association board, has
already taken steps to tamp down the rhetoric and negotiate a
settlement. Becton has appointed a trustees' committee to examine
the dispute for 'GBH: ``We'd be willing to consider mediation,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Rey is not alive to sort out the tangled juridical knot
woven by her mischievous, fictional lunch ticket, Curious George.
Second-guessing the intentions of the intelligent, spiky writer,
who once blurted out, in a moment of weakness, ``I hate
children!,'' may become the work of the courts.
</P>
<P>
   But Ong, who lived with Rey for the last seven years of her
life, has no doubt what her friend would say to those who are
opposing her deathbed philanthropy: ``If Margret were here, she'd
tell them all to go to hell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
