<HEADLINE>
NEW OAKLAND MAYOR FACES A HUGE URBAN CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Standing in line last week at Peet's coffee
shop in Oakland, I overheard the following conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Woman in her 30s: ``I'd like to shop in Oakland, but I've had to
go to San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Man in his 30s: ``We've been going to Walnut Creek, which is so
un-Oakland.''
</P>
<P>
   This being the December holiday gift-buying season, the lament
of these two Oaklanders highlights a deficiency that faces Jerry
Brown when he becomes Oakland's mayor on Jan. 4: a lack of
retailing choices in the East Bay's largest city.
</P>
<P>
   The relative dearth of retailers isn't a life-and-death
situation. Yet it is one problem that Brown could attempt to solve
that would go a long way toward making his imminent ascent to power
in urban America memorable, at least for Oaklanders starved for
retailing choices.
</P>
<P>
   Any improvement in Oakland's retailing prospects that Brown can
effect would be a plus for him, despite fast-changing consumer
trends. Buying goods over the Internet is the coming wave, and
catalog shopping is already popular. Nonetheless, as the coffee
line conversation indicated, Oakland residents now go to San
Francisco, Alameda, Emeryville, Walnut Creek and San Leandro to
shop for goods that could very well be sold in Oakland, but aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland once had a lot of stores which sold clothes, appliances,
furniture, shoes and other consumer goods. Along the once-glorious
Broadway between 14th and 20th streets, only one major retailer
remains _ a Sears.
</P>
<P>
   The decrease in shopping options in Oakland is a symptom of a
larger problem _ the flight of the white middle class to the
burgeoning East Bay suburbs and the loss of good-paying industrial
jobs. Oakland still has middle-class people who live in some lovely
neighborhoods, but the city has a larger proportion of poor people
than other cities in Alameda County. Retailers don't like to locate
near a lot of poor people.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the former California governor with a flaky reputation,
inherits a city with more problems than just a retailing shortage.
A weak economic base, for one. A troubled school system, for
another. A nagging crime situation, to cite a third.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has said his highest priority is to reduce crime. That
makes him sound like any other politician, not one known for his
far-out, sustainable-environment views.
</P>
<P>
   Even as its downtown continues to struggle, Oakland is showing
signs of surprising health elsewhere. Jack London Square is
booming, with new restaurants, a famous jazz club, a multiscreen
movie theater, and a Barnes and Noble bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from the desultory Broadway corridor is the Old Oakland
neighborhood, which for years stood dormant. It is now coming to
life with new housing being built and a popular Vietnamese
restaurant drawing enthusiastic crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Other Oakland neighborhoods like Piedmont Avenue, Rockridge,
Lake Shore and Grand Lake, Chinatown, Temescal and Dimond-Laurel
are in pretty good shape with good housing values and small-ticket
shopping areas.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations for Brown remain high. For all of his fame,
however, he has never been known to be attentive to economic
nuts-and-bolts issues like creating good jobs and enticing the
middle class to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   He can talk environmental sustainability all he wants, but
Oaklanders want a broader economic base so they won't have to leave
town to buy Christmas gifts _ or leave town altogether to find a
good school system.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Brown is going to find out soon that winning an election
is a lot easier than governing a city with a weak economy and a
huge inferiority complex.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
