<SLUG> BC-SANTA-LIFESTYLE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA GETS REAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Mass. _ Santa had just started his midday break at
the Burlington Mall, where two shopper-clogged corridors stood
between his throne and the tranquility of a back office.
</P>
<P>
   Bear in mind that Santa of Burlington gets just two breaks
during a 13-hour work day here. Biology would suggest the guy might
make a dash of it. But not this Kris Kringle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yo, wassup?'' he offered as greeting to two teenagers coming
out of a CD store. He chatted with them about the latest Tupac
release. Then he went down on his haunches to meet and hug a pair
of disabled visitors in their wheelchairs.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a man on a break from a myth. This was a veteran
politician working the crowd as only someone who truly believes in
himself can do. Santa is doing the same thing at other large malls,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that Santa nowadays is living his myth as never
before, according to members of his most critical audience, the
beard-pulling children, not to mention parents and mall marketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began to notice a change a few years ago,'' said Sheila
Hennessy, a spokeswoman for the Burlington Mall. ``Santa came to us
with a real beard, a real gut, and, most importantly, a real
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The pillow-packed Santa stand-ins with polyester whiskers and a
ho-ho hum attitude would appear to be a dwindling lot. While the
Santas at several malls declined to discuss their salary, some can
earn upwards of $2,000 weekly for the seasonal gig.
</P>
<P>
   It may be proof that sometimes nice guys finish first.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for example, the Santa at the Natick (Mass.) Mall. He
asked that another name he uses not be published.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be right. Santa is the name I identify with
most,'' he explained between visits. For the four years he's been
at Natick, his wife has worked by his side, making children smile
for the camera. Her name? Mrs. Claus, of course.
</P>
<P>
   When the Natick Santa is off duty, he said he lives in Wilbraham
as a retired scout camp manager.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer he volunteers at a state park in the
Berkshires where he cuts grass and where his off-season wardrobe
includes a green elf's hat and red suspenders. The neighborhood
kids are convinced his primary mission is reconnaissance,
monitoring behavior prior to deciding who gets what.
</P>
<P>
   This Santa's repartee with the children on his knee typically
went like this:
</P>
<P>
   Santa: What did you bring me?
</P>
<P>
   Child: Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Santa: Oh yes you did! You carry it all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Child: Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Santa: You've got love! You've got a hug for me!
</P>
<P>
   (Big hug.)
</P>
<P>
   Santa: See, I told you so.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 seconds have passed and a new child climbs upon his
knee. He is one of the 11,000 children visiting Santas this season
at each of the country's 1,800 enclosed malls, according to
industry estimates. What is missing from the Natick exchange _ and
exchanges in a growing number of malls, according to Santa _ is
forced laughter or any protracted discussion about what toys are
wanted for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies a paradox shadowing the new, improved, ``real''
Santa. Increasingly, he's talking love, not greed, in the heart of
American malls where, figuratively speaking, management might be
content to have patrons shop 'til they drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's just fine,'' said Sally Hertz, a spokeswoman for
the South Shore Plaza in Braintree. ``Santa _ the real Santa _ is
what we want at the center of our community.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braintree Santa also goes by the name of Dan Headstream, a
retired teacher from Conyers, Georgia. He has a southern accent,
but explains it to Massachusetts children this way: ``I spend time
at the South Pole, too.''
</P>
<P>
   To watch Santa/Headstream work with children is to watch a
grandparent dawdle over his namesakes. This is his second year at
the Plaza, where management provides him with an off site
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   He contends children can spot a fake Santa faster than a camera
can flash. ``That's why a lot of them cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Laura Doerfer, 5, and her brother Byron, 6, clambered
upon Santa's knees to discuss the type of cookies he liked best.
The Doerfers live in Needham, where, at least in one home, Santa's
cookies will be sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother, Priscilla, watched from a distance, her eyes fixed
on the exchange and the ease with which her children and Santa
talked recipes.
</P>
<P>
   And in the gaze was just a hint of mystery, or maybe it was
hope, that this bearded man in red was the real thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
