<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENOMINATION DRAWING A NEW KIND OF CATHOLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new Catholic parish begun in Peabody, Mass. last year with
just a handful of people now regularly draws 50 worshipers to
Sunday Mass. Nothing unusual about that.
</P>
<P>
   Except that St. Francis of Assisi is not the the kind of
Catholic church that would immediately come to mind. It is
Catholic, but not Roman Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   St. Francis is the first parish in Massachusetts belonging to
the Catholic Apostolic Church in North America, a denomination
whose existence can be directly attributed to Christianity's
complex and, often, tumultuous history.
</P>
<P>
   Over the centuries, as the Roman Catholic Church grew around the
bishop of Rome into an institution that now rules one billion Roman
Catholics worldwide, not everyone wanted to be governed by the
Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Most history students know about the schism with Orthodox
Christians in the 11th century or the Protestant Reformation in the
16th century, which gave birth to new Christian religions.
</P>
<P>
   Much less known, principally because they are relatively small,
are several independent and self-governing Catholic churches that
bear many similarities to the Roman Catholic Church, including
celebrating the same sacraments.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these denominations have broken away or refused to be
part of the Roman Catholic Church for theological or administrative
reasons. They all claim to be as genuinely Catholic as the church
headed by the pope, although the Vatican does not recognize most of
these denominations.
</P>
<P>
   Some have been around for hundreds of years, while others, like
the Catholic Apostolic Church in North America, are newcomers to
the Catholic world.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Apostolic Church distinguishes itself from the
Roman Catholic Church because it does not believe the pope has the
authority to teach infallibly, allows priests to marry, and is less
strict in its views on gays and people who are divorced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reaching out with the vision of what would Christ do,''
said Bishop Willard Schultz of New York, the denomination's
presiding bishop. ``We don't turn people away. We try to find in
each other Christlike images and examples rather than being
judgmental. We seek to teach and learn from one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1949 in New Mexico, the Catholic Apostolic Church
claims 30,000 to 35,000 members in the United States, including
several former Roman Catholic priests. But in the last three years,
Schultz said, the church's membership has grown by several
thousand.
</P>
<P>
   The denomination, Schultz said, is benefiting from two trends in
American society: the desire by many Americans to find deeper
spiritual meaning in their lives and the disenchantment some Roman
Catholics feel toward a church they believe is too rigid.
</P>
<P>
   St. Francis, which was started in July 1997, was born out of
controversy involving Roman Catholic parishioners angered by the
Archdiocese of Boston's decision to close their church, St.
Joseph's in Peabody.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rev. Gerry Clements, a priest ordained in the Catholic
Apostolic Church, saw parishioners protesting in front of St.
Joseph's _ one of several churches shuttered by the archdiocese in
recent years _ he offered to help.
</P>
<P>
   The parishioners asked Clements to say Mass, a move that
archdiocesan officials tried unsuccessfully to stop. A short time
later Clements and some former members of St. Joseph's started St.
Francis, which meets at a Lutheran church.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very close family because many of the people here
came to this church as a group from St. Joe's,'' said Clements, who
is now one of three priests from the Catholic Apostolic Church
serving in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Another of them, the Rev. Joseph Reynolds, a former Roman
Catholic priest, recently launched St. Jude's, a new parish in
Methuen.
</P>
<P>
   Clements said he has long had a desire to be a priest but the
Roman Catholic Church was never a possibility because he is
married.
</P>
<P>
   ``After much searching, the Catholic Apostolic Church became the
one I felt most comfortable in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Stewart, a professor of nursing at Simmons College and a
baptized Roman Catholic, recently became an ordained permanent
deacon at St. Francis. In the Roman Catholic Church women are not
allowed to be ordained deacons. Women are still excluded from the
priesthood, however, in the Catholic Apostolic Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud to be part of such an inclusive church, one
that elevates the role of all members, including women,'' said
Stewart, who helps provide nursing care to homeless people in
Boston. ``This is the Catholic church I feel is right for me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments to Diego Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107-2378; or via e-mail to religion(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
