<HEADLINE>
ENVIOUS STARR; A DISNEY CENSOR; THE FUN OF WRITING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've all read that bawdy bestseller known as The Starr Report
(``Unimpeachably spellbinding! I couldn't put it down!'' _ W. J.
Clinton), and we've all wondered at times about the character and
motivations of its ``author,'' Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   In this week's Time magazine, in his most extensive interview
this year, the independent counsel lets slip a few tantalizing and
telling remarks about the president he spent so long pursuing, and
whose downfall he may yet achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Authors Eric Pooley and Michael Weisskopf observe that when
Starr talks about President Clinton, ``a hint of envy creeps into
his voice,'' and that certainly comes across when Starr says of
Clinton: ``It must be nice to have that kind of I.Q. Doing well
academically . . . but not having to spend all that terribly much
time doing it.'' Starr recounts details of a chance encounter with
President Clinton in a crowded elevator two decades ago, when
Clinton was a boy-wonder governor and Starr was a young lawyer with
his nose to the grindstone. ``I just remember him as being very
attractive,'' says Starr. ``There was a buzz about him in the
elevator.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fascination of the battle between Clinton and Starr
_ who share the cover as Time's Men of the Year _ is that two such
polar opposites would end up locked in mortal combat with a
president's fate hanging in the balance. One irony begets another:
Pooley and Weisskopf write that ``Starr believes his reputation
died for Clinton's sins'' _ and of course, Clinton feels the same
way about Starr.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Walt Disney Co. bought ABC in 1995, executives on both
sides vowed that the editorial independence of the network's news
division would not be compromised.
</P>
<P>
   That pledge began to ring hollow to many in October when ABC
News president David Westin killed a story that was highly critical
of ABC's corporate parent. The story by investigative reporter
Brian Ross found that convicted pedophiles were working at Disney
World and blamed Disney's failure to conduct background checks on
new hires.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Brill's Content nails Westin and ABC News for the
decision to spike the Ross report, which was, according to writer
Elizabeth Lesly Stevens, ``a well-sourced story, one that . . . met
the standards of fairness and reportorial backup commonly found in
investigative television pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   But it apparently didn't meet Westin's standards. Stevens
reports that when Westin got a look at the show's script in
October, he repeatedly demanded of Ross, ``Are you crazy?'', before
killing the story.
</P>
<P>
   Dishearteningly enough, Stevens concludes that the most likely
scenario is not that Disney ordered the story yanked, but that
Westin _ a former corporate attorney who is trying to move out of
the shadow of his formidable predecessor, Roone Arledge _ ``moved
proactively to avoid grief from his bosses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole mess validates the viewing public's worst fears
about conglomerate ownership of major news outlets,'' Stevens
writes. ``In this case, an otherwise powerful, prestigious news
operation has shown itself incapable of covering _ or unwilling to
cover _ a major cultural and economic force in American life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There will always be an England, of course, but its national
heroes come under some eye-opening scrutiny this month in the
British magazine Realm.
</P>
<P>
   Take King Arthur, among the most enduring of English national
legends. Author Michael Jenner points out that whichever
sixth-century nobleman the Arthur story is based on, he and his
knights fought to defend not an English realm but a Celtic one.
Moreover, Jenner notes that Arthur's sworn enemies were ``the very
Angles and Saxons who eventually prevailed and went on to give
England both her name and identity.'' (It's as if we Americans were
suddenly told that George Washington was actually a Tory.)
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Arthur wasn't technically an Englishman, but surely St.
George, England's patron saint, was? Nope. It turns out that St.
George was a Palestinian soldier who ``never actually set foot in
England.'' Jenner even questions whether the robber-archer upon
whom the Robin Hood myth is based actually stole from the rich and
gave to the poor: The 18th-century book on which the legend is
based is now considered suspect by scholars, having been proven to
have been ``strongly influenced by the ideology of the French
Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Delbanco delivers a wonderfully word-drunk valentine to
the writing craft in the January Harper's magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Delbanco structures his piece around the duke of Gloucester's
famously fatuous put-down of Edward Gibbon upon the completion of
Gibbon's ``The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman
Empire'': ``Another damned, thick, square book! Always scribble,
scribble, scribble! Eh! Mr. Gibbon?''
</P>
<P>
   Delbanco's answer to the ``Why write?'' question implied by the
dismissive duke takes many forms, but the one I liked best is this:
Writing is simply fun. ``If there weren't pure pleasure in the way
words edge up against one another, in the way paragraphs fit . . .
then we'd all have to be a higher- and bloodier-minded bunch,''
writes Delbanco. ``Because the average wage is maybe a penny a
page, or a dime each twenty hours, and the average reward is
anonymity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4130 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGHTECH-MAGNET-2ND &LR;  &UR;      12-23 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHTECH-MAGNET-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... have shrunk.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Immigrants at the top of educational attainment are as
educated or more educated than comparable Americans,'' says Miriam
Wasserman, author of a recent article on immigration for the
Regional Review magazine of the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The India contingent is a prime example.
</P>
<P>
   So many Indian and Pakistani entrepreneurs have converged on the
Boston area that they established an East Coast chapter of The
Indus Entrepreneurs, or TIE, a network started in Silicon Valley
six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Open Market Inc.'s co-founder, Shikhar Ghosh, the son of a
businessman in India, came to Boston in 1978 to attend Harvard
Business School. He believes that Boston's Indian population is
markedly different from New York's, where ``the news stands and
cabs are run by people from south Asia.'' In Boston, ``you go to a
high-tech convention and you'll run into more Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   Bright students denied admission to the prestigious Indian
Institute of Technology in Bombay _ students like Eswar
Priyadarshan _ are easily admitted to US colleges, say Indian
expatriates. India's best high schools provide excellent
preparation for high-tech fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't the hot shot there. When I came here I was on fire,''
says Priyadarshan, the son of a Cambridge-educated English
professor. The younger Priyadarshan came to Boston in 1982 from
Bangalore, India, to attend Boston University. ``Once I started to
get those 4.0s I was on a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   After earning his bachelor's and master's degrees in computer
science, he joined Open Market as an engineering director.
</P>
<P>
   While reasons for immigrating differ by country, goals converge
at Sitara Networks, which calls itself the ``International House of
Software.'' More than one-third of employees at the Waltham
Internet company, headed by a Pakistani, hail from some 15
countries _ from China and Cuba to Indonesia and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very easy to come in if you have any amount of
education,'' says Boris Boruchovich, Sitara's director of software
engineering who emigrated in 1979 from St. Petersburg, Russia.
``You take a number of classes, learn some basic things in computer
engineering, and find a job. Most people I know who immigrate _
this is the route they take.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston has one of the biggest Russian immigrant populations in
the country. Communities such as Brookline have large populations
of Russians Jews, who first came to the city in droves around 1890.
</P>
<P>
   When Fima Furman's father brought him and two siblings to Boston
in 1991, soon after their mother had died of cancer, the family
relied on two other Russian families for support. One for financial
help; one for a place to stay while his father searched for work as
a software engineer.
</P>
<P>
   The Furmans, who are half Jewish but are Russian Orthodox in
practice, fled Moscow amid rising anti-Semitism and the frightening
prospect of military service, which might require they ``go to
Chechnya and kill your own people,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The family chose Boston ``because we have already friends here,
connections here,'' he says. A second reason: ``Boston is an
economically growing city with lots of high-tech and biotech and
software companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Furman, 24, completed his high school education at Newton South,
earned a bachelor's degree from Brandeis University and now works
in a lab at Hybridon, a biomedical company. And his education
continues. He is taking an intensive course in C++ computer
language and hopes to combine it with his biology expertise.
</P>
<P>
   After years in this country, Nguyen has acquired the
accoutrements of a suburban family man, including a soft briefcase
with his employer's logo and a Nautica windbreaker. He lives in
Everett with his wife, whom he met on the boat from Vietnam, and
two children. He won the gold medal for Ping Pong in Massachusetts
and set up classes in Chelsea to teach English to Vietnamese
children. He still carries the well-worn letter from the Bureau of
Immigration &AMP; Deportation in Manila, dated Oct. 16, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nguyen never wanted to leave Vietnam, he says he is
happy to be employed in a field in which anything seems possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Vietnam, I cry sometimes at night. You love something but
you can't do anything,'' he says. In this country, ``I am like a
fish in the ocean _ I can do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
TRADITION OF IMMIGRANT ENTREPRENEURS &QL; 
 &QL; 
With its many universities, the Boston area has long been a magnet
for foreign-born people. In recent years, the attraction has
intensified along with the boom in the state's technology
industries. Here is a sampler of foreign-born businesspeople who
started local technology companies.
</P>
<P>
