<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIZE-WAR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOTHING SIZE OFTEN AN IMMEASURABLE PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and l coding; includes sizes text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a problem that has countless women grumbling in store
dressing rooms across America and catalog retailers like Eddie
Bauer, L. L. Bean and Lands' End complaining bitterly about
millions of dollars in merchandise returns.
</P>
<P>
   In the chaotic world of women's clothing sizes, the numbers that
shoppers see on garment tags, from tiny 2 all the way to 20, have
become all but meaningless. Women waste hours trying on clothes
that droop or squeeze, and catalog vendors end up with costly
returns from similarly frustrated mail-order customers.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog companies say the answer to decades of frustration
over finding the right fit is simple: Create sizing standards
across the industry.
</P>
<P>
   But that is anathema to upscale clothiers such as Donna Karan
and Ellen Tracy, which use ``vanity sizing'' to make shoppers think
they are spending their big bucks on fashionably small-sized
outfits.
</P>
<P>
   High-end designers have learned that it is profitable to flatter
women by offering tiny sizes on big garments. The result is that a
woman could fit into a size 6 from one manufacturer but have to
jump all the way to a 12 from another.
</P>
<P>
   The push to eliminate the decades-old guessing game in women's
apparel is being spurred largely by the fast-growing mail-order and
Internet apparel businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Catalog retailers know that accurate sizing is critical since
women can't try on their merchandise. More and more catalogs devote
pages? catolog pages are devoted to explaining sizes and
measurements.
</P>
<P>
   Some department stores, such as Target, also are pushing for
consistency to help their customers, and are urging vendors to
comply with a current? (or is comply wrong verb?) set of standards
in sizing.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time since 1942, a major three-year was it a
3-yr study in 42? study is underway to measure the size and shape
of American woman.
</P>
<P>
   This initiative pleases many in the industry who say too many
women are suffering from fitting-room fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the market transitions to a more relevant set of standards,
it will make more obvious those who are not in synch,'' says
Michael Alexin, vice president of design and product development
for Seattle-based Eddie Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   But the high-end designers are not eager for any of this. They
have made money on vanity sizing, and that has led to today's
haphazard size labeling. (The exception to the high-end rule that
smaller is better is, no surprise, in bra sizing. For more
expensive bras, size labels tend to run big.)
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Goldsberry, associate professor of retailing at the
University of Arizona in Phoenix, says pricey designers have
learned all too well that many women love to exclaim, ``I have a
wonderful dress! And it's a size 2!'' And that they will cough up
extra dollars to say that.
</P>
<P>
   Burt Hunton, vice president of Wolf Form Co. in Englewood, N.J.,
which makes garment-fitting forms for companies such as Donna Karan
and Ellen Tracy, says high-end designers will never go along
willingly with a uniform sizing system.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still want to do their own thing. . . . It makes the
woman customer feel better,'' Hunton says.
</P>
<P>
   He says Ellen Tracy sells size 8 clothes with measurements that
other apparel makers sell as a size 12.
</P>
<P>
   While some shoppers may feel flattered and pay for the
privilege, the sizing game infuriates others, who would like to see
women's clothes come with meaningful, consistent measurements _ in
inches _ as men's clothing does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to see measurements on clothes,'' says Meredith
Pooler, 18, after using holiday gift money to buy herself
custom-fit jeans at Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. in Boston. ``You never know
with different makers what your size is or what a size small,
medium or large means.''
</P>
<P>
   But most people in the industry don't think manufacturers will
start displaying actual measurements on garment tags, as is done
for women's clothing in many parts of Europe, any time soon. They
say American women don't want to see their hip measurement on a
tag. And some clothes makers say the standard trio of measurements
(bust, waist, and hips), plus height, are often overly simplistic
predictors of fit.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not they are eager for standards, almost everyone in
the industry agrees that there's a need for updated information on
the size of the American woman as we approach the millennium. This
information will help all clothing manufacturers develop
better-proportioned and better-fitting clothes, regardless of how
sizes are labeled.
</P>
<P>
   The only sizing chart based on actual measurements of American
women dates to 1942, when more than 10,000 military women were
measured at different body points. The US Department of Commerce
used this data to assign size numbers from 2 to 20 to correspond to
different sets of measurements.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, this data is hopelessly outdated. The average
woman then was 5 feet 2 inches and weighed 129 pounds. Today, the
average woman is about 5 feet 4 inches and weighs about 142 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   While makers of mass-produced clothes may have followed these
guidelines in the 1940s, companies later began to realize that the
shape and size of the typical American woman were growing. Each
company tinkered with its numbers in its own way.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five decades, women's sizing became increasingly
haphazard. Finally, in 1994, the American Society for Testing and
Materials, which sets sizing standards in the industry, came out
with new guidelines. It was based on then-current practices in the
industry, but no new measurements.
</P>
<P>
   According to this chart, which is followed more or less by
catalog vendors and some product lines today, a size 10 woman would
measure 36 inches at the bust, 28 inches at the waist and 38 1/2 at
the hips. In 1942, a 10 measured 33 1/2, 24 1/2, and 35 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   But many apparel makers aren't happy with the chart, and even
the society acknowledges it should have updated the measurements of
women. But an attempt several years ago to drum up funding for a
new measurement study failed, largely because many manufacturers
didn't want to help.
</P>
<P>
   What emerged in its place is a three-year study, sponsored and
funded by the Society of Automotive Engineers, the US Air Force and
some apparel manufacturers. For different reasons, they all want
updated figures on the size of the typical male and female aged 18
to 65. The Air Force wants to make better flight suits, the auto
makers want better-fitting seats, and clothes makers want
better-fitting garments.
</P>
<P>
   The study began last December and will measure more than 10,000
people in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you have a database, businesses can begin to cater to a
particular clientele,'' says Jo Ann Pullen, who heads the textiles
committee for the Testing and Materials Society and is also a high
school instructor of consumer and health issues in Northfield.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an alternative to standardization: mass
customization. Some companies envision customers outfitting
dressing rooms with high-tech body scanners that record multiple
body measurements. Garments would then be custom-designed for a
particular body type.
</P>
<P>
   David Bruner, manager of research and development for TC
Squared, a company in Cary, N.C., says the beauty of body scanning
is that women won't ever have to know any numbers. The information
can be put in a file, and used to make their clothes. ``There's no
stigma attached to a size,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Bruner acknowledges that a big obstacle to this effort is the
cost. Body scanners sold by his company cost about $100,000 each,
and so far, he says, he has sold exactly two.
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss is experimenting with a program called ``Original
Spin'' that allows Meredith Pooler and other customers to obtain
jeans for $55 that are custom-fitted to their measurements, though
for now that information is obtained with old-fashioned measuring
tapes. The system also allows customers to choose options for
color, fly and leg opening.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the wave of the future turns out to be standardization
or mass customization, ``the status quo is very difficult for
women,'' says Susan Ashdown, associate professor in the textile
department at Cornell University. ``The industry is finally waking
up. The whole level of frustration with clothes shopping has
increased.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOW WOMEN GROW BUT STAY THE SAME SIZE &QL; 
 &QL; 
In 1942 manufacturers relied on a US Department of Commerce chart
to put sizes on their clothes. Since then, companies have departed
from the chart and each has gone its own way. The only updated
sizing chart in 1994, from the American Society for Testing and
Materials. It attempted to summarize the typical sizing practices
in the industry today, though many companies deviate wildly from
it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ! Size 6 ! Size 10 ! Size 14 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ! 1942 / 1994 ! 1942 / 1994 ! 1942 / 1994 &QL; 
Bust ! 31 1/2 / 34 ! 33 1/2 / 36 ! 36 1/2 / 39 &QL; 
Waist ! 22 1/2 / 26 ! 24 1/2 / 28 ! 27 1/2 / 31 &QL; 
Hips ! 33 1/2 / 36 1/2 ! 35 1/2 / 38 1/2 ! 38 1/2 / 41 1/2 &QL; 
Height ! 5'2'' / 5'4 1/2'' ! 5'3 1/2'' / 5'5 1/2'' ! 5'4 1/2'' /
5'6 1/2'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOURCE: American Society for Testing and Materials &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
