<SLUG> BC-STAGE-ROUNDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH TOPICS TACKLED ON NEW YORK STAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When plays with difficult subject matter fail,
critics and producers often blame a lazy and feckless audience more
interested in theater as diversion. That's the argument trotted out
for the failure of the critically favored musical about Siamese
twins, ``Side Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet people will leave home to see tough issues explored onstage.
Look at the success of ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane'' and ``Wit,''
both on and off Broadway. Two new plays, one about lesbian love and
gay-bashing, the other about civil war and matricide, are playing
to packed houses while the producers of another wait nervously to
see if a musical about the lynching of a Jewish man in Atlanta will
be a success.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Parade''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly nothing new for musicals to deal with grim
subject matter. ``West Side Story'' and Stephen Sondheim raised the
bar, and until ``The Lion King,'' you couldn't get a musical to be
taken seriously unless it dealt with mass death (``Titanic''),
prostitution (``The Life''), or a serial killer (``Jekyll &AMP;
Hyde'').
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, these were about other things as well, with large
helpings of heroism, romance, and redemption. There is so little of
any of those virtues in the story about the hanging of Leo Frank
that it's easy to see why ``Parade'' makes its producers nervous,
particularly since one of them, Livent, recently filed for
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   There is much that is right with ``Parade,'' which opened last
week at Lincoln Center, including the unique collaboration between
the center and Livent. Jason Robert Brown finds a middle ground
between Sondheim and more melodic predecessors. Carolee Carmello as
Mrs. Frank has a gorgeous voice and does as much justice to ``You
Don't Know This Man'' as ``Ragtime'' diva Audra McDonald does on
her CD. The staging, under Harold Prince's direction and with
Riccardo Hernandez's sets, keeps things flowing dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the first act is quite striking, from the prologue of a
rebel soldier singing about ``The Old Red Hills of Home,'' which
sets the stage for the conflict between Southern tradition and
Yankee interloping. (Frank came from New York to run the National
Pencil Factory in Atlanta.) Britt Craig, playing a drunken reporter
lamenting the lack of ``Big News'' on his beat, turns in a
terrific, brassy solo.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum is largely spent, though, by the time the stage is
set for the murder of Mary Phagan, a factory employee, and Frank's
trial. If you know the story, there aren't any surprises. Worse,
there aren't any surprises in the music, which stops driving the
story forward in the second act.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem is an overly mousy performance by Brent
Carver. Part of the point, of course, is that Frank didn't fit in
with the good ole boys, but Prince goes too far in stereotyping
both sides. Alfred (``Driving Miss Daisy'') Uhry, who wrote the
book, wanted to show how torn he was between his Jewish pride and
Southern pride, but you wouldn't know he was particularly proud of
either from ``Parade.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Stop Kiss'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Diana Son's ``Stop Kiss,'' Sara has her identity splits as
well _ she's a completely assimilated young Asian-American on the
one hand and a straight woman increasingly attracted to Callie,
another straight woman. Their first kiss results in a ferocious
gay-bashing that leaves her fighting for her life.
</P>
<P>
   Did we mention that this is a comedy? Not a funny ha-ha comedy
perhaps, but it is funny. Son alternates scenes between the
couple's developing relationship and the aftermath of the beating.
As in ``Parade,'' the best part is the first scene, in which we
meet Callie, played to hiply spaced-out perfection by Jessica
Hecht. Sara, played by Sandra Oh, has just arrived in New York and
comes to Callie's apartment to deposit her cat and the two begin an
awkward push-pull dance with each other.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sara: I hate jazz. I don't like the sound of saxophones.
</P>
<P>
   Callie: My sister plays the saxophone.
</P>
<P>
   Sara: Oh, I'm sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Callie: I hate my sister.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not Oscar Wilde, but Hecht in particular has such charisma and
timing that we feel we're watching more than a sitcom. (Hecht was a
regular on ``The Single Guy'' and plays a recurring part on
``Friends.'' Oh won a Cable Ace for ``Arliss.'') But despite the
excellent acting and fine writing and staging, how much more than a
sitcom are we getting?
</P>
<P>
   The Public Theater audience, one would assume, is already on the
side of the two women just as the Lincoln Center audience is
already on Frank's side. It's also dubious how well this would play
outside of New York with all its Village references.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``Stop Kiss'' is more than the sum of its
parts. It isn't a ``lesbian comedy''; it's a comedy . . . with
lesbians. Its rewards are in the simple chemistry of two people
making their way in a confusing world. As the relationship
develops, that chemistry is reward enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Electra'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making difficult subject matter easy is not always, perhaps
ever, the most satisfying for audiences. Note the near-ecstatic
reaction to Zoe Wanamaker and the very tough adaptation of
``Electra.'' Like ``The Blue Room'' and the new adaptation of
``Cabaret,'' this is an import from England of a Donmar Warehouse
production, although Wanamaker is supported here largely with
American Equity actors.
</P>
<P>
   If sex is a degraded commodity in those two productions, life
itself is in a ``Mad Max''-like shambles in ancient Greece.
Wanamaker's Electra even looks like a postnuclear survivor with
bloody scabs all over her head. Her clothing is off the Salvation
Army rack, including an oversize overcoat. It belonged to her
father _ Agamemnon _ the victim of her mother's murderous rage.
Clytemnestra (Claire Bloom) conspired to do away with him after he
sacrificed another daughter, Iphigenia.
</P>
<P>
   Frank McGuiness's adaptation is similar to Paul Schmidt's
``Phaedra'' adaptation at the American Repertory Theatre. Elements
of modern idiomatic language underline the contemporaneousness of
the issues. Once violence becomes the option, all sides in a civil
war feel equally justified. Electra, her brother Orestes, and
Clytemnestra are equally right from their perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   Wanamaker and Bloom are so powerful in their agony, however,
that anything but revenge seems an unsatisfactory option. Director
David Leveaux's program notes suggest a more pacifist conclusion
and we may agree with him, but Sophocles's tragedy lies in the
inevitability of the characters' obsessions. Electra becomes
Hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Kidman bares her body onstage in New York, but Zoe
Wanamaker bares her soul.
</P>
<P>
   (``Stop Kiss'' runs through Jan. 31 at the Public Theater and
``Electra'' through March 28 at the Barrymore Theatre. Tickets for
``Parade'' at Lincoln Center are on sale through the end of March,
but it might be extended.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4135 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-23 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIMARCO'S TRIUMPH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Trimarco is heading for the exit.
</P>
<P>
   He's 59, a lawyer, who'll serve on a couple of boards. The four
kids are educated. He heads for the the country house in New
Hampshire when his wife, a Superior Court judge, can get away. Half
his career has been in government service, which is not bad for a
Massachusetts Republican. For eight years he has been first deputy
treasurer under Joe Malone, the political consigliere in an office
that has been run, by virtually all accounts, in a model fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Trimarco is a big boy, and understands how the game works.
But he's at the stage where he really doubts whether the public or
the press really give a rat's fanny about whether government works
honestly or just groans along out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going out as a whiner. It was fun. We did it our way.
We didn't buckle. We go out with a helluva record. We cut the
treasurer's budget in half. We cut the staff from 280 people to
135. At the state pension funds, we took them from the worst
performing funds in the country to one of the best. We brought in
professional managers, we used no political investors. You can
still make mistakes, but when you make political investments,
instead of purely professional investment decisions, you make more
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Trimarco ``played Mr. Inside to Joe's Mr.
Outside.'' Trimarco is philosophical about Malone's up-or-out
kamikaze challenge to Acting Governor Cellucci in the bitter GOP
primary last fall. He is more disheartened by the public's
indifference and the press's lack of aggressive monitoring of
government. When the media cares not enough about what goes on,
beyond the titillation of scandal or the whiffs of incense given
off by smoldering ambitions, doing the right thing by the public is
an uphill grind.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of this is automatic pilot. It needs administering, and
decision-making, and paying attention'' by those running important
public offices, he said. ``The press doesn't want a `good news'
story about a program that's working right; it's only interested in
controversy, in bad news.''
</P>
<P>
   Had his luck been better, he might have been a GOP member of
Congress. Trimarco ran twice and lost against former Representative
Nick Mavroules, subsequently unhorsed by scandal. Trimarco grew up
in the Bronx, graduated from Dartmouth and BC Law School, where he
was on the Law Review and afterword clerked for Chief Justice
Joseph Tauro on the state's Supreme Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   If he had gone to Congress, he would have voted on the Clinton
impeachment last week, a development he sees as injurious to the
Republican Party everywhere. Acknowledging the GOP House losses of
last November, and the public's siding with Clinton during that
election, he asked: ``Has something changed? Did I miss
something?'' Trimarco is one of the GOP moderates, in the tradition
of the Sargents, Saltonstalls, Richardsons, Brookes, Volpes, and
Welds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people wield power very well, as if they were born to
it.'' Frank Sargent, Ed Brooke, Mike Dukakis, Bill Weld were some
of the names he ticked off. ``Other guys get drunk with it; they
live to see their names in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   With Malone, he continued, ``We came in, tried to make a
difference, and I think we did. But I ask myself: `Does anybody
care?' '' He answered his own question. ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Does the press care? Does the public? He can't answer that. He
said neither he nor Malone wanted to hang around in the treasurer's
office beyond two terms. He's seen too many other lifers under the
Dome. ``They hang on. They delude themselves that they're
indispensable to the office.''
</P>
<P>
   When the late Governor John A. Volpe was appointed as the first
Italian-American to be ambassador to Italy in the early 1970s,
Trimarco went with him as his counselor. He got an early lesson in
how a government functionary with gumption can change things.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1972, Nixon and Kissinger were flirting with a coup against
the Italian government, do you believe it?'' The US ambassador
preceding Volpe, Graham Martin, had been moved to South Vietnam,
where his strong anticommunist sentiments mirrored those of
Nixon's. Trimarco said Martin had approved a stream of US funding
for a secretive group of ``right-wing Italian Catholics'' who
wanted to topple the Fanfani government. Martin sent Volpe a
scorching letter from Vietnam demanding Volpe maintain the secret
funding channel.
</P>
<P>
   When Volpe politely refused to reinstate the funding, said
Trimarco, the ambassador got a visit from General Vernon Walters, a
national security operative. Trimarco said, ``Volpe says that
General Walters made it very clear that Nixon and Kissinger want me
to continue this money thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Trimarco: ``Volpe was a man of good instincts, who always tried
to do the right thing, very humble. I said to Volpe: `You have all
the cards. Send a message that the only way you'll do this is if
they fly you back to the Oval Office and give you a direct
face-to-face order. They can't stand the flak. He said, `OK, let's
send that message.' And they never called him back on it, and to
the best of my knowledge, the money stopped. It was a great moment.
It showed me that one person can make a difference in government,
if you have some moral convictions. You look back on that today,
and it's laughable. But you have to be willing to step up and
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
