<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4136 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGHTECH-MAGNET-ART-2     12-23 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHTECH-MAGNET-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAND OF HIGH-TECH OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Includes immigrant entrepreneurs, immigrant origin text tables)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ During three years in a refugee camp, the letter was
all that Minh Nguyen had anticipated. When it finally arrived, he
could not open it.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnamese refugees crowding around Nguyen, awaiting news of
their own, grabbed the letter that would grant or deny him
political asylum in the United States. ``I hear, `You got it! You
got it!' '' he says, recalling the joy overwhelming him as the
message of freedom sank in.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Jeet Singh's passage was papered with college
letters of acceptance. From Princeton University, Columbia
University, Swarthmore College, and the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. ``I came to MIT,'' says Singh, the only son of an
Indian diplomat who has lived on five continents, ``because I liked
Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a world of difference in the life experiences that
brought Nguyen, 38, and Singh, 35, to Boston. What they share is
membership in the growing group of immigrants who have succeeded in
making careers in a center of cutting-edge technology.
</P>
<P>
   Boston universities have for decades been a magnet for foreign
students. But in more recent years a uniquely well-educated
immigrant population is also being attracted to the area by its
booming high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   Many are like Nguyen, who worked his way through college and, as
a software writer for Cambridge-based Lotus Development Corp.,
helps fill a yawning gap in the local supply of skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   A few, like Singh, founder of Art Technology Group, a Boston
designer of Web sites, are continuing the entrepreneurial tradition
perhaps best represented by Chinese immigrant An Wang, founder of
Wang Laboratories Inc., one of Massachusetts' early computer
company successes.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign-born residents _ 13 percent of the state's population of
6 million _ say that software, the Internet, and biotechnology
provide a discrimination-free arena in which they are judged by
what they can do. And they do a lot, either through tenacity or
with advantages of being educated in school systems superior to the
American system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have the skills, the competence, the desire, you can do
anything you want,'' says Malik Khan, the 43-year-old founder of
Sitara Networks Inc., who emigrated from Pakistan in 1974 to attend
MIT. ``I've lived in Asia, in Europe, the US _ I've never found a
system quite like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of immigrants arrive in this country with little
money or advanced schooling. Many labor in low- and moderate-paying
service and manufacturing jobs in hopes of improving their lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big lump (of immigrants) at the bottom end and a
small lump at the top end'' of educational attainment, says George
Borjas, a professor at Harvard University's Kennedy School of
Government and expert on immigration patterns. But, he adds, ``The
small lump ends up in a place like Boston'' due to its
concentration of universities and technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the state's immigrant population is better educated than
immigrants nationwide. According to Massachusetts Insight, a public
policy consulting group, 33.2 percent of immigrants arriving here
after 1990 have bachelor's or graduate degrees. That is up from 28
percent of the immigrant population arriving in Massachusetts
before 1990.
</P>
<P>
   That counters a national trend in which 25.2 percent of
post-1990 immigrants hold college degrees, down from 32.8 percent.
By comparison, about one-fourth of US-born residents in
Massachusetts _ and nationwide _ have college degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russian immigrants head to Boston, for example, ``because
they had technical jobs in the country where they were from,'' says
Miriam Stein, communications director for the Massachusetts
Immigrant and Refugee Advocacy Coalition. ``And Boston is a
high-tech magnet, so it's easy for them, and there's a low
unemployment rate so jobs are available.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back in Vietnam, a college education was Nguyen's goal when he
slipped into the night in 1989 to board a wooden boat docked on the
beach of his home town, Nhatrang. It took six days and seven nights
for 150 refugees to cross the South China Sea and arrive at a
Philippine refugee camp, from which Nguyen would eventually be
admitted to the United States in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   He believes he was denied an education at home because his older
brothers had been in the South Vietnamese army. Nguyen still
carries his application to study oceanography in Vietnam. On it, he
detailed his brothers' affiliation; Nguyen never heard back from
the college. His mother languished in poverty while his brothers
were in jail. Finally, Nguyen left Vietnam after authorities
accused him of plotting to leave and he was regarded as an illegal
resident in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Once in Boston, Nguyen attended Bunker Hill Community College
and then the University of Massachusetts-Boston, earning a
bachelor's degree in computer science. Turning down two other job
offers, he joined Cambridge-based Lotus last year and was recently
promoted, he says. ``I'm happy to say that.''
</P>
<P>
   John C.C. Fan, president of Kopin Corp., was a pioneer when he
emigrated in the early 1960s from Hong Kong to attend the
University of California at Berkeley. He came to Boston to earn a
doctorate in applied physics at Harvard University and, in 1984,
founded Kopin, a Taunton maker of computer parts.
</P>
<P>
   Having come from a former British colony gave him an advantage:
fluency in English. Today, many immigrants not conversant in
English, he says, are drawn to high tech because they are at ease
with the universal languages of math or science and ``they don't
need to be fluent in the language.''
</P>
<P>
   Fan employs a polyglot work force _ as do many other immigrant
entrepreneurs in high tech _ a practice that reinforces the
immigrant influx. One in five of Kopin's 150 workers emigrated _
many hold advanced degrees _ from countries like Russia, Cambodia,
Vietnam, Thailand, Taiwan, and South Korea. ``We have everybody,''
Fan says.
</P>
<P>
   At growing high-tech companies desperate for talented
programmers, immigrants can be a life-saver. Massachusetts' work
force is growing only 1 percent a year, according to a recent
study; without immigrants, the work force would have shrunk.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
