<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS: NO TIME FOR PATS ON THE BACK YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The screws, as he likes to say, are being tightened. For his
part, they will be not let up even if the game has no affect on his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to play this game just like we play all of the
others,'' said Jets coach Bill Parcells after practice at the
team's Long Island facility. ``To win. At this time of year (going
into the playoffs) it is important that you keep your team playing
a high level. We will approach this like it is a playoff game. We
won't rest guys. We will play our best people as the game
dictates.''
</P>
<P>
   As is his wont before so-called ``big games,'' Parcells was not
happy with the way his team worked out Tuesday. ``Let's just say
that I yelled a lot,'' he said when asked why his voice was raspy.
``Seems that we got some players that forgot how they got here. We
tried to remind them how it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells watched video of the Patriots' victory over San
Francisco and was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they did a very good job,'' he said. ``(Robert)
Edwards ran the ball well. He did a good job of picking where he
wanted to go. Scott (Zolak) made some nice throws in tough
situations. In that touchdown drive (in the fourth quarter) he hit
two big ones. One of them looked like a third and 16 or 17, and the
other was fourth down. Defensively, they did some nice things in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big game for them. They have a lot at stake. I know
most of the kids on that team and what they can do. They'll come in
here giving it everything they've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said the Jets have not finalized a new long-term
contract for quarterback Vinny Testaverde, but thinks it will get
done within the next couple of weeks. Most of the important
elements of the deal have been completed, but there are a few
things to be ironed out. When someone asked Parcells earlier in the
day why he was giving a new deal to Testaverde when the team held
an option for next year, his retort was: ``because he deserves it .
. . that's why.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parcells thinks the AFC was as good as any division in the
league this year, and that the four teams headed into the playoffs
will benefit from it. ``All these teams should be
battle-hardened,'' he said. ``We had an awful lot of big games
against each other during the season, and those are the kind of
games that get you ready for the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   How the divisions fared:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Division ! Out of Div.! v. AFC! v. NFC &QL; 
(! used as column separator) &QL; 
 &QL; 
AFC East ! 23-14 ! 32-25 ! 9-8 &QL; 
AFC Central ! 14-23 ! 26-32 ! 7-10 &QL; 
AFC West ! 23-14 ! 27-28 ! 13-6 &QL; 
NFC East ! 15-24 ! 6-13 ! 27-29 &QL; 
NFC Central ! 21-16 ! 10-7 ! 30-28 &QL; 
NFC West ! 20-18 ! 8-9 ! 29-29 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The AFC holds a five-game lead over the NFC in games between the
conferences this year, but there will be five more games this
weekend. &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Local fans think the Patriots have had injury problems this
year, but they are nothing compared with what has happened to the
Jacksonville Jaguars, who have 12 players on injured reserve,
including Don Davey, Jeff Lageman, and Seth Payne (all starting
defensive linemen), starting running back James Stewart, who was
having his best season, starting center Mike Cheever, and seven
other players who were on the 45-man roster at the beginning of the
season. It is still questionable whether Mark Brunell will be ready
to play in the playoffs. It looks as if the Jaguars will host
Pittsburgh next Monday night with their third-string quarterback,
rookie Jonathan Quinn, at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Pittsburgh, backup Mike Tomczak was tough on starter
Kordell Stewart in a Steeler postgame radio show last Sunday.
Tomczak said Stewart did not work hard enough at preparing for
games, and some of the other players, in the midst of a
tremendously disappointing season, care about themselves more than
team accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The AFC playoff picture illustrates the importance of home
cooking. Look at the teams that have qualified. Denver is 7-0 at
Mile High, where it will play the rest of the season in its quest
of another Super Bowl. Miami is 7-1 at home, and the Jets and
Jacksonville are 6-1. New England and Buffalo are 6-2. The
Patriots, Miami and Buffalo all have losing records on the road,
and all three are on the road this weekend . . . Jerry Seeman,
director of officials, said referee Phil Luckett made a great call
Monday night on the so-called ``backward pass'' thrown by John
Elway. ``As soon as the passer's arm starts forward, no matter
where it goes after that, it is a forward pass,'' said Seeman.
``Elway was hit from behind as his hand was coming forward to throw
the ball. The ball went behind him and hit the ground. When it did,
it was an incomplete pass, just like it was called.'' . . .
Consider this: Zolak was the 33d backup quarterback in the league
to start a game this season, which indicates the physical beating
the quarterbacks have been taking. And it appears that just one has
taken every snap for his team _ Colts rookie Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
