   With
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-CLUBS-CLAIMS (Carlsbad, Calif.) _ Golf club manufactures
have long claimed or implied that their high-tech clubs improve a
player's game. But this year, the manufacturers found themselves in
the uncomfortable position of asserting that their clubs do not
really lower scores after all. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PRUDENTIAL-SUIT (Undated) _ Two years after Prudential agreed to
compensate millions of policyholders to end a lawsuit contending
that the company's agents engaged in dishonest sales practices, the
program is running months behind schedule and, across the country,
people are complaining. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERCOMPUTE-SUIT (Undated) _ A federal court has rejected, at
least temporarily, the International Trade Commission's finding
that underpriced Japanese supercomputers threatened to injure the
Cray Research division of Silicon Graphics. The decision gives the
commission 90 days to reconsider its 1997 finding against NEC and
Fujitsu. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   DASSAULT-BRIBE (Paris) _ Serge Dassault, the chief executive of
Dassault Aviation, is found guilty by a Belgian court of charges
that he bribed Belgian political parties to get defense contracts.
He is given a two-year suspended sentence. Among the 11 other
defendants is Willy Claes, a former head of NATO, who receives a
three-year suspended sentence. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 67
points, or seven-tenths of 1 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up
28 points, or 1.3 percent. Elsewhere, prices fell 1.6 percent in
Hong Kong, while the Tokyo market was closed for a holiday. Shares
rose 2 percent in Frankfurt, 0.7 percent in London, 0.6 percent in
Brazil and 0.3 percent in Mexico. On the American debt market, the
long bond was down 11/32 point, with the yield at 5.16 percent. By
Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
