<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX GM ISN'T FAZED BY NEGATIVE FEEDBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dan Duquette seemed almost at peace with himself
Tuesday as the Red Sox general manager held court to discuss the
team's offseason: a period in which the club has lost Mo Vaughn to
the Anaheim Angels and has yet to achieve equal value in return.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the signing of pitchers Mark Portugal and Mark Guthrie,
plus second baseman Jose Offerman, counts for something. But things
looked a lot worse last winter, and good things happened in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Who's to say lightning can't strike again?
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to be steady year-round in this business,'' said
Duquette. ``We've been able to help our ball club for next year and
for the long haul with some of the acquisitions we made. They may
not be established players, but they should be players who can help
us have a good, competitive ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   You heard this first when Vaughn turned down the Red Sox and
opted for a $80 million payday. Duquette had similar thoughts after
the winter meetings in Nashville, where instead of a power hitter,
he landed Guthrie, a 32-year-old relief pitcher. And you're going
to keep hearing it until Duquette can either pull off a trade or
sign one of the 39 free agents who weren't tendered contracts by
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said now is not the time to give in to his critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those jobs where you're not going to please
everybody all the time,'' he declared. ``You really need to focus
on what it takes to have a good competitive team year in and year
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what Abraham Lincoln said. If he spent all his time
trying to answer all the charges against his administration, he
wouldn't have time in the day to do the job he needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has sought to impeach Duquette _ yet. But there have been
many negative articles written about his tenure in Boston and the
ball club's immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette makes no apologies about his offseason moves or the
loss of Vaughn. The team will continue to seek a top power hitter,
although now he mostly likely qill arrive via a trade. In the
meantime, the Sox will be built as much around pitching as it is
hitting.
</P>
<P>
   If no trade presents itself, Sox fans will see the latest
products of the farm system, outfielder Trot Nixon, for example.
This still doesn't explain how a club that finished 22 games behind
the Yankees in the American League East can hope to do better. Or
beat out the improved Orioles or Angels for the wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   It's all how you look at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of good things about this ball club going into
the 1999 season,'' said Duquette. ``The addition of Offerman. The
continued maturation of Garciaparra. The maturation of the
catchers, Jason Varitek and Scott Hatteberg. We are going into the
season with four established major league starting pitchers (Pedro
Martinez, Bret Saberhagen, Tim Wakefield, and Portugal), something
we didn't have a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand Texas and California have been very active. But
our primary competition will be in the AL East. You never know
what's going to happen going into the season. If you look at the
way the final standings were, you'd see some big gaps from the
start. We should be able to supplement the ball club and still be
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was mentioned by Duquette several times during the
interview, but qithout a trace of anger. It has become a business
deal that didn't work out for traditional reasons. Nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough resources to put together a competitive ball
club,'' insisted Duquette. ``And the fact that we've made the
playoffs two of the last four years bears that out. We have an
established farm system now. That's going to be very helpful to us
over the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the money that some of these top players are getting is
obscene. The biggest challenge for our club is paying that kind of
money to one player. This isn't the NBA, where you have one star
and four complementary players and win the title. You need a number
of top-quality players to win the pennant. A number of decisions
for your franchise are made based on your economics. But if you
make the right number of common sense decisions, you have a pretty
good ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   If the season opened today, replacing Vaughn could be done in
several ways. The key spot becomes second, not first base. If Jeff
Frey starts at second, it makes Offerman the designated hitter, and
either Mike Stanley or Reggie Jefferson will play first. If
Offerman is at second, look for Jefferson to DH and Stanley to play
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, Stanley played first when Vaughn got hurt last
season. In fact, the same thing happened two years ago. We're
making good progress toward having a championship-caliber team.
We'd like to have a top quality ball club that our fans can be
proud of when we host the All-Star Game next July.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette added that while the Sox may not have Vaughn, the Sox
roster is full of players with multiple-year contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've communicated directly to our fans that we'd like to have
a good ball club year in and year out,'' he said. ``Since the
advent of free agency in 1976, the Red Sox have the best record of
any team but one (Yankees). Our fans know we have a number of
top-quality players under contract for several years under salaries
we can support.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why so many free agents have turned down a chance to play
in Boston, Duquette said there is no one answer. Certainly, it's
not the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the players understand the significance of playing in
historic Fenway Park,'' said Duquette. ``They understand the fans
are there to appreciate your effort. We've always built our ball
club through the farm system and trades. We've utilized free
agency, but it hasn't been the primary route for great Red Sox
players. The bottom line is that we'd like to win a World Series
championship and we have the resources to put together a
top-quality team here in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After four years of searching the Far East for the right arm,
the Sox Tuesday acquired righthander Tomokazu Oka from the Yokohama
Baystars, the 1998 Japan Series champion.
</P>
<P>
   Oka had only a 7-8 record in 25 games for Yokohoma's top farm
team, but struck out 98 and walked just 31. Oka will report to Fort
Myers, Fla., and will likely open the season at Pawtucket.
</P>
</TEXT>
