<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, Dec. 24:
</P>
<P>
   BOOMER-TOYS (New York) _ Not since Kane whispered Rosebud has
the nation thought so hard about the toys from its past.
Baby-boomers, now parents and grandparents, are hitting their
second childhood. A generation about to slip into senior
citizenship has created a growing market for newly-produced classic
toys, log-building sets to electric football boards to Dr. Seuss
books, and they don't have to go to toy stores to find them. By
William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-ROOM (Undated) _ To a child, one of the sweetest and most
long-lasting Christmas gifts is a room of one's own. And it's
clear, as every parent knows, that children are sometimes their own
best interior designers. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   STORE-GATES (New York) _ Unconsoled by recent drops in reported
crime, store owners in New York City continue to seal their
investments each night behind riot-proof shields that first
appeared in great numbers here during the late 1960s. The
persistence of this riot-proofing is a sign that retailers, like
old generals, are still stubbornly fighting the last war. But a new
type of gate that is now becoming more widespread is the perfect
addition to the streetscapes of Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's safer
but sterner New York. By Philip Nobel.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   NEA-ROBBINS (Undated) _ After years under congressional siege _
and a spring rally on the Right to annihilate it _ the National
Endowment for the Arts, whose budget was finally secured in
September, might understandably be looking for steady ground to
tread. But under the leadership of a new chairman, William J. Ivey,
who has said that he believes the endowment should be as important
as the Department of Defense, the NEA is marching, not slinking, to
the front lines in its support of the arts. On Tuesday, Ivey
announced the bold appointment of Mark Robbins, a curator, teacher
and artist, as the new design director, a position that has been
vacant for more than 18 months. By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   FLOWER-ARRANGING (New York) _ Japanese women coming to New York
for lessons in flower arranging seems as absurd as New Yorkers
going to Tokyo for rudeness seminars. Three centuries ago, when
forest covered Manhattan, the art of floral design called ikebana
flourished in Japan, where the intricate craft is still revered as
a national treasure, like the tea ceremony. By Jessica Siegel.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   VIRTUAL-APARTMENTS (Undated) _ Let's say you're a developer with
a pile of rubble where a new building is going to be. How do you
move those multimillion-dollar three bedrooms before you can say,
``The stock market's down 512 points again''? In the old days, you
rented an office (preferably ground floor) in a fancy location, put
some easels around the room, stuck up architects' renderings and
handed out embossed brochures _ and coffee. But now there's virtual
reality _ the catchall term for computer-generated videos that
mimic a visit to an existing or still-imagined building. It is
becoming part of a growing number of sales pitches. By Tracie
Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEMADE-WINE (Minneapolis) _ Looking at a wish book from
Semplex of U.S.A., one of the country's leading specialty houses,
serving amateur winemakers since 1962, I spied a $154.25 trilevel
Steam Juice Extractor imported from Finland and used to crush
grapes painlessly and efficiently. I also noticed the $389 Buon
Vino Super Jet Filter, an Italian import capable of pumping 80
gallons of wine an hour. But no way was I buying any of it. My
family has its own claptrap tin wine press, which my uneducated
country-boy grandfather quixotically lugged across Europe and to
the United States three generations ago. By Neal Karlen.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
