<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG ROAD BACK FOR TYSON 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Mike Tyson's newest sweatshop is a boxing gym from
back in the day. It is a squat, cinder block building that sits
broken down and beaten at 1755 Van Buren, where it shares broken
glass and a plot of dirt with a metal taco shop called Taqueria
Hermosillo. It is a place of work but also a place to remind Mike
Tyson how far he strayed from his roots.
</P>
<P>
   To say the neighborhood is seedy would be to insult the word,
not the neighborhood. It is a place where there are few dreams
left, and the ones that remain were long ago broken. It is the kind
of place that produces fighters.
</P>
<P>
   It is here amid the smell of sweat and hot sauce where the
youngest man to ever win the heavyweight championship comes five
days a week in a dark blue Rolls-Royce to try and rebuild his own
broken dream. Here, in a place they used to call Madison Square
Garden until Tyson started coming around, he is preparing himself
to go back to the day when he was the most feared fighting machine
on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not even his exile to Arizona has allowed him to avoid the
bizarre legal twists that have dogged him for years because the
minute word got out that Tyson would be training for his return to
boxing at the Madison Square Garden gym, letters started coming to
Richard Rodriguez that were not nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't Madison Square Garden no more,'' the gym owner said
despite the huge sign that hangs between two boarded-up windows.
``Ever since Mike came here, New York started getting on our ass.
They been on our case with (threatening) letters (about using the
Garden's name). So now it's Mike Tyson Enterprises-Ricky Ricardo
Gym.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rodriguez better hope the estate of Lucille Ball and
Desi Arnez doesn't get wind of that because that is how life goes
around Tyson. Always a whirlwind. Always someone suing somebody or
someone accusing somebody or someone hollering at somebody or
someone punching somebody.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is all Tyson is interested in for now. He is back in
the punching business, having rid himself of nearly all the angry
elements that seemed to make chaos his constant companion.
</P>
<P>
   Don King, Rory Holloway, John Horne, and Richie Giachetti are
all gone, replaced by a quiet businessman from New York named
Shelly Finkel and a quiet trainer named Tommy Brooks, both of whom
once worked for Tyson's fistic albatross, Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Where once there was a cacophony of sound and fury whenever
Tyson would prepare for a fight, now there is only rap music and
the swish of a jump rope as he readies himself for a Jan. 16
appointment in Las Vegas with South African heavyweight Frans
Botha. Those sounds and the ever present drone of Steve
``Crocodile'' Finch, Tyson's personal loudspeaker, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pound for pound, baby!'' Finch is screaming on a cool
afternoon four days before Christmas as Tyson works the jump rope.
``Ezzard Charles! Joe Louis! Dick Tiger! Pound for pound! Bob
Foster! Bobby Chacon! We goin' to war! All-time, baby. Pound for
pound! All-time greats! Mike Tyson! Sonny Liston! Mike Tyson!
Archie Moore! Mike Tyson! Mike Tyson! Mike Tyson!''
</P>
<P>
   As Finch hollers his eyes are fixed on a small, black stopwatch
around his neck. Tyson is seemingly oblivious to the small crowd of
scruffy-faced kids, neighborhood hangers on, media watchers, and a
strange guy in the back in a spray-painted jacket that read in
several places ``Bleep the Police!''
</P>
<P>
   Finkel sees the latter and quickly grows concerned. Soon he is
talking to James Anderson, father of Atlanta Falcons running back
Jamal Anderson and a former New Jersey cop who is starting his
second tour as Tyson's chief of security. Within minutes, the man
in the potentially offending jacket has quietly disappeared while
Tyson goes on about his business.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, it is not the hurt business. He sparred six rounds
Monday and Brooks keeps him on a tight schedule of alternating days
of hard work followed by review. This is a day for reviewing
techniques Tyson had long ago forgotten, things the Old Man, Cus
D'Amato, taught him back in the day when he was a boy with dreams
being raised by an old eccentric who had dreams, too.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Tyson wants to go back to. He wants to go back to
when his life was more about boxing than drama. When it was more
about opponents than lawsuits. Back to when it was simple to
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to stay humble,'' Tyson said Tuesday. ``Cus used to tell
me the more important you are, the more humble you should be. I try
to get people not to look at me as a superstar but it's hard.
Sometimes I forget who I am but when I'm around people, I remember
who I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man who was bringing me some food one day says, `Hello, Mr.
Tyson.' I told him to call me Mike. He says, `No, no. You're Mr.
Tyson, sir. I would love to be you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Please don't say that brother. You don't want to
be me.' And he says, `Yes, I do. I got six children and but one
check.' I told him I got millions and no friends. You can always
get some financial aid. But you can't get no friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is not here to serve in that role. He is not here to be
Tyson's friend or his lawyer or his psychiatrist. He is here to
refresh his memory of things that once made him impregnable in a
boxing ring. Here to bring him back, if a 32-year-old power puncher
on a two-fight losing streak who has fought an average of 2.9
rounds a year the past seven years can come back.
</P>
<P>
   After 13 years as an assistant to his father-in-law, Lou Duva,
and to Holyfield's head trainer, Don Turner, Brooks accepted
Tyson's offer to go on his own and took over his training in
November. It was odd, leaving Holyfield for Tyson, but it was a
move Brooks acknowledges was done for the reason most everything is
done in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
