<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1356EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4150 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     12-23 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 PHOENIX: ... in boxing.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Evander gave me a platform to show my talents as a trainer,
but Evander has two or three fights and then he'll go on about his
business,'' Brooks said. ``This is a kid with eight or 10 fights.
Holyfield and I will always be tight as far as I'm concerned. He'll
always be in my heart. But this is a business. I got to look out
for me and my family. It was a hard decision but it wasn't, because
how long can you be an assistant?''
</P>
<P>
   Not any longer for Brooks, who made his mark with Tyson their
first day of training when he had him do a drill in which he had to
punch as fast as he could in those 30-second bursts. When it went
on too long, Tyson doubled over and threw up in exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   When he was done, Brooks said, ``Punch! You can't stop punching
in a fight if you throw up.'' In recent years, Tyson has had no
such taskmaster. He has had people who knew they were employees and
acted accordingly. Brooks knows it, too, but he also knows he's
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the guys around him have been yes men,'' Brooks
explained. ``He was training them. That's not the way it's supposed
to operate.''
</P>
<P>
   That day it didn't. Tyson kept punching as sweat poured down his
face and his stomach rumbled. Finally he yelled, ``Kill me!'' Then
he kept on punching.
</P>
<P>
   After two straight losses to Holyfield, a 17-month suspension
for biting Holyfield's ears in the rematch, financial collapse and
the banishment of his former friends and management team to a
courtroom where men in suits will fight over him, Mike Tyson has
come back to the basics. Back to work.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the hard, clean stuff of boxing. And back to a
broken-down gym and a new trainer intent on pushing him back to
where he once thought was his rightful place in the world _ the
throne room of boxing's most glamorous division.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take a refresher course no matter how long you've
been fighting,'' Brooks said. ``Now that he's been beat twice, guys
aren't intimidated like they used to be. That bully syndrome
doesn't work. Now he's got to fight. Maybe he needed to get beat to
realize the bad habits he got into.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked, Tyson brushes that notion off while acknowledging he
hasn't done this kind of fundamental work in a gym ``since I was a
kid.'' Then for nearly an hour he banters with a half-dozen writers
from around the country, discoursing on why Bill Clinton shouldn't
be impeached (``We knew who he was. We all get caught up in that
situation. We're all men. We're just glad we didn't get caught.''),
and on how he hopes his children ``become good people and not bums
because they're in a position to make a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   He explains why he paid for the funeral of a poor white teenager
in Phoenix who was shot in the throat when she pushed two young
black girls down to get them out of the line of fire during a
neighborhood shootout because ``we gotta be socialists about
things. It's the 21st Century and we human beings can't take care
of our own. I'm not a communist. I'm a socialist. Jesus Christ was
a socialist. Allah was a socialist. We have to love each other or
we'll all die together because no one in the government is going to
help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later he wanders off to corporate sweatshops in Honduras
that makes clear to him that ``we're all capitalistic pigs. We
don't care.'' Then it's on to the bombings in Iraq and the need for
welfare reform because ``welfare is like crack. The government
needs to give people a job. Then if you don't want to do nothing
send your ass to jail . . . My mother was on welfare because she
was broken. She was an educated lady. She went to college. But her
spirit was broken. This is all deeper than being a fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that but at this juncture of his life he remains a fighter
first, wich is why he is back in this broken part of Phoenix
looking for answers and himself. As he works to get back the head
movement and flurries of punches that once made him a champion,
Mike Tyson thinks about things and has come to a conclusion about
his life that is simple and clear and clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fighter,'' he says. ``Now I realize, with not much chaos
in my life, I wasn't conscious of some things. I'm sorry if I
grabbed a girl's butt or cursed her out or what not. I'm sorry if I
was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows I'm an (expletive) sometimes but the spotlight
is not on you all. I'm sure you're (expletive), too. I'm just in a
different position. I'm a complex person just happy to fight
again.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, word comes from one of his PR men that it is time to
join Santa Claus in the ring to hand out Christmas toys to
neighborhood kids. Tyson and Jamal Anderson have supplied the toys
and as Tyson looks up a line of kids _ black, white, Hispanic, all
poor _ has formed from the ring, down the steps to the floor, along
the wall, out the door, passed the taco shop, and around the corner
for half a block. They have gathered at a place where he is
learning to fight again to wait for a toy. Santa Claus is in the
ring, red hat and white whiskers, waiting, too.
</P>
<P>
   Before he leaves, Tyson is asked one last thing. He's asked
about the perception that he's some kind of animal, a perception
fueled by his rape conviction and the cannibalism Holyfield drove
him to 17 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The once and perhaps future heavyweight champion thinks for a
moment and then smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'm a good animal,'' he says. ``I hope I'm
domesticated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
