<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4153 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     12-23 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC LEVELS CHARGES AGAINST W.R. GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just what W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. needs right now: another ``Civil
Action'' of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   The US Securities and Exchange Commission Tuesday filed a civil
suit against Grace and a administrative complaint against seven
former Grace executives, alleging they manipulated financial
results at the company's former Waltham, Mass. subsidiary, National
Medical Care, from 1991 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC charged that Grace employed a ``cookie jar'' accounting
strategy that stashed as much as $20 million of excess profits at a
time the company believed it would not be rewarded for beating
financial expectations. The idea, according to the SEC, was to
declare the profit at some later date when operations were not
running so well in a process known as financial ``smoothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Constantine L. Hampers, the well-known and sometimes
controversial chief executive of National Medical Care, was among
the seven executives named in the administrative complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Grace denied the allegations Tuesday in a written statement.
``Grace continues to assert the financial statements were not
fraudulent,'' the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is the first of its kind since SEC chairman Arthur
Levitt focused on the government's concern over corporate
``earnings management'' and shady accounting practices in a closely
watched speech three months ago. Levitt specifically cited cookie
jar reserves among five ``hocus pocus'' accounting practices in his
comments.
</P>
<P>
   SEC officials said Tuesday the Grace suit was the first of a
string of cases it expected to file over the fraudulent reporting
of corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly financial fraud in its many forms is our top
priority,'' said Richard Walker, the SEC's director of enforcement.
``There are a number of cases that are going to be coming in the
first months of the (new) year.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt has outlined a handful of accounting issues that will
come under increased regulatory scrutiny, including some that are
commonly found in high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   Large ``big bath'' special charges that sweep many expenses and
problems under the rug, creative accounting for acquisitions and
mergers and questions of when a sale is recognized as actual
revenue are among the leading accounting issues raised by
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has settled one other ``cookie jar'' reserve case this
year, involving Sensormatic Electronics Corp. The new Grace suit,
filed in US District Court in Miami, alleged that the company
deferred unexpected earnings of National Medical in 1991 and 1992.
Grace assigned the money to reserves, which it drew upon in 1993
and 1995 to hike the reported profits of both the health care unit
and Grace itself, the SEC alleged.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic example of the kind of situation in which
we've been critical of the process of earnings management,'' said
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, Grace said its outside auditor was aware of
the reserves and issued unqualified opinions on each of the
company's annual statements in question. It said it had disclosed
the SEC investigation leading to the suit in public filings.
</P>
<P>
   National Medical, at various times the subject of a bidding war
in the mid-1990s among Hampers himself, Baxter International and
Fresenius AG of Germany, was merged with Fresenius in 1996. Grace
shareholders got $2.25 billion and a 44.8 percent stake in the new
Fresenius Medical Care AG.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting charges come at a time when Grace is already
bracing for a wave of negative publicity, anticipating the release
of the film ``A Civil Action,'' starring John Travolta. The film,
based on the best-selling book by the same name, recounts the legal
battle of three companies, Grace most prominent among them, and
eight Woburn, Mass. families who blamed toxic waste that leached
into the town's water supply for six deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits were dropped in 1986 in return for an $8 million
settlement. The film, which opens Christmas Day in New York and Los
Angeles, will premiere in Boston on Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Grace is already directing reporters and film reviewers likely
to write about the movie to a company Internet site, ``Beyond A
Civil Action, Woburn Issues and Answers.''
</P>
<P>
   The site attempts to support the company's contention that it
did not contaminate the town's water, though it concedes ``we made
mistakes in addressing the concerns of the community and government
agencies regarding the impact of waste disposal practices'' at
Grace's Woburn plant.
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
