<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4209 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMAS-RETAIL-HNS &LR;      12-23 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-RETAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAIL SALES MAY NOT BE AS MERRY AS FORECAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Retailers and analysts said as recently as last
month they had the no-fail ingredients for successful holiday
sales: low unemployment and inflation, high consumer confidence and
a healthy stock market.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Christmas, those bright expectations are dimming.
Retailers are projecting sales at stores open at least one year to
increase 3 percent to 4 percent over last year instead of the more
optimistic 5 percent to 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (retailers) are fully aware of the fact this holiday
season is turning out to be a disappointment,'' said Kurt Barnard,
president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report in Upper Montclair, N.J.
``Many are beginning to cut prices further than they already have
and doing everything imaginable to get people into the stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnard recently adjusted his 4 percent to 5 percent sales
increase projection, which he said retailers had criticized for
being low, to 3 percent to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The BTM/Schroeders retail chain store index reported Tuesday
that sales for the week ending Dec. 19 fell 1.7 percent from the
same week last year. The forecasting service has lowered its
year-over-year increase projections for the whole season to 4.5
percent from 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The International Council of Shopping Centers said sales at mall
specialty stores dipped 0.7 percent during the third full week of
the holiday period compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite positive economic indicators, it appears the
unseasonably warm weather as well as dramatic domestic and
international political events have distracted shoppers,'' said
John Konarski, ICSC's senior vice president of research, referring
to President Clinton's bombing campaign in Iraq and the impeachment
process in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Barnard said retailers generally underplayed the impact of
developments in the second half of the year, including the Asian
economic crisis and the bearish stock market during the summer. In
addition, he said, planned layoffs at blue-chip companies such as
Boeing, Citigroup and Johnson &AMP; Johnson have dampened holiday
spirits.
</P>
<P>
   According to First Data Corp.'s TeleCheck Services, which tracks
sales paid for by check, same-store sales from Nov. 27 through Dec.
20 on the West Coast were down 1.9 percent over the same period
last year with a dramatic 9.3 percent drop in sales in the San
Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston-based service blamed the West's weak export market,
cutbacks in oil and refinery production, and consolidations in the
financial sector and other industries for the downturn. TeleCheck
spokeswoman Marjorie Fowler said the summer's market fluctuations
had an especially strong impact on the Bay area because of its
concentration of volatile high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   The generally balmy autumn across much of the nation may also
have affected sales of items such as coats and cold-weather
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Gagne, senior vice president of Strategic Weather Services,
a Pennsylvania-based company that provides advice to retailers and
manufacturers on the effects of weather and shopping, said the
later the warm weather continues through the season, the less
likely merchants will recover lost sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will think I got this far into it without buying an
overcoat, so I'll just ride it out and make do,'' he said. ``And
when retailers look back and consider the recent cold and snowy
weather, it will be a case of too little too late.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gagne said since people are compelled to shop for holiday
gifts, other categories of merchandise benefit from the unseasonal
weather. Those include such all-season items as jewelry, consumer
electronics and home furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of home furnishings rose 9.1 percent in the second week of
December over the same period last year, according to the ICSC's
poll of specialty stores. The group reported clothing sales were
nearly flat, rising just 0.1 percent during that same period.
</P>
<P>
   Barnard said housewares and home goods would continue their
strong showing, fueled by solid home sales and an aging population
that spends time and money on their homes. Barnard also predicted
other winners this season would be the discount stores, with sales
increases of 5 percent to 7 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
   He said department stores would be the big losers because
price-conscious shoppers look elsewhere. ``Department stores are
going to limp badly, depending on how good a cane they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Macy's, however, said the department store chain is ``on plan''
with the sales expectations it set earlier this season, although
the store does not disclose its predictions. Macy's spokeswoman
Merle Goldstone confirmed that sales of home furnishings were
especially strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The warm weather did hurt us a little bit. With the return of
cold weather, things are turning out OK,'' she said. ``It's not the
greatest, not the worst.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1421EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4227 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-RUSSIA-START-TRE     12-23 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-RUSSIA-START-TREATY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 AFTER THE U.S. BOMBING OF IRAQ, IT WILL BE HARD TO SECURE RUSSIA'S
RATIFICATION of the START II TREATY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The world is now digesting the grave consequences of the use of
force by the United States and Great Britain against Iraq. By
arrogating to itself the functions of prosecutor, judge and court
marshal, the United States has dealt a heavy blow to the United
Nations _ and to the hopes of establishing a just and effective
international legal order.
</P>
<P>
   One theme is prominent in Russian comments on the U.S. air
strikes: Russia has been snubbed; its opinion was simply ignored.
Many politicians, even such serious ones as Moscow's Mayor Yuri
Luzhkov, are now saying that as a response to this show of power,
Russia should be rebuilding its own economic, political and
military might.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, by using military force, Washington was not defying
just Russia alone. In the same way, the United States dismissed
curtly the viewpoints of other nations too _ including China,
India, France, Italy and the League of Arab States, all of whom
subsequently objected strongly to the bombing raids. The reaction
in Russia, at this time, is symptomatic. It follows naturally from
what has happened to the country in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   By now, with the close of 1998, the failure of Boris Yeltsin's
political and economic course has been laid bare. One crisis after
another this past year has dramatized the consequences of his
misguided policies. The financial collapse that started last August
has hit even those people _ the 10 percent to 15 percent of the
population _ who actually had benefited from the ``reforms.'' As
for the majority of Russian citizens, even Yeltsin himself has had
to admit that, yes, they live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   And yet these pseudo-reforms, which have done great harm to
Russia's economy, to its health and education systems, to its
science and culture, were applauded by the West. There was pro-U.S.
euphoria in Russia at one point; but today this has given way to
anti-American sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   More and more of our people are wondering: ``Why does the United
States so much like the policies that are so bad for us?''
</P>
<P>
   All too often, Washington's reactions are just wrong. When, for
example, the failure of Russia's previous governments forced yet
another change and the appointment of the cabinet of Yevgeny
Primakov, Washington's response was not right. By freezing the
loans promised to the previous Russian cabinet, the International
Monetary Fund followed suit and made things even more difficult _
all of this at a time when Primakov is desperately trying to
stabilize the situation.
</P>
<P>
   In the West and in the Russian media, his cabinet is often
called pro-Communist and anti-reform. As I have said time and again
_ both in Russia and during a recent lecture tour around the United
States _ this is far from the truth. In fact, the new Russian
cabinet is made of pragmatic, no-nonsense people, with a great deal
of experience. Its leaders are far from being fly-by-night
trend-setters; they are not fooling around. They are wise men who
are concerned about the country's future and understand that there
can be no return to the past.
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely this kind of cabinet that gives Russia a chance
to gradually extricate itself from a post-Cold War crisis that dims
the bright future we envisioned just a short time ago. It is
Primakov's kind of cabinet that will give this country a chance to
integrate into the global economy and establish long-term
cooperation with the West.
</P>
<P>
   Of course we are not going to simply jump on the bandwagon and
support without reservation whatever the United States might do,
nor should the rest of the world expect such thoughtless
endorsement. With a cabinet like Primakov's, Russia is an honest
and reliable partner with which other leaders and nations can deal.
</P>
<P>
   I have no doubt that, but for the U.S. attack against Iraq, the
Primakov government would have secured the Russian parliament's
ratification of the START II treaty. It has collected dust in the
Duma since 1993; after promising work by Primakov, the talks were
likely to resume. Some opponents were won over. The limits of 6,000
warheads under START I would be cut in half. Now, after the battle
was fought, it must be fought again. After what has happened, this
will be an uphill task. Once again, resentment has built up and is
cresting thanks to this aggressive bombing. As it is, one aide to
President Yeltsin has already stated carelessly that ``one may well
give up'' on the arms-control treaty.
</P>
<P>
   How disappointing on the eve of the new century, when peace and
diplomacy are still the right road.
</P>
<P>
   On this issue, as on many others, the Russian cabinet has to
contend with interference from all kinds of quarters. What is
needed is something quite different _ to help this government and
thus help Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Americans often ask me: Why should we help Russia? Often the
question is posed sincerely and in good faith. But other times one
detects the barely submerged tone of a self-proclaimed ``victor''
in the Cold War. There is no victor; I believe it is plain that
moving into the 21st century, we all must stand together.
</P>
<P>
   I think that the illusion of America's omnipotence, now so
common among U.S. politicians, will one day vanish and it will
become clear that in today's boundaryless world NO ONE can have a
monopoly on leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the bombs rained on Iraq and shortly thereafter, new
centers of economic power and political influence were continuing
to emerge. Alliances may shift; Russia could become a strong and
friendly partner to the West. But today many people regard such a
prospect as highly unlikely, and recent U.S. actions have not
brought it any closer.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a major effort by both sides in the coming year to
put things back on course.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow, with a new
office at Northeastern University, in Boston. He also writes a
monthly commentary column for La Stampa, a newspaper in Turin,
Italy.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
