<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4268 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF     12-23 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME
</HEADLINE>
  By Marilyn Stasio 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't let the down-home charms of Margaret Maron's Southern
mysteries con you with their coziness. Behind their honeyed
accents, the friendly characters in HOME FIRES (Mysterious
Press/Warner, $22) have plenty of secrets to hide and grudges to
settle. Even Deborah Knott, the fair-minded circuit court judge who
knows all the clan issues in the backwoods of North Carolina, where
she dispenses justice, has to remind herself that race and religion
have a way of changing everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desegregation's been a real mixed bag down here,'' Deborah
acknowledges. ``Took away some of the old sore spots, brought in a
bunch of new ones.'' But when someone starts burning down black
churches and her own rowdy nephew is implicated, the judge realizes
the issues go deeper than she thought. Even among her own kith and
kin, the old ``ain't-no-racists-here'' protestations won't hold up.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing what Maron manages to pack into the whodunit
format: soft-focus scenes of a country summer, witty descriptions
of fractious families and feuding neighbors, and wonderful
anecdotes about the legendary locals who can dowse a well and talk
the warts off your hand. All that, plus a keen understanding of the
ambiguities of race relations in the rural South and pointed
character insights that nail the sinners but leave them enough
dignity to stand up in church on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Joh Rowland's latest period novel, THE CONCUBINE'S TATTOO
(St. Martin's, $23.95), makes me wonder: Would any well-bred
20-year-old bride of a high-ranking official in the court of a
17th-century Japanese shogun 1) refuse to perform the domestic
duties for which she has been trained; 2) demand that her husband,
the shogun's ``most honorable investigator of events, situations
and people,'' allow her to investigate a murder; or 3) express
herself in the tone of a modern woman? (``I'm educated; I can read
and write as well as any man. . . . You think I'm weak and stupid
because I'm a woman. . . . I'd rather die than submit to you or any
other man!'') Offhand, I would say, not in a million years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Lady Reiko's contemporary sensibility and anachronistic
manner, Sano Ichiro's new wife does a pretty job of spying in the
palace quarters where the shogun's favorite concubine has been
poisoned ingeniously, with the ink she mixed for a tattoo. Rowland
has a painter's eye for the minutiae of court life, as well as a
politician's ear for intrigue, so the sleuthing is conducted amid
sumptuous scenes of imperial excess and under the watch of
imperious villains. Although some characters get lost in this
panoply of settings, which include a puppet theater, a morgue and a
martial arts academy, everyone (especially those who are not to be
trusted) is beautifully dressed.
</P>
<P>
   Faith Fairchild, the amateur sleuth in The Body in the Bookcase
(Morrow, $22) and earlier mysteries by Katherine Hall Page, is so
perfect you want to go for your gun. A classic blonde with a nice
figure and a successful catering business (she shares her recipes,
of course), Faith has a perfect husband (a minister, no less), two
perfect children (well-behaved, naturally) and a lovely home in
Aleford, one of those picture-perfect Massachusetts towns where it
never rains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I feel as if I'm living in a Currier &AMP; Ives
calendar,'' says Faith, whose saving grace is her good-natured
refusal to take herself too seriously. It isn't her sense of humor,
though, but a burst of outrage that jolts her into action for this
smartly executed excursion into the shady side of the antiques
trade. When an elderly librarian dies during a house burglary,
Faith is horrified; and when the thieves hit the parsonage, making
off with her own family heirlooms, she goes into attack mode.
``Aleford had been violated'' is her battle cry as she tears
through New England towns quaint and cruddy, searching pawnshops,
auction houses and dealers' markets for her lost treasures.
Although the master thief is too close to home to make the
conclusion believable, this undercover look at the dark side of the
antiques trade turns up all kinds of inside dope sure to fascinate
-- and infuriate -- paranoid property owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winter was setting in,'' Skye Kathleen Moody tells us in
WILDCRAFTERS (St. Martin's, $23.95), ``and in Toleak, Wash., winter
is a dank, still, deeply melancholy time.'' Still, it is a great
time for spinning tall tales about the half-human, half-elk monster
the Indians call ``the Unknown.'' When an Indian child goes missing
from the Bogachiel National Wildlife Preserve and his frantic
parents see elk hooves in the snow, one thinks, Uh-oh, it's that
darned Unknown, all right. But Moody, who is after bigger game,
grafts the regional folk legend to a more disturbing environmental
story about the ``wildcrafters'' who roam the rain forest,
illegally harvesting devil's club and valerian root -- and poaching
forbidden species of wildlife -- to supply the $5 billion market
for antiaging products. Moody makes a chilling case for the impact
of the ``Fountain of Youth'' industry on the ecosystem; but in
these wild and gorgeous settings, I still tend to go for the
Unknown.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad that Gail Bowen is such a stodgy writer, because
she does a couple of remarkable things in her new Joanne Kilbourn
mystery, VERDICT IN BLOOD (McClelland &AMP; Stewart, $20.95). For one
thing, she presents us with the appealing portrait of an amateur
sleuth who is neither young and improbably perky nor old and
absurdly feisty. Joanne, who is ``past 50'' and a grandmother,
teaches political science in Regina, Saskatchewan, and is raising
two adopted children. She's no ball of fire, but she's very real.
So are her adopted children, her Indian boyfriend and his troubled
nephew and an 83-year-old houseguest from Saskatoon whose holiday
visit is wrecked when her friend is beaten to death in a public
park. Joanne's investigation of the murder is less than inspired;
but Bowen writes so unaffectedly about unromantic matters -- the
lives of older characters, their extended families and
nontraditional domestic arrangements -- that it's worth tagging
along.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
