<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4269 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CANCELED-NYTS     12-23 1561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CANCELED-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCOLLECTING CHEEVER
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Family of John Cheever vs. Academy Chicago Publishers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Anita Miller &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 363 pp. Lanham, Md.: Rowman &AMP; Littlefield
Publishers. $27.95 &QL; 
 &UR; -------- &QL; 
 &UR; The 5:48 Is Canceled &QL; 
 &UR; By Richard Dooling &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   After a mere 12 years on the bench, Learned Hand, a Federal
judge whose influence was so great that he was sometimes called the
``10th justice'' of the Supreme Court, reportedly said, ``As a
litigant I should dread a lawsuit beyond almost anything else short
of sickness and death.'' Reading ``Uncollecting Cheever,'' by Anita
Miller _ a tale of litigious woe _ it's easy to see why.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, a small publisher, Academy Chicago, signed a contract
with John Cheever's widow, Mary, for the right to publish an
unspecified number of hitherto uncollected short stories. It paid
an advance of $1,500 against royalties. Half the advance and
royalties were to go to Franklin Dennis, the publisher's
representative who had approached the Cheevers with the idea.
Instead of a book of 68 Cheever short stories (which Academy
Chicago thought of as a companion to the 1978 edition of ``The
Stories of John Cheever'' issued by Alfred A. Knopf), the
ill-defined terms of the publisher's contract produced four years
of litigation, four court judgments, legal fees of over $1 million
and, finally, a book of 13 Cheever stories already in the public
domain.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the publishing world will recall reading about the
interminable lawsuits or being called as witnesses or being asked
to write articles on behalf of one side or the other. Law students
and legislators will learn a lot from ``Uncollecting Cheever''
about the mortal perils of careless drafting. Lawyers and veteran
litigants will not be surprised to learn that the legal dispute
brought out the worst in everyone connected with it.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest weakness of the book is also its main attraction _
the litigant-author. Anita Miller and her husband, Jordan, were the
owners, operators and editors of Academy Chicago. Unlike other
prodigious nonfiction anatomies of pitched legal battles,
``Uncollecting Cheever'' vividly shows us what acrimonious civil
litigation looks like from the perspective of the acrimonious
litigant: Exhibit A in a kind of Caine Mutiny of the author's
sanity induced by years of legal warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Miller inventories and catalogues all the foibles and
shortcomings of her adversaries, every slight she or her enterprise
received from the Cheevers and their media sympathizers, their
lawyers and the judges who ruled against her. All the petty,
lawyerly behavior of opposing counsel is set forth, seasoned with
the helpless outrage of the losing side, whose own lawyer lacked
legal authority or a sound contract to administer direct
chastisement to the adversaries. The book is at its weakest when it
merely summarizes the depositions of the major players _ Mary
Cheever, her daughter, Susan, and her son Ben _ and filters
excerpts of their testimony through the manifestly strabismic eye
of Anita Miller.
</P>
<P>
   She and her publisher take pains to position this book in part
as the story of a small publishing house struggling against the
corporate, big-money, big-book mentality of East Coast publishers.
The Cheevers were advised by people like the literary agent Andrew
Wylie (described in quotations Miller takes from Vanity Fair as
grasping and avaricious) and Martin Garbus, the renowned First
Amendment lawyer who zealously, and therefore despicably,
represented them. Garbus said materialistic things to Miller like
``You won't sell as many books as Random House.'' He called
witnesses like Robert Gottlieb, the former head of Knopf. But
ultimately Academy Chicago was litigating not with those people but
with the Cheever family, who (horrors!) thought they could make
more money if these stories were published by a major publisher and
who probably matched their adversaries in legal fees for the
pleasure of venting spleen and winning lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what Studs Terkel says in a blurb on the jacket, this
book does not read like ``a case of a small press bullied into
defeat.'' It sounds more like the tale of a small publisher that
carelessly drafted an important contract (without consulting a
lawyer) and the family of a renowned author who foolishly signed it
(without consulting a lawyer). Then both parties called in lawyers
and fought for four years to best each other in a species of combat
that differs from violence only insofar as there is usually no
bloodshed in litigation. Perhaps both sides now appreciate
Voltaire's observation: ``I was never ruined but twice, once when I
lost a lawsuit and once when I won one.''
</P>
<P>
   In her perceived role as a victim of injustice, Miller urges
that there was nothing unusual about this contract and that the
court decisions against Academy Chicago threaten all authors and
publishers. But most publishing contracts are with living authors,
and the dimensions of the manuscript are expressed by estimating
the number of words. Here the contract named Mary Cheever and
Franklin Dennis as ``author'' of ``The Uncollected Stories of John
Cheever'' with nothing said about number of pages or number of
stories. True, after the litigants presented four courts with their
dispute, Miller correctly observes that the court decisions
``invaded the traditional relationship between publisher and
author.'' But isn't that what the parties paid their lawyers a
million dollars to obtain?
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately we can't say if these opinions will invade the
relationship of other authors and publishers; the opinions are not
in this volume, presumably because the judges made the mistake of
unanimously ruling against Academy Chicago. Miller scrupulously
chronicles every letter, comment and fact favoring her right to
publish 68 Cheever stories for a $1,500 advance. But she denies us
the opportunity to see for ourselves what four different courts _
including the Illinois Supreme Court _ said about her case when
they ruled against her and Academy Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of including the opinions in an appendix or quoting them
at length and perhaps analyzing their shortcomings, Miller simply
complains about the rulings, or relates how one of the Illinois
appellate judges nodded off during oral arguments, or how James
Heiple, the Illinois Supreme Court Justice who wrote the court's
opinion voiding Academy Chicago's contract with the Cheevers, later
resigned as Chief Justice after being censured for trying to use
his position to escape traffic violations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we are served endless passages chronicling the
helplessness of courts when it comes to resolving the intractable
rancor of committed legal adversaries. Judges who preside over
divorce disputes and custody battles will recognize the sort of
litigants who schedule a hearing to divide evenly seven Bruce
Springsteen albums. In the context of the Cheever litigation, we
find judges attempting to resolve the parties' differences about
how many pages the collection should contain. The two sides had
used totally different ways of estimating word counts per page in
different hearings, and a Chicago judge, Roger Kiley, found serious
inconsistencies when he wrote an order specifying the size of the
book that was not to be. ``I dealt with the evidence I had,'' Kiley
said. ``I couldn't read anything into it.'' Academy Chicago's
lawyer said the judge was ``off 36 pages on my estimation.'' He
could have said 180 pages, Kiley said, or 230. He was just trying
to fix what he thought ``was a fair refinement on a difficult
concept,'' intending that the ``parties wouldn't use it as a device
to incorporate in their adversarial positions, but would actually
use it to solve the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A fter treating us to the minutiae of other squabbles over line
spacing, margins and whether a piece is a story or a ``sketch,''
``Uncollecting Cheever'' becomes a pathetic case study of the
insidious effects of litigation on the human psyche. Think of
``Bleak House'' as narrated not by Dickens, but by one of the
suitors of the endless fictional quagmire of Jarndyce v. Jarndyce.
By the time it's over, the reader keenly appreciates how one must,
at all costs, ``keep out of Chancery. . . . It's being ground to
bits in a slow mill; it's being roasted at a slow fire; it's being
stung to death by single bees; it's being drowned by drops; it's
going mad by grains.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the notable publishing figures featured in ``Uncollecting
Cheever,'' perhaps the literary agent Lynn Nesbit proved on
hindsight to be the most perspicacious. When confronted with the
dispute and the Academy Chicago contract, which had reportedly been
vetted by one of her underlings and signed by Mary Cheever _ a
contract, which, if enforced, would have allowed Nesbit and her
agency to receive a percentage of the profits from this book _
Nesbit said: ``I'm not going to get embroiled in a mess. I'll just
drop this contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, if the litigants had been half so wise.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dooling is a lawyer. His most recent novel is ``Brain
Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1434EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4270 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WOODS-NYTSF     12-23 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WOODS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISS NOBODY
</HEADLINE>
  By Tomek Tryzna 
 Translated by Joanna Trzeciak 
 296 pp. New York: Doubleday. $23 
 -------- 
 Into the Woods 
 By Brian Hall 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In the opening scene of Tomek Tryzna's fearlessly ambitious
debut novel, ``Miss Nobody,'' his protagonist, Marysia Kawczak, a
15-year-old girl living in the final years of Communist Poland,
experiences her first period. Having thus symbolically discovered
adolescence, she clutches it and for the next 300 pages never lets
go.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a novel of character but a literary fairy tale, and
Tryzna lays down his scheme at the start. Marysia is at work in a
potato field _ we could think of it as a Polish avatar of the
Garden of Eden _ when she feels ``something very odd'' in her
stomach. Leaving the garden, she goes into nearby woods _ yes, they
are dark _ and has a confused vision involving a princess abducted
by ``ugly hairy monkeys'' dressed as men, and a beautiful young man
with a spear sprouting painfully from his belly, who begs her to
``grab it and pull.'' Disgust and fascination mingle within her as
the young man's blood mingles with the blood flowing down her leg.
</P>
<P>
   Next we learn that Marysia and her family must leave her village
of Jawiszow, a word carrying connotations of ``openness,'' to take
up residence in the nearby city of Walbrzych, whose German name,
Waldenburg, means ``forest city.'' The country girl is lost in the
urban landscape until she meets two schoolmates who will be her
Virgilian guides through this dark wood: Katarzyna Bogdanska,
familiarly called Kasia, and Eva Bogdaj. Most readers, one assumes,
would immediately notice the complementary surnames, but Tryzna
here, as in several places in his novel, belabors the point:
``Bogdanska and Bogdaj,'' Marysia muses. ``Strange. As if
everything went in pairs.''
</P>
<P>
   When fairy-tale characters are surprised by the fairy-tale
aspects of their lives, they are asking to be mistaken for real,
but with Marysia this is something we cannot do _ nor, I think, is
it Tryzna's intention that we do so. His book is highly colored,
emotionally stylized, stuffed tight with meaning and deliberately
two-dimensional. Since indeed everything in it comes in pairs, it
most resembles a painted diptych, whose form it embodies.
</P>
<P>
   Part 1 is the left panel, and its presiding genius is Marysia's
first guide, Kasia Bogdanska. Her surname derives from
``God-given,'' and she is ethereal and sickly, golden-haired, a
tormented musical prodigy, a genius in both senses. Her mother's
professional plaque on the apartment door identifies the daughter
as well: ``Internal Medicine Specialist.'' She is Spirit. The right
panel, Part 2, belongs to Eva Bogdaj, black-haired, beautiful,
superficial, concupiscent. Put a colon between her two names and
you get a line from a playscript about the Fall: ``Eve: God,
give!'' You are what you eat: she is the apple itself, all juicy
and tempting Flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Kasia and Eva hate each other. They vie for Marysia's
soul, as though whispering from her right and left shoulders. Both
are anti-Christian, or, more specifically in Poland, anti-Catholic.
Kasia's Spirit is not the Holy one but the anima, as in animism.
Unlike Marysia's mother, when Kasia loses a screwdriver she doesn't
pray to St. Anthony, whom she calls a ``monopolist,'' she prays to
the screwdriver. Thus she is a radical individualist who believes
that everyone is her own God, and her First Mover isn't the Father
or Fate but Freedom. Her efforts in Part 1 are directed toward
getting Marysia to cast off her religious chains.
</P>
<P>
   Kasia ultimately succeeds, and Part 2 describes Marysia's
hedonistic exploitation of her newfound freedom in the company of
Eva Bogdaj, whose rich family owns a country estate that amounts to
a pleasure dome of food, sex and consumer goods. The name of the
place derives from a traditional Polish soup, presumably the very
one they eat on Marysia's first visit, as though partaking, at the
entrance to the Dionysian grove, of an aphrodisiac. Dreams follow,
of snakes and ``stinky ponds,'' of fluorescent tubes and ashtrays.
The atmosphere of this hothouse is encapsulated in the line ``So we
sat hugging each other, until dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   One can read in all this a parable not merely of the
individual's journey from innocence to experience, or of the soul's
vacillation between spirit and the world, but also of Poland in the
last decade. Marysia re-enacts her country's transition from the
paradise, ironically conceived, of its twin safe houses of
Communism and Roman Catholicism into the materialist freedom, also
ironically conceived, of the West: a freedom that is not sunlit, as
the usual epithet would have it, but dusky (dark woods, Eva's black
hair), confusing and dangerous. Tryzna's freedom seems like
adolescence, like an endless forking of shadowed paths, like
turbulence leading toward something as unimaginable within the
confines of his novel as maturity is to a 15-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   A fine novel could result from the fleshing out of this
skeleton, and Tryzna deserves credit for wiring it together. But
for the most part he clothes the bones in gauze and chintz. Fairy
tales for adults need either subtle ideas or fresh images. Part 1
is Tryzna's ``idea'' panel, and Kasia's teachings run to wheezing
apothegms along the lines of ``Happiness is being true to one's
self'' and ``We have one life and our moral obligation is to live
it according to our own inner nature.'' (Perhaps this sounds less
trite to Polish ears than to American ones.)
</P>
<P>
   Part 2 must skate on a bright, melting surface. We don't expect
ideas from Eva, we expect seduction. She does seduce Marysia, but
the language is too flat, Tryzna's eye too lazy, to corrupt the
reader. Tryzna straitjackets himself throughout in Marysia's anemic
voice, rendered into a shorn English by Joanna Trzeciak. Much of
this section reads like a banal soft-core tease _ when will the two
girls do it? _ with a lot of quickened breathing, moaning and
shivering. There is also a persistent element of sadomasochism that
signals not revelry at all but fastidiousness, a guilty conscience
(those stinky ponds, those ashtrays). Granted, this might have been
the point of the scheme, but it doesn't appear to be the point of
the narrative voice, which lingers hungrily over these passages in
a way that suggests we are to find them as arousing as the other
humid entanglements. I sensed at this point, and occasionally
elsewhere, a confusion of intent, a blurred vision.
</P>
<P>
   There is talent here, waiting for a more controlling hand. And
this novel will find its admirers because it _ like, for example,
``The Magus,'' by John Fowles, or Hermann Hesse's ``Demian'' _
enacts in its own voice and vision the adolescence of its
characters. Its view of the creative process, through Kasia's
musical composition, is an archromantic one, full of satanic
overtones, suffering, exhaustion, transfiguration. (She ought to
have a bust of Adrian Leverkuhn on her mantelpiece.)
Adolescentlike, the narrative touches frequently on large subjects
without risking any real comment on them: ``We talk about music and
philosophy until evening.'' When we do get philosophical details,
they tend to sound like these thoughts of Marysia's: ``It's warm,
the stars are shining. The earth seen from afar is a little star
just like they are. A little light in the darkness. That's what we
all are here, on this earth. Somehow I feel comfortable with that
thought.'' And this is toward the end of her spiritual journey.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, she's only 15. But I think _ and I have to add
``personally'' because I am of course aware of the immense
popularity of ``The Magus'' and ``Demian'' _ that what makes
adolescence interesting to an adult reader is the ways in which it
must eventually confront adulthood. That confrontation never
occurs. Marysia looks in every mirror she sees: ``I could stand
here and stand here and look at myself until the end of the
world.'' That she wants to is plausible. But that she is allowed to
-- that the narrative not only provides her with a succession of
admiring alter egos but itself mirrors her overcharged,
underinformed rhapsodies -- is an artistic failure.
</P>
<P>
   To take the careerlong view, however: ambition and fearlessness
in first novels should count for more than achievement. ``She
really knows how to talk about all this stuff very concretely, but
at the same time, you don't really know what it's all about. In the
end, you don't know anything but one thing: that it's all
wonderful.'' That is Marysia talking about Eva, but it sounds
equally like authorial pleading, hence a suspicion on Tryzna's part
that he can do better. This, plus his closing pages, which finally
cast doubt, albeit too late, on the soft solipsism that comes
before, are promising signs for his next effort.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hall's most recent novel is ``The Saskiad.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
