<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-EXPOSURE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
--------
</HEADLINE>
 
 Southern Exposure: A roundup of books about Antartica  By Robert R. Harris 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spring of 1912 was not kind to the British Empire. On April
14, the Titanic met its fate with the ice in the North Atlantic.
Just a few weeks earlier, at the opposite end of the earth, Robert
Falcon Scott had met his, although word of his disaster didn't get
back to England until the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-six years later, the popularity of tragedies involving
ice and death _ movies like ``Titanic'' and books like ``Into Thin
Air'' _ has led to renewed interest in what the British like to
call the heroic age of exploration, and specifically in the
expeditions led by Scott and Ernest Shackleton. The lucky result
for those who've long been fascinated by these polar journeys is
the publication of new books about Scott and Shackleton and the
reissuing of many others, some long out of print and hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   The two new books are ``A FIRST RATE TRAGEDY: Robert Falcon
Scott and the Race to the South Pole'' (Houghton Mifflin, $25), by
Diana Preston, a British journalist, and ``THE ENDURANCE:
Shackleton's Legendary Antarctic Expedition'' (Knopf, $29.95), by
Caroline Alexander, the guest curator of an exhibition of the same
name that will open next April at New York's American Museum of
Natural History (in association with which her book is published).
Together the books frame the story of the epic struggles to explore
Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   Scott and Shackleton first went south together on Scott's
Discovery expedition of 1901-4 (although all these forays to
Antarctica had long official titles, they are more popularly known
by the names of the ships the men traveled on). It proved to be an
unhappy match. In his recently reissued biography, ``SHACKLETON''
(Carroll &AMP; Graf, paper, $18.95), Roland Huntford notes that both
men were ``spectacularly inept and unprepared.'' Neither could ski
or drive the few sled dogs they had with them, and when they headed
toward the pole (man-hauling along with Edward Wilson, who later
perished with Scott), progress was excruciatingly slow. Relaying
for most of the 850 miles they journeyed, they barely crossed the
82d parallel and had to race death back to their ship. Both Scott
and Shackleton came away from the effort with a mistrust in the
usefulness of dogs in crossing the polar landscape _ a prejudice
that was to have profound consequences later _ and with an abiding
dislike, bordering on hatred, of each other.
</P>
<P>
   On the journey all three men suffered from scurvy. Shackleton
was the worst off. The facts are muddied, but it is clear that at
times he could not help pull; at one point he also rode on a sledge
in order to brake it. When the men returned to the Discovery, which
had been frozen in the ice, a relief ship was waiting. Scott, who
was staying another season, had Shackleton invalided home. When
Scott later published ``The Voyage of the 'Discovery,' '' he wrote
that Shackleton had been carried on a sledge _ twice _ but didn't
mention that he might have been on the sledge to slow it down. The
insult was too much for Shackleton, and the final spur to organize
his own expedition.
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton's 1907-9 Nimrod expedition was either a spectacular
success or a failure _ depending on whether you think it's better
to succeed and die or fail and live. Along with Frank Wild, Jameson
Boyd Adams and Eric Marshall, Shackleton crossed the 88th parallel
and got to within 100 miles of the pole, besting Scott's Furthest
South by 360 miles and making, in Huntford's words, ``the greatest
single leap forward to either pole of the earth that anyone had
ever achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   As Scott had done _ and was to do again _ Shackleton took ponies
on his trek, animals that are horribly unfit for polar travel (they
sink through the snow's crust, and all their food must be carried;
by contrast, dogs eat dogs). Had he known how to handle dogs,
Shackleton would surely have attained the pole. As it was, he might
have. The men were done in. They could have forced their way
through, but in all likelihood they would have died on the way
back. Within reach of his goal, Shackleton turned, and he and all
his men lived.
</P>
<P>
   Another success of the Nimrod expedition was the first journey
to the South Magnetic Pole (the one a compass actually points at,
as opposed to the point that marks the axis of the earth's
rotation), accomplished by an Australian, Douglas Mawson, and two
others. Mawson later led a team to the Antarctic on the Aurora
expedition of 1911-13, during which he embarked on his own epic
sledge journey, although he wasn't seeking the pole. Two companions
died, one disappearing into a crevasse, and Mawson tells the
dramatic tale in the excellent and until recently long out-of-print
memoir ``THE HOME OF THE BLIZZARD: A True Story of Antarctic
Survival'' (St. Martin's, $27.95).
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton returned from the Nimrod expedition a hero. Scott was
livid. Before Shackleton left England he had promised _ had been
forced to promise, really _ to stay clear of Scott's Discovery base
at McMurdo Sound. Ice conditions forced Shackleton to land there.
In Scott's view, he was a poacher. Still, the South Pole was up for
grabs, and Scott meant to take it. A Norwegian named Roald
Amundsen, who had just conquered the Northwest Passage, had other
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the story of the subsequent race for the South Pole
has best been told in a book that has not been recently
republished. Roland Huntford's ``Scott and Amundsen'' is one of the
great debunking biographies. It was reissued in paperback in the
mid-1980's as ``The Last Place on Earth,'' the title changed to
match that of a television series based on the book and shown here
on Masterpiece Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Huntford devastates Scott's reputation, examining in detail
every plan, decision and action related to the expedition of
1910-13 with the whaler Terra Nova. It was on this journey, of
course, that Scott did reach the South Pole, only to find he had
been forestalled by Amundsen, who got there a month before him.
Scott and four other men died on the return trip: first, Edgar
Evans; then, Lawrence Edward Grace (Titus) Oates; finally, Scott,
Wilson and Henry Robertson (Birdie) Bowers starved and froze in
their tent in a blizzard just 11 miles from a depot of food. (Diane
Preston points out that had they averaged but 350 more yards a day,
they would have reached it.)
</P>
<P>
   After Evans died, Oates was badly racked by frostbite and scurvy
and was slowing the others down. It was his sacrifice, futile as it
turned out, that was immortalized by Scott in his posthumously
published diary, ``SCOTT'S LAST EXPEDITION: The Journals'' (Carroll
&AMP; Graf, paper, $14.95). ``It was blowing a blizzard,'' Scott wrote.
Oates said, '' 'I am just going outside and may be some time.' He
went out into the blizzard and we have not seen him since.''
</P>
<P>
   Did it happen that way? Scott, if nothing else, was a very good
writer, and the (heavily edited) account of his last expedition is
what made him a hero, the glorious failure who so captivated the
imagination of the waning British Empire. In fact, his writing is
bettered by only one other of the participants. The youngest member
of the Terra Nova expedition, almost chosen for the final, doomed
polar party, was Apsley Cherry-Garrard (whose biography is being
written by Sara Wheeler, the author of ``Terra Incognita: Travels
in Antarctica''). Years after he returned to England he wrote what
is arguably the masterpiece of polar exploration. ``THE WORST
JOURNEY IN THE WORLD'' (Carroll &AMP; Graf, paper, $16.95) is Edwardian
in outlook and sentiment, understated, sincere yet ironic, full of
subtle hints about what really went on with Scott, definitive about
what the men endured.
</P>
<P>
   Even Huntford grants Scott's literary ability. But, with
relentless determination, he shows that Scott was, above all, a
bungler on a grand scale. Huntford comes close to calling him a
murderer. Huntford's Amundsen, on the other hand, is a latter-day
Viking, the consummate polar traveler, aware of the value of skis
and dogs, obsessed with perfecting equipment, intent on not
stretching supplies.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A First Rate Tragedy,'' Preston sets out to rehabilitate
Scott. After Huntford, it's an enormous task, and she doesn't
manage it. She provides a concise and readable narrative of Scott's
two expeditions. But when it comes to refuting Huntford she accepts
as accurate and incorporates just about all his criticisms of Scott
_ that he relied on ponies (again) and not enough on dogs; that he
still didn't know how to use skis to good advantage; that he
ignored Oates's early advice to force the ponies on as far as
possible, shoot them and lay the crucial depot (the one he came so
close to on the return) farther south; that he failed to learn an
early lesson regarding the evaporation of his cooking fuel; that he
didn't take enough food; that the late decision to take a fifth man
along on the final push for the pole threw off all the calculations
for supplies and nearly resulted in the deaths of three more of his
men, those in the last of the support parties.
</P>
<P>
   There is something of a 90's sideshow to the debate over Scott.
Huntford has charged that while Scott was in Antarctica, his wife,
Kathleen, was having an affair with Amundsen's mentor, Fridtjof
Nansen. Nansen was the Chuck Yeager of polar exploration. He
pioneered skiing and sledging techniques and improved much of the
equipment used on the ice. His renowned Arctic drift (1893-96) in
the specially designed ship Fram (which he later reluctantly
allowed Amundsen to use in the south) resulted in a dash for the
North Pole that brought him and Hjalmar Johansen farther north than
anyone had been before.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation of an affair between Nansen and Kathleen Scott
caused a storm in England, and Huntford repeats it in his new
biography, ``Nansen'' (which has been published in England but does
not yet seem to have an American publisher). Kathleen Scott met
Nansen when her husband went to Norway seeking advice before
leaving on the Terra Nova expedition. To little avail, Nansen urged
Scott to rely more on skis and dogs. Early in 1912, Nansen was
lecturing in Berlin. Kathleen attended, and she and Nansen stayed
in the same hotel. Huntford says they slept together. After Scott's
death, Nansen proposed marriage and was turned down. Preston says
that Kathleen was visiting relatives in Berlin and that she was too
sensible to have an affair. The books leave things there, but in
England the controversy has turned on Kathleen's chronicling of her
menstrual cycle in her diary; and the discussion, it seems, has
come down to arguing about just what are sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   And so after pretty much granting all of Huntford's points,
Preston says, in effect, that Scott was a hero anyway, that we
should appreciate his achievement rather than criticize his
failure. That's fine, but she is not persuasive that Scott was the
leader Shackleton proved to be in the final episode of the heroic
age of British exploration.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Shackleton's Endurance expedition of 1914-17 has
everything a polar saga could possibly have _ fierce storms, a
relentless ice pack, heroic fights for survival, a near-miraculous
open-boat journey, an almost continuous doubling of the danger
every time salvation looms. It has everything except death, and
that is what has kept it in the shadow of Scott's tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1914 Shackleton set out to cross Antarctica on foot. He sent
a party in Aurora, Douglas Mawson's old ship, to the Ross Sea to
lay depots for his party to use when they crossed the continent.
Shackleton and a crew of 27 went to the Weddell Sea on the
Endurance. They never made it to land. Ice conditions were bad, and
the Endurance was frozen into the pack in January 1915. The men
wintered in the ship until November, when the Endurance lost its
battle and was crushed. From November till April 1916 they camped
on the ice floes. They had only dogs with them this time;
Amundsen's lesson had been learned.
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton and his men drifted far to the north with the ice
pack, and on April 9, when it finally broke up (and after the last
dogs had been shot), they took to their three small ship's boats
(named after expedition patrons) _ the Dudley Docker, the Stancomb
Wills and the James Caird. After six terrible days, during which
Shackleton and Frank Wild, his second in command, went sleepless
for 100 hours, they all made it to Elephant Island, the first land
they had set foot on in 497 days. But Elephant Island was nothing
more than a dismal rock north of the Antarctic Peninsula; they were
without radio and knew no one would look for them there. So they
reinforced the largest of the boats, the James Caird, which was all
of 22 feet long, with a freeboard of just over 2 feet, and got
ready to sail for help. For what was to be an 800-mile open-boat
journey in the fiercest waters on earth, Shackleton chose Frank
Worsley, the captain of the Endurance; Harry McNeish, the ship's
skillful carpenter and something of a troublemaker; Tom Crean, Tim
McCarthy and John Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   They set out for the island of South Georgia on April 24 and
sailed for 16 days, battling winds of 80 miles per hour and waves
60 feet and higher. And it was winter. If they missed the island,
there would be nothing but ocean between them and Africa. They
didn't miss, although they met with a fierce storm just as they
were drawing toward land (nearby, the same storm sank a 500-ton
steamer). But they anded on the opposite side of the island from
where the whaling stations were. Shackleton, Worsley and Crean
crossed the island's uncharted mountains in three days. They then
retrieved the three others and the James Caird, and made plans to
rescue the men left on Elephant Island. Three times Shackleton was
stopped by the ice, but he finally got through and rescued all the
men. They had spent 22 months living on the ice and the barren
island.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the great adventure stories (Wolfgang Petersen,
the director of ``Das Boot,'' is making a movie version), and it's
been told well many times. There is Huntford's ``Shackleton,'' of
course. Alfred Lansing's ``ENDURANCE: Shackleton's Incredible
Voyage'' (Carroll &AMP; Graf, paper, $10.95) is short, riveting and the
book that introduced many to Shackleton. And now back in print _ in
two editions _ is Shackleton's own account: ``SOUTH: A Memoir of
the Endurance Voyage'' (Carroll &AMP; Graf, paper, $13.95) and ``SOUTH:
The Last Antarctic Expedition of Shackleton and the Endurance''
(Lyons, paper, $16.95). He dictated the book to a New Zealand
journalist, Edward Saunders, but it's a rousing read nonetheless.
``We had reached the naked soul of man,'' he famously summed up,
with only small hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Endurance: Shackleton's Legendary Antarctic Expedition,''
by Caroline Alexander, features the work of the expedition's
photographer, Frank Hurley. When the Endurance was crushed in the
ice and sinking, Hurley went back and retrieved the tins that held
his glass plates from the icy water. He and Shackleton selected the
best and, because they couldn't afford to haul the extra weight,
destroyed many more. Some of these photographs appear in many of
the books about the Endurance expedition, but Alexander has added
ones that have never been published, and nowhere are these stunning
photographs so well reproduced.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander retells the entire story, of course, but she also
complements Hurley's photographs with moving word portraits of the
crew. Frank Wild, who was with Scott on Discovery and with
Shackleton on Nimrod, was greatly responsible for the survival of
the Endurance's men on Elephant Island (his diaries are being
prepared for publication). Harry McNeish, who never seems to have
forgiven Shackleton for having his ship's cat shot when they had to
abandon the Endurance, was the lone crew member to mutiny
(Shackleton threatened to shoot him). Tom Crean had been with Scott
on the Terra Nova and should have been chosen for the dash to the
pole; physically, he was probably the strongest man to serve with
both leaders. Perce Blackborow was a young stowaway whose
frostbitten toes were amputated under awful conditions on Elephant
Island. Tim McCarthy survived on the ice floes for nearly six
months, held his own on the hellish trip to Elephant Island and
served admirably on the open-boat journey to South Georgia.
Shackleton called him ``the best and most efficient of the sailors,
always cheerful under the most trying circumstances.'' He returned
to England to find the world still at war and, three weeks later,
was killed at his gun in the English Channel. F. A. (Frank) Worsley
expertly guided the James Caird to South Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Worsley, who during the 16 days at sea in the Caird was able to
obtain only four navigation sightings and still managed to get the
tiny craft to South Georgia, wrote his own charming book,
``SHACKLETON'S BOAT JOURNEY'' (Norton, paper, $13). ``In steering a
small boat before a heavy gale,'' he writes, ``don't look back --
it may disconcert you.'' He also wrote an equally fine longer
account of the expedition, ``ENDURANCE: An Epic Polar Adventure''
(Norton, $25.95). Long out of print, it will be published again
next May.
</P>
<P>
   That both Scott and Shackleton were flawed we cannot doubt.
Shackleton's expeditions all failed to attain their goals; Scott
reached the South Pole but paid a heavy price. From our distance it
is hard to judge them as leaders. But Apsley Cherry-Garrard was
with Scott and took his measure. During the winter before Scott
left for the pole, Cherry-Garrard, Wilson and Bowers completed a
brutal Antarctic journey (fighting temperatures as cold as 77 below
zero Fahrenheit) in search of, of all things, emperor penguin eggs.
He was an unassuming young man, who learned polar exploration by
experiencing conditions at their worst, and he was perceptive about
his fellows. As fate would have it, he also reviewed Shackleton's
``South.'' ``I believe Shackleton has never lost a man,''
Cherry-Garrard wrote. ``He must have had some doubts as to whether
he would save one then. But he did, he saved them every one.''
Still, Scott, like another British icon, Princess Diana, died
tragically, and that is what so often seems to capture the public's
heart; the disasters that ended their lives became the foundation
for their myths.
</P>
<P>
   Robert R. Harris is an editor at the Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
