<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4272 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FEVER-NYTSF     12-23 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FEVER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
--------
</HEADLINE>
 
 Charity Stories 
 By Mark Richard 
 147 pp. New York: Nan A. Talese/Doubleday. $19.95  Fever Dreams 
 By Tobin Harshaw 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time an actual carnival appears in Mark Richard's story
collection, ``Charity,'' it seems a bit superfluous. After all,
Richard's world outside the fun house includes an ex-con whose
teeth are filed into daggers, a boy whose legs have become ``stiff
sticks of long black hair,'' a corpulent patriarch bedecked in
garbage bags and speaking in tongues, someone called the Human
Skeleton, a cheerleader who ``got a tattoo that look like a man's
organ'' and enough other grotesques, oddities and freaks of nature
to keep P. T. Barnum flush until doomsday.
</P>
<P>
   That being said, it's surpris-ing to find that Richard's baroque
plotting and opaque prose belie the heart of a sentimentalist. The
best stories in the collection _ those few with story lines tight
enough to constrain Richard's unruly language _ deftly illuminate
the most primary of emotional experiences: in ``Gentlemen's
Agreement'' a son discovers his real bond with his oft-absent
father; in ``The Birds for Christmas'' two hospitalized boys find
true charity in the form of a drunken Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   Richard's characters are often children (all are boys, actually)
who for the most part are broken and unloved. But don't think for a
minute that they're victims _ the sense of menace that pervades
these stories more often than not emanates from these urchins. One
of the tamest is Michael Christian of ``The Birds for Christmas,''
a patient in leg braces whose dearest holiday wish is to see
Hitchcock's ornithological invasion on ``The Late Show.'' Forget
Frosty the Snowman, says Michael, '' 'I want to see 'The Birds,'
man. I want to see those birds get all up in them people's hair.
That's some real Christmas TV to me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the boy with a tail in the title story, who
threatens another patient in his hospital wing, a child in a body
cast: ``I paid them money to kill you for me, the boy with the tail
told the broken child. . . . You don't have any money, said the
broken child, and the boy with the tail opened a fist and showed
him a penny.''
</P>
<P>
   Creepiest of all, perhaps, is the child in ``Memorial Day'' who
collects scorpions while chatting with Death, here a dapper figure
in a white dinner jacket who munches on fortune cookies and
characterizes himself as ``a people person.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can't write these children off (well, the boy with the
tail maybe); they've been dealt a poor hand in Richard's
determinist world and they can't help acting in character. How was
the son in ``Gentleman's Agreement'' going to make good on a
promise to stop throwing rocks at cars when that ``baby-headed
tomahawk stone revealed itself in the dust''?
</P>
<P>
   Richard's adults are equally trapped by circumstance. In stories
like ``Where Blue Is Blue,'' a sort of murder mystery, he gives a
glimpse into the dead-end lives of the human flotsam populating the
tourist and fishing towns of the Virginia and Carolina coasts.
Richard has lived in this world, and not much seems to have changed
in the century since the locals' wounded longing for an easier life
found voice in sea chanteys like ``Riley'': ``Wish I were Cap'n
Riley's son, I'd lay around and drink good rum.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard finds unexpected decency and humor in these characters
when he keeps the action in the recognizable world. But when he
relaxes his grip on plot and language, the entropy isn't pretty.
Typical is ``Fun at the Beach,'' a sort of postapocalyptic
Frankie-and-Annette story that, after a very funny epistolary
prologue, lapses into a tedious exercise in black humor.
</P>
<P>
   But my deepest qualm about this story and Richard's other fever
dreams (as well as his earlier novel, ``Fishboy'') is that the
grotesques that pop out from behind every corner don't seem to be
anything more than curiosities -- they don't cause us to think
differently about our lives or question things we take for granted.
Sometimes, it seems, Richard is no less an exploitationist than
Barnum.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin Harshaw is an editor at the Op-Ed page of The Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
