<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SINGER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE WISEGUYS WEEP
</HEADLINE>
  The Jimmy Roselli Story 
 By David Evanier 
 Illustrated. 258 pp. New York: Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $24 
 -------- 
 The Wedding Singer 
 By Vincent Patrick 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``JIMMY ROSELLI is Hoboken's other great singer,'' David Evanier
asserts in the opening line of ``Making the Wiseguys Weep.''
Evanier quotes Scott Harlan, a vocal coach: ``There's no other pop
singer I can think of that can sing . . . in such a pure, romantic
style _ certainly not Sinatra or Tony Bennett _ and also have the
capability of doing the pop stuff too. . . . This guy could sing
bel canto at Carnegie Hall as well as at a little corner bistro.''
Another vocal coach, Carol Lees, said: ``A person without a great
voice can get up and perform a song and never hit a note right but
put it over. There are people who can do that, and it's a lot of
what actors have to do. There's Walter Huston's 'September Song';
Durante's 'I'll See You in My Dreams.' Sinatra did it in the later
years. That's all about style and interpretation and how they play
with the song. Roselli doesn't do any of that. He honors the music
as it was written and the meaning of the words as they were
written, and he allows it to come through his beautiful voice in a
really pure way.'' Since a reader's receptiveness to a book about a
performer is influenced by his opinion of the performer's talent,
let me go on record as a big fan of Roselli.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Roselli's mother died two days after giving birth to him
in 1925; his father, a prizefighter and the black sheep of the
family, left him for good, though he remained in Hoboken during
Jimmy's childhood there, working as a bartender and rebuffing the
young boy on the few occasions he tried to establish a
relationship. Jimmy was taken in and raised by his paternal
grandfather, a longshoreman who permitted only Italian to be spoken
in his household, which included his four daughters and two
sons-in-law (of whom he said that at the dinner table, ``You only
see the tops of their heads; everybody's eatin' ``).
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy's fine voice became apparent early on. By the age of 10 he
had discovered that a shoeshine box gained him entry to some of the
240 saloons that thrived in Hoboken in the 1930's, where he could
sing tunes like ``Danny Boy'' and ``My Gal Sal'' for sailors,
soldiers and prostitutes and collect $10 or $15 after a night of
passing his hat. During those years, Evanier writes, his
grandfather took him each week to the Italian theater and
vaudeville; after each performer, his grandfather would tell him,
``You can sing better than this guy.'' He was good enough at the
age of 13 to win first prize on the radio show ``Major Bowes'
Original Amateur Hour.'' The major slipped him a shiny quarter,
dime and nickel and said to tell no one. It was the beginning of
some 50 years of Jimmy's feeling he was being badly underpaid.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting question about the long career of Jimmy
Roselli (he is, at 73, still in fine voice, and packs them in when
he chooses to do a concert) is a question that lies at the heart of
this book: Why did he never achieve a level of recognition
commensurate with his talent? Evanier writes, ``The what-ifs about
Roselli's career center on two factors: Sinatra's influence and
wise-guy connections.''
</P>
<P>
   (Roselli incurred a lifelong enmity with Sinatra, and may have
paid dearly for it.)
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a more fundamental factor, which underlay his
problems with Sinatra and the mob and nearly everyone else whose
path crossed his professionally: Jimmy Roselli was a paradigm of
perversity and obstinacy. He could (so he claimed) cause the mob
boss Angelo (Gyp) De Carlo to paste his photograph on the bottom of
De Carlo's toilet seat. When a major agent, Lew Perry, suggested
that some mildly animated stage antics be added to his act, the
22-year-old Roselli replied: ``Listen to me. I came up here to
sing. . . . That's for guys who have no talent,'' and walked out.
He turned down the role of Peppino, the Neapolitan singer in ``The
Godfather Part II'' as well as appearances on Johnny Carson's
``Tonight Show'' and ``Regis and Kathie Lee,'' because none of them
would pay what he thought he was worth. He once answered Ed
Sullivan's admonition, ``It's exposure, Jimmy,'' with the
statement, ``I got so much exposure, I'm gonna catch pneumonia.''
He walked off a ``Merv Griffin Show'' engagement when told that
after singing he would not be invited to sit on the couch beside
the host. Evanier attributes Roselli's behavior to a streak of
self-destructiveness and a fear of success. I wonder if it might
not be, along with an unwavering respect for his own talent, a
level of prideful guilelessness almost incomprehensible in late
20th-century America, but not unknown in the cafes of southern
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Evanier, a magazine journalist, discusses the Sinatra-Roselli
feud frequently, but never makes clear its specific origins. It is
tempting to attribute it to the normal emotional responses of young
rivals raised just five houses apart in Hoboken, but the 10-year
age difference (Sinatra the older) and Sinatra's early success cast
doubt on it. What is clear is that these two men of very different
temperaments developed a lifelong mutual dislike whose intensity
can be gauged by Roselli's certainty that Sinatra was behind a New
York radio station's yanking him from the airwaves in the early
1970's, the ban lasting until 1991. (Evanier reaches no definite
conclusion regarding Sinatra's involvement.) Roselli's trouble with
the underworld is documented more thoroughly. During the crucial
early years of Roselli's career, ``a singer in that situation
really did not have any choice at all, if he wanted to play in the
restaurants and clubs,'' Robert Buccino, of New Jersey's Organized
Crime and Racketeering Bureau, told Evanier. Like other performers
of the time, Roselli dealt with the mob. Unlike the others, he was
apparently unable to kowtow sufficiently and show the respect
demanded by them. He drove the wiseguys crazy, in what seems to
have been a love-hate relationship; when they weren't threatening
his life they were at his shows, accompanied by wives and mothers,
literally crying through his Neapolitan classics or his English
renditions of songs like ``Little Pal.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Jimmy Roselli, from the older Italian-Americans who
revere him to those like Evanier himself -- captivated years ago by
the singer's arresting voice coming from a jukebox in those most
Neapolitan of surroundings, Lanza's on First Avenue -- will welcome
this thorough treatment of Roselli's career. (A minor omission is
any discussion of formal, classical voice training, which one
assumes, upon hearing Roselli, that he must have had.) Those who
know nothing of Roselli will meet in ``Making the Wiseguys Weep''
an American original _ a performer who finally succeeded not only
in spite of his enemies but in spite of himself. If it sends them
out to sample his singing (as it ought to) Evanier will have
performed a well-needed service.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Patrick's new novel, ``Smoke Screen,'' will be published
in January.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
