<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-KAISER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON SUNSET BOULEVARD
</HEADLINE>
  The Life and Times of Billy Wilder 
 By Ed Sikov 
 Illustrated. 675 pp. New York:Hyperion. $35 
 -------- 
 From the Kaiser to the Oscar 
 By Andrew Sarris 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The epigraph to the preface of Ed Sikov's finely wrought and
prodigiously researched biography of Billy Wilder quotes the
congenitally feisty filmmaker thus: ``In real life, most women are
stupid -- and so are persons who are writing biographies of
Hollywood celebrities.'' This pronouncement helps explain why
Wilder refused to grant Sikov even a token interview, but it is
wildly inaccurate when applied to the author of ``On Sunset
Boulevard.'' With the insights of a sophisticated film scholar and
the expertise of a tenacious reporter, Sikov takes us with Wilder
on a 90-year roller-coaster ride from the twilight years of the
Austro-Hungarian Empire through Weimar Berlin, Hitler and the
Holocaust to the last sunsets of the Hollywood studio system.
</P>
<P>
   But if the second part of Wilder's derisive quotation is
incorrect, the first part, with its woman-hating bravado, has
misled even so astute a chronicler as Sikov to take Wilder at his
word too often and too relentlessly. Indeed, I lost count of the
number of times Sikov uses variants of the word ``misogynous'' to
describe Wilder's work. Misogynous compared with whom? John Huston,
Orson Welles, Sam Peckinpah? Any writer-director responsible for
the ecstatic explosions of romantic love in ``The Major and the
Minor'' (1942), ``The Lost Weekend'' (1945), ``Sabrina'' (1954),
``Love in the Afternoon'' (1957), ``The Apartment'' (1960) and
``The Private Life of Sherlock Holmes'' (1970) can hardly be
singled out for censure amid the overall sexism of the motion
picture industry both in Wilder's time and in our own.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the facile allegations of cynicism leveled at Wilder,
even by a onetime and repentant detractor like me, tend to be
overemphasized in the book, which is otherwise a perceptive and
profound appreciation of one of Hollywood's most accomplished and
consistently iconoclastic filmmakers. Sikov acknowledges that
Wilder's harshest films seem in retrospect gentler and more
civilized than the brutish spectacles to which we have been
conditioned in the increasingly apocalyptic 1990's. Yet it can be
argued that Wilder even in his own era was compelled by his
contrarian tastes to inject new twists and turns into the familiar
Hollywood formulas for comic and dramatic shock effects. He
particularly enjoyed persuading big stars to undertake roles
radically at variance with their amiably sympathetic screen
personas. Ginger Rogers was induced at the peak of her popularity
to play a 12-year-old pre-''Lolita'' pseudo-nymphet in ``The Major
and the Minor.'' Handsomely likable leading men, like Fred
MacMurray in ``Double Indemnity'' (1944) and Ray Milland in ``The
Lost Weekend,'' were virtually rediscovered as a cold-blooded
murderer and a nasty drunkard, respectively. William Holden, a
boyish all-American type, vaulted to maturity and stardom as a
self-loathing screenwriter-gigolo in ``Sunset Boulevard'' (1950), a
part turned down by Montgomery Clift. (The role also reflected
Wilder's own checkered past as a taxi dancer and gigolo in Weimar
Berlin.)
</P>
<P>
   Not that Wilder ever lacked other reasons to be cynical. From
the day of his birth on June 22, 1906, in Sucha Beskidzka, south of
Cracow, in the Galician province of the decaying Austro-Hungarian
Empire, his existence was clouded by a virulent anti-Semitism that
long antedated the Nazis. He faced it in Vienna, where he began his
career as a journalist in 1925, and in Berlin, where he plunged
into screenwriting.
</P>
<P>
   These years are shrouded by Wilder's lifelong flair as a
fabulist of the first order. Many of his recollections of this
shadowy period are contradicted by other people's memories, but
Sikov keeps the narrative flowing forward by treating the most
muddled material as revealing in its own right. After all, what
Wilder may have fabricated in his interviews as biography he later
transformed into movie scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   Sikov follows Wilder through a maze of paradoxes. Though
Hollywood considered him more a screenwriter-director than a
director-screenwriter, he very seldom wrote a script without a
collaborator. To explain Wilder's professional survival in
Hollywood's ultra-Darwinian jungle _ his directorial career
extended from 1942 to 1981, with a very high percentage of critical
and commercial successes, including six Oscars _ Sikov skillfully
interweaves the myriad details of moviemaking. In particular, he
describes the contrasting chemistries of Wilder's two collaborative
``marriages'' with his writing partners Charles Brackett (from 1938
to 1950) and I. A. L. Diamond (from 1957 to 1981). Wilder's
unilateral ``divorce'' from Brackett _ who was older, more highly
educated, more socially prominent than Wilder, but pathetically and
vulnerably dependent _ right after the co-writing coup of ``Sunset
Boulevard'' is treated as a sour note in Wilder's triumphant
processional through talking pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder's first project after breaking with Brackett was ``Ace in
the Hole,'' an angry assault on the public's morbid fascination
with human disaster on a scale intimately identifiable enough to
incite a press feeding frenzy. (Sound familiar?) Unfortunately, the
paying public in 1951 stayed away in droves. Sikov aptly considers
this to be one of Wilder's most personal films, because of his
biographical proximity to the morally marginal reporter
protagonist, played by Kirk Douglas with an unmodulated
self-destructive intensity. Wilder, after all, had cut many corners
himself as a struggling reporter in Vienna and Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder rebounded from this setback with a succession of less
personal but more commercially palatable movies with a variety of
screenwriting collaborators. Then in 1957, with ``Love in the
Afternoon,'' he joined forces with Diamond, a young screenwriter
with whom he could work much more smoothly than he ever had with
Brackett. As with his second wife, Audrey Young, to whom he has
been married for close to half a century, Wilder was second-time
lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was more than luck. When Wilder chose to flee Germany
virtually the day Hitler came to power, and could not persuade his
mother and other family members to do likewise, he did not follow
other Jews into doomed German-speaking Austria but decided instead
to move to Paris, where he had few contacts and little familiarity
with the language. But his ultimate destination was always the
United States, a country he had learned to love from the movies he
had seen as a child with his Americanophile mother. In fact, she
had changed his name from Samuel to Billie in honor of Buffalo
Bill. (Much later, ``Billie'' defeminized his name to Billy.) The
point is that Wilder never became a full-fledged participant in the
German Jewish diaspora of the 30's and 40's. Though he has never
lost his German accent, he has spent most of his adult life in
pursuit of the American idiom in movies, radio, sports and popular
music. His published interviews and movie dialogue are peppered
with up-to-date American slang and pithy turns of phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Of all his fellow German Jewish emigres, Wilder most admired and
adored Ernst Lubitsch, with whom he and Brackett had worked on
``Ninotchka'' (1939), with Greta Garbo. But the director who
influenced him the most stylistically _ and this is one of Sikov's
most notable revisionist coups _ was Howard Hawks, with whom he and
Brackett collaborated on the 1941 comedy ``Ball of Fire.'' What
Wilder admired in Hawks was his ability to edit in his mind, so as
to leave no ``covering shots'' for producers to play games with in
the editing room. Also, Hawks, in Wilder's eyes, never betrayed the
script for the sake of a personal flourish of visual virtuosity.
</P>
<P>
   Sikov, whose previous books include ``Screwball: Hollywood's
Madcap Romantic Comedies'' and ``Laughing Hysterically: American
Screen Comedy of the 1950's,'' can be credited for emphasizing at
long last the crucial contributions of the composers Miklos Rozsa
and Franz Waxman to the emotional sweep of many of Wilder's best
films. Also acknowledged are Wilder's two favorite alter egos,
William Holden and Jack Lemmon, who served repeatedly as the most
conspicuous icons in the Wilder oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Sikov has painted as good a portrait of Billy
Wilder, the man, the artist, the showman, the self-promoter, the
profitably prescient art collector and the successful businessman,
as we are likely to get from the outside. Indeed, Sikov's is less a
still portrait than a blurry, moving picture of an eternally
restless human being, racing from country to country, pacing up and
down during screenwriting conferences, dashing about from one set
to another and from one story idea to another.
</P>
<P>
   Photo: Oscar night in 1961: Billy Wilder with three Academy
Awards and Elizabeth Taylor. (From ``On SunSET Boulevard'')
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Sarris's most recent book is '' 'You Ain't Heard Nothin'
Yet': The American Talking Film _ History and Memory, 1927-1949.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
