<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MYSTERIES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKING A LEG
</HEADLINE>
  Collected Writings 
 By Angela Carter 
 Edited by Jenny Uglow 
 641 pp. New York: Penguin Books. Paper, $15.95 
 -------- 
 Mysteries of the Normal and Ordinary 
 By Wendy Steiner 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELA CARTER would surely have smiled at the fact that Jenny
Uglow, the editor of ``Shaking a Leg,'' has arranged this
collection of Carter's journalism in odd categories so as ``to
define and separate but also to tease and provoke.'' How fitting to
cast these prose provocations in the language of a mascara ad _ or
one for lingerie! Carter herself had been tempted to describe Grace
Paley as a martini: ``wry, dry, tender, ironic.'' Equal parts
esthetician and folklorist, Carter used Kant to explain industrial
blight and the Greeks' golden section to advocate high heels with
long skirts. Had this book been organized chronologically, from its
first entries in the 1960's until her death in 1992, she would have
emerged as a faultless barometer of the shifting pressures of her
era. As it is, this Borgesian mishmash is the structural equivalent
of Carter's truculent whimsy.
</P>
<P>
   With the publication of her brilliant first novel, ``Shadow
Dance,'' in 1966, Carter began emphatically to speak her mind. Her
eight subsequent novels and her folk-tale and essay collections
punctuated a continual outpouring of cultural journalism. Ah, the
privilege of being a woman writer in heady post-1960's London! She
thought of these days as ``a brief period of public philosophical
awareness that occurs only very occasionally in human history;
when, truly, it felt like Year 1, that all that was holy was in the
process of being profaned and we were attempting to grapple with
the real relations between human beings.'' Women for the first time
in history were free to shake off the Blakean ``mind-forg'd
manacles'' of their femininity and shape their own identity,
exploring the luscious codes of female semiotics _ beauty, sex,
art, fairy tales, fashion, domesticity _ that had been trivialized
so very long by men.
</P>
<P>
   Carter approached the task with utter fearlessness. She would be
titillating if she wanted to be, or just irreverent: ``The question
every thinking woman in the Western world must have posed herself
one time or other,'' she wrote of Beauvoir and Sarte, is ``why is a
nice girl like Simone wasting her time sucking up to . . . boring
old . . . J.-P.?''
</P>
<P>
   She made a specialty of subverting sentimentality, noting in an
essay called ``Constructing an Australia'' that the koala ``has
been stricken by a sexually transmitted disease, an affliction that
severely damages its reputation as the marsupial most suitable for
children.'' She portrays D. H. Lawrence as a stocking fetishist,
and William and Dorothy Wordsworth as a pair of drug-crazed hikers
searching for a connection. ``Only a handful of eccentrics enjoyed
mountains until a mountain got up and followed Wordsworth across a
lake,'' she observes. Shocking, willful, extravagant _ every cut
and quip at the same time reveals a striking intellectual acuity.
Roland Barthes's mind is ``clockwork on odd days and fireworks on
even.'' In discussing Josef von Sternberg's film ``The Blue
Angel,'' she remarks that ``the significance of the femme fatale
lies not in her gender but in her freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   I have never read sequences of sentences whose trajectory is so
utterly unpredictable. Carter gives and gives and then snatches
away before you know what hit you. In an essay about her Scottish
relations, she describes ``my ain'' as ``simple, poor and plain
folk.'' So ``we proclaim with the characteristic disingenuousness
of the colonialized.'' Here she knew what was coming and tricked
us, but elsewhere she walks us through her own surprise.
</P>
<P>
   We visit a Norwegian art gallery with her in ``Munch and
Antibiotics,'' gazing at pictures of ruddy-cheeked farmers and
saucer-eyed children. One of them has ``the terrible beauty of
innocence . . . so that you look at him as if he were just glimpsed
before being swept away by some storm.'' And then it dawns on her
that he is about to be swept away: ``Dear God -- it isn't an art
gallery at all; this is a terminal ward. . . . The death bed, the
fatal diagnosis, the child who will not live and therefore must be
idealized, sentimentalized, or the death will be quite
intolerable.'' She leaps from there to our century, when children
are not expected to predecease their parents, and back to Munch's,
in which a mother avoids the eyes of her suffering child because
she knows that someone -- but who? -- is to blame, and finally
onward, headlong, to the conclusion: ``Munch's vision is
incompatible with antibiotics. . . . And they say there's no such
thing as progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly an essay in the collection does not harbor such surprise.
We might trace it to Carter's ``family talent for magic realism.''
Her mother's people had no indoor bath, but had a piano and went to
see Shakespeare at the Old Vic. The ``but'' here is mine, not
Carter's. She reports these facts in an autobiographical essay in
an uninflected sequence, as if the absence of a bath and the
presence of a piano are as unremarkable as the reverse. Her history
is full of such reversals. From a childhood rich in love she
emerged an anorexic adolescent. At the university, studying
English, she was drawn to stories of monsters and continued to find
them everywhere: reviewing a 1983 exhibition of Tudor artists, she
fixed on a portrait of Elizabeth I that ``shows her stiff as an
ironing board and stuck with pearls like lice, water-monsters
embroidered on her skirt.''
</P>
<P>
   The word ``ordinary,'' in Carter's magic realist mind-set, is
mysterious. After the Cuban missile crisis, ``nobody could ever be
ordinary again,'' she writes, but her loved ones taught her that
nobody ever had been ordinary. ``As my grandmother used to say:
There's nowt so queer as folk.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's nonfiction is pervaded by an ethnographic wonder that
renders the Sunday advertising supplement in a Providence, R.I.,
newspaper as exotic as tattooing practices in Japan or Portuguese
festivals of the phallus. She was an unofficial expert on such
festivals, by the way, along with pub songs, wrestling, pornography
and a vast array of topics whose naughtiness is the preoccupation
of outmoded minds. But at the same time, she could take Tom Wolfe
to task in a review for merging ``a jamboree, filigree way of
writing'' with a ``polemical stand for social realism'' or attack
the historian Robert Darnton for insisting on the unfamiliarity of
the past and hence ``marginalizing otherness.'' She loved to have
things both ways -- and why not? She could exercise her female
prerogative if she wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   In Carter's family, ``to love Shakespeare was a kind of class
revenge,'' and esthetics was a perfectly good tool for political
analysis. The results of such thinking are sometimes tiresome.
After all, not everything objectionable can be laid at the door of
``Thatcher's Britain'' or ``the twilight of capitalism,'' and even
if the proliferation of ``gourmet'' food books is proof of ``a
widespread and unashamed cult of conspicuous gluttony in the
advanced industrialized countries,'' should food enthusiasts really
hang their heads because children starve in Ethiopia? Carter,
recovered anorexic, is wryly repulsed by the voluptuousness of
cookbooks, but she can still stomach a little class superiority.
There is something not quite right to her ``about a coconut kirsch
roulade as a concept. It is just a bit . . . just a bit Streatham.
Its vowels are subtly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But just when you think you've got her _ Carter, the 1960's bore
_ she turns the cliche on its head. ``The sense of limitless
freedom that I, as a woman, sometimes feel is that of a new kind of
being. . . . I am the pure product of an advanced, industrialized,
post-imperialist country in decline.'' Well then, bravo for the
whole post-this-and-that imperialist-industrialist shooting match.
It can't be so bad if it produced a woman who could value D. H.
Lawrence's fiction and yet mock him mercilessly because he would
have hated her _ a female ``blackbeetle,'' she imagines him calling
her.
</P>
<P>
   Post-1960's liberation gave us a woman who was proof even
against Clark Gable's Rhett Butler: ``Irresistible Rhett,'' she
described him, ``his ears rampant as if ears were secondary sexual
characteristics.'' This was a woman who searched all through
literature for a model of female fulfillment and found it in
Chaucer's Alison, who managed to have sex with the man of her
choice ``to her own satisfaction and with no loss of either her own
self-respect or the respect of her male creator, which is more than
a girl like her will be able to do again, in fiction, for almost
more than half a millennium.'' Alison's ``giggle'' at her success
is the equivalent, in Carter's cosmos, of the Buddha's smile.
</P>
<P>
   It may be puzzling to consider Angela Carter's charms as a
writer: her irreverence and rock-bottom good sense; her petulance
and surprising erudition; her willful self-contradiction and sense
of moral responsibility. Add it up and you have something like
Enobarbus' verdict on Cleopatra: custom cannot stale her infinite
variety _ a male take on feminine perfection if ever there was one.
But Carter is ahead of us here, as always. ``Perhaps we mistook
permissiveness for liberty,'' she opines. ``Who is it, do you
think, who is permitting you to do all those exotic things?''
Whoever it is _ or, sadly, was _ we should be profoundly grateful
that Carter did them and left us this image of a woman:
contradictory, fulfilled, quite often giggling.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Steiner is the Richard L. Fisher Professor and chairwoman
of the English department at the University of Pennsylvania. Her
most recent book is ``The Scandal of Pleasure: Art in an Age of
Fundamentalism.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
