<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
--------
</HEADLINE>
  New &AMP; Noteworthy Paperbacks 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 Casanova: The Man Who Really Loved Women 
 By Lydia Flem. Translated by Catherine Temerson. Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $13 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Belgian scholar argues that Casanova was far more than a
sexual athlete _ in his high-spirited virtuosity he was the
embodiment of the Enlightenment. ``Perpetually captivated by
Casanova, as lover, adventurer or wanderer, Flem makes us
determined to seek out his company,'' Jonathan Keates wrote here in
1997.
 &UR; Pfitz &QL; 
 &UR; By Andrew Crumey. Picador USA, $12 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this slender novel, an 18th-century German prince mobilizes
the collective mental powers of his subjects to create an elaborate
imaginary city. Unfortunately, reality creeps into his vision of
esthetic purity, in the form of a young cartographer who falls in
love with another worker. '' 'Pfitz' is a surprisingly warm and
likable book, a combination of intellectual high-wire act and good
traditional storytelling,'' Andrew Miller wrote here in 1997. The
author ``develops his story with admirable rigor, seizing on both
the comic and the philosophical potential of a world in which the
actual and the imagined have become fatally blurred.''
 &UR; Taking Wing: Archaeopteryx and the Evolution of Bird Flight &QL; 
 &UR; By Pat Shipman. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the fossilized skeleton of a prehistoric creature that was
half bird and half reptile was discovered in Bavaria in 1861, it
touched off a long-running debate about the dinosaurian ancestry of
birds. The author of this account makes a strong case for such a
link. ``Shipman brings to her excellent book the authority of a
paleontologist and the talent of an accomplished writer on science
for popular audiences,'' John Noble Wilford said here earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   After Man: A Zoology of the Future, by Dougal Dixon (St.
Martin's Griffin, $15.95), envisions the species on earth 50
million years from now, like the vortex, a giant whale-like
creature descended from penguins. In 1982 in these pages, Timothy
Ferris found this illustrated book full of ``endearing and
plausible specimens'' that ``engender reflection about the
mysterious forces at work beneath the skin of real animals.''
 &UR; Panther in the Basement &QL; 
 &UR; By Amos Oz. Translated by Nicholas de Lange &QL; 
 &UR; Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $11 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A patriotic boy is accused of treason after befriending a gentle
British soldier in Jerusalem just before Britain's departure from
Palestine in 1947. In 1997 our reviewer, Lee Siegel, called this
``an insightful, inventive and lyrical'' novel that uses ``the
theme of betrayal to explore the status of the individual in a
country where public and private landscapes are constantly
merging.'' The Far Euphrates, by Aryeh Lev Stollman (Riverhead,
$13), is a first novel about a lonely rabbi's son growing up in
Ontario during the 1950's and 60's and the extended family of
troubled adults around him. '' 'The Far Euphrates' is remarkable
both for Stollman's eloquently understated prose and for the ease
with which he constructs his artful plot,'' Margot Livesey wrote
here last year.
 &UR; The Sea of Trees &QL; 
 &UR; By Yannick Murphy. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $12 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Set in Indochina during the 1940's, this first novel is narrated
by a young girl who comes of age in a Japanese internment camp and
in postwar Saigon. ``Her story unfolds through a dreamlike
progression of glinting surfaces, telling gestures and precisely
rendered moments, in which matter-of-fact horror butts up against
absurdist hilarity,'' Catherine Bush wrote here in 1997.
 &UR; At Risk &QL; 
 &UR; By Alice Hoffman. Berkley, $13 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A middle-class family's comfortable world is shaken to the core
when their 11-year-old daughter contracts AIDS from a blood
transfusion. ``In its simplicity and directness and restraint there
is very often a compelling power'' to this novel, Jim Shepard said
here in 1988.
 &UR; Gershwin &QL; 
 &UR; By Edward Jablonski. Da Capo, $17.95 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   The author maintains that the brash optimism of George
Gershwin's music was emblematic of a vibrant young America rising
to its potential in the arts and business. In 1987 our reviewer,
Francis Davis, said this biography features ``a wealth of pertinent
detail and fresh musicological insight.'' The same publisher has
reissued The Complete Lyrics of Ira Gershwin, edited by Robert
Kimball ($35), which tracks the artistic growth of George's older
brother and his search for fresh ways to avoid cliches. In 1993 in
these pages, Sheldon Harnick said this book should be ``in the home
of everyone who has an interest in the art of the musical
theater.''
 &UR; Empire of Light: A History of Discovery in Science and Art &QL; 
 &UR; By Sidney Perkowitz. Joseph Henry, $16.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A physics professor explores the nature of light and the complex
human responses to it, as well as various theories of the
phenomenon through the ages. In 1996 one critic called this a
``smoothly written, comprehensive and thoroughly enjoyable''
overview written with ``a fine awareness of light's appeal to our
esthetic senses.''
 &UR; Skull Session &QL; 
 &UR; By Daniel Hecht. Signet, $6.99 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An out-of-work teacher with Tourette's syndrome, hired to fix up
a vandalized Hudson Valley estate, finds that the damage may be
linked to some missing high-school students. This is ``an
accomplished first novel . . . that keeps the reader guessing till
the very end,'' Charles Salzberg said here this year. _Scott Veale
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
