<HEADLINE>
--------
</HEADLINE>
 
 Books in Brief: Nonfiction  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 SEXUAL McCARTHYISM 
 Clinton, Starr, and the Emerging Constitutional Crisis 
 By Alan M. Dershowitz 
 Basic Books, $23 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man who eagerly defended O. J. Simpson and Claus von Bulow
has little good to say about anyone involved in the investigation
of President Clinton. America's most vigorous and least
self-effacing legal commentator, Alan M. Dershowitz, feels that
this inquiry is rooted in dubious politics, that Kenneth Starr has
pushed it too far and that Clinton's evasions do not justify his
impeachment. For the White House, however, this is only tepid
comfort. A self-proclaimed Democrat and Clinton supporter,
Dershowitz nonetheless rips ruthlessly through what he calls a
``remarkable series of blunders'' committed by Clinton, his
advisers and his lawyers. When Paula Jones sued, Dershowitz argues,
the President should simply have filed no answer. Taking a default
judgment might have minimized embarrassment and cost as little as
$25,000 (versus the $850,000 Clinton has now agreed to pay), as
well as denied prosecutors their grounds for hunting obstructions
of justice. In needless litigation, Clinton recklessly fought his
way to where his lawyers should never have let him go, the point
where lies and denials risked perjury charges. The only mercy shown
in ``Sexual McCarthyism'' (which collects five years of columns and
opinion pieces) is its reluctance to say that Clinton's ``sex
lies'' actually constituted perjury. Dershowitz chides Paula Jones,
ridicules Monica Lewinsky, second-guesses Clinton's lawyers, paints
Starr as a minion of the tobacco lobby and damns Clinton himself
for weakening criminal defendants' rights, censoring the Internet
and opposing gay marriage. Dershowitz eloquently vents his scorn --
shared by many -- for the mirthless satire that the Starr
investigation has become. _Allen D. Boyer
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
