<HEADLINE>
--------
</HEADLINE>
 
 Books in Brief: Nonfiction  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 Grown Up All Wrong 
 75 Great Rock and Pop Artists From Vaudeville to Techno 
 By Robert Christgau 
 Harvard University, $29.95 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Applying the language and ideas of academic critical theory to
popular music, and adding a good dose of gonzoesque irreverence,
Robert Christgau, the senior music critic at The Village Voice,
created a brand of music writing that inspired a small but fierce
group of critics at alternative weeklies. The subjects in ``Grown
Up All Wrong,'' a collection of previously published pieces,
include Elvis Presley, the punk girl band Sleater-Kinney, the rap
artist KRS-One, the country singer George Jones and the minstrel
singer Emmett Miller, among many, many others. He writes on each
with equal erudition, examining the artists and their music as both
cultural products and influences. No pop act is too weird, arty,
commercial or schlocky for Christgau's contemplation. His
antielitist impulse makes him a likable critic, but his attempt to
straddle the ivory tower and bohemia produces a labored writing
style that tends to grate. Alliteration and contrived rhythms
abound (think Derrida meets Wolfman Jack), as do academic
hand-me-down-words like ``bricolage'' and ``pomo.'' In the end,
however, the results are brilliant; his exploration of the Rolling
Stones' relationship to black music, for example, is enlightening.
And though Christgau mostly writes about the ``human beings
rock-and-roll'' creates for him, whenever he pauses to offer a
close reading of music, the results invariably satisfy. _Laura
Jamison
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
