<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-AFFRIMATIVE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
--------
</HEADLINE>
 
 Books in Brief: Nonfiction  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 AFFIRMATIVE ACTS 
 Political Essays 
 By June Jordan 
 Anchor/Doubleday, paper, $12.95 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike so many other radicals of her generation, June Jordan has
not abandoned her revolutionary fervor. Whether protesting the gulf
war, the verdict in the Rodney King case or the end of affirmative
action at the University of California, where she teaches
African-American studies at the Berkeley campus, Jordan remains
earnestly engaged in left-wing causes. ``Affirmative Acts,'' her
new collection of essays, many of which are interspersed with
poems, is an interesting, if uneven, analysis of those and other
pitched battles of the decade _ the conflict in Bosnia, the
implementation of workfare, the appointment of Clarence Thomas to
the Supreme Court. Jordan is at her best when she uses personal
experience to bolster her arguments for political change. An essay
about the need for more breast cancer research is emboldened by a
frank discussion of her mastectomy. Similarly, a vivid, haunting
poem about being raped _ once by a white friend in East Hampton,
and then, some time later, by the head of her local N.A.A.C.P. _
aids her development of a polemics of resistance. Not all of these
efforts to intertwine her private and public lives are equally
successful. ``Root Canal to the Future of Women'' is a far-fetched
attempt to extract political significance from her oral surgery;
likewise, ``My Mess and Ours'' draws a gratuitous parallel between
Jordan's penchant for organizing her home and that of Americans for
compartmentalizing and ignoring social ills. Also problematic is
Jordan's frequent use of the overwrought prose of politically
correct cliche. Still, her lyric writing is a powerful mix of the
inspirational and the dispiriting. ``Revolution,'' she writes,
``means telling the truth.'' _Johanna Berkman
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
