<HEADLINE>
--------
</HEADLINE>
 
 Books in Brief: Nonfiction  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 CHARLES AT FIFTY 
 By Anthony Holden 
 Random House, $24.95 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor Prince Charles. For the last 20 years, Anthony Holden has
been his unwanted and dogged shadow as the author of two previous
biographies, the second of which Charles called ``fiction from
beginning to end.'' This new one, ``Charles at Fifty,'' is irksome
from beginning to end. Holden, who also wrote ``Diana: Her Life and
Her Legacy,'' makes his feelings for the late Princess of Wales _
``the innocent young girl'' whose ``habitual candor was
delightful'' _ as clear as the Queen's English. ``What kind of man
could throw away such a pearl?'' he asks. He tells us: one with ``a
built-in selfishness'' who forced his paramours to ``call him
'Sir,' even in moments of intimacy.'' In other words (which Holden
is all too glad to supply), a man who has a ``butterfly mind.'' And
those ears! Holden writes that Charles had been told point blank by
Earl Mountbatten, ``You can't possibly be King with ears like
that.'' While Holden certainly does his best to keep the reader
from adoring his subject, it is impossible not to feel sad for
Charles, the little prince whose ``first word was not 'Mama' but
'Nana,' '' for his nanny. ``What is it about Charles that seems to
have made him his own worst enemy?'' Holden wonders. What, indeed!
With biographers like Holden, why turn on yourself? _Andrea Higbie
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
