<HEADER>
A4282 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MASTERS-NYTSF     12-23 0351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MASTERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
--------
</HEADLINE>
 
 Books in Brief: Nonfiction  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Infants, as the French ethnologist Alain Epelboin observes in
the preface to BABIES CELEBRATED (Abrams, $39.95), are the
``tyrant-kings'' of most cultures, and some 200 color photographs
in this glossy volume prove his point well. With the guidance of 16
cultural anthropologists, the authors, Beatrice Fontanel and Claire
d'Harcourt, explore _ in words and in photographs collected from
numerous sources _ the many ways that anxious parents around the
world clothe, feed, soothe, transport, bathe and otherwise protect
and placate the fussiest members of their societies. Readers will
find no end of exotic traditions: diapers made of yak hair and
camel dung, the smoke ``baths'' given to Australian aborigine
babies, the smearing of soot and yak butter on the infant's
fontanel in Tibet. Here, too, are the elaborate predecessors of the
Snugli: fur-lined in Siberia, beaded in Senegal, gorgeously
embroidered in Guizhou, China. The authors note that a pervading
concern in these societies, as in our own, is the fragility of
small children. In many parts of South America, Africa and Asia,
where infant mortality is high, babies are viewed as ``vagabond
souls'' who may, at any moment, wander out the door of earthly
life. Hence, in Burkina Faso, Vietnam, Yemen and elsewhere,
necklaces, bracelets and cords are strung around a baby's body as a
means of tying the child to life. Some readers, particularly
parents, may find practicality behind the symbolism _ the bright
red pompoms adorning the headgear of Yao babies in Thailand, for
example, may attract good fortune but also serve as effective head
bumpers. Coins, beads and shells dangling from baby carriers and
clothing, used to ward off evil in many cultures, provide a
comforting distraction as well. _Suzanne MacNeille
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
