A4285 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BLAST-NYTSF     12-23 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BLAST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
--------
</HEADLINE>
 
 Books in Brief: Fiction  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 BLAST FROM THE PAST 
 By Kinky Friedman 
 Simon and Schuster. $23 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kinky Friedman has achieved cult status by being ingratiatingly
offensive, both with his country band, Kinky Friedman and the Texas
Jewboys, (cq) and with his superbly silly series of detective
novels, which mix real and fictional characters and feature
Friedman himself as a funky private eye, operating out of a
Manhattan loft with the help of his buddies, the Village
(Greenwich, that is) Irregulars. Friedman has raised political
incorrectness to something like an art form, but with such patent
good will that only the most humorless could disapprove. ``Blast
From the Past'' is a prequel to Friedman's previous books, shifting
back to the 1970's to show how the Kinkster got started as a
detective. This time around, the cast includes a Vietnam casualty
who returns from the grave, Abbie Hoffman (fleeing the Feds under
the name of Barry Freed) and a band called the Shalom Retirement
Village People. The ``mystery'' is of the flimsiest and wouldn't
mystify an idiot, being merely an excuse for Friedman to show off
his inspired tomfoolery. From beginning to end, the Kinkster keeps
the gags coming fast and thick. If this kind of stuff makes you
laugh, then you'll like ``Blast From the Past.'' And what's not to
like, anyway? _Brooke Allen
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
