<HEADER>
A4286 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PROVIDENCE-NY     12-23 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PROVIDENCE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
--------
</HEADLINE>
 
 Books in Brief: Fiction  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 OUTSIDE PROVIDENCE 
 By Peter Farrelly 
 Main Street/Doubleday, paper, $12.95 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the end of ``Outside Providence,'' someone asks the novel's
narrator, Tim Dunphy, ``Ain't you gonna say something funny?'' When
Tim responds with ``I'm gonna miss you,'' his questioner replies,
``That supposed to be funny?'' ``No,'' Tim counters, ``it's
supposed to be sad.'' It's easy to imagine Peter Farrelly,
co-writer and co-director of the movie ``Dumb and Dumber,'' having
the same exchange with his readers. Those who expect slapstick
guffaws will be surprised to find that much of ``Outside
Providence'' is quite grim. Its central character, the
aforementioned Tim, is wallowing in working-class Pawtucket, R.I.
Looking to improve his son's lot, Tim's father cashes in a whole
lot of favors and manages to get him into a tony boarding school,
Cornwall Academy _ which turns out to be no less hazardous than
Pawtucket, except the kids have more money and fewer morals. Tim
and his girlfriend are exceptions: though not angelic, they're
honest, compassionate and don't make as many jokes about
flatulence. Tim survives Cornwall, but the novel struggles there,
since it's hard to make a story about brutish boarding school
students seem fresh. Fortunately, Farrelly also spends a good deal
of time in Pawtucket, where his descriptions are raw and unnerving
_ and as mesmerizing as a traffic accident. _Liam Callanan
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
