<HEADER>
A4287 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NO-NYTSF     12-23 0248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NO-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
--------
</HEADLINE>
 
 Books in Brief: Fiction  Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 No 
 By Carl Djerassi 
 University of Georgia, $24.95 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Renu Krishan, a Madras-born, American-educated Ph.D., is sent to
Israel by her department head at Brandeis University to work on a
reproduction research project. While there, she falls in love with
Jephtah Cohn, a sabra who is her fellow researcher. Together, they
discover that nitric oxide (NO) can help cure male impotence. From
this starting point, Carl Djerassi, the originator of the
contraceptive pill as well as the author of a number of novels in
what he calls the ``science-in-fiction'' genre, follows the growth
of an international vogue for this new wonder drug. Djerassi
peoples his pages with scholar-scientists both dedicated and
conniving, jackal lawyers and Nobelists with surprisingly sharp
eyes for profit. The author himself has a sharp eye for his female
characters, especially Renu. All this should have added up to
great, readable fun, except that ``NO'' often appears to have been
hastily slapped together, with depressingly obvious seams in a
choppy narrative. It's as if Djerassi had pulled the draft of an
earlier work off the shelf and given it the once-over-lightly.
_David Murray
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
