<HEADER>
A4288 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-OCCUPATION-NY     12-23 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-OCCUPATION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
--------
</HEADLINE>
 
 Books in Brief: Fiction  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   First published in France in 1986 as ``Le Pierrot Noir,'' Roger
Grenier's spare and elegant novel, ANOTHER NOVEMBER (University of
Nebraska, cloth, $40; paper, $12), is a meditation on personal and
political loyalties. The unnamed narrator reminisces about Pau, in
southwestern France, where he and his friends grew up at the time
of the Spanish Civil War. When World War II comes to France, the
stresses of the Occupation bring out the essential characteristics
of each individual, particularly those of Charles Merlin, the
richest boy in town and the most spoiled. Charles's collaboration
with the Nazis is not so much an ethical collapse as a confirmation
that morals are as nothing to him when measured against his
personal comfort. In contrast, the narrator performs admirably in
the Resistance (as did Grenier in real life), but his heroism is
related in an offhand manner, as if it were not a choice but
something inevitable _ ``It wasn't much.'' Seamlessly translated by
Alice Kaplan, the novel is built around the recurring image of a
carousel at the St. Martin's fair, which comes to town every
November. Among its other attractions are a Pierrot figure who
wears black silk instead of the star-struck lover's lunar white
and, conversely, a boat ride with gondolas that are painted white
rather than the jet black of the Venetian originals. These devices
suggest that life is not what it seems; yet the melancholy tone of
``Another November'' appears to exist not because a thing can prove
to be its opposite but because in the end there are no surprises.
_William Ferguson
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
