<HEADER>
A4310 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT24-COX     12-23 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget forThursday, Dec. 24,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WEATHER
</P>
<P>
   WEATHERWRAP _ ATLANTA _ Winter's harsh debut has resulted in
three deaths in Texas and plunging temperatures across the nation.
A homeless person froze to death in Austin and two more people were
killed in a 50-car collision on icy I-35 in the Texas capital. And
in North Carolina, high temperatures tumbled 40 degrees from the
low 70s
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday to 33-34 degrees. The story will be 12-15 inches and
will move by 8 p.m. EST. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE TO TEXAS PAPERS: Austin will move a separate winter
weather story slugged AUS-WEATHER with details of the interstate
pileup and hundreds of minor accidents.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVELTIPS _ As many tips for safe driving as we can come up
with. (Spencer, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WEATIPS _ Other cold weather tips. (Spencer, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   SARALEE-RECALL _ At least one person in Georgia has been
sickened with listeria, the bacteria that is forcing Sara Lee to
recall cold cuts and hot dogs nationwide. CDC is investigating four
deaths _ three elderly people and a fetus _ and more cases are
likely, because the illness has a three-week incubation period.
It's unclear how much meat is involved or whether it just involves
meat that might have been sold in a grocery story or meats that
would have been sold as sandwiches in cafeterias and delis. (Kim,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-PRESIDENT _ AUSTIN, Texas _ In public _ in the kinds of
things political advisers politically advise _ and in private _ in
the kinds of things your mother tells you to do _ uncandidate
George W. Bush is doing the kinds of things a presidential
candidate does. Texans saw it recently when he named longtime and
trusted family friend Chase Untermeyer as chairman of the State
Board of Education and when State Insurance Commissioner Elton
Bomer moved over to the governor's staff. And one man in Davenport,
Iowa saw it recently when the governor of Texas thought it was
important to offer long-distance congratulations on the birth of a
child. Bush insists he is still undecided on whether to run, but
the Iowa dad said Bush sounds like a candidate. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-BANISHEDBABIES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Between 1949
and 1973, at least 2,200 babies born to unwed mothers are known to
have been spirited out of Ireland and adopted to families in the
United States. Many birth records were altered and many
intentionally misplaced. Church and state acknowledge they
conspired to keep the secrets. ``You have to understand that to
have a child out of wedlock in Catholic Ireland back in the '50s
was the most heinous thing you could do,'' says Bill Neylon. ``It
was considered shameful and despicable. It was a mortal sin in the
eyes of the government as well as the church.'' Neylon, a
44-year-old West Palm Beach physical trainer, was one of the 2,200
who would become known as the ``banished babies'' of Ireland.
(Moffett, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PIGS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's got a pig picture
gallery. It's got Paul Thompson's views on the benefits of playing
music for pigs. It's even got a little section on pig humor.
Welcome to www.pigfarmer.com. The 6-month-old site was set up by
Thompson's daughter and son-in-law in response to the Stuart pig
farmer's continuing problems with his golf community neighbor.
(Hartnett, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MYLAN-LAWSUIT _ DAYTON, Ohio _ When she went to the drug store
last spring for her monthly $30 prescription, Barbara Gamsu was
``horrified'' to learn the price had more than tripled. Her generic
anti-anxiety medication, lorazepam, now cost $96.85. ``The people
all knew me at the drug store, so I had a fit right there at the
counter,'' Gamsu recalled Tuesday. ``'What the heck is going on
here?!' This was a generic drug.'' The indignation of Gamsu and
countless other lorazepam customers will surface in court through
lawsuits filed by the U.S. Federal Trade Commission and 10 state
attorneys general. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
