<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 ART ADV.: Photos with SIZE-WAR, SANTA-LIFESTYLE and HIGHTECH-MAGNET
are being transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HONDURAS-MILITARY (Rio Amarateca, Honduras) -- The US military,
hunting for a new home in Central America after its planned
departure next year from Panama, has capitalized on Hurricane Mitch
relief to soften the ground for a possible broader role in
Honduras. By Richard Chacon. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OCTUPLETS-FUTURE (Houston) -- When some or all of the Chukwu
octuplets leave their hospital womb, the response from this city
will no doubt be measured against the extraordinary embrace the
McCaughey septuplets have received from their hometown in the 13
months since their birth. By Mitchell Zuckoff. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   SIZE-WAR (Undated) -- Battle is under way between mass
merchandisers, who sell through catalogs and want sizes to be
updated and standardized, and more upscale clothiers who prefer
``vanity sizing.'' By Patricia Wen. 1450 words. (a and l coding;
includes sizes text table) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NYHAN-COLUMN (Undated) -- For eight years Tom Trimarco has been
the political consigliere in an office that has been run, by
virtually all accounts, in a model fashion. By David Nyhan.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ A Supreme Court appeal makes for good
theater, but with thin prospects for victory, the Boston School
Committee is better off with an entirely new admissions process for
Boston Latin School. By Derrick Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) -- St. Francis belongs to the Catholic
Apostolic Church, a denomination whose existence can be attributed
to Christianity's tumultuous history. By Diego Ribadeneira.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Martin F. Nolan is not writing today. Eileen McNamara is
writing on a local topic; her column will not move.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SANTA-LIFESTYLE (Burlington, Mass.) _ The best Santa can make
$2,000 weekly for their December gigs, but their believability
depends on their all-Santa, all-the-time lifestyles the other 11
months of the year. By David Arnold. 750 words. &UR;  &LR; PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-GAMES (Undated) -- Video games have become more
accommodating of the variety of computer systems available for them
to be played on. By Michael Saunders. 1450 words.
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Boston) -- Margret Rey, creator of Curious George,
left a fortune to charity _ the subject of monkeyshines by some of
Boston's best-known ``charitable'' institutions. By Alex Beam. 1100
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STAGE-ROUNDUP (New York) -- People will leave home to see tough
issues explored onstage. Look at the success of ``The Beauty Queen
of Leenane'' and ``Wit,'' both on and off Broadway. By Ed Siegel.
1200 words.
</P>
