<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4320 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RPT-TEEPEN-COLUMN24-C     12-23 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RPT-TEEPEN-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    REPEATING TO CORRECT SPELLING OF LEWINSKY
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: Tom Teepen's column is being sent on Wednesday this week
instead of Thursday to accomodate papers with early holiday
deadlines.
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: One America elected Clinton, another America
impeached him
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The America that impeached President Bill Clinton is strikingly
different from the America that re-elected him just two years ago _
far whiter, far more male, far less female.
</P>
<P>
   The differences are a disturbing feature of the House's action.
In effect, the decision to remove the president from office was
made by the America that voted not to re-elect him in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   Run the numbers in three key categories: Clinton's re-election
voters were 58 percent female, 17 percent African American and 31
percent white male. Of the 228 House members who voted to impeach
the president, all but 17 were white and male _ 92.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only 7 percent of the impeachment electorate was female and, of
course, the single black vote for impeachment was an infinitesimal
.004 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The skewered demography was there from the get-go, in the
Judiciary Committee as it took up impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   All 21 committee Republicans are white. Only one is a woman.
None is black. Nearly half come from the South. Of the 16 Democrats
in the committee, five are African American, three are women. The
Democratic muster leaned to the northeast states.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those disparities were sustained when the issue moved to
the full House. Only the regional tilt was righted. (Twenty-five
percent of Clinton's re-election vote came from the 11 former
Confederate states; ditto impeachment.)
</P>
<P>
   This impeachment, when you get right down to it, was the work of
a bunch of 55-year-old white guys sitting around talking to
themselves, and talking themselves into it.
</P>
<P>
   No one could expect that the impeachment vote would be a perfect
match with the electorate or an exquisite microcosm of the
population at large. But disparities this great, especially when
combined with the overwhelming partisanship of the vote, go a way
toward explaining why the radical decision to unhorse the president
strikes so many Americans as inauthentic.
</P>
<P>
   A representative democracy like ours can take a lot of
roughhousing. As mean and defamatory politics has been in recent
years, it still hasn't hit the low set by the richly slanderous
election of 1800 that sent Thomas Jefferson to the White House,
with Sally Hemmings as the Monica Lewinsky of her time. No
journalist these days would write the billingsgate the opposition
press routinely heaved at Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the drift of the Republican Party into hard-shell
ideology, computer-driven reapportionments that are making more
purely Democratic and purely Republican districts and the now
common resort to personally and mutually destructive political
campaigns are driving large numbers of voters out of the system and
leaving it disproportionately to eager disputants.
</P>
<P>
   To those strains add, now, a divisive impeachment carried out by
a cadre that is not even close to being representative of the
American citizenry. We are, all in all, giving our political system
as severe a testing as it has faced since its breakdown into civil
war. It is a testing prudent managers would have never let happen.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
