<HEADER>
A4367 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-YEAREND-EXHIBITIO     12-23 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-YEAREND-EXHIBITIONS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART OF MODERN ART, POLLOCK, BEATS LOUDEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27)  
 (af)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON POLLOCK, AT THE MUSEUM OF MODERN ART &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's possible to second- guess the show _ to question, say,
whether the classic years are too tendentious or the last pictures,
like ``Blue Poles,'' are shortchanged. But great exhibitions are
supposed to make you think twice.
</P>
<P>
   This is a landmark survey of a painter whose value, which
remains difficult for many people to grasp, goes to the heart of
what makes modern art modern. Art exhibitions don't usually have
the dramatic pace of theater, but this one does.
</P>
<P>
   The climax comes with the big drip paintings, when the size of
the gallery expands to match the scale of the pictures and the
effect is a little like arriving at a precipice: as the space opens
up, one has a sense of being on the edge of something amazing.
Because it's as cogent and beautiful as it is, the show (organized
by Kirk Varnedoe and Pepe Karmel, on view until Feb. 2) ought to
convert Pollock skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   PIERRE BONNARD, AT THE MUSEUM OF MODERN ART &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With this show Americans had a chance to see why Europeans rank
Bonnard with Picasso and Matisse among painters, although an
equally germane comparison might be Proust, Bonnard having turned
everyday details, the stuff of the life around him, into a
profound, associative art of observation and memory.
</P>
<P>
   John Elderfield, the Modern's curator, made the museum's
basement galleries look good, for once. Bonnard's paintings of his
wife were true elegies of love, and the self-portraits, which ended
the show, were so touching that they broke my heart.
</P>
<P>
   `FLOWERS UNDERFOOT: INDIAN CARPETS OF THE MOGUL ERA,' AT THE
METROPOLITAN MUSEUM
</P>
<P>
   Having opened late last year, the show, strictly speaking,
doesn't belong on the list, but it's too good to go unmentioned.
This was a once-in-a-lifetime assemblage of Indian carpets, a
curatorial feat that was historically rich and above all drop-dead
gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Daniel Walker, it provided a concise lesson in
Mogul history while delighting the eye. Woven from pashmina or
Himalayan goat's wool and silk, spectacularly colored, the prime
rugs (there were 50 carpets in all, many of them enormous)
represent an imperial civilization at its peak. We are talking
about an art so refined that the most intricately woven Mogul
carpet had 2,100 knots per inch.
</P>
<P>
   GABRIEL OROZCO, AT MARIAN GOODMAN GALLERY
</P>
<P>
   This show (through Jan. 9) is by one of the more ingenious young
artists to come along in a while, who makes unanticipated poetry
out of a Ping-Pong table and turns trash into art. There are also
videos, drawings and a pavilion, with pianos for walls. Part
Surrealist, part Conceptualist, part formalist, Orozco is someone
whose diverse and unpredictable work raises a basic question: what
is the point of looking if you are not open to what you see?
</P>
<P>
   `SACRED ARTS OF HAITIAN VODOU,' AT THE AMERICAN MUSEUM OF
NATURAL HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   A celebration (on view to Jan. 3) of an amazing culture, which
mixes African, European and indigenous New World influences. The
show's success involves the way it bridges the gap between
ethnology and art. While carefully describing the history and
theology of Haitian Vodou, it presents works by painters like
Hector Hyppolite that convey the religion's visual efflorescence _
altogether, in other words, a spiritual and esthetic tour de force.
</P>
<P>
   MARK ROTHKO, AT THE WHITNEY MUSEUM OF AMERICAN ART
</P>
<P>
   It looked better at the Whitney than at the National Gallery in
Washington, whence it came, and it had one unforgettable section:
Rothko's pictures of the early 50s, their ecstatic colors layered
in veils with the quality of breath on a pane of glass. They
conveyed something truly exquisite and mysterious, like fresh love.
</P>
<P>
   `THE ART OF THE MOTORCYCLE,' AT THE GUGGENHEIM MUSEUM
</P>
<P>
   Lighten up. So what if the show turned the museum into a big
parking-garage ramp? It looked spiffy, attracted more visitors per
day than any exhibition in the Guggenheim's history and was, if not
the blockbuster of the year, then the novelty blockbuster of the
year. It also added to art jargon terms like single-overhead-cam
valve gear with enclosed rockers.
</P>
<P>
   SIGMAR POLKE, AT MICHAEL WERNER GALLERY
</P>
<P>
   With two dozen strange, beautiful new paintings by this
visionary German master, the show (through Jan. 16) is a tiny
fraction of the size of the gigantic, amazing retrospective that
was in Bonn then went to Berlin earlier this year. But a little
Polke is still a lot to contemplate. What he does is always magic:
clever, wild and, from a technical point of view, nearly impossible
to figure out.
</P>
<P>
   These works are perfect examples, their images suspended in
translucent layers of resin, like insects in amber.
</P>
<P>
   `PICASSO AND PHOTOGRAPHY: THE DARK MIRROR,' AT THE MUSEUM OF
FINE ARTS IN HOUSTON
</P>
<P>
   The postcards, cartes de visite and other photographs Picasso
collected somehow escaped widespread scrutiny until this show last
winter, which broke new ground. Picasso turns out to have been
directly inspired by these images when he painted ``Les Demoiselles
d`Avignon.''
</P>
<P>
   The value of the exhibition (organized by Anne Baldassari) was
therefore out of proportion to its size, and it confirmed that the
sources of Picasso's genius, like the sources for all great art,
are endless.
</P>
<P>
   BEATRICE WOOD (1893-1998) The ``It'' Girl of the American
avant-garde, Wood, who died on March 12, a few days after her 105th
birthday, made luster-glaze pots that are objects molded in light.
Apart from her art, she was also famous for having been one of the
great American characters: an actress and dancer, she was a
co-founder of the Dadaist journal ``The Blindman'' and a
mischievous romantic who, when she was past 100 told interviewers
that she had become a teetotaler because ``if I was going to be
seduced, I wanted to be sober.''
</P>
<P>
   She became the inspiration for Rose in the film ``Titanic,'' and
James Cameron apparently even thought of casting her in the role.
Too bad he didn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
