<HEADER>
A4371 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POP-YEAREND-ALBUMS-AR     12-23 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-YEAREND-ALBUMS-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW HIP-HOP HORIZON; A BANSHEE'S RAW RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27)  
 (af)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAURYN HILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While most hip-hop stayed in a holding pattern, Lauryn Hill of
the Fugees came out with a solo debut album, ``The Miseducation of
Lauryn Hill'' (Ruffhouse/Columbia), that accepts no boundaries. She
raps and sings; she uses rhythm-and-blues, pop, reggae and gospel;
she balances preaching and reminiscences, romance and
self-assertion, single motherhood and a career.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hill can sound righteous or utterly unguarded and
heartbroken; throughout the album, her grace matches her
determination. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE RIO PMP300 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A $199, 2.4-ounce, cigarette-pack-size gadget from Diamond
Multimedia announces an era when music will be zapped over the
Internet instead of preserved in plastic. With the Rio, computer
music files in the MP3 format, which can be bounced around the
Internet, become portable outside the computer, without the
physical presence of a cassette or CD.
</P>
<P>
   Major labels have refused to release their catalogs as MP3s, but
CD tracks can easily be compressed into MP3 files; most of the MP3
music on numerous Web sites is unauthorized and free for
downloading. The major labels fear piracy and have sued to get the
Rio off the market. Meanwhile, independent labels, free-thinking
bands and avid fans as well as sleazy bootleggers are taking
advantage of music's new mobility. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALANIS MORISSETTE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rock's avenging banshee returned to claim her loyal audience
with an album, ``Supposed Former Infatuation Junkie'' (Maverick),
of song therapy: wailing and crooning about all kinds of past
turbulence, from eating disorders to romantic misfires to crippling
depression. She proved that at least one 1990s superstar has a
loyal audience, and on stage at the Hammerstein Ballroom in
October, she sounded even better, supercharging her songs with
bruising Led Zeppelin stomps and seething, spiraling guitars.
Remembered fury still sounded raw. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLOQUE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The power of rock, too often taken for granted in the United
States, is just gathering force across Latin America. Bloque, a
band from Colombia, hot-wires local traditions from across Colombia
with funk, hard rock and jazz; it doesn't imitate American and
English styles, it colonizes them. Bloque improved on a superb
album, ``Bloque'' (Luaka Bop/Warner Brothers), with some of the
year's most galvanizing performances in live shows at Fez, making
music that was smart, sly, passionate, funny and utterly committed
to making a significant racket. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOAO GILBERTO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To mark the 40th anniversary of the first bossa nova record,
Gilberto's ``Chega da Saudade,'' the gentle singer and master
guitarist played a few select concerts, including one at Carnegie
Hall during the JVC Jazz Festival. Never raising his voice, smiling
just once, and accompanied only by his own lithe, restlessly
syncopated guitar, he brought to the songs of his youth an older
man's reflections on how fleeting pleasure can be, suffusing them
with the wistful, untranslatable melancholy that Brazilians call
``saudade.'' Subtlety never sounded more profound. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BECK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the mix-and-match overload of ``Odelay,'' Beck proved he
didn't need jack-in-the-box sounds or ironic distance. He took his
band into the studio and, in two weeks, came up with a thoughtful
album, ``Mutations'' (DGC), about ``the end of the end.'' Folksy
but skewed, the music slips free of the dead ends Beck sings
about. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUENA VISTA SOCIAL CLUB &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sense of occasion was unmistakable when this confederation
of older-generation Cuban musicians, younger traditionalists and
their catalyst, Ry Cooder, gathered for the Carnegie Hall debut
that few of them had ever expected to make. With the razzle-dazzle
of the pianist Ruben Gonzalez and the fervent voices of Ibrahim
Ferrer and Compay Segundo, the music was courtly and flashy, tinged
with old-fashioned romance and eager showmanship.
</P>
<P>
   It summoned nostalgia for an imaginary pre-revolutionary Havana
of ease and elegance. And it added historical perspective to an
influx of Cuban music that has swept through jazz and _ with
American appearances by top Havana dance bands like Paulito y su
Elite, David Calzado y la Charanga Habanera and N.G. La Banda _
taught salsa fans some new steps. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PEARL JAM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Realizing that one band couldn't unconsolidate the concert
business, finding that its sales weren't always going to be
stratospheric and shedding some self-importance in the process,
Pearl Jam settled into making music. It came up with one of its
best albums, ``Yield'' (Epic), and returned to touring with a
recharged sense of purpose while it played to enough loyalists to
fill arenas. The band sounded magnificent on stage, and a live
album, ``Live on Two Legs'' (Epic), released with little fanfare,
proved it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BURT BACHARACH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A wave of rediscovery crested in 1998 for Burt Bacharach, whose
songs are being newly appreciated for their strange, off-center
melodies and the heartbreak (from Hal David's fastidiously morose
lyrics) concealed behind the lilt. Pop hipsters continued to
re-evaluate lounge and easy-listening music; current hit makers
from Sheryl Crow to the Barenaked Ladies gathered to sing Bacharach
tunes on a cable-television special; a boxed set appeared.
</P>
<P>
   And Elvis Costello seized the chance to collaborate with his
idol on an album of new songs, ``Painted From Memory'' (Mercury),
and to sing them on tour. The album and concert were both laborious
near-misses (and reminders of what a brilliant illusion Dionne
Warwick's effortlessness was), but Bacharach's reputation has
definitely been made over. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JANET JACKSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Proving that the pop concert spectacle still survives, Janet
Jackson brought the year's most impressive pop revue, ``The Velvet
Rope'' tour, from the arena circuit to HBO. Amid the choregraphy,
hit tunes and lip-synching, Ms. Jackson examined lust and power,
affection and abuse, longing and death. Who needed spontaneity?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1524EST &QL; 
