<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-YEAREND-ALBUMS-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, JAWS DROPPED, AND HEARTS BEAT FASTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASES SUNDAY, DEC. 27)  
 (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEVINE'S DVORAK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The year's striking musical moments often came during events
ostensibly about other things. James Levine's Met Orchestra concert
at Carnegie Hall in mid-November advertised Milton Babbitt's new
piano concerto, but it was a performance of Dvorak's G major
Symphony that made the jaw drop and the heart beat faster.
</P>
<P>
   Here was a locus of points: the sophistication of a big-time
orchestra, the dead-on contact with late 19th-century style, and a
simple sympathy with the dancing and singing of rural Central
Europe. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEETHOVEN IN CLEVELAND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The listener went to Cleveland early in October to hear Charles
Ives's newly cobbled ``Emerson'' Concerto for piano and orchestra
but came away with a performance of Beethoven's ``Eroica'' Symphony
that spoke of collaboration onstage and a sense of community in the
audience. Christoph von Dohnanyi and the Cleveland Orchestra
provided a kind of informed fervor not often encountered in the
concert world. The audience at Severance Hall gave every indication
of appreciating just what was happening before it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PICKER'S `EMMELINE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Emmeline'' at the New York City Opera at the beginning of
April gave us a new American opera that might last awhile. Tobias
Picker's modest yet substantial work rises blessedly above a long
line of recent mediocrities from this country, each having promised
much and delivered less. There is a Shaker-like quality to
``Emmeline,'' a piece that sang handsomely and held together nicely
in Francesca Zambello's sparse production. Patricia Racette sang
the title role. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIGETI IN LOS ANGELES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Groygy Ligeti's Requiem in late April in Los Angeles gave New
York a lesson in what festivals, large and small, are meant to do.
This big and frightening choral work was the centerpiece of
Esa-Pekka Salonen's brave series with the Los Angeles Philharmonic
based on Ligeti's music. The Requiem is both chaste and raucous,
with a cartoonish approach to the liturgy not inappropriate to our
times. Reacting to a strong performance, a big audience swallowed
hard and took it all in. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATING CARTER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Europeans have carefully choreographed their 90th-birthday
tributes to Elliott Carter, but I like the rich and disorganized
rush of concerts coming from every side of New York's musical
community. Speculum Musicae presented a Carter program at the
Miller Theater in late October, looking back to the imposing Double
Concerto of 1961 but also offering such airy, light-filled new
chamber pieces as ``Luimen'' for six instruments. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATING GERSHWIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eurocentric symphony orchestras are making hardy, if halting,
attempts at the Gershwin centenary. But one of the most interesting
pockets of celebration was a weekend conclave in mid-March at the
Library of Congress in Washington. There practitioners, scholars,
family members and friends spent three days with music of Gershwin
and contemporaries like Vernon Duke. Some of the papers dragged,
but Dick Hyman, Alan Feinberg, Michael Feinstein, Bolcom and
Morris, and others were there to pep things up. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROOK'S `DON GIOVANNI' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mozart's ``Don Giovanni,'' continuously in the operatic
repertory since its premiere just over 200 years ago, found a
friend in the director Peter Brook, whose simple yet carefully
considered production at Aix-en-Provence, France, in July fixed
attention where it belonged. There was a young, strong cast on an
outdoor stage and a correspondingly good band of student players in
the pit, conducted by Claudio Abbado. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KREMER'S VIVALDI &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If it is fashionable to trash Vivaldi's ubiquitous ``Four
Seasons,'' Gidon Kremer and his Kremerata band reminded listeners
of this music's great power and originality with a concert in early
August at Avery Fisher Hall. Every familiar movement was rethought,
sometimes not to my liking but performed with a concentration and
skill that removed these pieces from the status of elevator music,
where they have languished for too long. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AX AND KREMER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two items from the ambivalence department: First, Emanuel Ax in
early August at Avery Fisher Hall playing Chopin's F minor Concerto
on an 1840 Broadwood piano with the Orchestra of the Age of
Enlightenment. It may have been the wrong instrument for us today,
but what sensitive, graceful musicianship it was. Remember, too,
Astor Piazzolla's tango opera ``Maria de Buenos Aires,'' again with
Kremer and his Kremerata in early October at the Majestic Theater
of the Brooklyn Academy of Music. Overwhelmed by its own literary
ornateness, the work is nevertheless a window onto the exciting no
man's land between popular and classical cultures. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MET PRODUCTIONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We expect so much of the Metropolitan Opera that when its vast
resources fail us, we remember. Reviving Offenbach's ``Contes
d'Hoffmann'' in February was a gratifying success, but one mourns
the sometimes misdirected assets of this fall's ``Nozze di Figaro''
and the anti-opera self-indulgence of Franco Zeffirelli's new
``Traviata.'' The Robert Wilson-meets-``Lohengrin'' experience in
March had its opening night problems, too. Is the labor-intensive
Wilson style wrong for a big, busy repertory house? It may well be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1526EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
