<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4380 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMAS-BREAKFAST-T     12-23 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-BREAKFAST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE YOURSELF A MERRY LITTLE BREAKFAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a golden afterglow to Christmas morning. The presents
have all been opened, but the yuletide magic still lingers. Lights
twinkle on the tree, carols warble from the stereo, and the holiday
catches its breath. Christmas dinner is hours away. In the meantime
... well, it IS a holiday. So let's eat.
</P>
<P>
   Just a little something to tide you over till that midday feast.
Or maybe heavier fare if your major Christmas meal was savored on
Christmas Eve or won't be served until late on Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   A special breakfast. Simple but elegant _ who needs extra work
at this busiest of seasons?
</P>
<P>
   Here are some recipes that don't require a major last-minute
shopping trip and can be prepared quickly _ or even in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE AND BANANA SALAD WITH YOGURT DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6
</P>
<P>
   2 navel oranges
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons chopped mint
</P>
<P>
   3 bananas, sliced
</P>
<P>
   Yogurt dressing, below
</P>
<P>
   Grate peel from oranges and reserve for dressing. Peel oranges,
removing all the white pith. Cut oranges into 1/4-inch slices to
make wagon wheels, or section them, removing all membranes.
</P>
<P>
   Combine oranges and mint. Refrigerate, covered, a couple of
hours or overnight. Add bananas no more than 1 hour before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serve salad in a pretty glass bowl, with yogurt dressing on the
side.
</P>
<P>
   YOGURT DRESSING:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons honey
</P>
<P>
   Combine yogurt, peel, orange juice and honey. Refrigerate,
covered, until needed. Serve on the side with fruit or pound cake.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving, with dressing: 99 calories, 2
grams fat, 24 grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 5 milligrams
cholesterol, 20 milligrams sodium, 15 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``_Nathalie Dupree's Comfortable Entertaining'' (Viking, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT SCRAMBLED EGGS WITH SMOKED SALMON
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of white pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound smoked Scottish salmon, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   2 slices white toast, crust removed
</P>
<P>
   10 small mushrooms, sauteed in butter
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, whisk together eggs and cream until completely
blended. Whisk in salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   In a small skillet, heat butter over medium heat until a drop of
water sizzles. Add eggs and cook over low heat until set. Do not
overcook.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange salmon in overlapping slices around the edges of two
plates. Place one slice of toast at center of each plate. Cover
with scrambled eggs and place five mushrooms at edge of each mound
of eggs. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 373 calories, 23 grams fat, 15
grams carbohydrates, 26 grams protein, 469 milligrams cholesterol,
1038 milligrams sodium, 55 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``_The International Breakfast Book'' by Martha Hollis
(Macmillan, $25)
</P>
<P>
   SANTA FE CHEESE CASSEROLE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10 to 12
</P>
<P>
   1 pound Monterey Jack cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   1 pound Cheddar cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   2 4-ounce cans green chile peppers, drained and chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 egg whites, stiffly beaten (but not dry)
</P>
<P>
   2 medium tomatoes, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh cilantro sprigs
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium-large bowl, place the two cheeses and green chile
peppers, reserving 1 tablespoon of green chiles. Mix cheeses and
chiles.
</P>
<P>
   In another medium bowl, beat together egg yolks, evaporated
milk, flour, salt and pepper. Fold in egg whites. Fold this mixture
into cheese mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Place mixture in a buttered 3-quart casserole dish. Bake for 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange tomatoes on top and bake 30 minutes more. Garnish with
reserved green chile peppers and cilantro sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 344 calories, 27 grams fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 22 grams protein, 148 milligrams cholesterol,
682 milligrams sodium, 70 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``_ Chile, Corn and Croissants'' by Joan Stromquist (Tierra
Publications, $17.95)
</P>
<P>
   APRICOT SAUSAGE COMPOTE
</P>
<P>
   Makes approximately 2 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound uncooked sausage
</P>
<P>
   1 15-ounce can apricot halves, drained
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Place sausage in a medium skillet. Cook on medium-high heat
until well-done, stirring constantly. Drain off grease.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in apricots and brown sugar. Cook until well heated.
Compote can be prepared the day before and reheated. Serve with
waffles or pancakes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per 1/2-cup serving: 147 calories, 8 grams
fat, 14 grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 21 milligrams
cholesterol, 334 milligrams sodium, 49 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``_ Chile, Corn and Croissants''
</P>
<P>
   OVERNIGHT WAFFLES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon instant yeast
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound (1 stick) butter, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Canola or other neutral oil for waffle iron
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Before going to bed, combine yeast, flour, sugar and salt and
stir in milk, then butter and vanilla, if using. Mixture will be
loose. Cover with plastic wrap and set aside overnight at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, brush waffle iron lightly with oil and preheat
it. Separate eggs and stir yolks into batter. Beat whites until
they hold soft peaks. Stir them gently into batter.
</P>
<P>
   Spread a ladleful or so of batter onto waffle iron and bake
until waffle is done, usually 3 to 5 minutes, depending on your
iron. Serve immediately or keep warm for a few minutes in a low
oven.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving, based on 4 servings:: 544
calories, 30 grams fat, 54 grams carbohydrates, 14 grams protein,
186 milligrams cholesterol, 627 milligrams sodium, 50 percent of
calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``_ How to Cook Everything'' by Mark Bittman, (Macmillan, $25)
</P>
<P>
   GRAPE CLAFOUTIS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 cups seedless green or red grapes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon rum flavoring or 2 tablespoons rum
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Heavily butter an 8- or 9-inch
baking dish or pie pan.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle grapes with half the sugar and let stand 30 minutes.
For batter, in a bowl or food processor beat together remaining
sugar and egg yolks. Then beat in the egg. Gradually beat in
butter, then flour. Finally, add rum flavoring, almond extract and
milk. Beat until very smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Pour one-third of batter into prepared pan. Spoon grapes and
their juice, if any, over batter. Pour remaining batter over
grapes. Bake tart on lower rack of oven until a toothpick comes out
clean, about 40 minutes. Texture should be soft and nearly
custardy. Cool slightly and serve from pan in wedges or squares.
Tart may be prepared several days in advance and refrigerated or
frozen up to 3 months. Serve it warm, reheated or at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 435 calories, 20 grams fat, 61
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 153 milligrams cholesterol,
191 milligrams sodium, 41 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``_ Nathalie Dupree's Comfortable Entertaining''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
