<HEADER>
A4381 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-YEAREND-SHOWS-$ADV     12-23 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-YEAREND-SHOWS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX, LIES AND VIDEOTAPE, VIDEOTAPE, VIDEOTAPE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE BILL CLINTON SHOW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No fictional drama could possibly compete. During the first
presidential impeachment of the 20th century, television became
more than the playing field; it was an active participant, as the
voracious 24-hour news channels pushed the story along.
</P>
<P>
   Think of how powerfully Bill Clinton's sex-and-lies scandal was
molded by these endlessly replayed images: Monica Lewinsky, in her
black beret, standing in a rope line to greet the president;
Clinton wagging his finger at the public and saying words we now
know by heart: ``I did not have sexual relations with that woman,
Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, for four straight hours television viewers watched
the videotape of the president's testimony before the grand jury
(in polls, his approval ratings rose); last week, audiences were
the witnesses as the House of Representatives voted to impeach him
(in polls, his approval ratings rose). We have lost count of his
televised apologies.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal highlighted the Jekyll and Hyde nature of the
24-hour news channels: the influential CNN and MSNBC and the
tag-along Fox News Channel. At their best, they offered a
comprehensive yet intimate view of the Clinton presidency in the
process of unraveling; in their tackiest moments, they became the
Psychic Friends Network of politics, with blather like ``What is
Hillary feeling?'' Yet their incessant talk and presence continue
to define this unimaginable historical drama. Next to the
impeachment, even the green-glowing night images of missiles
landing in Baghdad seemed familiar. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE LAST `SEINFELD' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   True fans were disappointed in the dark, absurdist final
episode, in which the fictional Jerry Seinfeld, along with George,
Elaine and Kramer, was locked in a jail cell for a year. But the
finale is among the year's most significant television events
because of the manufactured media frenzy surrounding one comedian's
decision to end his eight-year-old series; is that really something
to be distraught about?
</P>
<P>
   ``Seinfeld'' was a cultural touchstone (it's the reason you're
sick of hearing ``Yada, yada, yada''). Yet with network audiences
bleeding away to cable, it may also be a dinosaur, the last network
show able to whip up that kind of hysteria. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SPORTS NIGHT' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This ABC comedy-drama is the one sign of life in the wilderness
that was this network season. Set behind the scenes of a fictional
television show, it is a superbly written and acted look at the
tangle of work, life and love in the 90s, having more in common
with a comedy of manners like ``The Rules of the Game'' than with
ordinary sitcoms. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `FROM THE EARTH TO THE MOON' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Tom Hanks as executive producer, HBO's 12-part mini-series
about the Apollo moon missions did more than accumulate Emmys; it
has been credited with rejuvenating the genre. (Hanks and Steven
Spielberg will produce a World War II mini-series for HBO.) Viewing
the Apollo project through a haze of nostalgia for all-American
ambition, ``From the Earth to the Moon'' helped set the current
mood of longing for an age (any age) of lost heroism. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE CBS SUNDAY MOVIE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nostalgia continues. Week after week, with the mawkish
``Touched by an Angel'' as a lead-in, a sentimental, formulaic CBS
made-for-television movie lands in the Nielsen ratings' top 10. As
bland as warm milk, some of the most popular have stars whose very
names signal fuzzy longings for yesterday: Debbie Reynolds as a
granny in ``A Christmas Wish,'' Jack Lemmon as a gramps in ``The
Long Way Home.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MR. SHOW WITH BOB AND DAVID' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The conservative gust that brought a battle about leadership and
morality to Washington was echoed in entertainment, as the huge
sweep of nostalgia had its countervailing trend in shows with
cutting-edge attitudes. Though schmaltzy television movies get big
ratings, cult audiences are devoted to `` Show,'' HBO's wickedly
satirical sketch comedy series with Bob Odenkirk and David Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Among their wittiest sketches: Guests on a Jerry Springer-style
show, stranded in a lifeboat. Along with Comedy Central's ``Upright
Citizens Brigade,'' another brazen sketch comedy show, it is
sometimes tasteless but always inventive, and with smaller
audiences can afford to be daring in a television climate that
prizes no-risk jokes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALL `BIOGRAPHY' ALL THE TIME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If `` Show'' displays a hard-edged comic sensibility, A&AMP;E's
enormously popular ``Biography'' and its raft of clones are
evidence of the softheaded cult of celebrity. A&AMP;E's ``Ozzie and
Harriet'' episode may have proved the Nelsons were not picture
perfect, but it wasn't exactly hard-hitting. And ``Biography''
seems positively debunking next to fluffier wannabes, which include
a profile of Helen Gurley Brown on Lifetime's ``Intimate Portrait''
and Cyd Charisse on ``Bravo Profiles.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `N.Y.P.D. BLUE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There will be no guest appearances by Jimmy Smits, now that his
character, Bobby Simone, has been killed off. The Bobby episodes
were tear-jerking and toughly realistic; Rick Schroder has turned
out to be surprisingly effective as a scrappy new detective. This
tired and aging series did something almost unheard of in
television: it took risks and was rejuvenated. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JACK KEVORKIAN ON `60 MINUTES' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The term ``guest appearance'' suits this headline-grabbing
stunt, which placed Dr. Jack Kevorkian and the CBS news magazine in
cahoots. When ``60 Minutes'' showed a staged death, a tape of
Kevorkian administering lethal drugs to a terminally ill patient,
the hard line separating news from manufactured reality all but
disappeared. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `LOLITA' GOES TO SHOWTIME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, no one would have made a nearly $60 million art
film. As it turned out, Jeremy Irons and Dominique Swain were
spectacularly moving as Humbert Humbert and his nymphet in Adrian
Lyne's eloquent film of the Nabokov novel.
</P>
<P>
   Shunned by Hollywood because of its cost, slender commercial
prospects and flammable subject, the movie was bought by Showtime.
Here is proof that however haphazardly, art survives in unlikely
places.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1528EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4383 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DOG-AUCTION-NYT &LR;      12-23 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DOG-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOG DAYS FOR SOME WEB CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ala.)   (af)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They call themselves the Ebay 14. While the name may sound like
a group of political prisoners, they are actually a handful of pet
advocates who say they got kicked off of www.ebay.com, the online
auction service, after complaining about the auction of several St.
Bernard puppies this month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 14, with canine-style email names like ``stbernard1'',
``rridgebacks'' and ``rescue'', said they were suspended from the
service for sending messages protesting the auction of the dogs
Dec. 16. Members of the group oppose such auctions because they
think that buying a pet through the Internet is ill-advised. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Complaint: AUCTIONING LIVE ANIMALS IS AGAINST EBAY POLICY,''
wrote one of the suspended members, Deborah Busby of Hoover, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Another person, also suspended, wrote to say: `No responsible
dog-breeder would sell like this. No responsible person would
bid.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The notes were posted on one of the bulletin boards run by
ebay.com to allow comment on the sellers offering goods through the
service.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Chu, a spokeswoman for ebay.com, said her company
permits the animal auctions because they are legal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chu said the members were suspended because they had
violated the site's policy by posting criticisms of a seller with
whom they had not done business.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail to the members informing them of their suspension,
ebay.com said it was taking the step because it believed they had
engaged in a practice called ``feedback bombing,'' in which an
organized effort, often using aliases, is made that lowers the
level of discourse.
</P>
<P>
   Although the writers of the messages said no organized effort
had been made, it appears that some of them learned of the auction
through bulletin boards for people interested in animals.
</P>
<P>
   After issuing the suspensions, ebay.com told the members that
they could be reinstated if they posted a ``positive'' message on
the bulletin board to balance out the earlier negative ones. Ms.
Busby did so _ that is, she checked off the ``positive'' box
provided to rate the seller, but also wrote that she had had not
experience with him _ and her service was restored.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she said, ``I am left with a very bad taste in my
mouth. I don't beleive that I could, in good conscience, support
Ebay by purchasing anything through their site.''
</P>
<P>
   Some animal advocacy groups say they agree that animals should
not be bought through auction. Bob Slay, an American Kennel Club
official, said,``Auctions are bad for dogs, because so often the
dog goes to a home where the new owner has not given sufficient
thought to responsible ownership,'' Slay said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ann Church, senior director of government affairs for the Humane
Society of the United States, was also critical of the
practice.``It goes against what we tell people to do when selecting
a new pet,'' she said. ``It's going to be a member of the family,
and live for 10 to 25 years, depending on the species. It's not
something to do on a whim.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Animal advocates fear that pets bought on line who don't get
along in their new homes will be sent to shelters and euthanized. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For prospective owners, buying on line can also pose problems,
say the advocates. They will not be able to tell how well an animal
is socialized or what health problems it might have. It is also
difficult to verify a pet's pedigree on line or to return an animal
that does not work out.
</P>
<P>
   The American Kennel Club has decided that as of April 1999 it
will not register dogs sold via auction or raffle _ whether on line
or otherwise _ unless they have tattoos or microchips as a form of
permanent identification prior to being sold. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1529EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
