r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORTWORTH-MUSEUM-TEX     12-23 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORTWORTH-MUSEUM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM DESIGN COMES DOWN TO EARTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Tadao Ando's original vision for the Modern
Art Museum of Fort Worth was so radical that it seemed not of this
world. His six concrete boxes encased within glass were stark, but
so beautiful that they captivated almost all who looked at his
drawings and models.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ando's plans have been brought a bit closer to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   His new museum is less radical _ less heavenly, perhaps _ but
still promises to be a building of great beauty and historical
significance. It will show art to astounding advantage, thus
attracting important acquisitions and shows. And it will lure
visitors from around the world, affording an art experience that
will bring them back again and again.
</P>
<P>
   The Osaka, Japan-based Ando was chosen in early 1997 over five
other architects to design a museum that is expected to open in
2002 on a site immediately east of the Kimbell Art Museum. Since
his commission was announced, Ando has worked with the Modern's
building committee and project supervisors to refine his proposal _
to specifically meet the needs of museum staff and programs, as
well as to reduce costs and better accommodate the extremes of
Texas weather.
</P>
<P>
   The design-development process has culminated in a model,
drawings and floor plans that give viewers an idea of what the
facility will be like. Still, changes will continue to occur and,
as they do, the Modern's installation will keep evolving.
</P>
<P>
   Because the installation is geared partly toward members of the
architectural community, some materials might seem a bit dense to
the average viewer. I know they were to me. But patient reading of
floor plans in relation to the model brings out Ando's ideas about
what will be built. At the same time, some changes can be seen by
comparing the latest model with an earlier one.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some things we can anticipate:
</P>
<P>
   A smaller building. Ando's original proposal called for 75,000
square feet of exhibition space _ an awesome amount _ in addition
to back-house space, museum shop, restaurant and auditorium. Now
exhibition space has been reduced to about 53,000 feet, which is
less expensive and more realistic. The new Modern still will be one
of the largest contemporary art museums in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction was partly accomplished by shrinking the overall
plan, which initially called for six linked rectangular modules _
four short and two long _ that formed a sort of chunky L-shape. The
crux of the L would nestle a graceful pond.
</P>
<P>
   Most viewers will notice that one of the short modules has been
deleted, too _ although there is be add it later. The pond remains.
</P>
<P>
   Concrete and glass _ and metal. First, there were modules cast
from poured-in-place concrete, as opposed to pre-cast, encased
within seemingly endless expanses of glass. Glass and concrete have
a primal importance to Ando, who is known worldwide for his
virtuosic work in concrete poured into forms erected on the
building site.
</P>
<P>
   However, Fort Worth's plans may include a few elements of
pre-cast concrete as well as a third material: metal.
</P>
<P>
   Panels of subtly finished metal will flank the glass walls on
either side of the main entrance and will wrap the west corners of
each of the modules. On the museum's north side, the metal will
continue along nearly one-third of the facade. Metal will replace
some glass for a few reasons, one being the scorching Texas sun.
</P>
<P>
   Ando has made metal integral to other projects, including his
Suntory Museum in Osaka. There, metal panels introduce another
texture and another means of enclosure where concrete might have
been too much of a good thing or simply too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   It's debatable whether the use of metal dilutes the aesthetic
integrity or the impact of Ando's initial proposal. But I suspect
that, although the eventual experience of the building will seem
less radical, the quality of the experience will not be diminished.
</P>
<P>
   FLOATING PAVILIONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The north and east facades of the museum, which can be seen
across the pond _ and which appear to be floating on the water _
remain clad in glass. Now, though, instead of being the most
powerful statement of an overall theme _ the concrete boxes inside
glass boxes _ the floating facades become the signature view of the
museum, its unique claim to fame. Other views of the building will
be handsome, no doubt, but they will lack the distinction they
originally had.
</P>
<P>
   CAR PARK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another change that reduces project cost and makes the museum
more mundane is the decision to place parking above ground. Ando's
initial design didn't specify where cars would go: His first model
was surrounded by a grassy park that suggested parking might be
underground. But now a car park, densely planted with trees and
ground cover, will wrap around the west and south sides of the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   INTERIOR ISSUES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ando's team asked Michael Auping, the Modern's senior curator,
to tell them how he wanted galleries arranged. The solution is a
system of movable walls that break Ando's modules (and the spaces
between them) into comfortably proportioned rooms for art.
</P>
<P>
   Two rooms will be 2 stories high, with interior walls of poured
concrete. All other walls will be clad in drywall sheets, with one
crucial exception. From the beginning, Ando has called for an
elliptical gallery adjacent to the museum's grand staircase from
the ground floor to the second floor. Designated as a sculpture
gallery, the room had to be defined by a wall of continuous
concrete if this singular structure was to have any integrity.
</P>
<P>
   THE ENTRY EXPERIENCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The metal panels flanking the museum's glass-walled grand
entrance will allow the new Modern to reveal itself to visitors
more gradually than in Ando's original plans. The entry experience
promises to combine tantalizing views (of the pond, for example)
with easy-to-comprehend options: Visitors will immediately see all
their options, from cafe to lower galleries to restrooms to the
stairs to the second floor.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDUL/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
