<HEADLINE>
IN A BUSY CENTURY, 1998 WILL STAND OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 27)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even though the curtain will descend on 1998 this
week, the tumultuous events of the past few weeks, both here and
abroad, will continue to resound through the new year and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   They will demonstrate the accuracy of those wise words of
William Shakespeare that are etched into the wall of the National
Archives: ``What's past is prologue.''
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment of William Jefferson Clinton by the House of
Representatives was but one act in a long-playing drama that
reached a climax on Dec. 19, but will not reach its denouement
until sometime in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment vote was one of the seminal events of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other president, Andrew Johnson, was impeached by the
House, although the Senate fell one vote short of removing him from
office in 1868. Richard Nixon would have been impeached had he not
resigned in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Repercussions from the impeachment of Clinton as well as from
the upcoming Senate consideration of Clinton's lies and
indiscretions will be felt far into the future.
</P>
<P>
   The strangest aspect of the impeachment pageant is that Clinton
continues to ride high in the public opinion polls, even though he
stands accused of perjury and obstruction of justice. He has
retained a remarkable hold on public approval, while the popularity
of the Republicans has dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow's generations will ask parents and grandparents if they
remember the impeachment of Clinton and where they were when it
happened. Some individuals will try to balance their reminiscences
of that event with recollections that during Clinton's presidency,
the United States enjoyed a period of unparalleled prosperity and
balanced the budget for the first time in 30 years, while the
president helped broker peace deals in Northern Ireland and the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, another matter that will echo through the ages is
the public distrust of politicians in general. Millions of
Americans appear willing to forgive Clinton's bad behavior and even
revelations about the past extramarital affairs of his Republican
accusers, Reps. Henry Hyde of Illinois, Bob Livingston of Louisiana
and Dan Burton of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   But many concede that their faith in their political leaders has
diminished. The unsavory conduct of our pubic leaders has simply
intensified the pessimism that engulfs many Americans when they
look to the White House and Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   There are other events that will spill over into the new year
and possibly beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The troubles with Iraq will not disappear simply because we
battered that country with four days of bomb and missile attacks.
Even though the United States and Britain claim to have damaged the
Iraqi weapons program, Saddam Hussein, the bloody brute of Baghdad,
is certain to cause more trouble in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The decision of Israel's parliament to force a new election
early in 1999 will have an important effect on peace efforts in the
Middle East. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's political future
is in jeopardy as are the accords between the Israelis and the
Palestinians that Clinton helped broker this autumn in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the first seminal event of the 20th century was the
assassination of William McKinley and the ascendancy of Teddy
Roosevelt to the ``bully pulpit'' of the presidency in 1901.
</P>
<P>
   As the surprise leader of a Republican Party that had
demonstrated little social consciousness in the decades since the
Civil War, Roosevelt launched a series of reforms that shocked
party stalwarts but pleased the people. He secured a lasting place
in history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1903, on the beach at Kitty Hawk, N.C., Wilbur and Orville
Wright made the first successful flight of a heavier-than-air,
mechanically-driven airplane. On that first flight, the flying
machine remained aloft for only 12 seconds, but in those 12 seconds
it sparked a brilliant revolution in travel, warfare and
eventually, space exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Revolutions in communications were launched in 1920 with the
first licensed radio broadcast in America and in the 1950s when
television spread to nearly every home.
</P>
<P>
   In 1917, the United States joined World War I and emerged the
following year as a victor and a world power.
</P>
<P>
   History was made in 1933 when Franklin D. Roosevelt was
inaugurated president and unveiled policies to save an America
prostrated by the ravages of the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   There was no more major event in this century than the beginning
of World War II in 1939, the same year that Albert Einstein
informed Roosevelt that it was possible to develop an atomic bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Seminal events of tragic proportions were Adolf Hitler's grasp
of power in Germany in 1933 and Josef Stalin's refusal at the end
of World War II to honor his promise to stage democratic elections
in Poland and other East European nations.
</P>
<P>
   History was made in a colossal way on Dec. 7, 1941, when the
Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor propelled America into World War
II, and again on June 6, 1944, when Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower led
the massive invasion of occupied France.
</P>
<P>
   The world entered the nuclear age on Aug. 6, 1945, when the
first atomic bomb was dropped on Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans remember where they were and what they were doing
on April 12, 1945, when FDR died. Many more remember Nov. 22, 1963,
the day John F. Kennedy was assassinated; Aug. 9, 1974, the day
Nixon resigned; and July 20, 1969, when Neil Armstrong became the
first human to walk on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it is with seminal events. They have a lasting
impact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
