<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With CLINTON-YEAR. FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27.
 &HT;    Eds: If desired, a full set of Clinton approval data is on the
Web at http://www.gallup.com/polltrends/jobapp.htm.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are key dates in President Clinton's year, and the
percentage of Americans who said they approved of the way he was
doing his job in the first Gallup Poll taken after the event.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 21: Washington Post breaks Monica Lewinsky story. (58
percent)
</P>
<P>
   Jan 26: President Clinton says of Lewinsky, ''I did not have
sexual relations with that woman.'' (67 percent)
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 27: Clinton makes his State of the Union address, insisting
that any budget surplus be used to ``save Social Security first.''
(67 percent)
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 23: Under threat of attack by the United States and its
allies, Iraq agrees to let United Nations inspectors have free
access to suspected weapons sites. (63 percent)
</P>
<P>
   March 27: Meets with South African President Nelson Mandela
during six-nation Africa trip. (63 percent)
</P>
<P>
   June 26: President Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin
appear at Beijing's Tiananmen Square in the highlight of Clinton's
visit to China. (61 percent)
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 17: Testifies to Independent Prosecutor Kenneth Starr's
grand jury. Later than night, tells the nation in televised address
that he misled people and that ``I did have a relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky that was not appropriate _ in fact, it was wrong.'' (66
percent)
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 11: Starr's impeachment referral to Congress is released
to Americans on the Internet as Clinton acknowledges in a speech,
``I have sinned.'' (63 percent)
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 21: Clinton receives a standing ovation while addressing
the United Nations General Assembly even as his videotaped
testimony to Starr's grand jury is released by the House. (66
percent)
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 16: President Clinton and congressional leaders hold
separate news conferences on a balanced-budget bill that most
observers said reflected Clinton's priorities. (65 percent)
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 23: Along with Israel's Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and Palestinian Authority head Yasser Arafat, Clinton signs the
land-for-peace Wye Accord at the White House. (65 percent)
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 3: Democrats do better than expected in midterm elections.
(66 percent)
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 6: House Speaker Newt Gingrich announces he will resign
from Congress. (66 percent)
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 14: In Gaza, watches Palestinian leaders renounce
destruction of Israel. (63 percent)
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 19: The House approves two articles of impeachment. (73
percent).
</P>
<P>
   Source: News reports; Gallup Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
