<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4448 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-YEAR-$ADV27-C     12-23 1741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-YEAR-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With CLINTON-DATA. For release Sunday, Dec. 27.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Five days before becoming the first president in
130 years to be impeached, President Clinton traveled to the tiny
desert sliver of Palestinian-controlled Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before Yasser Arafat and about 700 of his followers,
many of them former terrorists, Clinton called on Israelis and
Palestinians to set aside half a century of enmity and bloodshed,
and find within themselves the courage and strength to forgive past
transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   Only then, Clinton said, could both sides move forward and build
their own future on higher ground.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the beginning of mutual respect after so much pain is
to recognize not only the positive characteristics of people on
both sides, but the fact that there has been a lot _ a lot _ of
hurt and harm,'' Clinton said, as first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
and their daughter, Chelsea, looked on. ''The time has come to
sanctify your holy ground with genuine forgiveness and
reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did in so many speeches this year, Clinton was addressing
one conflict, but might as well have been speaking of another.
</P>
<P>
   For in a year dominated by a White House sex-and-deception
scandal that's far from over even now, perhaps no theme has more
closely echoed Clinton's intensely personal journey than the very
public efforts he has made in search of peace and reconciliation
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Whether in South Africa or Northern Ireland, the former
Yugoslavia, the Korean peninsula or the Gaza Strip, virtually every
line Clinton has uttered about the need for political, ethnic or
racial healing has reverberated through his own struggle to regain
the trust, respect and cooperation of his family, friends and
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''These past few months have been a torturous process of coming
to terms with what I did,'' Clinton said two weeks ago in the Rose
Garden. ''Nothing _ not piety, nor tears, nor wit, nor torment _
can alter what I have done. I must make my peace with that.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton has struggled, so has the nation.
</P>
<P>
   For both, the heart of the problem is that Clinton's efforts at
redemption _ the faint-hearted mea-sorta-culpa in August, the
abject supplication before clergy a month later; and even his
post-impeachment plea last weekend on the darkest day of his career
for the country to ''stop the politics of personal destruction'' _
came only after seven long months during which Clinton, in his
words, ''misled'' the nation and those nearest to him, using the
full weight and authority of the highest office in the land.
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate weighs whether to convict him of House charges
that he committed perjury and obstructed justice, it must do so
against the backdrop of a larger question:
</P>
<P>
   Between the day, Jan. 26, when Clinton stood in the Roosevelt
Room, wagged his finger and declared to the world, ''I did not have
sexual relations with that woman, Monica Lewinsky,'' and the day,
Aug. 17, when he announced from the Map Room, ''Indeed, I did have
a relationship with Miss Lewinsky that was not appropriate. In
fact, it was wrong,'' did Clinton so sully his office and so
thoroughly undermine his credibility as to render himself unfit to
continue as president?
</P>
<P>
   With remarkable consistency, the American public has answered
''No.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year in which his approval ratings have held well above
60 percent, his popularity actually surged to record levels
following the Dec. 19 impeachment votes by a House bitterly divided
along partisan lines.
</P>
<P>
   He owes much of his enduring popularity to an economy that
continues to grow after seven and a half years of expansion,
bestowing upon Americans the blessings of the lowest rates of
unemployment, inflation and interest in a quarter of a century.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason, certainly, is that Clinton has succeeded in
persuading the American public that he has been busy trying to
address such kitchen-table concerns as health care, education and
public safety even as he traveled the globe working to advance and
defend the country's economic and security interests.
</P>
<P>
   There has been something else at play, though, in the national
psyche.
</P>
<P>
   At some level, the nation's sense of fairness seemed to be
offended by some Republican's relentless pursuit of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, polls showed a public dismayed by the Republican
insistence on moving forward with impeachment proceedings. Few
seemed to buy the argument that a process characterized by rank
partisanship was truly driven by conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a year in which one political tremor followed
another, it was the Republicans who seemed to bear the brunt of
public scorn for their handling of a scandal of Clinton's making.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have predicted last January that by year's end Clinton
would still be standing, but his congressional nemesis, House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, would not?
</P>
<P>
   And yet it is Gingrich, R-Ga., who is leaving Congress to take
the blame for his party's disappointing showing in the Nov. 3
elections. His party, which some had expected to pick up two dozen
seats in the House, instead lost five.
</P>
<P>
   As if to further underscore the perversity of the political
year, the heir to Gingrich's throne, Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La.,
also resigned after being forced by media inquiries to admit a
string of marital infidelities of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Far from taking seriously Livingston's challenge to follow his
lead and step down, Clinton wound up the year vowing to remain in
office ''until the last hour of the last day of my term,''
asserting that the notion of resignation has ''never crossed my
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   It's now for 100 senators to decide how to rebuke Clinton for
his conduct in the Lewinsky matter. Even before the House stained
his legacy with impeachment, however, Clinton, the office he holds
and the nation he serves had all paid a price.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment the Lewinsky allegations surfaced, Clinton's
every move was viewed, at least in part, according to how it might
affect or be affected by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   It was on the minds of Congress, the press and the public when
Clinton delivered his State of the Union address a few days later,
toured Africa last spring, battled to get the first balanced budget
in three decades through a hostile Congress in October and
campaigned for his fellow Democrats in November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's making it a bit complicated to get the agenda across,''
said Clinton's former spokesman, Michael McCurry, in a stunningly
prophetic piece of understatement last January.
</P>
<P>
   Just last December, weeks before the Lewinsky allegations
surfaced, Clinton gave one of the most illuminating performances of
his career. It was a 100-minute press conference at which he
articulated near-complete mastery of a complex domestic, economic
and international agenda, all but silencing critics who said he was
preparing to stagger somnolently through the remainder of a
lame-duck administration.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, every press conference the president has given this
year has been dominated by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Whether standing alongside Nelson Mandela in Cape Town, Boris
Yeltsin in Moscow, Vaclev Havel in Washington or Kim Dae Jung in
Seoul, Clinton has been pelted with question after question about
his relationship with the former White House intern and his
strategy for avoiding impeachment over it.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was so jarring two weeks ago in Jerusalem that
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel was reduced to pleading
with local reporters, ''as a favor,'' to ask a question about the
imperiled Mideast peace process Clinton had traveled to the region
to try to salvage.
</P>
<P>
   At no time, though, did the scandal and its many ramifications
more thoroughly occlude the message of White House action than when
Clinton launched air strikes against Iraq just 24 hours before the
House was scheduled to begin debate on four impeachment articles.
Three days later, just hours after the House approved two of those
articles, Clinton called off the strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Accusations that Clinton had timed the strikes to offset
impeachment action weren't confined to his political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   A global survey by CNN showed that among U.S. allies and foes
alike, there was a widespread impression abroad that Clinton waged
war on Iraq to throw a public relations smoke screen across
impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of Moscow, CNN reported, 56 percent of this
country's former Cold War adversaries believe Clinton's troubles
with Monica resulted in death and destruction for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton's denials nor those of his national security
team have dimmed that ugly and potentially dangerous perception of
U.S. foreign policy goals, pointing to a fresh challenge for the
White House in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the strains with the press and Congress, beyond the views
from afar, perhaps the greatest toll the year of scandal has taken
has been on Clinton's overarching goal of bringing the nation
together as one. Above all else, that is the vision that carried
the young Arkansas governor to the White House six years ago. That
was the promise of the man from Hope.
</P>
<P>
   As he looks out over the country today, Clinton can't be
encouraged to see how his own conduct has polarized the land. For
while his popularity has survived the scandal, Americans are deeply
divided over how to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   In an ABC News/Washington Post poll of 1,285 adults nationwide
on Dec. 19 and 20 _ the day of, and the day after the House
impeachment vote _ 59 percent said Clinton should not have been
impeached; 40 percent said he should have been.
</P>
<P>
   That suggests that Clinton and the Senate have a long way to go
in trying to build a consensus for a way to move forward toward
higher ground.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's hope, perhaps his guiding star, is that others will
ultimately regard him as a man who, despite his complexities and
flaws, has learned at last to lead with his better instincts in a
journey he concedes is far from complete.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we had to wait for perfection, none of us would ever
advance in any way,'' Clinton said early this month, in a speech on
human rights that, like so many others, held meaning in a parallel
context.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one,'' said Clinton, ''has a corner on the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
