A4451 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX     12-23 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IAN MOORE GOT OVER THE BLUES _ AND HE'S A HAPPIER MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hey, when are you going to play some blues, dude?''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Moore gets that a lot, usually from some guy with beer on
his breath and attitude to spare. He paid his $15 or so and he
wanted to hear the sort of deep-fried, guitar-solo-stuffed sounds
that Moore made his name with, first as a hired hand with Joe Ely
and then as a solo artist who released two CDs on Capricorn
Records.
</P>
<P>
   And Moore didn't give it to him, isn't going to give it to him
and doesn't much care if not giving it to him means that Mr.
Blueshound won't come back.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Moore was going to be a guitar hero and play long solos all
night long; it's what everybody wanted except, well, him. And so he
doesn't do it anymore, opting instead to offer up a highly eclectic
acoustic/electric mix of rock, folk, gospel and ambient sounds, and
shows that feature instruments such as violin, melodica and
bouzouki. With a little blues thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   That has cost him his contract with Capricorn _ the label, he
says, just couldn't fathom that he didn't want to be the next
Stevie Ray Vaughan. It's also meant he's had to form his own label,
Hablador, to put out his third studio CD, the recent ``Ian Moore's
Got the Green Grass.''
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, it means he sometimes faces heckling and booing at
his concerts.
</P>
<P>
   But he says it's also made him a much happier man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that I can grow and change,'' says Moore, speaking from
his home on an island in Washington state, an ``inspirational
space'' where he moved this past June. Right now, he says, he's
looking at a seal sunning itself on some rocks. ``That's what I
want. I'm an artist. I'm a musician. Is someone else better able to
decide what I should play? Give me a little credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore released two studio CDs, in 1993 and 1995, and did fairly
well, opening for the Rolling Stones and Bob Dylan. His star was on
the rise _ or, at least, it looked that way from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   The truth was, he says, that he was lacking in confidence and
wanted to make an even more eclectic CD than '95's ``Modernday
Folklore,'' which included a bunch of folk, psychedelia, soul and
gospel touches.
</P>
<P>
   Capricorn, he says, was unhappy about that direction and
underpromoted the CD. He didn't feel appreciated or understood, and
when, in 1997, he turned in his third CD, the label rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost went to blows over this,'' he says. ``I saw myself
as making a Southern Gothic thing, and they freaked out. I wasn't
doing what they were telling me _ how dare I go against their
wishes? The end was last winter, and it was pretty messy.''
</P>
<P>
   He and the label parted ways, and he looked for a deal elsewhere
_ only to find that nobody would sign him for what he thought he
was worth. He was scared to do his own CD, but singer/songwriter
David Garza urged him to give it a try, and meeting producer Mark
Addison finally convinced him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of things I wasn't allowed to express on CD
before,'' he says. ``I never had support for this material; Mark
gave me a lot of support.''
</P>
<P>
   So he cut ``Green Grass,'' a CD that goes off in a lot of
directions; there's folk-blues on ``Paris, Texas,'' acoustic guitar
and strings on ``Airplane,'' some
light-alternative-meets-the-Beatles rock via ``Pennyroyal Tea,''
and some nice covers of Terry Allen's ``Border Palace,'' the
Beatles' ``Hey Bulldog'' and Dylan's ``You're a Big Girl Now.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore is very proud of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CD is very unfiltered,'' he says. ``On `Folklore,' I did a
Curtis Mayfield-ish song and a Stevie Wonder-ish song. You could
see me open up creatively. This is a logical next step from that.
I've always written country and pop and gospel songs, and the label
was never interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm changing my fans one by one, but it's a slow process,'' he
says. ``When I went out on tour, I confronted all the people who
want me to pick up my Strat and solo on every song. I've lost
people, but I've also gained people who are like, `This is what
you're about.' It's great to feel you're doing something good and
have confidence in it. It's almost cooler when people don't get it.
At least it's really me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
