<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4456 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TV24-COX     12-23 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    C-SPAN ASKS SENATE TO ALLOW TV COVERAGE OF CLINTON TRIAL
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ C-SPAN urged Senate leaders Wednesday to update the
130-year-old rules on conducting an impeachment trial to allow
gavel-to-gavel television coverage of any proceedings against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1868 impeachment trial of President Andrew Johnson _ the
only such case in the nation's history _ the Senate decided that
all debate on procedural matters as well as on the ultimate
question of guilt or innocence would take place behind closed
doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the Senate makes preparations for a trial of the president,
we urge it to adopt rules that will keep this process open to the
public,'' Brian Lamb, chairman of the public affairs cable TV
network, said in a letter to Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Specifically, we formally request that the Senate permit
televised coverage of its deliberations after the evidence has been
presented by the parties,'' Lamb urged. Copies of the letter were
sent to Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., and other senators who
will be instrumental in establishing the rules of a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules modified only slightly since 1868, the final
deliberations and vote would be closed to the public. In addition,
the Senate could vote to hear testimony from witnesses in closed
session. Some members have raised this possibility to avoid a media
circus should Monica Lewinsky, Linda Tripp or other controversial
high-profile witnesses be called.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in the rules that requires that all the
witnesses be heard in open session,'' Sen. Mitch McConnell said in
an appearance on the NBC program ``Meet the Press'' on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we actually end up having to hear from some of the more
infamous witnesses we're now all too familiar with, there's no
prohibition under the Senate rules from hearing those witnesses in
closed sessions,'' McConnell said. ``This will not be a spectacle.
It will not demean the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1868 rules require that ``the doors of the Senate shall be
kept open'' during most of the trial unless there is a motion ``to
close the doors.'' If there were no objection to the motion, the
Senate would go into closed session. If there were an objection, a
vote would be taken with a simple majority determining the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, TV cameras were first installed in the Senate
chamber in 1974 for the possible trial of President Nixon, who
resigned rather than face impeachment, according to Congressional
Quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN 2 has provided complete live coverage of every Senate
legislative session since June 2, 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb, who established the C-SPAN networks that cover Congress
with funding from the cable television industry, urged the Senate
leaders not to turn off the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hopeful the Senate will choose not to interrupt the
public's ability to witness every step their elected
representatives take in the process that will determine whether the
president remains in office,'' Lamb wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
