. 
The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
CIVIL-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``A Civil Action,'' taken from
Jonathan Harr's absorbing, nonfiction book about a
precedent-setting pollution trial, is a far cry from the silly
melodramatics we're accustomed to in John Grisham courtroom movies.
The film is an admirably serious and intelligent look at the legal
system. Unfortunately, it's a very complicated, very tedious legal
system. 2 { Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
HURLY-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ After enduring the torrent of
pretentious chatter in ``Hurlyburly,'' you will want to lock
yourself in a closet for a month just to give your ears a rest.
It's that bad. 1 star. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
STEPMOM-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Contrived, manipulative and
possessing the emotional depth of a Furby, ``Stepmom'' nevertheless
manages to work the audience's tear ducts. 2 stars. By Bob
Strauss. 
. 
PATCH-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Though supposedly a true story about
an irrepressible clown who upsets medical conventions by trying to
heal through laughter, ``Patch Adams'' doesn't feel honest for a
second. 2 stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
MIGHTY-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Kids should be enchanted and amused
by this pleasant, undemanding remake of ``Mighty Joe Young.'' 2 {
Star. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
DELTA-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Sometimes, good for you can be kind of
good. That's the case with ``Down in the Delta,'' which is
basically the kind of finger-wagging problem film that's meant to
instruct more than entertain. 3 Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
