<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE-FOR-ALL PARENTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christmas shopping can be the shovel that digs you into the tomb
of debt. That's why I put a lot of careful thought into the gifts I
buy my family.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I got a great deal on this electronic gadget for my
sister. It's a cellular phone with a rotary dial. It's pretty
compact, so you have to use a toothpick in the finger holes, but it
came with a lovely cotton carrying case.
</P>
<P>
   See, not only did I save money on the phone, but ultimately, my
sister will save money, too. I figure that by the time she dials
10-10-324-777555666222 - 1 - AC, she'll forget who she was trying
to call. Those cell phone bills get outrageous if you're the
talkative type.
</P>
<P>
   I have a cellular phone for work and emergencies, but I keep it
in the trunk of my car so I'm not tempted to yak on it while idling
in traffic. I tried just going with a pager, but I could never find
a convenient pay phone, and if I did, I never had the correct
change.
</P>
<P>
   The convenience stores wouldn't give me change unless I bought
something. After purchasing 100 packages of gum, I figured it would
be cheaper just to buy a phone. If I have to make a call, I keep it
as brief as possible. ``It's me. Kid sick. Fever. Buy Tylenol.
Liquid. Cherry. Love.'' Click.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, this is the time of the year that we strengthen our
bonds with the family, a little quality time. I am determined to
become more than an ornament to my two boys before this holiday
season is over. Toward that end, I've rented a terrific video
called, ``Wrestling For Moms'' or ``Hugging With An Attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   My young guys have called a total moratorium on hand holding,
hugs and kisses. When I walk in the door after work, all I get is,
``Hi, Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   When my husband comes home, it's a totally different story:
``Dad's home! Let's get him!''
</P>
<P>
   They pile on their father as soon as he walks in the door, and
then it's a free-for-all until they break something, usually
something that I cherish. So I figure that if I learn to wrestle,
maybe I can get in on the action. I feel so left out sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   I tried it once before, but my technique wasn't very good. They
pinned me in about 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, you gotta say `Uncle,' '' my oldest son ordered as he
tried to shove my right foot into my left ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncle,'' I groaned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say, `Uncle Fester,' '' my youngest son commanded while he
pinned my arms to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncle Fester!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Say, `Uncle Fester has a big boo boo head.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys! If you two don't get up off me, I'm going to ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, you're no fun. Dad never gives up.''
</P>
<P>
   That was pretty humiliating coming from a 3-year-old and a
5-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Well, a few years have passed, and I've been watching those guys
and a little ``WD-40,'' or whatever that wrestling program is
called, and now I'm ready.
</P>
<P>
   But first, I've got just a little more shopping to do. I need
three AAA batteries and a box of toothpicks to go with that phone
for my sister. I'll let you know how the big match with the boys
goes next time.
</P>
<P>
   Now, shop 'til you drop. Only six more days until Christmas!
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
