<HEADER>
A4466 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURLY-REVIEW-LADN     12-23 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURLY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HURLYBURLY'LIP SERVICE TO BEING MEANINGFUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 1 Star 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In ``Hurlyburly,'' Sean Penn's cocaine-addicted,
loser casting agent has a habit of finishing every one of his
endless, run-on prattlings with the words ``blah blah blah.'' The
trait wouldn't be so annoying if anything that came before the
``blah blah blah'' was articulate, smart or even interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, about an hour into this pseudo-intellectual exercise in
``truth-telling,'' everything uttered by the featured group of
misogynistic poseurs starts to blur together like watercolors left
to dry in a rainstorm. By the time it ends (and believe me, you
must possess remarkable patience in order to remain in your seat),
it all starts to sound like ``blah blah blah.'' And after enduring
the movie's torrent of pretentious chatter, you will want to lock
yourself in a closet for a month just to give your ears a rest.
It's that bad.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Hurlyburly,'' David Rabe has adapted his 1984 off-Broadway
play for the screen, whittling it down from three hours to a more
concise but still tortuous two hours of navel gazing,
self-absorption and phoniness.
</P>
<P>
   None of the characters feel real, and even though they're all
superficially different in a one-note sort of way, the psychobabble
that comes out of their mouths seems all of one piece. Meg Ryan's
stripper (!) spews the same claptrap as the movie's misanthropic
men. In that respect, ``Hurlyburly'' could just as well have been a
one-man show. Certainly it wouldn't have been any less tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is centered around the Hollywood Hills home occupied
by Penn's Eddie and his detached partner, Mickey (Kevin Spacey), a
man who feels nothing and readily demonstrates that absence of
conscience whenever possible. Among their friends _ and friendship
is defined a little differently by this group _ are a thuggish,
wanna-be actor (Chazz Palminteri) fond of throwing women out of
speeding cars and a smarmy screenwriter named Artie (Garry
Shandling) who courts favor with his pals by dropping 13-year-old
hitchhikers (Anna Paquin) off as ``care packages.'' (``Consider her
a pet,'' Artie says.)
</P>
<P>
   Through all the drugs and swearing and instances of statutory
rape, Eddie desperately tries to make sense of his world. He has a
girlfriend, Darlene (Robin Wright Penn), but has a tough time
believing she really cares for him, particularly after she has a
one-night stand with Mickey. Eddie's biggest problem, though, is
his self-hatred _ that and the fact that during a typical day he
ingests enough drugs to kill the population of a small nation.
</P>
<P>
   None of the characters' whining leads anywhere, which makes
sitting through the the film's two-hour length all the more
frustrating. There are no revelations, no discoveries, no insights
into the human condition. All we have is a bunch of disgusting men
(and masculine women) behaving very badly for no apparent reason.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that ``Hurlyburly'' is a complete mess, it
isn't hard to figure out why such a stellar group of actors became
involved. With its long, inflated stretches of dialogue, this is
the ultimate vehicle for anyone who likes to hear the sound of his
own voice. But if you're trapped watching the movie, it's like
being stuck in the corner of some godawful party, held prisoner by
the ramblings of a self-important windbag.
</P>
<P>
   Blah, blah, blah, indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1618EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4468 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVIL-REVIEW-LADN     12-23 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIL-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HARD CASE TO MAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2 { Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``A Civil Action,'' taken from Jonathan Harr's
absorbing, nonfiction book about a precedent-setting pollution
trial, is a far cry from the silly melodramatics we're accustomed
to in John Grisham courtroom movies.
</P>
<P>
   The film is an admirably serious and intelligent look at the
legal system. Unfortunately, it's a very complicated, very tedious
legal system.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here isn't that adapter-director Steven Zaillian
loses us in the details of what was a drawn-out, highly technical
case against two large corporations. The legal issues, and even the
eye-glazing scientific evidence, is presented clearly enough.
What's wrong is that Zaillian, who wrote the screenplay for
``Schindler's List'' and made his directing debut with the
well-regarded ``Searching for Bobby Fischer,'' fails to engage us
with the material.
</P>
<P>
   The book may be harder to digest than the movie, but it is
correspondingly more interesting as well. In his desire to be
accessible, Zaillian oversimplifies the story, resulting in a film
that rarely delves below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   John Travolta's lead performance is like the movie itself:
deceptively rich until you realize that it really isn't. He plays
personal injury attorney Jan Schlichtmann, a well-dressed,
oily-haired, Porsche-speeding operator who revels in his
disreputable, avaricious professionalism. He gleefully defends his
ambulance-chasing ways on local radio talk shows, and claims to
enjoy his status as one of Boston's most eligible bachelors.
</P>
<P>
   We'll have to take his word on that last one, though, since one
of the film's big failings is that it never reveals anything about
Schlichtmann's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, he's initially reluctant to take on the case of eight
grieving, working-class families in Woburn, Mass., who believe
polluted drinking water was responsible for the high rate of
leukemia among their children.
</P>
<P>
   The parties most likely responsible _ if, indeed, their
responsibility can be proved _ are small manufacturing concerns.
Schlichtmann's own little firm needs big pockets to go after, since
they're the type of lawyers who work on contingency and, in fact,
would have to invest loads of their own money to work up the kind
of evidence the case would require.
</P>
<P>
   But then Schlichtmann discovers that the offending businesses
are subsidiaries of giant conglomerates W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. and
Beatrice Foods. Fueled by greed and arrogance, he commits his firm
to taking on the big boys. And he could just beat them _ except, at
the most inopportune moment, the killer litigator grows a heart.
</P>
<P>
   This is doubly bad news, since Schlichtmann's main opponent is
an eccentric but ruthless old legal crocodile played by a serenely
sinister Robert Duvall, who steals every scene as effortlessly as
his character steals every advantage. The movie's other great
performance comes from the always-reliable William H. Macy, who
plays the Schlichtmann firm's resourceful but increasingly frazzled
financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Zaillian is at his best when detailing how the good little
lawyers lose everything in their increasingly lopsided
confrontation with the big guns. He's less successful at
delineating why Schlichtmann changes from a shrewd strategist into
an obsessive crusader. Indeed, some of his moves in the movie,
though clearly designed to evoke Schlichtmann's ethical redemption,
just make him look stupid.
</P>
<P>
   That may be the only thing ``A Civil Action'' has in common with
a Grisham film. But it's not a good thing to have in common with
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1618EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4469 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS-YEAREND-$ADV27-     12-23 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS-YEAREND-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR STORIES, ON THE BEACH AND IN THE HOME  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `SAVING PRIVATE RYAN' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg took the enormous risk of recreating the
experience of World War II combat and reminding contemporary
audiences of all the patriotism, shock and horrific sacrifice that
it entailed. And in a film year otherwise devoted to the darkest
visions of American life, he touched a long-buried, fundamental
nerve.
</P>
<P>
   This wrenchingly visceral war epic was also a bravura visual
achievement, with the swiftness and economy of its storytelling and
the terrifying, furious immediacy of its battles. Audiences were
rightly stunned by so fierce and meaningful a re-examination of the
American character under fire. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `HAPPINESS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Todd Solondz turned out to be no mean stunner himself. His
merrily outrageous, expertly written ensemble piece was a true
original, able to achieve the most perverse insights with unnerving
empathy, and without the slightest straining for effect.
</P>
<P>
   This filmmaker seems to come naturally by the skewed,
murderously funny world view that yielded the biggest and best of
the year's pitch-black comedies. And his wicked screenplay plumbed
the collective misery of its lonely characters with dazzling
finesse. As structurally elegant as it was taboo-shattering,
``Happiness'' arrived at just the right moment.
</P>
<P>
   The worst excesses of tabloid culture paled before Solondz's
matter-of-fact glimpses of family life. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE BUTCHER BOY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delving into the mind of a troubled young hero might have been
solemn business from a filmmaker less imaginatively offbeat than
the director of ``The Crying Game.'' But Neil Jordan filled this
study of the boy's disintegrating sanity, based on Patrick McCabe's
equally daring novel, with ever more chilling ebullience as it
began to inhabit the boy's mind.
</P>
<P>
   Brilliantly juxtaposing external and subjective reality, Jordan
created a wildly fanciful mental landscape within a workaday Irish
town and melted the boundaries between madness and reason to
electrifying effect. Eamonn Owens, whose only previous
international exposure had been marching with his youth band in New
York's St. Patrick's Day parade, gave an unforgettably blistering
performance in the central role. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `HENRY FOOL' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   None of Hal Hartley's earlier films matched the ambitions of
this deft cultural allegory, with its wry tale of art and fame in a
tug of war. Minimalist in style yet sweeping in vision, Hartley's
story centered on a Queens janitor with a resemblance to a young
Samuel Beckett and a previously untapped genius for rousing the
populace with his written word.
</P>
<P>
   When he fell into the hands of a literary shaman with enough
overweening pretensions for the two of them, Hartley had a field
day with the possibilities. Beautifully meticulous despite the
occasional needless gross-out, it featured Parker Posey at her most
divinely petulant and the best of this filmmaker's shrewdly deadpan
style. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mischievously literate Elizabethans, hilarious backstage farce
and the sultry teamwork of Joseph Fiennes and Gwyneth Paltrow (as
passionate prototypes for Romeo and Juliet) made this the most
enchanting entertainment of the year. With a sparkling screenplay
by Tom Stoppard and Marc Norman, John Madden's film had the
temerity to speculate about Shakespeare's life on the basis of his
work. Rarely has such presumptuousness paid off so shamelessly
well. Amid a splendid supporting cast, the stars shone even more
brightly than Sandy Powell's spectacular costumes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `A SIMPLE PLAN' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sleeper of the year, this finely calibrated thriller brought
out the best in Scott Smith's novel about the poisonous effects of
a windfall on small-town characters in a stark, snowbound setting.
Its biggest surprise, beyond the way Bill Paxton and Billy Bob
Thornton outshone even their acting collaboration in ``One False
Move,'' was the transition made by Sam Raimi from cult horror films
to such adroit, subtle storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Modest as it looked, this drama built inexorable momentum as it
weighed the consequences of its characters' every misstep, and
created a shockingly smooth continuum between good and evil. The
stars, cast as brothers, played their last scene together like the
instant classic that it is. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE CELEBRATION' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Vinterberg made this boisterous Danish film under an
exacting set of creative restrictions, which made its freewheeling
brio that much more triumphant. The camera swiveled and soared
through an elaborate family reunion, with a skeleton in every
closet and an irrepressibly robust quality to the whole gathering.
</P>
<P>
   For its sheer vigor without tricks, stunts, makeup or fancy
lighting, Vinterberg's film was a refreshing change and a
remarkable achievement. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BULWORTH' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a year that cried out for political satire, Warren Beatty
delivered one with sharp claws. He played a senator driven to
despair by his own lack of conviction until, uproariously, candor
set him free. If the idea of a 60-year-old white rapper raised a
few hackles, it also embodied the anything-goes spirit that turned
a potentially broad, partisan comedy into a bona fide breath of
fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty's panache, vaporized in films like ``Love Affair,'' made
a welcome re-emergence. And Oliver Platt's supporting turn (as a
slick aide trying to keep the senator looking respectable) was one
of the funniest performances of the year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE OPPOSITE OF SEX' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Family values, 1998-style, as Christina Ricci's evil minx
exploited everyone in her path. Sour as this show of nonstop
cynicism appeared, it made for an unexpectedly generous,
conciliatory comedy from the writer-director Don Roos, not to
mention a delectably funny one. And it delivered some of the year's
most knowing ideas about the making of sexual connections in these
endlessly complicated times, as it intermingled gay and straight
characters, innocent and scheming ones, with fearless aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ricci and Lisa Kudrow were outstanding as diametrically
opposed characters trading acid-dipped repartee. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `WESTERN' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Major themes and high drama were nowhere to be found in this
misleadingly titled French road movie. But its humor and
tenderness, combined with the slyest of deadpan timing, made it one
of the high points of my moviegoing experience this year. Shot in
wide-screen format amid a series of tranquil Brittany landscapes,
it watched two gentle drifters form a rueful friendship, explore
their surroundings and try amusingly and dismally to beguile women.
It's on this list only because I smile at the memory of it and
remember every frame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1619EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
