<HEADER>
A4477 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIGHTY-REVIEW-LADN     12-23 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIGHTY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MIGHTY JOE' YOUNG AT HEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2{ Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This pleasant, undemanding remake of ``Mighty Joe
Young'' plays like ``Free Willy'' with fur.
</P>
<P>
   The new version of the 1949 kiddie favorite gives the
giant-ape-on-the-loose-in-L.A. story line an eco-conscious gloss.
This time, the 15-foot gorilla isn't shipped over from his African
homeland to headline a cheap vaudeville show; he's shipped over to
be the star attraction at a nature conservancy park. It's not
irresponsible drunks but evil poachers (Rade Sherbedgia _ who used
to call himself Serbedzija _ and Peter Firth) who get Big Joe all
riled-up and loose on Hollywood Boulevard this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Paxton is the compassionate white hunter/zoologist and
Charlize Theron is the beautiful white jungle girl who are Joe's
best friends. She and Joe both lost their mothers when they were
little primates _ courtesy of those same evil poachers, in a
sequence that owes a lot to Spielberg's ``The Lost World'' _ and
their bond, as fundamentally hokey as it may be, is genuinely
touching.
</P>
<P>
   Joe himself is a pretty cuddly creation. Slicker than the
stop-motion puppet created in 1949 by Willis O'Brien and Ray
Harryhausen (the latter, along with original ``Joe'' heroine Terry
Moore, makes a nice little cameo appearance in the new movie), the
new 2,000-pound gorilla is a state-of-the-art creation. Designed by
five-time Oscar winner Rick Baker, who has excelled at the hairy
thing in the likes of ``Greystoke'' and ``Gorillas in the Mist,''
the new Joe is a seamlessly expressive blend of animatronics,
computer graphics and guys in monkey suits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as in the first film, it's impossible to believe that
this lovable lumberer actually frightens the citizens of Los
Angeles while he avoids a small army of cops. Unlike O'Brien's more
indelible creation King Kong, Joe has never generated the tragedy
and terror that his big brother unleashed. He still doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Ron Underwood, who made ``City Slickers.'' He
does his best to prevent this thoroughly Disneyfied remake from
seeming more silly than it is. Of course, it wouldn't be ``Mighty
Joe Young'' if it wasn't goofy, so it's just as well that Underwood
didn't succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Kids should be enchanted and amused, and that's all this junior
varsity film fable should ever aspire to anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
