<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4479 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-YEAREND-ART-$AD     12-23 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-YEAREND-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TITAN PASSES; PROVOCATIONS ABOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27)  
 (Eds: Please note subslug for ROBBINS-DANCE)  
 (af)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEROME ROBBINS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the titans, Robbins was arguably the most original of
choreographers. He regarded the New York City Ballet as a
continuing experiment, and his death in July robs the company of a
major creative voice that influenced its profile for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Michel Fokine, George Balanchine, Antony Tudor and
Frederick Ashton, Robbins was one of the 20th century's greatest
ballet choreographers; he was not just the greatest American-born
ballet choreographer. Nonetheless, he was American and his genius
distilled the mood of his times, no matter how obliquely. His
achievement on Broadway was brilliant, but his most profound
commitment was to ballet. Robbins's gift was for the startling
image with the ring of truth. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MATTHEW BOURNE'S `SWAN LAKE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The marketing of this ``Swan Lake'' as a Broadway show rather
than a dance production will go down in the annals of hype as a
classic attempt at tomfoolery. Cameron Mackintosh, the producer
behind Bourne's modern-dress version, mounted a
ballet-is-boring-but-this-is-different campaign. Poppycock.
</P>
<P>
   Bourne has done a perfectly good job at a polished
entertainment, but it is no more original than other updated and
rechoreographed 19th- and 20th-century classics. Remember Mats Ek's
``Giselle'' in an insane asylum, Maguy Marin's ``Coppelia'' in a
housing project, Mark Morris's 1960s ``Nutcracker'' (``The Hard
Nut''), Angelin Preljocaj's ``Romeo and Juliet'' along the Berlin
Wall, and so on?
</P>
<P>
   And boring was not exactly the word for Rudolf Nureyev and
Margot Fonteyn, who drenched every ``real'' ``Swan Lake'' in
passion. By the way, many dance companies have performed on
Broadway. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ETHAN STIEFEL AND ANGEL CORELLA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the good news department, 1998 saw the artistic breakthrough
of these two already superb dancers. Different in style, both often
appeared in the same roles at American Ballet Theater. There was
astonishing depth, thanks reportedly to Kevin McKenzie's coaching,
in each dancer's debut as Albrecht in ``Giselle'' at the
Metropolitan Opera house. In ``Le Corsaire,'' Stiefel reached the
level of powerhouse technique that had previously eluded him while
Corella's natural virtuosity exploded into a higher dimension. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `FASE,' BY ANNE TERESA DE KEERSMAEKER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Belgian experimental choreographer's 1982 piece to Steve
Reich's music received a stunning revival at the Kitchen. In this
tour de force, minimalist structures pack expressionist wallop.
Form generates meaning here: rigor, repetition and reductive
movement converge into complex layers, giving this seminal piece a
direct emotional impact. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIRSKY UKRAINIAN NATIONAL DANCE COMPANY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For sheer dance power, there is nothing like a first-class
professional folk company from the former Soviet Union. Pavel
Virsky, who died in 1975, founded this troupe in Kiev in 1937. The
company, performing at City Center, came back with its astonishing
virtuosity intact. A new crop of young male dancers contributed
larger-than-life bravura. These were performers to appreciate as
great dancers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE VERTIGINOUS THRILL OF EXACTITUDE,' BY WILLIAM FORSYTHE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A short, plotless ballet, danced superbly at City Center by the
San Francisco Ballet, ``Thrill'' was, in this view, the season's
best ballet. It is a brilliant outburst of neo-classical style. The
music is not electronic, as expected from Forsythe, but by
Schubert, and the classical footwork, dynamically enhanced, focuses
on changes in speed and direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eidos: Telos,'' the full-evening work that Forsythe presented
with his Ballett Frankfurt at the Brooklyn Academy, is a more
typical experience, with its radical theatrics and dislocated
movement. ``Thrill'' takes us into a higher level of invention. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VAGANOVA BALLET ACADEMY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a historical first, there was the United States debut of 65
pupils from the training ground for the Kirov Ballet in St.
Petersburg, Russia. Americans have seen classroom demonstrations
and performances presented by the schools of the Bolshoi Ballet and
the Paris Opera Ballet. The Vaganova students, more disciplined
among the girls than the boys, offered a close-up at the Brooklyn
Academy of Music of the classical style that has developed in the
fountainhead of Russian ballet. A handful of Kirov stars were
guests.
</P>
<P>
   The continuity from classroom to stage was thus made evident and
a joint appearance with the School of American Ballet made another
link: George Balanchine founded the American school and graduated
from the Russian one. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EIFMAN BALLET &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Love him or hate him, Boris Eifman proved a revelation as a
choreographer. ``Red Giselle'' and ``Tchaikovsky,'' which the
Eifman Ballet from St. Petersburg presented in its New York debut
at City Center, showed a creative side to Russian choreography that
Americans have not seen. To call Eifman a Russian counterpart to
Kenneth MacMillan at the Royal Ballet is to suggest a similar
interest in narrative studies of character, warts and all.
</P>
<P>
   Much more significant is Eifman's expressive rendering of ballet
technique. One forgives the provocative simplicities of his
scenarios; one admires the extraordinary passion of his work and
his dancers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TWYLA THARP'S `KNOWN BY HEART' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This work for American Ballet Theater is too gripping and too
good to be overlooked because, at first glance, it seems imperfect.
The shifts in music (Mozart, the percussionist Donald Knaack and
Steve Reich) are deliberate and there may be method to the overlong
Reich section. The choreography as a whole dazzles with its
outpouring of invention, especially its gleaming classicism for
Julie Kent and Angel Corella and the startling bravura for Ethan
Stiefel and his witty partner, Susan Jaffe. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `LA MORT DU CYGNE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This unearthed treasure, a 1937 French feature film by Jean
Benoit-Levy, hauntingly evokes the Paris Opera Ballet on the eve of
World War II. Under the auspices of the French Institute/Alliance
Francaise, Yvette Chauvire, Janine Charrat and Mia Slavenska
movingly discussed their youthful roles in this rarely seen movie.
A masterpiece like this deserves more than a single screening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1621EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
