<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4519 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEINEM-UPDATE-ANTI-I     12-23 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEINEM-UPDATE-ANTI-IMPEACHMENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTEST THE IMPEACHMENT CHARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By GLORIA STEINEM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It is time to register outraged and principled opposition to the
impeachment charade now going on in Washington.
 &HT;    We know that the huge majority opposes President Clinton's
impeachment. Too often, the press has attributed this irrefutable
fact, which is shown clearly in the public-opinion polls, to some
notion of economic comfort, as if Clinton were being supported only
out of the selfishness created by a good economy.
 &HT;    In fact, those who support Clinton the MOST are those who
benefit from our economy the LEAST.
 &HT;    Opposition to impeachment exists because people around the
country are smart enough to know that ``Impeach Clinton'' and even
``Impeach Hillary'' bumper stickers have been sported and sold ever
since the Clintons entered the White House, by many of the same
right-wing groups who now stand for his impeachment.
 &HT;    People are smart enough to figure out that the Congress members
voting for impeachment have a suspiciously high correlation to
those owned by such obsessed minority lobbies as the tobacco
industry, the National Rifle Association and anti-abortion
organizations _ all sworn enemies of Clinton and his majoritarian
policies.
 &HT;    Do I agree with all of Clinton's policies? Of course not. I'll
never forgive him for signing the welfare bill. I'm proud of the
National Organization for Women and other women's groups who staged
a hunger strike outside the White House in the vain hope of
dissuading him.
 &HT;    But I also know that he has stood for equal economic and human
rights far more than the so-called Republican opponents _ and I
know what interests that angers.
 &HT;    I also know that even if President Reagan or President Bush had
been guilty of the same sexual misjudgment _ and then tried to
conceal it _ I wouldn't have supported their impeachment either.
Indeed, when the right-wing congressman Bob Bauman (of Maryland)
was accused of a sexual episode with a young man, the only question
I and other feminists asked was: Was this welcome sex or not?
Because if it was welcome, then it wasn't sexual harassment. And it
wasn't our business.
 &HT;    My fear is that the right wing is distorting and defeating
sexual-harassment law in much the same way that they have tried to
distort and defeat affirmative-action law.
 &HT;    Remember, these are the same folks who opposed sexual-harassment
law in the first place. Phyllis Schlafly testified in Congress
against it and insisted that if women just dressed and behaved like
ladies, they wouldn't have this problem.
 &HT;    But now, the right wing is trying to use its version of the law
to peacefully assassinate a president. In the process, they have
convinced more than 60 percent of Americans that sexual-harassment
law has gone too far; that it forbids all sex in the workplace, all
sex between unequals, even all sex outside of marriage _ none of
which it does or should do.
 &HT;    In fact, sexual-harassment law has nothing to do with welcome
sex. The use of the word ``welcome'' is an innovation of this law.
``Consent'' can be coerced. ``Welcomeness'' cannot. It's the
religious right wing that is the Ayatollah here, not the creators
and supporters of sexual-harassment law.
 &HT;    Bill Clinton should not have had to testify about Monica
Lewinsky at all. The enjoyment of mutually welcome sex does not
constitute a ``pattern and practice'' of unwelcome sex. Unequal
status may be an index of suspicion, but it is not dispositive, as
lawyers say. We who support sexual-harassment law are not the sex
police. Any idea that this law allows such policing will only
defeat a good and much-needed statute.
 &HT;    We should also call for an end to the humiliation of Monica
Lewinsky. This young woman broke no law, yet found herself
surrounded by FBI agents and denied access to her own lawyer. She
has been forced to reveal the most intimate details of her private
life _ under threat of her own imprisonment, and even the
imprisonment of her mother.
 &HT;    We owe it to her and ourselves to protest against the jokes,
humiliation and ridicule she has suffered. She has the right to
privacy, sexual expression and legal protection _ and if she does
not, neither do we.
 &HT;    We should also admit that we may be projecting our own
experience. For example, I have two women friends who were sexually
abused by their fathers. They have a hard time believing that
Monica could have been there voluntarily. I know another woman who
was done in by a faithless husband. Clinton's example hits a
bruise, and she reacts with pain and anger. I've been lucky enough
to have neither experience, and so can believe that Monica was
there voluntarily.
 &HT;    I don't even believe that power is the ultimate aphrodisiac.
When I was Monica's age, Eisenhower was president. I wouldn't have
gone to bed with Eisenhower, would you? I rest my case.
 &HT;    It's clear that many men and some women in the media hate
Clinton for reasons of the culture wars, even though they agree
with him on issues more than I do. It drives them crazy that
Clinton has won the most powerful position in the world without the
proper ``masculine'' behavior.
 &HT;    For example, his origins were lower-class (the same guys seem to
feel differently about the philandering of President Kennedy or
President Bush); he loved and remained close to his mother; he
married a wife who was at least his equal; he refused to go to war;
and he actually listens.
 &HT;    In other words, Clinton refused to play the usual male game _
and won anyway.
 &HT;    But none of these personal reasons can justify impeachment.
Clinton's behavior _ self-defeating and reckless as it was _ does
not constitute ``treason or other high crimes and misdemeanors.''
 &HT;    The only thing that might be gained here is an understanding
that the religious right wing has won a disproportionate control of
Congress because so few Americans vote. If we get mad enough to
stop being the democracy with the lowest voter turnout in the
world, even this painful charade may have been worth it.
 &HT;     c.1998 Gloria Steinem 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gloria Steinem is an author, editor and founder of Ms.
magazine. This article is adapted from her remarks at the ``Rally
Against Impeachment,'' sponsored by Americans Against Impeachment,
at New York University School of Law, on Mon., Dec. 13.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
