<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARIA DID NOT SING HER OWN SONGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My husband and I disagree about whether Natalie Wood did her
own singing in ``West Side Story;'' I say she didn't. Who's right?
_ A.H., Northbridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: You are. The singing was performed by Marni Nixon, who also
sang for Audrey Hepburn in ``My Fair Lady'' and Deborah Kerr in two
films, ``An Affair to Remember'' and ``The King and I.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon sings as Grandmother Fa in the Disney film ``Mulan.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood was not told that her singing was going to be dubbed, Nixon
told the ``St. Louis Post-Dispatch'' in 1993. ``They let her sing
the whole thing, and then threw it away. In Audrey's case, she was
actually taking singing lessons. They told her they would only dub
the high notes, and then, of course, they threw the tape away
without telling her.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Moreno's songs in ``West Side Story'' were dubbed by Betty
Wand, who also performed for Leslie Caron in several films.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Jim Bakker's theme park still in business? _ R.A.B., Fort
Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Heritage USA, which was renamed New Heritage USA after Bakker
lost ownership, closed its doors in 1997 after several years of
declining business.
</P>
<P>
   Gaylord Entertainment, owners of the Grand Ole Opry, held an
option to purchase the 2,000-acre property for a $250 million,
1,000-room hotel. That agreement was canceled in October.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Mill, S.C., resort and water park was one of the most
popular U.S. tourist attractions before Bakker's conviction on
federal fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   Bakker sold more than 150,000 ``lifetime partnerships'' offering
a free hotel room at Heritage USA three nights each year for life.
The cost was typically $1,000. He was paroled in 1994 after serving
five years of a 45-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I contact the mystery novelist Sharyn McCrumb? _
L.C., Hillsdale, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to McCrumb in care of Gibson Media Consultants, 8339
Morningside Drive, Manassas, VA 20112.
</P>
<P>
   McCrumb, a former professor of journalism and Appalachian
studies at Virginia Tech, has written 10 Elizabeth MacPherson and
Jay Omega mysteries. Her most recent book, ``Ballad of Frankie
Silver,'' is the fifth in McCrumb's Ballad series of Appalachian
novels.
</P>
<P>
   The writer has an official Web page at www.swva.net/aphill.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBR/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
