<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4540 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-23 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RALLY AROUND THE PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This MEANS-COLUMN usually is filed on Thursday)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The irony of the House impeachment of President
Clinton is that he would be re-elected if the presidential election
were held today.
</P>
<P>
   It has stunned conservative Republicans, the Washington
establishment and the senators who now must put him on trial that a
hefty majority of the public is rallying behind the president
despite his impeachment on charges of perjury and obstruction of
justice.
</P>
<P>
   Polls taken after the House vote indicate that Clinton's job
approval ratings actually went up across the country. A New York
Times/CBS poll, typical of the others, reported that 72 percent of
those surveyed approved of the way he is handling his job.
</P>
<P>
   The 72 percent that said they approved included 90 percent of
the Democrats surveyed, 74 percent of the independents, 35 percent
of the conservative Republicans and 61 percent of all other
Republicans. An impressive sweep indeed.
</P>
<P>
   And although nearly two-thirds of those surveyed said Clinton
does not share their moral values not even half of them _ only 41
percent _ felt that Congress does any better in sharing their moral
values.
</P>
<P>
   It is important that our national leaders understand what is
going on here, although at the moment they seem to be struggling
with conflicting interpretations, complicated by their own
emotions. It is difficult for them to get past hardened opinions of
their own: Either they loathe Clinton for a pattern of lying or
they think sex is a private matter, even in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans I know who watched the House hearings are angry at
the partisanship of the Democrats, who repeated each other in their
arguments against impeachment. Democrats I know who also watched
are similarly furious at the GOP's rote exaggeration of the damage
done by Clinton to the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody came away enlightened. Nobody felt justice was being
fairly meted out by an impartial body. But the burden of creating
that impression was largely that of the Republicans, who controlled
the institutional process and the majority votes. They failed, and
the public noticed.
</P>
<P>
   The same partisanship among viewers was evident after the
president's upbeat performance on the White House lawn after the
House rebuke. It either was (a) proof that he is so shameless he
doesn't realize what hit him or (b) proof that he is such a
determined leader he won't give in to what he sees as an unfair
assault by his enemies. You could view it either way, depending on
your own bias.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the president did not have much choice short of hiding
in a closet with a paper bag over his head. He does not intend to
resign, so he must try to govern. And to lead he must carry on as
though his spirit is not broken and his very being is not shaken.
</P>
<P>
   He must appear tough and resilient, as we expect our leaders to
be. Whatever the private truth, he must never let us know. It is
his strong public persona around which voters rally.
</P>
<P>
   That is only one of the reasons why the public still supports
Clinton in spite of the fact that he is a lying lecher. The House
GOP majority, the snooty Washington social elite and self-important
media biggies don't get it because they never liked Clinton in the
first place. In their view, he was slippery white trash, not one of
their own and not deserving of his position.
</P>
<P>
   But voters are more sensible and independent than politicians
like to believe. The public is happy with Clinton's policy
leadership; the budget is balanced, the economy is strong, no
American soldiers are dying on foreign soil, the nuttiest
right-wing and left-wing notions are stalled and life is generally
good. Women in particular feel his diversity programs have advanced
their opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Most voters have no desire to change presidents. They view such
an event as an unsettling development bound to create uncertainty
and instability. They are satisfied with the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argue disingenuously that kicking out Clinton would
not be upsetting because another Democrat, Vice President Al Gore,
would take his place. But Gore is not Clinton; it was not Gore's
name at the top of the 1992 and 1996 ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would be an accidental, unelected president and therefore
lack a mandate to do much of anything, just what the Republicans
want. And voters realize no two individuals are alike; the country
is not yet sufficiently familiar with Gore's thinking to know just
how that difference might play out.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a sense in the country that Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr's ruthless pursuit of Clinton's private life was
gross overkill. It strikes terror in the most innocent of hearts to
realize that if the subpoena power can do this to a president,
worse can be done to the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   As a nation, we have an innate sense of personal privacy. We are
curious about the messy lives of celebrities who invite media
scrutiny but we don't want our own lives exposed for others to
judge. It should not be surprising that voters identify more with
the president than Starr.
</P>
<P>
   We always rally around the flag when the flag is in trouble. It
is in our patriotic nature. And for good or ill, the president of
the United States still personifies the flag.
</P>
<P>
   (Editors: Oops. In an earlier column, I gave the incorrect date
of the Time magazine cover of Adolf Hilter. It was 1938.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1640EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-CHRISTMAS     12-23 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-CHRISTMAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    AFTER THE BOMBINGS IRAQIS PREPARE FOR CHRISTMAS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD _ He is still pulled through the skies by reindeer, but
it's under the crescent moon of the Islamic Iraqi night. He is
welcomed with ``Jingle Bells'' in English and Arabic and he is know
as Baba Noel, not Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will he visit the homes of the five percent of the
population that is Christian, he'll stop at some homes of the many
Muslims who take part in Christmas in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, he will not have enough treats in his sack to
keep this from being another rough Christmas in Baghdad. This city
is catching the Christmas spirit just a week after four days of
missile attacks from U.S. and British forces.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature is in the 70s, but inflatable plastic Baba Noels
dangle on the fronts of stores while the customary portraits of
President Saddam Hussein hang by the cash registers. Offices play
Christmas music for callers on hold and Iraqis are ready to
celebrate in a multi-denominational way that is unusual in the Arab
world.
</P>
<P>
   On a busy intersection in this city of five million Arabs,
Muslim youth Samar Hussein came with his lifelong Christian friend
Ronny Latif, to pick out a Christmas tree from a street vendor.
</P>
<P>
   Latif, 16, will take the tree home. But Hussein, 17, will enjoy
the Christmas festivities also and they will share each other's
feast. Hussein will attend Latif's Christmas party, and Latif will
join in the evening's Ramadan dinner with Hussein. They will eat
minced lamb meat, kabobs and date pies. ``We are like brothers,''
says Hussein, who noted that Christ is considered a prophet in the
Muslim Koran. ``(Christ) is a prophet sent by God, just like
Mohammed.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Muslim holy month of Ramadan coincides with
Christmas. Out of respect for the majority religion, Christians are
asked not to celebrate Christmas too publicly.
</P>
<P>
   There will be fewer Christmas parties in nightclubs and no
alcohol in public. But, even many Muslims will have trees in their
homes and tell their children the story of Baba Noel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a new year for all of us, not just for Christians,''
says Layla Aziz, 24, a Muslim who works in a flower shop that sells
Christmas decorations. She will have a tree at home this year.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Nahhal, a Lebanese who directs the Iraqi office of the
Middle East Council of Churches, says the participation by Muslims
in Christmas is partly because Christians and Muslims have never
had the kind of conflicts here that they have in other Arab
countries. The 11th century European crusaders, for example,
trounced Lebanon and Syria but did not reach Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 900,000 Christians in Iraq. The most famous is
Tariq Aziz, deputy prime minister, who is Saddam Hussein's point
man in the public relations battle with the United States. Some say
he has obtained his prominent public role precisely because he is a
Christian and therefore not a political threat to Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 50 churches in Baghdad, and others are under
construction. There may be another 50 around the country and some
areas are majority Christian.
</P>
<P>
   But, things are hard in Iraq for Christians and Muslims alike
right now. Trade sanctions in place since Iraq invaded Kuwait in
1990 have left the economy in a deep depression. Recently Virginia
Michael, a 36-year-old Christian Iraqi, brought her children to the
streetside tree stand, where you can buy a scraggly pine for about
$4. One of Michael's sons hopes to get a Sega game cartridge this
year and her little daughter wants a bicycle. Another daughter on
roller skates zipped around the Christmas trees for sale.
</P>
<P>
   With her curly brown hair, sweater and pants, and her fluent
English, Iraqi-born Michael could pass for an American shopper.
But, a month ago, she and her husband, a musician and studio
engineer, sold their 1985 Mazda for $2,000 in hopes they can use
the money for applying for visas and attempting a move to the
prosperous United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents, who moved from Iraq to Chicago, send money. But she
has not seen them for nine years. Of course, their week before
Christmas was ruined by the missile strikes. ``I wish this would be
the last Christmas I spend here,'' she says, shaking her head and
appealing for Americans to stop the bombing. ``I believe it will
never be safe here.''
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas, her family sings ``Jingle Bells'' in Arabic. But,
as they shop for trees, her 5-year-old daughter Maryann is singing
a different jingle she picked up last week: ``Down with America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you hear what she's singing?'' Michael says with disbelief.
``I would like to live anywhere it will be safe for my children and
they will not have to think of these songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week she, her husband and their four children slept
together on the kitchen floor, away from the windows that rattle
during the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling my kids that maybe Santa would not come this
year. Maybe he's busy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But, now that they have the tree, they will decorate it with
balls and angels and cook stuffed chicken for Christmas. She thinks
Baba Noel will be able to come through, after all, with Maryann's
bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will try to do my best,'' she says. ``She's been asking for
a long time and I cannot break her heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
