<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Business Card That Says a Lot
</P>
<P>
   Business cards have become crowded with Web page and e-mail
addresses, cellular phone numbers and other contact information,
but a New York company has found a way to include pictures,
graphics and a resume, among other things. How, you ask? Well, the
space isn't (italics)on(end italics) the card, it's embedded in it.
</P>
<P>
   Ember Media Corp. has begun selling the new card, called
DigiCard, which is about the same size and shape of paper cards,
though with a hole. That is because the card fits into the CD-ROM
tray of a computer. The card carries 16 megabytes of information,
plenty of data to make someone remember who you are, said Ember
Media's president, Clayton Banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My desk is filled with business cards and I have no idea who
these people are anymore,'' he said. ``I'll hand you a business
card and you'll always be able to plug that sucker in and remember
who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, he said most of the cards, at more than a $1 each, that
have been ordered have not been for use as business cards but as
marketing devices. For instance, the Okidata Corp. ordered 50,000
cards to promote its new color printer to distributors and agents. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a Game, Crime Pays, If You Are Organized  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Popular simulation computer games like Sim City and Civilization
reward players for building strong, smoothly-running communities.
Now comes a new strategy game that also rewards the occasional
murder, extortion plot and torching of local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The game is Gangsters: Organized Crime, which puts the player in
the position of an aspiring mob boss. The idea in this $49.95 game,
made by Eidos Interactive of San Francisco, is to make the right
business decisions necessary to slowly take control of a city that
resembles Chicago (where else?).
</P>
<P>
   But to become an underworld king, you must be more than a mere
violent reactionary with a yen for overtaking a metropolis. You
have to recruit hoods, decide how and where to deploy them, choose
how much violence you'll use and allocate resources.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and maybe worst of all, deal with lawyers and accountants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like Sim City where you build something, a fire
happens and you send out fire trucks,'' said Gary Keith, spokesman
for Eidos. ``You're a mob boss and the goal is to be the richest
and most powerful man in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it should be renamed Sim-sin. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apple's On-Line Store Closed for Renovations &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was the week before Christmas, and all through North America
consumers were snatching up Apple Macintosh computers as fast as
Apple could make them. So why, then, did Apple close its online
store for the holidays?
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino, Calif., computer company, which earlier this year
brazenly vowed to teach Michael Dell a thing or two about selling
computers over the Internet, has been herding potential customers
away from its Web operations (www.store.apple.com) in recent weeks,
at the height of the busiest sales time of the year. And then, this
week, visitors to the Apple Store were greeted with a notice that
the site would be closed for renovations until Jan. 5. (Apple
executives did not respond to requests for comment.)
</P>
<P>
   The Web site message asks shoppers to patronize retail stores
that sell Apples.
</P>
<P>
   Does this signal that Apple is trying to appease its retail
dealers, who are not crazy about Apple competing with them. Not
necessarily, said Tim Bajarin, president of Creative Strategies
Inc., a consultancy in Campbell, Calif. He noted that anyone who
ordered a Macintosh on line after Dec. 17 would not receive it by
Christmas anyway, because of shipping times.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who insist on buying via the Web, there are
alternatives: Macmall.com and Macconnection.com, to name two.
</P>
<P>
   Bajarin noted it is probably no coincidence that the Apple Store
is expected to reopen on the same day that Steve Jobs, Apple's
chief executive, makes his opening keynote address at the Macworld
Expo in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1649EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
