<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRTUAL-APARTMENTS-NY     12-23 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRTUAL-APARTMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTER THE COMPUTER-GENERATED CONDO AND WALK AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn.)  (js) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Let's say you're a developer with a pile of rubble
where a new building is going to be. Today's market for luxury
condominiums may not last forever. How do you move those
multimillion-dollar three bedrooms before you can say, ``The stock
market's down 512 points again''?
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, like the late 1980s, you really had no choice:
you rented an office (preferably ground floor) in a fancy location,
put some easels around the room, stuck up architects' renderings
and handed out embossed brochures _ and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   But now there's virtual reality _ the catchall real estate term
for computer-generated videos that mimic a visit to an existing or
still-imagined building. It is becoming part of a growing number of
sales pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard to explore a vision of a building with the
old techniques,'' said Jessica Schick, director of sales for the
Macklowe Organization. ``Now we're able to take buyers inside our
heads. You can understand the mood of the place, walk around.''
</P>
<P>
   Macklowe paid $100,000 for a three-minute computer-generated
video of its unfinished new condominium building at 145 E. 76th
St.It was designed by Hugh Hardy, with interiors by Peter Claman.
Apartments are priced from $1.55 million for a three bedroom (plus
library and dining room) to $6 million for the penthouse.
</P>
<P>
   At the Macklowe sales office, prospective buyers sit in front of
a television set for an imaginary trip to see what the hulking
16-story steel frame will eventually look like.
</P>
<P>
   There are the antique-nickel front doors. See them swing open to
admit the lucky new owner. See the tall columns and the white
marble floors incised with geometric designs. There are the
Palladian-influenced doors leading to the courtyard, which the
marketers call a ``cortile'' (because anything Italian is
fashionable these days). Look! There's a tile mural on the wall of
the cortile, and in the middle something that looks like a
smokestack. It is an obelisk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obelisk is coming out,'' Ms. Schick said. ``We're going to
have a fountain instead.'' There are no pictures of the apartments.
</P>
<P>
   If you walked around the construction site now, it would be
difficult to rhapsodize about the cortile. It is a slab of
concrete, covered with trash and surrounded by barbed wire. ``This
is where you saw the doors open,'' Ms. Schick said cheerily,
pointing to a chain-link fence near a plywood construction cabin.
</P>
<P>
   But the new sales pitch seems to be working. Eight of the
building's 20 condos have been spoken for. Occupancy is scheduled
for late March.
</P>
<P>
   While the use of action renderings to sell unbuilt buildings is
new, a handful of national real-estate chains use their own version
of virtual reality: visitors to their Web sites can click on
certain (usually high-end) apartments and houses and zoom through a
panorama of the rooms, following a pointing hand as it sweeps
across kitchen counters and up the staircase. The National
Association of Realtors reports that buying properties on the
Internet is soaring. And virtual-reality designers say that
animated renderings and those that show existing housing are both
suddenly big business.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Lewis, vice president for marketing at Ipix, a large Oak
Ridge, Tenn., company that specializes in virtual-reality videos,
said that the number of real estate clients ``really started taking
off in the last six months and now doubles monthly.'' At the end of
1997, he said, there were 100 Ipix vignettes on 100 brokers' Web
sites; now there are 5,000. At David Williams 3D Media, a
four-year-old computer-animation company in Manhattan, Williams
said the use of virtual reality for selling real estate has grown
from 30 percent of his business to more than 75 percent in the last
two years.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Barbara Corcoran, chairman of the Corcoran
Group, a large Manhattan real estate company, tried to interest
Donald J. Trump in virtual reality to sell condominiums at Trump
International Hotel and Tower, his bronze-clad edifice at Columbus
Circle. She didn't envision a television set showing a video but a
custom-built circular room, with life-size computer-generated
images ringing the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Trump turned her down.
</P>
<P>
   In May, William and Arthur Zeckendorf began using virtual
reality to sell their new 43-story tower at 515 Park Ave., at 60th
Street, and have been refining it ever since. Last month, they
unveiled a new 15-minute ``tour'' of the building, with people,
furnishings _ and William and Arthur Zeckendorf, pointing and
welcoming in every room. Their take on virtual reality cost
$100,000, William Zeckendorf said.
</P>
<P>
   The 515 Park show comes with music by Aaron Copland. As
``Appalachian Spring'' winds down, the narrator intones that this
will be the first new apartment building on Park Avenue in 70
years. ``That's the part that always gets me teary,'' Zeckendorf
said, rising to flick off the giant television set.
</P>
<P>
   Some marketers are not so sentimental _ or so enamored with the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we have just sold $2.5 billion of product without it, we
are obviously not impressed,'' said Louise Sunshine, chief
executive of the Sunshine Group. ``We're actually building a
kitchen and powder room and bathroom for the Chatham in our
showroom _ the moldings, the doors, the floors.'' The Chatham is
the building being built by Related Companies at the corner of
Third Avenue and 65th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ms. Sunshine said, she takes a fresh look at the
state of virtual reality every six months. ``We're waiting for the
technology,'' she said. ``It's not upscale enough for us yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1703EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4617 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-LEARN-TO-READ-ART     12-23 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LEARN-TO-READ-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERPATHS LEADING TOWARD THE JOYS OF READING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 Alice Keim, a teacher, is the technology coordinator for the Horace
Mann Lower School in the Bronx, N.Y.  
 By ALICE KEIM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most common complaints about computers is that they
can take the place of reading. That is not a new complaint. Each
time a new distraction has arrived _ comic books, television _ the
same fear has been trotted out. Now it's the computer that looms
over children, enticing them to stare aimlessly at a screen for
hours.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, some basis for these fears. New technology
does, at times, distract children from educational activities like
reading. Do not, however, underestimate the power of interactive
technology to help build skills. Many of today's toddlers can click
a mouse and operate a computer long before they know their ABC's.
</P>
<P>
   They are learning computer skills early and are still learning
to read at an appropriate age. Building on the children's
familiarity with computers, software companies have produced
programs that help children build reading skills starting in the
preschool years.
</P>
<P>
   Reading software is available for all elementary school students
of any age, although it tends to be more effective for the earlier
elementary and preschool years. Programs can help very young
readers gain basic reading skills and confidence, and slightly
older learners build comprehension, vocabulary and grammar.
</P>
<P>
   Computer programs can never replace reading books, singing songs
or working with alphabet blocks, but they are a valuable complement
to these activities.
</P>
<P>
   The programs act as personal tutors, waiting for children to
respond to questions or repeat sounds before progressing. For
decades, children have sung along as their favorite television
characters taught them to sound out letters.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive programs add a whole new dimension to this
transaction by responding to children in a way that the one-way
television broadcast cannot. Just as ``Sesame Street'' has become
an acknowledged and valued educational resource, so, too, will
educational software.
</P>
<P>
   The reading programs on the market today use a variety of
approaches: phonics, drills, visual repetition and games. When
looking for a reading program, it is important to ask what the
program does that cannot be done better through more traditional
teaching methods.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the program has talking characters that are more
entertaining than the still pictures, or its audio helps a child
work more independently. Perhaps your child has difficulty sitting
for a block of time, and a software program provides enough
variation in activities to keep the child's interest.
</P>
<P>
   When shopping for any educational software, remember to pick
programs with characters and activities that will appeal to your
child. Even at the preschool level, there is a huge variety
available, from simple programs based on picture books that read
aloud with your child to full-fledged programs that are like games.
While many programs are designed for independent work, others work
best if a parent is working with the child. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   READER RABBIT'S READING
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-9 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The Learning Company; $29.95; Windows 3.1, 95 and 98, and Mac
7.0.1 and higher.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Reader Rabbit programs are among the most popular programs
for early elementary students. What is really impressive are the
improvements made to this already appealing, educationally sound
product.
</P>
<P>
   The story line: Reader Rabbit; his sidekick, Sam the lion, and a
helpful mouse, Mat (short for Matilda), are on a vacation in search
of their imaginations. After you sign in, the screen flashes to a
map with points of interest marked with pictures of books. Thirty
books across three levels are supposed to be read to get to the end
of the map.
</P>
<P>
   The first stop on each level features a Sound Sorter game, which
requires the child to help a monkey by sorting colored crystals.
The monkey has three pots with a word written on each one. He holds
a crystal and then says a word, and the child is supposed to put
the crystal in the pot with that word. My first-grade students
loved this game.
</P>
<P>
   The monkey and animation made them giggle, and they became
determined to sort all the crystals. Some words in this section are
too complex for younger children to sound out, but even they can
repeat the words shown on screen again and again, helping them
memorize some words and pick correct answers.
</P>
<P>
   Once the phonics activity is completed, the child needs to read
two books. The books allow children to repeat words and then hear
their own voices played back. Children are supposed to read aloud
with the computer at every level. But I noticed that children
working alone tended to flip through the pages quickly without
repeating the words or answering the questions in an effort to move
to the next game.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The second stop on each level features a picnic-basket rhyming
activity in which the player must create a huge sandwich out of
pieces of food with words written on them _ the object is to create
rhyming piles. And the user meets a friendly vowel owl looking for
her voice. She introduces short and long vowel sounds, and the
other characters on the screen emphasize these sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The third stop includes two new reading books and questions
similar to those that appeared in the earlier level and a game
called Silly Syllables. In this game the player must put together
sounds to create new words.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with the program is with the Help section: it was
left over from an earlier program and is essentially useless to a
child.
</P>
<P>
   Reader Rabbit uses audio throughout. There is no consequence for
wrong answers, and words and sounds can be repeated whenever
needed. That allows children to answer by process of elimination,
but it also gives them many opportunities to figure out the correct
response. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BAILEY'S BOOK HOUSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 2-5 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Edmark; $19.95; Windows 3.1, 95 and 98, and Mac 7.0.1 and
later.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is an example of interactivity that fails to interact. The
Bailey's Book House program is popular but doesn't accomplish
anything that could not be better accomplished away from the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey is a cat who hangs out in his play book house. Different
areas of his house lead to different learning activities. The
Three-Letter Carnival section, for example, has two different areas
of activity.
</P>
<P>
   The first area shows a lawn with different characters and
objects scattered around. Click on any object and the word for it
is written out and sounded out slowly. Reading with your child can
accomplish this goal better.
</P>
<P>
   The second level is better. The child must fill each car of a
roller coaster with rhyming words. If the first car has a bug in
it, the user could click on pictures of a rug, a jug and a mug to
complete the train. Every word is spoken out loud when the child
picks it.
</P>
<P>
   If the user clicks on the typewriter in Bailey's house, the
Letter Machine pops up. If your child likes to use the computer,
this is an effective tool for teaching the alphabet and letter
sounds. Clicking on any letter brings up that letter and a phrase
using it.
</P>
<P>
   The sound quality of the program is excellent, and it is easy to
hear the emphasis on the letter sounds. But, again, the same goal
could be accomplished with a good alphabet book.
</P>
<P>
   The Read-a-Rhyme section is a wonderful area for parents to work
with their children. The screen shows a phrase with a missing last
word. In the corner are four pictures of words that would complete
the sentence with a rhyming sound.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``Rub-a-dub-dub, three kids in a ...'' could end with
tub, sub, shrub or club, depending on the user's choice, and the
completed sentence is then read aloud and the sentence is shown as
an animated picture. Children find this hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   The My Friend activity is something like a digital Potato Head.
This area should help cement the words for body parts, like eyes
and nose, but the presentation is too confusing. On the screen are
an animated creature and three columns, two with descriptive words
and one listing body parts. Click on a word to change the
character's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   I watched some kindergartners play with this program and they
clicked furiously, paying no attention to the actual words. Some of
the level's elements are effective for teaching the children to
identify body parts but not for recognizing actual written
vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   The program is designed for 2- to 5-year-old children and
consequently does not require any reading skills. That is
important, as many programs that cater to this age group fail to
recognize that even the simple words ``click the mouse'' on the
screen mean nothing to a child who cannot read.
</P>
<P>
   Children may learn some basic vocabulary from Bailey's Book
House, but the program is too simple. Children will probably
outgrow it quickly. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARTHUR'S COMPUTER ADVENTURE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-7 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Broderbund; $29.95; Windows 95 and 98, and Macintosh.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arthur's Computer Adventure is part of the respected Living
Books Interactive Adventures Series. Several parents recommended
this program to me and when I carried the box through the halls of
my school, several children wanted to know when they could start
playing with it. While the box says it is for children 3 to 7, it
was clear from my students' responses that children as old as 10
enjoy the program.
</P>
<P>
   After exploring the activities section of the game, which stars
the Arthur character of the books by Marc Brown and of PBS's most
popular children's show, I quickly realized why my students were so
enthusiastic. There are five activity areas, all of them fun but
none of them particularly educational.
</P>
<P>
   I loved the Deep Dark Sea, where I navigated a scuba-diving
Arthur around the hazards of the deep sea but was horrified that
this could in any way be classified as educational. The game is
pure entertainment and does not, as the publisher states, help
children learn about world geography or ocean life.
</P>
<P>
   In Frankenfish, children can combine features of different fish
to create new sea creatures with funny names; I found it equally
disappointing. While it provides some basic information about fish
types, the information is superficial.
</P>
<P>
   Other sections provide useful reading exercises. In Treasure
Hunt, the player matches pictures with the words identifying them
to move along a path to a treasure. If the given word is ``mom''
and the player correctly clicks on a picture of Arthur's mom, the
player progresses three spaces, one space for every letter in the
word. When you win the game, you get to choose what to do with the
treasure and read a newspaper article about your decision.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At a store run by D.W., Arthur's sister, players can hone their
counting skills by providing change to pay for various items. The
activity also has a cafe where the player follows D.W.'s direction
for various recipes by dragging various ingredients to her mixing
bowl.
</P>
<P>
   My students quickly discovered that they did not need to listen
to D.W. and that there was little consequence to not following a
recipe. D.W. does not even react when the player puts three worms
in the mixing bowl rather than eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Toy Copter also proved disappointing. The player navigates a
remote-controlled fire helicopter around a room while trying to
drop water balloons and firefighters on targets. Although that was
initially fun for my students, they quickly tired of it and moved
on. Like too much of this program, the educational content seemed
to be an afterthought. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   READING BLASTER VOCABULARY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9-12 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Knowledge Adventure; $20; Windows 3.1 and 95, and Mac 7.1 and
later.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kids 9 to 12 years old are a tough audience for educational
software. These children have already discovered the world of
electronic games, and some have formed a clear aversion to any
software related to learning.
</P>
<P>
   Reading Blaster picks up the challenge. This program's
characters are cute, but they are also suave and on the edge of
cool. Rave the detective is a green monster with two large eyes and
no other facial features. At a press conference on the opening
screen, players are assigned to solve a crime.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery and clues center on a mansion where a party is going
on. Rave explains that the party guests like to play word games and
that the child, armed with a map and a word list, will have to beat
them at their own game to find the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, there is a mouse party. To earn a clue, the
player must complete eight sentences by choosing from vocabulary
words that the mice sporadically hold up on signs. But the game is
irritating because the words appear too slowly.
</P>
<P>
   In the corridor, there is a well-designed arcade-style horse
race game. You move your horse ahead by choosing a letter (using
on-screen alphabet buttons) and then pressing Go. The object is to
write the longest word possible without ending the word. If players
try to write the word ``slide,'' for example, the player that is
first to form ``slid'' moves ahead.
</P>
<P>
   This is an excellent game and challenges students both to form
words and to recognize roots of words. The fourth graders I
observed playing this game became truly determined to keep the
words going for as long as possible in this section. It is as much
an exercise in logical thinking as vocabulary building.
</P>
<P>
   The program contains several other activities including a
crossword puzzle and a simple definitions test. For the latter, you
are seated at a card table with four monster guests and you click
on a stack of cards.
</P>
<P>
   Each card contains a vocabulary word. The monsters scribble down
a possible definition, and you must select the one that is correct.
The effect is similar to the age-old use of flash cards and can
help students prepare for tests and quizzes. It is hardly an
innovative game, but playing against the monsters in a mansion is
more fun than flipping through flash cards.
</P>
<P>
   After you have gathered all of your clues, you go back to your
detective notebook. You have six clues that you put together to
form three words that turn out to be the true clues to evaluating
the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene reminiscent of Agatha Christie, Rave assembles all
the characters in the library. When the user finds a suspect that
matches all three clues, the mystery is solved.
</P>
<P>
   I particularly liked the ability to create your own word list. A
parent or teacher could easily customize this program for practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1708EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
