<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEA-ROBBINS-NYT &LR;      12-23 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEA-ROBBINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK ROBBINS, ARTS ENDOWMENT'S POINT MAN IN DESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (js) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After years under congressional siege _ and a spring rally by
conservatives to annihilate it _ the National Endowment for the
Arts, whose budget was finally secured in September, may
understandably be looking for steady ground to tread. But under a
new chairman, William J. Ivey, who has said he believes the
endowment should be as important as the Department of Defense, the
NEA is marching, not slinking, to the front lines in its support of
the arts.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Ivey announced the appointment of Mark Robbins, a
curator, teacher and artist, as the new design director, a post
that has been vacant for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, 42, is currently curator of architecture at the Wexner
Center for the Arts and an associate professor of architecture at
Ohio State University, both in Columbus. Born in New York, he
studied architecture in Florence and London and in 1981 received
his architecture degree from Syracuse University. He opened his own
architectural practice in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's visible, and that's what's needed,'' said Hugh Hardy, the
architect who is a former chairman of the endowment's Design Arts
Advisory Panel and who was consulted in the search for a design
director. ``It has been a long, difficult battle to find someone.
People who are creatively engaged think that Washington will put
them to sleep rather than offer them an opportunity to make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Robbins, who was under consideration last year to become
dean at the Yale School of Architecture, is credited by many for
his indefatigable commitment to establishing the Wexner as a
laboratory for exploring new ideas in architecture and design.
``Mark Robbins will lead the arts endowment in strengthening the
presence of design in this country,'' Ivey said.
</P>
<P>
   During his five-year tenure at the Wexner, Robbins'
interdisciplinary approach proved to be as provocative as the
deconstructed fortress that houses the center, a design by Peter
Eisenman. There, Robbins originated exhibitions ranging from
``House Rules,'' which matched architects with social critics to
design houses, to ``On the Table,'' opening on Jan. 30, a look at
how tables divulge a wealth of information about class, sex, race
and social rituals.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Robbins was in Washington to familiarize himself with
a new bureaucracy and to pursue the task of finding a loft.
``There's never really been any industry here,'' Robbins said,
sounding exasperated at the prospect of leading the downtown life
in a Federal-style town house.
</P>
<P>
   As for his goals in his new post, which starts with overseeing
the distribution of grants in the design field, Robbins said, ``I'd
like to look at design in the widest possible scope and at the ways
the public realm can be enhanced by it.'' He added that he saw the
suburban no man's land _ the strip mall and the parking lot _ as
the public spaces most in need of attention. ``The only truly
public space we've invented is the mall and the parking lots where
you see so many kids parked in cars drinking beer. Perhaps we can
find a better focus for these interim spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   As an installation artist, Robbins has contributed to what are
known as gender studies, a loosely defined area of inquiry that's
been popular on campuses since the early 1990s. Ralph Lerner, the
dean of the School of Architecture at Princeton University,
described gender studies as ``a waning subject in architectural
discourse,'' which, he added, had ``helped us think about a lot of
things in fresh ways, including domesticity and the relationship
between architecture and the state of women and minorities in
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins' work in gender studies included a 1994 installation, at
the Museum of Modern Art in Saitama, Japan, that analyzed what he
described as ``the fetishization of the blond, blue-eyed woman.''
The installation included a brick wall with a small opening that
framed views of the museum's Meiji-period paintings of
``impressionistic, creamy-pink Caucasian nudes,'' he said. Robbins
hopes to bring the same spirit of inquiry to his new job. ``After
all,'' he said, ``education is the first step toward action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
