<HEADER>
A4629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEMADE-WINE-NYT     12-23 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEMADE-WINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE THAT BURNS IN THE LAMP OF MEMORY
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Minn.) (bl) 
By NEAL KARLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ As usual, I didn't start holiday shopping this
year until the mound of catalogs in my living room reached chair
height. Speed-leafing through these paeans to yuppie gewgaws, I
paused at a funky-looking wish book from Semplex of U.S.A., one of
the country's leading specialty houses, serving amateur winemakers
since 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, I spied a $154.25 trilevel Steam Juice Extractor
imported from Finland and used to crush grapes painlessly and
efficiently. I also noticed the $389 Buon Vino Super Jet Filter, an
Italian import capable of pumping 80 gallons of wine an hour. But
no way was I buying any of it. My family has its own claptrap tin
wine press, which my uneducated country-boy grandfather
quixotically lugged across Europe and to the United States three
generations ago.
</P>
<P>
   My grandfather fled Russia in 1911, leaving behind his wife and
two young daughters late one night. A half-step ahead of the czar's
draft board, he carried only one reminder of home. It might have
been smarter to choose something light and easy to conceal. Instead
he took that bulky wine press, which he carried on his back across
Europe and then transported over the Atlantic to America.
</P>
<P>
   The family wine press, you see, could travel free; his wife and
children would have to pay steerage. His plan was to earn passage
to America for them as quickly as possible. But it was seven years
before he could send for them, from someplace called Minnesota. In
the meantime, he began using his wine press in his new world, which
was overflowing with Scandinavians; for the uneducated country boy
who spoke no English, the wine press was home.
</P>
<P>
   My grandfather made sweet peasant wine. In the old country, his
homemade wine was so righteously tasty, he had won the honor of
making it for religious sacraments in the village. His wine came
from a secret recipe, with all that entails. It was never written
down, of course. Only one family member in each generation was
taught the precise combination that yielded the wine, which was
sacramental enough to please the village's religious leaders, yet
carried the wallop of a Joe Louis uppercut.
</P>
<P>
   My grandfather, an Orthodox Jew, arrived in a land populated by
Norwegians and Swedes and kept making the wine that had made him
famous back home. He had a small but appreciative audience among
the small number of fellow Jewish emigres, who, like the
grandfathers of Bob Dylan and Joel and Ethan Coen, had emigrated
from czarist Russia to the banks of the upper Mississippi. Because
of his wine, my grandfather was a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Prohibition? Not for him. He received a religious exemption for
his sacramental wine. And if the leftovers went to the neighbors,
so what? He never charged anybody.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1930s, his Mason jars of wine were going out as Christmas
presents to neighbors named Olson, Swenson and Andersen. Always
willing to provide a free ecumenical snort to the good Lutherans,
my grandfather died in 1974, as Willie Loman would have had it,
``well liked.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long before that, he revealed the recipe to my father. Upon
inheriting the wine press, my father moved it from my grandfather's
basement to our suburban garage, where every fall, to the
neighbors' dismay, a truck unloaded hundreds of pounds of
Michigan-grown grapes. And there in the garage it sat, a
century-old contraption that looked like the Tin Man's head in
``The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   My American-born father, a physician, added a few improvements
to his father's packaging. He gave away the Christmas wine in
recycled Lacroix and Evian bottles, labeling it ``Karlen's Purple
Foot Special,'' after the grape-stamping scene in ``La Dolce
Vita.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the recipe came to me. Personally, I thought it was
ridiculous to labor so hard to make something you could easily buy.
(That would be Manischewitz.) But traditions are traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The red Concord grapes came in mid-September, 400 pounds of
fruit divided into 20-pound lugs, or boxes. We worked like
stevedores. My father and I set the old press atop a 40-gallon
barrel; as he loaded the fruit into the hopper, I turned the crank.
</P>
<P>
   We poured in about 80 pounds of sugar, covered the whole thing
up and returned every five days to stir it with a stick. Somewhere
along the way, we funneled out the dregs and spread them on the
garden. A flock of sparrows descended on the muck, and in minutes
the yard was filled with drunken birds. The scene looked like a
cross between Hitchcock's ``Birds'' and Bukowski's ``Barfly.''
</P>
<P>
   All the sparrows eventually got home safely, and six weeks
later, on a crisp October day, the wine was ready for the
ecumenical folks of Minneapolis. Among the first tasters were two
friends of mine, musicians who considered themselves arbiters of
cool. They declared our wine better even than Jagermeister, nectar
of certain alternative bands of the '90s. They asked for more wine,
even after I warned them. Yet they, too, made it home safely.
</P>
<P>
   I probably could buy one of those Semplex specials, a machine to
mash and siphon and adjudge fermentation ratios automatically. But
that isn't the point. The press, I realize, is not just a way to
make way-cool wine. It is a way to remind myself of the illiterate
young man who carried a heavy wine press he had hammered together
himself across half a world. It is a way to remind myself of an old
man who had arthritis and no English, yet could woo the neighbors
with his potion.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century after he died, I can see both him and where I
came from. I come from people who have a tradition. Like most
people who keep traditions, I will continue, no matter how much
backbreaking work and strenuous cranking our yearly winemaking
entails.
</P>
<P>
   As John Kennedy said about the space program, we Midwestern
sentimentalists do things not because they are easy; we do things
because they are hard. This evening, Karlen's Purple Foot Special,
vintage 1998, made the old-fashioned way, will be ready for
delivery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
