<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOMELESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ANNOUNCES FUNDING INCREASE FOR HOMELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: California, New York, Texas, Washington)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taking a break from impeachment woes, President
Clinton Wednesday unveiled $850 million in federal grants to help
the homeless find housing, job training, child care, and mental
health and substance abuse treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also announced that his budget proposal for fiscal 2000
would include $1.1 billion in assistance to the homeless, a 15
percent increase from the current funding level. ``It will be the
largest effort to combat homelessness in the history of America,''
Clinton said in a speech in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $850 million, $700 million is for 1,420 homeless projects
in 300 communities nationwide. These grants will serve 330,000
homeless people and are the centerpiece of the Clinton
administration's six-year effort to combat homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``Continuum of Care'' grants, they are aimed at helping
homeless people find permanent shelter while attempting to
alleviate some of the underlying causes of homelessness: A lack of
education and job skills, mental illness, and drug and alcohol
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development awarded a total
of 307 grants out of 460 applications received, HUD Secretary
Andrew Cuomo said. HUD awards the grants on a competitive basis to
encourage local governments and agencies to address the homeless
problem. The prospect of future awards is intended as an incentive
to do a good job in serving this population.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the old carrot and stick approach,'' Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $150 million is for Emergency Shelter Grants that
give immediate food and shelter to the homeless. These grants are
awarded through a formula that takes into account the size of a
city's homeless population, as well as its housing needs.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said HUD was being extra aggressive in monitoring how
funds are spent to guard against waste and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo was asked whether Clinton's participation in the
announcement was calculated to give the appearance of normalcy at a
time when the president faces an impeachment trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is functioning normally and this is what he
would do,'' Cuomo said, pointing out that Clinton has participated
in these grant awards in previous years. ``The president is doing
his job, if anything with more vigor than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the cities receiving awards: Albany, N.Y., $1.1 million in
Continuum of Care grants and $159,000 for emergency shelter; San
Francisco, $12.9 million in Continuum of Care grants and $891,000
for emergency shelter; Seattle, $12.1 million in Continuum of Care
grants and $533,000 for emergency shelter.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, San Antonio received $713,000 for emergency shelter
and Beaumont received $82,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
