<HEADER>
A4681 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-JOEYOUNG-TEX     12-23 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-JOEYOUNG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS BIG APE'S IN GREAT SHAPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Gus Van Sant's Psycho ``re-creation'' _ remember it? _ came
out a few weeks back, a common naysayer argument was that
filmmakers shouldn't remake good pictures when there are so many
bad and mediocre ones they can improve upon. A better, unaddressed
question is why so many remakes miss the spirit of their source
material. Disney, fond of plundering its past, is one of the worst
offenders; its latter-day ``Flubber'' and ``101 Dalmatians'' are
crass desecrations of the originals, and this summer's ``Parent
Trap'' lacked the initiative to be anything but a carbon copy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Disney should remake other studios' material, because
``Mighty Joe Young,'' a remake of a 1949 RKO picture, comes as a
pleasant surprise. Despite some dismissible flaws _ including a
hefty budget that's too big for such B-movie material _ it respects
the original without succumbing to reverence. It doesn't quite have
the pacing of the first ``Joe,'' which had a Saturday-matinee
panache that led to a new peril every two minutes, but it stands as
a satisfying update of a perfectly good movie.
</P>
<P>
   What marks the new ``Joe'' most _ and what will turn off some
people, even if they're unfamiliar with the original _ is a '90s
political correctness. Joe's best human friend, Jill, played by a
limpid-eyed Charlize Theron, is a feisty feminist who grew up with
the gargantuan gorilla after poachers killed both their mothers.
Hero Gregg (Fort Worth's Bill Paxton, ruddy and rediscovering his
restlessness) is no longer a sidekick to a show-biz hack, but a
zoologist working for a nature conservancy.
</P>
<P>
   To save Joe from poachers, Jill and Gregg take him to Los
Angeles, where he's not a freak-show attraction as in the original
but instead a fund-raising conduit for a struggling animal-rights
group. Cynics may be forgiven for thinking that the movie at times
looks like a co-production of the Humane Society and the Discovery
Channel, and for wondering why the fresh-scrubbed Jill models the
latest in J. Crew jungle wear despite having lived her life away
from civilization.
</P>
<P>
   As long as it's satisfied with being a remake of the 1949
``Joe,'' however, this new gorilla-size edition runs over its
problems with the speed of a cheetah. Director Ron Underwood, no
stranger to B movies (''Tremors'') or crowd-pleasers (''City
Slickers''), brings an easy mainstream appeal to the proceedings,
and Theron and Paxton work well as essentially supporting players
to Joe, the film's real star. The special effects and Rick Baker's
creature design are convincing enough to grab the attention of even
a jaded '90s filmgoer.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mark Rosenthal-Lawrence Conner screenplay can't resist
going a little further than its source, also throwing in a ``Moby
Dick''-inspired subplot about a megapoacher (Rade Sherbedgia)
wanting revenge on Joe, who bit off a couple of his fingers a long
time ago. This strays from the original's simple charm, even as it
leads to scenes that echo the original's best set pieces without
simply reproducing them.
</P>
<P>
   These are the problems the nitpickers will focus on. Better to
concentrate on the film's qualities, the chief being that like the
original, it's a highly entertaining popcorn movie. Considering all
the bloated B pictures we've sat through this year _ ``Deep Impact,
Godzilla'' and ``Armageddon'' _ we should welcome one that,
although still a little bloated, remembers to have a heart as well.
</P>
<P>
   P.S.: Look sharp in a party scene for Terry Moore and Ray
Harryhausen, the original movie's star and the special-effects
meister who first brought Joe to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mighty Joe Young'' is rated PG for violence and a couple of
moments that might be unsettling to young children.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
