<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By LESLIE LAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvesting Pine Nuts
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do pine nuts come from pine trees and, if so, what type of
pine tree? I love pine nuts, but they're so expensive _ can I grow
my own here in Klamath Falls, Ore.?
</P>
<P>
   A. You won't be able to grow pignolias, the most famous variety.
They come from the Italian stone pine, Pinus pinea, a handsome,
umbrella-shaped tree that is' native to the Mediterranean and too
tender for life in Klamath Falls, though it grows well in places
like mid-coastal California. Nurseries in your area are more likely
to offer assorted cultivars of the much hardier Swiss stone pine,
P. cembra. This species also yields nuts (as does any pine with
``stone'' in its name), but it is prized for its ornamental value
and is not usually grown with pesto in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Del Tredici, the director of living collections at
Harvard University's Arnold Arboretum, said your best bet is P.
koraiensis. It is the source of those ubiquitous Chinese pine nuts,
and it is a very tough character, able to withstand high winds and
temperatures of 20 and 30 below. But before you go rushing out to
plant a few, there are a few things to bear in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Nut-bearing pine trees tend to be slow growers, and though
grafted plants might bring your wait for the first nuts down from
15 or 20 years to something more like 5 or 6, it's going to take a
good long time before you see much of a crop. That crop will be
encased in extremely hard shells, the shells tightly clasped in
cones that are themselves well fixed to the upper branches of the
trees. (You cannot wait for them to fall of their own accord; by
that time the blue jays and squirrels will have beaten you to the
nuts.)
</P>
<P>
   Has Dr. Del Tredici ever harvested nuts from the
well-established specimens at the arboretum? No, he said: ``The
cones are unbelievably sticky, for starters _ just to handle them
is a commitment.'' Planting the trees is a commitment, too, of
space as well as time. Our pinon-nut-bearing Southwestern native,
P. edulis, can take bush form under extreme conditions, and some P.
cembra cultivars are comparatively modest in size. But P. pinea is
a big tree, and P. koraiensis is, at least potentially, huge. Dr.
Del Tredici saw some in China that were more than 100 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Still game? Here are two mail-order sources: Porterhowse Farms,
41370 SE Thomas Road, Sandy, Ore. 97055, (503) 668-5834, offers P.
cembra and P. koraiensis; the price list of 850 conifers is free; a
descriptive manual costs $6. Edible Landscaping, PO Box 77, Afton
Va. 22920, (800) 524-4156, offers P. cembra and P. pinea; free
catalog.
</P>
<P>
   A Cachepot Gift
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have my eye on an antique china cachepot as a Christmas
present for my mom, whose favorite piggyback plant is in a plastic
pot. But the cachepot is about four inches wider than the pot it
would contain. Does that matter?
</P>
<P>
   A. Assuming the plant in question is large enough not to look
silly in its new home, there is no reason to worry about a bit of
extra width.
</P>
<P>
   Your mom can just fill in the unused space with sphagnum moss or
pretty pebbles. What does matter is the depth. If the top of the
actual pot is way below the edge of the cachepot, the air around
the plant may stay so damp that it causes fungus problems.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the tops of the pots even, just prop the inner one on a
couple of stones or a layer of pebbles. This is a good move with
any cached pot, since it will elevate the drainage hole. (That
which is unseen tends to remain uncleaned; cachepots almost always
end up with pools of water in the bottom. )
</P>
<P>
   Looking for New Suspects
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you have a few proven winners for street containers
(whisky barrels)? The local garden club plants 20 to 30 barrels
with annuals each spring. They are the same from year to year, with
perhaps a change in the color of geraniums. The center is planted
with a dracaena, followed by petunias and geraniums, finishing up
with vinca. The care of these barrels is hit or miss. Some are in
full sun and some in partial shade. I would love to have a list of
annuals this fall so we can plan for some changes next year.
</P>
<P>
   A. The list of inexpensive plants that will perform under the
conditions you describe is not long, but there are a few directions
in which you could branch out: marigolds, for instance. The little
signet types, including Lemon Gem and Tangerine Gem, are just as
foolproof as their larger, more familiar cousins, but they have
prettier foliage and a more attractive fragrance _ especially Lemon
Gem, which deserves its name. Alyssum and lobelia are also
stalwart, carefree bloomers that put out a lot of color over a long
season. All of these flowers are small _ tiny, in the case of
alyssum _ but there are so many that the overall effect is bright.
</P>
<P>
   If you need something with bigger flowers, don't forget
nasturtiums, which are famous for thriving on neglect. Mixed-color
assortments can be hard to blend with other plants, but single
colors like the delicate primrose-yellow called Moonlight are easy
to work with. And what about dahlias? Though they take a bit longer
to bloom, they look good even when all green, and the flowers are
striking for a long time once they get going.
</P>
<P>
   If you used ivy geraniums instead of the vinca, you would have
trailing leaves and flowers to boot. Or, if small leaves are
important, the vinca might be replaced by Helichrysum petiolatum,
sometimes called the licorice plant. The silvery gray variety is
more reliable than the chartreuse one called Limelight, but the
Limelight is a very handsome plant that will look great with strong
blue lobelia or the equally blue, very low-growing Anagallis
monellii (blue pimpernel). Your center height might come from a
small canna like Tropical Rose, or you could be daring and plant a
clump of the multicolored Swiss chard called Bright Lights.
</P>
<P>
   If you are willing to plant two kinds of barrels, consider
fuchsias and trailing begonias for the ones that get some shade.
</P>
<P>
   Seeds for most of these plants _ and the plants themselves _ are
widely available. For the less-common ones try Thompson and Morgan
Inc., PO Box 1308, Jackson, N.J. 08527-0308; (800) 274 7333. The
company offers a free catalog. Dwarf cannas are cheaper by the
dozen from Wayside Gardens, 1 Garden Lane, Hodges, S.C. 29695-0001;
(800) 845-1124; free catalog. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to:
</P>
<P>
   Garden Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10036
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished
questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
