<HEADLINE>
HOW TO HAVE A REALLY COOL, COLLECTIBLE YULE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While you're home for the holidays, look carefully at the
Christmas decorations.
</P>
<P>
   Is the same old Santa figurine in his same location on top of
the piano? How about the stockings? Are they as old as you are? Is
the tree skirt from the same decade? If the answer is yes, you are
surrounded by collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   Old Christmas decorations are hot. Terry Kovel, co-author of
``Kovels' Antiques &AMP; Collectibles Price List 1999,'' says Christmas
collectibles can be anything from Santa candy dishes to feather
trees _ especially feather trees. A 3-footer with musical stand
from Germany will fetch more than $600.
</P>
<P>
   A tree stand that plays three tunes and turns the tree with a
wind-up key is worth $450.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday jewelry _ those little rhinestone wreaths and trees,
seemingly worn by every schoolteacher in America _ is another
big-bucks collectible.
</P>
<P>
   Kovel and her husband, Ralph Kovel, supreme beings in the
antiques trade, gave holiday jewelry to their staff this year.
</P>
<P>
   Terry says the best holiday items to look for at garage sales
are aluminum trees with revolving colored lights. Papier-mache
figurines and Dresden cards made of paper and tinsel are highly
regarded. If you find them at yard sales, buy them. If you own
them, consider selling them at an auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, ornaments, with a few exceptions, don't hold their
value next to new ones. Exquisite antiques sell for about the same
price as new, elaborate ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   The one company that hit a homer with ornaments is Hallmark.
``They made a series that moved and made noise; they cost $45 new,
and they are selling at a good price now,'' says Terry Kovel, who
lists a 1981 Hallmark rocking horse at $500 in her book. A 1980
Cool Yule, Frosty Friends from Hallmark is valued at $400.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for Beanie Babies Christmas ornaments, or Beanie
Babies of any stripe. They are not appreciating in value, Kovel
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who thinks they will send a kid to college on the
proceeds of their Beanie Baby collection is wrong,'' she says,
adamantly. ``If past history holds true, only a very few will hold
any value. We've seen it with Avon bottles and Jim Beam bottles;
anything that is offered as a limited, collector's edition is
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovel says the flotsam from the present that seems to have
captured the interest of collectors is anything that is used as a
substitute for money _ debit cards, credit cards and phone cards,
``even the early, ugly, metal charge cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember them? If you do, you're old enough to have Christmas
decorations worth some money. You might want to cash in the
Christmas collectibles when those credit-card bills come rolling in
next month. Then, retire the cards _ they may be worth something
someday.
Christmas Collectors Clubs
</P>
<P>
   Collector's Courier
</P>
