<SLUG> BC-FILM-LITTLEVOICE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE ARE SOME CATCHES IN THIS `VOICE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much will be written about Jane Horrocks' spot-on impersonations
of Shirley Bassey, Judy Garland and Marilyn Monroe and others in
``Little Voice.'' But it's not Horrocks' gift for mimicry that
gives the movie a lift. It's something in her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The key comes in a scene in which Horrocks is belting out ``Get
Happy.'' Showboating, rump-shaking, working the crowd, Horrocks
looks for all the world like the diva she's pretending to be. But
when you look closely, her eyes still say that a scared, intensely
shy woman isn't far beneath the surface. Actors love to slip into
roles in which they can mask themselves; rarely do they do what
Horrocks does, which is let the essence of her character show
through.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the essence of ``Little Voice'' shows through as
well; it wears a mask of originality, but you don't need to look
too closely to see that its story _ repressed person works toward
breakthrough _ is older than some of the show tunes Horrocks sings.
Her character, LV, is introverted to the point of near-autism. She
rarely speaks and spends most of her time in her room, listening to
her father's record collection. She stacks the records around the
turntable, as if they were part of a shrine and the turntable an
altar. When she sings along, she hasn't just absorbed the music;
she has let it possess her.
</P>
<P>
   You'd sequester yourself, too, if you had a mother like LV's.
Mum is a vulgar, man-chasing shrew played by ``Secrets and Lies' ''
Brenda Blethyn at such a pitch that you're not sure if you're
getting irked by the character or the performance (hint: probably
both). One of the guys she brings home is a talent scout played by
Michael Caine (who seems rejuvenated _ maybe too rejuvenated _ by
the role). When he overhears LV singing, he figures there's gold in
them thar trills, and he tries to start her on a singing career.
</P>
<P>
   That's not so easy. If a diva like Barbra Streisand suffers from
stage fright, imagine what it's like for someone who borders on the
agoraphobic. (It's probably no coincidence that two of LV's three
idols died early, unhappy deaths.) The only person who has LV's
best interests at heart is a shy telephone repairman (Ewan
McGregor, turning down his sex appeal to give a winningly modest
performance). His pigeon-racing hobby, however, figures into a
closing metaphor that's just too ham-handed to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Herman, who directed last year's terrific ``Brassed Off!,''
adapted ``Little Voice'' from a play and does his level best to
obscure its stage origins. The movie is full of lighting tricks and
swooping crane shots, and it climaxes in a spectacularly edited
sequence that reveals new levels of ugliness in Blethyn and Caine's
characters. But the movie's first half feels underdramatized, and
it's not until Horrocks begins singing that it begins to ignite.
She gives us a reason to see the movie, but what surrounds her
isn't so absolutely fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Voice'' is rated R for sexuality and strong language.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
