<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4784 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-STEPMOM-TEX     12-23 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STEPMOM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `STEP' IN THE WRONG DIRECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a number of interviews, ``Stepmom'' stars Julia Roberts and
Susan Sarandon have voiced their unhappiness with the movie's
title, which is the least of its problems. Sarandon is the ex,
missed dearly by the children she doted on. Roberts is more attuned
to her career as a fashion photographer than to her new life as a
stepmother to Ed Harris' kids. His adolescent daughter doesn't like
Roberts. ``Stepmom'' has the kind of undercurrents we've all seen,
either up close or when an argument within one of these grafted
nuclear families breaks out at the supermarket. It's also the kind
of movie they do all the time on Lifetime. Just because ``Stepmom''
has bigger stars doesn't make it any better. It's merely more
expensively staged.
</P>
<P>
   The battle lines are drawn: young, hip and desperate to break
through vs. older, not-so-cool and attuned to her kids' needs.
(Given the kind of animosity that can crop up in these
relationships, you wonder why this movie wasn't called
``Stepmonster.'' It certainly can't be called ``Dad,'' because the
father, played by a harried, put-upon Ed Harris, disappears for at
least an hour.) Sarandon has the upper hand here. She gets to be
the angrier of the two women _ the loving mama lion _ because she's
sacrificed her career to her cubs, and they love her. The fact is,
though, there are no tensions between her and her kids. She's so
much the perfect mother that she's not very interesting. Sarandon
flashes her wide, insolent eyes and delicate sneers, doing her best
to give this underwritten role any authority.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts has a little more to work with. She's not really suited
for instant motherhood, which the movie illustrates through a
sitcom-ish opening scene. ``Stepmom'' lurches from comedy to
melodrama, trying to plant its feet directly where ``Terms of
Endearment'' has been before, with two powerhouse actresses _ well,
one anyway _ bonding through laughter and tears.
</P>
<P>
   But director Chris Columbus lacks the audience-pleasing
shrewdness of ``Endearment'' (and ``As Good As It Gets)'' director
James L. Brooks. Columbus falls back on the mortifying spectacle
that ``The Big Chill'' introduced 15 years ago: white people
lip-synching Motown songs into hairbrushes, a sequence that has now
calcified into a standard piece of business. ``Stepmom'' is full of
'em, as we get to watch Sarandon and her kids bop to ``Ain't No
Mountain High Enough'' by Marvin Gaye and Tammi Terrell. (A more
appropriate Gaye and Terrell duet for this movie would have been
``If I Could Build My Whole World Around You,'' because Sarandon's
kids are the center of her life. Considering Sarandon's daughter's
anger and fear of abandonment, Columbus should have gone all the
way and had her mouth Nine Inch Nails' ``Hurt).''
</P>
<P>
   Columbus returns to the scene of a crime _ holiday season
mawkishness _ that has been berry, berry good to him. He banged a
dinger with the first ``Home Alone.'' Unfortunately, it's been big
swings and misses ever since, the worst being ``Mrs. Doubtfire'' _
which writer Larry Gelbart dismissed as ``Tootsie Vs. Kramer.''
There may still be people with a taste for being manipulated this
relentlessly. If so, this is just the glass of room-temperature
Diet Coke you were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepmom'' is rated PG-13 for adult language.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/
</P>
</TEXT>
