<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4805 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SHAKESPEARE-TEX     12-23 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SHAKESPEARE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS BARD'S FOR YOU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not long before ``Shakespeare in Love'' lets you know that
it's not your English Lit professor's Shakespeare. We see the Bard
plugged by writer's block, struggling to come up with words for
something called ``Romeo and Ethel the Pirate's Daughter,'' tossing
a crumpled sheet of paper into a souvenir coffee mug from
Stratford-on-Avon.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cheerful anachronism that winks at the audience and
razzes the purists, an invitation to join in the fun. And what fun
it is. John Madden's bawdy and boisterous direction gets spirited
performances out of an energetic cast, and the screenplay by Marc
Norman and Tom Stoppard is overflowing with wit and romance.
</P>
<P>
   The script portrays Shakespeare as something of a hack-for-hire,
willing to steal lines he has overheard on the street and to borrow
from his superior rival, Christopher Marlowe (a briefly seen Rupert
Everett). Joseph Fiennes, much more memorable here than in
``Elizabeth,'' plays the Bard with restless passion; even when he's
standing still, he appears to be ready to jump out of his skin.
Shakespeare's muse is eluding him _ actually, she's turning up in
the wrong beds _ and his writer's block remains until he meets
Viola de Lesseps (Gwyneth Paltrow). She's a noblewoman so enchanted
by Shakespeare's words that she disguises herself as a man to play
the part of Romeo, at a time when women weren't allowed on stage.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a leap of faith to accept Paltrow's getting away with
the ruse, but the movie's exuberance makes us willing to make that
leap. Shakespeare and Viola quickly fall for each other, but the
course of true love never did run smooth, and she's been promised
in marriage to the strutting, cash-strapped Lord Wessex (Colin
Firth), who sees her as more of a business deal. There's comedy and
tragedy in this, and it informs Shakespeare's writing of ``Romeo,''
which begins to take on a different form.
</P>
<P>
   If Fiennes and Paltrow sometimes let themselves go a little too
much, staring at each other like lovestruck collies, they make up
for it with the passion of their scenes together. They define
chemistry, because together they're more than the sum of their
parts. Paltrow is still developing as an actress, but she shows
something beyond movie-star potential when she has the right
leading man _ and Fiennes is her best match yet.
</P>
<P>
   They're boosted by a terrific supporting cast, all of whom tear
into their parts, especially Geoffrey Rush, breaking away from
recent dourness to play the befuddled theater owner Philip
Henslowe; and Judi Dench, as imperious as ever as Queen Elizabeth
I, full of wisdom and withering one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the co-credited screenplay, the movie appears to be
mostly Stoppard's work. When he's at the top of the game, he's
peerless in wordplay, as he showed in the Shakespeare-oriented play
``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead.'' But ``Rosencrantz''
couldn't survive the transition to screen; despite good
performances from Gary Oldman and Tim Roth, it had a sluggishness
that defeated the script. Madden has no such problem here; his
camera is as restless as Fiennes' body, and the movie moves with
nearly hyperactive zest. Now and then, Madden overindulges himself,
but why begrudge him a little fun when he's offering us such a good
time?
</P>
<P>
   As everything unfolds, the movie comes together as an astute
commentary on theater and on moviegoing itself. The result is a
sublime convergence of director, script and actors. It couldn't
make a better commentary than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love'' is rated R for nudity, sexual situations
and some violence.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
