<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Dec. 24. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EURO-CITIZENS (The Chunnel, England-France) _ The year 1999 is
the official start-up date of the Euro, the common European
currency that will unite 11 countries monetarily. But throughout
Europe, a different kind of integration has already taken root. A
new generation of Europeans _ mobile, fluent in several languages
and aggressively non-nationalistic _ are already living the kind of
borderless, cosmopolitan existence that the single European
currency is supposed to introduce. By Alessandra Stanley. (With a
map.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MISSILE _ Developments in U.S.-China satellite/missile
techology-transfer case. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ATTACK (Jerusalem) _ Muslim guerrillas in Lebanon fired
Katyusha rockets into northern Israel on Wednesday, wounding 13
people. The attack was retaliation for the killing of a Lebanese
woman and six of her children in an Israeli bombing raid on
suspected guerrilla targets on Tuesday. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Undated) _ Developments on impeachment: Rep. Tom DeLay
and freshman Senate conservatives seek to slow down train to
censure. The senators argue that evidence must be presented before
any votes are taken in any trial. By David Dao.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-LAWSUITS (Boston) _ First the states successfully sued the
tobacco companies. Now at least a dozen cities are preparing to sue
the gun industry in a growing campaign to ultimately win in court
the handgun controls that gun interests have blocked them from
winning in state legislatures and in Congress. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   WINTER-STORM _ Across the South and Southeast, a sudden winter
storm caused seven people to die in traffic accidents and pileups
from San Antonio to Memphis. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FATAL-FIRE (New York) _ Four people died in the smoke-filled
stairwell of an Upper West Side highrise on Wednesday as they tried
to escape a fire that spread from a burning Christmas tree in a
19th-floor apartment occupied by the family of the movie actor
Macauley Caulkin. The morning fire drove dozens of residents to
seek chilly refuge on their open-air balconies and left hundreds
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CANDY-CHILD-DRUGS _ Drug companies, trying a new approach in
treating children, are selling over-the-counter remedies that are
as tasty and chewy as soft candy and bubble gum or could be
mistaken for ordinary lollipops. These products, though, are not
meant to treat a sweet tooth but instead are for ailments like
colds, sore throats and even asthma. Critics of these products take
a far more skeptical view, contending that while some, like the
chewy Tylenol, have clear medicinal value, others offer no more
therapeutic benefit than, say, chicken noodle soup. By Dana Canedy.
(With a photo.)
</P>
