<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-ROOMS-ART-2TAKES     12-23 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-ROOMS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHILD DREAMS OF A ROOM, AND THE DREAM COMES TRUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y. )  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ELAINE LOUIE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Maya Bogdanow, 9, moved into a new bedroom, she wanted
exotic beaded curtains that glittered like rubies and sapphires in
front of her bed. ``My friend, she has them at her house,'' Maya
said. ``And I liked the idea. They're pretty. I can tie them back
any way I want. And they're noisy. You can hear them whenever
people come in.''
</P>
<P>
   So her parents, Larry Bogdanow, an architect, and Deborah
Shaffer, a filmmaker, scoured the city and finally found the
curtains at Little Rickie, a shop on the Lower East Side
specializing in vintage wares (three rows of beads, $11.95 each).
The beads' veiled mystery and privacy made their young daughter
feel like Scheherezade.
</P>
<P>
   When Rebecca Barrett, 16, wanted to summon blue skies and clouds
into her bedroom, her parents, Ron Barrett, an artist, and Barbara
Schubeck, a graphic designer, bought her two cans of paint _ one
blue, one white _ for $30, and left her alone to realize her
fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   To a child, one of the sweetest and most enduring gifts is a
room of one's own. And as every parent knows, children are
sometimes their own best interior designers. When they ask for a
wall to draw on, a place to put their toys, a ladder to climb to a
loft, they are trying to become masters of their small universes _
usually a bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a statement that a child wants to be autonomous and wants
to have control over the environment,'' said Dr. Barbara Scales,
who retired this year as the head teacher at the Child Studies
Center at the University of California at Berkeley and is an author
of ``Play at the Center of the Curriculum,'' a textbook
(Prentice-Hall, 1998). ``What the adult has to do is make it
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   By helping to design the room, Dr. Scales said, ``a child will
not only feel independent but will grow strong and be
independent.'' Parents still need to hover, of course. ``But you
want unobtrusive supervision,'' she said, ``because the moment the
adult comes in, the fantasy play will collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   A parent who designs a theme room for a child _ cowboys and
Indians, or Curious George _ risks stifling the child's
imagination. ``It's a fixed environment that kids tire of,'' said
Ro Logrippo, author of ``In My World: Designing Living and Learning
Environments for the Young'' (John Wylie &AMP; Sons, 1995). ``All too
soon it becomes the baby room.''
</P>
<P>
   But a child's needs change. The same girl who wanted her Beanie
Babies at her fingertips one year may want them on a high shelf the
next. A 4-year-old's loft bed is a secret hideaway for him and his
friends. Later, he may use it as a corner for solitude.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms that make children happy don't require extravagant
spending. No Biedermeier bureaus or Arts and Crafts rocking chairs.
No $5,000 trompe l'oeil murals. Here are nine innovative rooms,
many of them inexpensive and child-approved, whose design elements
were often as simple as a very large bulletin board or a few cans
of paint in a child's favorite colors. What was essential was
listening to the child's articulated (or somewhat inarticulated)
wishes.
</P>
<P>
   WALL OF STEEL
</P>
<P>
   How can a child go merrily through life without having a place
to put the spelling quiz with the perfect score or the shiny satin
ribbons awarded for track? Unlike cork boards, which require pins
that make holes, magnetic boards need only magnets, preserving
treasures for a child's notion of forever.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Callaway, 8, who lives in San Francisco, has a practical
mother. Barbara Callaway, a landscape architect, who bought a
3-by-5-foot piece of galvanized sheet metal that fit a door,
drilled four holes, inserted four screws and in a scant 30 minutes
made her son happy.
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $30. Source: Goss Heating and Ventilation in San
Francisco; (415) 751-0393.
</P>
<P>
   SOPHISTICATED PINK
</P>
<P>
   Girls may love pink but not necessarily in a fluffy, ruffly way.
When Roberto Reichard, a petroleum engineer, and his wife, Jennifer
Kenny, a management consultant, bought a 1920s Spanish-style house
in San Francisco, they asked David Weingarten and Lucia Howard, of
Ace Architects in Oakland, to paint the interior.
</P>
<P>
   ``We chose motifs found in Spanish Colonial architecture _
squares related to the cross, the four-pointed star _ blown way
up,'' Weingarten said.
</P>
<P>
   But when their daughter, Julia Reichard, 4, looks up at the pink
and reddish-pink squares on her ceiling, she simply sees her
favorite colors done the way she likes them. ``Not froufrou,'' Ms.
Kenny said.
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $600 to paint the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   EVERY BEAR IN ITS PLACE
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad tried counting them, but he lost track,'' Elizabeth
Foster, 9, said of her stuffed animals. Her father, Jonathan
Foster, a New York architect, stopped counting at 106, of which
roughly half are Beanie Babies. They were sloppy little squatters
in a room belonging to a child who said, ``I like having it neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it is. Her father designed a home for the animals _ a
30-foot shelf that's 6{ inches deep, wraps around three walls, and
has a molding edge so the animals don't fall off. To reach them,
Elizabeth uses a metal grabber.
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $250 to build the shelf; $7.99 for the grabber at a
hardware store.
</P>
<P>
   DRAW ON THE WALL? OF COURSE
</P>
<P>
   When 4-year-old Alexander Roche's mother, Isabel Marcal, who
works at the United Nations, is cooking, he can hang out in the
kitchen and draw on a wall _ with washable markers. The wall and a
sliding pocket door are covered in Greensteel white marker board,
which is steel with a porcelain coating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a double whammy,'' said Robin Osler, the Manhattan
architect who suggested the specially treated steel, which doubles
as a magnetic board. ``Isabel can write notes to herself, and
Alexander can draw on the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Cost: about $440 to cover wall and pocket door. Greensteel:
(800) 766-4204.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
