<SLUG> BC-MIGHTY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MIGHTY JOE' YOUNG AT HEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2{ Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This pleasant, undemanding remake of ``Mighty Joe
Young'' plays like ``Free Willy'' with fur.
</P>
<P>
   The new version of the 1949 kiddie favorite gives the
giant-ape-on-the-loose-in-L.A. story line an eco-conscious gloss.
This time, the 15-foot gorilla isn't shipped over from his African
homeland to headline a cheap vaudeville show; he's shipped over to
be the star attraction at a nature conservancy park. It's not
irresponsible drunks but evil poachers (Rade Sherbedgia _ who used
to call himself Serbedzija _ and Peter Firth) who get Big Joe all
riled-up and loose on Hollywood Boulevard this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Paxton is the compassionate white hunter/zoologist and
Charlize Theron is the beautiful white jungle girl who are Joe's
best friends. She and Joe both lost their mothers when they were
little primates _ courtesy of those same evil poachers, in a
sequence that owes a lot to Spielberg's ``The Lost World'' _ and
their bond, as fundamentally hokey as it may be, is genuinely
touching.
</P>
<P>
   Joe himself is a pretty cuddly creation. Slicker than the
stop-motion puppet created in 1949 by Willis O'Brien and Ray
Harryhausen (the latter, along with original ``Joe'' heroine Terry
Moore, makes a nice little cameo appearance in the new movie), the
new 2,000-pound gorilla is a state-of-the-art creation. Designed by
five-time Oscar winner Rick Baker, who has excelled at the hairy
thing in the likes of ``Greystoke'' and ``Gorillas in the Mist,''
the new Joe is a seamlessly expressive blend of animatronics,
computer graphics and guys in monkey suits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as in the first film, it's impossible to believe that
this lovable lumberer actually frightens the citizens of Los
Angeles while he avoids a small army of cops. Unlike O'Brien's more
indelible creation King Kong, Joe has never generated the tragedy
and terror that his big brother unleashed. He still doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Ron Underwood, who made ``City Slickers.'' He
does his best to prevent this thoroughly Disneyfied remake from
seeming more silly than it is. Of course, it wouldn't be ``Mighty
Joe Young'' if it wasn't goofy, so it's just as well that Underwood
didn'tAT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT
D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT
D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT
D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT
D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT
D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT
D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT
D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT
D18006350017 AT D18006350017 AT D18006350017 f`OE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1846EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-ROOMS-ART-2TAKES     12-23 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-ROOMS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: (800) 766-4204. 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRINGING THE OUTDOORS IN
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe she's preparing for a life of homelessness,'' Ron
Barrett mused, when asked why his older daughter, Becky, 16,
painted drifting clouds on the wall of her Manhattan bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. ``I like being outdoors,'' Becky said.
</P>
<P>
   If she couldn't do it literally, she was able to do it
figuratively. Last year, she painted the wall in less than half a
day, subtly fading the blue as it descends from the ceiling to the
floor. This summer, she went to a sailing camp in the British
Virgin Islands, where every night, she slept on the bow of a
51-foot boat under a canopy of stars. ``The next step,'' she said,
``is putting glow in the dark stars on the ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $30 for two half-gallon cans of paint, blue and white.
</P>
<P>
   VEILED SLEEP
</P>
<P>
   When Maya Bogdanow asked for a sleeping alcove painted pale
lilac in the rear and pale blue in the front, with a beaded
curtain, her parents obliged. Bogdanow gave her paint samples to
choose from, and Ms. Shaffer bought three curtains with glinting
plastic bits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the sound of it,'' Maya said. ``When I move my
blankets, the beads move.''
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $46 for two gallons of paint, and about $36 for three
boxes of beaded curtains, each with a 36-inch track. Little Rickie,
49{ First Ave. (Third Street); (212) 505-6467.
</P>
<P>
   MURPHY NURSERY
</P>
<P>
   ``Eliot was a bit of a surprise,'' Richard Fernau said of his
youngest son, who will be 2 in a week. In 1996, when Fernau, an
architect in Berkeley, Calif., and his wife, Sarah Cunniff, a
lawyer, discovered that she was pregnant, they improvised a nursery
from what would have been a bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   In a 6-by-8-foot room, Fernau designed what he calls ``the
Murphy nursery,'' a room where each wall is a niche. One holds a
pullout drawer that doubles as a crib, another has a bunk bed and a
third has a sink. (The fourth wall is the door.)
</P>
<P>
   The crib, plywood with a perforated metal side, slides in and
out. The shelf above the crib was designed to flip up, fastening
onto hinges, so that Eliot could stand up in the crib without
bumping his head. The shelf is also a changing table, with shallow
shelves above.
</P>
<P>
   The bed is 5 feet long and 30 inches wide. When Eliot was a year
old, he moved from the crib to the bed. To make sure he wouldn't
fall out of the bed, yet also be able to stand up in it, Fernau
designed a sliding pocket panel 30 inches high; it's hidden in the
wall. There is storage above the crib, under the bed and in the
crib itself.
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $1,500 to build the wall with the crib; $5,000 for the two
niches with the crib, bed and storage space; $8,000 for the entire
room.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-AGE MEMORIES
</P>
<P>
   Zoe Feigenbaum, 16, transformed the fireplace in her bedroom
into an altar, a floor-to-ceiling architectural shrine to
teen-age-hood, New York City style.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the things I like to remember,'' she said. First,
there's romance: red roses, carefully preserved and darkening at
the edges _ gifts from her boyfriend. Then there's Manhattan,
revealed in antique metal signs: Hires Root Beer, Nectar Tea. ``I
collect them because I love the city,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   A bleached animal skull is a memento of a trip to Arizona, a
ceramic elephant a gift from her grandfather ``just before he
died.'' Then, next to a glass jar of quarters, there are three
chrysanthemums _ one white, one yellow, one burgundy _ floating in
a silver bowl.
</P>
<P>
   TO READ OR DANGLE
</P>
<P>
   At age 6, Molly Solomon became what educators call ``a reluctant
reader,'' said her mother, Kathy Solomon, the owner of Tootsie's, a
children's bookstore in Manhattan. ``She loved being read to,''
Mrs. Solomon said, ``and was so attached to me that she thought if
she read on her own, I wouldn't read to her anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Molly, now 9, solved her own problem. If she had a special place
to read, she said, it might inspire her. What Molly wanted was a
treehouse but settled for its urban substitute: a walk-in closet
transformed into a reading alcove.
</P>
<P>
   The closet is 5 feet wide, 7 feet deep and 10 feet high, and has
a louvered door. A carpenter built a platform 4{ feet above the
floor, and since Molly likes to imagine herself a mermaid, Concetta
Pereira, an artist, painted the closet to resemble an underwater
grotto.
</P>
<P>
   The alcove worked. ``Within six months, Molly was reading past
her grade level,'' Mrs. Solomon said. (She still reads to her
daughter every night.) But when Molly gets restless, she can hang
upside down like a bat, dangling from the clothes rack that the
carpenter forgot to remove.
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $100 for the platform; $500 for the artist's painting.
</P>
<P>
   LOFT LADDER
</P>
<P>
   With the ceiling at 11 feet 7 inches, there was no place to go
but up when Valerie Boom, a Manhattan architect, designed bedrooms
for her children, Maxine, 8, and Henry, 4.
</P>
<P>
   Each child now has a play loft that starts 7 feet 6 inches from
the floor. The lofts are carpeted, and each is furnished with a
single mattress for sleepovers. To reach the lofts, Maxine and
Henry use wooden library ladders attached to steel poles, which
they roll to the edge of the loft, then grab a steel bar on the
edge of the loft and toss themselves over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has ever fallen down,'' Ms. Boom said.
</P>
<P>
   Cost to construct the bedrooms and lofts: $11,000. Oak library
(or loft) ladders start at $450, and tracks at $5 a running foot.
Available at Putnam Rolling Ladder, 32 Howard St. (Broadway); (212)
226-5147.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
