<HEADLINE>
DELAY URGES SENATE TO HOLD CLINTON TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Majority Whip Tom DeLay urged the Senate on
Wednesday not to short circuit the impeachment process without
holding a trial that examines all the evidence in the Monica
Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without any review of the evidence, it is premature to be
talking about a deal or short circuiting the process,'' the Texas
Republican said in a statement aimed at slowing talks of a
compromise that would let President Clinton serve out his term.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was released after five of DeLay's House
colleagues _ Reps. Sherwood Boehlert and Benjamin Gilman of New
York, Mike Castle of Delaware and Jim Greenwood of Pennsylvania _
who voted for impeachment last week announced they now favor
censure as an alternative to the Senate removing Clinton from
office.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay fought last week to block any censure resolution from
being offered on the House floor, claiming that impeachment was the
only remedy permitted by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, DeLay said the reason the House adopted
articles of impeachment charging the president with perjury and
obstruction of justice ``was due to overwhelming evidence'' in the
case. He claimed that much of that evidence is locked up in the
House office building and has never been publicly aired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before people look to cut a deal with the White House or with
their surrogates who will seek to influence the process, it is my
hope that (senators) will spend plenty of time in the evidence
room,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   If senators take the time to reflect on that evidence, he added,
then the 67 votes needed to convict Clinton might just ``appear out
of thin air.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House declined to comment publicly on DeLay's
statement. But privately, some aides expressed anger over his
suggestion _ which was also made during the House hearings on
impeachment _ that there may be evidence of other wrongdoing beyond
what the president has been charged with in the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they've got another charge to make against the president,
then they ought to say so rather than trying to claim that there's
some secret information of some sort that's really damning to the
president,'' said one close Clinton aide. ``That's really a cheap
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it's unclear how many senators are willing to sign off
on censure as an alternative to a Senate trial, a number of
Democrats and Republicans have suggested over the last few days
that any attempt to convict him of the charges leveled by the House
would fall short of the required two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   Both Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Minority
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., have been polling their own caucuses.
Aides for Daschle have indicated that most of the Democrats and a
fair number of Republicans don't support the idea of removing
Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Lott aides say he is also putting together an advisory group to
help guide senators as they begin their historic proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But it is still uncertain as to whether the senators will be
able to reach a bipartisan compromise involving censure or some
other punishment that would allow the president to finish out his
term.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate ends up taking the House's charges against Clinton
to trial, it would be only the second time in history that a
president has faced impeachment proceedings. The first was in 1868
when President Andrew Johnson was impeached. He was acquitted in
his Senate trial by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., said on MSNBC Wednesday that the
Senate should at least start the trial process before senators make
up their minds about the case.
</P>
<P>
   He said members at any time during the process could decide with
a simple majority of 51 votes to dismiss the case or approve
censure or some other alternative punishment short of removal from
office.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., also said Wednesday that he believes
it would be a mistake not to start the trial. Smith is among
several GOP senators trying to hold off any move toward censure.
But he acknowledged that censure is one of several options that
could emerge as a trial proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   While DeLay and other Republican conservatives are hoping
Clinton will resign before the Senate begins it proceedings, Vice
President Al Gore reiterated Tuesday that resignation is not even a
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Clinton) will definitely not resign. ... He is more likely
to get hit by a meteor than he is to make a decision to resign,''
Gore said in an interview with Cable News Network.
</P>
<P>
   Polls over the past few days have continued to indicate that
most Americans remain solidly behind Clinton and against
resignation. They also show that support for Republican lawmakers
at an all-time low because most Americans believe that they are out
to get Clinton for purely partisan reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Those surveys have alarmed some Republican leaders outside
Washington. In an interview Wednesday with CNN, Wisconsin Gov.
Tommy Thompson said he doubted Clinton would be impeached and
called on Republicans to put it behind them and get back to their
legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
