<HEADER>
A4825 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STRING-ORCHESTRA-2     12-23 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STRING-ORCHESTRA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY FOR STRINGS: AN ANNUAL CHRISTMAS SEMINAR FOR YOUNG
MUSICIANS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Mass., Calif., Md., Ill.)  (nk) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the last 30 years concertgoers in New York,
particularly those with an abiding interest in the future of
musical performance, have observed a tradition that has become
nearly as intrinsic to the holiday season as tree lighting, window
displays and sidewalk Santas. On Christmas Eve a few thousand
listeners make their way to Carnegie Hall to hear the young
participants in the New York String Orchestra Seminar perform the
works they have been studying during a 10-day series of classes,
coaching sessions and rehearsals at the New School. Many
concertgoers return a few days later to hear a second program.
(This year's is on Monday.)
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood that someone on the stage will be heard from
again is high: Violinists Cho-Liang Lin, Gil Shaham, Nadia
Salerno-Sonnenberg, Pamela Frank and Maria Bachmann; violist Paul
Neubauer, and cellists Yo-Yo Ma and Matt Haimovitz attended the
seminar in their student days. So did three of the four players in
each of the Muir, Orion, St. Lawrence and Ying Quartets, and
hundreds of musicians who now play in orchestras and chamber
ensembles in the United States, Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the defining moments for me as a teen-ager,''
said Ma, who attended the seminar in 1971, when he was 16. ``The
passion of people your own age is very important. It puts you in
touch with a larger world, beyond schooling and everything else you
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the lure of these concerts for their first 25 years was
Alexander Schneider, the violinist who directed the seminar and
conducted the orchestra from the time the project was started in
1968 until his death in 1993. Schneider, who had been a member of
the Budapest String Quartet, the legendary ensemble that flourished
between the 1930s and the late 1960s, imparted to his students the
expressive style that prevailed when he was young but that had
largely died out as interpretive tastes came to favor literalism
over subjectivity.
</P>
<P>
   Under Schneider's baton, musicians from 15 to 22 were able to
recapture the charm of that style, and the violinist and conductor
Jaime Laredo, who took over the program after Schneider's death,
has preserved that approach to a great degree. This year's concerts
are dedicated to the memory of Schneider, who was known as Sasha.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but bring something from him to these
performances,'' said Laredo, ``although there are ways we differ a
lot. Beauty of sound wasn't that important to him, and if something
wasn't precise, it was all right. But in terms of the dynamics and
articulation and his way of making music come alive, that's where I
got so much from him. He had an extraordinary love of music
making.''
</P>
<P>
   Laredo's programming, like Schneider's, centers on the Classical
and Romantic repertory, although he has included a few
comparatively easygoing contemporary works, among them pieces by
Ellen Taaffe Zwilich and George Walker. He points out, however,
that although the repertory is mostly standard, most of the young
musicians in the orchestra have never performed it before.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's program is devoted entirely to Mozart and
includes the ``Marriage of Figaro'' Overture, Symphony No. 35 and
Piano Concerto No. 24, with Peter Serkin as the soloist. Monday's
concert includes Prokofiev's ``Classical'' Symphony, Elgar's
Introduction and Allegro for Strings (for which the Guarneri
Quartet joins the orchestra) and a Vivaldi Concerto for Four
Violins. The soloists, all seminar alumni, are the concertmasters
of four American orchestras: Martin Chalifour, from the Los Angeles
Philharmonic; Herbert Greenberg, from the Baltimore Symphony;
Malcolm Lowe, from the Boston Symphony, and William Preucil, from
the Cleveland Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The seminar, which is sponsored by Carnegie Hall and the New
School, is like the music world in general, and music schools in
particular, in its balance of competitiveness and collegiality. It
is open to players living or studying in the United States,
although they need not be Americans: this year's class includes
students from Helsinki, Beijing, Jerusalem and Sapporo, Japan.
Every year more than 250 players audition for 60 full scholarships,
which cover the course, food and housing. After the seminar,
participants receive photographs from the sessions, a list of one
another's addresses and a periodic newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Auditions are held each fall in New York, Boston, Chicago,
Cleveland, Rochester and San Francisco. Juries in each city listen
to the applicants, but the only one to hear them all is Isidore
Cohen, a violinist who played in the Juilliard String Quartet and
the Beaux-Arts Trio and has coached at the seminar for the last 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sasha used to do the traveling,'' Cohen said, ``and I think
Jaime did some, but he was too busy, and he needed someone to do it
who knew how Sasha worked, so I agreed. At the auditions, we have
the musicians play the music that we are going to perform at the
two concerts. We want to see how motivated they are, whether
they're interested enough to work out the difficult spots. And we
ask them to play two solo works of a contrasting nature.''
</P>
<P>
   When the musicians arrive in New York (this year's seminar began
on Saturday) they are given a schedule that runs virtually around
the clock. A typical day begins with an early breakfast, followed
by a three-hour orchestra rehearsal. Three more hours of orchestral
work follow lunch, and after dinner the players regroup as chamber
ensembles for three hours of formal coaching with Laredo; Cohen;
Isaac Stern; Felix Galimir; members of the Guarneri, Juilliard and
Orion String Quartets, and several soloists and orchestra
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Officially the day ends after the chamber music class, but most
of the musicians continue playing music into the night. They also
have to find time to practice their orchestral music, not to
mention the music they were working on with their own teachers at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 10 days we practically didn't get any sleep,'' said Lin,
the violinist, who participated in the seminar in 1977 and 1978 and
has returned in recent years as a member of the coaching faculty.
``We stayed up playing chamber music and having jam sessions until
2 or 3 in the morning. When you're 17 or 18, you don't think about
fatigue. You just have a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   The seminar was started in 1968, the year after the Budapest
Quartet disbanded. Frank Salomon, Schneider's manager, had heard
about a seminar that the quartet offered in Buffalo in which the
ensemble members coached young quartets during the day and led
Vivaldi concertos at night. Schneider had also recently done a
coaching seminar on Long Island, and it occurred to Salomon that
Schneider's pedagogical leanings might be harnessed for 10 days of
coaching around Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Both Salomon and Schneider already had an association with the
New School, where they directed a concert series that has recently
been renamed the Schneider Concerts. And when they told Isaac Stern
about the idea, Carnegie Hall became a co-sponsor of the seminar.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers established an age limit of 15 to 22 for that
first seminar, until they heard a 13-year-old girl play the violin.
``I got very upset about it and said that I didn't want to take
responsibility for having a 13-year-old girl in a hotel in New York
for 10 days,'' said Salomon, who still runs the seminar. ``But
everyone insisted, and she was so talented. So I wrote to her
parents, and in the end she did participate. And that was Laurie
Carney, who is now in the American String Quartet.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The program costs $180,000 a year (up from $70,000 the first
year), or about $3,000 for each student, a third of which is
covered by grants from a foundation that Schneider set up to
support various causes, mostly related to education and Israel.
Private and corporate donations and foundation grants cover part of
the budget as well. And Salomon noted that the coaches work for
what he described as ``honorariums, not fees.''
</P>
<P>
   But Salomon, who is also the seminar's principal fund-raiser,
said those grants had shrunk considerably over the last 15 years.
Government support, too, has all but vanished. The National
Endowment for the Arts, which in past years gave the seminar
$30,000 a year, has reduced its grant to $3,000. Salomon is trying
to raise $270,000, enough to cover 30 scholarships for 3 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it isn't easy,'' he said. ``Less and less money is being
given to classical music, unless you're the Metropolitan Opera.''
</P>
<P>
   The structure of the seminar has not changed much since 1969,
but the transition from Schneider to Laredo has brought a change of
atmosphere. At rehearsals, Schneider had an explosive temperament,
which few seem to have taken personally. Ma, when enumerating the
most valuable aspects of the program, included ``being coached and
yelled at by Sasha Schneider.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, he definitely yelled a lot,'' said Ms. Bachmann, the
violinist, who attended in 1981. ``He wanted it louder all the
time. But I think what he was asking for was intensity of feeling
rather than volume of sound. He struck me as someone who had an
aura that inspired people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lin found himself more directly in the line of fire. He was a
16-year-old student at the Juilliard School when he auditioned for
the seminar, and to his surprise, Schneider made him concertmaster
of the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a concert with the Juilliard Orchestra the day of the
first session,'' Lin said. ``So when I showed up for the first
rehearsal with Sasha, I was two hours late. They were working on
Stravinsky's `Apollo,' which has a huge violin solo. When I
arrived, he growled, `Sit down,' in that gravelly voice of his, and
within a few seconds, the orchestra reached the violin solo. He
coached me in that solo for half an hour, in front of the
orchestra. That was a baptism by fire, and I figured that if I
could survive Sasha Schneider, I could do well in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider was not the only coach who could be temperamental, or
whose anger had a transformative effect on his students. Another
was Schneider's brother Mischa, who had been the cellist in the
Budapest Quartet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mischa Schneider was an important influence on me,'' Ma said.
``And our relationship started in a funny way. I was a rowdy kid,
and I was fooling around when he was coaching us. And he actually
left the room. He was hurt, not because we weren't paying respect
to him, but because he felt we were taking music that he cared
about too lightly. That was a revelation for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Has the calmer atmosphere had a negative effect?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Lin said. ``Jaime tends to get his results
through encouragement, persuasion and cajoling, whereas Sasha's
style was basically volcanic. Both ways work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
