<SLUG> BC-SUPERSHOW24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta loses Super Show to Las Vegas for 3 years
 &HT;    By Susan Harte and Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Super Show, a sporting goods trade show that
annually brings 100,000 people and bestows a $70 million economic
impact on Atlanta, is leaving town for at least three years. After
its late-January stint here in 1999 and 2000, it will be held in
Las Vegas in 2001, 2002 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Graveline, executive director of the Georgia World Congress
Center, was not surprised that Atlanta will lose its largest
convention. ``They have been trying to find a place to go. They
have been excellent. They have worked with us (to overcome
Atlanta's space problems) for several years. If there is a surprise
for me, it is Las Vegas. It is hard to take a show this size and
find a place to put it. I understand that Las Vegas is stringing
together several facilities to accommodate the show.''
</P>
<P>
   The news follows at least a year's worth of conflicting reports
about how long the convention _ which has been in Atlanta since it
began in 1985 _ would stay here. Earlier reports indicated the show
might go to Orlando in 2001 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Show made the decision to leave Atlanta despite the
anticipated approval of an expansion of the Georgia World Congress
Center. The proposed $225 million expansion of the GWCC _ where big
conventions such as the Super Show are housed _ would add 450,000
square feet of space, giving the convention center 1.4 million
square feet of meeting space.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion would put the GWCC on a par with similar
facilities in Orlando and Las Vegas, both major competitors for
lucrative trade shows.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest trade shows are pushing the limits of space
at the GWCC.
</P>
<P>
   Comdex, the nation's largest computer trade show, held its last
meeting here in June 1997. The show, which attracted about 100,000
to its spring meeting here, moved permanently to Chicago. Comdex
holds its larger winter show in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Graveline said Wednesday the convention bureau feels fairly
optimistic about winning approval for the GWCC expansion, ``but we
still have to receive legislative approval this upcoming session.''
If approved this session of the Legislature, the expansion would be
completed by mid-2002.
</P>
<P>
   But the earliest the Super Show could return to Atlanta would be
2004, according to John Riddle, president of the North Palm Beach,
Fla.-based Sporting Goods Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
   The association wants to alternate locations between eastern and
western parts of the country, Riddle said Wednesday. The SGMA will
solicit letters of interest from several cities east and west of
the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, Orlando and New Orleans will be invited to submit
proposals for the third week of January in 2004, 2005 and 2006.
Riddle said a decision will be made by June.
</P>
<P>
   Although the winner will be determined primarily by convention
and exhibition space, amenities such as hotel-rate breaks, low
airfares, transportation and available entertainment will influence
the decision, said Jo Ann Worthington, a member of Meeting
Professionals International, a Dallas-based trade group of
convention planners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space is the critical thing. You also have to have the ability
to house conventioneers. And things to do in the vicinity of the
trade show are very important,'' said Worthington, who is also
associate vice president of the Los Angeles Convention Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
