<SLUG> BC-BIZMAG24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Too much rides on the merger wave
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Exxon and Mobil, $86 billion. Travelers Group and
Citicorp, $73 billion. NationsBank and BankAmerica, $62 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Those are just a few of the megamergers announced or completed
in 1998, a record year for such deals. To understand why it's
happened, Fortune (Jan. 11) says, ``Just follow the money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has more financial capital than it knows what to do
with,'' says the magazine. ``This extraordinary abundance of money
available for investment has fueled this greatest-ever merger wave.
... ''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to this money, there is too much of everything: steel,
paper, chemicals, cloth, airline seats, cars, gold, silver and
aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overcapacity leads to brutal price competition, which leads to
consolidation,'' Fortune explains.
</P>
<P>
   Still more forecasts
</P>
<P>
   Business Week (Dec. 28/Jan. 4) bases its double edition on the
theme of ``shifting to a lower gear.'' With profits under
increasing pressure, investors will have to pick their spots in an
economy marked by ``weaker growth'' and a market without ``lofty
gains.''
</P>
<P>
   Smart Money (January) says the worst thing about the year-end
rally was probably the realization for many investors that they
missed a ``spectacular buying opportunity'' in the 1998 correction.
The magazine lists its stock picks and cautions investors about
Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Money (January) says economic growth and profits will slow in
1999, but low interest rates will prevent a serious recession and
help send stocks still higher _ including 10,000 for the Dow Jones
industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be an ostrich
</P>
<P>
   In its year-end double issue, The Economist (Jan. 1) asks, ``Can
anything, after the turbulence of 1998, still be considered
unthinkable? Ostriches everywhere have had to pull their heads from
the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there are still some important issues we continue
to take for granted, which may be a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We question whether it is really right to assume, as many do,
that nuclear weapons will never be used by (nation) states, that
democracy will continue to spread . . . that shares (of stock) are
always the best long-term investment.''
</P>
<P>
   On nickels and dimes
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever wondered what it's like to live on the minimum
wage, journalist Barbara Ehrenreich tells you in Harper's Magazine
(January).
</P>
<P>
   As a waitress, she learns some of the worst experiences are not
the loss of what money can buy, but how much workers can abuse each
other when they cross over from employee to manager status.
</P>
<P>
   The most redeeming feature of low-wage work, she says, is ``the
camaraderie of people who are, in almost all cases, far too smart
and funny and caring for the work they do and the wages they're
paid.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1850EST &QL; 
