<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSCOW-MAYOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBITIOUS MAYOR PUTS STAMP ON MOSCOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Christmas came early to Moscow's storefronts and
display windows this year, and Vyacheslav Mironov's tiny computer
goods store was no exception, thanks to Moscow's Santa police.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Russia celebrates Christmas according to the
Orthodox Christian tradition on Jan. 7, Yury M. Luzhkov, Moscow's
powerful and ambitious mayor, ordered businesses to put up their
decorations early, lest the capital seem lacking in holiday cheer.
</P>
<P>
   A huge, roly-poly Santa grins next to the frowning statue of the
poet Vladimir Mayakovsky. Crinkly-nosed Kris Kringles smile down
from posters and store shelves. Someone from the city government
even appeared in Mironov's shop to ensure his Western-style Santa
Claus and cheery reindeer were in place.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov's ambitious municipal projects have earned Moscow the
reputation as an island of prosperity in turmoil-stricken Russia
and transformed its mayor into a favorite to succeed Boris N.
Yeltsin as president.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes Luzhkov stand out is his interest in the little
things, such as where businessmen put their Santas.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has reshaped the Russian capital by combining elements
of the free market and the Soviet-style command economy. His city
government has a hand in much of Moscow's business activity, then
uses the proceeds to finance grand architectural projects and stage
attention-grabbing events, such as the city's gala 850th birthday
party in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As the ailing Yeltsin's power wanes, Luzhkov has stepped up
efforts to attract national attention to his can-do leadership, his
Czar-like demeanor and engineer's grasp of microscopic detail. He
promotes a public persona that exudes competence, confidence, and
the-buck-stops-here decisiveness.
</P>
<P>
   These are the qualities, Luzhkov says, that Russians crave after
years of crisis and Yeltsin's absentee leadership. Luzhkov has yet
to declare himself a candidate for the Kremlin. But Saturday, at
the founding congress of ``Fatherland,'' his new political party,
the mayor promised to do for the country what he has done for
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will drag Russia out of the morass,'' he said, his round
face etched in its trademark Edward G. Robinson scowl. ``Gentlemen,
the experiment is over.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when euphoria over the defeat of Communism and
Russia's opening up to the West has faded into disillusionment,
humiliation, and despair, Luzhkov talks about restoring national
pride.
</P>
<P>
   He is a noncommunist nationalist who has spoken out against
racism and anti-Semitism. He is a teetotaling sports enthusiast and
an Orthodox Christian who displays his tolerance for other faiths
by inviting religious leaders to all of his political functions.
With his weekly trips to construction sites and mall openings,
Luzhkov portrays himself as a concerned city manager who has given
something back to the people who elected him.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow voters thanked him in 1996 by electing him to a second
four-year term with more than 90 percent of the vote. His
generosity beyond Moscow is vast. Luzhkov has played the role of a
concerned head of state, bailing out bankrupt Russian hockey teams
and crisis-struck Russian regions, even providing garbage trucks
for the West Bank city of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   It is a resume that none of his likely competitors _ Communist
leader Gennady Zyuganov, liberal lawmaker Grigory Yavlinsky or
Alexander Lebed, the retired general and recently elected Siberian
governor _ can match. Polls indicate that Luzhkov would beat any of
the three in a run-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Luzhkov) is definitely the person to beat,'' said Michael
McFaul, a Stanford professor and a leading expert on Russian
politics.
</P>
<P>
   But first, McFaul and other analysts say, Luzhkov must overcome
several obstacles. Chief among these is the resentment in a poor
land toward the rich capital, and he is the ultimate Muscovite.
When Luzhkov campaigned for Lebed's opponent in Krasnoyarsk
gubernatorial elections in April, Lebed won the most votes in
districts where the Moscow mayor gave speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a more serious problem is that Luzhkov's can-do
reputation is based on the boom his city enjoyed until this summer.
But then came the August collapse of Russia's financial system.
Hundreds of thousands of Muscovites suddenly found themselves out
of work as businesses went bust and foreign investors fled.
Moscow's prosperous image began to suffer.
</P>
<P>
   The city has had difficulty paying its debts, and some critics
think that Luzhkov is in a race against time. Elections are
scheduled for June of 2000, but Yeltsin could die before that,
forcing an early vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any candidate, Luzhkov needs early elections,
because he realizes that the Moscow miracle is ending,'' says
Andrei Piontkowski, a Moscow political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the city remains a showcase for the brand of capitalism
Luzhkov has been building since 1992, when Yeltsin appointed him
mayor and he began transforming Moscow from a drab, gray Soviet
population center to a gleaming capital with world-class ambitions
and Western-style amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Under Luzhkov's direction, buildings have been scrubbed and
painted, roads have been paved, and dozens of sweeping
architectural projects have been completed. Among these are the
$300 million reconstruction of the Church of Christ the Savior,
which was demolished by Soviet dictator Josef Stalin, and a
cavernous $100 million underground shopping mall next to the
Kremlin, under the square where Soviet tanks once paraded.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Luzhkov has rejected the anti-Soviet
principles proposed by Yeltsin's reformist governments during the
past six years. Instead of restructuring Moscow's Communist-era
industry and encouraging the independence of private business,
Luzhkov's government has heavily intervened to prop up the city's
industry. But his showcase projects, bailouts of automakers AZLK
and ZiL, have cost the city dearly while failing to yield
definitive results.
</P>
<P>
   While Luzhkov preaches respect for ethnic diversity, Moscow
police enforce draconian Soviet-era residence restrictions on
migrants from the Caucasus and Central Asia. Although these rules
go against Russia's 1993 constitution, police routinely arrest,
beat, and extort money from dark-skinned people, according to New
York-based Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov's hard-line foreign policy posture also contrasts with
the generally lenient line of Yeltsin's presidency. Luzhkov demands
that the Ukrainian naval port of Sevastopol should be returned to
Russia. He proposes a political union with Serbia. He condemns
citizenship laws in Latvia limiting rights for Russian speakers as
``genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   And Luzhkov has lashed out at the Yeltsin policies that resulted
in shady insider privatization deals. These allowed the creation of
a corrupt class of ``oligarchs'' whose murky business empires
thrived while the country suffered.
</P>
<P>
   But Luzhkov's critics charge that his system is not much better.
Early in his six-year rule as mayor, Luzhkov won exemption for his
city from a federal program to sell off state-owned industrial
holdings. Moscow kept ownership over public property.
</P>
<P>
   Using this control as leverage, Luzhkov has changed the city
government into a multibillion dollar real estate and industrial
empire, with its own television and cable stations, newspapers, an
oil refinery, and a controlling share in more than 180 other
enterprises. And what the city does not own in Moscow, it controls,
thanks to its firm grip on all municipal land and its cozy
relationship with the holding company AFK Sistema, which the weekly
newspaper Novaya Gazeta recently called ``one of the biggest
empires in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had money and power in the hands of thieves for
years,'' says Yury Schekochikhin, a liberal lawmaker who has
investigated corruption in Luzhkov's administration. ``Luzhkov's
administration means money and power in the hands of bureaucrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that the city's dual role as chief regulator and
leading entrepreneur has fostered cronyism, discouraged
competition, and helped make Moscow the world's third most
expensive place to do business after Tokyo and Hong Kong. Business
executives tell dark tales of harassment by tax police and fire
safety inspectors for those who buck the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Moscow economy is terribly bureacratic and regimented, and
the result of that is massive corruption,'' Yegor Gaidar, a leading
liberal economist and a former acting prime minister, said in a
recent article. ``Everyone who has had anything to do with the
Moscow municipal structures knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   But few people dare to come out and say it. Luzhkov takes anyone
who does to court. City hall says he has won 42 defamation
lawsuits, one of them against Gaidar for writing that article.
Local reporters take note and give Luzhkov a wide birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishing something negative about Luzhkov is impossible in
the Russian press,'' says Piontkowski. ``The next day they'll shut
off your plumbing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
