<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD TIMES NOW, BETTER TIMES AHEAD FOR FEMALE ATHLETES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three days before Christmas is an inappropriate time time for a
lesson in basic Darwinism.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot imagine being a player, coach, or other employee of the
American Basketball League, because from everything I've been
hearing Tuesday's demise of the women's professional league was not
exactly something everyone concerned saw coming. I cannot imagine
going to bed one night with a job and awakening to discover that
your world had just fallen apart.
</P>
<P>
   My heart goes out to the players, particularly, because there is
more to being a female professional basketball player in this
country than simply being an accomplished athlete. These women are
crusaders and standard-bearers for female athletes of all
description. You can call it an athletic version of Ya-Ya
Sisterhood, if you like. These woman have been playing to satisfy
themselves, to put food on the table, and to prove a point.
</P>
<P>
   That point is that women can play basketball very well and that
theirs is a game with its own essence and own specific
entertainment value.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the beginning that the harsh dictates of
modern sports economics had doomed this league to a quixotic
status. Experts in the field said, almost without exception, that
the ABL had more quality players than the rival WNBA, whose last
three letters speak to an unbeatable corporate might. It didn't
matter. The ABL had a paltry TV contract, and thus has became the
Little Engine That Couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Just examine the facts. The WNBA, with a 30-game summertime
schedule, has lucrative contracts with NBC, ESPN, and Lifetime. The
ABL, playing a 44-game traditional wintertime schedule, was going
to be seen only 14 times on Fox. CBS was going to do two playoff
games. Better players or not, that was the ABL's lot in life.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so may we step back a minute? As sad as this day is for the
principals, is it not possible that something good can come from
all this? Please, now. Doesn't simple common sense tell us that
having two leagues competing for talent in a marginal sports
setting was lunacy? Having two women's leagues in the same sport in
this country _ even if their seasons did not overlap _ was madness.
</P>
<P>
   You may not feel that way if you adopt the view that the feisty
ABL, which started a year earlier than the WNBA, was somehow more
virtuous. This is now a clear triumph for the bully with superior
resources, and we in America traditionally love the underdog. To
make an au courant analogy from ``You've Got Mail,'' the WNBA is
the aggressive conglomerate Fox &AMP; Sons Book Store and the ABL is
Meg Ryan's adorable Shop Around The Corner. The Big Guy won in the
movie, and the Big Guy wins here. The Big Guy almost always wins.
</P>
<P>
   But the end result of all this will be a strengthened women's
game. Or is it possible I'm missing something here? One powerful
league, with lots of financial resources and every great female
player we can produce under one umbrella, sure sounds a lot better
to me than two female leagues competing in a country where full
acceptance of female basketball players is surely a long way off.
</P>
<P>
   Women's basketball is a growth stock, to be sure. I maintain
that there is no sport in this country that has demonstrated more
technical improvement during the past quarter-century than women's
basketball. Only the very best All-Americans of the early and
mid-'70s would hope to secure a starting spot on a good women's
college team today, and the average star player of the time would
be fortunate to draw a uniform on teams such as Connecticut,
Tennessee, Louisiana Tech, or Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The women's game is not the aerial act the men's game has
become, and so what? When you see a good women's game today you are
looking at the men's game of the '60s or early '70s, and, believe
me, that's a good thing if it means there is less emphasis on
flying through the air and on endless stretches of my-turn,
your-turn one-on-one play than on passing and teamwork. The women
can play. Let me assure you that there isn't a man in the NBA I
would rather see in the middle of a 3-on-2 fast break (itself a
dying concept among the men) than the mercurial Dawn Staley, all
5-feet-whatever of her.
</P>
<P>
   But most men don't want to hear about it, and until a women's
league can rise to a consistent level of play that will attact the
attention of good, solid basketball fans that happen to be male,
the sport can never be the complete success it deserves to be. The
fastest way for that to happen is for all the best players to be
gathered under one corporate roof. Diluting the product with two
leagues was ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the more ``deserving'' league has perished while the
arrogant bully has survived, but the brutal reality is that the
greater good of The Cause will be served by a strengthened WNBA,
which, I may be premature in assuming, will now do the proper thing
and switch to a winter schedule.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be a Merry Christmas for those directly involved.
But there may now be many Merry Christmases in the future when
there is one completely stocked women's league playing the
absolutely best women's basketball anyone has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
