<SLUG> BC-MA-YANDLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVICTED MURDERER'S COMMUTATION ALLOWED TO STAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Joseph Yandle, the convicted felony murderer who won
his freedom three years ago but landed back in jail last summer for
fabricating a record of Vietnam War heroism, Wednesday kept his
gubernatorial commutation, although he could still face some long
prison time.
</P>
<P>
   The Governor's Council rejected 5 to 2 Governor Paul Cellucci's
request that it revoke the commutation from Yandle, who had served
23 years in prison. The council approved his commutation in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Yandle's future now depends on the gubernatorially appointed
Parole Board, which had revoked his parole in August after reports
surfaced that he had lied about his war record.
</P>
<P>
   The board is set to take up Yandle's case on Jan. 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope is that they keep him in jail,'' Cellucci said after
the the Governor Council rebuff. ``I would hope that he is not
released soon.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jonathan Shapiro, Yandle's lawyer, questioned the wisdom of
keeping his client incarcerated, particularly since the Governor's
Council has never taken action on about a dozen other commutations
given to inmates who later commited serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only issue now is whether the punishment fits the crime,''
Shapiro said after the vote. ``What sense is there to keep a person
in prison . . . for essentially telling a lie?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if the members of the parole board show the same
integrity shown by members of the Governor's Council, then they
will not punish Mr. Yandle any more than he has been punished,''
Shapiro added.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci had argued that former Governor William F. Weld had
recommended the commutation to the council based in part on
Yandle's false claim to have had a distinguished combat record.
However, Weld's letter to the Governor's Council recommending
Yandle for commutation never mentioned his supposed war heroism.
</P>
<P>
   Yandle had stated in a commutation request in the 1980s _ which
was denied _ that he had become addicted to drugs in Vietnam and
that the addiction helped push him into a life of crime when he
returned. He won strong support from Vietnam War veterans groups in
his bid for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Yandle was the driver in a 1972 hold-up of a liquor store in
which a clerk was shot to death. After his 1995 commutation, Yandle
moved to Vermont where he worked as a teacher and youth counselor.
</P>
<P>
   At a Governor's Council hearing last week, Yandle, who was
praised by his supporters as a savior of troubled youth, apologized
for fabricating a combat record. He also pleaded to be allowed a
chance to return to his Vermont home. If the council had revoked
the commutation, he would have had to serve the rest of his life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those councilors who voted against revoking the
commutation argued that there was no evidence that Weld and
then-Lieutenant Governor Cellucci had backed Yandle's bid for
freedom based on his false military documents.
</P>
<P>
   Councilor Christopher Iannella Jr., a Democrat from Jamaica
Plain, said the record shows that the board of pardons had approved
Yandle's commutation because of his record of rehabilitation in
prison, and not his Vietnam War record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was released from prison because of his institutional
record, not because of his military record,'' Iannella said. ``He
was a model prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rapucci, one of two sons of the murdered store clerk,
Joseph Rapucci, and his wife, Ann, sat grim-faced through the
meeting. Afterward, both declined comment, but attorney Bob Launie,
Ann's cousin, denounced the council's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we are disappointed with the vote,'' said Launie,
who said it showed that Yandle's ``lies and deception . . . have
served him very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Launie, like Cellucci, said he thought that Yandle's supposed
Vietnam War heroism had played an important role in the commutation
of his life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yandle got to the Governor's Council in 1995 through the fraud
he committed,'' Launie said. ``We have an advisory opinion . . .
which clearly stated that they considered it. The governor has
stated he considered it at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Hudner, state commissioner of Veterans Services, who had
supported Yandle in his 1995 bid for a commutation, also decried
the council's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did commit an abhorrent crime'' in using forged military
records to support bogus claims of war heroism, Hudner said.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said the council's decision is a signal that lying and
commiting fraud will be tolerated in these kinds of cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It attacks the integrity of the entire system if you can
obtain a commutation or pardon by fraud,'' Cellucci told reporters
after the council vote.
</P>
<P>
   He also rejected any interpretation of the vote as a political
defeat for him. ``I think it is a defeat for right and wrong,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
