<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-RESIGN-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR ASSOCIATE QUITS OVER QUESTIONABLE LOAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Prime Minister Tony Blair's closest confidant, the
architect of the Labor Party's 1997 election victory, resigned
Wednesday over his failure to disclose that he had received a loan
from someone who came under investigation by his own department.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Peter Mandelson, the trade and industry minister
in Blair's Cabinet, said he was stepping down to spare the
government embarrassment and to redeem its pledge to be ``whiter
than white, squeaky clean.''
</P>
<P>
   A principal thrust of Blair's successful campaign had been
repeated pledges to run a government free of the kinds of scandals
that plagued his Conservative predecessor, John Major. Mandelson, a
prime persecutor of the Tories, told the prime minister, ``We can't
be like the last lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson said he had erred in not making the necessary
declaration of a $625,000 low-interest home loan he accepted in
1996 from Geoffrey Robinson, a millionaire colleague in the
government whose outside business interests have come under
scrutiny by his office. Robinson, the paymaster general, also
resigned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In an exchange of correspondence that captured the sadness both
Blair and he were experiencing, Mandelson said, ``Dear Tony, I can
scarcely believe I am writing this letter to you,'' and Blair
responded, ``Dear Peter, You will know better than anyone the
feelings with which I write to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson, a member of Parliament from a district in Northeast
England and formerly the Labor Party's director of communications,
was credited with recasting the party's fusty image to make it
electable after 18 years in opposition. ``It is no exaggeration to
say that without your support and advice we would never have built
New Labor,'' Blair wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson changed the party's red-flag symbol to a red rose and
shaped its agenda to suit the tastes and desires of an electorate
that the party researched through his office's focus group
techniques. He also encouraged leaders of the party to redirect
their political approach to make it more alluring to middle-class
voters and business.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, he became a suspect figure to members of the
party's left wing and trade union movement and to people who
resented the secrecy of his methods and his close friendship with
Blair. The prime minister often quipped that Mandelson was the man
that New Labor had to learn to love.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson also became the principal target of Conservatives
looking for a Labor figure with more public vulnerability than
Blair, who continues to enjoy record approval ratings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He was largely responsible for recasting Labor, and, by
extension, Britain, as fast-paced and up to date.
</P>
<P>
   The dashing 45-year-old Mandelson became the government's most
cosmopolitan member, appearing at society and cultural events and
mixing with royalty. He successfully resisted blunt efforts by the
press to make him formally declare his homosexuality. He was the
only member of the government with this social season's most
coveted ticket: an invitation to the 50th birthday party for
Charles, the Prince of Wales, at his Highgrove estate.
</P>
<P>
   His success in that world and his growing comfort with its
tastes may have contributed to an overreach that produced
Wednesday's downfall. In 1996 Mandelson decided he would like to
move from his modest home in Clerkenwell to a much larger one in
the more fashionable Notting Hill area of west London. His salary
as a back-bench member of Parliament was $72,000. The house cost
$790,000.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, his colleague on the back benches, extended the loan,
and Mandelson bought the house. He said at the time that he
expected that money from a coming family inheritance would enable
him to pay it back promptly.
</P>
<P>
   He did not record the transaction with record keepers in
Parliament, did not acknowledge it in his formal mortgage
application and did not mention it to Blair or other government
colleagues when questions about Robinson's financial interests
ended up being investigated by the department of which he had
become the head.
</P>
<P>
   When a report appeared in The Guardian on Tuesday, Mandelson
went on radio and television to say that he had done nothing wrong
and that he had ``insulated'' himself from any involvement in the
Robinson inquiry. By Tuesday night he had become persuaded that the
lapse constituted an ``impression of wrongdoing,'' and he called
the prime minister to offer his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the loan Wednesday, he said: ``I should have been
more open about it. I should have informed my colleagues. I should
have informed my permanent secretary, and in so doing I would have
protected myself against the appearance of a conflict of interest
that has subsequently arisen.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some suggestion in the comments and exchange of
letters Wednesday that while Mandelson may be leaving his coveted
Cabinet seat, he will not be far away from the government. Blair
ended his brief letter with the sentence, ``But I also want you to
know that you have my profound thanks for all you have done and my
belief that, in the future, you will achieve much, much more with
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
