u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FED-RATES-NYT &LR;      12-23 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NOVEMBER'S RATE CUT, FED WAS CONCERNED ABOUT MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Reserve's decision Nov. 17 to cut
interest rates was driven by concern that problems in the financial
markets might again intensify and drag down the economy, according
to a summary of the meeting released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed cut its benchmark rate a quarter of a percentage point
at the meeting despite the possibility that a reduction might push
stock prices unsustainably higher, and in the face of evidence that
the economy was not slowing as much as most analysts had expected,
minutes of the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the policy-making Federal Open Market Committee
also voted at the Nov. 17 meeting to remove its formal bias toward
further rate cuts and to adopt a neutral outlook _ one that did not
lean either toward monetary easing or tightening. At its subsequent
meeting, on Tuesday, the Fed held rates steady. The minutes of
Tuesday's meeting will be released in February.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank committee concluded at the November meeting
that ``further easing was not likely to be needed over the months
ahead unless ongoing developments pointed to a more substantial
decline in the growth of economic activity or further ebbing of
inflation than was currently anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Some investors interpreted the account of the November meeting
to mean that the Fed might be more hesitant to reduce interest
rates next year than economists had assumed, especially because
economic indicators in the last month have suggested that growth
remains robust despite the continuing global financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices, which had been up sharply, dipped after the
minutes were released Wednesday afternoon but then rebounded
sharply. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 157.57 points, to
9,202.03.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed minutes said the decision to cut rates in November ``was
viewed as a close call by several members,'' and that while the
economy was expected to slow heading into next year, ``the
expansion currently displayed only modest signs of moderating from
what seemed to be an unsustainable pace.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee was particularly concerned about the stock market,
which after plunging over the summer had rebounded substantially
and by November was again at levels that some analysts thought was
unsustainable, particularly if corporate profits did not keep pace
with investors' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the committee's members, the minutes said, ``saw some
risk that an easing move at this point might trigger a strong
further advance in stock market prices that would not be justified
on the basis of likely future earnings and could therefore lead to
a relatively sharp and disruptive market adjustment later.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, the committee decided that it should cut
rates one more time to help calm the markets and in particular to
help ease a persistent credit squeeze. The almost total absence of
inflation gave the Fed considerable leeway to lower rates, the
minutes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A further easing move would complete the policy adjustment to
the changed economic and financial climate that had emerged since
midsummer,'' the Fed continued, ``and would provide some insurance
against any unexpectedly severe weakening of the expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to reduce the federal funds target rate on
overnight loans between banks, to 4.75 percent from 5 percent, was
approved by a 10-to-1 vote at the meeting, the minutes said. The
dissenter was Jerry Jordan, president of the Federal Reserve Bank
of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who is perhaps the most single-minded inflation fighter
in the Fed, said that two previous quarter-point rate reductions
during the fall had been sufficient to deal with the problems in
the financial markets and that an additional rate cut risked
reigniting inflation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
