<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV27     12-23 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV27 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: WHO'S WATCHING WHOM ON TV?
 &HT;    Advance for release Sunday, Dec. 27
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON We spent the last half of this century watching TV.
In the century to come, television will watch us.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, we're already there. In 1999, cable companies, using
digital set-top boxes, will be able to selectively target both
programs and ads not only to individual households but also
uniquely to each TV set in that household. The fare will be based
on viewers' watching and buying habits.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials we see depend on which programs we select. In
the future, software can insert customized commercials in ways that
are cloaked to viewers.
</P>
<P>
   A cable outlet could then cull lists of high net worth retirees
and match those names to its subscriber base. Only those people
would then see ads for, say, a financial product. Or only the
dog-owners, similarly identified by their credit card purchases,
would see dog food commercials.
</P>
<P>
   A monograph posted on the web by the ``Addressable Advertising
Coalition'' explains what's about to happen:
</P>
<P>
   ``Technological advancements in cable systems, direct broadcast
satellites and the coming telephone company video operations offer
the promise of even further micro-targeting of ad messages. Digital
telecasting offers message targeting to the individual residence.''
</P>
<P>
   Money is an issue. As the coalition's paper notes, cable
operators have regarded ad revenues ``to be peripheral rather than
a core business, because advertising revenue per home, per year is
$25.97 vs. $428.05 per home, per year in subscriber revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   But privacy is also an issue _ one that the industry paper
skirts, noting merely that ``addressability ... can be transparent
to the consumer unless the consumer wants to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Government regulators permit the cable industry to gather data
on customers. Operators can collect and aggregate information on
individuals if they have ``prior written or electronic consent of
the subscriber,'' as the Federal Communications Commission puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agency's rules, that data can then be disclosed to
outsiders ``if such disclosure is necessary to render, or conduct a
legitimate business activity related to cable television or other
service(s) provided to the subscriber.''
</P>
<P>
   Cable lawyers argue their legal road is already paved. Web
publishers, using ``cookies,'' keep abreast of what users do on
their sites and where they go when they leave. Local telephone
companies mine data from call records. They then use those records
in their direct marketing campaigns and make them available to
cops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just taking it up another level,'' Cynthia Brumfeld, a
senior analyst at Paul Kagan Associates Inc., told the trade
publication Interactive Week. ``(American Express) already knows
everything you buy and Amazon knows what you read. It's just having
all of these things funneling through one centralized place.''
</P>
<P>
   In small towns, where newspapers often print lists of most local
happenings, privacy has long been a relative matter. Now the same
criteria are about to be extended to the global village. Before
that occurs, it would be wise to be sure we're standing on sound
legal and ethical feet.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
