<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARKANSAS-SUSPECT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN ARKANSAS KILLING CAUGHT IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUEVO LAREDO, Mexico _ An American wanted for murder in Arkansas
and who evaded authorities in three states was captured among
Christmas shoppers by the Mexican police Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   James Edward Tillis, 30, briefly fought with two bicycle
policemen who spotted him walking a few blocks from the Rio Grande
in a shopping district popular with tourists visiting from nearby
Laredo, Texas, police chief Pedro Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. authorities negotiated for his return, a tattered and
remorseful Tillis remained in the custody of the Mexican federal
police on charges he illegally entered this country.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Mexican police officers had been searching for Tillis,
who does not speak Spanish, and had last been seen soaking wet in
near-freezing temperatures after jumping in the Rio Grande Tuesday
to escape U.S. Border Patrol agents.
</P>
<P>
   Personal problems triggered a Sunday incident when, Tillis said,
he attacked two people, including his ex-girlfriend's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin King, 44, of West Helena, Ark., was killed. Brenda Green's
throat was slashed, but she was released from a hospital Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my temper and was caught in a whirlpool of sin,'' a
handcuffed Tillis said as he sat in the federal police headquarters
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that happens, anything can happen,'' he said. ``I want to
apologize to the families _ mine and theirs _ for their
suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Tillis' alleged crime wave rolled into Texas Monday when a state
trooper near Austin stopped him when he saw the man using a coat
hanger to get into a vehicle, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle turned out to be stolen, and Tillis escaped into
nearby woods, the police said. He said he later tied up a man and
stole clothes and a truck before heading to Mexico to start a new
life.
</P>
<P>
   Tillis, who wore a ragged Dallas Cowboys jacket and green
trousers, said he had spent the night with a family in Nuevo Laredo
who saw that he was wet, desperate and needed a place to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of poor people here,'' said Tillis, who is
from Mississippi. ``We're all poor, and they'll help you out.''
</P>
<P>
   It was here, Tillis said, that he thought he could catch a
breather from a manhunt that included authorities in Tennessee,
Arkansas and Texas. He said he planned to go to the coastal resort
of Acapulco.
</P>
<P>
   A Mexican federal prosecutor, who declined to give his name,
said Tillis would be held on immigration charges and could serve up
to two years in prison before being deported to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he'd get caught, we just didn't know when,'' Capt.
Bill Williams of the West Helena Police Department said by phone
from Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Alcorta Flores, one of the policemen who arrested Tillis,
said there was a brief struggle, but he and the other officer
managed to handcuff the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can handle ourselves here,'' Alcorta said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1914EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
