<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POP-LIFE-NYT &LR;      12-23 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-LIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP LIFE: COUNTRY `SPICE GIRLS'; JULIAN LENNON REDUX; RECORD
SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEEKING MODELS WHO CAN SING
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One night, David Foster had a dream. It was more
of a realization, actually, but he calls it a dream. He was
thinking about niches, and what kind of gaps there are in popular
music that need to be filled.
</P>
<P>
   One was for soul singers on the order of Teddy Pendergrass and
Marvin Gaye. Since Foster, whose recent experience is as a producer
for musicians like Celine Dion, Whitney Houston, Natalie Cole,
Michael Bolton, Barbra Streisand and Toni Braxton, has been
plunging deeper into country music, he didn't feel immediately
compelled to fill that gap.
</P>
<P>
   Then he began to think about the Spice Girls. They make great
records, he thought, but they aren't as strong vocally as they
could be. What if he _ David Foster, 14-time Grammy winner _ put
together a Spice Girls equivalent in country music, but with better
singers, and built them to last?
</P>
<P>
   After all, with Shania Twain and the Dixie Chicks topping the
charts, the line between country singer and professional model is
beginning to blur.
</P>
<P>
   And so Foster began his search for Lace _ a conceptual
combination of the Spice Girls, Ms. Twain and the Dixie Chicks.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't heard of Lace, don't feel bad. They don't exactly
exist yet. But try to remember the name and see if, by the end of
next year, his dream has become a pop music reality.
</P>
<P>
   Lace has already recorded an album for Foster's label, 143
Records, with Chris Farren (who also worked with Deana Carter)
helping with production. But the trio's lineup isn't complete. One
singer, Annalee Fery (the real-life girlfriend of Jonathan
Silverman of NBC's ``Single Guy''), still needs to be replaced
because she didn't fit the mix. And Foster doesn't want to release
the record until he has the faces to match the music. The album,
led by the single ``I Want a Man,'' is likely to be in stores in
March or April.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he thought the prospects were for a country-pop
crossover group like Lace, Kerry Wolfe, the operations manager at
the Milwaukee country-music radio station WMIL, noted that people
have called the female trio the Dixie Chicks the Spice Girls of
country, although the tag is not exactly accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all boils down to the music,'' he said of Foster's Lace.
``If he is putting together a package that's visually attractive
and they can sing and sell a song, then by all means, bring it
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster discovered two members of Lace in Canada. It began with
Beverley Mahood, an acclaimed Canadian country singer whose
independent-label video, ``Girl Out of the Ordinary,'' he spotted
on television in his hotel room one night. Eventually, he tracked
her down and put the first piece of Lace in place. She was a
perfect candidate _ Ms. Mahood had been singing since she was 6
(first performing on a bill with Anne Murray), and grew up not just
on Patsy Cline but also on pop singers like Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   The second singer is Giselle Brohman, who has a different look
and a higher voice than Ms. Mahood. But Foster is having trouble
finding a third member. Everyone who fits the bill, he said, wants
a solo career and he is hoping Lace will have a ``five- to ten-year
run.''
</P>
<P>
   The new band is ``going to turn heads,'' said the 24-year-old
Ms. Mahood. She has also signed a deal for a solo record with
Foster.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the Spice Girls concept, Ms. Mahood said she
didn't mind the comparison. ``Who wouldn't want to be the Spice
Girls right now?'' she asked. ``I want to be the Spice Girls, but I
want to be the Spice Girls with a lot of talent and I want to be
around for a couple of years at least.''
</P>
<P>
   Lace's manager, Tom Cross, said: ``The trick is this third
singer. It's easy to find a deadly looking girl. It's really hard
to find a deadly looking girl who's deadly talented. If this isn't
real, it won't work. We argue about the third girl every day.
David's looking, we're looking.''
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly is Foster looking for in a Lace member? ``Beauty
and talent and youth,'' he said, quickly adding, ``Does that sound
like a sexist remark?''
</P>
<P>
   He thought about his question for a second and then added, half
apologetically, ``It's my vision.''
</P>
<P>
   A LENNON RETURNS
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the record Julian Lennon released in May in Britain is
coming to the United States. It is scheduled to be in on stores on
Feb. 23 the Fuel 2000/Universal Records label. It is ``Photograph
Smile,'' the first record that Lennon (son of John) has put out
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The album is so admired it makes one wonder why it took so long
for an American record label to release it. Unlike the record by
his half-brother Sean, ``Into the Sun'' (which was released in
Britain the same day as Julian Lennon's album), ``Photograph
Smile'' is pure Beatles-esque pop.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if Julian Lennon wasn't the son of a Beatle,
``Photograph Smile'' (originally released on Julian's label, Music
From Another Room) would be hailed as a retro-pop classic and
Julian a more mainstream contemporary of underground pop savants
like Apples in Stereo, the Wondermints and the High Llamas.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the legacy of Julian's father hangs all over
``Photograph Smile.'' Lennon's voice is eerily similar to his
father's solo work, and his lyrics begging for world peace and
offering love as the answer to all problems follow in Dad's
footsteps. At times, Julian seems to be quoting songs like ``Lucy
in the Sky with Diamonds'' and ``Nobody Told Me.'' But his more
traditional pop instincts seem to be as derived from Paul McCartney
as they are from his father.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Lennon has said that this feels like his first real album
because it is the only time he has had complete artistic freedom.
The record is filled with swelling strings, lush melodies and
lyrics that vacillate between apology and devotion.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Sean's record, when ``Photograph Smile'' errs it is
toward the middle of the road instead of the fringes. The album
begins with Julian declaring, ``I have walked through the fire as
an ordinary man,'' perhaps referring to his musical time off _ five
of those years spent waiting for an old record contract to expire.
</P>
<P>
   Then he declares, cannily, that ``Daddy's work is never done.''
</P>
<P>
   CHARTING SALES
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for last-minute musical Christmas presents,
here is what the rest of the country is buying.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures released Wednesday by Soundscan, a company
in Hartsdale, N.Y., that monitors music sales, the No. 1 selling
album for the fifth consecutive week was Garth Brooks' ``Double
Live'' two-CD concert set. It sold 548,000 copies last week, nearly
100,000 more than it did the week before.
</P>
<P>
   At No. 2, Celine Dion's disk of holiday cheer, ``These Are
Special Times,'' holds its place for a third week with 535,000
copies sold.
</P>
<P>
   At No. 3 is 'N Sync's self-titled album, followed by albums by
Jewel, Mystikal, the Backstreet Boys, Mariah Carey, Shania Twain,
the Offspring and 'N Sync again with its Christmas record. In the
meantime, Whitney Houston's album ``My Love Is Your Love''
continues to disappoint, sliding down the charts this week to No.
25.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, in a period when the record business generally
stops releasing music by big-name acts because most labels are on
vacation and have already put out their major albums around
Thanksgiving time, new music by three artists emerged in the Top
40: Mystikal (at No. 5), Busta Rhymes (at 13) and DJ Clue? (at 26).
</P>
<P>
   All are rap acts, a genre that continues to mystify the
established record business by breaking all the rules and getting
away with it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
