<HEADER>
A4885 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOGEN-TOBIN-BOS &LR;      12-23 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOGEN-TOBIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOGEN CHIEF QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   James R. Tobin abruptly resigned Wednesday as president and
chief executive of Biogen Inc. for undisclosed personal reasons,
surprising both Wall Street analysts and the local biotechnology
community.
</P>
<P>
   His sudden departure comes exactly five years to the day that he
left Baxter International Inc., the Deerfield, Ill., medical
products company at which he was president, to join Biogen.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin's resignation and the lack of a definitive explanation why
caused Biogen shares to drop 7 1/16, or 8 percent, to 79 15/16
Wednesday, after hitting a 52-week high Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, 54, will be succeeded by James L. Vincent, Biogen's
chairman, who said he will serve as president and chief executive
of the Cambridge company for one to two years.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned about Tobin's decision to leave, Vincent repeatedly
stressed the reasons were unrelated to the biotech company's
performance or his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``He decided to tender his resignation,'' said Vincent. ``This
was not a discharge or a gentle pushing or a whisper in the ear,
nothing to do with the board or the company suggesting that we
wanted to him to leave. This event is not connected with any other
happening at the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Since joining Biogen in January 1994, Tobin has been
instrumental in getting Avonex, the company's injectable medication
to treat multiple sclerosis, on the market. Its strong sales have
made it the biggest-selling drug in the field. He also helped
expand Biogen's pipeline of promising new drugs and forge several
drug development alliances with leading pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``His leaving came a bit suddenly, but we have a good management
team and the company is doing great,'' said Phillip A. Sharp, a
Biogen director and head of the biology department at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, who earned $973,000 in salary and bonus last year, was
unavailabe for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with Wall Street analysts, Vincent stressed
there will be no ``lurching changes,'' and that the company will
stick with its corporate strategy. He said there were no
disagreements over the direction of the company, adding he does not
expect any other departures of senior Biogen executives stemming
from Tobin's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Tobin's personal reasons for exiting the company
were related to alcohol or drug abuse, Vincent said he would not
comment beyond saying they were personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be lots of scenarios that people will think about,
but there really are no other issues involved with this event,''
said Vincent, adding he did not know of Tobin's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to joining Biogen, Tobin had a 21-year career at Baxter,
where he rose from financial analyst to president.
</P>
<P>
   He told the Globe in 1994 he joined Biogen, ``looking for a new
challenge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1928EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
