<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clouds loom over Lockheed Martin production, purchases
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Lockheed Martin Corp.'s aircraft plant falls silent
today for an annual weeklong holiday shutdown, workers and
executives can look back on favorable events during the year.
</P>
<P>
   Deliveries of new C-130J cargo planes finally began after
several delays, and the F-22 fighter has just won an initial
production contract.
</P>
<P>
   Yet clouds keep popping up on the horizon for the plant and its
9,200 employees.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the acting secretary of the Air Force said in
Washington there are no plans _ yet, anyway _ to accelerate
long-term C-130J purchases to help fill a looming order gap between
2001 and 2004. Unless the Air Force pushes up some orders, the
Marietta, Ga., production line could face at least a temporary
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Lockheed Martin warned for the second time that
fourth-quarter corporate earnings would be hurt by various factors,
including the lag in C-130J deliveries. At least two Wall Street
analysts cut their rating on the aerospace giant's stock, which
plummeted 14 percent on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the latest news is conventional wisdom that the
Marietta plant's clout with the Pentagon and Congress soon will
wane. The exit of Republican House Speaker Newt Gingrich, whose
district includes the plant, leaves it with no highly placed
political patron for the first time in decades.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lockheed Martin's corporate growth has made
the Marietta plant a smaller piece of a bigger pie than it was only
a few years ago, before Lockheed merged with Martin Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes magazine rattled nerves by suggesting in its last issue
that Bethesda, Md.-based Lockheed Martin and its cost-cutting
executives could get rid of an outdated ``albatross'' by closing
the Marietta plant and moving its programs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The article questioned whether a planned $350 million
write-down, disclosed in recent Lockheed Martin financial filings,
is really an early installment on plant closing and severance
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer quite simply is no,'' said Terry Graham, executive
vice president and chief operating officer for Lockheed Martin
Aeronautical Systems, the division headquartered at the Marietta
plant.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Graham acknowledged the plant, built
by the Air Force during World War II and leased by Lockheed Martin
since, faces challenges and uncertainty. But he expressed
confidence it will be sustained.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the level of business we have, with a backlog of C-130J
orders through 2001 and the F-22 program moving forward, anyone's
assertion (that the plant should be closed) is just unfounded,''
Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   He said it would be too costly to move its work to other plants
even if Lockheed Martin's top brass wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   Just this month, the plant completed a $35 million overhaul of
the tooling and assembly line for the C-130J, with a goal of
cutting production time and costs. Also, tens of millions have been
invested in the F-22 final assembly line and special testing
facilities for the state-of-the-art fighter, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Graham and his boss, Aeronautical Systems President William
Bullock, both were installed within the past two years with a
mandate to update the plant's processes and cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   That came in the wake of the troubled C-130J development
project, whose costs rose to $900 million and which ran about two
years behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most military programs, Lockheed developed the plane at
its own expense, gambling it could then generate a profitable mix
of U.S. and foreign orders.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chairman and Chief Executive Vance Coffman, Lockheed
Martin has closed about 16 million square feet of factory space
elsewhere. But James Fetig, a spokesman at the Bethesda
headquarters, backed up Marietta management, saying ``there's no
chance Marietta will be moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say a shutdown ordered from Bethesda is an extreme
scenario they doubt will occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be a little surprised. In fact, I would be a lot
surprised,'' said Paul Nisbet, of JSA Research. He said C-130J
program delays and costs have been troubling but do not tarnish its
long-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about twice the price of earlier models and that has
undoubtedly slowed sales, but it's very likely to be in production
for the next 20 years,'' Nisbet said. ``They may not make more than
20 or 25 a year, but that's enough, and it has no real
competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Filling the gap
</P>
<P>
   The order gap looms large nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   The Marietta plant has built 33 C-130Js so far _ deliveries were
held up until the plane gained certification last summer _ and has
orders for another 57. That's enough to keep the production line
open into 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five of those orders are from the U.S. government, the
rest from foreign buyers such as the British Royal Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Air Force wants to eventually buy 150 more C-130Js to
replace aging older models, but it doesn't want them until 2004.
Hence the possible production gap.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by Gingrich, the Air Force last month sent a team to
Marietta to explore ways to prevent a break, since the costs of a
shutdown and restart could inflate the price of planes built later.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said Aeronautical Systems proposed that the Air Force
push some purchases forward and buy an average 12 planes a year.
``We've shown we can save them big money doing it that way,''
Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Air Force Secretary Whitten Peters on Wednesday told
reporters in Washington there is no plan to accelerate the
purchases, although he added there would be more discussions.
Whether his comments simply restated the situation or suggest the
Air Force is digging in its heels remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's no change in their position,'' Graham said. ``We're
still optimistic we're going to work this problem and get it
solved.''
</P>
<P>
   If an accelerated Air Force order doesn't materialize, Graham
said, Aeronautical Systems will try to fill the gap by generating
separate orders for Air National Guard or Reserve planes, or from
the Marine Corps. It also continues to seek more foreign orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any debate about a role for the
C-130J,'' said Steve Kosiak, an analyst at the Defense Budget
Project in Washington. ``The question is whether we need them
sooner or later.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Air Force might well save money in the long run by
accelerating purchases but added: ``The problem is you can make
that case with any weapons program, and you can't accelerate them
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question becomes whether you end up delaying one program
to accelerate another, which negates the benefits,'' Kosiak said.
</P>
<P>
   Dwindling influence?
</P>
<P>
   An unknown is the impact of Gingrich's departure, which follows
by two years the retirement of Democratic U.S. Sen. Sam Nunn, a
heavyweight on defense matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gingrich made a major suggestion to the Air Force that it
consider buying C-130Js in the first place, when Lockheed needed an
initial order,'' Kosiak noted. ``The Air Force had been reluctant
but seemed to come around.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Kosiak said it is simplistic to assume
Gingrich's departure leaves the Marietta plant friendless. He noted
the C-130, in both old and new models, has long enjoyed broad
support in Congress because of its use by Guard and Reserve units
in districts across the nation. Congress routinely buys more than
the Pentagon seeks for Guard and Reserve modernization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been a single-party, single-state, or single-man
program,'' Graham said. ``To think that one person could drive
purchases is just naive.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from keeping the C-130J and F-22, Marietta plant
executives hope to land contracts for modification work on older
C-130s, C-5 airlifters and P-3 naval patrol planes, Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Longer-range, they are eyeing a contract for a new carrier-based
utility aircraft for the Navy, but that's still a decade or so
away.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of the Marietta plant is unused, which also has
prompted speculation Lockheed Martin may seek a partnership in
which it would make parts for a civilian aircraft company. Graham
acknowledged that potential but added it remains speculative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're exploring a number of possibilities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
