<HEADLINE>
CINCINNATI'S MARTIN HATES GETTING HIS SHOTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kenyon Martin likes to complain. He particularly likes to gripe
when he gets too many shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?
</P>
<P>
   A basketball player moaning and groaning about too many
offensive opportunities. What's next? A presidential impeachment?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anyone thinking I'm being selfish, looking at it
like, `All the plays are for him,' '' said Martin, who made it
clear he was not pleased with himself after gunning 10 shots in the
season opener. ``I just want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a 6-foot-8 junior center from Dallas Adams High School,
has been a big reason why Cincinnati is 10-0 and ranked No. 4. The
Bearcats have plenty of perimeter scorers, but for the team to be
successful, it needs a dependable scoring threat in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Martin is averaging a modest 11.2 points per game,
third-best on the Cincinnati roster. He also averages 6.9 rebounds
and 2.8 blocked shots per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenyon's the kind of guy that does a lot of things that aren't
going to show up on the box score,'' Huggins said. ``He makes the
pressure defense so much better, and what he doesn't block, he
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tremendously improved offensively, he's just not very
assertive. He's very happy if somebody else scores and we win. It's
very admirable in a lot of ways. But for us to continue to be
successful, he needs to be more offensive minded than what he's
been.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati has victories over Duke (when it was ranked No. 1)
and at Minnesota (which was ranked No. 17). The Bearcats, who,
under coach Bob Huggins' command, play some of the toughest defense
in the country, could be a team to reckon with come March.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has had his moments. He had 16 points and 16 rebounds in
the season opener at Rhode Island. And he had 22 points against
Nicholls State, breaking a string of five consecutive games scoring
in single digits.
</P>
<P>
   ``My numbers aren't real good, but teams still notice I'm out
there,'' said Martin, who twice has been named Conference USA's
player of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholls State noticed when Martin blocked a shot by catching
the ball, then turned and dribbled the length of the court before
throwing a perfect lob pass for a dunk. Nevada-Las Vegas noticed
when Martin made 11 of 12 shots for a season-high 23 points, and,
by the way, had 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Martin was content to rebound and block shots while
allowing Bobby Brannen to do most of the front-court scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's happened to Ken is that a year ago he was the
`other' guy, and now he's `the' guy,'' Huggins said. ``It was Bob a
year ago, and that's shifted to Kenyon. He's so unselfish he's not
going to try to make a lot of things happen on his own.''
GOTTFRIED'S ADVISERS
</P>
<P>
   First-year Alabama coach Mark Gottfried figures that he has
learned his coaching moves from some of the best. He played for the
Crimson Tide under Wimp Sanderson. And as an assistant at UCLA he
spent time asking questions of the Wizard of Westwood, John Wooden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an opportunity while I was at UCLA as a young coach to
go over to Coach Wooden's house on a number of occasions,''
Gottfried said. ``I'd sit for hour after hour and we'd talk very
little about basketball, but mostly about life situations. I'd ask
him, `As a coach, how would you handle this situation?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Sanderson is one of the people who's always there for me
to go to for advice and wisdom. I enjoyed playing for coach
Sanderson. He's a great coach, and I don't think that nationally he
ever got the recognition he deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old Gottfried, who was 68-24 in three seasons at
Murray State, is becoming recognized as one of the nation's top
young coaches. The Crimson Tide was 10-2 going into last night's
championship game of the Pearl Harbor Classic against Michigan
State.
CURRYING FAVOR
</P>
<P>
   Before their game at Kansas State's Bramlage Coliseum on
Saturday, Missouri-Kansas City players tried to elicit some
sympathetic support from the home crowd. During pregame warmups,
they wore T-shirts that said ``Congratulations K-State Football
11-1'' on the front and ``No BCS'' on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be the only \Rpolitical\S statement we make all year,''
Kangaroos coach Bob Sundvold said. ``\RBill\S Snyder's group has
done a great job. It's a tribute to what they've done in football.
We just thought we'd have a little fun with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats proceeded to have a little fun with the Kangaroos,
winning 67-39.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, UMKC's T-shirt idea isn't original. In January 1995,
Missouri played at Nebraska and wore T-shirts congratulating the
Huskers on their 1994 national championship in football. And
Sundvold is a former Missouri assistant coach. No longer missing
Person Auburn's sizzling 11-0 start _ the school's best in 40 years
_ got a boost when Adrian Person became eligible after transferring
from Southern Union junior college in Alabama . The 6-7, 240-pound
Person is the nephew of former Auburn stars Chuck and Wesley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got better range than Chuck,'' Southern Union coach Ron
Radford told the ``Birmingham Post-Herald''. ``He's better in the
post than Chuck or Wesley. He's the total package. He can play from
small forward or power forward.''
BRIEFLY
Drake's 83-80 victory over Creighton on Dec. 12 ended the Bulldogs'
39-game Missouri Valley Conference losing streak. ``For the new
guys, they hadn't experienced it, but for us who knew, it's
something I'd never wish upon my worst enemy,'' third-year coach
Kurt Kanaskie said of the streak.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Steve Lavin is keeping pace with John Wooden. In his
67th game, Lavin won his 50th game as Bruins coach. Wooden also got
win No. 50 in game No. 67. Now all Lavin needs is to win 10
national championships.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 Duke's 71-60 victory over No. 3 Kentucky should not have
been a surprise. The game was held in East Rutherford, N.J., and
the Blue Devils are now 5-0 there. In 1986, 1988, 1989 and 1990
they won East Regional finals at the Meadowlands (it's now
Continental Airlines Arena) to reach the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA forward Rico Hines on the young Bruins' inconsistent play:
``We're like a quarter-horse. We're good for a half. Sometimes, we
look like All-Americans for stretches. It's a mental thing. We have
to learn to put people away.''
</P>
<P>
   Creighton has its best team since Tony Barone was a sideline
jumping bean there earlier this decade. The Bluejays are 8-2, and
their two losses were on the road at Nebraska and Drake. Creighton
has given Iowa its only loss, and Sunday defeated No. 19 Oklahoma
State, coached by former Creighton coach Eddie Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   The Pearl Harbor Classic, a three-day tournament that concluded
last night, had an interesting twist. Seven of the eight teams were
from states that had ships docked at Pearl Harbor on Dec. 7, 1941.
Players from the teams participated in a special ceremony at the
Arizona Memorial to honor the veterans of that historic event.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1978, Arkansas' season tickets have sold out before the
season. But the Razorbacks aren't drawing the crowds in Bud Walton
Arena. Attendance for the Dec. 7 game against Western Carolina was
12,646, the smallest in the arena's six years. Through six home
games, Arkansas was averaging 15,789; seating capacity is 19,200.
</P>
<P>
   Update: Last week, we reported how Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun
was unhappy with the facilities and fan control at Pittsburgh. The
Big East Conference investigated and found no basis for UConn's
charges that its players were pelted with soft-drink bottles and
racial slurs during the Dec. 12 game. However, Pitt officials
acknowledge that renovations to Fitzgerald Fieldhouse have made
locker-room facilities inadequate.
</P>
</TEXT>
