A4898 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DOWNINDELTA-TEX     12-23 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DOWNINDELTA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELOU USES A LIGHT HAND IN DIRECTING DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've ever heard Maya Angelou read her poetry, you know of
her lilting voice and authoritative rhythms. She sounds so perfect,
it's as if no one else should read her works, yet they speak for an
experience shared by millions.
</P>
<P>
   Angelou doesn't bring that authority to ``Down in the Delta,''
her directorial debut; although it's directed by a poet, it
restricts its poetry to a few lyrical frames. The prosaic touch may
be a good thing. Too many first-time directors, especially those
from nonfilm disciplines, inflict a distracting self-consciousness
on their material, as if they needed to prove to themselves and the
audience that they're directing. Angelou, however, uses a light
hand for this simple story about unconditional love and not being a
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta, played by Alfre Woodard in a delicately modulated
performance, is a single Chicago mother _ and not a very good one,
at first. She's trying to put her life back together, but every
minor setback sends her back to the liquor store or the crack
house. Her family is becoming frayed; son Thomas (Mpho Koaho) is a
sharp preteen who hustles tourists by charging them for photographs
and is already taking on a fatalistic attitude. Young daughter
Tracy (Kulani Hassen) is autistic; she still stays in a playpen at
a time when most kids are pitter-pattering through the house.
Loretta's mom finally has enough of Loretta's antics and sends
Loretta and her family down to Biloxi, Miss., to learn a few life
lessons on Uncle Earl's farm.
</P>
<P>
   Life's not easy for Earl (Al Freeman Jr.), either; his wife
(Esther Rolle) is suffering from Alzheimer's, his lawyer son
(Wesley Snipes, not beating anyone up, for once) is distant, and
his all-chicken restaurant is dependent on a nearby
chicken-processing plant that may be closing. Freeman plays Earl
with saintly patience and world-weariness, as if he had aged to a
point where he decided that raising his voice was a waste of time.
He puts Loretta to work, and predictably enough, she starts coming
around.
</P>
<P>
   If all that sounds like the stuff of a TV movie, well, it is.
``Delta'' was destined for cable's Showtime before Miramax decided
to give it a theatrical release, and despite its summertime
setting, it's as Christmasy as a Waltons special. Angelou uses
restraint instead of manipulation; she's not out to jerk tears out
of you. She's also smart enough to let her experienced actors,
including Rolle in her last performance, do most of the work.
</P>
<P>
   She is hamstrung, though, by the movie's budget and Myron E.
Goble's TV-level script (its PG-13 rating seems harsh, considering
that it's for scenes of substance abuse that are hardly pro-drug).
Filming in and near Toronto, Angelou is unable to give the Delta
scenes a sense of place. You hear cicadas, but you don't feel the
sticky Mississippi summer (or see the river, or the Gulf _ or the
Delta, for that matter). Angelou's directorial debut is a modest,
qualified success, but it's mostly because of Woodard and Freeman,
as well as Koaho's fresh performance. It's sure to play well when
it returns to TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down in the Delta'' is rated PG-13 for scenes of drug and
alcohol use.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
