<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4903 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAFTA-TRADE-LATINTRAD     12-23 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAFTA-TRADE-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADING PLACES
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By SERGIO R. BUSTOS, with JOACHIM BAMRUD and research by GABRIELA
CALDERON 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Herminio Blanco, Mexico's secretary of Commerce and Industry,
says he would have laughed 10 years ago had someone told him that
his country would even approach Japan to become the United States'
second-largest trade partner behind Canada. Blanco, his country's
former chief NAFTA negotiator, would have laughed harder still at
the notion that Mexico would become the world's second-largest
recipient of foreign direct investment dollars among emerging
markets behind China. These days, Blanco and other Mexicans can
credit the five-year old trilateral pact for their trade success.
 &HT;    In 1997, Mexico was the United States' third-largest trading
partner, trailing Japan by less than US$20 billion. And since the
beginning of NAFTA in 1994, Mexico has averaged $11 billion per
year in foreign direct investment, according to the Mexican
government.
 &HT;    Between the 1997 Asian crisis and the economic uncertainty that
has since prevailed throughout the world, NAFTA has proven to be a
valuable trade agreement for all three countries, but especially
the United States, says Blanco. In 1998, every U.S. state
experienced negative growth in exports to Japan and Asia in 1998.
That was not the case with Mexico, he says.
 &HT;    U.S. exports to Asia dropped $14 billion during the first six
months of 1998 as compared to the previous year. U.S. exports to
Mexico and Canada, however, increased $11 billion during the same
period, according to the U.S. Department of Commerce.
 &HT;    ``The exports to Canada and Mexico helped us preserve jobs and
growth,'' U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky told a
group of business leaders gathered in New York in October to
discuss foreign trade trends.
 &HT;    Sas Mexico's Blanco: ``Mexico was a safety net for all U.S.
exporters.''
 &HT;    U.S. exports to Mexico were expected to show double-digit growth
in 1998. During the first eight months, exports reached $51.3
billion, an increase of 14.2 percent over the same period in 1997,
according to the U.S. Department of Commerce. Imports grew by 11.2
percent to $61.4 billion.
 &HT;    In 1997, total U.S.-Mexico trade stood at $158.5 billion, a 21.1
percent increase over 1996 and nearly twice the levels of 1993 _
the last year before NAFTA _ according to the International
Monetary Fund, which included trade from Mexico's maquiladoras. All
in all, U.S. trade with Mexico grew an average of nearly 18 percent
in the 1994-97 period.
 &HT;    The trade balance changed significantly before and after NAFTA.
Whereas the United States experienced two relatively minor deficits
and two surpluses in the 1990-93 period, it posted only one
relatively small surplus and three major deficits in the 1994-97
period. In 1997, the deficit had grown to a whopping $15.7 billion.
The deficit came despite strong export performance from the United
States. In the 1990-93 period, U.S. exports grew 46.7 percent,
while imports from Mexico grew 32.3 percent. In the 1994-97 period,
though, imports from Mexico _ growing 73.1 percent _ far outpaced
U.S. exports, which grew 40.4 percent.
 &HT;    The deficit was partly spurred by the 1994 Mexican peso crash.
It boosted Mexican exports but decreased Mexican imports. In 1996
and 1997, Mexico's economy turned around with exports continuing
growth, spurred by restructuring among many Mexican companies.
 &HT;    In 1997, U.S. exports to Mexico reached $71.4 billion, a 25.7
percent increase over 1996. Imports from Mexico grew by 17.6
percent, reaching $87.2 billion.
 &HT;    Canada's trade with Mexico also has grown at impressive levels,
both before and after NAFTA. Total bilateral trade went from $617
million in 1990 to $2.7 billion in 1993, an increase of 338
percent, according to IMF data. Average annual growth during that
four-year period was 59.7 percent. Between 1994 and 1997 trade went
from $3 billion to $4.1 billion, an increase of 34.3 percent.
Average annual growth during that period was 12.7 percent.
 &HT;    Unlike the U.S.-Mexican trade balance, Canada's trade with
Mexico has followed a consistent ``zig-zag'' pattern since 1990.
Starting with a Canadian surplus that year, the balance has given
each country a surplus or deficit every other year. In 1997, Mexico
boasted a surplus, with its exports to Canada of $2.1 billion
higher than imports of $1.9 billion.
 &HT;    Mexico's Secretariat of Commerce and Industrial Development
(known by its Spanish acronym SECOFI) projects that total trade
among Canada, Mexico and the United States could reach more than
$520 billion in 1998, up some $20 billion from 1997.
 &HT;    Two researchers at the University of Miami's North-South Center
argue in a recent book that NAFTA only reaffirmed an ongoing trend:
the economies of the United States, Canada and Mexico are becoming
one. ``This process did not begin with NAFTA or the Canada-U.S.
Free Trade Agreement,'' the researchers, Stephen Blank and Jerry
Haar, writes in Making NAFTA Work. ``This profound change in
patterns, structures and strategies of business around the world,
and especially in North America, is being driven by the interlinked
forces of global competition, regulatory liberalization and
technology.''
 &HT;    Much of the success of NAFTA is attributed to the massive
reduction of tariffs on a wide range of goods and services. Before
NAFTA was signed, the Mexican tariff on U.S. goods, for example,
averaged 10 percent. Since NAFTA was signed, Mexico has reduced its
average applied tariffs on U.S. imports to an average of less than
3 percent. On the other side of the border, U.S. tariffs on Mexican
imports averaged just over 2 percent, but they have been cut in
half. And more than half of U.S. tariffs on Mexican goods do not
pay any duty at all.
 &HT;    A look at specific sectors shows how the increased trade has
translated into a boom for certain industries. A 1997 study by the
U.S. Trade Representative's Office found that the reduction in
tariff and non-tariff barriers helped to increase overall U.S.
exports of motor vehicles, electronic components, textiles and
apparel, computers, chemicals and a variety of agricultural
products. The study also noted that NAFTA increased U.S. imports of
Mexican textiles and apparel, and light trucks. The report reviewed
12 sectors, ranging from automotive vehicles and parts to
telecommunications equipment.
 &HT;    ``It is Mexico that has seen the most impressive trade benefits
by far, with its new unprecedented levels of access to the U.S. and
Canadian markets,'' says Carol Wise, a Johns Hopkins University
political science professor and a NAFTA expert who edited a book on
the impact of NAFTA on Mexico, ``The Post-NAFTA Political
Economy.''
 &HT;    Isaac Cohen, former director of the Washington office of the
United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America and the
Caribbean, agrees. ``NAFTA is more important for Mexico and Canada
than for the United States,'' says Cohen, currently an economic
advisor for U.S.-based McConnell Vald es Consulting. ``NAFTA is
providing a set of rules under which investment and trade links
have intensified, reaching levels of interdependence that were
inconceivable without the (pact).''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</TEXT>
