u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOSCOW-SHOPPERS-BOS &LR;      12-23 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSCOW-SHOPPERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSCOVITES COME UP WITH CASH FOR CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Their buying power battered, their savings lost in
failed banks, Muscovites are putting a tough year behind them and
plunking down their devalued rubles for holiday gifts.
</P>
<P>
   With full shelves, cheery staff and decked halls, Stockmann, a
sparkling new Finnish-owned department store, is happy to oblige
them. At first glance, the scene does not look it belongs in a city
struggling through its worst economic crisis in years. But the
buyers tell another story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard this year, because my expenses have not decreased,
but my income has,'' said Valery Shalamov, a 35-year-old
entrepreneur shopping in the interior design department. Shalamov
says he did not lose all of his money, and he will probably give
friends and loved ones gold jewelry, like he did last year. ``But
there is not the same holiday feel as before.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the August economic meltdown, Moscow was what some
described as a boomtown, where shining office buildings and
post-modern malls went up at an astonishing rate. Now the boom is
over, evident by the empty spaces outside Stockmann's and
throughout the rest of the unfinished Smolensky Mall.
</P>
<P>
   The panic buying and long lines of the first days of the crisis
are a long gone, but for many people, life has not returned to
normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course the crisis has affected my life, since my salary was
in rubles,'' Alfia Safuanova, 25, who works at an oil company, as
she looked over Stockmann's collection of crystal dishes. Like many
upscale stores, Stockman sets its prices in dollars. The Russian
currency has lost 70 percent of its value since August, putting
many once-affordable items out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Muscovites continue to buy. One possible reason is the
estimated $20 billion in US dollars Russians have hidden under
their matresses. Not everyone kept their cash in banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis hurt my company, but although it affected my mood,
it did not affect my personal financial situation that much,'' said
a Stockmann shopper who gave only his first name, Ave. ``It takes
more than that to get to me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Anastasia Saschikhina, a researcher at the Globe's Moscow
Bureau, contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
