<SLUG> BC-FLEET-LEAKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT ACTS TO PLUG FLEET CONSUMER LEAKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Connecticut authorities have subpoenaed documents from
Fleet Financial Group Inc. and other institutions as part of an
investigation into whether bank customers are getting the financial
privacy they expect.
</P>
<P>
   The action, by Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal,
marks the first time the state has named a specific bank as part of
its inquiry into an underground trade in bank-account information.
</P>
<P>
   With other New England officials, Blumenthal is examining
whether a group of small private investigative firms used false
pretexts to learn the specifics of dozens of consumer bank
accounts. Such data isn't supposed to be released without customer
permission.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet is not a target of the investigation, Blumenthal said in
an interview Wednesday. The bank said it is cooperating with the
probe.
</P>
<P>
   But the subpoenas, sent out last month and disclosed Wednesday,
suggest Fleet and other banks may come under scrutiny themselves
for their dealings with the asset-search firms.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Blumenthal's office filed a civil complaint against
one such firm, Norwalk-based NRS Information Services Inc. and its
owner, Frederick Acker.
</P>
<P>
   The state alleges NRS employees routinely tricked
telephone-service employees at financial institutions into
disclosing data by impersonating bank customers. As a result,
according to the complaint, ``Numerous persons have had their
private financial information unlawfully purloined and sold to
third parties'' such as collections agents.
</P>
<P>
   The state also alleges in its complaint that NRS practices
included ``contacting employees at financial institutions and
paying those employees to provide private financial information on
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaint doesn't name any institutions where activities
took place, and Blumenthal declined Wednesday to discuss whether
Fleet employees were among those who received payments. But he said
the inquiry is continuing and that such behavior could open a bank
to civil suits by the state or by individuals whose records were
improperly accessed.
</P>
<P>
   Acker's attorney, Frederick Ury, said his client denies the
state's allegations, inlcuding the notion that NRS paid bank
insiders for information, and said he plans to defend against them
``vigorously.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether NRS ever did work directly on Fleet's
behalf. In 1996, the bank hired another firm in Connecticut, Summer
Associates, to research the assets of a developer who had defaulted
on some loans. He later complained about the tactics used to check
up on him. That firm, which like NRS has been closed, remains under
investigation by the state.
</P>
<P>
   In response to complaints, Fleet ceased doing business with
Summer in 1996 and, earlier this year, stopped using outside
asset-search firms.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Fleet spokesman Jim Mahoney said the bank is trying
to make its own employees more guarded with telephone callers who
may seek information.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been more attention to these issues in recent
months, and procedures have been tightened'' as a result, said
Mahoney said. For example, the bank now often requires callers to
provide specific information such as account numbers and maiden
names.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the records from Fleet, Blumenthal's office also
has subpoenaed records from a Connecticut law firm and from a
credit-reporting agency, other officials said.
</P>
<P>
   They declined to identify either organization, but the complaint
against NRS states the company ``unlawfully'' obtained consumer
credit reporters from one of two leading credit-reporting agencies,
Equifax Inc. in Atlanta and the former credit-reporting units of
TRW which are now part of Experian Corp. in Orange, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Wednesday, spokesmen for both companies said they
couldn't immediately comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
