<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.Y.)  
 CULTURE NOTES: O'KEEFFE PAINTING GOES TO N.J. MUSEUM; NEW YORK POPS
NEARS UNION AGREEMENT; ABT BRINGS `MERRY WIDOW' TO NEWARK; $1
MILLION GIFT TO YADDO 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia O'Keeffe's ``Skunk Cabbage'' has taken root at the
Montclair Art Museum. The 1922 painting has been donated to the
museum by Henry H. Ploch of Clifton, N.J., a longtime supporter.
The painting is the first O'Keeffe in the collection of the museum,
which specializes in 19th-and 20th-century works by artists like
Alexander Calder, Maurice Prendergast, Max Weber, Marsden Hartley,
John Marin, Charles Burchfield and Arthur Dove. ``Skunk Cabbage''
will hang in the museum's lobby from February to May and will
become a part of a permanent collection installation that is to
open in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   IN LABOR
</P>
<P>
   A tentative contract agreement with the New York Pops was
announced Wednesday by Local 802 of the American Federation of
Musicians. The orchestra canceled its holiday concerts a week ago
when its freelance musicians struck after negotiations over wages
broke down. The union did not disclose terms of the agreement,
pending a ratification vote that will not take place until after
the orchestra returns in mid-January from a tour of Japan.
Musicians of 11 New York freelance orchestras have been working
without contracts since September, and the New York Pops agreement
prompted hope that it would provide a pattern for other
settlements. The musicians are continuing to strike the Little
Orchestra Society.
</P>
<P>
   FINE ROMANCE
</P>
<P>
   With Susan Jaffe leading off in the title role, American Ballet
Theater will bring its production of ``The Merry Widow'' to the New
Jersey Performing Arts Center's Prudential Hall in Newark for five
performances beginning on Monday and ending on Jan. 3. Derived from
Franz Lehar's 1905 comic operetta, set to his music and
choreographed by Ronald Hynd for the Australian Ballet in 1975, the
American Ballet Theater version of the internationally popular tale
of romance and social intrigue will be danced by such stars as
Ashley Tuttle, Julie Kent, Christine Dunham, Jose Manuel Carreno
and Angel Corella.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   The artists' community Yaddo, which will observe its 100th
anniversary in 2000, has received $1 million for its Centennial
Gift Campaign. The contribution _ $500,000 from the private equity
firm Spencer Trask &AMP; Co. and $500,000 from its founder and
chairman, Kevin Kimberlin, and his wife, Joni _ is the largest
single gift to Yaddo since April.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the novelist Patricia Highsmith bequeathed her
entire estate, valued at $3 million, to the 400-acre community in
Saratoga Springs, N.Y. Yaddo was founded by Spencer and Katrina
Trask, husband and wife, to provide artists with a supportive
environment where they would find uninterrupted time to think,
create and work. Kimberlin named his company for Trask (1844-1909),
an early backer of Thomas Edison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 1952EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4925 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LADN-BUDGET &LR;      12-23 0314
