   HAHN-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Today's Army National Guard can handle
everything from earthquakes and floods to forest fires and other
emergencies, but some of their military cohorts apparently don't
always know their left foot from their right. Just ask Washington
Army National Guard First Sgt. Cecil B. Osborne Jr. An Army surgeon
had trouble locating and removing damaged joint tissue in Osborne's
knee. He operated on the wrong knee. The right knee was the right
knee.
</P>
<P>
   By Jon Hahn. (Story will move in the ``l'' category.)
</P>
