<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFT, RIGHT, LEFT, RIGHT: AN ARMY DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Today's Army National Guard can handle everything from
earthquakes and floods to forest fires and other emergencies, but
some of their military cohorts apparently don't always know their
left foot from their right.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Washington Army National Guard First Sgt. Cecil B.
Osborne Jr. of Kirkland, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   An Army surgeon at Madigan Army Medical Center had trouble
locating and removing damaged joint tissue in Osborne's knee.
</P>
<P>
   He operated on the wrong knee. The right knee was the right
knee.
</P>
<P>
   An incredulous Osborne said the surgeon operated on his left
knee less than an hour after confirming with him that the right
knee needed the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physician's assistant and the attending nurse and the
anesthesiologist ... they all came up to me while I was on the
gurney and they confirmed my name and that I was to have surgery on
the right knee,'' Osborne recounted.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the surgeon did the same thing ... confirmed my name and
that he was going to operate on my right knee. He even manipulated
the right knee as I was lying there on the gurney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there was some sort of commotion, some trauma case coming
in, and I thought they might have to reschedule me because of all
the activity, but they said there was no problem, that my surgery
would be all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't until I was coming out of anesthesia that I realized
something was terribly wrong,'' said Osborne, who is a building
maintenance contractor in civilian life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor came out of the operating room and said everything
went fine, but there was `a little problem: We did the wrong
knee.'''
</P>
<P>
   Well sir, they just don't do things like that in Osborne's
Company C, 3rd Battalion, 161st Mechanized Infantry unit in
Redmond, Wash. Never since he was drafted in 1971 and in all his
time in Korea and in Army National Guard in Oregon and Washington
has Sgt. Osborne seen a snafu like this one.
</P>
<P>
   His mechanized infantry unit has seen a lot of duty in recent
years, including fighting forest and brush fires in Eastern
Washington and seasonal flooding on this side of the mountains. The
unit also was activated during recent hoopla about the Makah Indian
whale hunt preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually we meet one weekend a month and train two weeks every
summer. And because of my rank, I'm also usually at meetings one or
two weekends every month.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, while on his regular two-week training stint near
Yakima, Osborne fell from the tailgate of a truck and injured his
right knee while helping his supply sergeant set up the unit's
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a stupid sort of accident,'' he says. ``The leg hurt,
but not enough to go off duty. I later had it checked out by the
appropriate medical officer and we filled out all the required
paperwork because he said it looked like the kind of injury that
could cause me trouble in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, it did, but Osborne limped along. In the
meantime, he had surgery for an unrelated condition, which went off
without a hitch at Evergreen Hospital Medical Center in Kirkland.
</P>
<P>
   His troubles didn't really start until that injured right knee
began hurting real bad, and his regular civilian family doctor
advised him it probably would need surgery. ``And since it was a
service-related injury, we knew that my regular hospitalization
insurance wouldn't pay for it,'' Osborne said. ``Besides, the Army
paperwork had already been filled out.''
</P>
<P>
   So the surgery was approved and scheduled for Madigan, first for
last spring and, eventually, for last August, which is where and
when everything went wrong. And Osborne has been stewing about it
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until an inquiry from this column earlier this month
that the hospital officially admitted a mistake and apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that a surgical procedure was performed on the
opposite knee of Sergeant Osborne at Madigan Hospital,'' the
hospital's officially terse statement began. Noting that the
wrong-side surgery was ``a mistake greatly regretted by all,'' the
hospital said it launched an immediate investigation, which led to
new presurgical procedures ``to assure a similar incident will
never be repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Madigan spokesman Mike Meines, all surgery patients
will now meet with the attending anesthesiologist or anesthetist to
identify the surgery site, and that site will be marked with
indelible ink before anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, we offer a most sincere apology to
Sergeant Osborne and his family,'' the hospital's statement
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a warm fuzzy. More of a precise, militarily correct
statement that failed to note _ nor would they respond to direct
questions about _ the name of the Army surgeon or the attending
personnel or the cause of the mistake or, for that matter, any
particulars of the official investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne said last week: ``There's been no information (from the
Army) to me about their investigation, nor an apology, nor copies
of my medical records, as requested by me, my civilian doctor and
my lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier interview, Osborne conceded wryly: ``The surgeon
personally apologized to me and then said they were going to
correct the error by getting me back in to do the correct leg,''
Osborne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said: `I don't think so, Doctor, Sir ... not me! Never
again!' He said that as my superior officer, he could order me back
in. That's when I contacted the administration and basically told
them: `I'm not coming back into your hospital. You botched it, and
I'm going to have it done by a civilian doctor.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was leaving the hospital, a nurse told me: `Don't let
them sweep this under the carpet.' The entire (surgical) floor knew
about it. I told my wife: `Get me outta here!' I got home and I
began throwing up. I couldn't believe it! Even as my stomach
started calming, I became more and more outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne said the Army ``went through a week or so of hemming and
hawing and finally authorized payment for a civilian doctor to do
the surgery on the right knee.'' And Osborne was paid the
equivalent of 21 days of military pay for time lost due to the
surgery and recuperation.
</P>
<P>
   And although he remains active in his National Guard unit, he
has not received any compensation for time lost from his civilian
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday I'm going to have to go back into that hospital, or
send in a soldier I'm responsible for, and I want to feel confident
that they'll do the right thing for me or for one of my men,''
Osborne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told there's no legal recourse, that you can't sue
the military. But that's an issue I will pursue, because I think
soldiers should have recourse if something goes awry in surgery,
elective or not. If a civilian doctor made this mistake, he'd be in
big trouble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
