<HEADER>
A4941 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-IN-1998-TEX     12-23 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-IN-1998-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YEAR IN TEXAS ARTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
 &HT;    c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This has been a year in which Texas art news often made national
and international news, underscoring the state's increasingly
important role in the art world. But, that bit of bragging aside,
our first big art story could not have been less auspicious ...
</P>
<P>
   JANUARY/Houston: Still grieving for founder Dominique de Menil
(who died on the last day of 1997), the Menil Collection opens the
giant Robert Rauschenberg retrospective it is sharing with
Houston's two other art museums.
</P>
<P>
   But, on its first public day, Harris County constables
confiscate several artworks from the Menil _ not for controversial
content, but because Rauschenberg is being sued by an unhappy,
Austin-based art dealer named Alfred Kren. The show goes on; the
suit eventually is settled.
</P>
<P>
   JANUARY/Fort Worth: Kimbell Art Museum Director Ted Pillsbury
shocks the art world by announcing his retirement after nearly 18
years of brilliant service. Girding itself to find a new director,
the Kimbell becomes one of an unprecedented number of major U.S.
museums with an opening at the top. The Whitney Museum of American
Art, the Phillips Collection and some 20 other institutions are
searching. Then the Phillips announces its hiring of Dallas Museum
of Art Director Jay Gates, and another museum joins the game of
musical chairs.
</P>
<P>
   FEBRUARY/Washington, D.C.: The American Institute of Architects
gives the Kimbell its 25-year award _ celebrating the 25th
anniversary of its Louis Kahn-designed building. This is historic;
it's the first time any architect has received the award two years
in a row. The year before, Kahn was recognized for his library at
Phillips Exeter Academy.
</P>
<P>
   FEBRUARY/Fort Worth: ``Renoir's Portraits,'' which the Kimbell
helped organize, opens in Fort Worth, after drawing record crowds
in Chicago. It's the closest thing to a North Texas blockbuster
this year.
</P>
<P>
   MARCH/Austin: The stodgy Huntington Art Gallery at the
University of Texas is renamed the Blanton Museum of Art. With
that, the institution launches a year of changes that take it from
the visual arts basement to the penthouse. In rapid succession, the
Blanton presents a major historic survey of lithographs, acquires
one of the world's most important private collections of baroque
artworks (the Suida-Manning Collection) and, in December, announces
that its new building will be designed by museum-architecture
hotshots Herzog &AMP; de Meuron of Basel, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone by its local academic museum, two other visual
art venues in Austin ratchet up their own prestige with sexy
building projects. The Austin Museum of Art chooses Richard
Gluckman to design its downtown facility, and the Texas Fine Arts
Association opens its new home _ an adaptive reuse designed by Gary
Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   AUGUST/Fort Worth: The Kimbell's director search ends jubilantly
with the appointment of Timothy Potts, 40-year-old director of
Melbourne's National Gallery of Victoria, Australia's oldest and
largest art museum. An archaeologist, art historian, critic and
financier, Potts arrives in Fort Worth with his family in early
November.
</P>
<P>
   AUGUST/Austin, etc.: UT's Ransom Humanities Resource Center
scores big, acquiring the David Douglas Duncan photographic
archive.
</P>
<P>
   Many museums will acquire art en masse this year: The
International Museum of Folk Art in Santa Fe lands the Neutrogena
Collection; the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art pulls in big
chunks (including a stunning group of early Rauschenbergs); the
Indianapolis Museum of Art acquires the acclaimed Josefowitz
Collection of paintings and prints by Paul Gauguin and his Brittany
followers. Also, the San Antonio Museum of Art opens a new wing
named for Nelson Rockefeller, whose daughter gave San Antonio her
father's superb collection of Latin American folk art.
</P>
<P>
   SEPTEMBER/Fort Worth: Two exhibitions open at the Modern at
Sundance Square and the Contemporary Art Center of Fort Worth, both
devoted to works by Ed Blackburn and Linda Blackburn (and their a k
a Ray Madison). If ever a pair of local shows deserve to go
national, these two do.
</P>
<P>
   The two exhibits take their place among several significant
exhibitions originating in North Texas this year. These included:
``The Painted Sketch'' at the Dallas Museum of Art; ``Agnes
Martin/Richard Tuttle'' at the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth;
Jaume Plensa's ``Dallas ... Caracas'' installation at the McKinney
Avenue Contemporary in Dallas; and the Kimbell's presentation of
four masterpieces by Caspar David Friedrich. Other local
exhibitions of note _ just passing through, thank you _ include
presentations of Thracian gold, Lalique jewelry and Mughal
manuscripts at the Kimbell, the DMA and the Kimbell, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   SEPTEMBER/All over: Fall blockbusters get under way with a
presentation of late Delacroix paintings at the Philadelphia Museum
of Art. The spate of brilliant shows continues with van Gogh in
Washington, D.C., Jackson Pollock at the Museum of Modern Art and
Mary Cassatt in Boston. But not all the hits focus on single
artists: The Met's display of early Flemish paintings and the
Guggenheim's joint effort with the Pompidou Center are popular
surprises.
</P>
<P>
   OCTOBER/Las Vegas: We learn what Ted Pillsbury has been up to
since leaving the Kimbell in midsummer: He's been helping casino
magnate Steve Wynn launch his new Bellagio resort. Packed with
major works of art by Manet, Picasso, Willem de Kooning and Andy
Warhol, among others, Bellagio is an art world anomaly that
attracts international attention. Wynn's ticket for the collection?
About $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   NOVEMBER/Dallas: The Trammell and Margaret Crow Collection of
Asian Art opens next door to the DMA, promising to be a popular
success with the potential to score scholarly points, as well.
Meantime, there's no word on Ray Nasher's sculpture garden (another
immediate neighbor), but Duke University announces that Nasher has
given the university $7.5 million for a new art museum in his name.
</P>
<P>
   NOVEMBER/Fort Worth: Finally, the Amon Carter Museum announces a
Philip Johnson expansion plan _ one that involves demolishing all
but his original 1961 building and constructing a spacious new
museum that will be clad in handsome brown granite.
</P>
<P>
   DECEMBER/Dallas: The Meadows Museum at Southern Methodist
University breaks ground for its new Meadows Museum, in a style
described as ``collegiate Georgian,'' designed by Hammond Beeby and
Babka. And the Dallas Museum of Art ends its director search when
DMA trustees announce that they have hired Jack Lane to succeed
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDUL/
</P>
