<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Gold''
</P>
<P>
   Gold Records
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Gold,'' a bestseller in England brought to the United
States by Integrity Music, is a unique, thoughtful, welcome
addition to the Christian music field.
</P>
<P>
   Intertwining the prose of John Bunyan and British author Adrian
Plass with songs by Phil Baggaley, Dave Clifton and Ian Blythe, it
traces the ``pilgrim's progress'' toward the gates of heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The songs, performed by Mal Pope and Julie Costello, range from
contemporary praise cuts to those with Celtic and world-music
influences. The album begins with upbeat tunes that gradually give
way to those with more of a contemplative feel.
</P>
<P>
   But what sets ``City of Gold'' apart are the spoken words,
sometimes reverent, sometimes whimsical. ``Heavenly Playground''
takes its title literally, as Plass imagines a giant playground
where even big boys can frolic. ``Cricket'' expresses the hope that
that game will be played in the afterlife, in clever words that an
American audience can relate to.
</P>
<P>
   Plass' vision is a tad limited. He seems to see paradise as
merely an extension of the good things on Earth, like games and
flowery meadows, but he explains himself while talking to God on
Heaven: ``I love this world you made. It's all I know.''
</P>
<P>
   The album also lacks an explanation of how to get to heaven.
Still, it's a worthwhile project with much more substance than the
run-of-the-mill release.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
