A4943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SARALEE-RECALL24-COX     12-23 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARALEE-RECALL24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recalled meats sold in Georgia
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hot dogs, deli meats and other meat products thought
to be involved in a nationwide outbreak of a serious food-borne
illness, listeriosis, are included in a nationwide recall.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak has caused 40 severe illnesses in 10 states,
including one possible case in Georgia, and the deaths of a fetus
and three elderly adults in Ohio and New York, the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee Corp. has voluntarily recalled certain products
manufactured at the Bil Mar Foods plant in Zeeland, Mich. The
products are identifiable by the codes EST P261 and EST 6911 on the
packaging. The company could not say how much product was recalled
or how much was distributed in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Hot dogs included in the recall are labeled Ball Park, Bil Mar,
Bryan Bunsize and Bryan 3-lb. Club Pack. Other brands are
Grillmaster, Hygrade, Mr. Turkey, Sara Lee Deli Meat and Sara Lee
Home Roast.
</P>
<P>
   Listeriosis, caused by the bacterium Listeria monocytogenes, is
relatively rare, and most healthy people don't become severely ill.
But the disease poses a serious threat to pregnant women and
fetuses, the elderly or those with weakened immune systems.
Symptoms range from fever and diarrhea to meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   Listeria is found in soil and water. The bacteria have been
found in raw meats and vegetables, processed foods such as cold
cuts and soft cheeses and unpasteurized milk or foods made from it.
</P>
<P>
   Listeriosis causes 1,850 serious illnesses a year and kills 425,
or 23 percent of those seriously ill.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak began in early August, but the low number of cases
made it difficult for health officials to recognize the outbreak
and then pinpoint its source. Listeria has a three-week incubation
period, which forced investigators to ask people to recall what
they had eaten the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   At least 16 of the 40 infected people had consumed cooked hot
dogs during the month before they became ill. Investigators aren't
sure how well the hot dogs were cooked, and caution people using
microwaves to make sure their food is cooked throughout.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 19, the strain of Listeria involved was isolated from an
open package of hot dogs, some of which was eaten by an infected
person four weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Because some of the recalled food products have a long shelf
life and may have been distributed throughout the nation, health
officials advise people to check their refrigerators and freezers.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers can return products, opened or not, to the place of
purchase for a full refund.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC, which is investigating, recommends thoroughly cooking
meat and washing raw vegetables. People especially at risk may want
to consider reheating deli meats before consumption and avoiding
soft cheeses such as brie or feta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because it's the holidays, don't let your guard down,''
warned Dr. Stephen Ostroff, the CDC's associate director for
epidemiologic science. ``People tend to get a little sloppy in how
they prepare and handle foods. But it's no less risky because it's
December instead of July.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee's has a consumer hotline for questions: 1-800-247-8339.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
