<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4949 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORALS-LIVINGSTON-BOS     12-23 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORALS-LIVINGSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE RAGES OVER LIVINGSTON DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Coalition-Backlash)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Who got Bob Livingston?
</P>
<P>
   It has become a hot question since the speaker-designate shocked
the House on Saturday with his decision to decline the leadership
post and resign from Congress after confessing that more than once
he had been unfaithful to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton suggested it was the Republican Party's
pervasive, misguided, and mean-spirited ``politics of personal
destruction'' that ruined the career of a good public servant.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Christian right insist it was Larry Flynt, the
publisher of Hustler magazine, who despicably ``outed'' Livingston
for his affairs, undermining the moral authority of the incoming
speaker. Some even said Flynt might be acting in concert with the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal groups assert Livingston did not step aside voluntarily
but was driven out by a small, zealous band of GOP social
conservatives who threatened to withhold their votes and deny the
Louisiana Republican the speakership when the election was held in
January.
</P>
<P>
   As in almost everything connected to the impeachment of Clinton,
Livingston's demise is tinged with rancor and partisanship, as
Democrats and Republicans, liberals and conservatives, squabble
over the sexual morality of public officials and find ways to blame
each other for a decision that Livingston has said was his own.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Greg Ganske, an Iowa Republican who met privately
with Livingston as he pondered his future last Friday, said he is
so troubled by the latest buzz, and sure that Livingston's decision
was ``his and his alone, made for the good of his family, the
party, and the country,'' that he circulated a letter to his House
colleagues Wednesday, calling for an end to the ``pernicious
story'' that he was forced out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That somebody would put the country ahead of their own
political gain is something that the cynical press and the
president's defenders either can't understand or just can't
tolerate, as a comparison to a president who has no shame,'' Ganske
wrote. ``So they are trying to denigrate Bob's motives by
insinuating that he really didn't have any choice, that he wouldn't
have been elected speaker anyway because of `sexual McCarthyism' of
our party. Let us end that pernicious story right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Welton Gaddy, executive director of the Interfaith
Alliance, a nonpartisan clergy group formed to counter the
Christian Coalition, said it's not cynical to see Livingston could
not pass the ``dangerous, dangerous litmus test'' of the religious
right: That an act of moral wrongdoing disqualifies you from high
political office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly at least suspicious, if not confident, that the
Livingston scenario developed with an eye on the influence of the
religious right, which holds the Republican Party captive,'' Gaddy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Christian right and their allies in Congress
vehemently deny they put pressure on Livingston to resign after he
disclosed acts of adultery to the House Republicans last Thursday.
Representative Zach Wamp, a Tennessee Republican and often a
spokesman for young Christian conservatives in the House, discussed
members' ``concerns'' with Livingston early Saturday, but he did
not tell him his support had seriously eroded, a Wamp aide said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Phyllis Schlafly, founder of the Eagle Forum, and the
Rev. Lou Sheldon, chairman of the Traditional Values Coalition, had
let fellow conservatives on Capitol Hill know by then that electing
Livingston speaker ``wasn't going to work,'' Sheldon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no loss,'' said Schlafly, adding that Livingston's
behavior was ``not acceptable'' for a House speaker. ``He was part
of the old guard, and this has had a very good effect in shaking
the old leadership, pushing it to the sidelines to make room for a
younger generation of conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon said questions about Livingston's morality became
relevant only when he tried to step up into a top leadership role.
He noted that several GOP lawmakers, including Judiciary Committee
chairman Henry Hyde, have admitted adultery and have not faced
recriminations from the Christian right.
</P>
<P>
   ``When have we ever exposed a single homosexual? When did we
ever out a Henry Hyde?'' Sheldon asked. ``Larry Flynt is the person
who indirectly is establshing an era of sexual McCarthyism because
he is going around outing these people and making lot of money in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet people on the left aren't charging him with the politics
of personal destruction,'' Sheldon said. ``They are trying to make
us into Larry Flynt.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, Flynt bought a full-page ad in the Washington Post
and offered as much as $1 million to women who would disclose their
affairs with public officials. Livingston learned Flynt was
prepared to publish a report on his infidelities and chose to
reveal it himself first.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Larry Flynt thing got to me, and I made the decision (to
give up the speakership),'' Livingston told the Washington Times
this week. Flynt claims he was scooped on the story by the Capitol
Hill newspaper Roll Call, which disclosed the allegations on its
Website.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt's threats of more disclosures are putting a chill in the
air on Capitol Hill and causing gossip about who is, and who is
not, ``Flynt-proof.'' The conservative grapevine is also spreading
stories about the White House either encouraging the Flynt
enterprise or at least not condemning it loudly enough, aides to
some members say.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said
President Clinton ``despises the politics of personal destruction
that Larry Flynt and others practice. He believes it should stop.''
Lockhart noted, however, the White House doesn't have ``any control
over what a newspaper publisher does.''
</P>
<P>
   The Interfaith Alliance is going to address the politics of
personal destruction in a series of as many as 10 regional summit
meetings of religious leaders next year. The purpose, said Gaddy,
is to reaffirm broad moral principles in public and private life
but try to get politics and partisanship out of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always a danger that when you engage in a campaign of
ritual purification, you will be held to the same hypocritically
high standards that you hold your enemies to,'' said Chip Berlet, a
senior analyst at Political Research Associates, a private group in
Somerville that monitors the conservative agenda. ``Of course, the
religious right is reaping what is has sown.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when we engage in a television-era equivalent of a public
stoning, and when Larry Flynt becomes an icon of the Democratic
Party, things have gotten really absurd.'' Berlet said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
