<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4952 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKNOTES24-COX     12-23 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKNOTES24-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Quick-hit bios are an entertaining read
</P>
<P>
   By Don O' Briant
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   The problem with most biographies is their sheer heft. Drop one
of these tomes on your toe and you'll suffer for days. Sometimes
you'll suffer even if you don't drop it. Laundry-list biographies
can be as tedious as reading a list of begats in the Old Testament.
</P>
<P>
   Readers will have no such difficulty with the Penguin Lives
series of biographies published jointly with Lipper &AMP; Co. The
small-format books range from 128 to 256 pages and are written by
authors who are both entertaining and succinct.
</P>
<P>
   The first two books in the series (Viking plans six per year)
are Larry McMurtry's ``Crazy Horse'' (Viking, $19.95) and Edmund
White's ``Marcel Proust'' (Viking, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry is a natural fit for Crazy Horse. The author of
``Lonesome Dove'' wrote the book, he says, ``because I have some
notions about what he meant to his people in his lifetime, and also
what he has come to mean to a generation of Sioux in our century
and even in our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing simply but eloquently, McMurtry goes to the heart of the
man whose betrayal by the U.S. government became a tragic chapter
in the history of the American West.
</P>
<P>
   White, the author of ``A Boy's Own Story,'' was drawn to Proust
because of his longtime fascination with the writer. ``I first read
Proust when I was in high school, and even wrote a term paper on
him; I read Proust the second time when I was 30 and had hepatitis,
then again when I moved to Paris in 1983. Like me, he was
interested in love, friendship, art and society, which have become
themes in my novels as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is more of a literary appreciation than a straight
biography, but White also illuminates some of the darker corners of
Proust's life and reveals the writer to be more than an eccentric
recluse. According to White, Proust was a dazzling wit in Paris
salons and an unhappy homosexual who desperately sought fame and
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   The biographies of Proust and Crazy Horse are being shipped to
stores this week. Other works scheduled next year include Jane
Smiley on Charles Dickens, Carol Shields on Jane Austen and Mary
Gordon on Joan of Arc.
</P>
<P>
   PRIZE PROSE: After all the publicity, one would think Tom
Wolfe's ``A Man in Full'' was the only novel published in 1998.
Well, it was the literary event of the year, but several other
authors walked away with major prizes. Here's a recap of the year's
big winners: Alice McDermott's ``Charming Billy'' edged out Wolfe
for the National Book Award; Philip Roth's ``American Pastoral''
won the Pulitzer Prize for fiction; and Ian McEwan's ``Amsterdam''
was awarded Britain's Booker Prize. Other winners this year include
Charles Wright's ``Black Zodiac'' (Pulitzer Prize for poetry);
Jared Diamond's ``Guns, Germs and Steel: The Fate of Human
Societies'' (Pulitzer Prize for nonfiction); Rafi Zabor's ``The
Bear Comes Home'' (PEN/Faulkner Award); Edward Ball's ``Slaves in
the Family'' (National Book Award for nonfiction and Southern Book
Critics Circle Award for nonfiction); Gerald Stern's ``This Time:
New and Selected Poems'' (National Book Award for poetry); James
Lee Burke's ``Cimarron Rose'' (Edgar Allan Poe Award for
mysteries); Paul O. Zelinsky's ``Rapunzel'' (Caldecott Medal for
children's literature); Karen Hesse's ``Out of the Dust'' (Newbery
Medal for children's literature); and Joe Haldeman's ``Forever
Peace'' (Hugo Award for science fiction). The prizeless Wolfe,
meanwhile, can console himself with the fact that he topped Tom
Clancy as Amazon.com's best-selling author of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A COUP FOR BRIGHTLEAF: The winter issue of Brightleaf ($6.95), a
literary magazine published in North Carolina, features an
uncollected short story by Eudora Welty. First published in The
Atlantic in 1940, ``Hello and Goodbye'' was never included in any
of Welty's short story collections. Brightleaf editor David Perkins
describes the story as ``a light piece, but one that reflects the
sophisticated irony of this great writer already in flower.''
Brightleaf also includes a 14-page section on Welty with a tribute
by Atlanta writer Anthony Grooms, a profile by Boston writer Sally
Jacobs, and reviews of Welty's recently released ``Collected
Works.'' The Mississippi writer will celebrate her 90th birthday in
April.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O' Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
