<HEADER>
A4956 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALFREWOODARD24-COX     12-23 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALFREWOODARD24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woodard watchers keep their eyes on hers
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some actors are known for their voices, their hair, their comic
timing or their muscled bodies. Alfre Woodard should be known for
her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   While talking and emoting are obvious components of acting, the
strongest dramatic moments can happen in silence. Woodard knows
that. She's a watcher, a listener. Nominated for a supporting
actress Oscar for the 1983 drama ``Cross Creek,'' the actress, 45,
has also starred in ``Passion Fish,'' ``Grand Canyon'' and ``How to
Make an American Quilt.'' She played Winnie Mandela in the TV movie
``Mandela.'' She mingled with the crew of the starship Enterprise
in ``Star Trek: First Contact.'' And she won an Emmy for her role
as a nurse facing complex moral issues in ``Miss Evers' Boys,''
partly shot in the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Down in the Delta,'' opening Christmas Day, the Tulsa,
Okla., native plays Loretta, a single mother headed for
self-destruction _ until her own mom (Mary Alice) sends her down
South to stay a summer with Uncle Earl (Al Freeman Jr.) and come to
terms with herself and her family heritage. It's the first feature
directed by poet Maya Angelou.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard talked to us recently about the new movie.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what did you connect with in ``Down in the Delta''?
</P>
<P>
   A: I connected with Loretta. I found her very real, and I
recognized her. She was a human being that I would care to know.
She's funny and she's fun, and she would be honest with me in a way
that my other friends, who are more well-bred, couldn't be that
honest with me. I wanted to play somebody like that, knowing you've
got a very delicate piece of music to play, in terms of her arc.
She starts out in such turbulence, and then you've got another hour
and a half to sustain her music to the end.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you worry about working with Maya Angelou, since this was
her first time directing a film?
</P>
<P>
   A: You know, people ask me about first-time directors. That's
like saying, ``You know, Picasso, this is your first painting. In
10 years, I'll buy one of them.'' You can't really think that way
with an artist. There are people who have made hundreds of millions
of dollars on their pictures, but I still consider them
first-timers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So this movie is supposed to be in the Mississippi Delta, but
it was shot outside Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   A: That was easy. Well, I shouldn't say that. I remember
thinking, ``Toronto?!'' But it's a very interesting locale. And I
am a stickler for one thing, because I've shot in Canada before.
You can tell an African-Canadian from an African-American if
they're trying to act Southern. So I said, ``All the Canadians have
to pass my Southern test. Don't be actin' like no Canadians.'' But
they did very well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Yeah, when Hollywood makes a film set in the South, they seem
to think there's just one single Southern accent.
</P>
<P>
   A: I know. I've been in pictures where they will say, ``She's
Southern.'' And I'll say, ``What state? Louisiana? What part of
Louisiana?'' Is she from New Orleans, or the bayou, because there's
a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is your own family anything like the family in ``Down in the
Delta''?
</P>
<P>
   A: My father is an Uncle Earl (the Al Freeman Jr. role) times
100. He's a tough taskmaster. But he's also all that a human being
could be, in terms of understanding his connectedness, his heart,
his openness. Maya and I have really good family, and my family is
so big we run the gamut, honey. I have a sister and brother and
they have four kids, and I've got two kids (Mavis, 7, and Duncan,
5). My father's from a family of 12, my mother from a family of 23.
I am related to just about anybody you meet, once you get to
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you have fun when you were shooting ``Miss Evers Boys''
in Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   A: I never had any time off, I never did. I went to the Fish
Market every once in a while, but sometimes it was takeout because
I had to be up at 5 a.m. I wouldn't call it fun. You know what my
father calls me? Because every few months he has three new phone
numbers for me. My father says, ``You filled up my address book.
You need to get me another address book.'' He says, ``You know what
you are? You're a high-class migrant worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
