<HEADER>
A4960 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHERWRAP-COX     12-23 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHERWRAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winter weather blasts through the nation
 &HT;    By Todd C. Duncan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sudden blasts of harsh winter weather across the nation are
being blamed for dozens of deaths and injuries on treacherous icy
roads, including a 64 car wreck in Texas. The cold rush also sent
thermometer readings plummeting in much of the South.
</P>
<P>
   In some central states, such as Ohio, predictions of a white
Christmas were premature and cries of joy were heard throughout
Colorado's ski areas this week as the last fall snowstorm Sunday
left badly needed powder on the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Three people died and dozens were injured in more than 300
traffic wrecks Wednesday morning in Austin, Texas, including two
chain-reaction accidents on Interstate 35 involving 64 vehicles, as
freezing rain and temperatures caused slick conditions across
Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Light precipitation was expected to continue throughout the
evening Wednesday as temperatures hovered near 30 degrees. More
surface roads were freezing Wednesday afternoon, creating new
problems for highway crews trying to keep bridges and overpasses
clear for holiday travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Austin police recorded 337 auto accidents on city streets
between midnight and noon Wednesday, more than four times the 75
collisions police typically see on a rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists were cautioned to avoid I-35 Wednesday as emergency
management officials continued tracking reports of icy patches.
</P>
<P>
   Icy weather also has caused flights to be cancelled or delayed
until late this morning at airports throughout Alabama, Louisiana,
Mississippi, Tennessee and Texas, says Delta Air Lines spokesman
Clay McConnell.
</P>
<P>
   However, the system is expected to return to normal by noon. Air
travelers were stranded overnight in Shreveport and Monroe, La.;
Little Rock, Ark.; Greensboro, Charlotte, and Raleigh/Durham, N.C.;
and Huntsville, Ala., he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No weather impact is expected in Atlanta today, except for
people flying into the above-mentioned cities,'' said McConnell.
</P>
<P>
   The chain-reaction Texas wrecks happened three minutes apart on
either side
</P>
<P>
   of the concrete barriers separating northbound and southbound
lanes on I-35. Police said ice was the cause in both accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The first collision, at 1:10 a.m., involved at least 24 cars and
killed a 19-year-old Austin woman and injured 20 other motorists
and passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The second chain-reaction wreck happened at 1:13 a.m. when at
least 40 vehicles collided on the southbound lanes. Three or four
cars skidded into retaining walls along the highway, and at least
three dozen vehicles behind them slammed into each other as they
tried to avoid collisions.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-year-old man died in the southbound wreck. Police said the
man, a former wrecker driver, was towing a Toyota sedan when he
slammed into the back of a large truck that had stopped to avoid
the pile-up.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the number of vehicles involved in both accidents is
a conservative estimate because many motorists drove away before
police were able to get witness statements from them.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours later, another woman, 38, was killed when her car
struck a semi-trailer on U.S. 183 near Austin. Her car exploded
upon impact, police said. Two others were critically injured. The
highway remained closed until just after 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Across the South temperatures plummeted from record-breaking
highs.
</P>
<P>
   High temperatures in North Carolina tumbled 40 degrees from the
low 70s Tuesday to 33-34 in the eastern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   In Asheville, N.C., the temperature topped out at 54 degrees at
sunrise. By lunchtime, it had fallen to 35 degrees. Wilmington,
N.C., hit a high of 80 degrees Tuesday afternoon, but the low was
expected to plummet to the 30s overnight.
</P>
<P>
   There's little chance of a white Christmas in North Carolina on
Thursday, but a 50 percent chance of a wet one, according to the
National Weather Service office in Newport, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The wet weather will likely include sleet and freezing rain in
the western two-thirds of the state, with rain east of Interstate
95. Throughout Wednesday afternoon, North Carolina highways had
remained quiet and free of holiday accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, the snow was preceded by a blast of frigid air that
drove high temperatures from the 60s down to near zero, shocking
bicyclists and hikers who had enjoyed a mild, dry fall across most
of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The coldest temperature early Wednesday was 25 degrees below
zero at Craig, in northwest Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   By Christmas Day, most of Colorado is expected to be dry, with
lows from 10 degrees to 15 below zero and highs up to the teens and
20s.
</P>
<P>
   Up to a foot of snow, combined with winds of 40 mph, forced
transportation officials over the weekend to close several highways
in north-central Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   When the skies cleared Monday night, temperatures plunged well
below zero. Winds at the higher elevations in southern Colorado
blew at 30 to 40 mph. The sun helped people there feel warmer. No
new snow is forecast for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   None of Colorado's ski areas reported new snow Wednesday, and
before the weekend storm, most of them sorely needed it. Few of the
ski areas would have been open without the snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service forecasters Wednesday cautioned people
to expect another very cold night across southern Colorado. With
temperatures likely to drop between zero and 15 below zero over
southeast Colorado and 10 below to 5 above zero in the high
valleys, they advised people to protect themselves and their pets.
</P>
<P>
   In and around Dayton, Ohio, local TV meteorologists are under
pressure to deliver the snowflakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people love it when it snows on Christmas,'' says
Priscilla Parham, a meteorologist at WKEF-TV (Channel 22).
</P>
<P>
   For the past two weeks, Parham; Fred Barnhill, a meteorologist
at WHIO-TV (Channel 7); and WDTN-TV (Channel 2) meteorologist Kathy
Ellis have been fielding a flurry of questions from Dayton-area
residents who insist that the best Christmas is a white one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people stop me on the street and demand that I
deliver snow,'' Barnhill says with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Some won't take no for an answer, according to Ellis. ``When you
tell them it probably won't be a white Christmas, they look
disappointed, then they say, 'Can't you do something to make it
snow?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Even people who hate snow like to have a little bit around
during the holidays, Parham says. ``The only difference is that
those people want it to disappear the day after Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was chilled out this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it looks like South Florida is going to be the
warmest place in the country,'' said Bernard Esposito,
forecaster-in-charge at the National Weather Service in Miami. Palm
Beach County and the Treasure Coast can expect temperatures in low
80s through at least Saturday, with nights in the upper 60s. The
sudden cold front that is wreaking havoc up north will stop short
of St. Augustine to Cedar Key until at least late Saturday or early
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
