<SLUG> BC-GIVING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Just Click and Give  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Looking for a way to spread a little last-minute holiday cheer?
Look no further than your PC: Charitable groups have gone online.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of charitable organizations are harnessing the
enormous popularity of the Web to make donating money as simple as
any other electronic transaction _ enter your credit card number,
click the mouse and you're done.
</P>
<P>
   United Way, the American Cancer Society, the Red Cross and
UNICEF are just a few of the nonprofit groups that have gone
high-tech in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very busy, and donating online is quick,'' said
Dave Sandretto, executive director of Second Harvest Food Bank of
Santa Clara and San Mateo counties. The group, which helps feed the
hungry, has had a Web site for several years and began accepting
online donations just before Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The site,  &LR; www.donatefood.org &LR; , currently only takes financial
contributions, but it will soon allow donors to purchase groceries
for Second Harvest though online grocer Peapod.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a natural for here. People in Silicon Valley are
on the Web, so it's very easy to click over to Second Harvest and
make your donation,'' said Sandretto.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that ease, he said, response has been slow _ only a
tiny &LR;   &LR; percentage of total holiday giving has come via the
Internet. Sandretto hopes the site will eventually provide a way
for people to give year-round, not just at holidays or when they're
solicited by Second Harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Besides smoothing the way for financial contributions, several
Web sites are dedicated to making it easy to help in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we make it easy, more people are going to do it,'' said Jay
Backstrand, president of ImpactOnline, a Palo Alto group that
operates a Web site matching volunteers to nonprofit groups across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Using the site,  &LR; www.volunteermatch.org &LR; , would-be volunteers in
a hurry can punch in their ZIP code and certain other
specifications _ when they'd like to volunteer, how far they're
willing to travel and if they're seeking an continuing or one-time
volunteer opportunity _ and pull up a list of volunteer
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Since the site was launched in earnest in April, ImpactOnline
has hooked up some 13,000 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Bay Area, these volunteers have helped with such
projects as delivering meals to people with AIDS (Project Open
Hand), teaching reading (Project READ), sorting food at local food
banks and feeding animals in a shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nonprofit organizations need people, and they need to be able
to get them without having to spend a lot of money,'' said
Backstrand.
</P>
<P>
   Listing with ImpactOnline is free for both volunteers and
nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   The group is supported by the Packard Foundation, along with
several individual philanthropists.
</P>
<P>
   Another Web site caters to those who want to do good in a
relatively painless way _ by shopping online.
</P>
<P>
   At  &LR; www.iGive.com &LR; , the enlightened shopper can buy goods from
21 merchants including software retailer beyond.com, eToys, Music
Boulevard, cosmetics direct-marketer Avon and online video retailer
Reel.com.
</P>
<P>
   A percentage of each sale goes to the charity of the shoppers'
choice _ as little as 2.5 percent at apparel retailer J. Crew and
up to 12.5 percent from eToys. In exchange for directing shoppers
to e-merchants, iGive collects a transaction fee on each purchase
equal to the amount donated to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Since the site began operating a year ago, 40,000 people have
used it to give a total of $180,000 to 43 different causes, said
Robert Grosshandler, chief executive of iGive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great way people can do good in their daily lives,''
said Grosshandler. ``There's a whole new Internet economy
developing, and nonprofits need to participate in that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
