<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-1STPERSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESCAPE ON AN ICE-COATED HIGHWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I have a special reason to be thankful this
holiday season: I'm alive.
</P>
<P>
   For a few harrowing seconds in Wednesday's wee morning hours, on
an icy stretch of Interstate 35, I thought my time had come.
</P>
<P>
   It was around 1 a.m., and bone-chilling cold outside. There was
no precipitation _ and no highway danger as far as I could tell _
as I drove north on I-35 in Austin to drop off a friend.
</P>
<P>
   With no warning, conditions abruptly changed as I got back on
the freeway heading south. It began to sleet. Hard.
</P>
<P>
   Ice quickly covered my windshield, almost instantly blocking my
view. I hit the defrost and windshield wipers.
</P>
<P>
   As my vision cleared, I saw some cars ahead of me. I remember
thinking, as my foot gently pressed down on the brake pedal,
``What's wrong with these dad-gum brakes?''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for me to realize my brakes were not the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   I was on the cutting edge of a Texas ice storm, completely out
of control in my 1989 Ford pickup heading down I-35.
</P>
<P>
   The people in the cars next to me were also fishtailing left and
right. That we would meet each other in a violent collision at that
very moment seemed certain.
</P>
<P>
   I saw no way out.
</P>
<P>
   With little left to do but pray, I kept my foot off the brakes
and my hands firmly gripped on the steering wheel. Somehow, in the
absurd ice gallery that I-35 had become, an opening appeared.
</P>
<P>
   And with no help from me or my balding-tired truck, I slipped
through. Twenty-five minutes later, after driving 10 mph on
sleet-covered streets, I was home _ and thanking my lucky stars.
</P>
<P>
   Those behind me were not so lucky. Nor were the ones who came
after them. When it was over, 59 cars had piled up on both sides of
the freeway, and two people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   I know that a thousand events could have conspired to produce a
different outcome. Having to stop at a single red light could have
caused me to show up two minutes later than I did. That might have
been too late.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it was.
</P>
<P>
   I will say a prayer this Christmas for the families who lost
loved ones on that bitterly cold freeway. For everybody else, I'll
say: Drive carefully, and count your blessings. .MDBR/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Root is Austin Bureau chief of the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
