</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LED BY INTEL, STOCKS RISE AS S&AMP;P 500 AND NASDAQ HIT RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks barreled ahead Wednesday with two main gauges
setting records and a third, the Dow Jones industrial average,
posting a gain that left it just 1.8 percent shy of uncharted
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Although trading volume trailed off with the approach of the
Christmas holiday _ the market will close at 1 p.m. Thursday _
mutual fund managers and other professionals were said to be busy
shuffling portfolios to cast them in the best light for year-end
reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple days, there's been a rush to get money to
work,'' said Robert von Pentz, a portfolio manager for Columbia
Partners in Washington. At the same time, he added, many investors
who otherwise might be inclined to cash in some profits remained on
the sidelines to avoid having to pay taxes on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were thinking of selling your big winners, you might
wait until January,'' von Pentz said. Unloading them then would
would defer the tax bite an extra year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the speculative frenzy in Internet stocks generally
subsided even as a few of them posted sensational gains.
Ticketmaster, for example, soared 32, to 80 1/2, while Ubid
rocketed 53 1/2, to 188, less than three weeks after going public
at 15.
</P>
<P>
   One source of market inspiration came from Merrill Lynch, which
raised its long skeptical view of Intel to ``accumulate,'' helping
to drive the stock up 5 15/16, to 125. Microsoft, another
technology kingpin, jumped 5 1/8, to 143 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the technology-laden Nasdaq composite index advanced
51.56 points, or 2.43 percent, to 2,172.54, handily surpassing the
record it set on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, the benchmark for many
portfolio managers, rose 24.97 points, or 2.07 percent, to
1,228.54, its third straight record. The Dow climbed 157.57 points,
or 1.74 percent, to 9,202.03.
</P>
<P>
   The day's relentless advance, which seemed to disregard both
President Clinton's impeachment and the latest batch of economic
reports, was dampened briefly after the Federal Reserve published
the minutes of its Nov. 17 policy meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Besides confirming an assumption that the central bank had
abandoned its bias toward lower rates, the minutes portrayed Fed
policy-makers as less convinced that the economy was about to slow
than many analysts had believed them to be.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the minutes seemed to harden the view that the Fed's
third rate cut this autumn would be its last for some time, stocks
resumed their advance and closed at or near their best levels of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   One prominent American casualty was Lockheed Martin, the
military contractor, which issued another warning of lower profits
and plunged as low as 82 before closing at 84 1/2, down 10 1/2. But
United Technologies, another company with military operations, was
the biggest gainer among the 30 Dow blue chips, up 3 7/8, to 108
5/16.
</P>
<P>
   The next three were Procter &AMP; Gamble and Wal-Mart Stores, each
up 3 7/16, and Coca-Cola, up 2 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the market remains comfortable with
large-capitalization growth stocks,'' said Daniel Eagan, a
portfolio manager at Black Rock Inc. in Philadelphia. Value stocks,
he suggested, will need to wait for ``another day.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug makers, some of which have been battered of late, rebounded
smartly. Pfizer rose 3 3/16, to 120 3/8; Merck was up 2 1/4, to 149
5/8, and American Home Products climbed 1 15/16, to 54 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Financial issues were mostly higher, with Suntrust, up 3 1/2 to
77 1/2, a leader among banks, and Charles Schwab, up 2 3/8 to 57
13/16, posting one of the biggest gains among brokers. Equifax,
however, which provides credit reports and other financial
information, skidded 9 1/2, to 34 1/2, after warning of an earnings
shortfall because it had been too optimistic about its European
business.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest major market in Europe Wednesday was Germany's,
where the main index climbed 2.03 percent. The gains in France and
Britain were 1.36 percent and 1.12 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, the Bovespa rose eight-tenths of 1 percent, but
stocks fell 1.59 percent in Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
