<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4996 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PATCHADAMS-TEX     12-23 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PATCHADAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS' ANTICS CAN'T `PATCH' UP THIS FILM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robin Williams is starting to seem more and more irrelevant by
starring in another of what seems like a series of movies about
contemporary nonconformists. (Collect 'em all!) His role as
unconventional medical student Patch Adams is the latest. When you
add this one to ``Dead Poets Society'' and ``Good Morning,
Vietnam,'' you get the feeling that Williams isn't paying a whole
lot of attention to his filmography. When he falls back on that
tired sight gag he uses to indicate bitchiness _ he hisses like a
cat and bares his claws _ the younger children in the audience may
think they're watching a big-screen TV and reach for the VCR's
fast-forward. Or wish they could.
</P>
<P>
   Pop singer Billy Joel once talked about having gone through a
deep, depressed state as a very young man _ he tried to commit
suicide by drinking furniture polish _ and committing himself to a
mental institution. After spending time among people who were
chronically psychologically disturbed, he gained a new insight _ or
perhaps just an insight _ into his problem and left the asylum.
Patch undergoes a similar transformation. He commits himself to an
asylum, but the suffering he sees, much of which comes at the hands
of an indifferent doctor, motivates him.
</P>
<P>
   While in the mental hospital, Patch immediately helps jittery,
fearful Rudy (Michael Jeter), a fellow patient who can't set foot
on the floor of the room because he's afraid of a vicious
(imaginary) squirrel. After he jokes Rudy out of his anxiety, Patch
leaves the institution and commits himself to a calling; he enters
med school so he can help people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patch Adams'' sets Williams up as a hippie messiah _ it takes
place in the late '60s and early '70s. Williams isn't as wound up
in this film as in some others, showing some of the radiant calm
evident in his ``Dead Poets' Society'' performance. When he has
such moments, his actor's training (he studied at Juilliard, at the
same time as William Hurt) is visible. (Considering that it's hard
to think of a Williams performance in which he isn't jabbering and
flailing as if he's trying to flag down a tow truck, he's a
surprisingly believable listener.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Patch Adams'' is an attempt to get to the serious side of the
road for Tom Shadyac, its director, as well. Shadyac directed the
Jim Carrey comedies ``Ace Ventura'' and ``Liar, Liar.'' (It seems
that not only does Carrey want Williams' career, his director and
writer do as well; ``Adams'' was written by Steve Oedekerk, who
scripted the ``Ace Ventura'' movies.) ``Adams'' is sunny and bright
_ Shadyac has found a visual realization of the late hippie era; it
looks like a rainbow. The picture glides along competently _ but
not only have you seen this movie before, you've seen this movie
before with Robin Williams in it. Counting ``Vietnam'' and
``Awakenings,'' this is the third time he has appeared in a bland
feel-good bio-film. And this is the second time he has played a
doctor in one of these neutered bios. ``(Awakenings'' was the
first.) It's too bad he wasn't given a chance to break down some
walls when he essentially portrayed the restless
philosopher-physician Oliver Sacks in ``Awakenings.'' And ``Patch
Adams'' is just ``Vietnam's'' Adrian Cronauer in a more maudlin
setting, as he brings laughter to the sick.
</P>
<P>
   His constant joking seduces most of the characters in the movie,
except the uptight medical school prof (Bob Gunton, flashing his
standard institutional villainy _ it's the J.T. Walsh role). Philip
Seymour Hoffman, a specialist at wormy creeps uncomfortable in
their own skin, is Patch's major competition, a cold, technically
brilliant student who lacks Adams' heart. He's lucky _ he's one of
the few who isn't won over by Patch's antics. Monica Potter plays
the determined, serious one, nervous because she's one of the few
female students at the school, and whom Patch liberates from
herself.
</P>
<P>
   You may find yourself wanting to like ``Patch Adams'' because
its heart is in the right place. Patch wants to bring empathy back
into the medical practice. (The movie should play especially well
in these days of medical-factory HMOs.) The film's guerrilla
assault on the medical establishment is reminiscent of the old days
when B movies sent doctors into the inner cities to make a
difference. But Patch is such a hero that even disaster sets him
back only momentarily; the entire picture is stacked in his favor.
I'm sure the real Patch Adams wishes his life were so easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patch Adams'' is rated PG-13 for crude humor and strong
language.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDBU/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 2055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
