<HEADER>
A4999 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JONES-RELIGION-TEX     12-23 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONES-RELIGION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THE BIBLE WERE A COMIC BOOK ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adam and Eve frolic in the nude. The drawings are so small, or
are done in such a way, that even the most prudish readers should
not object.
</P>
<P>
   The colorful images are featured in a new Bible done in the
upscale comic-book style of a graphic novel. It was released
recently by Lion Publishing in Oxford, England.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lion Graphic Bible'' is not the first attempt _ and I'm
sure not the last _ to bring the Bible to readers who might not be
attracted to a traditional version of Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   Adam is a muscular, bearded man, and Eve is an attractive young
woman with shoulder-length auburn hair. As might be expected, Adam
is wide-eyed when God creates a woman to keep him company.
</P>
<P>
   A balloon over Adam's head states: ``At last! One of my own
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   The next panel shows Adam and Eve looking into each other's
eyes, and the newly created man speaking to Eve in paraphrases from
Genesis: ``Bone taken from my bone, flesh from my flesh. I will
call you `woman' because you were taken out of man.''
</P>
<P>
   One close-up illustration shows Eve eating the forbidden fruit.
Bits of the fruit are popping out between her perfect teeth.
</P>
<P>
   A green serpent, first seen as walking upright, tempts Eve into
eating the fruit, and she shares it with Adam. After they eat it,
as most Bible readers know, they experience shame for the first
time and realize they are naked.
</P>
<P>
   When God confronts the couple trying to hide themselves, Adam
declares: ``It's not my fault! This woman you put here with me _
she told me to do it.'' Eve says the serpent tricked her, and God
curses the serpent, taking away his legs so he must ``crawl on his
belly in the dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   The realistic drawings are by award-winning British cartoonist
Jeff Anderson, who has worked with many well-known companies,
including DC Comics. British writer Mike Maddox did the script, and
lettering is by Steve Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``''The Lion Graphic Bible'' has been a labor of love for the
people here in Oxford,'' Paul Wilson, a representative of the
Oxford publishing firm, said this week. ``It has taken five years
for our illustrator to do the 2,000 pictures required.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales have been good in Britain, he said. ``The Lion Graphic
Bible,'' which sells for $29.99, has just become available in U.S.
bookstores. It is being distributed by Broadman &AMP; Holman, the
Southern Baptist Convention's publishing arm.
</P>
<P>
   Although there have been comic-book style versions of portions
of the Bible in the past, this is the first to cover the entire
Bible using sophisticated graphic novel-style drawings, Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Patterson of Nashville, a publicist for the Southern
Baptist Convention publishing agency, said the ``The Lion Graphic
Bible'' appeals to adults even though it is targeted at teens and
preteens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could reach a younger audience, too,'' she said. ``My son,
who is 4, loves it. He can't read the words, but he loves the
pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   One goal of ``The Lion Graphic Bible,'' Wilson said, is to lure
young people away from computers and videos and back to books. It
hopes to repeat the success of other graphic novels about Batman,
Superman and other subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The stories of Noah, Abraham, Jacob, Moses, Joshua, Samson,
Esther and other Old Testament characters are vividly related in
words and pictures.
</P>
<P>
   One panel shows an evil-looking knife that Abraham almost uses
to sacrifice his son, Isaac, until God stops him with the words:
``Abraham! Do not harm the child!''
</P>
<P>
   A retelling of the Christmas story focuses on the tension Joseph
feels when he discovers that his future wife, Mary, is going to
have a child. A glowing angel tells him, ``Do not be afraid to take
her as your wife, son of David.''
</P>
<P>
   Another panel states: ``Theirs wasn't the first wedding where
the bride was obviously pregnant, nor was it the last. But Joseph
trusted the words of the angel, and turned a deaf ear to the
gossip-mongers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some humorous touches are used in the stories of Jesus. When
Nicodemus, the Jewish scholar, visits Jesus late at night, a comic
panel shows Jesus yawning and saying, ``Rather late, isn't it?''
Salome dances seductively during the retelling of the beheading of
John the Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``The Lion Graphic Bible'' may not find its way into
seminaries, it will fascinate many young people _ and even adults _
searching for a fresh look at the age-old Scriptures. .MDBR/.MDNM/
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
