<SLUG> BC-ROCKETDYNE-LAWSUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT ENDORSES CLASS-ACTION SUIT OVER LAB CONTAMINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA MASCARO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. -- A class-action lawsuit over contamination
at Rocketdyne's Santa Susana Field Lab is to move forward after a
federal appellate court declined an appeal of the class-action
status, which paved the way for more than 200,000 residents and
workers to potentially join the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers will resume plans to begin notifying possible plaintiffs
within 90 days after receiving the decision Wednesday from the 9th
Circuit Court of Appeals not to take up the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another step forward in a long journey,'' said
plaintiff's attorney A. Barry Cappello from Cappello &AMP; McCann, the
Santa Barbara, Calif.-based firm that is the lead on the case.
``It's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocketdyne officials said that while they were disappointed in
the court's decision, believing there is no evidence to establish
the class, it was no indication of how the suit would play out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, we're disappointed by this,'' said Rocketdyne
spokesman Dan Beck. ``I think it's important not to read anything
into the 9th Circuit Court's ruling other than they didn't want to
deal with those issues at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judges Robert Beezer and A. Wallace issued a decision
Dec. 17 denying the appeal filed by Rocketdyne's parent company.
</P>
<P>
   The case is among a number of suits stemming from the field lab
where nuclear and chemical contaminants have been found in soil and
water on the site, where the company for decades tested rocket
engines in the hills above suburban Simi Valley in Southern
California's Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   The case claims toxins contaminated the ground and air affecting
a class of potential plaintiffs living, working or owning property
in a rectangular area bounded roughly by the Ronald Reagan and
Ventura freeways, from Simi Valley to the San Diego Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   The suit calls for medical monitoring of the plaintiffs and
compensation for property damage. The group excludes those with
cancer or other designated illnesses. Some of the area residents
who fall into that category are being represented in other
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Audrey B. Collins granted class-action
status in July, nearly a year after having denied the status on the
plaintiffs' previous attempt to move forward as a group.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, both sides received notice that the 9th Circuit
Court would not take up the appeal, essentially deciding not to
address the issue at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Cappello said Wednesday that his firm would begin planning class
notification, which could involve contacting between 200,000 and
500,000 residents, workers or property owners in the area.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on class notification would be held in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The case was filed by a resident against Rocketdyne's parent
company Boeing North America and Rockwell International.
</P>
<P>
   Rocketdyne officials have maintained that the case is without
merit, and that the plaintiffs have not produced facts to support
their claims about the contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (plaintiff attorneys) have yet to offer any proof that
anybody has suffered adverse affect because of off-site
contamination,'' said Beck. ``We will continue to defend against
this lawsuit as being completely without merit and lacking in any
scientific validity.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
