<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5004 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-LAWSUITS-2NDTAKE     12-23 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-LAWSUITS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BOSTON: someone else.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are signs that the dozens of gun companies, most of them
small and privately held, are taking steps to set aside customary
rivalries and mount a joint defense.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Feldman, executive director of the American Shooting
Sports Council, a trade association, has been busy lining up
national law firms with experience in tobacco litigation, like
Goodwin, Proctor &AMP; Hoar in Boston, to help represent the firearms
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are either going to address the issues that are coming at
us head on, or we are going to get picked off, one by one,''
Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the manufacturers who were sued in the tobacco
cases, he noted, but some of the cities are planning to sue not
only the gun makers but also the distributors and local dealers,
and some gun makers may be tempted to blame dealers who have been
caught selling illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Boyd, a lawyer with Goodwin, Proctor &AMP; Hoar, said the gun
companies as well as the cities could learn from the tobacco
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plaintiffs don't have to win all of these cases, they just
have to file enough of them and you can count on an aberrant
decision by a judge somewhere letting a case go to trial,'' Boyd
said. ``That creates enormous risk for the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These suits,'' he added, ``are far more political than legal.
They are a multifront attack through a public forum, and if you
don't rebut them politically you can find yourself losing entirely.
And that in turn affects judges who are sensitive to political
currents.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldman described the cities' resort to litigation as ``very
dangerous to American democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are supposed to be decided in the legislature,''
he said, ``not the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   But the mayors say that for too many years, the gun makers and
the National Rifle Association have controlled the state
legislatures and Congress as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is practically politically impossible to go into our state
legislature in Indianapolis and reasonably hope to get more
restrictive gun laws,'' said Mayor Scott King of Gary, which has
long had one of the nation's highest homicide rates.
</P>
<P>
   The mayors believe that by shifting the venue from the
legislature to the urban courtroom, where some jurors are likely to
have had firsthand experience with gun violence, they have a better
chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly what the courts are there to do, to fix
inequities that you can't accomplish in the legislature,'' said
Penelas, of Miami-Dade County.
</P>
<P>
   One difficulty for the cities has been to decide which legal
avenue to pursue: a product liability claim, the New Orleans model,
or Chicago's claim of a public nuisance, or both. Most cities say
they are leaning toward the product liability approach, although
the final decision depends on differences in state and city gun
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Rendell, of Philadelphia, believes that it
will take five or six years _ from suit filing until the end of the
appeals process _ to win any money from the industry. He envisions
a point in the interim when the cities will sit down to engage in
collective negotiations with the industry for a settlement
providing new controls.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes he would like are a limit of one handgun
purchase a month per customer, a ban on advertisements that guns
are safe and a halt to the production of large clips for handguns
and bullets that can pierce police armor.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rand, of the Violence Policy Center, said she worried that
such negotiations ``could be a disaster'' because many city
officials and gun-control groups ``would be willing to settle for
very little.''
</P>
<P>
   She said they ought to hold out for making the gun makers submit
to oversight by the Consumer Product Safety Commission, like other
industries, and forcing them to adopt more careful inventory
controls to prevent sales to criminals or straw purchasers acting
on behalf of criminals. Recent investigations by the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms have found that as many as half the
handguns used in crimes had been purchased from licensed dealers
within the prior three years.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Sharpe James of Newark, N.J., agreed that gun makers ought
to be subjected to additional federal regulation .
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's reached a point where we want to hold the gun
manufacturers accountable,'' he said. ``They are putting concerns
for profit over life. We've just allowed them to sell weapons like
popcorn and ice cream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
