r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANGER-IMMIGRANTS-AZR     12-23 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANGER-IMMIGRANTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECENT LATIN AMERICAN IMMIGRANTS FACE INCREASED DANGER HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ For years it has been a mantra among immigrants from
Latin America to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   You have gotten past all the thieves lurking in the shadows of
the border lands, past the Border Patrol dragnet. You are in the
big city, more than 100 miles from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Home free.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; But for many these days, the danger doesn't stop at the border.
</P>
<P>
   Police and federal agents say that crime against immigrants has
been escalating at a rapid rate recently because there's more money
to be made _ by charging more to smuggle, and mixing drugs with the
human cargo. That breeds robberies and violence and immigrants
often are caught in the crossfire. But they remain willing to take
the risk, fleeing worsening economic conditions back home.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, three immigrant families living in a southwest
Phoenix home were victims of a home invasion in which an infant in
its mother's arms was shot and critically wounded after demands for
cash, drugs and valuables were not met. The same residence also had
been invaded on two other recent occasions, one in which a man was
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   That follows another home invasion in central Phoenix in late
September in which a group of five robbers laid siege to a drop
house of 16 illegal immigrants, killing one man, pistol whipping
another and kidnapping a third.
</P>
<P>
   Some have been fighting back. One woman from El Salvador called
Phoenix police last year when a coyote, an illegal-immigrant
smuggler, demanded $2,000 more than the agreed-upon price to
release her two daughters who were brought illegally to this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Cases like that are the exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt these people are being targeted more and
more,'' said Phoenix police Sgt. Mike Torres. ``But we don't hear
very much about it because they think they will be deported.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Homan, who heads investigations for the Phoenix office of
Immigration and Naturalization Service, also said his office hears
about only a small percentage of crime in which recent immigrants
are victims or perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time it comes to anyone's attention is if someone is
shot and even that doesn't mean the police will be called,'' Homan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Homan said that drop houses are constantly being ripped off by
rival smuggling gangs and, sometimes, even by other people who live
in the area who anticipate big cash inside. drop houses are
residences where illegal immigrants are held after being smuggled
from the border until family or friends pay the coyote's fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is big now, just about as big as dope,'' Homan said.
``We took down one house a few weeks back at 18th Street and Van
Buren with 114 illegals in it which had $140,000 in cash inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to never find weapons in drop houses. Now, you seldom
find one that doesn't have numerous arms in it. The smugglers are
more violent now and the people they smuggle are more desperate to
stay here. You get more abuses but the silence about it is
deafening. For example, we have a major problem with hostage
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   One undercover INS agent, who asked that she be referred to as
Ophelia Ruiz to protect her true identity, said she had just
finished working a hostage case. A coyote had placed a gun to the
head of a man he had smuggled into Arizona and made him call his
wife, demanding additional money for his smuggling fee.
</P>
<P>
   Because of intensified security at the border, the cost of
smuggling an illegal from Nogales to Phoenix has increased from
$150 to $500 during the past three years. Ruiz also said she has
worked other cases where rival smuggling organizations rip off drop
houses just as most illegals inside have paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they (rival smugglers) will go and advertise back in
Mexico that this and that coyote isn't any good because they can't
offer security for the people they smuggle,'' Ruiz said. ``It's a
vicious cycle which leads to more crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz also said that most illegals are unaware when they come to
the Phoenix area that the coyotes also are smuggling drugs with
them, often hiding it on small children in groups of illegals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, people smuggling and drug smuggling were two
different things,'' Ruiz said. ``Now, 98 percent of the time, the
people smugglers have drugs also.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Shaffer can be reached at 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
