<HEADER>
A5009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      12-23 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FED DISCLOSES DISSENT ON NOVEMBER RATE CUT
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve's decision on Nov. 17 to cut interest rates
was driven by concern that problems in the financial markets might
again intensify and drag down the economy, a summary of the meeting
shows.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed minutes said that the decision to cut rates in November
``was viewed as a close call by several members,'' but the sole
dissenter was Jerry L. Jordan, president of the Federal Reserve
Bank of Cleveland. He said that two previous quarter-point cuts had
been sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   DURABLE GOODS ORDERS ADVANCE
</P>
<P>
   Orders for durable goods rose 1 percent in November, more than
expected. Consumer confidence remained high during December, the
University of Michigan said.
</P>
<P>
   FOR CHILDREN, MEDICINE OR CANDY?
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies are selling candy-like over-the-counter remedies
for treating children's ailments like colds, sore throats and even
asthma. But some doctors say that treating any medicine as if it
were candy is confusing and potentially dangerous for children.
</P>
<P>
   SUIT CITES CHASE AND J.P. MORGAN
</P>
<P>
   A suit filed in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn accuses Chase
Manhattan and J.P. Morgan of wrongfully seizing bank accounts and
safe-deposit assets of Jewish customers during the Nazi occupation
of France in World War II. Chase called the suit unnecessary;
Morgan said it would look into the issue.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED MARTIN WARNS ON PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin said profit this year and next year would be
even lower than it forecast last month because sales were declining
and production delays were increasing. Its shares tumbled 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
   CRAY TRADE RULING TO BE REVIEWED
</P>
<P>
   A federal court ordered U.S. trade officials to reconsider their
ruling that unfairly priced exports by Japanese supercomputer
makers threatened to harm the Cray Research division of Silicon
Graphics.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH INDUSTRIALIST CONVICTED
</P>
<P>
   Serge Dassault, 75, head of the French military concern Dassault
Aviation, was convicted by Belgium's highest court on corruption
charges involving two military contracts in the late 1980s, as was
Willy Claes, 60, a former NATO secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
   FORD LINK IS RUMORED FOR VOLVO
</P>
<P>
   Shares of both Volvo AB and Bayerische Motoren Werke AG, or BMW,
jumped on speculation that each carmaker was holding talks with
Ford Motor that could lead to a merger or another link. BMW called
merger rumors unfounded, while Volvo and Ford declined comment.
Excess capacity in the global auto industry has raised expectations
of more mergers like Daimler-Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   ITALIAN CENTRAL BANK CUTS RATE
</P>
<P>
   The Italian central bank reduced its benchmark interest rate
half a percentage point to a record low 3 percent, completing the
alignment of rates among the 11 nations joining the European single
currency.
</P>
<P>
   CITIES SUING THE GUN INDUSTRY
</P>
<P>
   Heartened by the success states have had in suing tobacco
companies and recovering hundreds of billions of dollars in
smoking-related Medicaid costs, more than a dozen cities are now
taking aim at the gun industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
