<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5010 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      12-23 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE AN ANGEL BY GIVING OTHERS A LIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A few days before last Christmas, I stood outside the
front door of a hospital in western Pennsylvania. The temperature
was in the 30s and I wasn't wearing a coat or gloves.
</P>
<P>
   I was cold, but not cold enough, so I wrapped my hands around
the support pole of an awning and held on until my fingers went
numb and began sticking to the metal.
</P>
<P>
   Then I pulled them off and ran into the building, up the stairs
to the second floor, down the hall to Room 205.
</P>
<P>
   I walked inside, sat down next to the bed, and put my freezing
hands on my mother's forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahhh, that feels good,'' she said, not opening her eyes.
``Where were you?''
</P>
<P>
   Just getting a little air, I answered, leaning over to brush my
icy cheek against hers, and to kiss her.
</P>
<P>
   It was one thing I could do at a time when it seemed as if there
was nothing I could do. She was feverish. She'd been in the
hospital for weeks. It was near the end.
</P>
<P>
   My father and brother and I filled the days as best we could,
waiting _ as the nuns in Catholic school used to say _ for angels
to come and get her.
</P>
<P>
   And they did. &QL; 
THE ONES I COULD SEE &QL; 
Afterward, it wasn't those angels I was most grateful to, however.
</P>
<P>
   It was the ones I could see. The nurses and doctors and hospital
volunteers who were there every day.
</P>
<P>
   We have people like that here.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them work for Hospice of the Valley, the oldest
not-for-profit hospice organization in town.
</P>
<P>
   Just recently, Hospice sent out a notice looking for more
volunteers to help patients and families dealing with terminal
illness.
</P>
<P>
   It involves four hours a week and might include anything from
reading, playing cards, talking or running errands. The kind of
things Gordon Murphy has been doing for the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a relatively new volunteer,'' the retired lobbyist
told me. ``I knew I wanted to do something useful with my time and
had read about Hospice. As it turns out, it's me who's benefited
most. I've seen so many wonderful people at work. And met so many
wonderful people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospice of the Valley is one of the organizations that have
received grants from ``The Republic's'' annual Season for Sharing
campaign. Every day there's a donation coupon printed on Page A2.
</P>
<P>
   The contributions are matched dollar for dollar by the Robert R.
McCormick Tribune Foundation in Chicago until the total reaches
$800,000. &QL; 
THE LITTLE STUFF COUNTS &QL; 
If you're like me, and don't have the wings to actually BE an
angel, it's one way to provide a little lift for those who work for
outfits like Hospice.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy volunteers at Gardiner House, a care facility for
terminally ill patients. Other volunteers visit Hospice clients and
their families at home. Still others help with fund-raising or
office work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with people at the very end of life,'' Murphy
said. ``It's difficult, but the compassion from the Hospice staff,
and the professionalism, really puts the patient's mind at ease.
And it really helps the families, who are dealing with so many big
things all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure that's true.
</P>
<P>
   But now, a year later, it's little things I remember.
</P>
<P>
   Family photos taped to a hospital wall.
</P>
<P>
   The sports page being read out loud.
</P>
<P>
   Cold hands on a warm face. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
