A5020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EQUIFAX-EARNINGS24-CO     12-23 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EQUIFAX-EARNINGS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Equifax shares plunge on earnings warning
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Equifax stock tumbled 22 percent Wednesday after the
company said fourth-quarter earnings would be about 31 cents a
share instead of the 41 cents expected by analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The slide knocked $1.4 billion off Equifax's stock market value.
</P>
<P>
   Equifax said about half of the earnings shortfall resulted from
the fact managers in Europe included in fourth-quarter internal
projections revenue that should not have been attributed to that
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are very disappointed with the developments in
Europe, we immediately assessed the causes and impact and moved
swiftly to make the appropriate management and process changes,''
Thomas F. Chapman, president and chief executive officer, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Nick J. Bevan, an Equifax executive vice president, was replaced
as head of the Atlanta-based company's European operations by C.
Richard Crutchfield.
</P>
<P>
   The European division's chief financial officer, whose name was
not disclosed, resigned, said Marietta Edmunds Zakas, corporate
vice president. Steve Ford, an Equifax controller, was named
successor.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement might give some investors concern about
financial controls at Equifax, said analyst Kevin R. Gruneich, who
follows the company for Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   But ``it really seems financial controls worked in this case.
The corporate headquarters found something was awry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Equifax ``will be in the penalty box'' for a while,
Gruneich said, he did not change his ``buy'' rating. ``I think it's
silly to downgrade the stock or to sell the stock after it opened
down $9.''
</P>
<P>
   Zakas said the fourth-quarter projection from Europe included
all the revenue on contracts that extend as long as three years.
The revenue should be recognized over the life of the contracts,
not just in one period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they were forecasting revenue for those was not
consistent'' with the company's practices, she said. ``They were
doing it incorrectly. It was caught at the forecast stage, we sent
a team to investigate ... then we changed management.''
</P>
<P>
   Zakas emphasized that projections, not reported results, were at
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is isolated to the fourth quarter. It is isolated to
Europe,'' she added. ``All of our other operating segments are
doing very well for the quarter and the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Equifax said the rest of the earnings shortfall is due to ``the
cancellation or postponement of several projects ... the
collectability of past-due receivables, increased bad check losses
... in Europe and a softening in the U.K. economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also wrote off its investment in RequesT, a start-up
joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   Zakas said Equifax now expects to report 1998 earnings of about
$1.34 a share, and $1.57-$1.59 a share in 1999, including the
impacts of Year 2000 computer costs and its Brazilian acquisitions.
The company earlier said the acquisitions would reduce 1999 results
by 7 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Equifax reported earnings of $1.24 a share, before
unsual items, a nonrecurring gain and an accounting charge.
</P>
<P>
   The profit warning was, as Zakas noted, ``uncharacteristic'' of
the company, which has been in business since 1899.
</P>
<P>
   Equifax has in the past consistently met or beat analysts'
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The company, whose headquarters are at 1600 Peachtree St. in
Midtown, employs 14,000 people in 18 countries, including about
2,800 in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Equifax processes bank and credit card transactions, authorizes
credit and check transactions, and sells consumer credit
information.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
