u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HUMMER-COLUMN24-C     12-23 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HUMMER-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doing less is better for Smith
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In these giddy days of uncommon deeds, a moment,
please, for those Falcons whose major contribution has been to do
less.
</P>
<P>
   When this team lost _ it used to do so regularly, you know _ the
Smith family was right out there, pilloried for all to see. Now, in
the midst of the Falcons' winningest season ever, you'd scarcely
know they still own the majority of the team. It is addition by
absenteeism, a strategy of non-involvement that has paid off
handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   No one seems happier about the results than the forgotten
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirteen-and-two, I have to pinch myself, it's so hard to
believe,'' said Taylor Smith, the team president and point man for
the Smiths since the death last year of his father, Rankin Smith
Sr. ``Every Monday, I find myself saying, `My God, we won again!'
And the way we win makes you feel good _ there are no flukes in the
way we play. It's just amazing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   What about ego? Doesn't this route to success rub against the
Jerry Jones that lives in every NFL owner? ``No, not at all,''
Smith said. ``You don't get too many opportunities to hire people
like (Dan Reeves). To have somebody like that, it was like a
relief. We needed a strong, strong leader in here, and that's what
we got.''
</P>
<P>
   What about missing the intimate involvement with the day-to-day
operations of an NFL franchise? ``Stepping back, that's the easy
part. ... Mainly in the contract area, my role is different. Thank
goodness. I don't want anything to do with that anyway,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one party that makes all the football decisions. The
way we were set up in the past, there was a personnel area and a
coaching area. I was the final say if anything came down between
them. Believe me, I like this set-up a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Smith still maintains a large, cluttered office in the
heart of the Falcons bunker, but there is no question about who is
running the show. One gets the truest sense of how much Reeves
means to the continuing health of this franchise by how eager the
Smiths are to hand over all authority and credit. Much hinges on
Reeves' recuperative powers. For everyone's sake, get well soon,
Dan.
</P>
<P>
   On the late October day in '97 that Rankin Smith Sr. died, the
Falcons lost to Charlotte to fall to 1-7. The man who had
wet-nursed pro football in the South did not live to see his team
turn around, but his son insists that he knew this day was coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible for me to think that we've won 19 of 23 games
since the day Dad died,'' Taylor Smith said. ``You could see from
the beginning that Dan was special. We were losing, but we were
barely losing. Chris (Chandler) was hurt, we had played Denver
tough (losing 29-21), played San Francisco tough (losing 35-28) but
we weren't getting anything out of it. (Rankin Sr.) felt really
good about Dan. I believe he's sitting up there and knows what's
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the sorry state of the Falcons, the Smiths spent much
of their days serving as a community punch line. The frustrations
all bubbled to the top of the organizational chart. They were
ridiculed as bumpkins unable or unwilling to construct a winner.
There grew the belief that the Falcons would never amount to
anything as long as the Smiths owned them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the glow of success, Smith chooses not to bare any old
scars. In fact, he'll join the chorus of those who have questioned
the past:
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in it, I know (criticism) is the nature of the
beast. It's hard. The highs and lows are unbelievable. It's been
real important to the family for this team to be a winner. I always
felt that while we didn't always make great decisions, we tried to
do things that were right. We didn't make any excuses for it; we
were just looking for the right fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way you can make any excuses as to what our record was. We
had some brief periods of success but never sustained it. We dug
ourselves a big hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've missed the boat for so long. Atlanta has really deserved
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, of course, is to make this team mean something in
the long run. There have been brief spikes in Falcons history,
always followed by the inevitable plunge. In 33 seasons, this
blighted franchise never has had consecutive winning records. Its
success has been as accidental as a winning lottery ticket or
lightning strike.
</P>
<P>
   The team president counts on Reeves' complete recovery from
bypass surgery and his continued immersion in the Falcons' affairs.
It is their last best hope for consistency. ``Dan wants to make
this thing special over a long period of time,'' Smith said. ``He
says that's the only way you're really successful.''
</P>
<P>
   At the present, these are among the best of times for the
Falcons' first family. They gather this Christmas at their
Thomasville plantation and gladly celebrate what they haven't done
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
