<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves speaks briefly to his players
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The doctor-imposed isolation of Falcons coach Dan
Reeves was suspended briefly Wednesday morning when he spoke to his
players by speaker phone from his hospital room, congratulating
them for their NFC West championship and telling them to play hard
this week against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   It was his second address to the squad since he had quadruple
heart bypass surgery Dec. 14, and the first since he was readmitted
to Piedmont Hospital on Sunday after experiencing an accelerated
heart rate two days after his original release.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, team officials were told Reeves would not be allowed
contact with players or assistants this week because the
54-year-old coach tried to do too much too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the rest has done Reeves good, although it is still
not clear when he will leave the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Team internist Charlie Harrison and heart surgeon James Kauten
``had a change of heart and allowed Dan to speak to the team,''
interim head coach Rich Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He congratulated the team (and) told them merry Christmas. I
don't know whether he'll be home at Christmas or what.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety William White said it was important to hear from
Reeves for the first time since the team clinched the NFC West
title with a 24-17 victory at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always great to hear from your leader, and he is our
leader,'' White said. ``He was real proud of the way we handled
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is listed in stable condition. He has been taking blood
thinners, and doctors have experimented with medications to
regulate his heart rate.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the morning after he was first released, Harrison
drove Reeves to team headquarters in Suwanee, where he intended to
review a 10-minute highlight film from the previous game at New
Orleans. Instead, he spoke only a few minutes and was too tired to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``His voice sounded really good (Wednesday),'' quarterback Chris
Chandler said. ``It sounded a lot stronger than on Saturday. He
said, `Merry Christmas,' but he didn't let us know when he might
get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said he was glad he made the decision earlier this week
not to rest any players this Sunday, even though the Falcons can
gain nothing in terms of playoff positions with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I did,'' Brook said, ``because I got that talk from
Dan very briefly this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Reeves) told us champions never stopped proving it,''
Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
