<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-WEATHER-COX     12-23 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-WEATHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three killed in Austin pile-up
 &HT;    By Kelly Daniel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Three people were killed and dozens injured Wednesday
in more than 400 traffic accidents, including two pileups on
Interstate 35 involving a total of 64 vehicles, as freezing rain
and temperatures wreaked havoc on roads and holiday travel plans
across Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   More freezing rain was expected today and forecasters warned
motorists to expect the same conditions this morning as they saw
Wednesday. Slightly warmer temperatures were expected today,
however, and officials expected conditions to improve during the
afternoon. Today's high should reach 34 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go through another bad batch of weather before
it starts clearing up,'' said Tony Perez, a meteorologist for the
National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency management officials cautioned people to stay at home
if possible, but conceded holiday travelers likely would be trying
to get to their Christmas destinations. If driving today, ``assume
that any wet spot on the road is ice,'' said Steve Collier, Office
of Emergency Management director for Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Travel throughout Texas was disrupted Wednesday by freezing
rain, sleet and snow, with the Dallas and Fort Worth areas
especially affected. The Department of Public Safety reported 10
people died across the state due to weather-related accidents as of
Wednesday evening, and Irving police added an 11th _ a man in a
multi-vehicle wreck got out of his car and was struck by another
car.
</P>
<P>
   In the Austin area, Wednesday's icy drizzle brought many
activities to a standstill. Austin and Travis County governments
sent non-essential employees on Christmas break a day early. Many
holiday shoppers stayed home. Some home health care providers were
unable to reach patients. Cold weather shelters were packed.
American Airlines canceled all its flights out of Austin Wednesday,
while other airlines struggled with delays. The Trail of Lights
Christmas display at Zilker Park was closed, but could be open for
its final night tonight if conditions improve.
</P>
<P>
   Austin police reported 360 traffic accidents between midnight
and 3:30 p.m. Wednesday _ more than four times the 75 collisions
they typically handle on a rainy day. Travis County also reported
52 wrecks by noon Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting it to get bad around the morning hours, but
things started to happen around 1 or 2 in the morning,'' said
Carlos Cordova, a city of Austin spokesman. ``There were just some
really bad collisions today. Just very tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst occurred in the 6100 block of I-35 near U.S. 290, when
separate chain-reaction accidents happened three minutes apart on
either side of the divided highway, killing two people, injuring
more than 20 and clogging all lanes.
</P>
<P>
   At least 24 vehicles slammed into each other on the northbound
side of I-35 at 1:10 a.m. after one vehicle hit an icy patch and
its driver lost control. Cynthia Perez, 19, of the Wells Branch
neighborhood north of Austin, died at Brackenridge Hospital after
being injured in one of the secondary crashes in the northbound
accident.
</P>
<P>
   While police rushed to the northbound side, at least 40 vehicles
crashed into each other in the southbound lanes at 1:13 a.m. Police
said three or four cars skidded into retaining walls along the
highway, causing a domino-effect pileup of trailing vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Ransel, 30, a wrecker driver, was pronounced dead at the
scene of the southbound crash. Police said he was towing a Toyota
sedan behind his wrecker truck when he slammed into the back of an
tractor-trailer truck that had stopped to avoid the pile-up. His
wrecker bounced off the rear of the 18-wheeler and hit another car
on the shoulder of the roadway, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Ice caused both interstate accidents, which were not related
even though they happened so close together, police said. A
concrete barrier separates the northbound and southbound lanes.
Police said the number of cars involved is a conservative estimate
because a number of drivers drove away or were waved on before
officers were able to get statements from them.
</P>
<P>
   Portions of southbound U.S. 183 near Mustang Ridge, in far
southeastern Travis County, were closed all day Wednesday after a
6:18 a.m. crash involving a car and a tractor-trailer truck near
Evelyn Road.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Lynch, 38, of Buda was pronounced dead at the scene. She
was driving north on U.S. 183 when she struck a sheet of ice and
slammed into the truck, which was traveling south. Her car caught
fire after the accident, an EMS spokesman said. Lynch was not
wearing a seat belt at the time, a Department of Public Safety
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Icy conditions were blamed for the majority of Wednesday's
wrecks. But too many drivers navigated the slick roads as if it
were a normal day and that contributed to the number of accidents,
emergency management officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty bad ice storm, as far as accidents are
concerned,'' Collier said. ``There is no reason to be driving
normal speed.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service forecast improved conditions today,
with a 50 percent chance of rain and freezing rain that would taper
off by late afternoon. The low should not drop below the uppers
20s, Perez said. By Christmas Day, temperatures should be in the
mid-40s and climb throughout the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wait and see and keeping fingers crossed, basically,''
said Terri Dusek, spokeswoman for Hospice Austin. The hospice, like
other home health care providers and delivery services Wednesday,
had problems getting nurses and workers to its 150 patients but
eventually were able to get to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's network of church-sponsored cold weather shelters for
men, youths and families were filled to capacity Wednesday. A
second youth shelter at the Congregational Church of Austin opened
Wednesday night after more than 20 young people showed up at
University Baptist Church Tuesday night. The Baptist church
normally shelters about a dozen people, said Sharon Bieser,
ecumenical outreach coordinator for St. Austin Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   The city's only full-time shelter, the ARCH building on West
Second Street, stayed open two hours later than normal and was
filled with an estimated 200 people _ twice the normal attendance.
More than 300 people took shelter at the Salvation Army on East
Eighth Street.
</P>
<P>
   Shelters needed winter clothing, food and volunteers, members of
the Austin Metropolitan Ministries said.
</P>
<P>
   A 75-year-old Granger man was treated for hypothermia at Johns
Community Hospital in Taylor after neighbors found him outside his
apartment Wednesday around 7 a.m. The hospital would not release
the man's name, but said he was in stable condition Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   One area mostly unaffected by the cold _ so far, at least _ was
the city's electrical power and telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the City of Austin Utility Department said
only 36 people since Tuesday had reported not having power, mainly
because they'd tripped their main breakers after plugging in too
many heat sources during the day. The number was average for a
24-hour period, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone wires also remained intact Wednesday, with little
danger expected from the relatively light winds and dusting of icy
accumulation, a Southwestern Bell spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writers Bob Banta, Debbie Hiott, Claire
Osborn, Leah Quin and Jason Spencer contributed to this report,
which also contains information from the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
