<HEADER>
A5028 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES24-C     12-23 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sack-happy Dolphins to test offensive line
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a season full of good news, Atlanta is worst in the
league in sacks surrendered per passing play, giving up 53 in 464
passing attempts, or one every 8.8 passing plays.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's opponent, Miami (10-5), has 45 sacks this season, tied
for second-most in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Atlanta's high sacks-surrendered total is attributable
to problems with blitz pickups, but it's also a reflection of
quarterback Chris Chandler tending to hold on to the ball a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   Often, he makes plays happen that way, as he did a few times
Dec. 13 at New Orleans. But sacks happen, too.
</P>
<P>
   A good example came in last Sunday's 24-17 win at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Harold Green made a mistake in the second half,
going the wrong way on a pass play, leaving Chandler no receiver on
the right side as he attempted a naked bootleg.
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in a sack by Detroit's Robert Porcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same play (as the 28-yarder earlier) out of a
different formation,'' said interim head coach Rich Brooks.
``Harold was supposed to be a receiver on the other side. What
Chris should have done ... was just throw the ball away. Instead,
he took the sack.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Trace Armstrong, who doesn't even start, leads the
Dolphins with 10.5 sacks. Right defensive end Jason Taylor, a
second-year player, has nine sacks, and rookie defensive end
Lorenzo Brommel, who doesn't start and has missed two games, has
eight sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Playoff picture
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, as NFC West champions and the No. 2 seed in the NFC
playoffs, will have a bye in the first week of the playoffs, the
weekend of Jan. 2 and Jan. 3. The next weekend, they will have a
home game, either Jan. 9 or 10.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week of the playoffs, the NFC East champion Dallas
Cowboys (9-6) will play either Arizona (8-7), the Giants (7-8) or
Tampa Bay (7-8), and San Francisco (11-4) will play Green Bay
(10-5).
</P>
<P>
   If Dallas wins, the Cowboys will come to Atlanta the following
week.
</P>
<P>
   If Dallas loses, the team that beats the Cowboys will go to
Minnesota the next week, and the winner of the Green Bay-San
Francisco game will come to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   As the No. 1 seed in the NFC, the Vikings are slated to host the
lowest-remaining seed. Even though both Green Bay and San Francisco
might have better records than Dallas, the Cowboys are seeded
higher (No. 3) by virtue of being division champions
</P>
<P>
   Ticket talk
</P>
<P>
   There are about 7,500 tickets remaining for the first playoff
game. There are a little more than 17,000 remaining for the second
home playoff game, if the Falcons have one.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials are cautioning fans who attempt to purchase
tickets from scalpers that counterfeit tickets are likely to be
plentiful, not only for playoff games, but also for this Sunday's
regular-season finale against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket manager Jack Ragsdale said that for the Nov. 22 game
against the Bears, there were at least 70 instances of fans getting
into the Georgia Dome with counterfeit tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Those fans usually found out that either the seat printed on
their ticket did not exist, or was occupied by a legitimate buyer.
Fans with counterfeit tickets are escorted out of the stadium, with
no refund.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson talks
</P>
<P>
   James Sims, the agent for running back Jamal Anderson, was in
Atlanta last Friday, chiefly to speak with Anderson, but he did
meet briefly with Falcons general manager Harold Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons began discussions six weeks ago on a contract
extension for Anderson, who has one year left after this. Both
sides say no deal will be done soon, meaning it will not happen
before Saturday, the last day a player can sign a contract
extension and have the signing bonus spread out over 1998 and the
additional years of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are in pretty good shape, as defensive end Lester
Archambeau (thumb), weakside linebacker Cornelius Bennett (knee)
and reserve cornerback Randy Fuller (shoulder) are all listed as
probable for Sunday's game. Archambeau had one of the three pins
removed from his broken left thumb, which may help alleviate some
pain. ... Miami left tackle Richmond Webb (triceps) and reserve
linebacker Larry Izzo (knee) are out. Running back Karim
Abdul-Jabbar (concussion) and starting right guard Kevin Donnalley
(knee) are questionable. Running back John Avery (ankle), starting
linebacker Robert Jones (quadriceps), starting cornerback Sam
Madison (hip) and reserve wide receiver and special-teams player
Nate Jacquet (concussion) are probable.
</P>
<P>
   The race
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle has led the Falcons in tackles
for nine consecutive seasons. Entering the final game, he and
Bennett are tied for the team lead with 112 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Next up: Free safety Eugene Robinson (88), Archambeau and strong
safety William White (77 each).
</P>
<P>
   Going for it
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta wins, it will be the first time in franchise history
the team has gone undefeated at home. ... The Falcons have scored
404 points, third-most in their history. They scored 426 points in
'81, and 405 in '80. ... Atlanta has scored 30 or more points six
times, one short of the team record, set in '80 and matched in '81.
... Anderson has 2,062 yards from scrimmage, trailing only the
2,176 by running back William Andrews in '83. Anderson also is
second in the NFL with 100 first downs, tied with Denver's Terrell
Davis, and trailing Indianapolis running back Marshall Faulk. Davis
leads all rushers with 1,830 yards; Anderson is second with 1,743.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   In two seasons, Chandler has thrown 23 touchdown passes from
inside the 20-yard line with no interceptions. He leads all
quarterbacks with a 121.2 passer rating in the fourth quarter. ...
With four interceptions this season, Robinson has 53 in his career,
making him the NFL's leading active interceptor and No. 16 in
league history. ... Atlanta, which leads the league in average time
of possession (33:32), is 13-0 this year when it has an edge in
time of possession, 0-2 when it does not. ... The Falcons worked
out former Canadian Football League defensive lineman Joe Fleming,
who played at New Hampshire, and cornerback Keith Thibodeaux, who
was waived earlier this season by Washington. Thibodeaux, who
played for the Redskins last year, played collegiately at
Northwestern State (La.). ... Atlanta will practice early today, at
10:30 a.m. and then practice Friday morning. Next week, when the
Falcons have a bye, they will practice Wednesday and Thursday. ...
In the past six games, 20 of Morten Andersen's 31 kickoffs have
gone into the end zone, and 13 have been touchbacks. ... Dan
Stryzinski has 24 punts inside the opponents' 20-yard line, tying
his career high, set in '93 with Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
