<HEADLINE>
THE REAL GIFT OF CHRISTMAS IS BORN AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   this, I am sitting in the house in which I grew up, the house
where I spent the first 22 Christmases of my life.
</P>
<P>
   And I am thinking about gifts.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't in a while, at least not in this fashion. As you grow
older, the old saw about it being better to give than receive rings
more and more true. As an adult, you're more concerned about
whether your wife will actually wear that pair of electric-blue
shoes you got her than you are with what's in the packages under
the tree with your name on them.
</P>
<P>
   But just lately I have been doing a mental rewind, trying to
remember the best gifts that I saw waiting as I trotted down the
stairs as a child, the tree in the sun porch visible from the
landing, my Christmas radar cranked up into overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   The electric-football game was a big hit, as I recall. The
electric-train set was also a winner, as were the fire engine and
the G.I. Joe and the toy saxophone. Sure wish we'd hung on to the
Rock 'Em-Sock 'Em Robots; they're supposedly worth a fortune today.
</P>
<P>
   Countless other gifts came and went _ played with, broken and
discarded before they made much of an impression. I doubt I'll ever
be able to dredge them up from my memory. &QL; 
FADING MAGIC
</P>
<P>
   I grew up the youngest of five children, the baby brother. For
much of my life I saw Christmas from that perspective. I was the
first to volunteer to get out the box of tree decorations from the
closet, the last to tire of hanging stockings on the mantel, the
only remaining holdout when it came time to drop whatever you were
doing and sit down to watch ``A Charlie Brown Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even I started to wear down a bit as I grew older. There was
magic in those gifts I unwrapped as a kid. Later in life, they grew
more serviceable, more practical. Yes, I'm always happy to receive
underwear, but it doesn't make me giddy the way a Monkees talking
hand puppet did. Can't be helped. Everyone grows up sometime, which
is not necessarily a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Things began to change a little when my siblings started having
children. On trips home for the holidays, I loved reading ``A Visit
From St. Nicholas'' to my nieces before they went to bed Christmas
Eve; I loved lending Santa a hand with toys that needed to be
assembled after they drifted off. Still, nice as it was, something
was missing.
</P>
<P>
   A BOY'S LIFE II But this year, my perspective has taken a nice
little jaunt in the Way-Back Machine. That's because this is the
first Christmas I'll spend with my own child. She is too young to
remember anything that goes on here, of course, but that hasn't
made the holiday any less festive for me. Despite her tiny status,
we have put her through many of the holiday paces, and it's been
wonderful. Seeing the holiday through her eyes has made me a kid
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Charlie Brown Christmas'' suddenly packed all its old power
_ Linus' holiday-saving soliloquy once again brought a tear to my
eye. I'm paying more attention to TV toy commercials. The mere
jingle of a sleigh bell is enough to make me break into an off-key
``Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran parents tell me it only gets better. Hard to imagine,
but I'll happily take them at their word. I'm enjoying this
newfound innocence and wonder too much to doubt them.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and about those gifts. I know they aren't what Christmas is
really about (ask Linus). Still, gifts have been on my mind lately.
</P>
<P>
   That's because this Christmas Eve, I'll read about the night
before Christmas to my own daughter for the first time. With luck,
she'll nod off shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   A little while later, I'll gather up the greatest gift I've ever
gotten _ the greatest gift I'll ever get _ and place her in her
crib for the night.
</P>
<P>
   I hope she sleeps through till Christmas. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
