President Clinton, accompanied by Housing and Urban Developement
Secretary Andrew Cuomo, reacts to a warm welcome at the Baltimore
Boys and Girls Club on Wednesday. Clinton told the crowd gathered
at the club that he would request an additional $150 million in his
next budget proposal over this year's spending to build more
affordable housing. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- BOOMER-TOYS-2, 12-23 -- A
tin robot bears a ``not for children'' disclaimer. Not since Kane
whispered Rosebud has the nation thought so hard about the toys
from its past. Baby-boomers, now parents and grandparents, are
hitting their second childhood. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- BOOMER-TOYS-1, 12-23 --
Mark Maltais shopping for model cars at Paul Smith, one of many
general retailers selling toys. A generation about to slip into
senior citizenship has created a growing market for newly-produced
classic toys, log-building sets to electric football boards to Dr.
Seuss books, and they don't have to go to toy stores to find them.
(Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- FLOWER-ARRANGING-2, 12-23
-- Flowering eucalyptus stems in Ryoko Ahta's American-style
bouquet. First Coca-Cola, then Levis and sneakers. Now comes the
ultimate insult to Japanese tradition: American flower arranging.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- FLOWER-ARRANGING-1, 12-23
-- For Akiko Ogita, the Western way of flower arranging means
learning to trust her instincts as she improvises a bucolic
bouquet. Japanese women coming to New York for lessons in flower
arranging seems as absurd as New Yorkers going to Tokyo for
rudeness seminars. But come they have, embracing and learning yet
another Western way. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- KIDS-ROOM-2, 12-23 -- Zoe
Feigenbaum, 16, remade the fireplace in her bedroom with mementos
of romance and travels and the Manhattan she loves. ``A child will
not only feel independent but will grow strong and be
independent,'' if her or she aids in the design of the room, says
Dr. Barbara Scales, who retired this year as head teacher at the
Child Studies Center at the University of California at Berkeley.
(Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SAN FRANCISCO -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- KIDS-ROOM-1, 12-23 --
Julia Reichard's bedroom ceiling is painted in an abstract pattern
of her favorite red and pink colors. To a child, one of the
sweetest and most long-lasting Christmas gifts is a room of one's
own. And it's clear, as every parent knows, that children are
sometimes their own best interior designers. (Terrence McCarthy/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVMENT-B&AMP;W, 12-23
-- Buying lumber is one thing; getting it home is another. Unless
you own a hatchback, your best option is to load the boards on the
car roof. First purchase a pair of roof racks. These will make it
easier to tie the load securely and protect the roof of your car.
Home centers, auto supply stores, and sporting good stores carry
roof racks. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BALTIMORE -- Dec. 23, 1998 --CLINTON, 12-23 -- President
Clinton poses for photos with members of the audience after
announcing plans for increased funding to help the homeless on
Wednesday. Clinton, who received a warm welcome at the Baltimore
Boys and Girls Club, said he would request an additional $150
million in his next budget proposal over this year's spending to
build more affordable housing. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PEARTH AMBOY, N.J. -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- CIR-LEARN-TO-READ,
12-23 -- Roseann DeLuca teaches her first-grade class in Perth
Amboy, N.J. Educators fear computers can distract children from
educational activities like reading. Building on the children's
familiarity with computers however, software companies have
produced programs that help children build reading skills starting
in the preschool years. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- CIR-ANCIENT-GAME-3, 12-23 --
The Asian board game of Go, the game of the samurai and used as a
tool to teach military strategy, has gone on-line. The advent of Go
on the internet has erased barriers of language and distance, while
lifting the game from obscurity in the United States. (Steve
Castillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- CIR-ANCIENT-GAME-2, 12-23 --
The Asian board game of Go was the game of the samurai and used as
a tool to teach military strategy. Among noble accomplishments for
gentlemen, Go ranked with calligraphy, poetry and music. Here a
bowl containing game pieces sits on a playing board. (Steve
Castillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SAN JOSE, Calif. -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- CIR-ANCIENT-GAME-1,
12-23 -- Tim Casey works on a game of Go as his wife Jennifer and
eight-month old son David look on. In the background is Casey's
older son Matthew. Casey helped set up the Internet Go Server,
which allows Go players all over the world to compete on line.
(Steve Castillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DES MOINES, Iowa -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- CIR-IOWA-NETWORK,
12-23 -- Judge James Twedt, left, and F. Montgomery Brown, the
defense attorney, take part in a parole hearing where the inmate,
seen in the monitor at center, takes part electronically. What the
prisoner is seeing is televised at right. The Iowa Parole Board
says that using this system eliminates the travel and security
costs previously incurred with transporting criminals to their
hearings. (Rodney White/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 21, 1998 --CIR-POSTAL-TECK, 12-21 --
Robert Reisner, the Post Office's vice president of strategic
planning, in his office at the U.S. Postal Service headquarters. In
the background is a portrait of William Hopson, a first generation
airmail deliveryman who was killed in a crash in 1928. Reisner is
working on the future of the Postal Service in the digital age.
(Guido Cassetta/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAN LEANDRO, Calif. -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- CIR-GEEK-HOBBIES
-1, 12-23 -- Software specialist Dean Dierschow with some of his
British Petroleum memorabilia. A game engineer at Segasoft
Networks, Dierschow says he has absolutely no connection to BP
except that ``as a kid, my favorite color was green.'' (Dan
Krauss/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SUNNYVALE, Calif. -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- CIR-GEEK-HOBBIES-2,
12-21 -- Alexia Massalin in her home surrounded by some of her 40
stuffed koala bears. Massalin, an engineer who is widely heralded
as a technical genius, likes giving and receiving piggyback rides
as well as collecting stuffed koala bears. (Dan Krauss/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
