<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 12/23/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) CARLSBAD, Calif. -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- GOLF-CLUBS, 12-23
-- Ely Callaway, 79, founder of the Callaway Golf Co., holding a
Big Bertha club in one of the factory's assembly areas. The United
States Golf Association's (golf's governing body) season-long
review of how technology affects the game hung over the industry
like a cloud all year; as the largest club maker, Callaway has been
one of the hardest hit. (Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 27 --
CANBY-THEATER, 12-23 -- Brent Carver as Leo Frank and Carolee
Carmello as Lucille Frank in the musical ``Parade.'' The cast is
able, the staging is smooth and the scenery moves on and off
without threatening the actors. Yet ``Parade'' is without life. It
plays as if it were still a collection of notes for a show that has
yet to be discovered. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- IMPEACH-MEDIA, 12-23 --
Members of the media outside the U.S. Capitol early Saturday.
Looking back on the past 11 months, many people inside and outside
journalism described the coverage of the presidential scandal as a
laboratory experiment for the post-modern media age -- the moment
when the diverse forces of the instant communication era converged
for the first time on a major political scandal. (Justin Lane/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 27 --
BIZ-WOMEN-ARCH, 12-23 -- Victoria Rospond, left, and Lea Cloud are
the founders of CR Studio, an architectural firm in New York. Only
7 percent of such firms are owned by women. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
DEC. 27 -- BIZ-PROFILE-ZELMAN, 12-23 -- Walter A. Zelman was an
official on Hillary Rodham Clinton's health policy team earlier in
this decade. He now leads the California Association of Health
Plans, a managed-care lobby. ``I decided I wanted something more
activist, more directly involved in policy,'' he says. (Don
Preisler/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 27 --
BIZ-PARKING-SYSTEM, 12-23 -- Bob Levitt eases his car into a
parking spot with the help of a Park Zone, a wall-mounted device
that is devoted to bump prevention. The Park Zone is easy to set
up. Attach it at eye level on your garage wall, park your car in
the desired spot, connect the coiled cord, press the activation
button, and voila! (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- CUBA-U.S., 12-23 -- A
police guard house along with video cameras are part of the heavy
security around the Cuban Mission to the U.N., site of various
bombings during the 1980's. Three Cuban diplomats at the United
Nations who are suspected of spying were ordered Wednesday to leave
the country, American officials said. The three men were linked to
espionage after an investigation by the FBI that led to the arrest
and indictment of 10 suspected Cuban agents in Miami three months
ago. The three men in New York have diplomatic passports, which
give them immunity from prosecution as spies. (Jack Manning/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 27 --
CANBY-YEAREND-THEATER-2, 12-23 -- Jesse Tyler Ferguson, left, and
Lea DeLaria in a revival of ``On the Town.'' The production is a
joyous feast of bountiful proportions, with its score by Leonard
Bernstein and book and lyrics by Betty Comden and Adolph Green.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 27 --
CANBY-YEAREND-THEATER-1, 12-23 -- Kathleen Chalfant as a scholar
dying of cancer in Margaret Edson's ``Wit.'' Death is proud in
Margaret Edson's very fine play at the Union Square Theater, but it
is met head-on in the text and in Ms. Chalfant's rich, gutsy
performance. Here is a one-of-a-kind experience: wise, thoughtful,
witty and wrenching. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 27 --
DANCE-YEAREND-2, 12-23 -- ``The Vertiginous Thrill of Exactitude,''
at City Center in October. This brilliant outburst of neo-classical
style dancing was, some felt, the season's best ballet. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 27 --
DANCE-YEAREND-1, 12-23 -- In bravura folk dancing, the Virsky
Ukrainian National Dance Company leapt high in ``Hopak,'' at City
Center in June. For sheer dance power, there is nothing like a
first-class professional folk company from the former Soviet Union.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NORWALK, Conn. -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- IMPEACH-SHAYS, 12-23
-- Rep. Christopher Shays during a news conference on Wednesday. To
his supporters in his district, in the Connecticut suburbs of New
York City, his vacillating positions last week on President
Clinton's impeachment all reflected rigorous research, deep
thinking and admirable independence. To his critics, it was
ludicrous hand-wringing. Shays returned to his district to explain
himself with the mantra that ``impeachable offenses were not proven
and the proven offenses were not impeachable.'' (Joyce Dopkeen/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 27 --
POP-YEAREND-ALBUMS, 12-23 -- Alanis Morissette during her furious
performance at the Hammerstein Ballroom. Rock's avenging banshee
returned to claim her loyal audience with an album, ``Supposed
Former Infatuation Junkie,'' of song therapy: wailing and crooning
about all kinds of past turbulence, from eating disorders to
crippling depression. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- CRIME-DECLINE, 12-23 -- New
York City Police cadets attend graduation ceremonies where 1,798
officers were added to the ranks in 1996. The number of murders
reported in New York City has fallen to 601 so far this year,
putting the city on pace to end the year with fewer homicides than
in it had 1964. However the size of the department has grown from
25,897 in 1964, to nearly 40,000. (James Estrin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) BOSTON -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- SIZE-WARS-BOS, 12-23 --
Frustrated by the chaotic system of sizing for women's clothes,
Meredith Pooler gets fitted for a pair of custom Levi jeans by
Xiomara Avillan, a Levi Strauss shift supervisor at the Prudential
Mall in Boston. The push to eliminate the decades-old guessing game
in women's apparel is being spurred largely by the fast-growing
mail-order and Internet apparel businesses. (Thomas James
Hurst/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) BRAINTREE, Mass. -- Dec. 23, 1998 --
SANTA-LIFETSTYLE-BOS, 12-23 -- Erich Ryan, 2, from South Boston
gets a hug from Santa (actually Dan Headstream from Georgia) at the
Braintree Plaza. The pillow-packed Santa stand-ins with polyester
whiskers and a ho-ho hum attitude appear to be a dwindling lot.
While Santas at several malls declined to discuss their salary,
some can earn upwards of $2,000 weekly for the seasonal gig. (John
Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- NY-FATAL-FIRE-2, 12-23 -- A
firefighter is taken from the scene of a fire which left four
people dead in New York's Upper Westside. The apartment was owned
by the family of Macaulay Culkin, star of ``Home Alone,'' among
other movies. The Culkin family was safe, a publicist said. The
dead, two men and two women, were found on higher floors of the
51-story building. It is believed they died of smoke inhalation.
(Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- NY-FATAL-FIRE, 12-23 -- A
firefighter looks from the window of an apartment following a fire
which killed four people. The apartment was owned by the family of
Macaulay Culkin, star of ``Home Alone,'' among other movies. The
Culkin family was safe, a publicist said. The dead, two men and two
women, were found on higher floors of the 51-story building. It is
believed they died of smoke inhalation. (Richard L. Harbus/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- WINTER-STORM, 12-23 -- A
man looks out from the door of an abandoned truck on Wednesday
which he was using as a shelter from the cold. On Tuesday, the
first day of winter, cold air spilled southward from Canada
plunging temperatures some 20 degrees Fahrenheit around the nation.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- IMPEACH-TEAM, 12-23 --
Rep. Bill McCollum, a member of the House Judiciary Committee,
tries to get the attention of the committee's chairman, Rep. Henry
Hyde, foreground, speaking to reporters, in order to return to the
committee for a vote in the U.S. Capitol in September. McCollum and
Hyde are currently two of 13 Republican Congressmen appointed as
managers of President Clinton's impeachment trial in the Senate. If
a trial should take place, Hyde would essentially be the lead
lawyer. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- HARLEM-NUTCRACKER, 12-23 --
Dancers in Donald Byrd's ``Harlem Nutcracker'' on Tuesday at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music. Unlike most productions in which Clara,
the heroine, is a little girl, Byrd's Clara is a widow and a
grandmother who at a family party has a vision of her deceased
husband and travels back in memory with him. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Dec. 23, 1998 -- ANOUSHKA-SHANKAR, 12-23 --
Anoushka Shankar, 17-year-old California girl and pupil of Ravi,
her father. She may be a Metallica fan, but she is also mastering
Indian classical music; her debut album, ``Anoushka,'' was released
in October. ``The second we walk into the music room, I am a
disciple,'' she says of the relationship with her father. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BALTIMORE -- Dec. 23, 1998 --CLINTON-2, 12-23 --
President Clinton, accompanied by Housing and Urban Developement
Secretary Andrew Cuomo, reacts to a warm welcome at the Baltimore
Boys and Girls Club on Wednesday. Clinton told the crowd gathered
at the club that he would request an additional $150 million in his
next budget proposal over this year's spending to build more
affordable housing. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
