<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5060 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIFE-SFCHRON &LR;      12-23 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIFE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Mutual Fund Firm for Sale  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
SIFE, a Walnut Creek mutual fund company specializing in bank
stocks, is seeking to sell all or part of the firm to finance
expansion, a company official confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Stead, SIFE's chief investment officer and manager of
its $1.06 billion-asset SIFE Trust Fund, said he expects a sale to
take place by summer. He said SIFE has frequently been contacted by
potential buyers, but doesn't have an offer on the table now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key issue for us is that we need more capital,'' Stead
said. ``We would like to grow our business and add additional
mutual funds.''
</P>
<P>
   SIFE stands for Selected Investments in Financial Equities.
</P>
<P>
   Investment bankers estimated the closely held SIFE could fetch
as much as $50 million if it sold all the equity in the firm based
on its estimated $5 million in pretax income.
</P>
<P>
   SIFE could attract a mutual fund family that wanted to add a
financial sector fund to its menu, said Joe Hershberger, a New York
investment banker with the firm Putnam, Lovell, de Guardiola and
Thornton, which specializes in the sale of investment management
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a robust market for mutual funds,'' Hershberger said.
``A lot of people are looking to expand the range of options for
their clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Investment bankers cautioned that SIFE's attractiveness to a
buyer is limited because the company manages just one equity fund.
</P>
<P>
   And, while Stead's track record is solid, he isn't the sort of
widely known star portfolio manager whose name would command a
premium in a takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years, SIFE Trust has averaged a 24.01
percent annual return, slightly below the 27.04 percent return of
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index. SIFE had been ahead of the S&AMP;P 500
until bank stocks fell hard last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Bloomberg News reported that SIFE had hired
the investment bank Paine Webber Inc. to find a buyer. Bloomberg
also reported that the Boston mutual fund group owned by Liberty
Mutual Life Insurance Co. bid unsuccessfully to buy SIFE.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Stead confirmed Paine Webber was
representing SIFE. He said the investment bank was hired because
``we were tired of having to react to bidders. We want to be in the
driver's seat.''
</P>
<P>
   SIFE would use proceeds of a sale to launch additional funds,
such as a global fund that would invest in both U.S. and foreign
financial institutions, Steads said.
</P>
<P>
   Stead said a condition of any sale would be that his team could
stay in place. His deputies include research director Scott Edgar
and analyst/trader Laurie Buntain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
