A5061 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FROST-SFCHRON &LR;      12-23 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FROST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Citrus Hit Hard By Frost  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   California citrus farmers have been slammed by two nights of
subfreezing temperatures, causing a preliminary $591 million in
agricultural damage.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit were farmers in the central San Joaquin Valley,
where the lemon crop is nearly a total loss and the navel orange
crop is in serious jeopardy with yet another freezing night
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Orange grower Darwin Smith was philosophical yesterday even
though the unusual winter freeze had ruined his entire crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``With farming, you work your crop for a whole year,'' Smith
said as he assessed the damage on his 75-acre grove in Orland,
north of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's harvest time and all of a sudden Mother Nature puts
you out. It's like working for a whole year and not getting a
paycheck. (But) when you get snow in San Francisco, where that
hardly happens, that's the way it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   The freeze hit Fresno, Tulare and Kern counties early in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   The state Agriculture Department said those counties reported
100 percent losses to lemon and grapefruit crops, while 50 to 70
percent of navel orange crops were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The valley's tangerine and mandarin orange crops were
``devastated,'' according to the California Citrus Mutual, the
state's main citrus trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Lemons were the first to go because they have less
freeze-inhibiting sugars than oranges.
</P>
<P>
   But naval  &LR; navel oranges in trees on the more exposed sides of
groves were also destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten worse as the hours go by,'' said Joel Nelson,
president of the trade group. ``We don't know what's left and
what's lost. It's not looking good.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers should start to see higher prices for the affected
fruits at supermarkets sometime after January 4, when fruit already
harvested begins to run out, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The damage in Ventura County, which accounts for 65 percent of
the state's lemons, and other southern California counties like
Glenn, San Bernardino and Riverside, will not be known until next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers set up fans with heaters and were running water through
their fields in a desperate attempt to raise temperatures just
enough to avoid damage as the thermometer dropped into the low 20s.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus crops generally can survive for about four hours below
freezing but Central Valley farmers have battled 10 hours of sub
25-degree temperatures, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy El Ni &LR; n &LR; o rains earlier this year delayed the citrus
harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the fruits would have been picked as early as
mid-October, but this year's crop wasn't ripe enough for harvest
until Thanksgiving week, meaning only about 10 to 15 percent of the
fruit has been picked, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Other crops such as strawberries, artichokes and lettuce were
not affected, &LR;  because they were dormant, already harvested or in
areas not hit by the freeze, said California Farm Bureau spokesman
Bob Krauter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; So far, the damage isn't as severe as that from a cold snap in
1990 that sent temperatures dipping into the teens.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the 1990 freeze slammed into the state overnight,
while the current cold snap, although milder, has lasted longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a slow death,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a farmer for 13 years, said he is resigned to the fact
that his crop and about 800 acres in surrounding Orland farms were
lost.
</P>
<P>
   He has crop insurance to cover the cost of planting and raising
the crop, but has yet to calculate the losses in sales revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cut into the oranges now and it's all ice,'' he said. ``In
a matter of weeks, they will all fall off to the ground and we will
start getting prepared for next year's crop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't do any good to get depressed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chose to be a farmer and I have to be able to take the good
years with the bad years. You have to be optimistic and think next
year will be better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
