<SLUG> BC-FBC-HERITAGE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Adversity can't keep Southern U. from bowl
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was supposed to be easy for Pete Richardson and his
Southern University Jaguars this season. Even in the Southwestern
Athletic Conference 1998 media guide, one headline read, ``Loaded
SU Team Has Manpower to Retain Crown.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Jaguars did repeat as SWAC champions. But the road
back to Atlanta and a berth in the Heritage Bowl has been anything
but easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the most challenging season since I've been at
Southern University,'' said Richardson, who took the job at the
school in Baton Rouge, La., in 1993 and promptly led the team to 11
victories.
</P>
<P>
   The first problem came during spring drills. All-SWAC running
back Steve Wofford broke his foot, and the effects of the fracture
lingered into the season.
</P>
<P>
   After a season-opening loss to Northwestern (La.) State, junior
quarterback Marcus Jacoby, a two-year starter, quit the team. Days
earlier, Richardson's decision to fire receivers coach Oscar
Williams had been met with varying degrees of disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   Then, before the team could adjust to senior Sam George at
quarterback, injuries began to cripple the offensive line. In the
eighth game, Southern faced Alcorn State, with Florida A&AMP;M, Texas
Southern and Grambling coming up.
</P>
<P>
   In the Alcorn game, George went down with a severe ankle injury
and missed the better part of two games. Punter Matt Bushart
injured a knee, limiting his effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his team's trials, Richardson has steered it back to
the Heritage Bowl for the third year in a row, and for the fifth
time since he became coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been inconsistent on both sides of the ball, and that
has mainly been because of injuries,'' Richardson said. ``But we've
found a way to win somehow. We've had some people step up and make
some plays for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wofford, a 5-foot-10, 180-pound senior who rushed for 1,274
yards last season, is one Jaguar who has played well. Despite being
slowed by the broken foot, he has played in 10 games and gained 996
yards. And when he was healthy, George, who has thrown for 1,661
yards and 17 touchdowns, was effective. The 5-8, 165-pounder, who
backed up Jacoby, probably will start Saturday instead of Troy
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, All-SWAC junior linebackers Channing Warner (80
tackles) and Endrick Claiborne (66 tackles) and senior safety
Jackie Mitchell (61 hits) have led the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most teams have 11-game schedules. We have 11 _ with the
Heritage Bowl down there at the bottom,'' Richardson said. ``It's
what we shoot for every year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
