<SLUG> BC-MIGHTY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MIGHTY JOE' YOUNG AT HEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2{ Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This pleasant, undemanding remake of ``Mighty Joe
Young'' plays like ``Free Willy'' with fur.
</P>
<P>
   The new version of the 1949 kiddie favorite gives the
giant-ape-on-the-loose-in-L.A. story line an eco-conscious gloss.
This time, the 15-foot gorilla isn't shipped over from his African
homeland to headline a cheap vaudeville show; he's shipped over to
be the star attraction at a nature conservancy park. It's not
irresponsible drunks but evil poachers (Rade Sherbedgia _ who used
to call himself Serbedzija _ and Peter Firth) who get Big Joe all
riled-up and loose on Hollywood Boulevard this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Paxton is the compassionate white hunter/zoologist and
Charlize Theron is the beautiful white jungle girl who are Joe's
best friends. She and Joe both lost their mothers when they were
little primates _ courtesy of those same evil poachers, in a
sequence that owes a lot to Spielberg's ``The Lost World'' _ and
their bond, as fundamentally hokey as it may be, is genuinely
touching.
</P>
<P>
   Joe himself is a pretty cuddly creation. Slicker than the
stop-motion puppet created in 1949 by Willis O'Brien and Ray
Harryhausen (the latter, along with original ``Joe'' heroine Terry
Moore, makes a nice little cameo appearance in the new movie), the
new 2,000-pound gorilla is a state-of-the-art creation. Designed by
five-time Oscar winner Rick Baker, who has excelled at the hairy
thing in the likes of ``Greystoke'' and ``Gorillas in the Mist,''
the new Joe is a seamlessly expressive blend of animatronics,
computer graphics and guys in monkey suits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as in the first film, it's impossible to believe that
this lovable lumberer actually frightens the citizens of Los
Angeles while he avoids a small army of cops. Unlike O'Brien's more
indelible creation King Kong, Joe has never generated the tragedy
and terror that his big brother unleashed. He still doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Ron Underwood, who made ``City Slickers.'' He
does his best to prevent this thoroughly Disneyfied remake from
seeming more silly than it is. Of course, it wouldn't be ``Mighty
Joe Young'' if it wasn't goofy, so it's just as well that Underwood
didn't succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Kids should be enchanted and amused, and that's all this junior
varsity film fable should ever aspire to anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-98 2216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981223.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-23 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5073 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINIMED-SURGE-LADN     12-23 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIMED-SURGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMED SHARES RISE ON HEARING NEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shares of MiniMed Inc. continued to sizzle
Wednesday, surging more than 10 percent after regulators set a
hearing date for the company's breakthrough diabetes treatment
system.
</P>
<P>
   The stock gained $9.375 to $98.625 for its seventh record close
in the last nine sessions. The issue has gained 26 percent during
that period and 85 percent since early November as bullishness has
grown over its micro-sensor for monitoring glucose levels.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's gain was triggered by the announcement that the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration has set Feb. 26 for an FDA advisory
panel to vote on MiniMed's device, which provides doctors with
continuous readings of a patient's glucose level.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Wilmoth, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney, said
final FDA approval is likely to come within three months if the
panel endorses the MiniMed product for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The announcement that the FDA has assigned a hearing date is a
light at the end of the tunnel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilmoth noted that the device will give doctors a better idea of
how much insulin to prescribe for a diabetic. ``Currently, big
swings in glucose levels represent the challenge for physicians,''
she said. ``The system will give physicians much more information
about the patient than they've ever had before.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has been impressed with the prospects for the device
because it has potentially widespread applications in the treatment
of diabetes. The current worldwide market for devices monitoring
glucose levels is estimated to be more than $3 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed has said it plans to first introduce the device,
described as ``minimally invasive'' for insertion in the abdominal
area, as a diagnostic tool. It will then introduce other
applications such as combining its insulin delivery pumps -- which
eliminate the need for daily injections -- with the monitoring
system to create what would be an artificial pancreas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This technology is very important,'' said Marc Davis, an
analyst with GS2 Securities. ``It would be very attractive for
those using the pumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Investor enthusiasm over MiniMed, which has about $100 million
in annual sales, has also been fueled by the growing possibility
that the Sylmar, Calif.-based company may attract a takeover offer.
Wilmoth said Wednesday's announcement makes that scenario slightly
more likely.
</P>
<P>
   Medtronic Inc., the world's largest manufacturer of cardiac
pacemakers, announced in early November it would make a $30 million
investment in MiniMed. The stock was trading at $61 before that
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
