<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGHTING SANTA AS PROBABLE AS BAGGING CLEMENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a nice Christmas stocking-stuffer it could have been for
the Rangers' loyal fandom.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, fantasize. Believe in Santa.
</P>
<P>
   To counter last month's Grinch-move of hiking ticket prices for
the third time in three years, team management announces that
coming down the chimney tonight would be none other than Roger
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's enough fantasy. Back to the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Clemens, it now appears the Rangers will be
delivering a partridge, a pear tree and Mark Clark.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointment is that Clemens' chance of ending up in
Arlington appeared very good, if not now, at least by Groundhog
Day. But this was dependent upon Clemens remaining his normal
greedy self.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, Clemens had his current team, the Toronto Blue
Jays, held hostage with both a trade demand and a doubling of his
salary demand. Rangers owner Tom Hicks had the money end of it
covered and, in player-value via trade, the Blue Jays were going to
be forced to take about a dime on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Then Clemens announced Tuesday he was withdrawing his Toronto
trade demand, and that he was no longer seeking a massive contract
renegotiation.
</P>
<P>
   This all but blows up the Rangers' opportunity to land Clemens.
Toronto suddenly deals again from a position of strength. For a
Doug Melvin, that means the Blue Jays will be asking for a
combination of Rusty Greer and/or Rick Helling, combined with top
prospect Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, the Rangers' general manager, refused yesterday to
completely eliminate himself, but he did say, ``This new
development seems to put Houston back in the driver's seat, or
either Toronto keeps Clemens. I think one of those will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two theories on why Clemens surprisingly backed off
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, commissioner Bud Selig stepped in privately and
advised Clemens' agents that the ``side letter'' in his Toronto
contract was not valid. This involved the agreement Clemens had
with former Toronto executive Paul Beeston that he could demand a
trade after two years in Toronto if the pitcher believed the Blue
Jays were no longer a World Series contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Side letters in a contract are basically not legal,'' Melvin
said. But that's what touched off a firestorm around Clemens three
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Beeston is now Selig's right-hand man in the
commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   The other theory is that after being vilified in baseball and in
the national media for ``greed,'' Clemens had a guilt attack. If
so, it would be the first time a baseball player was ever insulted
over being labeled ``greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens said Tuesday he no longer wanted to pitch in Houston
because of strong comments made by Astros general manager Gerry
Hunsicker, who was angry at the renegotiation demands. But Houston
owner Drayton McLane did keep open the line of communications with
Clemens' agents.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin: ``I think Drayton will work hard to mend the ill will
and, really, Roger could end up a hero in Houston, his hometown, if
he ultimately went there and pitched under the terms of his
existing contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said how active he continues to be in the pursuit of
Clemens depends ``on what Gord \RAsh, the Toronto GM\S has to say
if he calls. I don't know where we stand at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, Melvin and the Rangers had been the most active
club in trying to work out a deal for Clemens. But catcher Pudge
Rodriguez definitely won't be involved in trade talks, and Melvin
termed it ``highly unlikely'' that outfielder Rusty Greer would be
dealt.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves pitcher Rick Helling as the key figure in a Clemens
trade, but it would defeat the purpose of acquiring Clemens to
significantly strengthen a questionable rotation.
</P>
<P>
   And if a young outfielder like Mateo is not included, Toronto
doesn't figure to be that interested in making a deal involving
Helling.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Forget Clemens. It's no longer worth the price or
the effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers made the good run at acquiring him, had the good
chance to get it done, and then saw it collapse when Clemens backed
down from his trade demand.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson was strike one. Now Clemens puts the Rangers down
0-and-2 in the pitching-ace count.
</P>
<P>
   As Hicks said, smiling, after Johnson signed with Arizona,
``I've never been involved in a business where you can offer a guy
$12 million a year and he turns you down.''
</P>
<P>
   That's baseball, and that also means the Rangers' hunt for 1999
pitching help lingers on.
</P>
<P>
   (Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.)
</P>
</TEXT>
