<SLUG> BC-FBC-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE BOWL LINEUP BREEDS GREED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Some distressing news emerged from the Deep South
this week. Former coach Mike Gottfried, who was last fired by Pitt
but is currently sporting an undefeated record as an ESPN analyst,
announced that he is close to bringing a new bowl game to his
hometown of Mobile, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   If the group Gottfried represents produces a $2 million line of
credit to the NCAA by Jan. 8, then we will all have the thrill of
yet another bowl game in a do-nothing town.
</P>
<P>
   Someone needs to draw a thick red line to stop the breeding of
these bogus bowls, but it will certainly not be the NCAA. A bowl
game used to be a reward. Now it's often just a 12th game.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: There were 55 teams in Division I-A with winning
records this season. And 44 of those got into bowl games. If
Gottfried has his way, there will be 46 teams in bowls next season.
</P>
<P>
   Make that 48. The MAC is seeking approval to stage a bowl game
next season in Toronto at the SkyDome. And no, they won't play by
Canadian rules, although that would probably raise interest in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The system is basically out of control thanks to the wonderful
world of corporate sponsors. They not only hijack the names of bowl
games _ the Copper Bowl is now the Insight.com bowl _ they have
also created a mind-numbing menu of games that no sane fan can
decipher or follow.
</P>
<P>
   Quick, who's in the Micron PC Bowl? Guessed Miami and North
Carolina State correctly, huh?
</P>
<P>
   OK, what about the Humanitarian Bowl? (Answer below).
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone even watch these games? Not in person. Only 16,000
watched last year's Humanitarian dud between Cincinnati and Utah
State.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance figures are barely a concern to the old guys that
wear loud sports coats and run these games. Once they get corporate
sponsorship and secure a good TV deal, the rest is just icing on
the cake.
</P>
<P>
   A sellout would be nice, too, but that's not where the real
money is found.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad it will only get worse before it gets better. Even as
college football is headed toward a playoff system, there will
always be an array of often-meaningless bowls to be played.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, you wouldn't have the chance for 21 teams this season
to claim success because they won their final game of the season,
even if it was in the Motor City Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And no football coach wants to see that opportunity disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian Bowl answer: Idaho (8-3) plays Southern Miss (7-4),
live on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   On a roll: It's been a great month for Tennessee offensive
coordinator David Cutliffe. He was hired by Mississippi and will
get to coach the Rebels in the Independence Bowl. Then this week,
he received an oral commitment from quarterback Eli Manning, the
son of Archie Manning and brother of Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Low Tide? Although Alabama has reached the Music City Bowl,
coach Mike Dubose is just 11-11 after two seasons, and there are
rumblings he could be in trouble with a loss to Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Couch quandary: Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch is having trouble
deciding about whether to turn pro early. The Cleveland Browns
expansion franchise has the first pick, but no coach. Does Couch
want to risk playing for an expansion team without even knowing who
the coach is?
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has already denied his request to extend the deadline
for underclassmen past Jan. 8, so he has to make his decision in
the next couple of weeks. Couch has said he wouldn't mind playing
for Denver Broncos assistant Gary Kubiak, rumored to be the
front-runner for the job, but it's believed Kubiak may wait and try
to get hired by a more-established franchise.
</P>
<P>
   What's your number? Charter Oak High School's Steve Stevenson,
one of the more highly regarded wide receivers in the state, told
USC quarterback Carson Palmer this week he would only attend Troy
if he got to wear No. 3, which Palmer plans to wear next season.
</P>
<P>
   Looks like Stevenson will consider going elsewhere, because
Palmer made clear he's not spending another season wearing No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the ugliest number there is,'' Palmer said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
