<SLUG> BC-TV-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AGENCIES TRY TO PREDICT FALL TV HITS
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By GREG FARRELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Network executives like Peter Roth, the recently departed
president of Fox Entertainment, or Warren Littlefield, who left a
comparable position at NBC in October, are not the only people
whose careers and reputations ride on their ability to pick hits
for the fall television schedule.
</P>
<P>
   On the ad agency side, dozens of executives are responsible for
previewing the networks' fall schedules in May and June and
deciding which programs will be hits. The agencies' clients pledge
nearly $6 billion up front to buy commercials on prime-time shows
each fall, and these clients _ which include giant advertisers like
General Motors, Unilever and Procter &AMP; Gamble _ do not want to fly
blind in deciding what shows to support.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mystery to hit shows like ``ER'' or ``Ally McBeal.''
Agencies know who watches these programs, and the networks
guarantee a certain audience: if the show in question does not
deliver the viewers promised, the network will make it up to the
client by providing free commercial time _ ``make goods'' in the
industry parlance _ elsewhere on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The real challenge for agency prognosticators is to look at the
new shows that have no track record _ some 37 were introduced by
the six networks this fall _ and decide which to support and which
to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers are wary of associating themselves with programs of
dubious quality, and so woe to the agency that passed up an ad on
NBC's ``Frasier'' in favor of a commanding presence on ``The Secret
Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer,'' a UPN misfire canceled soon after its
debut.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, when there were only three networks, each of
which enjoyed huge ratings every night, the agency prognosticator's
job was easier. Today, with six networks competing for 55 percent
to 60 percent of the viewing audience on most nights, the
competition for every share point is fierce. Consequently, the big
agencies need people who can predict which shows will be hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role has become more important,'' said Steve Farella, the
executive vice president and director for integrated marketing at
Jordan McGrath Case &AMP; Partners in New York. ``Clients are more
interested in what's going on'' in TV programming.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Frank, who was a forecaster at Dancer Fitzgerald Sample,
said, ``We were one of only a handful of agencies that commented on
TV programs and had meetings with the management of the TV
networks,'' in the 1980s. After Dancer became part of Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi, Ms. Frank continued the practice at Zenith Media Worldwide
before joining MTV Networks last year as executive vice president
for research and development. ``In recent years, most every agency
is doing it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After viewing pilots last spring, Bill Cella, the executive vice
president for broadcast and programming at McCann-Erickson
Worldwide Advertising in New York, predicted which programs he
thought would make it and which would not. So far, most of his
calls have been accurate. In an internal booklet published last
summer for clients of McCann _ part of the McCann-Erickson World
Group unit of Interpublic Group of Cos. _ Cella predicted that
CBS's ``The Brian Benben Show,'' NBC's ``Encore! Encore!'' and
Fox's ``Costello.'' would be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is gut feel,'' Cella said. ``It's all about
writing in network television. It has to be sharp. Then you see
where they're going to place it: What night? What's the lead-in?
And then, star power.''
</P>
<P>
   How much influence do Cella's predictions have at the network
level? Not much, he says. ``My influence is with the sales
operations of the networks,'' he said. ``If they think I have a
problem with several of their shows, the creatives will listen. But
it would have to be an industrywide thing'' for an agency
executive's opinions to influence a programming decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever killed a show,'' said Jon Mandel, a
co-managing director of Mediacom, the media-buying unit of Grey
Advertising in New York. ``And I don't think the networks should
listen to what any single one of us says. But if they hear a
consensus building, they listen and they kill things.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Chrisanthopoulos, president for broadcast and
programming-U.S.A. at Ogilvy &AMP; Mather in New York, a unit of WPP
Group PLC, agrees. ``The networks call around to see if there's any
buzz for a show,'' he said. ``But they do it more from a pricing
standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Steele, who replaced Ms. Frank as lead forecaster at
Zenith last year but who is joining Fox Broadcasting as vice
president for research and marketing, takes a different approach.
Foremost in her book is a show's time period: where a show is
scheduled determines what kind of lead-in it will have and what its
competition will be on the other networks. Then she looks at the
show itself: who is the target audience? What's the genre? The
answer to those questions leads to the next question: Is there a
possibility that this show will bring in a new audience? Finally,
Ms. Steele looks at the quality of the show's pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilot is important,'' she said, ``but more and more, it's
not as important as you think. We've seen pilots we hated that went
on to become popular shows.'' As an example, Ms. Steele points to
the NBC hit series ``Friends''; she ``truly hated'' its pilot. Even
last year's big hit, ``Ally McBeal'' from Fox, caught her somewhat
by surprise based on the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   As to this season's biggest surprise, Ms. Steele says it is
ABC's ``Sports Night.'' ``It's a fabulous show,'' she said. ``It's
well written, smart and it takes chances in terms of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   None of these agency prognosticators predicted a strong fall
season, but none are happy with the accuracy of their forecasts
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we've made our predictions, we hope we're wrong
and that there are hits everywhere,'' said Chrisanthopoulos of
Ogilvy &AMP; Mather. ``We need network TV to stay vital.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
