<HEADLINE>
FAMILY MATTERS GIVE COOPER HER STRENGTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cynthia Cooper went to the hospital earlier this
month to visit her mother, who recently had given death the slip
for the umpteenth time. She just assumed that if there were any
frantic phone calls to be made she'd be the one doing the dialing.
</P>
<P>
   So when Cooper picked up the receiver at the hospital and heard
the hysteria in her sister's voice, fear rose like bile in her
throat.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine having your fervent prayers that the material world will
hold onto your mother interrupted by the news that your house had
burned to ash. For some people, that would have been enough to
purge the holiday season of its greetings and the plums of their
sugar and the winter wonder from the land.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, though, approached the calamity with uncommon
equanimity. Better to have lost 5,000 square feet of brick and
belongings, she reminded herself, than the woman who has been her
bedrock for the past 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person I grew up with was strong and independent and full
of life,'' Cooper said the other day from Houston. ``That's the
person I remember. To see my mom go through this terrible illness
is devastating. Sometimes it's unbearable to see what she's going
through. Everything else pales by comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Cobbs has been battling cancer for as long as the fifth of
her eight children has been playing ball professionally in the
United States. The cells in her body have been spreading but _
thank goodness for small blessings _ not as quickly as Cooper's
renown.
</P>
<P>
   A solid player on the USC teams that won back-to-back national
championships in 1983 and 1984, Cooper spent a decade playing for
lira and pesetas in Italy and Spain before the WNBA and stardom
found her, in that order. She was assigned to the WNBA team in
Houston before the inaugural 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   The rest, as they say, is history.
</P>
<P>
   The Cooper-led Comets have won back-to-back championships and
Cooper, who was totally eclipsed by Cheryl Miller and Pam and Paula
McGee at USC, has put up numbers that would make Michael Jordan
drool. A two-time league MVP, Cooper is an overnight sensation that
arrived some two decades late.
</P>
<P>
   Now that she has made it, she'd gladly slow down and take a
leisurely victory lap and soak up the sweet perfume of success, if
only life would stop placing in her path hurdles far taller than
the ones she used to clear while running track in high school.
</P>
<P>
   You want obstructions of justice? This month alone, Cooper has
faced her mother's marked decline after a few months of enough
small miracles that the player had allowed herself to believe that
cancer finally had surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   There was the fire, accidentally set by her 5-year-old nephew
Tyquon, whom she is legally raising as her own. And then there was
the maniac who ran her off the road one night as she was returning
home from _ where else? _ the hospital, giving Cooper a real pain
in the neck to add to all her other woes.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire thwacks 70 home runs and one popular weekly anoints
him one of the 25 most intriguing people of 1998. Meantime Cooper,
35, has carried the Comets, her mother, seven nieces and nephews
and her six surviving siblings on her back without complaint or
kudos. That makes her far more interesting in our eyes, even if you
won't find her sharing a ``People'' cover with the likes of Cameron
Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there's something about Mary's daughter. Cooper's
devotion to her family surpassed laudable a couple of legal
guardianships ago. She has raised a niece and four of her nephews
from infancy and provides a safe harbor for four others.
</P>
<P>
   When she's not playing basketball or promoting breast cancer
awareness or making sure inner-city kids have access to computers
or fulfilling her obligations to her sponsors, which include Nike
and General Motors, she usually can be found attending
parent-teacher conferences, school recitals or her nephews' and
nieces' sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   She is a no-nonsense, hands-on parent just like her own mom, who
somehow found the time to show she cared even when, as Cooper put
it, ``it seemed like she was working 24-hour days'' to keep her
kids clothed and fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people want their parents to give them the magic words to
success,'' Cooper said of her upbringing in Watts. ``What my mother
did was she put a reality twist on everything. She showed us by
example how to have a better life. For 20 years she did it through
hard work and sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people inherit their mother's eye color. Cooper got Cobbs'
work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-10 shooting guard has made herself into a superstar,
using elbow grease to smooth over the rough edges of her talent.
</P>
<P>
   Because Cooper can control the flow of a basketball game the way
a damkeeper can water, it's doubly difficult for her to accept that
there are some things she can't bend to her will. Her mother's
health, for example. Cooper finds herself increasingly willing to
suspend belief at the drop of the latest so-called cancer cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when you hear rumors they have a magical drug,''
Cooper said with a sigh. ``Because the reality of it is, whatever
it is, it ain't working.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time Cooper is able to keep a stiff upper lip. And
if it starts to quiver?
</P>
<P>
   ``I go for a jog to kind of gather my thoughts and emotions and
get myself under control,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   So much has been out of her hands this holiday season. Thus, it
is no small blessing to Cooper that the fire that claimed so many
of the gifts her loved ones would have been unwrapping this week
left untouched the greatest gift of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Christmas Day,'' she asserted, ``we will appreciate that we
are all together.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
