<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ABORTION-SLAY-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR OF MAN SOUGHT FOR QUESTIONING IN DOCTOR'S KILLING FOUND AT
AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Vt., Canada) 
 (nk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A car belonging to the man wanted for questioning in the October
killing of a Buffalo, N.Y., doctor who provided abortions has been
found at Newark International Airport in New Jersey, law
enforcement officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The police still have not located James C. Kopp, the itinerant
antiabortion protester from Vermont who witnesses believe they saw
jogging in the Amherst, N.Y., neighborhood of Dr. Barnett A.
Slepian on the morning of his slaying. But on Friday, they found
Kopp's black 1987 Chevrolet Cavalier _ which had also been spotted
near Slepian's home in the days before the shooting _ in the
long-term parking lot of the airport, keys in the ignition.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Trevor, a spokesman for the Port Authority of New York and
New Jersey, said the car had been at the airport since Dec. 4, a
month after the FBI named Kopp as a material witness and issued a
warrant for his arrest. Law enforcement authorities have not named
Kopp or anyone else as a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has impounded the car and its contents for analysis, but
Trevor said the officer who discovered the car found only a spare
tire, some scrap papers and a map in the dirty vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That car doesn't solve this case,'' said Michael A. Mason, of
the FBI's office in Buffalo, where a multi-agency task force has
tracked 1,100 leads since the Oct. 23 slaying. ``Finding the car
finds us the car that a witness saw in the area at that time.
That's all it does. It doesn't get us any closer to where he is
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason said the car was left at the airport with expired New
Jersey plates, rather than the Vermont tags it had when seen in
Amherst. The FBI had put out an alert throughout the United States
and Canada for both the black Cavalier and a green 1977 Dodge
Aspen, which was also registered to Kopp.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement authorities said they do not know whether Kopp
took a flight after the car was left at the airport. There is no
video surveillance in the long-term lot, which houses about 32,000
cars a day, officials said. Videotapes from inside the airport
remain under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers do daily checks of the lot at midnight and log
every car in the computer, Trevor said. On Friday an officer
noticed that the car's inspection sticker was torn and expired, and
when he checked the vehicle identification number he discovered the
FBI alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything that's going to be a
case-breaker'' in the car, said Keith McKaskill, an inspector in
the Winnipeg Police Department, which is part of the U.S.-Canadian
task force investigating the attacks on Slepian and four other
abortion providers in western New York and Canada. ``We have no
idea where he is.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The car in Newark is just the latest link law enforcement
officials say they have found between Kopp and the New York
metropolitan region.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities believe that Kopp was working construction jobs
in the region in the days leading up to and directly after the
Slepian shooting. FBI agents have interviewed the owner of a
delivery service in Hoboken, N.J., and a contractor in Jersey City,
both of whom said Kopp worked for them recently.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Grodofsky of Jersey City said in a recent interview with
The New York Times that Kopp _ whom he knew by the name Clyde
Swenson _ did carpentry work for him from about March until August,
when Kopp said he was taking a job with a contractor in Manhattan.
Grodofsky said Kopp also lived in a building he owns in Jersey City
off and on for about two months ending in early November.
</P>
<P>
   Grodofsky described Kopp as a ``true believer'' who attended
Mass frequently, had antiabortion stickers on his dashboard, and
once got in a fight with another worker who was drinking on the
job. Kopp and Grodofsky talked often of the Bible and World War II,
Grodofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a highlight every day,'' Grodofsky said. ``He was
funny. He was incredibly smart.''
</P>
<P>
   In the dingy apartment where Kopp stayed, he left behind some
plastic containers from Taco Bell, two paperback novels _ an Agatha
Christie mystery and a war story _ several marketing manuals and a
Spanish-language calendar from a Roman Catholic funeral home.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Castillo of Jersey City, who worked with Kopp on
construction projects for Grodofsky, described him as ``a little
strange,'' comparing him to a hermit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said: `I'm a pro-lifer, I don't believe in a woman
choosing,''' Castillo recalled of one conversation about abortion.
``I said, `What's wrong with a woman's choice?' He said: `It's not
right. It's a woman's right to choose for the baby to live. The
Lord will prevail.' He blew me away with that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Buffalo clinic where Slepian worked, abortions continued
as scheduled Wednesday. Doctors from around the country have flown
in to keep the clinic operating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping that what they find in the car can help with the
investigation,'' said Melinda DuBois, director of the clinic,
Buffalo GYN Womenservices. ``The longer it takes to find this guy,
the colder the trail goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
