<SLUG> BC-PROTECTING-PARENTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS AGE; FAMILIES MUST MAKE PLANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- You're having a nice Christmas Day get-together
with your parents and you wonder for the 100th time if you should
finally have the heart-to-heart chat you know is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you've seen the film ``One True Thing,'' in which Kate
Gulden (Meryl Streep) loses her health, forcing her to become much
closer with her grown daughter, or you've heard the stories about
nursing-home bills driving families into bankruptcy. But if you're
like most adults with senior-citizen parents, chances are you'll
talk about the weather instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a part of us that would like to preserve our parents
as omnipotent and eternal because that allows us to be an eternal
child,'' said Margaret Huyck, professor of psychology at the
Illinois Institute of Technology. ``The idea of confronting them as
not being reliable and then gone -- that's something we don't want
to deal with. And parents often want to preserve that illusion.''
</P>
<P>
   As unappealing as it sounds to discuss a parent's health care
and financial well-being, avoiding it is a critical mistake. ``You
wouldn't believe how often people don't talk about these issues
until it's an emergency situation,'' said Gail Reid, an American
Express certified financial planner in Glendale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a blessing to have good health that you've got to do
something while you still can.''
</P>
<P>
   The first step is simple, according to Matty Kent-Dychtwald, a
consultant and lecturer on aging issues. ``You need to get through
your own psychological unease about the problem,'' she said. ``You
need to say, `I don't want to end up in a bad situation with no one
knowing what to do.' I believe that once you're past the emotional
barrier, the rest isn't that difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you need to discuss, experts say:
</P>
<P>
   -- Is there a living will instructing doctors what they should
and should not do if extraordinary measures are needed?
</P>
<P>
   -- Is there any estate planning, including a will?
</P>
<P>
   -- Has anyone been given power of attorney so that a parent's
affairs can be handled if the parent become disabled?
</P>
<P>
   -- Are there plans for long-term medical care and how will it be
financed?
</P>
<P>
   Experts admit that starting such a discussion isn't easy.
``Talking about this should be done when people are feeling good
about each other,'' Huyck suggested. ``It's important to figure out
just how competent your parents are, because the most offensive
thing to do is assume that if someone is over 70, they must be
losing their faculties.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent-Dychtwald strongly suggested an oblique approach: ``You
need to have a very frank conversation but you can start by just
asking `How do you feel today?' as part of bringing up the need to
exercise. It's very simple to ease into the other questions and
it's the most important issue anyhow.''
</P>
<P>
   The payoff for working out the details is peace of mind, said
Grace Lebow, co-founder and co-director of the Aging Network
Services in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``People as they get older appreciate it when their children
show an interest in their lives,'' she explained. ``They all say
they don't want to burden their kids, but they usually love it when
they can talk about it because parents do think about these issues
as they get older. It's happening to all their friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Lebow also noted that if parents don't want to talk about these
issues, they'll let you know right away. ``If that happens, I
always suggest letter writing,'' she says. ``It works well because
everyone can make sure that their needs are understood.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
