<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENTS PAST 
MISSING PERSON 
PETER PRINCIPLE
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON WITH PHOEBE HOBAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist, who is to preside over any
Senate trial of President Clinton, may profit from public interest
in impeachment even before he gavels the proceeding to order.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, William Morrow's Quill division will issue a
paperback version of Rehnquist's six-year-old book, ``Grand
Inquests: The Historic Impeachments of Justice Samuel Chase and
President Andrew Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrow said that Rehnquist would receive royalties on the
25,000-copy reprint, but a Morrow spokeswoman, Sharyn Rosenblum,
declined to say how much money was involved. A Supreme Court
spokeswoman had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some authors who write epilogues for their second
editions, Rehnquist did not add anything to ``Grand Inquests.'' The
text will appear exactly as it did in hardcover in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's not appropriate for him to do any updating on
it,'' Ms. Rosenblum said.
</P>
<P>
   Hints on the chief justice's thinking on presidential
impeachments may be hard to discern. Forrest McDonald, who reviewed
``Grand Inquests'' in The New York Times Book Review in 1992, wrote
that Rehnquist's account of the Andrew Johnson impeachment in 1868
left some questions unanswered. ``Why did Congress bother to
impeach the president at all,'' McDonald asked, ``when he had less
than a year of his term remaining?''
</P>
<P>
   Dated Card
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some 1998 Christmas cards date back a bit. Consider
the one from the Michelangelo Hotel, at 152 W. 51st St., which
shows the hotel staff with Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably over a year ago, in the wintertime,'' said
Debbie Rearley, who works in the hotel's marketing office.
</P>
<P>
   The man in the Santa suit, Michael Blackman, is still the
general manager. But there have been some changes of personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in the picture,'' said Ms. Rearley, who joined the
staff in September.
</P>
<P>
   Tell-Some Memoir
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Lawyer: A Life of Counsel and Controversy,'' the
posthumously published autobiography of Arthur Liman, is not one of
those tell-all memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   It does not tell all about the three men named Peter involved in
its completion.
</P>
<P>
   The book looks back on Liman's career as a partner at Paul,
Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison; his investigation of the 1971
Attica prison uprising, and his work as chief counsel to the Senate
committee that investigated the Iran-contra affair.
</P>
<P>
   The acknowledgments credit Peter No. 1, Peter Sistrom, a former
associate of Liman's at Paul, Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to be a ghostwriter,'' said Sistrom, who worked
as an editor and researcher on a 100-page transcript of notes Liman
had written on _ what else? _ legal pads after he was found to have
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we never had a formal arrangement, which was odd, given
that we were two lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sistrom's work on ``Lawyer'' ended when he took what he called
``a leave of absence'' from the project in the spring of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Peter No. 2. The title page says that Liman wrote the book
``with the assistance of Peter Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the manuscript was done,'' said Israel, a former
publisher at Putnam. ``But parts of it were sketchy. I think there
was a feeling on Arthur and Ellen's part that we needed to make a
big push, and I was called in semi-extremis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a terrific amount of work by spewing faxes back and
forth.'' (Ellen is Liman's widow, who said that a non-Peter _ their
son Lewis, an assistant U.S. attorney in Manhattan, was also
involved.)
</P>
<P>
   The finished manuscript was delivered to Peter No. 3, Peter
Osnos, who had left Random House to start his own firm, Public
Affairs, shortly before Liman's death on July 17, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is emphatically Arthur's book,'' Osnos said, ``but he was a
lawyer, not a memoirist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
