<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APOLOGY OK BY PALMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The last page has finally been written _ literally
_ regarding some of the controversial comments made after last
month's USC-UCLA football game.
</P>
<P>
   USC quarterback Carson Palmer said he has received a handwritten
letter of apology from UCLA linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo over
Ayanbadejo's statements about the true freshman. Ayanbadejo said
Palmer was ``terrible'' and that the Bruins' redshirt freshmen
quarterbacks were better than Palmer following UCLA's 34-17 victory
over the Trojans at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nice thing for him to do,'' Palmer said. ``I had
heard about it (before) because his coach was upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Palmer accepted Ayanbadejo's apology, he said the
comments will still motivate him for next season's game against the
Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely going to remember that next year against
UCLA,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Making the pitch: USC coach Paul Hackett is starting to get more
and more questions about the future of juniors Chris Claiborne and
R. Jay Soward.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne is fully expected to turn pro after the season, and
Soward appears to be headed in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   Strictly as a coach, Hackett would love to have both players
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to what they really want to do,'' Hackett said.
``We're going to run a tight ship, get degrees and play hard-nosed
football. If both of those guys come back, we've got a chance to
make a real jump next season.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton on mend: Tailback Chad Morton missed Wednesday's practice
to rest his sore ankle, although Hackett said he didn't think it
would affect his status for the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been next (week), I'd really be panicking,'' Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Soward also missed his second straight day of practice because
he has had a cold.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes no better: Wide receiver Windrell Hayes, who has a
sprained big toe, went home to Stockton and did not practice
Wednesday with no improvement in his condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how he is in a few more days,'' Hackett said. ``He's
certainly in jeopardy for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep it down: USC practices have been quieter this week, with
only limited use of the air horn used to end drills. The reason is
that adjacent Dedeaux Field has been transformed into a replica of
the Detroit Tigers' spring-training facility for a baseball movie
being filmed starring Kevin Costner.
</P>
<P>
   And the film's crew asked for less use of the loud air horns on
Howard Jones Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
