<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LEAFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO'S HAT TRICK HELPS SINK TORONTO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ While most teams have looked back on memories of past
games in their final trip to the historic Maple Leaf Gardens, the
Stars decided to create new memories last night.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Mike Modano's first hat trick of the season and Ed
Belfour's sometimes frenetic goaltending, the Stars crumpled the
Maple Leafs, 5-1. The victory extended the Stars' unbeaten streak
to 10 games (7-0-3) and was only Toronto's second loss in the past
11 (9-2) games at the venerable Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs are scheduled to move out of the 68-year-old
building Feb. 20 and into the new Air Canada Centre, signaling an
end of the last pre-1960s building in the NHL. And while many teams
have been caught up in the nostalgia of the moment, the Stars were
too tired to be involved in the hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   ``After playing those three games in four nights, we really felt
like we needed the energy,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said of his
decision not to practice at the Gardens in the morning. ``We didn't
want to cheat ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had plenty of energy and few distractions, receiving
all five goals from the Modano-Jere Lehtinen-Brett Hull line and
moving to a 20-5-6 record. The Stars have a league-best 46 points.
</P>
<P>
   While Modano's energy clearly was up, the Stars as a team
started slowly. The Maple Leafs outshot the Stars, 7-1, to start
the game, and Belfour was tested early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our goalie was the best player on the ice early in
the game,'' Hitchcock said. ``Eddie saved our bacon.''
</P>
<P>
   And that performance by Belfour paid off when Modano zipped a
wrister through the legs of Maple Leafs goalie Curtis Joseph four
minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to get it on net,'' said Modano, who broke a
seven-game goal-scoring drought. ``It just kind of slipped
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto fell to 19-12-2, and Joseph dropped to 14-10-2. The
former Edmonton Oilers goalie, who joined the Maple Leafs as a free
agent in the off-season, was facing the Stars for the 17th time,
playoffs included, since April 1997. Joseph is 5-12 in those games.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, the Stars had Cujo's number. With Toronto's Gary
Valk off for elbowing, Hull scored his 10th goal of the season at
the 9:46 mark of the first period by deflecting in a Darryl Sydor
shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs came back to make it 2-1 on a Sergei Berezin
goal, but Modano gave the Stars a 3-1 first-period lead when he
ripped a 45-foot slap shot past Joseph with the Stars short-handed
at the 17:47 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen quickly punched that to 4-1 at the 5:41 mark of the
second period when he deflected in a Derian Hatcher shot for his
team-leading 11th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars would lead the rest of the way, but that didn't mean
Lehtinen would stay in the goal-scoring lead alone for the Stars.
Modano registered his fifth career hat trick when he took a
Lehtinen pass on an odd-man rush and whistled a wrister past
Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   The Modano-Hull-Lehtinen line has 32 goals this season,
including eight points last night.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars ended their four-game pre-Christmas road trip with a
3-0-1 record and moved to 9-3-4 on the road this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to play on the road, so we have to be conscious of
the energy,'' Hitchcock said. ``We're just playing a strong road
game overall right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
