<SLUG> BC-GLF-WILCOX-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLES WANTS A FAST START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The personal trauma is behind him and ``Mr.
November'' again looks forward to life on the road.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not surprising that Fred Couples sounds like a man at
peace with where he has been and where his travels will take him.
After all, the road has been very good, making him a
multi-millionaire and one of the most popular golfers.
</P>
<P>
   Had it not been for a back that exploded on the driving range at
the 1994 Doral-Ryder Open and some wrenching emotional experiences,
who knows what heights Couples might have scaled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe I will play a lot early in the year,''
Couples said this week in discussing his 1999 schedule. ``All the
way up to the U.S. Open.''
</P>
<P>
   His West Coast swing includes traditional stops at the Bob Hope
Chrysler Classic, where he is defending champion, and Riviera
Country Club for the Nissan Open. Couples may even put in a rare
appearance at the AT&AMP;T National Pro Am at Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The nickname ``Mr. November'' comes courtesy of astounding past
performances in golf's ``silly season'' where players compete for
money rather than prestige. Couples turned it into his own personal
cash cow.
</P>
<P>
   Now the focus seems to be shifting to titles. There were times
in the past, he said, when he just went to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to win, that's a goal. If I get in a hot stretch,
I'll pay attention and work hard on my game. There have been times
when I just played _ and finished 25th _ but that's not me. My goal
is to win and play well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Couples owns one of the game's most effortless swings and it
brought fame and fortune in equal measures. He's a gallery favorite
wherever he goes and is one of the world's most laid-back athletes.
</P>
<P>
   But it was life away from the fairways and greens that opened
the deepest wounds and turned 1997 into what for Couples was a
statistical freak. He played 15 events, his fewest appearances
ever, and fell to 55th on the PGA Tour money list, his third-worst
showing in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Life away from golf was simply more important then. Couples'
father, Tom, was dying of leukemia and his girlfriend Thais Bren,
was battling breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The father, a former Seattle recreation and parks employee who
introduced his son to golf, died on Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   Couples mourned his loss and entered 1998 focused on winning. It
happened quickly, at the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a shock,'' he said of last year's win at the
Hope. ``I was doing a lot of things besides playing golf. (But) I
was pretty peaceful after the passing of my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   He also won the Memorial, Jack Nicklaus' personal tournament
that is one of the most prestigious titles on tour.
</P>
<P>
   Couples banked $1.7 million in official money this year and
climbed into 11th place in the world golf rankings. Best of all,
last summer he married Bren, who has recovered from her cancer.
</P>
<P>
   There are now more riches than ever on the table as the tour
enters the 1999 season and it is the kind of money that can still
get Couples' attention, though he has his own way of putting it in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Journeymen pros can earn $800,000 in a year if they win one
tournament and have a couple of other nice finishes. Most of us
would take it. Couples notes that's the salary of a utility player
in baseball or the 10th man on an NBA team, assuming the league is
ever seen in public again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a younger player I would be licking my chops. At 39,
I still am,'' he said. ``I think golf pays off in the long run.
Until we screw it up, I believe anyone playing golf should be able
to play for a lot of money for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Organizers of the Hope have distributed a record $1.5
million to Palm Springs area charities from the proceeds of the
1998 tournament. The event has raised $31 million since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Donations were made to 42 charitable organizations. The largest
donation, $1 million, went to the Eisenhower Medical Center....
Masters, British Open and World Match Play title-holder Mark
O'Meara has bagged yet another honor to cap a career season:
Official King of the Unofficial Money Season. Among players who
participated in at least two events, O'Meara pocketed the most
change, $730,000. His pal Tiger Woods finished second with
$650,000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
